<P>
   (NYT34) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-17 -- Gov.
George W. Bush introducing retired general Colin Powell to delegates
at the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia, Monday. Bush
speaking via a satellite hookup from a school in Ohio, noted Powell's
high-level service in national security positions in two GOP
administrations, then said, "I hope his greatest service to America
might still lie ahead." (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-16 -- Laura
Bush, surrounded by school children on stage at the Republican
National Convention, Monday. The former librarian and schoolteacher
admitted that she was "a little overwhelmed" to open the convention
that will nominate her husband for president, but said she felt
comfortable talking about education, "the living room of my life."
(Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-15 --
Retired general Colin Powell, the only black to serve as chairman of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff, speaking on opening night of the
Republican National Convention, Monday. Powell praised Texas governor
George W. Bush for bridging racial divides and urged the party to
follow Bush's lead and reach out to minorities, particularly blacks,
"and not just during an election year campaign." (Ruth Fremson/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-14 --
Retired general Colin Powell speaking on opening night of the
Republican National Convention, Monday, praised Texas governor George
W. Bush's "passion for inclusion," then bluntly challenged the GOP to
follow his lead. The Texas governor "has been successful in bringing
more minorities inside the tent by responding to their deepest
needs," said Powell. "He can do the same thing as president." (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-13 -- Laura
Bush, surrounded by school children on stage at the Republican
National Convention, Monday. The former librarian and schoolteacher
admitted that she was "a little overwhelmed" to open the convention
that will nominate her husband for president, but said she felt
comfortable talking about education, "the living room of my life."
(Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-12 -- Laura
Bush, in a warm convention testimonial at the Republican National
Convention Monday, said that her husband George W. Bush's values
won't waver "with the winds of polls or politics." America, she said,
wants a president who reflects "its heart and its values and its
leadership in the world. They will be looking for someone to uphold
that high honor and that trust." Mrs. Bush said the Texas governor
would fulfill that role. (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-11 -- Former
President George Bush and his wife Barbara greet George P. Schultz,
the former secretary of state, at the Republican National Convention
in Philadelphia, Monday night. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
