Republican delegates in all their glory on opening night at the
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia, Monday. (Chang W.
Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-9 -- Barbara
Bush, former first lady, acknowleges the crowd, as former President
George Bush sits beside her at the opening night of the Republican
National Convention. Bush won a standing ovation from supporters as
he arrived at the convention where the party will anoint his son its
presidential nominee. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-8 -- Former
President George Bush at the opening night of the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia, Monday. Bush won a standing ovation from
supporters as he arrived at the convention where the party will
anoint his son its presidential nominee. (Chang W. Lee/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- July 31, 2000 -- SHADOW-CONVENTION --
Ethan Nadelmann, a former Princeton Professor, a much-admired and
much-repudiated critic of recent administrations' wars on drugs.
Nadelmann has been supported by a small, powerful and eclectic group
of thinkers, including Walter Cronkite and George P. Shultz, the
former secretary of state. He is one of the creators of the "shadow
conventions," that will be held in Philadelphia and Los Angeles to
discuss issues that will not be considered at the other conventions.
(Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-7 -- At the
opening of the evening session of the Republican National Convention,
Monday, Speaker of the House Dennis Hastert gavelles the session to
order on a remote video screen from Carpenters Hall in Philadelphia.
(Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-6 --
Jennifer Leith holding an armful of Gov. George Bush masks she plans
to sell to any and all takers at the 2000 Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia this week. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-NC-AL-YOUTH-2 --
Josh Workman, 19, a North Carolina college student is the youngest
delegate at one of the biggest political parties of the year, the
2000 Republican National Convention. Workman, 19, edged out fellow
Alabama delegate Joy Barganier, 19, by two months to lay claim to
being the youngest delegate at the convention. The two represent an
emphasis by the GOP to put a youthful face on their party. (Jamie
Moncrief/Morning Star, Wilmington)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-NC-AL-YOUTH-1 --
Alabama delegate Joy Barganier on opening day of the Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia, Monday. Barganier, 19, was edged
out by North Carolina delegate Josh Workman, also 19, for the title
of youngest GOP delegate by two months. The two represent an emphasis
by the GOP to put a youthful face on their party. (Jamie
Moncrief/Morning Star, Wilmington)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-5 -- Actor
Robert Conrad embraces George P. Bush, nephew of Gov. George W. Bush,
during an event titled "One American Dream, Many American Dreams," at
the site of the Republican Naitonal Convention, Monday. At left is
Rep. Mary Bono, R-Calif. (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- July 31, 2000 -- POP-LYRICS-2 -- The
various ways in which "The Marshall Mathers LP," by rapper Eminem,
has been edited for content shows a remarkable change in the way
record companies and radio stations now handle explicit lyrics  as
well as the inconsistencies in these methods. Eminem's new album with
different labels indicating various edits. (Nancy Siesel/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- July 31, 2000 -- POP-LYRICS-1 -- The
various ways in which "The Marshall Mathers LP," by rapper Eminem,
has been edited for content shows a remarkable change in the way
record companies and radio stations now handle explicit lyrics  as
well as the inconsistencies in these methods. A customer listens to a
version of the CD at a record store. (Nancy Siesel/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- July 31, 2000 -- SCI-BROADWAY-DANCE --
Broadway shows are highlighting perfomers who are athletically
trained to handle challenging routines that highlight their skills.
Having more strength means more opportunities for choreographers to
create better physical roles. Christopher Jackson practices a
maneuver he will perform when taking on the role of Simba in the
musical, "The Lion King," which he will begin in mid-August.
(Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) DAYTON, Ohio -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-4 -- Gov.
George W. Bush with his wife Laura during a campaign rally in Dayton,
Monday. Later, Mrs. Bush left for Philadelphia where she was to
address the Republican National Convention who is expected to
nominate her husband for president later this week. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SANTA MONICA, Calif. -- July 31, 2000 --
BKN-KENYON-MARTIN -- Kenyon Martin, the 6-foot-9-inch, 235-pound
forward out of the University of Cincinnati and the overall No. 1
pick in the NBA draft, cuts a menacing figure on the basketball
court, but was tormented by bullies as a youngster. Martin at his
work-out facility in Santa Monica, Calif., preparing for his rookie
season with the New Jersey Nets. (Lee Celano/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-MESSAGE --
Network officials say the Republicans at the national convention are
almost obsessive in their efforts to squeeze every precious media
moment out of their prime-time opportunities. Adrian Pest, a
cameraman for ABC News, wears the latest in television technology, a
wireless monitor strapped to his stomach as he films the floor of the
First Union Center on Monday during the first day of the Republican
National Convention. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- July 31, 2000 -- NY-CHAMBER-MUSIC -- Of
the many social scenes that weave through New York's night life, few
are lesser-known than the chamber music crowd. And few have so many
dedicated denizens. Joan Edelstein, a flutist, right, reads a
magazine while waiting for her time to play. Other musicians from
left: Larry Beckhardt, an official with the Department of
Environmental Protection, playing the clarinet; Suzanne Chen, a
computer consultant, playing the bassoon, and Haskell Edelstein, Mrs.
Edelstein's husband, also plays the Bassoon. (Ruth Fremson/The New
York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) DAYTON, Ohio -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-3 -- Gov.
George W. Bush during a campaign stop, Monday. Bush was making his
way eastward on a six-day tour of battleground states that will bring
him to Philadelphia and the Republican National Convention on
Wednesday where he is to accept the party's nomination for president.
(Stephen Crowley/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-2 -- Members
of the New Jersey delegation dance in the aisles of the convention
floor Monday following the official opening of the Republican
National Convention. Republicans placed George W. Bush's name in
nomination for president Monday and ratified his carefully balanced
campaign platform, the opening acts of a convention scripted to
appeal to voters in the political middle. (Ruth Fremson/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PHILADELPHIA -- July 31, 2000 -- GOP-RDP-1 --  Dick
Cheney was greeted by cheers and chants Monday when he stopped by the
National Republican Convention as the name of George W. Bush, the man
who picked him as a running mate, was placed in nomination. Cheney
with his wife Lynne on the floor of the convention, Monday. (Jamie
Moncrief/Morning Star, Wilmington)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- July 31, 2000 -- WASHINGTON-MONUMENT -- The
long-running renovation of the Washington Monument, the capital's
555-foot-high exclamation point, went on hold Monday so summertime
tourists can ride up the newly uncovered obelisk. Visitors made their
way to the monument Monday. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) COLD SPRING HARBOR, N.Y. -- July 31, 2000 --
DNA-VOLUNTEERS -- A California startup company called DNA Sciences is
starting a Web site on Tuesday to recruit people to donate their DNA
to help find genes that cause disease. The company, which has DNA
double helix discoverer James D. Watson as a director and Netscape
founder James H. Clark as an investor, hopes to get 50,000 to 100,000
people to contribute by appealing to their altruism. Watson during an
interview in 1999. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) JERUSALEM -- July 31, 2000 -- ISRAEL-PERES-2 -- Prime
Minister Ehud Barak suffered embarrassment in Israel's parliament
Monday when he narrowly survived yet another no-confidence vote and
his party's candidate for president, Nobel laureate Shimon Peres, was
edged out by a relative unknown. Peres, right, shakes hands with
Moshe Katsav, a legislator from the opposition Likud party, after
Katsav won the presidency. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) AUSTIN, Texas -- July 31, 2000 --
SCI-VINES-BUTTERFLIES-2 -- Dr. Lawrence E. Gilbert and  Dr. Helene S.
Engler have reported in the journal Nature that the Heliconius
butterfly can overcome a vine's cyanide-producing compounds. A
Heliconius butterfly feeding on Passiflora. (Marsha Miller/University
of Texas at Austin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) AUSTIN, Texas -- July 31, 2000 --
SCI-VINES-BUTTERFLIES-1 -- Dr. Lawrence E. Gilbert and  Dr. Helene S.
Engler have reported on a butterfly that can overcome a vine's
cyanide-producing compounds. Gilbert and Engler examining the
Heliconius butterflies at work. (Marsha Miller/University of Texas at
Austin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) JERUSALEM -- July 31, 2000 -- ISRAEL-POLITICS-2 --
Prime Minister Ehud Barak suffered embarrassment in Israel's
parliament Monday when he narrowly survived yet another no-confidence
vote and his party's candidate for president, Nobel laureate Shimon
Peres, was edged out by a relative unknown. Barak alone at his seat
in the Knesset following Monday's votes. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) JERUSALEM -- July 31, 2000 -- ISRAEL-POLITICS -- Moshe
Katsav of the opposition Likud Party, center, celebrates his election
as Israeli president, Monday. Prime Minister Ehud Barak won a
no-confidence vote in parliament Monday, after parliament elected the
Iranian-born Katsav as Israel's new president, rejecting Shimon
Peres. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) JERUSALEM -- July 31, 2000 -- ISRAEL-PERES -- Shimon
Peres, the former Israeli foreigh minister who became prime minister
following the assassination of Yitzak Rabin, leaves the Israeli
Knesset Monday after losing a  parliamentary vote for the Israeli
presidency. The victory of Iranian-born Moshe Katsav of the
opposition Likud Party spelled a humiliating end to Peres'
half-century political career. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
*LITE
</P>
