<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9061 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GOP-NYT-1STLD-WRITETH     08-01 1324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-NYT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
 
(Eds: Changes throughout with new developments and background
details) POWELL CALLS FOR INCLUSION OF MINORITIES 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT9, 10, 11, 15, 19, 22, 23, 25, 26, 27, 28, 29,
30, 31, 32 are being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Republican Party put on its newly moderate
and disciplined face at the opening of its national convention
Monday as one of the party's most compelling figures, Colin L.
Powell, challenged delegates to rally behind Gov. George W. Bush
with a genuine commitment to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   At the party's last convention in San Diego four years ago,
Powell appealed for inclusiveness and spoke of his support for
affirmative action and abortion rights. On Monday night, he
repeated much of his rallying cry for inclusion _ but dropped any
reference to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party must follow Governor Bush's lead and reach out to
minority communities and particularly the African-American
community _ and not just during an election-year campaign,'' Powell
said pointedly in his remarks to the convention. ``It must be a
sustained effort. It must be every day. It must be for real.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not spare the party for its record on affirmative action,
there was ``cynicism in the black community'' because ``some in our
party miss no opportunity to roundly and loudly condemn affirmative
action that helped a few thousands black kids get an education.''
But, he added, ``hardly a whimper is heard from them over
affirmative action for lobbyists who load our federal tax codes
with preferences for special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The address by Powell, and a warm testimonial by Bush's wife,
Laura, about education and her husband's values, formed the
centerpiece Monday night of a tightly and painstakingly
choreographed presentation by the Bush campaign and by the
Republican Party that was aimed far beyond the First Union Center.
It was intended to persuade the public at large _ particularly
women, independents and even Democrats _ that their rightful place
was in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   The drive to put blacks out front on Monday night was especially
striking, and persistent, and included everything from the lineup
of entertainers to the choice of Powell as the keynote speaker.
There was a live remote of a black preacher from a gospel church in
South Philadelphia, followed by a performance of a gospel choir on
stage in the hall.
</P>
<P>
   It made for a particularly sharp contrast with the audience
because only 4 percent of convention delegates identify themselves
as black, according to a survey by The New York Times and CBS News.
</P>
<P>
   For the Republicans, it was not so much a matter of reaching out
for the black vote, but part of Bush's determination to portray his
party as tolerant and inclusive, in hopes of appealing to
independents and moderate Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   This image of a remade Republican Party on stage was also
unlikely given that many delegates seemed stirred by two famous
faces of the past in the audience: Bush's mother and father.
</P>
<P>
   After the Bush campaign decreed there would be no searing swipes
at Democrats, Mrs. Bush, in describing her husband, confined
herself to an implict comparison with Bill Clinton and Al Gore,
whom the campaign often portrays as obsessed by bald political
calculations.
</P>
<P>
   ``His core principles will not change with the winds of polls or
politics or fame or fortune or misfortune,'' Mrs. Bush said of her
husband. ``I know because I've known him through big legislative
successes and a few defeats. I sat by his side during some winning
and many losing baseball seasons. But George never loses sight of
home plate.''
</P>
<P>
   In the testimonial to her husband of 22 years, she went on: ``He
shares credit and doesn't cast blame. He sets a tone that's
positive and constructive, a tone that is very different from the
bitterness and division that too often characterizes Washington,
D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Her best received line was when she declared that people come up
to her and say, ``I want my son or daughter to respect the
president of the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bush, a former teacher and librarian, extolled her
husband's commitment to education and literacy. And she said he was
devoted to Head Start, a subject upon which the Republican ticket
has become suddenly vulnerable because of votes cast against it by
Dick Cheney, the vice-presidential candidate, when he was a
congressman.
</P>
<P>
   ``As first lady, I will make early childhood development one of
my priorities,'' she said, ``and George will strengthen Head Start
to make sure it's an early reading and early learning program.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush was still wending his way eastward to Philadelphia as
part of a six-day tour of swing states, he dominated the convention
on Monday. In a play on his nickname _ and an appeal to women _ the
letter ``W'' was emblazoned big and red on signs throughout the
arena. Underneath, in smaller letters, were the words, ``Stands for
women.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bush was not entirely absent. Shortly after his wife's
speech, he paid a surprise visit to the convention via satellite,
from Westerville, Ohio, where he spoke from a classroom. Appearing
on a giant screen in the hall, he offered raves for his wife's
speech, and said, ``I can't wait to stand before you on Thursday
night and tell America how I want to use these good times for great
purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he introduced Powell with a tantalizing hint that he would
appoint him to serve in a Bush administration, declaring, ``I hope
his greatest service to America still lies ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   While Powell has been mentioned as a possible secretary of
state, it was notable that Bush made those comments from a
classroom and that in his speech Powell talked only about domestic
issues. That may be, of course, that education was the dominant
theme Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks by Powell, the former chairman of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff, were far more partisan than four years ago, when he had
recently revealed that he was a Republican. When he addressed the
Republican convention four years ago, he also spoke of compassion
and people in need. But in that speech, he reminded delegates of
his support for abortion rights and while he saluted Bob Dole as a
war hero, he was much more effusive this year about Bush. People
close to Powell insisted they were not pressured into excising any
reference to abortion; they said the general felt it simply did not
fit the theme of the night: ``Opportunity With a Purpose. Leave No
Child Behind.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bush appeared before the NAACP earlier this month, Powell
said, it was not mere window dressing. He quoted Bush's declaration
that ``the party of Lincoln has not always carried the mantle of
Lincoln.'' And he said he spoke with Bush today and that ``he wants
the Republican Party to wear that mantle again. But he knows that
it will take hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   But the effort by Powell to avoid saying anything that could
stoke unrest among the approximately 22,000 people who crammed into
the hall _ including 2,066 delegates and 2,066 alternates _
underscored the degree to which Republicans are united behind Bush
in their determination to win back the White House. The program ran
with such tight-fistedness that at one point it was 20 minutes
ahead of the minute-by-minute schedule.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Powell focused on Bush's achievements in Texas;
he emphasized the ``compassion'' in the governor's ``compassionate
conservative'' slogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Texas, Governor Bush has reached out to all Texans _
white, black, Latino, Asian, native American,'' he said. ``He has
been successful in bringing more and more minorities into the tent
by responding to their deepest needs. Some call it compassionate
conservatism. To me, it's just about caring about people.''
</P>
<P>
   The 37th Republican convention opened when Erik Weihenmayer, a
blind mountain climber, led the delegates in the Pledge of
Allegiance. Throughout the day, a parade of women, blacks, Latinos
and recovered Democrats marched to the rostrum in a show that more
resembled an Up With People jamboree than a hard-driving,
calculated effort to retake the White House. Despite the
understated references to the current administration, the words
Clinton, abortion and impeachment appeared to have been banished
from the scripts today. Even Newt Gingrich was far removed from the
action; his role Monday night was as a commentator for Fox News.
</P>
<P>
   That left those tuning in on television with a buffed view of
the Republican Party _ and Bush _ far more moderate than the
delegates in the hall who voted Monday for a platform that hewed to
some fiercely conservative tenets, like the party's call for a ban
on abortion. With the usual internecine maneuvering largely absent,
and Cheney already selected as the running mate, there was little
suspense.
</P>
<P>
   That was reflected in the lack of enthusiasm in a roll call to
make Bush's nomination official _ the party's first three-day
rolling roll call _ that drew only the most perfunctory rounds of
cheers by delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Mr. Bush's chief strategist, said he did not believe
there was a contradiction between the moderate, inclusive message
Monday night and the fact that polls of the delegates show that
they are notably conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a gap between what Republicans believe
and what their candidate does,'' said Rove, in an interview on
``Political Points,'' The New York Times/ABC News webcast.
``Otherwise, they wouldn't have nominated him. And let me correct.
You said inclusive and moderate. What we're saying is it's
inclusive and compassionately conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the stage-managing, convention organizers had an
easy job because delegate after delegate said the party had not
been so unified since 1984, when Ronald Reagan cruised to a second
term. On the opening night of that convention, in Detroit,
Republicans bashed Walter F. Mondale relentlessly. But tonight,
party officials expressed such confidence with Mr. Bush's
positioning that they said they felt they could go easy on Vice
President Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine a convention that could be more
unified,'' Butch Davis, a delegate from Houston, said.
</P>
<P>
   It was no accident that the party held its 37th convention here
this week, the first Republican gathering in Philadelphia since
Thomas E. Dewey won the nomination in 1948. The party this year was
determined to underscore its commitment to a state that is not
reliably Republican.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the effort to portray Bush as a leader who could
work across party lines, his name was placed in nomination by his
lieutenant governor, Rick Perry. Perry told reporters that Bush
helped convinced him to defect from the Democratic to the
Republican party more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I proudly place the name of the current governor of the great
state of Texas and the next president of the United States into
nomination, George W. Bush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While cable networks and web sites covered the evening's events
extenstively, coverage on the big three broadcast networks was
fleeting and confined to the 10 o'clock hour at best. Only ABC
covered any part of Mrs. Bush's address; while CBS and ABC covered
Powell's speech virtually in its entirety. NBC relegated its prime
time coverage to MSNBC, its cable sister.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking from tradition, the Republicans abandoned their
traditional one-night roll calls of states _ which officials said
has become too interminable for a single sitting of prime time
television _ and Monday night began a rolling state-by-state tally
that will be spread over three nights. The party was careful to
juggle which states cast its votes so that Bush would not be
officially nominated before Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   When the roll call came to Arizona, the spokesperson for the
delegation was not that state's senior senator, John McCain, Bush's
most ardent foe in the primaries, but his wife, Cindy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father and mother strode into the hall at 8:40 p.m. Their
arrival was not announced. But as delegates began catching sight of
these most famous of Republicans, they rose to their feet and a
swell of applause came from the floor. When they were formally
announced moments later, they were greeted with a 30-second
standing ovation and chants of ``Bush! Bush! Bush!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
