<HEADLINE>
DISPUTES WESTERN RESOURCES AND PROTECTION ONE EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission's staff is alleging that
Western Resources Inc. and its Protection One subsidiary have had
``improperly inflated'' earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC staff said it was specifically concerned that some
aspects of Protection One's accounting could indicate
``manipulative intent.'' The matter was being referred to the
federal agency's enforcement division to consider further action.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations, disclosed by Western Resources in a filing with
the SEC late Friday, sent the company's stock down 81 cents Monday
to $15.81. Protection One lost 25 cents, closing at $2.
</P>
<P>
   Western Resources and Protection One said the accounting methods
used were proper. They said their position is supported by their
independent public accountant, Arthur Andersen LLP.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to strongly disagree with the position of the
(SEC) staff,'' said Robin Lampe, a spokeswoman for Protection One
in Topeka.
</P>
<P>
   Protection One in a July 25 letter to the SEC requested a
meeting with more-senior members of the SEC staff to discuss the
allegations. The SEC agreed to have a meeting, but Lampe said a
date had not been set.
</P>
<P>
   There were no estimates on how past financial results could be
affected at Western and Protection One if they are changed to meet
the SEC staff's concern, although they would have a ``material
adverse effect,'' according to Western's filing with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Western owns 85 percent of Protection One, which is a
monitored-security company. Financial problems at Protection One
were a key reason for Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co.'s decision in
January to terminate a merger with Western.
</P>
<P>
   Protection One had previously changed its accounting procedures
to satisfy SEC concerns over how Protection One was accounting for
acquisitions. That apparently did not fully satisfy the SEC staff.
</P>
<P>
   Among the recent concerns stated by the staff was the accounting
for the acquisition of Westinghouse Security Systems in 1997,
including the valuation of Westinghouse's monitoring software.
Other SEC concerns about Protection One include the accounting for
unexpected customer attrition.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC concerns about Protection One's accounting come as
Western Resources seeks to sell its utilities, KPL and KGE. Critics
and observers of the company say it will be important to examine
any proposed sale to ensure that Protection One's problems aren't
shouldered by Western's utility customers.
</P>
<P>
   One fear is that the utilities will be sold with more debt to
try to salvage what remains of Western Resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of cross-subsidization is a concern,'' said Walker
Hendrix, counsel for the Citizens' Utility Ratepayer Board,
Missouri's watchdog for utility customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
