<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9074 &Cx1f; kan-z
a w BC-KC-BUSH-KAN &LR;      08-01 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-BUSH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S CONGENIALITY AND LIMITED FOCUS ARE STRENGTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ George W. Bush's most valuable assets as
president could be his winning personality and ability to focus on
a specific agenda, political experts said at a seminar Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's use of those skills could be hampered by a Congress
bogged down in gridlock. As governor of Texas, Bush encountered a
far more congenial Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you can export the Texas model to Washington
and have it work,'' said Dan Balz, a political reporter for The
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The seminar on Bush's governing style was sponsored by the
American Enterprise Institute for Public Policy Research, a
conservative Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   With Balz on a panel were Republican Texas state Sen. Teel
Bivins; C. Boyden Gray, a longtime legal adviser to former
President Bush; Princeton University political scientist Fred
Greenstein; Republican Gov. Mike Johanns of Nebraska; and Dave
McNeely, political columnist at the Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will work to develop good relations with Congress, several
panel members said. He made a point of sitting down with 175 of the
Texas Legislature's 181 members in the weeks after he became
governor.
</P>
<P>
   McNeely recalled how Bush invited the state Supreme Court to an
early get-acquainted meeting. One justice said he had tried for
four years to get former Gov. Ann Richards, a Democrat, to do the
same thing. She never did.
</P>
<P>
   Getting people to like him is Bush's strong suit, Bivins said.
``Once you do that, it's a lot easier to get people to do your
bidding.''
</P>
<P>
   Because bills in Texas require two-thirds support for passage,
getting along with members of the opposite party is crucial,
McNeely said. Bush also was aided by a mentor of sorts, and a
Democratic one at that _ former Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, a longtime
Texas political power.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Bush can find a similar friend among Washington
Democrats remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure Bush would have been as successful in Texas if
not for that relationship with Bullock,'' Balz said.
</P>
<P>
   Also important for Bush could be his limited, but focused
agenda. So far, that agenda includes reforming Social Security,
cutting taxes and implementing a national missile-defense shield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to go right down that list...and convince people
those are the important issues that must be addressed,'' Johanns
said.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, Bush resembles former President Ronald Reagan,
who also found success with a finite list of issues. But Reagan had
one asset that Bush does not _ an unmatched ability to communicate
with the American people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man clearly is not a silver-tongued orator,'' Greenstein
said of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's supporters pointed to two other assets of the Texas
governor: A loyal staff that has stuck with him for years, and a
sense that his ego is not as tied into governing as President
Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, Greenstein said, ``is not as emotionally invested into
making it onto Mount Rushmore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
