A9075 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-DAVIS-CONTRIBUTIONS-S     08-01 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-CONTRIBUTIONS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS FUND RAISING NOW TOPS $21 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SACRAMENTO _ Gov. Gray Davis has raised nearly $21.4 million
since taking office in January 1999 _ more than four times what his
GOP predecessor did in his first 18 months in office.
<P>
   From January through June 30 of this year, the Democratic
governor raked in $8.1 million in contributions _ an average of
more than $1.3 million a month, according to a campaign disclosure
statement filed yesterday with the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing OK,'' said Garry South, Davis' chief political
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' relentless fund raising has been blamed by critics for
his slow pace in naming gubernatorial appointees and creating the
appearance that his administration caters to generous donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those so-called good government groups have said the same
thing before, and I'm sure they'll say it again,'' South said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is Gray Davis had more money spent against him in
the 1998 gubernatorial election than any candidate running for
office in the history of the United States of America. Believe me,
that makes an impression on you,'' said South.
</P>
<P>
   During his first 18 months in office, Pete Wilson, Davis'
Republican predecessor, raised $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never had $60 million spent against him,'' said South,
referring to the amount that Davis' primary and general election
opponents spent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   No other elected official came close to Davis in fund raising,
although Senate President Pro Tem John Burton, D-San Francisco,
reported raising nearly $2.3 million for the two campaign
committees he controls.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Bob Hertzberg, D-Van Nuys, raised nearly $1.4
million in the first six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   As leaders of their houses, Burton and Hertzberg bear the prime
responsibility for raising money to pay for this fall's legislative
races.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest initiative fight this fall is over Proposition 38
which would give parents $4,000 in state money that can be used to
help pay for private schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the initiative banked nearly $1.8 million in the
first six months of this year. Of that, $1.6 million came in loans
from the Timothy Draper Living Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Draper, a Silicon Valley venture capitalist, is the main backer
of the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, led by the powerful California Teachers Association,
reported raising $1.1 million. The CTA contributed $250,000 as did
the California Federation of Teachers and the California School
Employees Association.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Bill Lockyer raised $883,000 during the first
six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   He began the year with $1.9 million in the bank. He transferred
$2.6 million to a new campaign committee called The Lockyer
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer, who regulates gambling in the state, received
contributions from Indian tribes operating casinos, card clubs and
horse racing tracks.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Lockyer declined to accept $10,000 from an Indian
tribe that operates a casino.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe sponsored a golf fund raiser, with prices as high as
$25,000 a head. Lockyer said it was ``inappropriate'' for an Indian
tribe to sponsor an event on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would continue to accept contributions, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general's duty is to enforce the laws. Not unlike
the governor, he has responsibility for overseeing different groups
and organizations. Some of those entities make campaign
contributions, just as they do to other elected officials,'' said
Nathan Barankin, a Lockyer spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
