<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THE WELCOME MAT IS OUT, SINCERELY  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This space under new management!
</P>
<P>
   Welcome, boss!  &UR; Mi casa es su casa,  &LR; and vice versa, I hope.
</P>
<P>
   We are not sure exactly who the new chief is, but we are sure
that he/ she is a fine, honorable human being with such a keen
sense of humor that whatever he/she says, I can't help but laughing
obsequiously.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, we are using the editorial ``we'' here because there
is safety in numbers. Surely they wouldn't fire all of us who write
this column.
</P>
<P>
   I feel a little like Robert DeNiro today. I just watched
``Ronin,'' in which De Niro and three other guys are recruited to
do some murky, dirty deed. They don't know who their boss is or why
they are doing what they are doing. They only know they will be
paid.
</P>
<P>
   I really identified with De Niro in that movie, and I want the
new boss to know that if he/she tries to take away my column, he'll
have to catch me in a wild car chase through the streets of Paris.
The chase, of course, will include the obligatory smashing into the
fruit cart. I bet it's almost impossible to get collision coverage
on a fruit cart.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else around the Newpaper, I'm hoping I don't get
downsized. I'm already shrinking. I was in a doctor's office last
week, I measured myself and found that I am one inch shorter than
last time I checked. Gravity is a bitch. Fortunately, I gained one
inch around the waist, so my volume remains the same.
</P>
<P>
   CLINT REILLY and his attorney Joe Alioto did a fine job of
throwing several shrimp on the barbie, in the form of local
newspaper officials, politicians and Department of Justice bobos.
</P>
<P>
   Those folks all learned an important lesson: You can try pulling
sneaky backroom deals, but you can't get away with it!
</P>
<P>
   You can? Oh. Never mind.
</P>
<P>
   But Clint and Joe were wrong in saying the merger would kill
newspaper competition in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of OSTLER01 (44584 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Ha. Wait until the new boss informs me and Rob Morse that
whichever of us arrives first at the office in the morning gets to
use the chair.
</P>
<P>
   Regan McMahon wonders, ``Will the merging of staffs be like when
Tagi and Pagong tribes merged on `Survivor'? So far only Clint
Reilly has been voted off the island.''
</P>
<P>
   BOTH NEW San Francisco newspapers are off to Concorde-like
flying starts. The Examiner was purchased by the Fang family in
back-room dealings that Judge Vaughn Walker called ``malodorous.''
</P>
<P>
   Court testimony might lead one to believe that Mayor Willie
Brown was instrumental in brokering the deal that allowed the Fangs
to ``buy'' the Examiner for minus $66 million.
</P>
<P>
   I won't say the new Examiner is likely to go out of its way to
support the mayor, but there is a rumor that the first edition
under the Fangs will carry a front-page editorial nominating Willie
for the Nobel Prize in haberdashery.
</P>
<P>
   The new Chronicle, meanwhile, also starts off under a slight
cloud. Judge Walker wrote in his ruling that George Irish,
president of Hearst's newspaper division, ``simply was not a
believable witness.''
</P>
<P>
   In follow-up news stories of the court ruling, Irish was not
available for comment. Yikes. Newspaper honcho ducks own newspaper.
Unclear on concept.
</P>
<P>
   NAW, I'M NOT worried about Irish being mad at this mention. If
we can't kid our boss, whom can we kid? Besides, if he doesn't read
personal, vital e-mail from the publisher of his corporation's own
flagship newspaper, Irish isn't going to read some other paper's
wise-guy columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, honesty is way overrated. The entire presidential
campaign will be a battle to see which guy can do the best job of
fibbing away his political and personal record.
</P>
<P>
   AS FOR THE merger of the two newspaper staffs, Chronicle and
Examiner, it will be an adventure. I expect that the new owner will
announce a series of ice-breaker intra-staff mixers, dances, teas,
keggers and golf outings to Tahiti.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of OSTLER01 (44584 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  I'd like to keep writing a column, but I just work here, I do
what I'm told. Me and De Niro. Just don't assign me to push the
fruit cart.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'll be sent off to write obits, and if ever there was a
section of the paper that could use a little lightening up with
low-brow humor and cheap shots, it's that one.
</P>
<P>
   But if I show up for work one morning and they hand me a pick
and a canary, I'm going to have to tell them about my quadruple
hernia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
