<SLUG> BC-DNC-STREETS-LADN </SLUG>
 
L.A. MAY CLOSE STREETS DURING DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Anticipating thousands of demonstrators, Los
Angeles police said they plan to surrender downtown streets to
Democratic National Convention protesters as long as they obey
laws.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate protesters, Olympic Boulevard near Staples Center
and streets around Pershing Square will be closed periodically,
officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be times when the streets will have to be conceded
to the crowd because of the numbers and where it is not prudent to
confront the crowd, absent any other criminal behavior,'' LAPD
Cmdr. Tom Lorenzen told the City Council's Ad Hoc Committee on the
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want to be seen as creating a situation, as long as
people are peaceful and obey the laws. The strategy should begin
with intermittent closures.''
</P>
<P>
   Department of Transportation officials said they may have to
permanently close those streets during the Aug. 14-17 event.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they do not expect other areas of downtown will
be affected because of the stipulated agreement reached last Friday
to allow the demonstrators closer to Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The city also is keeping open the original protest site near the
expanded one, including portable toilets and water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to keep the downtown area open,'' said Frank
Martinez, city coordinator with the Democratic National Convention
Committee. ``With the new agreement, it essentially brings people
closer to Staples and the periodic closure of Olympic was always a
consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Bannerjee, Department of Transportation general manager,
said she thinks the city can manage periodic closure of Olympic
Boulevard and the area around Pershing Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a series of alternatives to deal with this and want a
chance to try those before we decide to close them off completely
during the convention,'' Bannerjee said. ``We are trying to be
flexible, and we have had a lot of experience with special
events.''
</P>
<P>
   The city plans to deploy a large force of traffic officers who
will be assigned to the same areas each day and have been trained,
said Dave Rosen, who has been developing the plans for
transportation department.
</P>
<P>
   Pershing Square has been included in the agreement so some
groups can use it as a staging area for marches through downtown
and to Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   One casualty of the dispute, however, is the decision by the
city Recreation and Parks Department to cancel a number of cultural
events that had been scheduled for the park.
</P>
<P>
   Pershing Square is across from the Biltmore Regal Hotel, which
will house the Tennessee delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore planned to stay there -- because
President John F. Kennedy had done so before his nomination -- but
the Secret Service decided to move him to Century City to avoid the
demonstrations.!dlim!!end!
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
