<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9081 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-GOP-CONVENTION-SFCHRO     08-01 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWELL SAYS BUSH AN EXAMPLE OF HOW GOP CAN BUILD TRUST
AMONG  MINORITIES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW and CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Retired Gen. Colin Powell, the most popular
African American in the Republican Party if not the country,
implored his party Monday night to reach out to minorities as the
GOP Convention opened with a decidedly moderate and united tone.
</P>
<P>
   Putting aside his more controversial support for abortion
rights, Powell praised Texas Gov. George W. Bush _ who will accept
the party's nomination Thursday night _ as an example of how the
``party of Lincoln'' can help build trust among minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party must follow Governor Bush's lead and reach out to
minority communities and particularly the African-American
community,'' said Powell, drawing enthusiastic cheers from the
delegates who are overwhelmingly white.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans had hoped that Powell would have a place on the
GOP ticket, something that Powell has repeatedly said he would not
consider.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush suggested that the former chairman of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff might have a place in his administration. Addressing
delegates via satellite from a high school in Ohio, Bush said of
Powell: ``I hope his greatest service to America might still lie
ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell's speech capped a tightly scripted opening night of the
four-day GOP convention, in which the names of President Clinton
and Vice President Al Gore _ usually favorite topics of GOP
ridicule _ were almost never mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Instead Republicans put on a multi-media extravaganza with the
chosen theme of ``Leave No Child behind'' and a line-up of speakers
included faces and themes more often associated with Democratic
gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Invocations were given by a Muslim cleric and a Jewish rabbi.
Video presentations featured gospel music from a local Baptist
church and tour of the East Palo Alto's KIPP Academy for
underprivileged children. Topic included ``empowerment,'' foster
care, immigration and literacy. Performances ranged from a funky
set by R&AMP;B artist Brian McKnight, to a tribute to Kate Smith and
the ever present thumping of John Philips Souza standards.
</P>
<P>
   Without opposition, Bush's name was placed in nomination, and
delegates approved his campaign platform in a voice vote, a
document largely tailored to fit his self-description as a
``compassionate conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro-choice advocates not only failed to amend language that
calls for a ban on abortion with no exceptions, they could not
gather enough support to bring the issue to the convention floor
for debate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's wife, Laura, made her national television debut, telling
the delegates: ``You know I am completely objective when I say _
you have made a great choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to more than 10,000 delegates, party luminaries, and
journalists packed into the home of the NBA's Philadelphia 76ers,
the former teacher took one of the evenings only swipes at Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``George's opponent has been visiting school lately, and
sometimes when he does, he spends the night before at the home of a
teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she continued, ``George spends every night with a
teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   In her biggest applause line, she said she hears Americans who
tell her, ``I'm counting on you ... I want my son or daughter to
respect the President of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush said of her husband, ``He shares credit and doesn't
cast blame. He sets a tone that's positive and constructive, a tone
that's very different from the bitterness and division that too
often characterize Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush and former first lady Barbara watched the
address from center-court seats, and were given a warm welcome from
the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Convention planners carefully held Bush and Powell's addresses
until after 10 p.m. on the East coast, when West Coast audiences
might tune in and when the 49ers-Patriots game was safely over.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike four years ago, when Republicans could hardly contain
their attacks on President Clinton, almost no mention was made of
either Clinton or Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Even outside the First Union Arena, dissent was hard to detect.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand advocates for the homeless disrupted traffic
but there were no major incidents in Philadelphia streets, where
blue-shirted police officers were a omnipresent force.
</P>
<P>
   Bush plans to arrive here Wednesday, and to accept the
nomination Thursday. ``I am on my way Philadelphia, and I am on my
way to victory in November,'' Bush said addressing delegates from
Westerville South High School in Ohio. Thousands of red, white and
blue balloons hung above the arena, ready for Bush's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1996 Republican convention, some people booed when Powell
said, `I believe in a woman's right to choose and I strongly
support affirmative action.``
</P>
<P>
   Powell did not mention abortion last night, but he chided some
in his party for missing ``no opportunity to roundly and loudly
condemn affirmative action that helped a few thousand black kids
get an education, but hardly a whimper is heard from them over
affirmative action for lobbyists who load our federal tax codes
with preferences for special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Beside race, Powell challenged Republican doctrine on spending
and class economics, saying ``The world is watching to see if all
this power and wealth is just for the well to do, the comfortable,
the privileged.''
</P>
<P>
   Some delegates were clearly not enthralled by Powell's comments.
A survey of delegates by the Associated Press found that 83 percent
are white while just 3.7 percent Black.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has openly speculated that he might nominate Powell as his
Secretary of State, but aides said no such announcement was
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The convention's opening night debuted a novelty: the first of a
``rolling roll call'' of state delegate votes cast over several
nights. Cindy McCain, wife of Bush's former campaign rival Sen.
John McCain, ``enthusiastically and unanimously'' began the
process, casting all 30 Arizona delegates for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Parsky, California chair of the Bush campaign, was fired
up and nearly hoarse as he shouted the glories of California during
the roll call vote. He made sure to tout just about every vote-rich
area of the state and went into exuberant, if lengthy, detail of
the Golden State's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, California didn't even cast its ballots. GOP
leaders want Texas to have the honor of putting Bush over the top
later in the convention.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; id  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; E-mail Carla Marinucci at  &LR; marinuccic &LR; sfgate.com &LR;  and Marc
Sandalow at  &LR; sandalowm &LR; nationalpress.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
