<SLUG> BC-FAST50-CORRIDOR-LADN </SLUG>
 
L.A. AREA HAS 21 of 50 TOP_GROWTH FIRMS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Twenty-one 101 Corridor companies are among the
finalists in Deloitte and Touche's annual survey of the 50
fastest-growing firms in Greater Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which covers a region stretching from Santa Barbara
to Riverside County, is dominated by companies along the Ventura
Freeway from Woodland Hills to Camarillo, suggesting the enduring
strength of the corridor's mainstays, said Rohit Shukla, president
and chief executive officer of the Los Angeles Regional Technology
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the overall list, there is no region that is
more dominant on that list than the 101 Corridor. Not even close,''
said Shukla.
</P>
<P>
   Deloitte and Touche will honor the 2000 Los Angeles Technology
Fast 50 companies and rank them by revenue growth over the past
five years at an awards presentation Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify, technology companies need to have been in business
for at least five years, had revenues exceeding $50,000 in 1995 and
$1 million or more in 1999. The professional services firm will
release specific data about each company's growth at the awards
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Insight Corp., Franklin Telecommunications Corp. and
QualityLogic Inc. are new in Deloitte and Touche's seventh annual
survey. Last year Dental Medical Diagnostic Systems of Woodland
Hills was designated as a jump-starter business, less than 5 years
old but growing rapidly. This year, it rated as a Fast 50 company
in the study.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Lee, executive vice president of development at Franklin
Telecommunications, said it was no surprise ``to see a lot of
neighbors on the list,'' referring to the myriad telecommunications
and broadband companies along the corridor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually surprising that we haven't grown more. That's
something we expect to take place in the next six to nine months,''
said Lee, whose company develops voice communications using
Internet protocol for corporate clients.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the list for the first time since 1995 is Thousand
Oaks-based biotech titan Amgen Inc., which reported $3.04 billion
in sales in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always pleased to be recognized for our financial
performance, as well as our discovering and introducing important
new drugs,'' spokesman David Kaye said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 21 of the top 50 businesses were 101 Corridor
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a remarkable tribute to the strength of the area,'' said
Shukla, who co-authored a report released last week concerning the
corridor's future. ``These are companies that have grown through an
era of incredible change, and they still maintained growth rates in
excess of 500 percent.''
</P>
<P>
