<P>
   &UR; GOP CONVENTION _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GOP-ASSESS-NYT _ A political analysis by R.W. Apple Jr. on the
modern convention and how it got there. Ronald Reagan used to
preach what he called the 11th Commandment: Speak no evil of other
Republicans. But now his party, and the other one, too, have gone
him one better, appropriating the physician's Hippocratic oath as
the unspoken guiding principle for their quadrennial gatherings:
First, do no harm. It is that thought, more than anything, that has
drained all of the drama and much of the meaning from modern
political conventions.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-DIARY-NYT _ The convention diary column by Matthew Purdy and
Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-CONGRESS _ With all the attention being paid to George W.
Bush at the convention, Republicans in Congress are relegated to a
back seat. Will this help the party maintain its narrow margin in
the House? By Adam Clymer and B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-FUNDRAISING _ Even though their presence on stage is
minimal, congressional Republicans are raising money by the
buckets-full. By John M. Broder and Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-MESSAGE _ How the message is communicated and how successful
will the GOP be in managing the TV images? By Peter Marks. 1,000
words.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-PROFILES _ Mini-profiles of Monday's convention speakers:
Elizabeth Dole, Patricia Funderburk Ware and Theodore Roosevelt IV.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-BUSH (Dayton, Ohio) _ As George W. Bush pushes on through
another battlefield, he makes few references to Clinton, but his
surrogates don't mince words. By Alison Mitchell. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-CLINTON-IMPEACH _ Less than two years ago this party led the
drive to impeach the president. These days the word is barely
spoken; includes an interview with Bob Livingston. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-INTERNET _ The view from the TV and computer monitor. By
Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PERES (Jerusalem) _ At the moment Monday when the
announcement of the first of the two Knesset votes for Israel's
next president made it all but certain that he had lost the last
major battle of his 60-year political career, Shimon Peres, Noble
laureate, three-time prime minister and one of the most enduring
standard-bearers for Middle East peace, remained proudly, though
unobtrusively, in character. The result, with 60 votes for Moshe
Katsav, 57 votes for Peres, and three blank ballots, brought
groans, slumped shoulders and moist eyes among parliamentarians
backing Peres' bid to become Israel's eighth president. To those
who know him well, the 76-year-old statesman appeared ashen, but in
the simplicity of his manner and words he did nothing, despite the
moment's pain, to bely his reputation for courtliness and courage.
By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DNA-VOLUNTEERS (Undated) _ A California startup company called
DNA Sciences is starting a Web site on Tuesday to recruit people to
donate their DNA to help find genes that cause disease. The
company, which has DNA double helix discoverer James D. Watson as a
director and Netscape founder James H. Clark as an investor, hopes
to get 50,000 to 100,000 people to contribute by appealing to their
altruism. The new effort reflects a major change taking place in
genetics: With the unraveling of the human genome, studies to link
genes to disease are starting to be done on an unprecedented scale,
involving far more people than ever before. In the past, scientists
usually found disease-causing genes by studying a few families or
some isolated village with a high prevalence of the particular
disease. Now, they need to survey many more patients and controls
to find statistical correlations between genes and disease or
between genes and drug effectiveness. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ When Goldman Sachs led a buyout
of AMF Bowling in 1996, some analysts wondered why a silk-stocking
investment bank would risk sullying its image in such a pedestrian
pursuit. But, after four years under Goldman's control, it is AMF's
image that has suffered as the company has racked up losses and its
stock price has sunk to 75 cents a share. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BUYING-ELECTRICITY (Undated) _ There was a time, not so long
ago, when buying electricity was a simple matter. The local utility
was the only game in town, the state set the rates, there was
little to do but sign on the dotted line. These days, not only are
there myriad utilities and upstart energy companies to choose from,
but countless permutations of ways to contract for electricity,
including buying it on the Web. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   LAW-FIRMS-STUDENTS (Undated) _ It seems like an odd recruiting
strategy in a tight labor market: Tell prospective employees that
they can expect to work longer hours and receive fewer perks than
they would at rival companies. But that is precisely what a large
Washington law firm is planning to do as it attempts to redefine
the summer-associate program that virtually all firms use to woo
law students. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POP-LYRICS (Undated) _ In the 1980s and early '90s major music
labels held themselves up as free-speech champions as they fought
against pressure groups attacking specific songs. But today, as the
record-buying audience grows even younger, political pressures
persist, and the music business continues to consolidate as well as
fight battles on the Internet front, those free-speech claims have
decreased and an array of song-lyric review and editing procedures
have become routine. Artists are routinely asked to re-sing lyrics,
edit out particular words and even excise entire songs from albums.
Changes made to songs for radio play are often far more extensive
than the simple editing required to make them conform to federal
regulations. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   MELVILLE-REVIVAL (Undated) _ Almost every year now there are new
books dealing with aspects of Herman Melville and adaptations of
his work on stage, in films or on television. ``Melville is in the
air,'' said Nathaniel Philbrick, who has hit the crest of that wave
with ``In the Heart of the Sea,'' which begins where ``Moby Dick''
ends. By Mel Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-ARTISTS-RANCH (Snowmass Village, Colo.) _ Arts in America:
The Anderson Ranch Arts Center is a bucolic center for potters,
photographers, painters, printmakers, woodworkers, sculptors, art
historians and critics. By Elizabeth Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``A Place in the Country,'' by
Laura Cunningham (Riverhead)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN (Philadelphia) _ Gail Collins observes the GOP
convention's opening day activities.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Thomas L. Friedman conjures up an
imaginary letter from Bill Clinton to Hosni Mubarak, president of
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ARATON-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column on the
Reds. New York fans should understand why Barry Larkin vetoed the
trade to the Mets: nearing the end of his All-Star career, he
deserved the right to stay in the town in which he grew up. But the
non-trade that remains baffling is the one involving Ken Griffey.
He, to paraphrase, could have been playing for a contender. By
Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EYE-SURGERY (Undated) _ Although the Food and Drug
Administration approved the procedure only two years ago, Lasik,
short for laser in-situ keratomileusis, has quickly grown into a $3
billion-a-year industry, with 750,000 Americans expected to choose
the surgery this year. Intended to correct nearsightedness, the
procedure can now treat farsightedness as well. With 1.2 million
American customers expected next year, Lasik is becoming the issue
in a financial turf war between ophthalmologists and optometrists,
between top-dollar surgeons and low-cost, high-volume centers. By
Kenneth Chang. &UR;  &LR;  (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EYE-WITNESS (Undated) _ A personal experience with laser eye
surgery which resulted in better than 20/20 vision. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EYE-DECIDE (Undated) _ Considerations to be made before
going through with this laser eye surgery.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CALIF-ANTS (La Jolla, Calif.) _ Because of a quirk of
evolution and genetics, Argentine ants are taking over California
while forming what scientists believe could be the biggest ant
colony in the world, stretching over 600 miles from San Diego to
San Francisco. The ants in this so-called supercolony are nearly
identical genetically so that different colonies do not fight one
another the way they do in their homeland. As a result they are
using a united family front to win territory from native ants. By
Jon Christensen.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PHYSICS-PARTICLES (Undated) _ Scientists announced that they
have succeeded in producing millions of well-known, if somewhat
obscure, particles called B mesons along with their antimatter
counterparts and plan to compare the decay rates of B's and
anti-B's with a precision that has never before been possible. The
comparison should provide a new measuring stick of one of nature's
most basic symmetries _ or asymmetries. By James Glanz. (1700
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DYSON-PHYSICS (Undated) _ An interview with Dr. Freeman J.
Dyson, the British-born theoretical physicist, astrophysicist and
author of books on scientific matters. He discusses WWII, the NASA
Mars program and his opposition to the newest version of the
Strategic Defense Initiative. By Claudia Dreifus.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GABON-FOREST (Undated) _ Ending a conflict over the fate of
a forest rich in both wood and wildlife, loggers, biologists and
the government of Gabon have agreed to keep bulldozers and chain
saws out of a 1,900 square mile reserve with the highest density of
large mammals ever recorded in a tropical rain forest. By Andrew C.
Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VINES-BUTTERFLIES (Undated) _ Heliconius butterflies have
acquired aggressive survival techniques like feeding on cyanide
carrying passion vines which make them posionous to pedators, and
has caused the plant to develop defensive tactics of its own.
Biologists suspect that this interaction between the vine and the
butterfly over millions of years caused their evolution into
different species. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT4,5) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SETI-TELESCOPE (Undated) _ The world's most powerful radio
telescope designed to listen for signals that may be coming from
civilizations elsewhere in the galaxy will be built at the Hat
Creek Observatory, 290 miles northeast of San Francisco. By John
Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH () _ News and notes on science: Items on the possible
discovery of a new moon orbiting Jupiter, transferred eye tissue
generating an eye on sightless fish. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TONSILS (Undated) _ The FDA has approved an new medical
technique that will shrink tonsils as an alternative to
tonsillectomies. The technique involves inserting tiny needle
electrodes into the tonsils to deliver radio frequency energy and
claims to be less painful and also allows a quicker recovery. But
experts caution that the technique is still highly experimental and
not likely to be widely adopted until more testing is done. By
Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-DRUG (Undated) _ Though just beginning Phase 3 trials
and still somewhat uncertain, cancer specialists are seeing
exceptionally promising results in cancer treatments in trials
involving head and neck cancers _ and a possible drug that attacks
cancer cells but leaves other ones alone. It is based on a
defective virus that can grow only in cancer cells. By Nicholas
Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AMERICN-YOGA (Undated) _ The popularity of New American
Yoga, and its varied Western approaches. And American yoga is
becoming pervasive. By Ann Powers
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: Experts
agree that fibromyalgia, (an ailment characterized by chronic
widespread musculoskeletal pain) is a real illness, and advise
medication to improve sleep, exercise and psychological counseling.
By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
