<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE TRADE FOR MARTIN WON'T HAUNT MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ No Jason Kendall? No Johnny Damon?
</P>
<P>
   No Travis Fryman? No David Segui? No John Vander Wal? No B.J.
Surhoff? No Jeromy Burnitz? No Matt Lawton? No Juan Gonzalez?
</P>
<P>
   No way!
</P>
<P>
   For more than a month, the Mariners fanned the flames of
anticipation, milking the tantalizing trek to the trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we're taking phone calls. Yes, we're here to prove we can
run with the big dogs. Yes, we want to show Alex Rodriguez and
anyone else who matters _ if there is such a category _ that we
mean business.
</P>
<P>
   The laundry list of candidates who could come in and push the
American League West leaders to the postseason and beyond (the
great hope) became an endless roll call of tradeable commodities
from all over the baseball map.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anyone the Mariners didn't consider trading for?
</P>
<P>
   Not if you listened to sports radio or your buddies at the gym.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, to Mickey the softball coach at Gold's Gym on
Aurora:
</P>
<P>
   I know you wanted Damon. Tough luck, huh? You said you'd settle
for Vander Wal, because he was the best pinch hitter available, but
he went and signed a two-year extension in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the clock ran out on general manager Pat Gillick and the
Mariners. In the end _ and we do mean the end, since the deal was
not completed until a half-hour before the deadline _ the Mariners
settled for outfielder Al Martin in a minor deal with the Padres.
The Mariners bid farewell to utility man John Mabry and
minor-league pitcher Tom Davey.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners lost the big-splash contest to the White Sox, who
snagged catcher Charles Johnson and Harold Baines; the Yankees, who
loaded up on Denny Neagle, David Justice and Glenallen Hill; the
Mets, who raked in Mike Bordick, Rick White and Bubba Trammell
without giving up much; the A's, who snared setup man Jim Mecir;
and the Indians, who plucked Segui for duty at first base and DH
and also obtained outfielder Wil Cordero, starters Jason Bere and
Steve Woodard and reliever Bob Wickman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still willing to overpay for the right player,'' Gillick
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mariners did not have to overpay because the right
player did not fall to them, especially after Tigers owner Mike
Ilitch pulled Gonzalez off the market on Sunday after the Mariners
had a deal they liked and were ready to make.
</P>
<P>
   Martin? Along with his speed and left-handed bat, he arrives
with baggage, although the Mariners front office and players swear
that, aside from charges of bigamy and domestic unrest that led to
police intervention this spring, Martin is a good guy.
</P>
<P>
   What else can they say? It's not every day you trade for an
accused bigamist with legal baggage.
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger point to be made about Martin is not his personal
woes, which in this baseball-crazed town will be overlooked if he
does a good job on the field and keeps his nose clean.
</P>
<P>
   How will Martin serve as a role player for the Mariners? Pretty
well, if you listen to Lou Piniella, who basically only wanted a
role player all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have carriers. We have stars who can carry this team. What
we needed was more of a supporting cast. This move improves the
club. Martin is very capable. He has good speed. Good bat. This
will allow me to keep this team nice and fresh,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin will play in left, spelling Rickey Henderson occasionally
_ a situation Henderson can live with, or so he said Monday upon
hearing the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to this point in your career, it's about winning,''
Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners may not have done enough at the trading deadline to
make them a legitimate World Series contender. In a little more
than two months, everyone will know for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope that along the way, the Mariners provide as much
drama as they've supplied during the first four months of the
season when, through pitching and defense _ especially at home _
they have earned the AL West lead.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate verdict on this deadline deal helps take the sting
out of the fact that it was not the big-bang trade everyone was
anticipating:
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners did not make a deal that is going to come back to
haunt them.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, with the Red Sox in town, you could look out at
Safeco Field and see Jason Varitek and Derek Lowe, two players who
have become major pieces in the Boston organization since coming
over from the Mariners at the trading deadline in 1997 in exchange
for Heathcliff Slocumb.
</P>
<P>
   Their presence helps one recall that age-old baseball phrase:
The best trades are the ones never made. For citizens of
Marinerville who thought Gillick should give up the farm _ and the
future _ for Damon; for anyone who figured Gonzalez was the big
bopper to come in and light up the Seattle sky, it is time to sit
back, relax, and take this team as it is.
</P>
<P>
   Good enough to have the third-best record in baseball. Loaded
with pitching _ the lowest ERA at home in all of baseball. Defense
that continues to make Oakland jealous. And now the Mariners have
an extra bat, and added speed to win more of those one-run games.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a waiver-wire miracle, it's going to have to be good
enough.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
