<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-ANALYSIS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL CONTENDERS RETOOL FOR STRETCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sammy Sosa didn't get traded. Neither did Juan
Gonzalez. But it seems like they were just about the only players
who weren't during a trading period as hectic as an Al Martin
family reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the David Justice trade between the New York
Yankees and Cleveland at the end of June and ending with the final
frenzied deals Monday afternoon, more than 100 major and minor
league players were traded, including, apparently, everyone in
Baltimore not named Cal Ripken Jr. The Orioles made five trades
involving 21 players, shipping out seven and adding 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many trades made I can't even keep up,''
Mariners general manager Pat Gillick said.
</P>
<P>
   If Gillick had trouble keeping up, consider poor Ricky Ledee,
who was traded twice in four weeks, moving down the ladder from the
Yankees to Cleveland to last-place Texas. By the time his mail
catches up to him, Ledee could be with the Wisconsin Timber
Rattlers. Or retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees getting Denny Neagle was a pretty big boost for
them,'' Gillick said when asked which teams he thought did well.
``And I like Jim Mecir, who Oakland got.''
</P>
<P>
   Who were the big winners and the poor losers? We'll have a
better idea after the season, but in the meantime, here's a quick
look at the deals made by Seattle and its fellow American League
contenders, and how they may affect this season's races.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET)NEW YORK: The Yankees wrapped up their shopping early,
dealing for Justice, Neagle and Glenallen Hill (and also picking up
Dwight Gooden) in advance of the deadline. Neagle is a huge boost,
giving the Yankees the dependable winner they needed with David
Cone possibly nearing the end of his career and Orlando Hernandez
aching.
</P>
<P>
   Justice (27 home runs, 77 RBIs) and Hill won't help defensively,
but they are productive hitters. Justice has six homers since the
trade and Hill already has helped the Yankees at the plate _ he hit
a game-winning grand slam Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET)CLEVELAND: After much debate as to whether it was wiser
to trade Manny Ramirez and spend the autumn watching the ``Drew
Carey Show'' or fight for their sixth consecutive postseason, the
Indians chose the latter, pulling off three significant deals last
Friday that vaulted them back into the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Having gained Ledee for Justice at the end of June, the Indians
traded him to Texas for former Mariners first baseman David Segui.
They traded Alex Ramirez and Enrique Wilson to Pittsburgh for
outfielder Wil Cordero, then traded Richie Sexson and Paul Rigdon
to Milwaukee for starting pitchers Jason Bere and Steve Wood-ard,
plus reliever Bob Wickman.
</P>
<P>
   Adding Segui, who is having an excellent season, gives Cleveland
perhaps the league's best infield defense, while Bere and Woodward
greatly help a staff that has used a club-record 29 pitchers. If
the Indians can stay healthy, they could find themselves where they
usually are in October _ Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET)TORONTO: The Blue Jays, who desperately needed pitching,
added it by trading for Esteban Loaiza, Steve Trachsel and Mark
Guthrie. Trachsel and Loaiza should help, but they might not be
enough for the Blue Jays, who have a 5.45 staff ERA.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET)CHICAGO: The White Sox already had the best record in
the league, then improved themselves by trading for Charles
Johnson, one of the game's best catchers, as well as designated
hitter Harold Baines, in exchange for catcher Brook Fordyce. With
Cal Eldred hurting, Chicago might need to add a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET)SEATTLE: Acquired for what appears to be the relatively
minor cost of John Mabry and minor league pitcher Tom Davey, Al
Martin gives the Mariners the left-handed bat they wanted, adds
some speed to the roster and gives manager Lou Piniella some
flexibility in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're better with him,'' Gillick said. ``Al Martin is going to
help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but Martin is a poor fielder and drove in only 27 runs
for San Diego. After an arrest this spring, he also brings more
baggage than United Airlines could misplace in a year.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET)OAKLAND: The Athletics gave up a top prospect, Jesus
Colome, but strengthened their bullpen in the short term by adding
the underrated Jim Mecir. He is a bit wild, but allowed only 35
hits in 49.2 innings for Tampa Bay. Is it enough to catch Seattle?
No. Is it enough to stay ahead in the wild-card race? Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET)BOSTON: The Red Sox had used 10 starters this season,
but unfortunately only one is named Pedro Martinez. Of the others,
only Tim Wakefield has an ERA under 5.00. That prompted a
seven-player trade that sent Jeff Frye and others to Colorado for
Rolando Arrojo as well as Mike Lansing (who has a $6.25 million
contract for next year). Arrojo, however, had a 6.04 ERA for the
Rockies and gave up five runs in 6.1 innings in his Boston debut
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Red Sox have the league's best ERA, but are 11th
in runs. Swapping Lansing for Frye and picking up Ed Sprague
doesn't adequately address that concern.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET)ANAHEIM: The Angels needed starting pitching, so
naturally they traded Kent Bottenfield (7-8, 5.71) for Ron Gant,
who has driven in himself more times (20) than his teammates (18).
If they don't re-sign Gant this winter, the Angels will have Adam
Kennedy to show for Jim Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or at jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
