<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-MARLINS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Versatile Lima boosts Astros
</P>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When last seen, Jose Lima was helping the grounds crew
get the field ready for tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   OK, not really. But Lima did just about everything else in the
Astros' 4-2 victory over the Florida Marlins Monday night at Pro
Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lima wasn't as sharp as I've ever seen him, but he did
everything that he needed to do to win,'' manager Larry Dierker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching?
</P>
<P>
   Lima held the Marlins to two runs in 6 innings, winning his
third consecutive decision after losing 13 in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Fielding?
</P>
<P>
   He started two double plays, including a barehanded dandy
earmarked for ESPN's Plays of the Week.
</P>
<P>
   Offense?
</P>
<P>
   He hit his first double in almost two years and scored what
proved to be the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   It was an all-around good day for the Astros' resident showman,
who tipped his hat to the sparse crowd of 8,044 that booed him as
he left the game in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (booing) is not going to upset me,'' Lima said. ``I'm a
showman when I'm out there. I like to entertain the fans. I like it
when they boo; all that does is fire me up.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to everything he's been doing between the lines,
Lima is doubling as somewhat of a psychic off the field. He vowed
not to lose another game the rest of the season _ and is making
good on that promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure people are saying, `There goes Lima talking trash
again,''' Lima said. ``But I said I was going to win 15 games in
1998, and I won 16. I said I was going to win 20 games last year
and I won 21. It's still Lima Time, no matter what. I can still
finish with 11 or 12 wins, and I'd be a happy camper.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio drove in three of the Astros' four runs, while
relievers Marc Valdes and Octavio Dotel each pitched 1 scoreless
innings to secure the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel, who struck out three of the four batters he faced, earned
his third save and extended his scoreless innings streak to 10 in
his 10th relief appearance of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins took an early lead on Preston Wilson's RBI single in
the first but Lima shut them out over the next five innings, with a
little help from the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Richard Hidalgo took away three runs from the
Marlins in the fourth inning alone. He gunned down Mike Lowell, who
ill-advisedly tried to score from second on Andy Fox's single.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo then chased down Ramon Castro's blast to center, which
almost certainly would have scored two runners, who could only
watch in amazement as Hidalgo ended the inning with a flair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense is a big part of the game,'' Hidalgo said. ``On the
first play, I was surprised he tried to score. I was playing in a
little, I got to the ball quickly and made a good throw. On the
other play, I just ran as hard as I could to catch the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio's eighth home run _ a solo shot over the left-center
field wall _ tied the score in the third. The home run snapped a
0-for-11 drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swung the bat well in Atlanta but I didn't have anything to
show for,'' Biggio said. ``Hitting is all confidence. You just try
to get to a point where you feel comfortable, and you go from
there. I've felt better over the last month.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlins starter A.J. Burnett retired eight of the 10 batters he
faced after Biggio's home run before creating trouble for himself
by walking Lance Berkman and Moises Alou to lead off the sixth.
That was enough to get Marlins manager John Boles out of the dugout
and reliever Ricky Bones into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Bones retired all three batters he faced in the sixth, but
Berkman was able to score on Tony Eusebio's ground ball to
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Further proving it was his day, Lima doubled to lead off the
seventh and scored on Biggio's sacrifice fly. It's was Lima's fifth
hit in 40 at-bats this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros added an insurance run in the ninth when Glen Barker
drew a one-out walk, stole second, advanced to third on a grounder
and scored on Biggio's infield single.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gave Dotel a margin of error, but he didn't need it,''
Dierker said. ``Barker was a big part of our team last year doing
just that. He helped us win a lot of games with his speed.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
