<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9092 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-TRADES-HNS &LR;      08-01 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TRADES </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deadline brings trading frenzy
</P>
<P>
   By RICHARD JUSTICE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder B.J. Surhoff and first baseman Will Clark were the
biggest names switching teams on Monday as baseball's contenders
raced to the 3 p.m. trading deadline with a final flurry of deals.
</P>
<P>
   Ten trades were made in all, with the Atlanta Braves pulling off
perhaps the most significant acquisition by obtaining Surhoff, a
widely respected veteran and a first-rate lefthanded hitter, from
the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals also made an impact move by obtaining
Clark from the Orioles in a deal that suggests Mark McGwire's knee
injury may keep him sidelined indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielders Rondell White, Tom Goodwin, Todd Hollandsworth and
Henry Rodriguez were among the other players who changed teams
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Teams can still make trades despite the passing of the deadline,
but only players who have cleared waivers can be moved. Some
general managers routinely file waiver claims on players to block
deals in the final weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some years, when the trade deadline passes with almost no
one of significance changing teams, the week leading up to this
summer's deadline was one of the busiest in history as contenders
loaded up for a run at a championship and losers cut their payrolls
to prepare for next season.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Yankees, Braves, Diamondbacks and Mariners _
four first-place teams _ appear to have helped themselves the most.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were in contention for Surhoff right up until
Orioles owner Peter Angelos ordered his baseball staff to do
nothing to help Yankees owner George Steinbrenner win a third
straight World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees had already done their work, acquiring David
Justice and Glenallen Hill for their offense, Jose Vizcaino for
their infield defense and Denny Neagle for the rotation in the four
weeks before the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very volatile market,'' Yankees general manager Brian
Cashman said. ``It's not easy trying to line up matches with
people, whether it's payroll, talent or a whole lot of other
issues. Some big names got floated out there. But it's not easy to
get to `yes.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable with the team we have. That's why we were able
to walk away and say no.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks got the best available pitcher by acquiring
Curt Schilling from the Phillies, and the Mariners got the
lefthanded bat they need by getting outfielder Al Martin from the
Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every other contender made at least one move, but some
blockbuster deals that had been discussed never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Despite hours of conversation involving several teams, the
Tigers were unable to trade Juan Gonzalez, and the Cubs still have
Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff believed he had survived the trading deadline until
learning that the Orioles had sent him to the Braves minutes before
the deadline. One of the most respected players in the game,
Surhoff tearfully said goodbye to the Orioles as he prepared to
leave for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles dismantled a losing team in a stunning 72-hour
period by trading reliever Mike Timlin and Clark to the Cardinals
in separate deals, designated hitter Harold Baines and catcher
Charles Johnson to the White Sox, shortstop Mike Bordick to the
Mets, and, finally, Surhoff and reliever Gabe Molina to Atlanta for
outfielder Trenidad Hubbard and two minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff's work ethic and professionalism should be a good fit in
an Atlanta clubhouse that has several other players like him. He
was hitting .293 at the time of the trade with 13 home runs and 57
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   He also has played in 427 consecutive games, the longest active
iron-man streak.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite a trade that moved him from a fourth-place team
to one that's on its way to a ninth straight division championship,
Surhoff, 35, found it hard to say goodbye to Baltimore, where he
was finishing his fifth season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wouldn't have expected it to happen the way it
happened,'' he said. ``It's not that I don't want to play in
Atlanta. I'm sure I'm going into a great situation, and I know it's
going to work out. I just thought I was going to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Braves manager Bobby Cox: ``He's really team-oriented. He's
high-quality and a still-good ballplayer at his age.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles sent Clark to the Cardinals for third base prospect
Jose Leon. Clark will play first base in place of McGwire, who has
been on the disabled list since July 6 with pain in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals still lead the National League Central by four
games, but they have lost 13 of 21 since McGwire left the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some uncertainty about Mark,'' Cardinals manager Tony
La Russa said. ``We think he's got a chance to come back, but in
the meantime, Will Clark's a winning type of veteran. He should
help us. That's a heck of a coup for us. I hope Mark comes back,
and then we can work them both in there together. But right now, it
really helps us.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark no longer hits with power, but he was batting .301 with
nine home runs and 28 RBIs in 79 games.
</P>
<P>
   In other Monday deals, the Toronto Blue Jays acquired pitchers
Steve Trachsel and Mark Guthrie from Tampa Bay for prospects; the
Los Angeles Dodgers got Goodwin from the Colorado Rockies for
Hollandsworth; and the Cubs continued to shuffle their deck by
getting White from Montreal for pitcher Scott Downs and sending
Rodriguez to the Florida Marlins for two minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
