<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER FLOPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maven of rant imbecility and barnyard humor savored by
IQ-challenged persons with Howard Stern scriptures lodged in their
vacuous heads, Dennis Miller made his much-ballyhooed sportscasting
debut Monday night during the San Francisco-New England telecast.
</P>
<P>
   Ho hum!
</P>
<P>
   Or better yet, humbug!
</P>
<P>
   Nothing against Dennis Mill- er, reigning Pinup Boy for the
dumbing down of America and alleged comedian who holds the unique
distinction of never having induced a laugh out of me.
</P>
<P>
   But I'd rather do an investigative piece on the social
significance of Dennis Rodman's tattoos, or put together a
photographic montage of Georgia Frontiere's Top 10 fa &QL; 
- celifts than I would watching a 49er-Patriot exhibition match.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, please, I have more important things to do with my
Monday evenings than to waste them listening to some
nepotistic-enhanced brother of a bigshot Hollywood agent bore me
into somnolence with his mindless musings, or watching a gridiron
exercise so meaningless that the teams' starters aren't allowed to
play beyond a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And, anyway, I find it difficult enough now to pay attention to
the NFL when the games are played for real, much less in the middle
of the summer when they aren't.
</P>
<P>
   The scandalous absurdity of the sprawling Southern California
basin, with the second largest city in America, Los Angeles, within
its confines, being without an NFL franchise continues to leave me
angered, saddened and increasingly indifferent to professional
football.
</P>
<P>
   How could we here in L.A., a sun-splashed metropolis of
millions, indisputably the entertainment capital of the planet, a
proven athletic mecca, one of the world's great tourist
destinations, enter a new millennium without representation in the
NFL?
</P>
<P>
   How could we here in L.A., with so many wealthy hustlers whose
vanities are larger than their net worth, with two teams in major
league baseball, the NHL, the NBA and even the NFL as recently as
1994, still not have an NFL franchise in its midst?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the NFL, an acronym for National Football League, has
become a shameless misnomer.
</P>
<P>
   How could this confederation of money-obsessed owners be
considered a national alignment without the presence of L.A. in it?
</P>
<P>
   It can't, of course, and, as every year passes without an NFL
franchise here, I find myself drifting farther away from the
league, not caring remotely as much about the games and the players
as I once did when the Rams and Raiders were in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I'll fork over $150 again to take DirectTV's NFL Ticket, but
that's only because my job forces me to pay at least peripheral
attention to a sport that still gets far higher TV ratings than any
other in this country.
</P>
<P>
   But I, like I'm sure a lot of other Southern Californians, find
my interest in the NFL waning ever more ominously, as it continues
to shut this venue out of its cozy little group for no other
discernible reason than appalling greed.
</P>
<P>
   L.A.'s only immediate hope?
</P>
<P>
   Natch, Al Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Please, don't laugh, or launch into a monologue of obscenities,
but the Raiders' owner deeply regrets his decision to return to
Oakland, even is going to trial next February against the city to
try to get out of the long-term stadium lease he signed with it.
</P>
<P>
   Will Al Davis win?
</P>
<P>
   He does have a lengthy history of jurisprudence success, and
it's known the Oakland mayor, Jerry Brown, not exactly a passionate
athletic patron, would gladly settle and let the Raiders depart if
he thought the team was headed for a court room victory that could
result in even more money being drained from the deplet &QL; 
- ed Oakland city coffers.
</P>
<P>
   I'd certainly welcome Al Davis and the Raiders back warmly,
inasmuch as the only professional football we have now in L.A. is a
club-level team that plays at the Staples Center and always scores
more points than Shaquille O'Neal and another new entry that soon
will perform at the Coliseum in a league created by wrestling
impresario Vince McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon is a shrewd guy with a vivid imagination, but you know
anything he's involved with will have about as much legitimacy as
Dennis Miller's football knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Davis is ever to bring his Raiders back to L.A.,
he will have to be given some sort of guarantee that a new stadium
will be erected for him and that he won't have to keep his team
indefinitely in that outmoded dump known as the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Pharaohs were able to build their pyramids faster than it takes
for L.A. to build a foot &QL; 
- ball stadium, and, even if Davis wins his latest legal suit,
there is no guarantee he will bring his team back to a city that
broke promises with him for 13 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guarantee any NFL team soon will be ensconced in
L.A., even though a year ago at this time fellows named Ed Roski,
Eli Broad, Ron Burkle and Michael Ovitz were loudly assuring us
that an NFL expansion team was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   You might recall that a $700 million bid by Houston's Bob McNair
reduced these L.A. blowhards to silence, which perhaps was the only
nice development that came out of the NFL's decision last October
to keep L.A. from its privileged domain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 0232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
