r s BC-BBA-MARINERS-MARTIN-S     08-01 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-MARTIN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS PICK UP MARTIN FROM SAN DIEGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the end, the Mariners didn't get the breakout deal
they'd been looking for.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Seattle didn't break the bank to pick up
left-handed hitting outfielder Al Martin from the San Diego Padres.
Martin, who will join the Mariners for Tuesday night's game against
Boston, came at the cost of outfielder/third baseman John Mabry and
minor league pitcher Tom Davey.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, hitting .306 with 11 home runs and 27 RBIs, is a good
addition to the Mariner mix, in that he's an experienced
left-handed hitter with above-average speed. Mabry was hitting .243
with one home run and seven RBIs; Davey was 8-6 with a 4.61 ERA for
Class AAA Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   Martin joins an outfield that is seriously overcrowded. He will
start some in left field in place of Rickey Henderson and in right
field in place of Jay Buhner. Of course, Stan Javier already does
that, so there are four men for two spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been resting our outfielders all along, and this move
adds to our ability to do that,'' manager Lou Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   How much rest is enough? Henderson, for one, wasn't sure. He's
played about five days out of seven since coming to the Mariners
from the Mets in May, and he's been productive despite a .254
batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if this is good or bad,'' Henderson said. ``I
know Al Martin is a good, little contact hitter. I don't know how
much rest I need. I don't make those decisions. I used to complain,
but nowadays I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella, the man who does make those decisions, said he hasn't
come to any resolution about how he's going to handle his surplus
of outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be plenty of playing time for everybody,''
Piniella said, a statement that could be challenged by some of the
players involved. On the other hand, as Javier said before the
trade was finalized, ``You want to play, but you also want to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners entered their game against Boston Monday night with
a 61-43 record and four-game lead in the AL West. So while they may
have coveted Juan Gonzalez or Manny Ramirez _ trades that would
have taken at least a couple of front-line players _ the Mariners
put together a less high-level deal that kept from tearing at the
fabric of their 25-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   Martin had been an object of desire for the Mariners all the way
back in spring training. At the time, he was with Pittsburgh, but
he wanted to be closer to his Scottsdale, Ariz., home. The Pirates
entertained an offer from the Mariners, but traded Martin to San
Diego instead.
</P>
<P>
   It was a trade that Martin wanted, but it came just before the
low point of his career and personal life, which wound up being
splashed across front pages and featured in news broadcasts in
March and April. In March, Martin was charged with assault,
physical injury and threatening or intimidating. His wife, Shawn
Haggerty-Martin, was charged with assault and domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   But it turned out that Haggerty-Martin was Martin's second wife,
the couple having been married in 1998 in Las Vegas. Martin and his
first wife, Cathy, have remained together. Mariners general manager
Pat Gillick first talked to Cathy Martin, not Al, when he called
the Martin household Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem happy,'' Gillick said. ``She said they were both
excited about the move.''
</P>
<P>
   And the general manager said they'd checked on ``what kind of
person he is'' before agreeing to the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some issues there,'' Gillick said. ``But we think
this (the battery charges) will be cleared up in the near future.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Martin's playing future, it's tied to the Mariners
through 2001. When the Padres acquired him, one condition of the
trade was that his contract option for 2001 at $5 million would be
picked up immediately, and it was. At the same time, an option for
2002 was eliminated. He's making $1.75 million this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a quality player, a hard-nosed player,'' Gillick said.
``He gives us an added dimension on the field, and I think he'll
fit in well.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
