<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-LEWIS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS' HANDS TIED UNTIL LEWIS RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After a long July, the Sonics hope the first week of
August is a short one.
</P>
<P>
   But the process of signing free agents, which begins today, will
largely depend on small forward Rashard Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old's return to Seattle is a formality, based on his
verbal commitment to the team last week. However, the deal Lewis
settles on has not yet been ironed out Either way, Lewis contract
will have a direct affect on how the Sonics proceed in free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has the option of signing a contract extending two or more
seasons that starts at about $3.9 million, or he can sign a
one-year deal for the Sonics' mid-level exception ($2.25 million).
Using the mid-level exception is the only way for Lewis to secure a
two-year deal with an opt-out clause. The major benefit for Lewis
taking the $2.25 million is that he can make himself eligible for a
maximum contract after next season.
</P>
<P>
   If he does that, the Sonics would have only a $1.2 million
exception to lure a free-agent post player.
</P>
<P>
   Confused?
</P>
<P>
   That would describe how several prospects feel, because the
Sonics have had only preliminary talks with free agents. Who they
bring in, and that player's contract terms, can be decided only
after Lewis signs his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has said he will return to Seattle sometime this week to
sign. It is believed that he is leaning toward accepting at least a
two-year deal, worth about $8.2 million. Such a deal, which could
be struck as soon as today, would make Lewis eligible for a ``Larry
Bird'' contract in 2002: a maximum seven-year pact starting at $9
million per year. The Sonics, operating over the $35.5 million
salary cap, can use their mid-level and $1.2 million exceptions to
bolster the frontcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll lay out all of the options to him when he gets here,''
Sonics president Wally Walker said last week. ``Then, he'll just
have to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Walker has had discussion with representatives for
free-agent forwards and centers, he hasn't been able to promise the
mid-level exception. The situation is not terribly alarming for the
Sonics, considering the quality of free agents available.
</P>
<P>
   After the first tier (Tim Duncan, Grant Hill, Tracy McGrady) and
second level (Lewis, Eddie Jones), there is a significant drop-off.
The Sonics will dangle money, hoping to entice the likes of Danny
Fortson (Boston), Brad Miller (Charlotte), Jahidi White
(Washington), Corie Blount (Phoenix), and Ben Wallace and Chucky
Atkins (Orlando).
</P>
<P>
   Veterans Oliver Miller (Phoenix), Kurt Thomas (New York), Sam
Perkins (Indiana) and Danny Manning (Milwaukee) also are available.
</P>
<P>
   Walker has been in contact with Perkins and Manning. Perkins, a
former Sonic, likely will re-sign with Indiana for more than the
$2.25 million exception. There is mild interest in Manning, whose
agent phoned the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has more interest in Fortson, a strong, 6-foot-8
rebounder who the Sonics tried to trade for last season. The Sonics
like White, a 6-9 banger and restricted free agent, meaning the
Wizards have the right to match offers.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a significant trade, dont expect the Sonics to make much
of a splash in the free-agent waters.
</P>
<P>
   Their No. 1 priority is re-signing Lewis. It is unlikely that
the team will look to move disappointing forward Vin Baker, who has
impressed the coaching staff with his summer workouts. Forget trade
rumors involving Gary Payton, who is guaranteed to return. Walker
said recently that there is ``nothing on the front burner'' in
terms of trades.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are still considering trade options; there just won't
be any deals of consequence.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Lewis, Walker's in-house business concerns center
Jelani McCoy and guard Vernon Maxwell.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy became a free agent when he exercised an opt-out clause in
June, but the Sonics are expected to re-sign the second-year player
to a deal starting at $1.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell's status is uncertain. Walker contacted Maxwells agent,
Dwight Manley, and told him of the team's intent to explore all
options. While the Sonics mull trading Maxwell, whose relationship
with Payton and coach Paul Westphal became rocky last season,
neither side has ruled out his return.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
