<HEADER>
A9096 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     08-01 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFC South best for Houston's new franchise
</P>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the hard part is over. We're back in the NFL, and
everything from here on out is gravy. Just the same, considering
the kind of bucks Bob McNair had to spend to accomplish this on the
city's behalf, his voice deserves to be heard on the matter of
realignment and Houston's place in it.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, we've got our cake. And now we want to eat it, too. Is
that so bad?
</P>
<P>
   If McNair were king, his NFL team would play in a division
consisting of the Titans, the Cowboys and, for comic relief, the
Saints. But although he's a fine fellow and possesses a regal
carriage, Bob isn't king. Hence, such an alignment is a no-go.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas shall forever remain an NFC East team, and there is no
room in the inn there for us. We can accept this, as long as the
new scheduling scheme that's being bandied about ensures regular
collisions between Texas' teams.
</P>
<P>
   An acceptable second choice, however, absolutely, positively
must guarantee twice-annual bloodlettings against the Titans, for
reasons that hardly need explaining. Of course, the league might
then also feel compelled to keep together the new Browns and the
Ravens nee Browns on the same grounds, and that's where things
start getting complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore, Cleveland, Houston and Tennessee could, in fact,
constitute a perfectly suitable division if the NFL weren't trying
to reorganize itself along loose geographic lines (save for
800-pound gorillas Dallas and Miami) and name its eight foursomes
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   But a solution is simply arrived at. Stick the Browns and Ravens
in the AFC Central with the Steelers and Bengals, never mind how
the Browns organization apparently has zero interest in stoking a
rivalry with Cleveland's vagabond exes. Or that Ravens owner Art
Modell won't push for it either. The bounty on his head in
Cleveland makes returning for games an unpleasant proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Houston's choices are these: (1) join Cincinnati,
Pittsburgh and Cleveland in a retro AFC Central, (2) team with
Indianapolis, Jacksonville and Tennessee in the AFC South, or (3)
join Jacksonville, Tennessee and Baltimore in a less geographically
challenged AFC South.
</P>
<P>
   McNair says he much prefers No. 1, citing all those wonderful
old rivalries from bygone Oilers days, but we suspect his reasoning
is more pragmatic than sentimental. If you're playing the
percentages, and horseman Bob is wont to, Houston's chances of
fast-tracking to competitiveness are definitely greater against the
tired old AFC Central faces, none of which save for Cleveland
figures to be particularly inclined to pursue excellence
aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers remain doggedly old-school under Dan Rooney, and
the Bengals will always be second-class cats unless Mike Brown
suddenly changes his cheapskate spots, er, stripes. The Browns,
meanwhile, will have just a three-season head start on Houston's
fledgling franchise, but Carmen Policy is a proven master of
finessing the salary cap and courting free agents. He dearly loves
spending the boss' money.
</P>
<P>
   McNair, for his part, is expected to have loose purse strings,
so general manager Charley Casserly wouldn't need to fear Carmen's
extravagant policies.
</P>
<P>
   In the first aforementioned AFC South, Bob and Charley would
have to burn bundles of cash to catch up with everyone. As long as
Bud Adams keeps selling out his Nashville digs, his bottom-line
reputation of yore won't be apropos, and both the Colts and Jaguars
are young and immensely gifted.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee-Jacksonville already generates genuine hateful
feelings between the teams and the not-dissimilar upstart cities
they represent, and Tennessee-Indianapolis is intense stuff, too,
because of Peyton Manning's storied college tenure as a Vol in the
Volunteer State. Tennessee-Houston will be at least as heated a
matchup, once Houston gains a measure of equal footing in terms of
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, in turn, feels no special affinity, good or bad, for
either Cleveland or Cincinnati despite the 27 years of AFC Central
competition. There were occasional isolated big games amid
countless forgettable ones. Even Pittsburgh-Houston was truly
special only during the Luv Ya Blue-Steel Curtain era. We never
came to hate Pittsburghers, or they us.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the AFC South _ preferably the Indy version because of
Manning's star power _ seems the more demanding option at the
outset, but the gratification gleaned from butting helmets with
that crowd will enhance Houston's encore NFL experience from the
get-go.
</P>
<P>
   Come on, Bob. Forget the past. Well, except the Oilers. Let's
bring them back to Houston every year, even if they're disguised as
Titans.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
