<HEADER>
A9097 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-MNF-MILLER-HNS &LR;      08-01 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MNF-MILLER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miller hits, misses with barbs in `Monday Night Football' debut
</P>
<P>
   By DAVID BARRON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   For Don Meredith, it was, ``Turn out the lights; the party's
over.''
</P>
<P>
   For Dennis Miller on Monday night, it was, ``Start blow-drying
Teddy Koppel's hair, 'cause this one's done.''
</P>
<P>
   And thus ended the first Monday Night Football broadcast of the
Miller regime.
</P>
<P>
   The comedian's debut as a network football announcer came in an
otherwise forgettable 20-0 NFL exhibition game won by the New
England Patriots over the San Francisco 49ers _ who were so bad,
Miller noted, that they should be called the 47ers _ at Canton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ABC doesn't expect blockbuster ratings for the game, since it
began at 4 p.m. on the West Coast. It served primarily as a
shakedown cruise for Miller and his new stablemates _ longtime MNF
host Al Michaels and Hall of Fame quarterback Dan Fouts in the
booth, and Hall of Fame running back Eric Dickerson and reporter
Melissa Stark on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Their boss, Don Ohlmeyer, the one-time MNF producer who was
brought in by ABC Sports president Howard Katz to overhaul the show
after five years of declining ratings, was pleased with his crew's
first performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some rough spots, but overall it was a good start,''
Ohlmeyer said. ``I was really pleased with the announcers for the
first game. I thought Eric and Melissa had a nice debut, and the
trio in the booth has the chance to be something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's performance, as might be expected of a broadcast
rookie, was somewhere between the Patriots' 20 and the 49ers' zero.
</P>
<P>
   He did show a few flashes of the ``nerd's knowledge'' he
professes to have of football. Perhaps the most extreme example
came after Patriots quarterback Michael Bishop ran the option for a
touchdown. Miller brought up the name of Jack Mildren, the former
Abilene Cooper quarterback who later became Oklahoma's master of
the wishbone.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller also mixed in so many one-liners that ABC might need
to bring in Jenna Elfman, who played drums with Bob Dylan on an
episode of Dharma and Greg, to provide rim shots.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them worked. When 49ers rookie receiver Eric Chew
fumbled, Miller said simply, ``Chew regurgitated.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of them didn't. In a painfully strained reference to the
site of the game, he said, ``You know, you can't get any good
Cantonese food in this town.''
</P>
<P>
   Some were in between. In an effort to assure viewers that ABC,
the company that is paying him millions, is actually a cheapskate,
he said, ``Believe me, the people on (the CBS reality show)
Survivor have a more generous per diem than we do. I had to buy a
BLT with fur pelts.''
</P>
<P>
   When the regular season begins, Monday Night Football will
dovetail into local news followed by Nightline _ thus the reference
to Koppel, the latter show's host. This week, however, ABC asked
the NFL to move the kickoff of the Patriots-49ers game to 6 p.m.
CDT so it could be followed by coverage of the Republican National
Convention from Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   With the GOP convention under way, Miller couldn't resist a
couple of political one-liners. ``Now there's a couple of 4-12
teams,'' he said after a promo for ABC's convention coverage. Of
Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee, he
said, ``I don't want to say that Gore lacks charisma, but his
personalized license plate is a random series of numbers and
letters.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller also plunged full-bore into the obscure references that
are so much a part of his comedy act. Examples included Italian
film director Sergio Leone, the NAFTA treaty, actor Jack Lord,
first baseman Bill Buckner, Lot the nephew of Abraham (as part of a
twisted reference to Hall of Fame defensive back Ronnie Lott), Fox
Sports News anchor Keith Olbermann, and, near the end of the
broadcast, the Big Giant Head of sports television critics, Rudy
Martzke of USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   However, Miller never uttered the word golly, which, as he has
told viewers on HBO and NBC in recent weeks, is shorthand for a
four-letter word you can't use on broadcast television.
</P>
<P>
   He was only mildly scatological, noting ABC's use of a new
camera attached to the cap of the field umpire and saying, ``I
think that's the new cup cam they've brought in. That's our next
innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   And while sarcastic, Miller certainly wasn't cynical. He
referred several times to the stadium noise and the intensity of
the hitting on the field that can't be grasped by a fan watching
the game on television, and he sounded positively giddy as the game
came to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't this so much fun?'' he said with a giggle. ``I can't
believe I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
