<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-ARE-BOSS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `DEMOCRATIC FAMILY' _ WHERE KIDS MAKE BIG DECISIONS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 525-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By CHERRY NORTON  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The days when father's word was law have
disappeared, with children as young as eight now having a big say
in many British households.
</P>
<P>
   Research published Monday shows the Victorian approach to
child-rearing, where children were seen and not heard, has
collapsed over the past 30 years with the birth of the new
``democratic family.''
</P>
<P>
   The study of 950 families shows that 78 percent of British
parents consult their offspring on important decisions such as
moving house or where to go on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that the family is becoming more democratic,''
said Tim Harrison, of Abbey National, which commissioned the study.
``Children have greater power and influence than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine out of 10 children dictate the choice of the evening meal
at home, and 65 percent help to choose the family's vacation
destination. Weekend and leisure plans were also joint decisions
with 84 percent of families deciding what to do and where to go
together.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to moving house, 42 percent of parents talk to
their children about it before agreeing to put the house on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Willmott, of the Future Foundation, who conducted the
study, said: ``It seems parents not only see involving children in
decisions from the outset as a route to family harmony but
recognize that their children can actually add value to big family
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters of the parents interviewed said the increased
communication had led to more open and honest relationships with
their children then they enjoyed with their own parents.
</P>
<P>
   Mary MacLeod, chief executive of the National Family and
Parenting Institute, which advises the Government on family policy,
said: ``Overall it is a good thing for young people as it enables
them to take more responsibility and be included. It also makes
them more mature and can really boost their confidence and
self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult when big decisions have to be made, like who
to live with when parents separate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decisions like this can be too much emotional responsibility
for many young people and parents should then take the
responsibility,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But family psychologists sounded a cautious note. They said that
although it could be beneficial for children to play a part in
decisions at home, making them more mature and teaching them how to
be good citizens, family democracy was a ``double-edged sword.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Lewis, professor of psychology at Lancaster University,
said: ``Children should be included in the discussions but there
are times when they need their parents to take responsibility for
big decisions which affect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people think that including the kids in decisions makes
for happy families but that is not necessarily the result for all
members of the household.''
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary findings from research being done by Professor Lewis
on family decision-making shows that some parents find involving
their children very difficult as they lose both power and authority
within the household.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, children and adolescents find some decisions
too stressful and expect their parents to take responsibility for
their welfare. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 525-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
