<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 03:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9140 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-BUSH-ASSESS-ECONOMIST     08-01 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ASSESS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH GETS HIS CHANCE TO SHOW HE'S `READY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors - This is cover story)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   This has been something of a rollercoaster year for George W.
Bush. Last autumn, his nomination as the Republican presidential
candidate seemed inevitable: the governor of Texas boasted a decent
record, a likeable character, a well-known name, a new slogan
(''compassionate conservatism'') and the most formidable money
machine modern politics has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the McCain insurgency; by February Bush had quashed
the turbulent senator, but only by spending virtually all his
$70-million treasure trove and losing a good deal of both his
likeability and his moderateness. A snarling right-winger, he won
his party's nomination, but had apparently handed the November
election to Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Republican convention beckoning next week in
Philadelphia, Bush has repainted himself once again. The
likeability is back; so is much of the moderation; and he has added
considerably more depth to the portrait.
</P>
<P>
   For the past four months, the supposedly lightweight Bush has
dominated the presidential campaign, unfurling policy after policy
and surrounding himself with serious-looking advisers; meanwhile,
Gore, the supposed policy wonk, has seemed stuck in a series of
tired relaunches.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is slightly ahead in the polls; and unless something
terrible happens at what promises to be a heavily overscripted
convention, he can expect to increase his lead.
</P>
<P>
   Where does this leave Bush? In with a real chance. Of course,
Gore will get his own post-nomination bounce in the polls after the
Democratic convention later in August. When it matters, in
November, the vice president may have the edge: Gore has the
incumbent's benefit of a remarkably strong economy (so far) and he
is an impressively brutal debater, whereas Bush's showing against
McCain was dismal.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how endearing Bush seems at the podium next Thursday
night, the appeal of his new self-portrait will not really be
tested until his televised contests with Gore in October.
</P>
<P>
   With that caveat, there is still plenty to be said _ much of it
good _ about the Bush who comes to Philadelphia. Those who worry
about him tend to bring up two charges. They are the ones that
dogged the rise to the presidency of another western conservative
governor, Ronald Reagan. Bush is said to be too extreme and lacking
the intellectual capacity to be president. Those charges ring
hollow.
</P>
<P>
   On some counts, Bush does seem too conservative. He has been a
strong opponent of gun control, something that will deservedly do
him few favors with women voters. Texas also has a poor
environmental record, which Gore will blame, not altogether
unfairly, on Bush's ties to the energy industry.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite the popularity of the death penalty in the United
States, Bush's record as a serial executioner may come back to
haunt him, particularly if it becomes clear that some innocent
people have been executed.
</P>
<P>
   Probably none of these issues will cost Bush the election. The
previous Republican candidate, Bob Dole, lost his way with
independent voters, the ``soccer moms'' of lore, by seeming
socially illiberal yet fiscally profligate. On the key social issue
of abortion, Bush may have done just enough to win himself a pass.
Officially, he has stuck to the anti-abortion record of the
Christian right; but there have been enough nods and winks to guess
that Bush, like his father, would not strive hard to outlaw it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on taxes, the economy is helping. Like Dole, Bush put
forward a big tax cut. The new predictions for future budget
surpluses have not only made that seem a bit less reckless;
crucially, they have encouraged Gore to offer a big cut of his own.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, Bush can claim to be a genuine reformer in
the vital matter of education. It would be better if he openly
campaigned for vouchers; but he is a far keener proponent of
structural reform in the public-school system than Gore, who is
firmly on the side of the teachers' unions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also been much braver about Social Security: Unlike
Gore, he would allow people to invest some of their public pension
in the stockmarket. Compassionate conservatism also introduces
fresh ideas about making more use of the private sector and
churches in helping America's poor.
</P>
<P>
   In foreign policy, too, Bush deserves some credit. He has been
more solid than Gore on free trade. There are question marks about
his grip of the missile-defense debate, and more generally of basic
facts about the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   But the man who once called Greeks ``Grecians'' has tried to
bone up on the issues and to provide himself with competent
advisers. A Bush administration with Richard Cheney as vice
president and perhaps Colin Powell as secretary of state would be a
force to be reckoned with abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Take these policies, add Bush's long record of working together
with the Democrats in Texas and his Reaganesque record of picking
good advisers, and he surely has a plausible candidacy. Of course,
one can wish for more _ much more.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike McCain, Bush will not shake up Washington's lamentable
system of money politics. On the other hand, there is precious
little hope of Gore doing so either. Bush may not be the perfect
candidate; but now his challenge is merely to prove he is a better
one than the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Purely in terms of the policies, Bush is certainly ready for
that comparison. But the next three months will probably be even
more about character: not just intellect, but temperament. The
American people, most of whom have paid scant attention to the
events so far, will have to get used to Bush, and to trust him.
</P>
<P>
   This was the part of the test that that other supposedly
ignorant western governor, Reagan, passed so triumphantly 20 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans may decide whether Bush is ``ready'' in this
sense only when they come to pull the lever on Nov. 7. Philadelphia
offers his first real chance to convince them that he is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
