<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 03:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9141 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-CHENEY-ASSESS-ECONOMI     08-01 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-ASSESS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY ADDS LITTLE TO THE TICKET AND DETRACTS LESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors - This is ``Lexington'' column)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When George W. Bush first described the running mate he wanted,
he said his choice would be ``electrifying.'' It ``would make your
eyes light up.''
</P>
<P>
   That was when his campaign wanted a bright new face _ someone
who would reshape the political landscape and epitomize the
generational change by moving the Republican Party away from those
ghastly people in Congress. Evidently Bush has now had second
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney is a rock-solid candidate, with all the charisma of
that inorganic substance. He fulfills the Hippocratic requirements
of a vice president (''First, do no harm''). He will not
contradict, embarrass or outshine Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Vice presidents are sometimes required to be the campaign's
attack dog. Cheney is easy-going, civil and patient, more like a
guide dog for the blind than the Hound of the Baskervilles.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, those may prove useful qualities. Cheney has
managed to play influential roles in Washington for a quarter of a
century _ most recently as defense secretary for Bush's father and
before that as No.2 in the Republican Party's hierarchy in the
House _ without making too many enemies in his own party (both
wings of which applauded this week's choice) or even among
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In picking his running mate, it was the cautious side of Bush's
personality that came to the fore.
</P>
<P>
   Caution has limitations as well as merits. One of Cheney's
advantages is that he seems to be no slash-and-burn Republican, no
Newt Gingrich. But note how he comes by this reputation: as a
leader of the generation that preceded the Republican revolution of
1994, not the one still recovering from it. When Cheney left
Congress to join President Bush's cabinet, the man who stepped into
his job as House minority whip was none other than the gentleman
from Georgia, Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney finally ends the Gingrich revolution. He brings the party
full circle. Personifying the status quo ante, he backs up Bush's
claim to be a new kind of Republican only if you think that going
back a political generation counts as going forward.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheney does fulfill the two other requirements Bush made
when he drew up the vice-presidential job specifications: that he
could step into the president's shoes if need be, and that he
should get along well with Bush personally. Even here, though, he
does so in ways that have a downside.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Cheney is qualified to take over the presidency is
putting it mildly. In terms of executive experience, he is probably
the running mate best qualified to be president in modern times. He
was in the Oval Office at a daunting time in recent White House
history _ when Gerald Ford set about rebuilding the executive
branch of government after the disasters of Watergate (Ford picked
Cheney to be his White House chief of staff at the ripe age of 34).
More recently, he actually served as defense secretary during a
war: the one in the Gulf, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has borrowed this splendid curriculum vitae to provide
himself with some surrogate gravitas and instant credibility in
foreign affairs. This is widely seen in America as a smart campaign
move. For the rest of the world it could prove more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself brings _ how to put this politely? _ no great
burden of preconception about the world's affairs. His
foreign-policy advisers do not lack for experience; but they also
include more than the normal ration of people who want to make some
radical changes in foreign and military policy (step forward
Richard Perle, Ronald Reagan's Soviet-squashing ``prince of
darkness''). Having a relatively cautious old buffer around to wag
a wary paw is obviously an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if the president himself is relying partly on the
foreign-policy judgments of others, Cheney's prudence and rather
mainstream hawkishness may not be enough. Especially when dealing
with new strategic threats, America may need a vice president who
can stand up and shove Bush in one direction or another _ and it is
not clear that Cheney would do that. This is one area where you
might want the vice president to bark more forcefully.
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for the other quality that got Cheney
picked: loyalty. Even by the paranoid standards of American
politics, Bush insists on and inspires undivided allegiance. He
said a big reason for picking Cheney was his confidence that he
could work well with him, a judgment based partly on Cheney's
service with Bush's father. The younger Bush was disgusted by the
people who abandoned the elder one in the latter days of that
troubled presidency. Loyalty, argues the governor of Texas, is the
glue that keeps his campaign staff a successful unit.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, loyalty has much to commend it. Bush's team remained
remarkably undivided even during the dark days (for them) of the
McCain insurgency. But so much is loyalty prized in this circle
that there is a real danger that Bush will shut himself off from
the variety and richness of views that comes from getting
conflicting advice.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Eisenhower, the modern president with the greatest
organizational experience, once said: ``I know of only one way in
which you can be sure you have done your best to make a wise
decision. You must get courageous men of strong views, and let them
debate with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not the Bush style. He surrounds himself with
long-serving allies. Many of them are no doubt highly capable
people. But there is a danger that they are too similar for Bush's
own good. Cheney, who until this week was the chief executive of
Halliburton, is even an oilman too.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is that the Bush campaign, even more than most, will
rise and fall on the candidate's own qualities. Cheney's lack of a
dowry in the form of votes from his home state expresses this
nicely (most of his political career was in Wyoming, which has a
grand total of three electoral-college votes, and where Democrats
are anyway on the endangered-species list).
</P>
<P>
   He adds little to the ticket and detracts less. The real lesson
from the Cheney nomination concerns Bush's growing self-confidence.
The name at the head of the ticket is the only one that matters.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, the choice of Cheney says that the
governor of Texas thinks he can win this li'l election all on his
own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
