   &UR; ENDORSEMENT OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you guys vote for Al Gore, you're out of your minds.''
(Actor Bruce Willis, providing a good reason to vote for the vice
president) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEBATE OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this will pretty much decide the election.'' (Maria
Pope, the producer of ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' which has
invited Gore and George W. Bush to a debate on the show. Letterman
will give points for responses and announce a winner. Gore has
accepted; Bush is considering; Ralph Nader is furious that he
hasn't been asked.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT WE REALLY, REALLY WANT: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``He's from four different ethnic groups, and he gets the
corporate vote because he golfs, which is the unofficial religion
of America.'' (Jeff Greenfield on why Gore should choose Tiger
Woods as his vice-presidential candidate, CNN, July 24) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALMA MATER: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``What I don't appreciate is people who think they're all of a
sudden smarter than the average person, because they happen to have
an Ivy League degree.'' (Bush, who was educated at Yale and Harvard
Business School, Washington Post, July 23) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLAH OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosperity and Progress: Fighting for the people, not the
powerful.'' (The catchy theme for the Democratic Convention; the
Republicans chose ``Renewing America's Purpose. Together.'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STAND BY YOUR WIFE: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are spending $1 million on television
advertisements showing President Bill Clinton praising Rick Lazio
last year. The Long Island congressman is now running against
Hillary Rodham Clinton for the New York Senate seat.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAY CUT: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Bush's running mate, Dick Cheney, earned $1.92 million last year
as chief executive of Halliburton, an oil-services company (not
including share options). The vice president's salary is $181,400. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAREWELL, SWEET PRINCE: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes has withdrawn from the Republican presidential race,
though he has not officially filed withdrawal papers yet. He will
endorse the Bush-Cheney ticket. (Washington Post, July 26) &QL;
</P>
