<HEADER>
A9177 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NOIR-AZR &LR;      08-01 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOIR-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-NOIR-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    IT'S `BLOOD SIMPLE' TO KNOW YOUR NOIR(a) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING {ndash} A COMPANION PIECE, ``BC-WALSH-INTERVIEW-AZR,
 &HT;    is embargoed till AUG. 4) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Audiences didn't know what to make of (beginitalic)Blood Simple
(enditalic)when it first popped up in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   In the era of (beginitalic)E.T. (enditalic)and
(beginitalic)Raiders of the Lost Ark(enditalic), here was a dark,
claustrophobic movie made on a tiny budget, with no big names in
the cast. The film's creators were two rookies: Joel and Ethan
Coen. The ``star'' was character actor M. Emmet Walsh, backed up by
an unknown actress named Frances McDormand.
</P>
<P>
   There was no way to tell the good guys from the bad guys. Every
time you thought you felt solid ground, a plot twist knocked you
off your feet. The whole thing just smacked of originality.
</P>
<P>
   But the style only seemed new. (beginitalic)Blood
Simple(enditalic), which was being re-released as a ``director's
cut'' in theaters Friday, was actually an homage to film noir, a
term coined by the French to describe American films released near
the end and in the aftermath of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hallmark of film noir is its sense of people trapped,''
Robert Sklar writes in (beginitalic)Movie-Made America,
(enditalic)''trapped in webs of paranoia and fear, unable to tell
guilt from innocence, true identity from false.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its villains are attractive and sympathetic, masking greed,
misanthropy, malevolence. Its heroes and heroines are weak,
confused, susceptible to false impressions.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly Steven Spielberg, is it?
</P>
<P>
   Some of the titles are familiar: (beginitalic)The
Killers(enditalic) (1946), (beginitalic)Double Indemnity
(enditalic)(1944), (beginitalic)Out of the Past (enditalic)(1947).
They are gritty, atmospheric films with reluctant heroes, scheming
females and ambiguous endings. They were underproduced, perhaps as
Hollywood's reaction to its own excesses.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)Blood Simple(enditalic), which touches all the
bases, gained a cult following through video rentals and gradually
became known as a classic. After the now-famous Coens opened the
door, Hollywood walked through it, cranking out more noir-type
movies, such as (beginitalic)The Last Seduction, Red Rock West
(enditalic)and the popular (beginitalic)L.A. Confidential.
</P>
<P>
   (enditalic)Some were faithful to the noir style, while others
were simply made to look like noir while copping out in the end. So
as you watch (beginitalic)Blood Simple(enditalic), here's a
checklist of what makes good noir:
</P>
<P>
   1) Low production values - These are not high-budget
productions, at least in terms of lighting and sets. For the
perfect template, take a look at (beginitalic)Detour
(enditalic)(1945), about a hitchhiker who takes a fatal wrong turn.
</P>
<P>
   2) The anti-hero - The main characters have to be slow on the
uptake (Burt Lancaster in (beginitalic)The Killers(enditalic)) or
at least disillusioned (Robert Mitchum in (beginitalic)Out of the
Past(enditalic)). They're not motivated by honor or duty, but by
greed or simply self-preservation.
</P>
<P>
   3) The femme fatale - Here's where (beginitalic)L.A.
Confidential (enditalic)loses it, with Kim Basinger as the hooker
with the heart of gold. Noir women are almost universally evil,
from the vicious Peggy Cummins in (beginitalic)Gun Crazy
(enditalic)to the diabolical Linda Fiorentino in (beginitalic)The
Last Seduction(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   4) Plenty of double-crosses - You can't trust anybody in a noir
film, especially the people you're sleeping with. Just ask Fred
MacMurray, who was charmed by Barbara Stanwyck's anklet in
(beginitalic)Double Indemnity(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   5) A strong crime element - Most of the best noir movies involve
private detectives or cops. There are some ((beginitalic)Sunset
Blvd., Lost Weekend(enditalic)) that stray more toward the
psychological, but trench coats and guns really help set the mood.
</P>
<P>
   6) No happy ending - The hero doesn't live, or at least doesn't
escape jail. Despite Hollywood's penchant for pat endings, the noir
hero rarely survives the film, either because he doesn't tumble to
the bushwhack or he turns out to be a stand-up guy after all.
</P>
<P>
   7) Snappy dialogue - Edward G. Robinson to MacMurray in
(beginitalic)Double Indemnity(enditalic): ``Guess I was wrong.
You're not smarter, Walter. You're just a little taller.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. So head for the video store, and then
(beginitalic)Blood Simple(enditalic), and you'll know your noir for
sure.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Contact Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
