<HEADER>
A9180 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-GOPKOLBE-AZR &LR;      08-01 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOPKOLBE-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-GOP-KOLBE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    GOP DELEGATES CONSIDER BOYCOTT OF KOLBE SPEECH(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By JEFF BARKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHILADELPHIA) - This isn't at all what Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz.,
had in mind, not on his big night at the Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe, the only openly-gay Republican in Congress, just wanted
to deliver a businesslike speech tonight on international trade, a
subject he probably knows more about than anybody in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But word filtered out Monday that a contingent in the Texas
delegation is considering a silent walkout during Kolbe's address
to protest the selection of a gay man delivering a prime-time GOP
convention speech.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is, Kolbe said in an interview Monday, that he doesn't
plan to discuss gay issues in his speech, or even refer to his
sexual orientation. In fact, some gay-rights groups have wished
Kolbe would adopt a higher profile regarding their concerns in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never denied my sexual orientation. I just don't make a
point of it. It isn't what I do,'' Kolbe said. ``Clearly, I'm known
for the work I've done on trade and Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe was silent for a moment when an (beginitalic)Arizona
Republic (enditalic)reporter asked him if he had heard that some in
the Texas delegation thought that his delivering tonight's speech
posed a moral issue, and that a protest was being considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. And then: ``I have no comment on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Carlson, chairwoman of the Tarrant County Republican Party,
said many of the Texas delegates have told her they want to send a
message to Gov. George W. Bush in a ``quiet way'' and have
discussed walking out, according to (beginitalic)the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram(enditalic)'s online edition.
</P>
<P>
   She told the newspaper she was disappointed that Bush, the
presumptive GOP presidential nominee, selected Kolbe to address
free trade issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it (a silent protest) is appropriate if we get a
speaker like that, who is not representative of most of the
delegates' beliefs,'' Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas delegate Cathy McConn of Houston told (beginitalic)The
Republic(enditalic), ``There was concern that he (Kolbe) was chosen
because he was openly gay - kind of like a quota'' But McConn said
she had not taken a position herself.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Mary Cheney, 31, one of GOP vice presidential
nominee Dick Cheney's daughters, is openly gay, and plans to
actively campaign for her father.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe arguably will become the most prominent openly-gay
Republican to address a GOP convention, according to the Gay and
Lesbian Victory Fund and other advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Sullivan, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said that as of
early Monday evening, there hadn't been any communication about
Kolbe's speech between the Texas governor and Carlson or the other
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope and believe that the delegates will be respectful of
all the speakers. Congressman Kolbe is speaking because of his
expertise and leadership on the issue of free trade,'' Sullivan
said
</P>
<P>
   A Texas walkout would be certain to provoke a spirited defense
of Kolbe by Arizona's lawmakers and other delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Republicans strongly supported Kolbe when he disclosed
his sexual orientation in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``My response to him was very brief,'' Rep. John Shadegg,
R-Ariz., recalled the following year. ``I said, `Jim, it doesn't
make a difference to me whatsoever. I could care less.' ``
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mike Hellon, the Republican National Committeeman
from Arizona, said, ``It (a walkout) would be a black mark on an
inclusive, positive convention. For Gov. Bush's own delegation to
do that, it would be mind-boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Kolbe, first elected to the House in 1984, declined
to confirm or deny rumors that he was a homosexual. He finally
disclosed it rather than be ``outed'' on the Internet by activists
angry with his vote in favor of a Republican-sponsored bill to deny
federal sanction of same-sex marriages.
</P>
<P>
   After he came out, Kolbe told (beginitalic)The
Republic(enditalic), ``I would rather be known as `Jim Kolbe, the
trade expert in Congress who happens to be gay,' rather than `Jim
Kolbe, gay congressman from Arizona.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan Wiesen, spokesman for the Gay and Lesbian Victory Fund,
said Monday, ``My sense is that most openly gay and lesbian elected
officials have to overcome attempts to pigeonhole them based on
their sexual orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe has quietly been an active member of the Log Cabin
Republicans, a gay political group that plans to honor him here at
a reception before the speech. He has consistently supported
legislation to ban employment discrimination against gays and
lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   David Smith, a spokesman for the Human Rights Campaign Fund,
said of a possible protest against Kolbe: ``I couldn't think of a
meaner thing that could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But Smith's organization, as well as other gay and lesbian
rights groups, have criticized the Republican platform as
antagonistic for, among other reasons, declaring that homosexuality
is ``incompatible'' with military service.
</P>
</TEXT>
