<HEADLINE>
HARVARD ALUMS LOOK OUT FOR ONE ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; News flash: Harvard MBAs love to throw money behind other
Harvard MBAs.
</P>
<P>
   As if they weren't already one of the tightest cliques on the
planet, a few alums decided at their recent five-year B-School
reunion that they wanted to make it even easier for their
entrepreneurial colleagues to raise funds from wealthy grads.
</P>
<P>
   Three Harvard guys last January started UniversityAngels.com, an
angel site to link individual investors with promising business
plans. The reason, says Rick Sasner, chief strategy officer for the
New York-based start-up: ``At one end of the room were people
looking for capital. At the other were people at financial
institutions looking for good deals to invest in.''
</P>
<P>
   So they jumped into the busy realm of matchmaking. Angel sites,
incubators, accelerators, and new venture groups are springing up
everywhere, in hopes of making a buck helping new companies get off
the ground. And the Harvard connection was, of course,
irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a comfort level when a Crimson alum is looking at a
Crimson MBA's business plan,'' Sasner said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard, along with its rival across the river, MIT, attracts
venture capitalists' attention at a startling clip. During school
months, Battery Ventures' Todd Dagres literally roams the halls at
MIT and lectures there. Polaris Venture Partners' Jon Flint and his
partners spend time with professors at both schools. They check in
regularly with the licensing offices at both to find out about new
technologies and ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard and MIT really are spectacular incubators for
talent,'' says Flint, who attended Hobart and University of
Virginia Law. ``They have a history of success that breeds
success.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, more than 25 of the 100 business plans submitted to the
annual entrepreneur contest at Harvard won venture backing,
spokesman Jim Aisner says. Those are highly unusual odds. Most
venture firms say they look at thousands of plans every year and
fund only a few dozen, tops.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean, however, that every young buck at Harvard
who's gunning to win the business plan contest has a brilliant
idea. Flint points out that the firm looks at business plans from
graduates of many less famous schools. Indeed, he notes, along with
Harvard's talent comes plenty of attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is also a level of arrogance there that's off the
charts,'' Flint says. ``Simply having a Harvard or MIT pedigree
does not ensure success.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the founders of UniversityAngels concede as much. They
decided to expand their initial concept of a Harvard-only site
(CrimsonAngels.com) to a network of sites that target alumni of 45
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 20 percent of the posted deals on the site still come
from Harvard. But the other 80 percent come from other schools
across the country. And not all plans make it through the company's
screens to the site. Of about 2,500 plans submitted to date, Sasner
says, 100 have been posted for review by angels.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best feature of the site: Alumni get the first shot
at investing in their fellow alums. If you went to Brown and none
of your fellow grads invest in your business, after two weeks the
rest of the network gets to see your idea. More money potential for
the start-ups, a bigger talent pool for the investors.
</P>
<P>
   Sasner and his cofounders, James Marcus and Charles Sanford,
have completed one deal so far through the site. Galileo Designs of
Atlanta raised $135,000 in about a month for its
business-to-business software product _ and then went on to raise
more money outside the network afterward.
</P>
<P>
   What's perhaps most interesting about the angel site, Sasner
notes, is that it's not all about tapping 20-something brains. Lots
of entrepreneurs filing plans there have been out of school for
many years but are still interested in connecting with investors
who were educated as they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very mature, seasoned professionals looking for
opportunities,'' Sasner says. Only 5 percent of the plans come from
undergrads. About 15 percent come from fresh MBAs, while the other
80 percent come from people who've been out in the world for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   For Sasner and Co., this business is a way to cash in on both
their Harvard stripes and the hip playground of the new economy and
venture capital, where the latest Harvard grads are heading after
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when the UniversityAngels founders graduated,
investment banking and consulting were still hotter careers than
venture capital. Observes Sasner: ``Everything they taught us in
1994 was useless.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Healy is a member of the Globe's staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
