<SLUG> BC-TECH-ROUNDUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELECOM: OUTWARD BOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the hotter trends in telecommunications today is unified
messaging, with dozens of firms offering new services to collect
all your voice mails, e-mails, and faxes in one digital mailbox to
save you time and hassle.
</P>
<P>
   Now the action is beginning to heat up on the flip side of
unified messaging _ ``outbound'' services that let you create a
message that is delivered simultaneously to dozens or hundreds of
people as an e-mail, a message on a cell phone or pager, a fax, and
even as a synthesized voice call.
</P>
<P>
   EnvoyWorldWide, known for its MessageBlaster service, is
introducing a new service with Bidder's Edge, a Web Burlington,
Mass. site that collects information about 170 Internet auction
sites and notifies subscribers when new bids have come in or
auctions are about to close.
</P>
<P>
   Two-year-old Bidder's Edge is using MessageBlaster to power a
service called PingMe that lets people track auctions and get a
message in any format they want.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of chaining yourself to the computer to follow the
auction for that 1969 Phil Esposito hockey card you're dying to
get, you can arrange to have any type of message sent to you
whenever there is a development in the bidding.
</P>
<P>
   In one version of the Bidder's Edge service, you could arrange
to get a phone call from a speech synthesizer that would tell you
of a development in a bid, then let you use your phone keypad to
dial in a new bid.
</P>
<P>
   The deal represents a new market for EnvoyWorldWide, a
Billerica, Mass. company whose system has been purchased by
businesses that want to be sure they get crucial information to
employees and executives through whatever communications device
they might be using.
</P>
<P>
   One recent client is Myteam.com, which uses MessageBlaster to
inform soccer-league parents and coaches when a game has been
canceled or a practice rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Envoy president Alain Daste said he sees a host of potential
markets, including trucking businesses wanting to get job
information to drivers and corporations wanting to alert employees
when the latest virus begins infecting e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susie in San Francisco might be delighted to get a long voice
mail from you, but before you pick up the phone to call Schatzie in
Stuttgart you might want to send a fax instead.
</P>
<P>
   That suggestion comes from a survey by Pitney Bowes of Stamford,
Conn., which looked at the messaging preferences of people in North
America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Notably, while 97 percent of white-collar workers in the United
States say they use voice mail several times a week or daily, only
35 percent in Germany do, and less than 75 percent in France and
the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Germany ranked highest in frequent usage of faxes, at 93
percent, ahead of the United States at 80 percent. And perhaps
reflecting the more laid-back approach to work on the Continent, 5
percent or fewer of British, French, and German workers carry
pagers _ compared to 25 percent in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Study author Meredith Fischer, a Pitney Bowes vice president,
said people should be aware of ``marked cultural tendencies.''
While many Americans are fine with trading voice mails, Europeans
find long voice mails ``irritating and somewhat of a personal
imposition,'' and Germans and French workers greatly prefer
traditional paper communication, she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink, the Atlanta Internet service provider, has added
Boston to markets where it is offering a self-installation plan for
getting high-speed digital subscriber line Net access. Verizon
Communications offers a similar plan, but it can sometimes be hard
to find stores that sell its DSL modems.
</P>
<P>
   Earthlink's service does not completely eliminate waiting to get
DSL. You have to call EarthLink to order the service; then the
company tells you when you can expect to have your DSL line
activated and ships you the necessary modem, filter, and software
to plug in yourself.
</P>
<P>
   For now, EarthLink only promises to reduce installation times by
up to 50 percent _ which may mean waiting two weeks instead of
four, but saves you waiting around the house for an installation
guy to show up. Genuity of Burlington, the former GTE
Internetworking, is partnering with EarthLink to offer the service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
