<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-PICTURETEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICTURETEL FUTURE HANGS IN BALANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PictureTel Corp.'s new president, Lewis Jaffe, says he can make
the troubled videoconferencing company profitable by next year with
new products that allow faster data transmission, giving users the
ability to butt into conversations.
</P>
<P>
   PictureTel has suffered losses and layoffs since 1997 as the
market for its equipment has stalled and competitors have gained
ground.
</P>
<P>
   But PictureTel hopes its fortunes will change as it rolls out
new products that process audio and video signals so quickly that
users will be able to interrupt each other when speaking on
videoconferences.
</P>
<P>
   The question of manners aside, most conference-calling equipment
to date has lacked the capability of interruption. The feature
makes video-based conversations seem more natural, and PictureTel
hopes it will also lead to more orders from corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very exhausting if you need to sit and wait until you
know someone's done speaking,'' Jaffe said. ``It adds tension to
the meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   PictureTel won't divulge sales targets for its equipment, known
as the 900 Series. But the Andover, Mass. company needs a lift.
</P>
<P>
   Its stock is down about 90 percent from its 1995 high of
$43.125. It already warned it won't meet expectations in its
second-quarter earnings, due out Aug. 1. And, in April, its
auditor, PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP, warned of ``substantial
doubt'' about PictureTel's ``ability to continue as a going
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the 900 Series has been much anticipated in the
videoconferencing industry. And despite the earnings problems, the
company this month received investments totaling $22 million from
Intel Corp. and the State of Wisconsin, and arranged a $35 million
credit line.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts think the reception of the 900 series could make or
break the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really need this,'' said analyst Andy Nilssen of
Wainhouse Research LLC. ``From what I've seen, it's either a
breakthrough or at least a really nice step forward. The bad news
is, they've lost a lot of market share while they've been getting
it ready.''
</P>
<P>
   PictureTel has already delayed the rollout of the 900 Series by
several months, meaning it will have more ground to make up against
competitors such as VTel Corp. of Austin, Texas, and Polycom Inc.
of Santa Barbara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The 900 Series devices are based on an Intel-backed PC software
standard known as `iPower,'' rather than the proprietary systems
PictureTel previously sold. The interruption capability stems from
audio software that processes signals with delays of just 200
microseconds, half the previous norm.
</P>
<P>
   Another feature allows 900 Series users to display paper
documents to each other in a separate on-screen window that will
display typeface fonts as small as 8 points, compared with the
previous minimum of 24-point typefaces. Prices will start around
$10,000, a third of some of PictureTel's current offerings.
</P>
<P>
   PictureTel has also begun an Internet-based subsidiary to
arrange video-conference calls, but the bulk of its 1,100 employees
still work on hardware. Before layoffs, employment peaked at 1,500
in 1996, mostly in Andover.
</P>
<P>
   But PictureTel stumbled as competitors offered cheaper products
with some of the same features, such as the ability to support
conferences from several locations at once. Last year, the company
lost $84.5 million on revenue of $323.3 million, and earlier this
month said it would report a wider-than-expected loss for the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   PictureTel turned out its previous chairman and chief executive,
Bruce R. Bond, last year after 20 months with the company following
hardware and software bugs in its products, which prompted some
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   The top titles have since reverted to cofounder Norman Gaut.
Jaffe was named president and chief operating officer on June 21. A
consultant who headed the restructuring practice at Arthur Andersen
LLP's Boston office, Jaffe had already begun working with
PictureTel when he was hired full time.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffe said more layoffs are still possible unless revenues
increase. He has also saved $5 million by canceling leases for
space near Andover where PictureTel once expected to employ nearly
2,500 people.
</P>
<P>
   But Jaffe insisted the 900 series is ready for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 900 is later than anticipated because of rigorous
testing,'' he said. Referring to the product recalls, he said:
``The company knows it can't go throught that experience again.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on a video link from another room in PictureTel's
headquarters, Jaffe's conversation seemed as direct as the words of
Captain Kirk appearing on-screen on the Starship Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is whether the technology will be enough to
breath new life into the company. One reseller of PictureTel
equipment, Jim Brown of Pittsburgh-based RoData Inc., praised the
900 Series but said it may be difficult for PictureTel to win back
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have the market-leading piece of gear, but to
leverage old accounts who may have just invested in competitors'
technology is going to be their challenge,'' Brown said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
