<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-BUILTINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL-TO-WALL WIRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Coming soon to a housing development near
you: wall-to-wall Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   Touting it as the best invention since indoor plumbing, Cisco
Systems Inc. and real estate developer Playa Vista have teamed up
to introduce the next-generation, ultra-wired homes.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine having instant, high-speed Internet access from any
phone jack in the house. Refrigerators, televisions, ovens, lights,
alarm systems would all be connected to the Web. That, of course,
means being able to control these appliances from any Internet
browser in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Playa Vista is building 14,000 of these high-wired homes in West
Los Angeles using Cisco's ``gateway'' technology to provide
ubiquitous Internet connections. The first of these ``smart homes''
is scheduled to be completed in April.
</P>
<P>
   What new capabilities will they offer?
</P>
<P>
   Residents will be able to preheat their oven on their way home
from work from a personal digital assistant that is connected to
the Internet. They can turn on the home security system from their
cell phone at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   When they're away from the house, they can monitor their
children through a Web cam. Defective appliances theoretically have
the ability to automatically self-diagnose and send an e-mail to
the manufacturer to dispatch a repair crew.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this is already available in bits and pieces. Many
personal computers now have high-speed Internet connections. And
with some effort, consumers can network several devices together to
share Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   What's new, Cisco executives say, is the ability for all devices
in the home to easily share a single Internet connection through
its gateway, a notebook-size black box that distributes Internet
access throughout a house. To get access, consumers would only need
to plug a device into any phone jack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet will become a utility, like water and
electricity,'' said A. Jared Headley, consumer solutions manager
for Cisco, which opened a model ``home'' on its corporate campus in
San Jose last week.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco plans to sell its gateway devices to housing developers
across the country, but also seeks to reach consumers who are
looking to wire existing homes.
</P>
<P>
   The devices, expected to be on the market in about six months,
will cost $500 each. That would not include the monthly fee charged
for the Internet service itself. Nor would it include the cost of
installing high-speed wires, which would add another $1,500 for an
existing home. Adding custom appliances, home entertainment
systems, and security devices could jack up the price tag by
$50,000 to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can
be reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
