<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, AUGUST 1 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT (moved Sunday, July 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 9
about an incentive offered by Talk magazine to attract advertising
from Bacara, a resort hotel in California, referred incorrectly to
monitoring of Talk's advertising pages by the Publishers
Information Bureau. The bureau indeed monitors Talk, and its
figures differ from independent estimates by an industry executive
that were used in the article. In February, the bureau counted
138.4 advertising pages, compared with 48.6 for the independent
count, although the larger figure included a special advertising
section. In March, it counted 48.8 pages, compared with 41.3; in
April, 70.3 pages, compared with 70.8; and in June 36.2 pages,
compared with 36.1.
</P>
<P>
   BC-COPYRIGHT-SUIT-NYT (moved Sunday, July 30)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 30
about a trial for copyright violation in the publication of a
software code that unscrambles a digital -videodisc referred
incorrectly to the design of a T-shirt shown in court. The
inscription depicted the software's source code, the original
programming instructions. The object code _ the instructions
translated into 0's and 1's _ was not shown.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SHIP-SALVAGE-NYT (moved Sunday, July 30)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 30
about a ruling that awarded Spain the remains of two sunken sailing
ships misstated the seat and jurisdiction of the Court of Appeals
for the Fourth Circuit, which issued the ruling. It is based in
Richmond, Va., not Norfolk, and covers West Virginia as well as
Maryland, Virginia and North and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT (moved Friday, July 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, July 28
about ``Kiarostami 101,'' a short by the film scholar Jamsheed
Akrami about the Iranian director Abbas Kiarostami, misstated plans
for it. Mr. Akrami is expanding the short; it is not being shown
with Mr. Kia-rostami's new film, ``The Wind Will Carry Us,'' at the
Lincoln Plaza Cinemas in Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
