<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9270 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN02-COX     08-01 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Each Cheney upside has a downside
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you think about it, and whatever you think of it, it is a
distinctly odd ticket that Republicans have convened in
Philadelphia to hosanna and to launch into the presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush was either, in the cliche, thinking outside the
box or not thinking at all when he picked Dick Cheney as his
running mate. Either way, no candidate before ever thought of going
to the voters in a tandem of two big oil guys from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   This a balancing act akin to a one-arm high wire artiste.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the announcement gave Bush a nice boost, taking W. from
a statistical dead heat with Al Gore in most polls to a 10 or more
point lead. Until its durability is tested, it's anybody's guess
whether the bump is because the choice is wildly popular or just
because, with few voters paying attention to either campaign so
far, prime time attention for anything better than a loitering bust
is a boon.
</P>
<P>
   The political accounting is mixed but would seem to lean to the
deficit side.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney certainly brings assets. As Bush said, he is a serious
man of proven public ability and completely credible as an
emergency president if it should come to that. He adds, if no
notable zing, the virtues of experience, calm counsel and
seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, as well, is canny in the ways of Washington, a former
congressman who, as a cabinet officer, served Bush the First well.
</P>
<P>
   But each of those points has a downside. It is at least awkward
for Bush that there should be a sensed need to bolster him with
companion gravity, as if he were not weighty enough on his own.
Cheney's selection adds to the impression -- already strong from
the many holdovers in the campaign _ that the proposed, new Bush
administration will be pretty much a revival of the first, with a
younger stand-in playing the real George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Is George W. his own man or just poppy's boy?
</P>
<P>
   It is clear enough who Cheney is. His congressional record met
every right-wing litmus test.
</P>
<P>
   He voted against Head Start and all gun control, including
regulations on armor-piercing bullets and a ban on plastic handguns
that can evade airport X-rays. He voted to cut AIDS research. He
opposed sanctions against South African apartheid and even a
resolution urging that Nelson Mandela be freed from prison. He
consistently fought environmental protection, even voting against
renewal of the Clean Air Act. He is an anti-abortion absolutist.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is betting Cheney's record will validate his candidacy with
the party's ever-restive right but that his mild manner and
civility will make Democratic efforts to exploit that record seem
alarmist. Cheney refuses to foam at the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. First Bush chipped a few of the pricklier burrs off the
hard right Republican Party platform, to make a little room for the
compassion part of his compassionate conservatism. Then he turns
around and names a man of the hard right to serve, he promises, as
one of his chief counselors.
</P>
<P>
   Which is it to be, really?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
