<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9285 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0802-CO     08-01 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roll out the Maytag and let the fun begin
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PELEE ISLAND, Ont. _ ``Okay, girls,'' Robin hollers, ``let's get
to it. Time to roll out the Maytag.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a relative newcomer to the island, and to octogenarian
Robin's sisterhood of gentlewomen of a certain age, I think she's
talking about some kind of dance _ maybe to the tune of Beer Barrel
Polka. I couldn't be more wrong. She's talking about laundry. It's
time to tear it up, clean it up, and wash everything that can't
outrun us _ in a 40-year-old wringer washer.
</P>
<P>
   Robin, in cut-offs and a pink terry tube top, directs the action
as she rolls the Maytag out of the storeroom and into the back
yard. My job is to haul hot water from the kitchen sink while
Sharon and Pat fill two galvanized rinse
</P>
<P>
   tubs with the garden hose. Right away I start in whining. ``Why
can't I have a cushy job like theirs?'' Robin says I can, just as
soon as I finish hauling the water and wiping off the clotheslines.
</P>
<P>
   If I thought playing Gunga Din in my nightshirt was a pain,
navigating the backyard to get to the clotheslines is even worse.
Recent heavy rains have turned it into a veritable swamp, and even
though I give the terrain a quick once-over before setting out, I'm
still into it over my sneaker tops. Clutching a wet rag, and
swearing under my breath, I slosh on, thinking once I reach higher
ground I'll be fine. Wrong again.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the black flies and mosquitoes take over. Obviously,
I'm the lead item on their breakfast menu. Instinct tells me to
drop the rag and run for cover, but I hate looking like a sissy. So
instead, I dance my way up one
</P>
<P>
   clothesline and down the other, slapping and wiping, and calling
my attackers names that would curl their mothers' wings.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I've beaten my way back through the bog, the old
Maytag is whooshing around a load of sheets. Pat, is rinsing a
clothes basket with the hose, and Sharon is poking around in the
washer with the non-business end of a
</P>
<P>
   long-handled squeegee.
</P>
<P>
   Robin flips a lever on top of the wringer to position it between
the washer and the first tub of rinse water as she explains to me
the quick-release mechanism on the top. ``If you get anything
caught in the wringer,'' she says
</P>
<P>
   with a sly grin, ``hit this red thing and it'll let it go.'' I
resist the obvious comment.
</P>
<P>
   It's rinse time now. Robin slides the agitator gear shift handle
into neutral and the wash stops splashing. Then she checks to be
sure the rollers are headed in the right direction before she feeds
the first sheet through.
</P>
<P>
   My job is simple. All I have to do is be sure the stuff coming
through the wringer doesn't roll around and get all tangled up and
cause an assembly line shut-down. So far, according to Pat and
Sharon who have somehow been promoted to on-site supervisory
status, things are going well.
</P>
<P>
   Then... ``It's got my rubber glove!'' Robin hollers, holding up
one bare hand as digital proof. I check. Sure enough, here comes
this yellow thing with bloated fingers squishing through the
wringer. Just before it clears, one
</P>
<P>
   finger explodes. I remind her not to lean into her work.
</P>
<P>
   Two gloves later, we've rinsed and are ready to hang. My
nightshirt is dripping wet, and we have four more loads to go. Pat
and Sharon are on clothespin detail. ``Hang the underwear on the
middle line where it won't show,'' Robin calls after them. They
argue that since the lines are 50 yards from the road it won't
matter. Robin insists. ``I don't want a bunch of tourists walking
by and looking at my drawers.''
</P>
<P>
   By three in the afternoon, we've earned our cocktail hour.
Everything is dried, folded, and put away _ except for a few damp
pieces draped over porch chairs.
</P>
<P>
   It's been fun _ and a learning experience. But once is enough.
As soon as I get home I'm heading for the basement to give my
23-year-old automatic a hug of newly-found appreciation. So much
for the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
