   The retirement planning Web site, with its appeal to
self-interest, is part of that effort. Halter and others answered
some basic questions about the new, online resources.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's new about the Internet retirement planner?
</P>
<P>
   A: Workers 25 and older already get an annual statement showing
how much their monthly retirement benefit will be at age 62, at
full retirement age, and at 70. About 125 million Americans get the
individual statement through the mail, usually about three months
before their birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   The three calculators at the Web site are much more versatile.
You can get a quick-and-dirty estimate or you can customize the
report by changing your retirement age or other variables. ``You'll
see how the Social Security benefit varies with those changes,''
Halter said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Aren't workers eligible for full benefits at age 65? A: Not
any more. The table shows how the threshold has changed. For
example, the oldest baby boomers will have to work until age 66 or
accept reduced benefits. People in the 1943-1954 bracket would get
about 75 percent of full benefits if they retired at age 62,
according to the American Academy of Actuaries. That's the earliest
age at which you can receive retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   For intensely detailed information, go to
www.ssa.gov/retire/agereduction.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are estimates from the online calculators guaranteed?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. They are based on assumptions, including your future
earnings and the rate of inflation in future years. You get
estimates, not promises.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do the calculators work?
</P>
<P>
   A: With the quick calculator, you type in your age and how much
money you will make this year. You get an instant but ``very
rough'' estimate, according to the SSA.
</P>
<P>
   The online version requires you to type in your complete
earnings history, using information from your annual statement. You
can try out other scenarios by changing your retirement age and
future earnings expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The detailed calculator must be downloaded to your own computer.
You can change the expected inflation rate as well as retirement
age and future earnings. It requires more thought but is presumably
the most accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Note that online and detailed calculators are available only for
PC users. A version for Mac users is expected in about 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can I still talk to a real person?
</P>
<P>
   A: The SSA is testing a system that will connect Internet users
to a customer service representative.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, you can e-mail a question. Go to the home page,
www.ssa.gov, and click on Questions. ``The response may give the
text of an answer or refer you to a Web site where the answer is,''
Halter said.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can call 1-800-772-1213 to talk to a real person.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can future retirees count on Social Security to survive long
into the future?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Absolutely,'' argues Halter. ``Social Security is the
single most effective anti-poverty program in U.S. history. Public
support will ensure that elected representatives focus on necessary
reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Renn, a certified financial planner in Midtown, sees it
differently. ``If you are in your late 50s, I would count on it,''
he said. ``But certainly if you are in your mid-30s to early 40s, I
would discount it heavily.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes that demographic pressures will force cutbacks.
Policy-makers could raise retirement ages even more or could reduce
the level of benefits. But Renn believes that a third alternative _
cutting back or eliminating payments to higher-income families _ is
the most likely fix.
</P>
<P>
   Then the question would be who gets tossed out. Should the
income limit be at $30,000, for example, or at $50,000 or even
higher?
</P>
<P>
   65 IS NO MAGIC NUMBER
</P>
<P>
   The government has raised the eligibility age for full Social
Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Year Fullof birth retirement age
</P>
<P>
   1937 or earlier 65
</P>
<P>
   1938 65 and 2 months
</P>
<P>
   1939 65 and 4 months
</P>
<P>
   1940 65 and 6 months
</P>
<P>
   1941 65 and 8 months
</P>
<P>
   1942 65 and 10 months
</P>
<P>
   1943-54 66
</P>
<P>
   1955 66 and 2 months
</P>
<P>
   1956 66 and 4 months
</P>
<P>
   1957 66 and 6 months
</P>
<P>
   1958 66 and 8 months
</P>
<P>
   1959 66 and 10 months
</P>
<P>
   1960 and later 67
</P>
<P>
   Note: Reduced retirement benefits are available after age 62.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Social Security Administration
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: The motherlode for Social Security information:
www.ssa.gov. For a very rough idea of how much income you will need
in retirement: www.asec.org
</P>
<P>
