<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, August 2, 2000 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-DEATHPENALTY _ Ruling by 11th Circuit panel in Alabama
death-row appeal is unsupportable. When judge writing for the
majority concedes the case against the condemned man is less than
overwhelming, the accused's attorney should have presented evidence
in mitigation during sentencing phase. Since he didn't, the
sentence of death should not stand. (The Atlanta Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ George W. Bush was either, in the cliche,
thinking outside the box or not thinking at all when he picked Dick
Cheney as his running mate. Either way, no candidate before ever
thought of going to the voters in a tandem of two big oil guys from
Texas. This a balancing act akin to a one-arm high wire artiste.
(Teepen, Cox News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ While much attention recently has been paid
the demands for return of art treasures looted by the Nazis, and
while Greece continues to insist Great Britain give back the Elgin
Marbles looted from the Parthenon two centuries ago, a court ruling
in Virginia late last month has turned this type of reclamation
into a tizzy. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ PELEE ISLAND, Ont. _ Robin, in cut-offs and a
pink terry tube top, directs the action as she rolls a 40-year-old
wringer washer out of the storeroom and into the back yard. My job
is to haul hot water from the kitchen sink while Sharon and Pat
fill two galvanized rinse tubs with the garden hose. Right away I
start in whining. ``Why can't I have a cushy job like theirs?''
Robin says I can, just as soon as I finish hauling the water and
wiping off the clotheslines. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ If George W. Bush was paying attention behind the
scenes during the 1992 convention in Houston's Astrodome, he was
learning how not to win a nation's heart. You don't win it by
repeating the phrase ``family values'' every other sentence, as
speaker after speaker after speaker did in the Astro-drone. They so
cheapened an already two-bit phrase that when all was said and
drummed it couldn't have been weighty to an ear mite. (Young, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
