<HEADER>
A9351 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CAR-CONFISCATION-HNS &LR;      08-01 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CONFISCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN FRANCISCO CONSIDERS SEIZING DRUG BUYERS' CARS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RACHEL GORDON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Buoyed by a recent state court ruling, San
Francisco Supervisor Amos Brown has resurrected a controversial
plan to confiscate cars allegedly used in San Francisco to solicit
drugs or prostitutes, even if their owners are never convicted of a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am hopeful that this ordinance will help alleviate the drug
and prostitution problems,'' which continue to plague many of our
poorer neighborhoods, said Brown, who floated an identical measure
a year ago that went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   He said most of the offenders come from outside the affected
areas, and residents and merchants are tired of watching their
neighborhoods deteriorate because of them.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, however, say the law would do nothing to get to the
root of the problems _ poverty, hopelessness and addiction _ which
lead to drug and prostitution trade.
</P>
<P>
   Brown first proposed the law on behalf of Mayor Willie Brown
last year, but backed off when he could not muster support on the
board. At the same time, a similar law in Oakland was challenged in
court by the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   But after the California 1st District Court of Appeal ruled
unanimously that Oakland's 2-and-1/2-year-old vehicle seizure law
doesn't conflict with state law, which allows a car to be seized
only after its owner is convicted of using the vehicle during a
crime, Supervisor Brown reintroduced the ordinance. More than 300
cars have been seized in Oakland since the city enacted its law.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU intends to appeal the ruling to the California Supreme
Court, and will challenge San Francisco's law when _ and if _ it
becomes law, said attorney Alan Schlosser.
</P>
<P>
   He said Supervisor Brown's proposal is unconstitutional, because
it penalizes people who haven't been convicted, and excessive,
because the fine _ the loss of a car _ may not match the severity
of the alleged crime.
</P>
<P>
   Innocent people, he said, may lose their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, cops and prosecutors can seize a car and
sell it at auction if they believe a crime has been committed;
there is no requirement for conviction. And the car's owner doesn't
have to be involved: They chance losing their car if they lend it
to a relative or a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the sale of confiscated vehicles are split between
police and prosecutors - the same people who decide whether the
cars should be taken in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most extreme and harsh forfeiture law I have ever
seen,'' Schlosser said of Brown's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown said a conviction is not necessary to know when an
alleged perpetrator is up to no good. The cops see them driving
around town looking for sex and drugs, and they should be stopped,
even if it takes drastic measures, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the people who have been raising hell in our
community,`` he said.
</P>
<P>
   The offenders, he said, ``are causing pain, death, misery,
suffering,'' and the city must intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Gavin Newsom vowed to fight the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Car seizures have no place in San Francisco,'' Newsom said.
The proposed law, he said, is akin to ``taking away our civil
liberties.''
</P>
<P>
   Newsom has asked the city attorney to draft alternatives to car
seizures, such as boosting fines for drugs and prostitution in the
most troubled neighborhoods, and stepping up enforcement of those
vice laws.
</P>
<P>
   He said seizure laws disproportionately affect poor minorities
who are unable to hire attorneys to fight for the return of their
cars. At the same time, he said, the laws do nothing to get to the
core of the drug problem, which he said should be addressed with
treatment services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
