<HEADER>
A9369 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-OAK-DEATH-HNS &LR;      08-01 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAK-DEATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OAK DEATHS CAUSED BY FUNGUS, RESEARCHERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JANE KAY   
 &HT;     c. 2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Sudden Oak Death'' syndrome, which has killed
thousands of Central California's coastal oak trees over the past
five years, is being caused by a newly discovered fungus akin to
the one that caused the Irish potato famine, University of
California scientists believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just recently found that the potential underlying cause of
the disease is a new fungus, and species related to it have caused
major epidemics around the world, including the Irish potato
famine,'' said David Rizzo, an assistant professor of plant
pathology at the University of California at Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The fungus targets the bark of tanoak, black oak and coast live
oak.
</P>
<P>
   Rizzo identified the fungus in June and believes it poses an
emergency threat to healthy oak trees that stretch from Santa
Barbara to southern Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five years, the disease has killed thousands of
trees from Big Sur to Napa, Sonoma and Solano counties _ already
under siege from rampant development of vineyards and housing
developments. Santa Cruz and Marin have been hit especially hard.
</P>
<P>
   At risk are black oaks that grow north to the Cascades, over to
the Sierra on the floor of Yosemite Valley and on foothills toward
Lake Tahoe, and in the Central Valley. Also at risk are coast live
oaks, which grow south to Baja California, and the tanoaks, which
stretch to Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Rizzo urged people to help stop the fungus' spread by not
carrying firewood from the counties where it has been identified to
the Sierra. Also, property owners should not move wood from
infected trees off their land, Rizzo said. Instead, they should
call their county Agricultural Cooperative Extension Service for
advice on treatment or disposal of dead branches or trees.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, people who hike or camp, or even drive through oak
woodlands in the counties that have the oak fungus, should clean
their tires, pets and shoes before going into clean areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The disease is carried by a microscopic two-tailed, swimming
fungus that first attacks bark in trunks and branches, scientists
believe. The fungus moves around by spores in soils, wind, water
and perhaps via insects, and is most active during the rainy
season. It's a member of the genus Phytophthora, and the species
hasn't been named or fully described yet.
</P>
<P>
   The fungus is related to the organisms that caused the Irish
potato famine of 1845-50 and the modern deaths of Port Orford cedar
trees in Northern California and southern Oregon, eucalyptus
forests in Australia and oak forests in Mexico, Spain and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers don't know whether the fungal species is native or
if it has been introduced in the past few years. The pathogen isn't
related to the oak wilt fungus, which attacks Eastern U.S. oaks,
they say.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fungus was isolated five weeks ago, ``Sudden Oak
Death'' syndrome has been around for at least five years.
Scientists suspected that some sort of fungi were killing stressed
trees.
</P>
<P>
   When Marin County started worrying about the fire, safety,
economic and environmental effects of acres of dying oak trees, the
University of California formed a multidisciplinary committee to
study the disease six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Observing the symptoms in test plots, they suspected that the
first sign of the fungal attack was a seeping or bleeding from
cankers, said Brice McPherson, a researcher in the Division of
Insect Biology at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   The disease dissolved the bark and entered the wood, leaving the
tree vulnerable to bark beetles. The beetles bored into the tree,
sometimes killing it within a month, inspiring the name ``Sudden
Oak Death.``
</P>
<P>
   Native oaks, including those being attacked by the fungi, grow
on about 11 million acres, about 11 percent of the state's land.
There, oak watersheds filter water, prevent erosion and provide
habitat for a wide variety of habitat, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, the California Oak Foundation, an Oakland
nonprofit, has been trying to get the state Department of Forestry
to protect the oak and pay attention to the diseases that attack
it.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, the state requested cities and counties to
pass ordinances to protect oaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some did and some didn't. There may be some places where they
are mandatory, but generally they are voluntary,`` said Gerald
Ahlstrom, the agency's chief of forest practice.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, thousands of acres have disappeared to bulldozing and
clear-cutting for growing grapes and commercial conifers and other
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``California's landscape is represented by the golden grasslands
and the oak woodlands. Their beauty has inspired poets and writers,
and each of us,`` said Janet Cobb, who founded the California Oak
Foundation in 1988. ``But they are so much more than being a
beautiful tree. We have taken this entire ecosystem for granted.
Most people have grown up around oaks, and it's not until their
neighbor cuts one down or the bulldozers turn on in the morning in
Sonoma County that people become totally alarmed.``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
