<SLUG> BC-AMHIGH-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS, PARENTS SHOW TRUE COLORS ON NEW FOX SERIES
</HEADLINE>
  With AMHIGH-REVIEW 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who needs rat dinners, ruthless tribal alliances and sand in
your shorts when you've got high school?
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; ` &LR; Survivor' is like a joke in comparison,'' observes Robby
Nathan, high school graduate and one of the subjects in
documentarian R.J. Cutler's new series ``American High,'' examining
a year in the life of 14 teen-agers at a suburban Chicago high
school. Without having to contrive goofy immunity challenges or
melodramatically extinguish a single torch, Cutler's series
artfully captures the angst, joy and sheer confusion of coming of
age in America today.
</P>
<P>
   Cutler  &UR; _ &LR;  an Oscar nominee for ``The War Room'' and an Emmy
nominee for ``The Perfect Candidate''  &UR; _ &LR;  and his team approached
the generically named Highland Park outside of Chicago, discussed
the project with students, teachers and parents and even taught a
media course during the school year. Once taping wrapped  &UR; _ &LR;  with
the seniors' graduation
 &UR; _ &LR;  the school was given the cameras and an editing bay.
</P>
<P>
   Students didn't audition for the series per se, but they did
apply for the video-diary course set up by Cutler's team. ``From
the pool of kids which were selected for the independent study
class, which was about 20, 25 people, we then selected the kids who
we focused on,'' Cutler explains. The resulting 13 half-hour
episodes were culled from 2,800 hours of footage, 800 of it from
the students themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried to keep it as real as possible so they didn't
interrupt our normal living, I mean, except when you went to the
mall and people were, like, 'What's the camera crew doing,
following you around?' '' says Morgan Moss, depicted in the series
as a troubled and rebellious student suffering from and acting out
because of attention deficit disorder, who seems to find a calling
when he teaches gymnastics to disabled children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were struck right away by the fact that these guys became
acclimated more quickly than we had ever imagined,'' Cutler says.
``We thought at the beginning people would be jumping up and down
and waving their arms in the camera, which of course becomes very
tiring to do after two or three days, then it would go away. But we
didn't experience that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch the show, it's kind of like, 'Whoa  &UR; _ &LR;  my
life!' '' says Sarah Mages, who will be a senior at the school this
upcoming year. ``All the things we say are obviously true because
we said it, but it's definitely a shock, you know, to watch your
life on TV. Of course, I'm not embarrassed of my feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to be embarrassed of your own life,'' offers
Nathan, who, as the series begins, is dating Mages and fending off
her fears about their relationship when he leaves for college.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, I just opened up,'' Nathan recalls. ``And I
think it was just because I was so pissed off at school, adults,
everything involved (in what) people just don't understand in kids,
their bossing us around and telling us what to do. And I think
that's why I just opened up, because I want things to, like,
change, for people to realize that we might be 17 or 18, but, like,
we've got a lot going on in our head, more so than anyone thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss admits, ``My first reaction when I saw the episode was,
'Oh, great, I'm the bad-ass.' But other people were like, 'I can't
believe you went there. It was so good. What you said was amazing.'
And I was embarrassed at first, but when I got to see my peers'
reactions, it turned out that it was all worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a new breed, I guess, of person,'' Moss adds of his
depiction in the series. ``Because there's the me that goes off and
lights off fireworks and stuff and goes and does whatever he feels
would be fun. And then there's the sensitive side of me that, you
know, loves working with disabled kids. Like, that's my passion in
life. There's a little chunk of every emotion or side of me in (the
show). I couldn't just sit and break myself down.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss' father, Alan, who appears in episodes as a calm, wry
presence who occasionally can lose his temper with his son, says
the show is a fair representation of his son and their family. He
says he and his wife gave their son freedom and privacy to create
his video diaries as he wished. Seeing it now, he says, ``(My wife
and I) can look at each other and kind of nod and say, 'Yeah, I
suspected that was in there,' or 'I knew that was going to come out
at some point,' and seeing that he was honest enough with that
camera where he was not revealing to his parents, necessarily, but
revealing to everybody who might see this that this is the person
that he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a wonderful thing for Morgan for his senior year
because my contention has always been, 'If we can just get this kid
to survive high school, he's going to become who he needs to be,'
'' Moss' father adds drolly. ``And particularly for a kid who has
what you could kindly call an alternative learning method. There
are very few things he could do that would surprise us, in terms of
doing something that's totally off the edge because he's been
pushing the envelope since he was in daycare.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American High'' is the series that proves that the ``reality
TV'' moniker doesn't truly apply to ``Survivor'' or ``Big
Brother,'' the students agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 'The Real World,' `Survivor' and all those reality-based
shows, we're the closest one you can get to reality,'' Moss
observes. ``With 'Survivor,' yeah, it's reality, it's real people
and stuff, but it's all set up. They're on an island, they have to
survive, they're getting paid at the end. With `Big Brother,'
you're put in a house, you have to live with these people and vote
people out. With 'Real World,' same thing. We're living in our real
houses, this is the way our life is, we talk about what we're
really feeling, not like (mimicking a whiny 'Big Brother'
houseguest), `I feel bad that Timmy today was all weird,' or
something like that, you know?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
