<SLUG> BC-AMHIGH-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FOX `REALITY' SERIES PRESENTS TEENS UNCENSORED
</HEADLINE>
  With AMHIGH-FEATURE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``American High'' opens with a noisy eruption of attitude from
what appears to be an obnoxious, slightly sociopathic kid who
flails away arrhythmically at a drum kit and declares he has no
time for school; boys just want to have fun. Sit patiently through
this outburst _ a pretty obvious bid to grab the MTV demographic _
and soon enough, the social context becomes apparent. And not long
thereafter, you'll be utterly absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   Though this 13-episode series _ from respected documentarian
R.J. Cutler _ has the bad luck to come out during and get lumped in
with the current reality-TV trend, ``American High'' more closely
resembles the amazing 1994 documentary ``Hoop Dreams'' in its
sensitive, detail-oriented, multistory approach to examining issues
confronting teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Following a core of 14 kids at a middle-class, Chicago-area high
school, the show, in concise thumbnail sketches, vividly essays
their aspirations and fears, their triumphs and setbacks _ and how
their family lives and the school itself contribute to their
general sense of self in the world.
</P>
<P>
   That loud, seemingly simple-minded kid at the beginning, Morgan,
quickly becomes perhaps the series' most complex subject. He
berates his younger brother for doing homework and says he can
learn for himself what is and isn't dangerous _ his response to a
possible accident would be, he suggests, ``Now that I only have one
arm, I realize not to do that again.'' He's funny, he's defiant,
he's a dope.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, however, it's learned that Morgan suffers from attention
deficit disorder and hates his medicine, that he saves wrappers
from candy bars his girlfriend bought him and that he has an
affinity for teaching gymnastics to disabled kids. Add his largely
sympathetic but long-suffering family, and his story becomes
surprisingly moving.
</P>
<P>
   And Morgan's just part of the equation. In the first four
episodes, you'll also meet Robby and Sarah, a senior and junior who
are certain they're made for one another, which only adds to
Sarah's apprehension at Robby's going away to college the following
year. There's also Kiwi, a football place-kicker who uses his fear
of failure to pump him up and is oblivious to the fact that his
pretty pal Anna has a crush on him; he cluelessly approaches her
for advice on how to deal with an awkward dating situation.
</P>
<P>
   Two young women have problems as compelling as Morgan's. Suzy is
obsessed about her weight and pleasing her father, who, in a video
diary, jokes that he hasn't been able to hold his daughter on his
shoulders since she was 3 weeks old. The way her face falls is both
comic and crushing. Meanwhile, Allie understands her no-win
position in the complex dynamic of her parents' recent divorce, but
that hasn't stopped her from imperiling her grades with an epic
trail of truancies. (Most parents, it should be said, largely come
off as fairly empathetic here.)
</P>
<P>
   Brad, a young man who recently announced that he's gay, and
Kaytee, an aspiring coffee house singer of silly ditties, are also
introduced; more students will be introduced in later episodes.
</P>
<P>
   There's no artificial pressure-cooker clamped on these kids as
in ``Big Brother'' or ``Survivor''; the drama is real and therefore
far more riveting. Teens will enjoy watching themselves as they
truly are; parents should watch it to get a clue as to what their
kids are about these days. And anyone who's a fan of good, smart
television should tune in, too. &QL; 
---------------------------- &QL; 
The show: ``American High.'' &QL; 
What: Documentary examining a year in the life of a suburban
Chicago high school. &QL; 
Where: Fox (Channel 11). &QL; 
When: 9 and 9:30 p.m. Wednesdays. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9378 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-WONDER-BREAD-HNS &LR;      08-01 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONDER-BREAD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WONDER BREAD MAKER LOSES BIAS SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PETER HARTLAUB  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The baking giant that makes Wonder Bread must
pay 21 current and former employees $11 million _ and may have to
pay much more _ after a San Francisco jury determined that the
company discriminated against its workers.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, which reached its verdict earlier this week, also
found that Interstate Bakeries Corp., based in Kansas City, Mo.,
had acted with malice against the workers, which could lead to
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Alioto, attorney for the 18 of the plaintiffs, started
bear-hugging her clients after the verdict was read.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too cool, too cool,'' she said outside of court. ``Such a
great San Francisco jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Interstate Bakeries said the case was far from
over. The company released a statement pledging to get the jury
verdict thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will appeal the decision,'' the statement read. ``We
believe that substantial legal errors were committed in this trial
and fully expect to be exonerated on appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the workers claimed to have experienced discrimination in
Interstate Bakeries' San Francisco or Santa Clara facilities,
including racial slurs and being passed up for promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate Bakeries is the nation's largest wholesale baking
company, with 67 bread and cake bakeries located in strategic
markets from coast to coast. The company also makes Twinkies, Snow
Balls and other Hostess products.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty phase of trial, in which jurors will hear even more
evidence to determine how much Interstate Bakeries will pay in
punitive damages, started late Monday afternoon and will continue
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict Monday was for ``actual'' damages, including money
to compensate workers for lost pay and emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Dunhams, a 38-year-old shipping clerk who was awarded
$174,800, said he would train white workers at the San Francisco
Wonder Bread plant, knowing they would be promoted over him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're training someone, and you know in a few weeks they're
going to be your boss,'' he said. ``I've got two kids. I don't want
them to go through that.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs had been claiming discrimination at the plants
for up to 30 years. Interstate Bakeries took over the San Francisco
plant in 1995, after it was owned by Ralston/Purina, said IBC
attorney Kathleen Maylin.
</P>
<P>
   Maylin said the company was not responsible for acts that
happened when Interstate Bakeries was not running the plant, and
that the damages award could be altered accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict came after more than two months of trial and nine
days of deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto, a former San Francisco supervisor and daughter of former
mayor Joseph Alioto, said her clients received more than $8.5
million of the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The rest went to the three clients of attorney Waukeen McCoy, a
former member of Alioto's firm who is now in the middle of a legal
dispute with Alioto.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen of the plaintiffs first filed the suit in June 1998, and
six joined later.
</P>
<P>
   They claimed that the Bay Area Wonder Bread facilities no longer
hired black employees and did not promote the existing 31 black
employees beyond entry-level positions. Only one black employee had
obtained a foreman position, a job they claim no one else wanted.
</P>
<P>
   In their filing, they claimed that they were subjected to racial
and of degrading slurs. One worker was referred to as ``boy'' while
others were allegedly called ``too lazy'' by one supervisor,
according to the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The employees were allegedly told not to congregate as a group,
for fear they'd form a gang.
</P>
<P>
   Some employees claimed that they were ignored or punished when
they complained to management. The black employees were so
disheartened that they referred to the bakery as the ``White
House.``
</P>
<P>
   Interstate Bakeries denied the allegations, even after the trial
was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``IBC has a very hard-working and diverse work force at our San
Francisco bakery,'' Interstate Bakeries said in the statement.
``More than two-thirds of the work force are members of various
minority groups. Over the part 10 years minority promotional
advancement at this bakery has been proportional to this
representation.``
</P>
<P>
   Wonder Bread employs almost 700 workers at its bakery in San
Francisco and distribution plants in Oakland and San Jose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
