<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTONIA-MERI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESTONIA'S `UNPRESIDENT' SETS PERFECTIONIST GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROHUNEEME, Estonia _ Returning home from abroad several years
ago, President Lennart Meri stormed past reporters and aides into
the Tallinn airport's grimy public restroom. There, amid the stench
wafting from the fungus-caked urinals, Meri announced he was
holding a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   As baffled reporters crowded in, Meri declared that if Estonians
were ever going to be taken seriously by the world, they needed to
clean up their act, literally. Soviet-era squalor, like the airport
restroom, would have to become a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Tallinn's airport and its restrooms are as clean and
efficient as any in the United States. The incident speaks volumes
about Meri and his governing style, at times stern and impulsive,
at others wise and kindly. Tiny Estonia _ roughly the size of
Vermont and New Hampshire combined _ must ``strive to be perfect,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   The professorial Meri, with his wispy white hair, thick glasses,
sharp wit and quirky manners, is approaching his final year in
office. The only president Estonia has known since it regained its
independence from Russia in 1991, Meri remains one of Eastern
Europe's most popular leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In an age of prepackaged and overmanaged politicians, Meri, 71,
is the unpresident. He is impulsive and sometimes undiplomatic. He
doesn't talk in sound bites. What he does is speak his mind in a
way that makes John McCain's Straight Talk Express look like
politics as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Meri disdains pomp. He often shocks world leaders, and his own
people, with what many consider impolitic comments and behavior at
state functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to violate official protocol,'' Meri said, smiling,
during an interview at his home.
</P>
<P>
   And violate protocol he does. He once chastised former president
Bush, saying he lacked a coherent Baltic policy. In an Estonian
independence day speech, Meri broke the celebratory mood by urging
Estonians to vote out corrupt officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will gather this scum with a ladle and throw it in a slop
pail,'' he told the nation. ``We will do it until there is no more
scum left to gather.''
</P>
<P>
   Meri's personal diplomacy has been credited with winning Estonia
a coveted invitation to begin negotiations to join the European
Union. He also has lobbied relentlessly for membership in NATO,
saying that when it comes to security for his country, which has
been invaded by Hitler's Germany and Stalin's Soviet Union, half
measures are insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Security is like virginity,'' he said. ``Either you are a
virgin or you're not. You either have security or you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Informal almost to a fault, Meri is more comfortable in a
sweater and blue jeans planting apple trees in his garden than
attending an official function decked out in a suit. In the early
days of his presidency, aides said, he always carried a Swiss Army
knife with him and was constantly making repairs on doors and light
fixtures in the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy with the ornate and stuffy atmosphere of the palace,
Meri moved to the seaside town of Rohuneeme, where he designed and
helped build a less formal residence last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of all, I wanted my teenage daughter to have a normal
life. Her friends were intimidated by the palace and were afraid to
visit her there,'' Meri said.
</P>
<P>
   Walking around the grounds, Meri smoothly turns the conversation
from horticulture to European history, from the Internet to
Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his native Estonian, Meri speaks five languages
fluently: English, French, German, Russian, and Finnish. He has
translated authors as varied as Alexander Solzhenitsyn and Graham
Greene into Estonian.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a diplomat, Meri was a filmmaker, writer, and
anthropologist before he was elected president. In Meri's youth,
his family was briefly exiled to Siberia. He later traveled
extensively in the Soviet Far East, writing and making
documentaries about the Finno-Ugric peoples there, who speak a
language similar to Estonian.
</P>
<P>
   When the Baltic independence movement took hold in the late
1980s, Meri quickly took a leading role. After Estonia won its
independence. he served briefly as foreign minister and as
ambassador to Finland. In 1992, he was elected president. He was
reelected in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a country gets the leader it deserves, you could say that
Meri is even better than Estonia, or most countries for that
matter, deserves,'' said Michael Tarm, editor of City Paper, an
English-language newsmagazine based in Tallinn.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his presidency, Meri was criticized for his blunt
style. He infuriated prime ministers and Parliament by meddling in
the country's day-to-day governance. But his popularity has
steadily increased and now hovers between 70 percent and 80
percent. As he prepares to leave office, he leaves a perplexed
nation, said Merle Kutt, a travel agent in Tallinn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard,'' Kutt said, ``to imagine anybody else as our
president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
