<HEADER>
A9398 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-01 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT THING YOU SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This month's prize for language trend-spotting goes to Lee
Schlesinger, who recently wrote to ask which was the right word in
the expression, ``If that's what she thinks, she has another
think/thing coming.'' Schlesinger had seen it both ways in print,
he said, so newspapers were no help.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing coming? You've got to be kidding, I thought. Maybe
a few typos, even a few misapprehensions, had made it into print.
But surely most people had heard _ on Nickelodeon, if not in life _
the stern warning, ``If you think you're going out dressed like
that, young lady, you've got another think coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, did I have another think coming. As it turns out,
confusion reigns in the media about this phrase. Over the past 25
years, it's appeared in newpapers and magazines as another thing
coming about one time in three. That's far too high a proportion to
blame on typos and mishearings; it means there's a sizable group of
writers and editors who really think it's thing.
</P>
<P>
   What swamp did this thing crawl out of? It predates Judas
Priest, the heavy metal band, so we can't blame them _ but they
helped the neologism along by calling a 1983 tune ``You've Got
Another Thing Comin'.'' And an odd musical coincidence suggests
that the early '80s may have been the tipping point for
think/thing: Only a couple of years before Judas Priest's hit, Bill
Holland wrote and performed a song called ``You've Got Another
Think Comin'.'' Holland, now Washington bureau chief of Billboard,
calls his creation ``a 4/4 medium tempo finger-snapper'' that
``owes a lot to Mose Allison.'' But the thing was already
encroaching: The Washington Post reviewer who caught Holland's act
transcribed his title as ``Another Thing Coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its origin, another thing coming is well entrenched,
especially among writers too young to have been told they had
another think coming. When readers tried to enlighten Laurie
Notaro, an Arizona Republic columnist, about the correct usage, she
didn't even bother to check it out _ she just told them they were
wrong, citing Judas Priest as her authority. (To be fair, this
doesn't mean she's a total idiot; her column is intended to get a
rise out of readers, and it does.)
</P>
<P>
   But metalhead etymology, in this case, is off by a century.
Think, though primarily a verb, is also colloquially used as a
noun; the first citation in the Oxford English Dictionary is dated
1834. In a late-19th-century example, an unnamed character proposes
``a cigar and a quiet think.'' This conscious appropriation of a
verb for noun use is nothing out of the ordinary; the same process
gives us ``a nice little lie-down'' (mainly English) and ``give it
a good leaving alone.'' To have another think coming comes along in
1937, as an American synonym for ``be mistaken,'' but it may have
been used decades earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, though, the meaning apparently faded. Is this because
parents stopped putting their feet down? Do we blame the boomers?
No matter: Once you have enough listeners who don't understand the
original phrase, it's easy to see how another think becomes another
thing. When the k in think butts up against the k sound in coming,
something's got to give, phonologically. Unless you're an annoyed
parent, enunciating carefully, the two k sounds will merge into
thin(g)koming.
</P>
<P>
   That's a normal process when consonants collide _ we pronounce
rank order as rangkorder and last temptation as lass temptation _
but the change can mislead a listener who doesn't know the words.
When Notaro told her readers, ``It's not `You have another think
coming,' unless you're watching reruns of `Hogan's Heroes,' '' she
was probably hearing think with the final k stressed _ sounding
like a sitcom German accent (or a very fed-up mom). But we don't
ordinarily pronounce that k. We're just supposed to know it's
there, if we're literate.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, it doesn't pay to get exercised about the evolution
of language. We all use expressions that our ancestors called
barbaric, and many of our bugbears will someday be standard. But
another thing coming is a real test of tolerance; ``You've got
another think coming'' is so clearly superior to the nonsense
variant nipping at its heels. So let's put aside, for the moment,
the correct use of graduate and the true meaning of beg the
question, and concentrate on propping up this time-honored idiom.
If you think the job will be easy, you've got another think coming.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Word appears every other week through summer. E-mail Jan
Freeman at freeman(at)globe.com, or write to her at The Boston
Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
