<HEADER>
A9401 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS &LR;      08-01 1753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN NEVER SPEND ENOUGH TIME IN AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLYING TO NAIROBI _ Snow-bonneted Mount Kenya lies below like a
gigantic rhino, seemingly intent on piercing the skin of the
single-engine Cessna with at least one of its triple horns
extending. But Stuart Hutchis, the Air Kenya pilot, has managed to
miss the majestic 17,058-foot landmark countless times, and,
thankfully, this is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kwa heri, Mount Kenya. Goodbye,'' says my friend, Aurelio,
showing off her Swahili. ``It's a wrench to leave. To leave Kenya.
To leave Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Agreed. This wondrous, troubled continent yet tops my visitation
list after eight excursions, sampling a dozen countries. Not
enough. Never enough.
</P>
<P>
   As the plane moves toward Nairobi, the departure point for
London, then Boston, so many memories crowd the neural mush. Most
of them terrific. Some apprehensive: concerns about the wildlife,
and more so about the friendly people of Zimbabwe, being led deeper
by the tyrant Robert Mugabe into the abyss of AIDS, unemployment,
inflation, corruption, shortages, and despair.
</P>
<P>
   What a wonderful country it would be if the president were as
concerned about his compatriots (other than his cronies), reform,
and the general welfare as he is about his own power and wealth. Of
course, sadly, that could be said about numerous leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys, like Mugabe,'' said an official at the US embassy,
``are scared of the people and what might happen to them if they
don't keep tight control. They've had bloody examples. They were
chilled by the beating Clinton took in the impeachment _ and that
was in a real democracy. It could go worse for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe put on a benign, welcoming face for American consumption
when Zimbabwe entertained the US Davis Cup team, knowing that he
would unleash the scripted terror when the tourists departed.
Though Zimbabwe is rife with attractions, an important source of
revenue, Mugabeism is likely to repel travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Falls is prime, one of those unique sites, like the Taj
Mahal, that exceeds expectations. ``You know it'll be very good,''
says Aurelio, ``and then you find the falls is even more
spectacular than its reputation. What about that double rainbow in
the mist on the Zambian side?
</P>
<P>
   ``And the Victoria Falls Hotel _ continuing in its Victorian
elegance _ is such a treat. The immaculate rooms, corridors, and
gardens . . . the view, from the magnificently tiled and landscaped
swimming pool _ the panorama of the falls foaming in the
distance.''
</P>
<P>
   At the nearby crocodile farm, the residents could use
orthodontists for their overbites, but won't find many volunteers.
You prowl catwalks just above a mob of them and shiver peering into
the stony eyes of these killers frequenting the local Zambezi
River.
</P>
<P>
   A guide named Jackson said, ``They look lazy, but fall in and
you'll get a response. There,'' he said, pointing out a star of the
pack, a 17-footer, ``that chap is 66 years old and keeps 17
females.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What a dirty old croc,'' said Aurelio.
</P>
<P>
   As Hutchis, our pilot, approaches Nanyuki, Kenya, I think again
of Harare and the gifted artists like Daniel Baradza at the
Chapungu Sculpture Gardens. Their studio is the outdoors where they
work in rain, sun, whatever weather, creating beguiling pieces out
of several shades of basalt. Roy Guthrie, the director, provides
stone for sculptors too poor to buy it. You wonder how they'll make
out if tourists are frightened away.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from them is another man in an al-fresco studio, the
engaging, bearded Don Black, who teaches tennis on his superb
backyard grass courts. He's a bargain at $8 an hour. Because this
Black is white, are he and his lush property endangered? He hopes
not. Since he has sired three world- class players _ Byron, Wayne,
and Cara Black _ who have brought acclaim to Zimbabwe, chances are
they're safe. But who knows with Mugabe?
</P>
<P>
   Hutchis descends to pick up more passengers, saying, ``We don't
land on the first pass. Have to look around to make sure the runway
is clear of animals.'' A week before, an elephant meandering on the
strip at Kariba had priority. That plane on which we rode circled,
waiting him out.
</P>
<P>
   The equator crosses Kenya at Nanyuki, a town that toes that
line. There, much earlier, we had encountered the enterprising,
self-anointed PhD in physics, Patrick Mutua. For five bucks, he
will demonstrate the scientific mysteries of water flowing
perversely on either side of the Big E. At no extra charge, he
threw in a certificate testifying that the possessor has, indeed,
straddled the earth's belt.
</P>
<P>
   Producing a pitcher of water, two bowls with drain holes, and
match sticks to float in the opposing currents, Mutua poured.
``Note the swirling water spinning the match sticks,'' he directed.
``On the north side of the equator the water moves clockwise, and
goes down the drain that way, as in your Boston. But on the south _
counterclockwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely. Awesome. At the least a Nobel Prize demonstration. I
told him it would be more dramatic (and profitable) if he used two
tubs, occupied by bathing beauties.
</P>
<P>
   From Nanyuki we had plunged into the Kenyan bush on safari,
getting the real African feel: bum-busting jaunts over cratered
make-believe roads and would-be tracks. ``We rent from Hurts,''
said one of the skilled drivers, Paul Mundati, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only hurts when you close your eyes,'' said Kim Edmunds, an
Ohio refugee now a professional guide, one of four such accredited
women. She meant that the countryside and its animal inhabitants
are so compelling they divert your mind from the jouncing.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of escape from so-called civilization can be
addicting, as Kim, never intending to stay, discovered. She
cherishes the spot where she was married. Anyone would. Her hilltop
on the Lewa Downs reserve with a basalt slab as altar and Mount
Kenya as witness, offers a forever vista of untamed grandeur. A
rugged climb, and worth it. Many of the guests appeared in formal
black-and-white garb: herds of zebra seeming as fond of the remote
sanctuary as Kim.
</P>
<P>
   The Danish writer Isak Dinesen (a.k.a. Meryl Streep in ``Out of
Africa'') captured the essence of bush wandering well, often in
letters to relatives: ``There is something about safari life that
makes you forget all your sorrows, and feel the whole time as if
you had drunk half a bottle of champagne _ bubbling over with
heartfelt gratitude for being alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``One only feels free when one can go in whatever direction one
pleases . . . pitch one's camp with the knowledge that one can fall
asleep beneath other trees with another view before one the next
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have spent four weeks in the happy hunting grounds, and have
just emerged from the depths of great wide open spaces, from the
life of pre-historic times, today just as it was a thousand years
ago, from meeting with the great beasts of prey, which enthrall
one, which obsess one so that one feels the lions are all that one
lives for _ strengthened by the air of the high mountain region . .
. filled with its wild, free, magnificent beauty in heat dazzling
days, in clear moonlit nights.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not quite so prehistoric as in her day. Our plane cruises
above land increasingly under cultivation and burgeoning villages,
indications that the bush is being squeezed constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless the incomparable safari experience remains, as
dealt by those faithful to preservation, like Will and Emma Craig,
proprietors of Lewa Downs, the vast conservation territory in the
Central Highlands, and their chief guide, Phil West. And by Ron
Beaton, the savvy ex-hunter who operates Rekero Camp in the Masai
Mara.
</P>
<P>
   Indelible is the wonder and elation of trudging and driving the
wilds with them. They still have a great hand to play, shuffling a
deck of brilliant wild cards _ lions, giraffes, elephants,
buffaloes, rhinos, hippos, leopards _ as well as a supporting cast
of zebras, wildebeests, hyenas, warthogs, a stunning variety of
antelopes, and more different birds than you could shake an
Audubonian tome at.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingwayesque, but Hemingway himself might not have liked it as
much since hunting has been banned in Kenya for several years. Not
that walking the neighborhood is always a stroll in the park.
That's why chaperones West and Beaton carry high-powered rifles.
One of Beaton's men, Salaton Kileya, will, on request, proudly show
you his scarred backside, barely retrieved from a lion. ``
`Half-ass Salaton,' we call him,'' says a colleague.
</P>
<P>
   My thoughts also go back to the 335 wonderful barefoot kids at
Ntugi Primary School, near Lewa Downs. Classrooms, dirt-floored
sheds of sheet metal and planking with no electricity or running
water, are nonetheless rare and lucky places filled with eagerness
to learn, and dedicated teachers working with primitive equipment
(bottle caps are used to teach counting).
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowledge is the Key to Success,'' says the prominent sign put
up by the tireless headmaster, John Ngeera. He attended this school
himself not long after its founding in 1969, and was taught by
jovial Katherine Kathurima, who remains as a guiding force.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lewa supports this and three other area schools, they
aren't sufficient. Most rural kids don't make it to school at all.
Will Craig said, ``We do what we can, and hope to do more. We'll
take any help we can get from anywhere.'' (Lewa Wildlife
Conservancy, Private Bag, Isiolo, Kenya.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We lack the basic tools, but we have spirit,'' said Ngeera,
and that was clear as he took us around.
</P>
<P>
   One helping hand is that of the Zoological Society of
Milwaukee's Foundation for Wildlife Conservation. Their current
project, said director Gil Boese (10005 West Bluemound Road,
Milwaukee, WI 53226) is building a pipeline from a reservoir to
Ntugi so that the school will have water for drinking and planting
a garden, and the kids won't have to schlep it, as now, five miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``An important subject in these schools is conservation,'' said
Boese. ``It's vital that the future community leaders, these kids,
learn the importance of preserving the wildlife, a great resource
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   You look into these young faces and pray they'll be part of
helping turn their country and continent onto a better path. They
stay with you, along with their cheery, hopeful response to life:
``Hakuna matata'' _ no problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
