<HEADER>
A9403 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-HOSPITAL-STRIKE-HNS &LR;      08-01 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-STRIKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BAY AREA HOSPITAL WORKERS POISED TO STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By ERIC BRAZIL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ More than than 3,000 workers at seven Bay Area
hospitals are poised to strike Wednesday for the second time in
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Rank-and-file health care workers represented by Local 250 of
the Service Employees International Union plan a two-day strike in
an escalating campaign for new contracts with Sutter Health and
Catholic Healthcare West.
</P>
<P>
   The union conducted a one-day strike on July 6, and management
spokesmen for both hospital chains say that they'll be better
prepared to cope with the next one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not prepared to put our patients at risk again,'' said
Carolyn Kemp, spokeswoman for Sutter Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to bring in replacement workers if need be.
We're not going to transfer patients as before . . . We are working
with some agencies to bring in temporary staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Polzoni, vice president for marketing of Catholic
Healthcare West, said, ``We've been ramping down the number of
patients in the hospital. Our (registered) nurses aren't striking,
and that will let us take care of patients. The emergency room will
stay open. We're confident that we can provide care to everyone who
needs it.''
</P>
<P>
   Local 250, which has 50,000 members statewide, insists that the
principal issue impeding contract settlement is patient care _ that
management refuses to give workers an effective voice in staffing
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp and Polzoni said their hospitals had committees in which
rank-and-file workers had a voice in all patient care issues, but
that the committees never meetS _ in large part because the union
members show no interest in their agendas.
</P>
<P>
   But Deborah Covington, a dietary aide and shop steward at
Sutter's Summit Medical Center in Oakland, said the problem was
that the committees ``look good on paper but they don't function.
When you get with these committees, we make no progress, and the
issues just lie there... We want the right to bring in neutral
parties to look at issues and then decide. They (management) don't
want us to have that right.''
</P>
<P>
   Wages are not an issue at the Sutter Health hospitals, but
retirement is. ``We have a very crappy retirement program,''
Covington said. ``One of my co-workers just retired, and right away
she had to go looking for work because she didn't have enough to
live on.''
</P>
<P>
   Wages are an issue at Catholic Healthcare West's St. Francis
Memorial Hospital and St. Mary's Medical Center in San Francisco
and Seton Medical Center in Daly City, both sides agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catholic Healthcare West pays the lowest salaries in the Bay
Area,'' said Local 250 spokeswoman Christy Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Healthcare West has offered the union's workers a 12
percent salary increase spread over the next four years. The union
is asking for ``more than we can afford,'' Polzoni said.
</P>
<P>
   Local 250 represents housekeepers, respiratory therapists,
licensed vocational nurses, clerks and a variety of technicians.
Nurses at the hospitals about to be struck are members of the
California Nurses Association, and whether they'll cross the picket
lines is a decision to be made by the individual RNs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
