<HEADLINE>
SPRUCED-UP WASHINGTON MONUMENT REOPENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER WALSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For years, Katie Dallman, 11, and her 12-year-old
sister, Natalie, have been fascinated with the Washington Monument
_ building paper models, watching television specials, and studying
its history.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a recent school project on the 112-year-old obelisk
that helped make the Dallman family the first visitors inside the
monument since it was closed 18 months ago to repair damage caused
by weather and time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got tickets on the Internet when Katie and Natalie were
researching the monument,'' said Steve Dallman, the girls' father
and vice president of a chemical company. ``When the confirmation
came back, it said 9 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 9 Monday, rangers with the National Park Service
escorted the first batch of visitors to the 555-foot monument,
which now features a less-obstructed view from the observation
deck, a graffiti-free interior, and a repaired marble exterior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like getting a new car,'' said Ernie Price, a ranger with
the park service. ``It's new and fresh and clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Lines for tickets, which designated a day and time to enter the
monument, started forming before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``A line is not unusual, but normally half the size is
considered long,'' said Price, who estimated that about 1,000
people would visit the monument Monday.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the six-member Dallman family, of Chesterfield, Mo.,
took the 70-second elevator ride to the top of the monument, a line
of about 300 people was moving along concrete paths leading to the
booth that was handing out a limited number of free tickets. Some
tickets are available in advance through a commercial agency for a
small fee.
</P>
<P>
   For Robert and Roberta Murray, of Auburn, Calif., the
hour-and-a-half wait in line is worth the nostalgia, as well as the
eagle's eye view of the White House, Lincoln Memorial, and Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to wait,'' Roberta Murray said. ``It's just a
very special site. It's very important for our liberty and knowing
who it's honoring.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Monument, which attracts 1.2 million people
annually, is not the only Washington edifice getting a makeover _
the Lincoln Memorial, the Capitol, and the Jefferson Memorial are
undergoing repairs.
</P>
<P>
   But the work on the city's tallest structure took on special
prominence because of the artistic aluminum-and-nylon scaffolding
that surrounded the monument during the renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the less-obvious refurbishments to the Washington
Monument were inside and included replacing the heating,
electrical, and air conditioning systems; patching chips in the
walls, cracks and water spots; and preserving the 193 commemorative
stones.
</P>
<P>
   The observation desk now features educational exhibits and
showcases two replicas of artifacts _ the aluminum cap on top of
the monument and a donation box that raised funds for the
marble-and-granite structure, which was built in 1884 and opened in
1888.
</P>
<P>
   Security also has been improved. Now visitors must pass through
a metal detector, and bags are searched by hand. Concrete barriers
prevent vehicles from getting near the monument.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the monument reopened Monday, the renovations are
not finished. It will close again in December for two months so
workers can replace the elevator with one that has glass panels.
This will allow better viewing of the commemorative stones,
including a solid jade representing Alaska that is worth millions
of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The $10 million cost of the face lift, which started in late
1997, was funded by a partnership of public and private entities.
It was the first major repair project on the towering Washington
figure since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Besides unusually long lines, there was nothing extraordinary
about the reopening of the monument, no fanfare or ceremonies. But
for the Dallman family, the trip would be something they will never
forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just glad to be a part of it, and it really made (the
trip) special,'' said Steve Dallman, who then pointed to his
children. ``It's something they can tell their grandchildren
about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
