<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO APES GET SCHIZOPHRENIA? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Are animals other than humans _ the great apes, for example _
known to have serious psychiatric conditions such as schizophrenia,
manic depression, etc.?
</P>
<P>
   J.B. Framingham, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, humans are by no means the only creatures that have
mental disorders. That this happens is important as it provides
animal models for human illnesses and plays an important role in
finding new treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from this, there are also accepted treatments for the
animal disorders themselves. For example, the US Food and Drug
Administration has approved the antidepressant clomipramine for use
on dogs to alleviate separation anxiety, the stress dogs feel when
they are left alone. Selegiline, another drug used to treat humans
for Parkinson's disease, also was approved to treat age-related
mental deterioration in dogs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail questions to drknowledge(at)globe.com; or send fax to:
617-929-9263, or a letter to Dr. Knowledge, in care of The Boston
Globe, Health/Science Section, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107.
Please include your initials and hometown. Selected questions of
general interest will be answered.
</P>
</TEXT>
