<HEADER>
A9414 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-RACE-UNIVERSITIES-BOS     08-01 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-UNIVERSITIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGES CUT RACE'S ROLE IN ADMISSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICK HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With an upcoming courtroom showdown and a presidential election
raising the stakes, affirmative action at state universities across
the nation has reached a turning point, as a growing number of
colleges gut or abolish boosts given to minority applicants,
particularly blacks and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since affirmative action became widespread,
freshmen planning to attend the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst and the University of Virginia this fall were not admitted
under policies that college officials acknowledge heavily benefited
some minority students with mediocre grades or test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Both schools have sharply reduced the role that race plays in
admissions, officials said. But because of aggressive recruiting
and revised admissions criteria, neither expect sharp dropoffs in
minority numbers this fall. Yet academic disparities among students
remain: For example, among the middle 50 percent of University of
Virginia incoming freshmen, black students' Scholastic Assessment
Test scores were about 200 points lower than those of white
students.
</P>
<P>
   UMass's previous policy helped spur a 13 percent increase in the
number of minorities at Amherst from 1995-99. The number of whites
enrolled fell by 9.3 percent _ or nearly 1,400 students _ during
that time.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Blaustein, UMass-Amherst's director of institutional
research, attributed the falling white enrollments to aggressive
diversity policies and changing demographics statewide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a trend we were expecting or hoping for, given the
commitment to diversity,'' Blaustein said. ``That was the direction
we were hoping to go.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, Florida's 10 public universities officially stopped
using preferences in admissions. Instead, they are taking all
applicants ranked in the top 20 percent of state high schools _ a
policy that relies on schools that are largely black or Hispanic to
guarantee pools of minority students. For example, for a mainly
Hispanic high school with 200 seniors, the top 20 percent policy
would guarantee admission to 40 students, many of whom would
probably be Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Although officials at many selective universities acknowledge
that some minority students have weaker academic records than some
white students who were rejected, they say the need for diversity
justifies the school policies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, preference policies have also been watered down because
of legal threats such as one that rocked the University of Georgia
recently, when a federal judge declared its affirmative action
policy unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   In language that reverberated throughout higher education, US
District Judge B. Avant Edenfield overruled a 22-year-old legal
precedent used by the college to defend affirmative action. The
desire for campus diversity, he said, was not important enough to
justify favoring minority students because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   ``To base racial preferences upon an amorphous, unquantifiable,
and temporally unlimited goal is to engage in naked racial
balancing,'' Edenfield wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Other rulings, particularly one by a federal appeals court in a
University of Texas case, have limited when state colleges can
favor members of one race over others. Most elite private colleges,
citing their independent status, still factor in race when
admitting students.
</P>
<P>
   Also driving the changes were the election of governors in
California, Virginia, Texas, and Florida who opposed affirmative
action programs. From that political environment emerged new
college trustees who saw racial preferences as discriminatory
against white students, and changed the policies in spite of campus
protests. Meanwhile, some voters have voiced their opposition to
affirmative action, with California banning the policy in 1996 and
Washington State approving a similar ban in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of affirmative action on campus, many agree, will
sooner or later be in the hands of the US Supreme Court. Partisans
on both sides of the issue see the election of the next president
as critical: the appointment of new justices could sway whether
race matters when future college admissions are decided.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial politics is a factor at the University of Georgia, as
officials mull an appeal of the ruling. Some are concerned that
eventually a majority of Supreme Court justices will find holes in
Georgia's admissions policy and rule sweepingly, ending affirmative
action at all colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the court to take one of the affirmative action
cases in the next several years,'' said Theodore M. Shaw,
associate-director counsel of the NAACP Legal Defense Fund, which
worked on the Georgia case. Because the law is now unclear, he
added, ``other institutions have panicked and cut and run from
affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   One that hasn't is the University of Michigan at Ann Arbor,
which is slated to go to trial in September over how it weighs race
when admitting undergraduates.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Bollinger, the university's president, said many college
leaders believe diversity is essential. But he is spending millions
of dollars to convince a federal court _ and the public _ that an
enriched college education requires a critical mass of minority
students on campus _ even if some have lower test scores or grades
than white applicants, who are rejected.
</P>
<P>
   On the Michigan campus, a majority of freshmen arrive from
all-white or all-black high schools, some never having analyzed a
novel or researched a history project with a member of another
race. ``The universities of this country have performed an
important role in our society _ helping youth see the world through
different eyes,'' Bollinger said.
</P>
<P>
   But at what price? Judy Hample, the executive vice chancellor at
the State University System of Florida, said resentments stirred by
what some see as playing favorites with applicants come at a high
cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an inherent unfairness in looking at race or gender
preferences in admissions,'' Hample said. ``The only time that's
justified is when you have current effects of some past
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida officials recently sent letters guaranteeing admission
to Florida students who graduated in the top 20 percent of their
high school class. About 13 percent of them are black and 14
percent are Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this tells students,'' Hample said, ``is you're not going
to be admitted because of the color of your skin. You're going to
get in because you're able to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   But students like Seth Avakian at UMass-Amherst say that racial
preferences ensure that colleges can create the learning
environment they think is essential. Such an environment influenced
him, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Concord-Carlisle (Mass.) High School, Avakian said, he never
really noticed that the resources, education, and family incomes
were substantial, but the diversity was lacking.
</P>
<P>
   His years in the dormitories at UMass-Amherst changed that. Some
students were once foster children. Some were financially on their
own. And the mix of ethnicities was jarring: He had grown up mainly
with white youths, except for some minority classmates who made it
to town from Boston via Metco, a racial desegregation program.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Concord bubble was burst,'' Avakian said. ``I realized
there was a real need for social justice, and that involved
creating greater equality among the races.''
</P>
<P>
   Having earned a bachelor's degree from UMass-Amherst a year ago
and now a graduate student there, Avakian said he sometimes wishes
his school took the stand that the University of Michigan did. But
as a student trustee as well, he thinks the financial risks would
have been too great.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of affirmative action say the Georgia ruling and the
steps taken by UMass and others are a sign of things to come: A
recognition nationwide that colleges decide the future of some
students on the basis of race _ and that the courts and voters will
continue to say: no more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chickens are coming home to roost,'' said Terry Pell, a
lawyer for the Center for Individual Rights, which brought the case
against Michigan. ``When you peel away the rhetoric about diversity
and look at what schools are actually doing, they're engaging in
racial mixing to get a certain group of students. And you can't
just gerrymander to get that mix.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
