<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9415 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-RICH-SISTERS-BOS &LR;      08-01 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-SISTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SISTERS OF CHARITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SANDY COLEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even in death, former schoolteachers Agnes and Margaret
O'Donnell are offering lessons: Live your life. Spend wisely.
Invest well. Remember to love.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the messages reverberating in the wake of their
absence as townsfolk marvel over what the two humble Northampton,
Mass. women left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Besides good memories, the O'Donnell sisters left money _ $2.4
million of it _ to 10 groups, including their church, schools they
attended, and a Boy Scout troop that served them some good pancakes
at Sunday morning fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters began plans to disburse the money 10 years ago, says
their lawyer, Robert Carey. The lucky beneficiaries learned about
their unexpected windfall in late July, after the sisters' estate
was finally settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just shocked,'' said Michael Pasternak, scout master of
Boy Scout Troop No. 103. ``It was impressive that someone who
didn't have any firm connection with the troop would leave a
donation for us.''
</P>
<P>
   But how in the world did they do it?
</P>
<P>
   Between the two of them, the sisters spent nearly 100 years
teaching elementary students in and around Florence, the
Northampton village where they were born. The younger of the two,
Agnes, died in 1997 at age 94. Margaret died last year at 100.
</P>
<P>
   When they retired in their 70s they were making around $8,500
per year, says Kathleen Sheehan, a close friend and former
principal of Leeds Elementary School, where Agnes taught for 49
years and Margaret taught for a few.
</P>
<P>
   And, even though the women lived modestly _ drove midsize
American cars, kept their childhood home, squeezed every year they
could out of their classic clothing _ they were not penny-pinchers
by any means.
</P>
<P>
   So, many are wondering, how did they amass $2.4 million on such
limited incomes?
</P>
<P>
   ``How could two schoolteachers, especially in their day,
accumulate this?'' asked the Rev. Roy Duquette of Annunciation
Roman Catholic Church, where the two sisters were parishioners.
</P>
<P>
   Wise investments, most people guess.
</P>
<P>
   And they are right.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 20 years of their lives, there was no need to
spend a lot of money. They were consummate savers. They lived in
the house they grew up in. And Margaret had some good investments,
which grew over time,'' said Bob Wolanske, Margaret's broker, who
is vice president of investments for A.G. Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Agnes and Margaret O'Donnell's father owned a grocery store on
Main Street. He died when the women were in their teens, and their
mother died six months later. They and a now-deceased brother then
went to live with their uncle and aunt in the house they eventually
inherited.
</P>
<P>
   Agnes, the more outgoing of the two sisters, cooked the meals.
It was the more serious Margaret who had a keen sense for making
money, say friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Margaret enjoyed stocks,'' said Wolanske, recalling that the
first time she walked up two flights of stairs to his office, she
was in her 80s, but looked about 75.
</P>
<P>
   She walked in, ``threw three papers on my desk, and said, `What
should I do with these dogs?,' '' referring to stocks that had not
done well, Wolanske said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Margaret didn't even have a will, Wolanske said,
and only a few stocks. But over time her portfolio bloomed to
include a collection of blue-chip stocks like General Electric,
tax-exempt bonds, and utility stocks, including some telephone
companies.
</P>
<P>
   She rarely touched any of the earnings, Wolanske said. But when
Agnes' health began to fail near the end of her life, Margaret
moved her to an assisted living facility and moved in with her.
(After her sister's death, Margaret moved right back to the house
the unmarried sisters grew up in.)
</P>
<P>
   Anytime Wolanske suggested some ways to spend some of the
earnings, Margaret would respond, ``I've done it all,'' Wolanske
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the sisters did not sit around saving foil or gift-wrap
paper to stretch a buck, notes friend and local historian Jim
Parsons.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they had a 19-inch black and white TV. And Margaret, known
for her heavy foot, drove a white Buick. Agnes, whom kids
affectionately called ``hot rod Aggie'' because you could barely
see her petite body behind the steering wheel, last drove a gray
Chevrolet sedan. The two ate out with friends often. Margaret
frequently flew to Europe, while Agnes, who hated to fly, drove
cross-country several times.
</P>
<P>
   But even as she indulged herself, Margaret also was practical.
Parsons recalls stories of her bringing back figurines from her
travels to sell to friends.
</P>
<P>
   While Agnes loved teaching, her sister always was one to take on
a second job, said Sheehan, including working as a hostess at a
local restaurant and building machinery at a Springfield, Mass.
armory during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Although people are surprised by the amount the two left, they
are not surprised by the act. In death, say friends, the O'Donnells
are doing just what they did in life: giving.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations they left money to underscore what they loved
in life: education, young people, and helping the less fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   Agnes is remembered as a woman who dedicated herself to visiting
sick friends. And Margaret's name is etched on a plaque at Cooley
Dickinson Hospital in Northampton. As a volunteer from 1969 to
1995, she worked 10,619 hours in the hospital's gift and coffee
shops. Only eight others have volunteered 10,000 hours or more.
</P>
<P>
   Gift shop manager Sharon Masters recalled a blizzard that
dropped at least a foot of snow and kept most people home. But
around 4 p.m., said Masters, ``in walked Margaret, and she was in
her 90s then. I said, `Margaret, how did you get here?' She said,
`Well, I drove, how do you think?' ''
</P>
<P>
   A stunned Masters asked the natural follow-up question: ``But
how did you get out of the driveway?''
</P>
<P>
   Said Margaret: ``I shoveled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Masters said, ``was typical Margaret.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
