<P>
   &UR; MANAGEMENT PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HONEST-TEA (Undated) _ It hardly seems the stuff consumer
thrills are made of: a weak, watery tea, brewed the old-fashioned
way, with hardly any sugar and even less caffeine. Marketing? There
is almost none. Television ads and celebrity endorsements? Zero.
Still, when Barry Nalebuff, a professor of game theory at the Yale
School of Management, and Seth Goldman, a former student started
Honest Tea two years ago, they were well aware that they would be
competing against teas made and marketed by the Coca-Colas,
Pepsi-Colas and Snapples of the world. But they also saw their
product as distinct enough from the brands of those giants to
attract a different customer. For Nalebuff, the development of
Honest Tea has been an eye-opening foray into the real world of
supply and demand, a world few academics get to experience day in
and day out. For Goldman, it has been a chance to see his former
teacher in a new light. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAMS-MAGIC (Undated) _ Pat Williams, senior vice president
of the Orlando Magic.
</P>
