<HEADLINE>
FOR THE HOLLOW CREATURES, IT HELPS TO BE INVISIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODS HOLE, Mass. _ From ``The Invisible Man'' in the 1950s to
this summer's ``Hollow Man,'' it has been a widespread fantasy and
a subject of literary and cinematic storytelling: the idea of
becoming completely transparent, able to observe anything and
anyone without the risks of being seen.
</P>
<P>
   For humans, it's just a daydream. But in the ocean it is not
just a fantasy but a fact of life; In fact, it is the norm.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is difficult to make a count of creatures that you
can't see, it is quite possible that invisible swimming creatures
are, in fact, more numerous than any of the animals on this planet
that can be seen. Transparent beings may be the dominant form of
life on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as two or three decades ago, nobody knew most of
these gelatinous sea creatures even existed. Some, such as
jellyfish, were well known; others had been seen in fragments
hauled up in fishing nets, but because they are so fragile and
incapable of surviving or holding their shape in air, and because
they quickly turn opaque when they die, their nature remained a
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Now, new species of such beings are turning up with increasing
frequency, and scientists are learning just how crucial their role
in marine ecosystems is. They include a dizzying variety of
different types of animals, including jellyfish, squid, worms,
crustaceans, snails and exotic types unlike any of the familiar
denizens of the deep; what they all have in common is transparent
bodies, usually made possible by gelatinous body parts and
specially designed skin and internal organs. They inhabit the vast
region of the oceans far offshore, from just below the surface to
just above the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, they are known as gelatinous zooplankton. Although
plankton are usually thought of as tiny creatures too small to see,
the term actually encompasses all marine animals that can't swim
strongly enough to control where they go.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their physical weakness, much of the life that exists
down below on the ocean floor may depend on them. They help to
transport food sources from the ocean surface to the bottom in part
by digesting it and concentrating nutrients in their waste. They
also serve as an abundant food source for predators.
</P>
<P>
   But they can also cause ecological harm: Fisheries in the Black
Sea have collapsed because of the introduction of a type of
jellyfish-like transparent marine organism called a ctenophore _
probably brought there accidentally in a ship's ballast _ that has
no natural predators there. Meanwhile, Georges Bank has suffered
from a bloom of a kind of jellyfish larvae, called hydroids, that
kills juvenile codfish, whose numbers are already severely reduced
from years of over-fishing.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to get to know these evanescent will-o-the-wisps of
life is to join them, by diving or using robotic or piloted
submersibles far out in the open ocean. That's what Sonke Johnsen
and Laurence Madin of the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution and
a handful of other researchers have been doing to learn about these
hidden beings that may dominate our biosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Only by going out into the open ocean, Madin explained, was it
possible to begin ``looking at these organisms where they live,
instead of as dead stuff in the bottom of a jar.''
</P>
<P>
   Open ocean diving is not for the faint of heart. There are no
points of reference, no way to gauge size or distance, and most
frightening of all, no place to hide. Just a vast, featureless and
disorienting expanse of open water. And that's the key to the
lifestyle of the sneaky majority of animals that inhabit this
region, which, collectively, account for more than 99 percent of
this planet's habitable space.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not used to being in an environment that's totally
exposed,'' Johnsen said in an interview last week. ``When you dive,
it's an unnerving feeling: Anything that wants to see you probably
can.''
</P>
<P>
   On these open ocean dives, the scientists typically use scuba
gear to dive about 80 feet down while attached to a long tether
from the surface. ``We look like we're bait on a long fishing
line,'' quips Johnsen.
</P>
<P>
   If there's nothing to hide behind, the only way to avoid being
eaten is to be very fierce (think sharks), very toxic (think
pufferfish), or very hard to find. For what may be the vast
majority of the ocean's population, being hard to find seems to be
the preferred strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a brutal hide-and-seek game out there,'' Johnsen said.
``It's an arms race between those that want to find things and
those that want to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   But surprisingly little is known about just how these animals
manage to be so invisible. That's the task that Johnsen has set for
himself.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, it seems impossible: How could living flesh
possibly be as transparent as a windowpane? But, in fact, the proof
that it can be done is right in front of our faces. In front of our
eyes, to be precise.
</P>
<P>
   The perfectly transparent cornea of the human eye is made of
essentially the same material as the opaque white of the eye that
surrounds it. The difference between the two is surprisingly
subtle. It comes down to packaging, a slight difference in the way
molecules are grouped and arranged.
</P>
<P>
   The key, Johnsen has found, is for the molecules to be packaged
in bunches whose size and spacing is about half the wavelength of
light or less, or about 200 nanometers (about 8 millionths of an
inch). That enables light to pass without being either reflected or
absorbed on the way.
</P>
<P>
   There are a variety of other strategies used by the invisible
creatures in the ocean. Some have specially textured skin that
blurs the reflective boundary between the creature and the
surrounding water. And most are largely made up of a transparent
gelatinous substance that is mostly water and is inherently
transparent.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some things that are very hard to hide. The
retinas of the eyes, for example, work by absorbing light, and that
necessarily makes them appear dark. And the contents of stomachs,
filled with freshly-eaten plant or animal life, are usually plainly
visible. Some such animals that feed on luminous organisms have
opaque stomachs to keep their contents from glowing like a beacon.
</P>
<P>
   The various strategies for achieving invisiblity work amazingly
well. ``Some are so transparent, they can be inches in front of
your face, and you wouldn't know it,'' Johnsen said. When trying to
collect a sample of one of these beings, he said, sometimes he
would get a glimpse of something when it catches the light just
right, and then he would ``reach down for the jar, and look up and
I can't find it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, these creatures range from the size of a thumb to a
basketball, but a few can be much larger. Some form long chains of
individuals that can reach 100 feet or more. Others are large but
almost as tenuous as tissue paper.
</P>
<P>
   On a cruise south of Nantucket in June, the Woods Hole
scientists saw one jellyfish _ a recently discovered type called
Deepstaria, named for a submersible called Deep Star _ just outside
the window of their submersible. It was three feet across and two
feet high and looked ``like a clear upside-down Hefty bag, with a
drawstring at the bottom, slowly pulsating,'' said Johnsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just mesmerizing, a remarkable animal'' he said. But
because it is so large and so delicate, nobody has yet succeeded in
bringing one to the surface for study.
</P>
<P>
   But even more familiar organisms, especially in their larval
form, can share the transparency of these exotic species. For
example, the larvae of some kinds of lobsters are about the size of
a silver dollar, but as thin as paper, and so invisible that they
could be right in front of your face without being noticed, Johnsen
said.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to estimate the numbers of these gelatinous animals
in the oceans. For one thing, their distribution is very patchy,
for reasons that are not yet well understood. And they can also go
through sudden blooms in which an area of thousands of square miles
can be overrun with billions of a particular species within days.
</P>
<P>
   ``They periodically just balloon and grow like mad,'' said
Johnsen. ``When they do, they clear out everything else in the
water column,'' devouring everything in sight.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened when a species of comb jellies, which
resemble jellyfish but belong to a different group, invaded the
Black Sea, devastating the local fish populations. And now, ``that
same species has moved into the Caspian Sea, and something similar
may happen there,'' Madin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can take a heavy toll on other animals,'' he said. ``They
can have a real effect on what the rest of the ecological community
is like.''
</P>
<P>
   But these explosions of gelatinous life might also play an
important role in helping to stave off global warming by absorbing
heat-trapping carbon dioxide from the atmosphere. It turns out,
Madin said, that many of these animals eat tiny plant-like
organisms floating near the surface that use carbon dioxide from
the air. By eating them and concentrating them into pellets of
waste that drift down to the sea floor, these creatures are
actually making sure that the carbon doesn't just return to the
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, they may be an important ``sink'' for carbon dioxide that
is added to the air by human activities such as burning fuel. It
remains to be seen how significant this effect may be.
</P>
<P>
   So, it now seems clear that, in the vast stretches of the open
ocean, what you can't see really can hurt you. But it may also help
you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
