<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MAGDALEN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAGDALENS: INTRIGUING ISLES IN ATLANTIC CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walking along a beach, with sand whispering under my feet, red
cliffs hovering nearby, and the sounds of both English and French
blending in the background, I realized that I had gotten my wish: I
had come to Canada's Magdalen Islands in search of something
different, and I had surely found it.
</P>
<P>
   The Magdalen Islands _ or, in French, Les Iles de la Madeleine _
are a new destination for many Americans, and one not quite like
any other. They are part of the province of Quebec, but are another
kind of Quebec, located in the heart of Atlantic Canada, some 780
miles from Montreal. And although they have a couple of
topographical similarities to nearby Prince Edward Island, their
look is largely different.
</P>
<P>
   That look is lovely, with low and rolling green hills, red
sandstone cliffs, fields sprinkled with wildflowers, and 200 miles
of beaches with sands that are white or golden, and occasionally
have a touch of pink. Dotted throughout are cafes, bistros, and
homes, many of them painted in vibrant blues and greens and
oranges.
</P>
<P>
   These islands overflow with opportunities for outdoor activities
and adventures: sailing, canoeing and kayaking, windsurfing,
horseback riding, biking, hiking, birdwatching, and cave
exploration by land or sea.
</P>
<P>
   They are friendly, filled with people whose love and, in many
cases, livelihood is the sea that surrounds them. The 14,000
islanders are mostly of Acadian heritage, and the sound of the
fiddle is the background music of their lives. They are fishermen
(and, in two cases, fisherwomen), farmers, artisans, and
shopkeepers, who celebrate the summer with frequent festivals _ and
who see no need to lock their car doors.
</P>
<P>
   And the islands are unique. On most of them, the spoken language
is French, but a softer French than you hear on mainland Quebec.
Yet because of the vagaries of geography and history, on two
islands the language is English. Thus you can experience the
phenomenon of driving a little way from an island where virtually
everyone is speaking French to a connected island where everyone is
chatting in English.
</P>
<P>
   Les Iles (or the Magdalens, or the Maggies, as they are
nicknamed) are a 65-mile-long, fishhook-shaped archipelago in the
Gulf of St. Lawrence. There are a dozen islands, seven of them
inhabited and all but one of those seven connected by long, thin
(and largely paved) sand dunes.
</P>
<P>
   The most common ways of reaching Les Iles are by plane, or by
taking the ferry from PEI, some 65 miles away. It is becoming more
usual, in fact, to combine a stay on PEI, with its British Isles
heritage and its own brand of beauty, with one on Les Iles, thus
experiencing what feels like a multi-nation vacation with a minimum
of travel.
</P>
<P>
   As I boarded the ferry CTMA Traversier, I was reluctant, as
always, to leave the color, charm, and conviviality of PEI. But at
the same time I was excited at the prospect of a new and different
place. And the joyous sound of French songs drifting from a lounge
aboard the ferry helped ease the transition.
</P>
<P>
   Since I would be staying on the southernmost island, Ile du
Havre Aubert, the idea was to explore from south to northeast, and
although I did some back-and-forthing, I largely stuck to that
plan. I would quickly learn that each isle has its own look,
personality, and even accent. Some highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Ile du Havre Aubert (Amherst Island, or Aubert Harbor Island).
The view from Havre sur Mer, the pleasant bed-and-breakfast where I
stayed, encompassed much of what I would see all over the islands:
the surf, the cliffs, fishing boats, a lighthouse, and the flag of
Quebec flying proudly.
</P>
<P>
   This island is known for its natural harbor, populated by both
pleasure boats and fishing boats. Here I watched lobstermen hauling
in the tasty crustaceans by the hundreds. Lobster is one of the
chief catches in the Magdalens, along with mackerel, herring,
scallops, and snow crab.
</P>
<P>
   A popular area is the historic site La Grave, which in addition
to being a favorite meeting spot is the site of the small but
complete Aquarium des Iles, with its shellfish, mollusks, and
seals. When I was there, a young employee began speaking to me in
French. When I indicated difficulty understanding, as would happen
occasionally during my stay, he switched to English to tell me the
seals were about to be fed. Thus I got the chance to watch Beke and
Bobo, the resident harp seals, chow down. La Grave has a cultural
center with a costumed historical musical, as well as a theater,
plus arts and crafts shops such as Les Artisans du Sable with its
intricate sand sculptures. There, too, are cafes and shops, some of
them in converted fishing sheds.
</P>
<P>
   Havre Aubert is also the home of the Musee de la Mer (Museum of
the Sea), which provides a good introduction to island life and
history, including information about the shipwrecks _ some say as
many as 700 _ off the island.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the island has the closest thing you're going to
find to a theme park in the Magdalens _ Le Site d'Autrefois, a
village that depicts island life and history through miniature and
full-sized displays, with everything from a tiny church and
graveyard, to a house of the 1930s that you can enter, to a shanty
made from an overturned boat that houses a real pig named Peggy.
The creator and enthusiastic host is Claude Bourgeois. After being
badly injured in a fishing accident, he decided to tell the story
of his islands by creating the village. To do so, he worked 70-80
hours a week for three years. And although he speaks no English, as
he points out displays, the message of joy in his creation comes
through clearly.
</P>
<P>
   Ile d'Entree (Entry Island). East of Havre Aubert, Ile d'Entree
is unusual in many ways. For one thing, it is the only inhabited
island with no land link to the rest of the others (it is about an
hour's ride by ferryboat or, in summer, tour boat). For another,
its 175 residents speak English. Although I didn't get a chance to
visit, those who have say it's like spending a day in the British
Isles, complete with Old World accents. The island is splendid for
hiking and offers grand views. Big Hill, the highest point in Les
Iles at 575 feet, is also here.
</P>
<P>
   Ile du Cap aux Meules (Grindstone Island). This is the
commercial center of Les Iles, and the municipality of
Cap-aux-Meules is where ferry riders arrive and get their first
view of the Magdalens. That is probably the least scenic view
they'll get, what with the cluster of businesses and services. But
soon you're surrounded by nature again. For my first, and one of
the best, views of the rich, red sandstone cliffs, I headed for the
Fatima region and Belle-Anse, which appropriately means ``Beautiful
Cove.'' That it was, with cliffs stretching far and waves washing
against them. Wherever there are cliffs, though, there is the
possibility that their edges have been weakened by erosion, and
there have been accidents, so keep back from them. Besides, a
distance from the edge, You will find sea parsley. I picked a piece
and found the taste refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   This island is fine for hiking and biking _ a network of trails
stretches to the other end of the connected islands. For strolling
and sunsets, there is the fishing port of L'Etang-du-Nord and the
enclave known as La Cote, with its shops, boutiques, restaurants,
cabarets, and festivals virtually every summer weekend. Over a
smoked mackerel sandwich with focaccia at Cafe la Cote, I watched a
sunset dye the sky red and yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Ile du Havre aux Maisons (House Harbor Island). Beauty is
commonplace on this isle, with its winding roads, little gabled
homes, beaches, and caves that can be explored at low tide. A
scenic route leads to La Pointe, where you can see Cap-aux-Meules
across the water and sometimes watch blue herons fishing for lunch.
And speaking of lunch, one of mine was at Au Vieux Couvent, a
former convent of the Sisters of Notre Dame, where I sampled the
blue mussels that are ``farmed'' here as well as a seafood
pot-en-pot, a kind of shepherd's pie.
</P>
<P>
   Three attractions on this isle drew my interest. One is La
Meduse, a studio and boutique, where you can watch glassblowers at
work and buy, or just look at, exquisite examples of their art _
little houses within globes, sheep, fish, flowers. Prices range
from about $10 to $300 US.
</P>
<P>
   A very different place is Fumoir d'Antan, a herring smokehouse
where you can watch some of the drying-salting-and-smoking process
and sample the herring. I found it enjoyable to watch the reaction
of the samplers: This is a food that you like or don't.
</P>
<P>
   Havre aux Maisons is also home to a cheese factory, Fromagerie
du Pied-de-vent, where you can see, sample, and, not surprisingly,
buy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9420 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-MAGDALENS-2ND &LR;      08-01 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MAGDALENS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... surprisingly, buy.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ile aux-Loups (Wolf Island). The scenery gets sandier, with more
dunes, as you head to the eastern part of the connected isles. Ile
aux-Loups is the smallest of the main islands, where you can see
clam diggers and sometimes buy the mollusks at roadside stands. The
Craft Cooperative has items for sale, and the Maison du Heron
presents an exhibit of fossils, walrus teeth, shells, and other
artifacts from thousands of years ago when aboriginal peoples
visited the islands. And although the name of this island
translates to Island of Wolves, the biggest wild creature you're
likely to see anywhere on Les Iles is a red fox. The ``wolf'' name
probably originated from the local name for seals: sea wolves.
</P>
<P>
   Grosse-Ile (Big Island). Suddenly the language is English again;
residents are largely fishermen of Scottish descent and their
families. Old Harry _ and I never did find out who he was _ is a
pretty area, with its big beach, wharf, boats, and cliffs. You
might want to stop in at the Holy Trinity Anglican church, as I
did, to see the stained-glass window that depicts Christ as a
fisherman, complete with bulky sweater, jeans, and boots.
</P>
<P>
   Old Harry is also where you can hear a haunting, foghorn sound
rising regularly from the caves. Some like to think that sound is
the moaning of the ghost of a man who fell from the cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   From Grosse-Ile, it's a 30-minute Zodiac ride to Ile Brion,
which, with Bird Rock beyond it, is a haven for birdwatchers, who
find Atlantic puffins, murre, great cormorants, and snowy owls
among the 240 species that have been observed. Although not in this
concentration, birds can also be found throughout Les Iles.
</P>
<P>
   One other point of interest appears near the entrance to
Grosse-Ile: a salt mine, where tons of salt are extracted and sent
to the mainland for de-icing roads. The long, low plant, which you
cannot visit but can't miss, employs about 200 people.
</P>
<P>
   Ile de la Grande-Entree (Grand Entry Island). You're in
French-speaking territory again. You're also in the lobster capital
of Quebec _ 100 lobster boats unload more than half the islands'
catch here. Appropriately, there is an annual lobster festival,
complete with celebrants in lobster suits. (I took advantage of
lobster-eating opportunities whenever I could, and one of the most
memorable dishes was lobster over pasta with vanilla sauce at Le
Table des Roy in Ile du Cap aux Meules. Another highly rated
restaurant is La Maree Haute on Havre Aubert. But for those seeking
just good lobster and other seafood dishes at relatively low
prices, one place to go is La Factrie, a restaurant, fish store,
and canning plant on the isle of Cap aux Meules.)
</P>
<P>
   Besides boats and beauty (and blue mussel farming),
Grande-Entree has the Seal Interpretation Center, which tells the
story of the harp and hooded seals who migrate from Greenland to
give birth in March on the ice surrounding the Magdalens. The seals
have come as close as 30 miles from the islands, and helicopter
tours are available. This, in fact, is the only place in the world
where the seals can be observed that way _ and observed by the
hundreds. The interpretation center does not ignore the controversy
over the clubbing to death of baby harp seals for their fur.
</P>
<P>
   On Grande-Entree, a unique adventure tour takes you into the
isle's red caves, with participants wearing wet suits and flotation
jackets. You don't even have to know how to swim.
</P>
<P>
   And here, as throughout the islands, you will see kites flying _
brightly colored kites in a variety of shapes, some of them being
flown from dune buggies. Because the island has few trees (most
were cut down by the early settlers for home-building and heat),
there are constant breezes, or sometimes winds, making conditions
ideal for the activity. People have even been known to meet their
future spouses while flying kites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I thought as I walked along the beach, I had certainly
found somewhere different. And then I had another thought: Vive la
difference!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1412EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
