<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TOMORROW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES AS A TALE, AND TOOL, OF SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE BIG TOMORROW 
Hollywood and the Politics of the American Way 
By Lary(cq) May 
University of Chicago Press, 339 pp., $32.50 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the most exhilarating work of revisionist film history
since Pauline Kael's ``Citizen Kane'' book. In a day when the mass
media more than ever seem designed to keep people stupid and
scattered, Lary May's ``The Big Tomorrow'' reminds us that the
first half of the 20th century was a lot more alive with populism
and activism than the second half. Far from teaching Depression-era
America to face the music and dance (even though what we mostly
remember is screenful after screenful of escapist fare set in
penthouses with white pianos), the period teemed with movies
questioning the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Will Rogers, hazily remembered today as a kindly, folksy
comedian, is recalled as the half-Cherokee populist he was,
dispensing sharp-edged political comment and calling for the
redistribution of wealth. Starting with the rich, double-edged
title of his book, resonating as it does with idealism and noir
sensibility, May argues that the Depression was actually a
liberating influence on the American mind, freeing it from blind
subservience to the establishment, which obviously didn't have all
the answers, encouraging artists to junk European models and invent
new ones, allowing hitherto marginalized voices to be heard in the
new _ and to some, shocking _ gangster movies, working-girl
comedies, and snappy musicals. New archetypes appeared, from
two-fisted working-class protagonists (Cagney, Gable, Stanwyck,
Davis) to sophisticated iconoclasts such as William Powell and
Myrna Loy in ``The Thin Man.''
</P>
<P>
   May describes how films began to dissolve the boundaries between
what Americans saw at the movies and what they read in their
newspapers and heard on their radios. Today's rap culture, he makes
clear, recalls the social role of '30s gangster films, with their
implied revolts against class exclusion. Hollywood even went on the
attack against stifling gentility in its comedies, ranging from W.
C. Fields and the Marx Brothers to screwball comedy. Vernacular
entered the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   From the openly populist films of Frank Capra to ``The Wizard of
Oz'' (based on L. Frank Baum's novel arising from a farmers' revolt
of the 1890s) to ``The Grapes of Wrath,'' films began advancing the
idea that people born poor are not inferior and can achieve common
goals; they also began replacing Anglo-Saxon Americanism with an
alternative pluralistic vision. Debunking the idea that moviegoing
collapsed in the years of economic hardship, May asserts that
moviegoing in fact doubled during the '30s. And people went to the
movies for more than escape.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened to the restless populism of those years? World
War II. With a new national demand for patriotic consensus, dissent
and questioning receded. The call for unity silenced radicals. A
shift occurred. The conversion narrative, with power stemming from
the bottom of the socio-economic pyramid, was replaced by one of
supremacy once again flowing from the top down _ a change
crystallized in ``Casablanca,'' when Rick must shed his individual
independence for hierarchical values.
</P>
<P>
   Having regained the upper hand, May says, the establishment knew
how to keep it. American individualism was diverted into the
private realm of consumerism in the postwar world, and themes
linking art and social renewal declined. America developed a split
personality _ handily charted, May argues, in the Bob Hope-Bing
Crosby road comedies, which he sees as an American quest for
wholeness sublimated to the vision of an escapist fairyland. Hope,
the id, is forever being tamed and literally crooned into
subservience by Crosby, the superego; May sees this as a replay of
the traditional minstrel show, where blacks represented the
pleasure principle threatening to turn white (civilized) men black.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the postwar ideal of consumerism and domesticity
offered an entirely satisfying alternative. The anxiety resulting
from the stifling postwar imperative to conform gave rise to film
noir, May argues, with its outsider sensibility lurking in the
shadows. (He might have added the films of Douglas Sirk, that
master portrayer of postwar American domestic and social
entrapment.) May genuflects to Billy Wilder (``Double Indemnity'')
and John Huston (``The Asphalt Jungle'') for their subversive
criticism of repressive postwar roles, and he notes the
criminalization of desire that set the stage for the counterculture
_ a revolt that was prefigured in the rebellious archetypes of
Marlon Brando, James Dean, and Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the reams and reams that have been written about Monroe,
May emphasizes the linkage between her refusal to feel guilty about
sex and the social liberation this view represented, both in her
own films and in ``Some Like It Hot,'' in a supporting role as a
singer who refuses to get hung up on gender-stretching and sexual
identity confusion. In May's view, Monroe completed the rejection
of traditional confining domesticity that the spunky tough cookies
of the '30s began, and she thus became a profound threat: a
celluloid sex goddess who turned out to be the real thing,
outgrowing the limits of the persona manufactured for her by a
patriarchal power structure.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long time since the world of film has received as
invigoratingly coherent an overview as May's. His take on what
movies once were (energizing, as opposed to enervating), and hence
can become again, is enough to get you believing in them again as
one of the regenerative forces America so sorely needs, and not
just a herd of bloated cash cows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
