<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRENDA BLETHYN'S BLOOMIN' CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days, Brenda Blethyn has been asked a certain question so
often one might confuse her with a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' the inquiry goes, ``have you, you know, ever tried, uh,
you know, marijuana?''
</P>
<P>
   In these scandal-happy times, such queries are usually posed to
politicians, not two-time Academy Award-nominated actresses. But
Blethyn politely smiles, and recites the story she has already told
dozens of times, and will probably tell a dozen times more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a nonsmoker, so I haven't smoked. But I have had a
confection of sorts, like a cake with (marijuana) baked inside,''
she said with a giggle. ``Everyone was laughing, but I didn't know.
It was really nice so I had another one, and it completely laid me
out. I slept like a baby. It was better than a hot chocolate.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the kinds of answers Blethyn has had to consider while
promoting her latest movie, ``Saving Grace.'' The film, which opens
Friday, stars Blethyn as Grace Trevethan, a proper English widow
who, in cash-strapped desperation, turns her considerable
horticultural skills to growing marijuana. The film, which plays
like Cheech and Chong directed by Preston Sturges, also stars Craig
Ferguson, Valerie Edmond, Martin Clunes, and Tcheky Karyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a delightful film. I'm so proud of it,'' said
Blethyn, dressed in a smart navy pantsuit, as she relaxed in a
Boston hotel conference room. ``I just thought it was very funny
the route this woman takes to find some money, and solve her
problems.'
</P>
<P>
   For most of her years, Grace Trevethan has lived a satisfying,
conventional life in an English village. She's been in a stable, if
unexciting marriage, and is content spending her days tending her
plants in her greenhouse. But when her husband dies unexpectedly
(and, truth be told, comically), Grace learns her life and marriage
were built on secrets and lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a woman who's comfortably well-off and thinks she's
kind of happy. She knows her husband has had some liaison with a
woman, but he stayed with her so it's not too much of a problem.
She lives in a lovely home, in a nice community, and she tells
herself everything is OK,'' Blethyn said. ``Suddenly, he's a goner,
and she's left in the most horrendous debt. He's hocked everything,
he's not the man she thought he was, and this other woman meant a
lot more than she realized. So she's left with nothing; she doesn't
even have memories to hold onto. Everything she'd experienced was
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   When her caretaker, Matthew (Ferguson, who also wrote the
script), asks Grace to look after some ``sick plants,'' _ his own
homegrown marijuana _ he convinces her that there is much money to
be made growing and selling marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grace is the most unlikely person, the most law-abiding
citizen. She doesn't know much about marijuana except how to grow
it,'' Blethyn said. ``She's a good, ordinary person. I know a lot
of people like her, and I think that's why audiences can relate to
her. They know people like her, or have found themselves in similar
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that the film features more blunts and pot references than
a Dr. Dre video, some might perceive the reefer madness of ``Saving
Grace'' as an endorsement of marijuana. For her part, Blethyn
believes marijuana should be legalized, but doesn't believe the
film promotes or condones its use.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's an ordinary woman in the face of extreme odds struggling
to solve her problem and finding herself in the process,'' Blethyn
said. ``As far as the marijuana is concerned, I think in
desperation if you're really up a blind alley, the survival
instinct kicks in. The film makes people consider how, far, in the
same situation, any of us would go, if you know you're not going to
hurt anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   In her own desperation, Blethyn said she has worked a few
regrettable jobs over the years, though nothing illegal. But jobs
such as cleaning hotel toilets are long in the past for Blethyn,
54, who has been one of the most acclaimed actresses in recent
years. Though she worked for decades on the English stage and in
British television, she was first recognized stateside in 1996 when
she played a downtrodden woman unexpectedly reunited with the
biracial daughter she gave up for adoption in ``Secrets and Lies.''
For that film, only her third, Blethyn was nominated for an Oscar
as best actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time around I couldn't believe it,'' she said. ``I
had absolutely no expectations because I found it absurd I even was
there.'' She lost to Frances McDormand (``Fargo''), but was
nominated again in 1999 for her supporting role as a bullying
harridan of a mother in ``Little Voice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The second time I knew what the procedure was, and I knew I
wasn't going to win _ and everybody I spoke to agreed with me,''
said Blethyn, who lost to Dame Judi Dench in ``Shakespeare in
Love.'' ``So I could just relax and have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the accolades, the films came with one drawback _
Hollywood stereotyping. After ``Secrets and Lies,'' Blethyn said,
she was offered lots of scripts about ``unfortunate women who cried
a lot.'' And after ``Little Voice,'' there were ``lots of scripts
about ferocious women who shouted a lot.'' (It was that image that
landed Blethyn her role as fabled pit bull gossip columnist Louella
Parsons in the HBO movie ``RKO 821.'')
</P>
<P>
   Petite and attractive, Blethyn misses the variety of parts she's
played on her beloved English stage _ ``glamorous-type roles, you
know, happy people'' _ but she isn't scoffing at her
still-burgeoning film career. She'll soon be seen in Billy Bob
Thornton's ``Daddy and Them,'' and is mulling several other roles _
perhaps even one which may allow her to wear ``a nice frock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an overnight success after 25 years, but it's all been
very nice. At my age you don't expect these things to happen,'' she
said with a laugh. ``It's the same thing with the nominations. It's
wonderful to have the whole movie industry talking about you, and
mentioning your name among people who are wonderful actors. You
don't lose, really. Getting the nomination is a win, especially if
you're an old-fashioned English girl from Ramsgate, Kent, in
England, d'you know what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
