<HEADLINE>
WANT RESPECT? DRESS UP BEFORE YOU TAKE OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Want to get better service, and maybe a little more respect,
while traveling? Then shed that garish T-shirt and the jeans with
the holes in the knees and dress up a little.
</P>
<P>
   That, according to a survey commissioned by Fodor's Travel
Publications, is the secret to snagging that extra bag of peanuts
or full can of Coke, that desired upgrade, or that extra bit of
attention from hotel staffs.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 600 American travelers, conducted by National
Family Opinion Research Group, found that 77 percent of men and 68
percent of women who dress well when traveling for business or
leisure do so because they get better service that way. Among other
reasons for eschewing sloppy garb:
</P>
<P>
   --The possibility of meeting someone interesting. Twenty-eight
percent of the women and 18 percent of the men surveyed gave that
reason for dressing up.
</P>
<P>
   --Concern about losing their nice clothes with their luggage.
Twelve percent of women and 9 percent of men listed that reason.
</P>
<P>
   So put on that sport coat or silk scarf. It just might enhance
your travel experience, and in any event you'll be helping to
beautify the environment. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Which is closer to Los Angeles: the Bahamas or
Hawaii? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: The Pennsylvania Dutch are actually of German descent.
The word Deutsche, meaning ``German,'' was incorrectly translated
as ``Dutch.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``There is a rare emotion, familiar to every intelligent
traveller , in which the mind seems to swallow the sum total of its
impressions at a gulp. You take in the whole place . . . and the
sensation involves for the moment a kind of thrill'' _ Henry
James. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: You can't sell peanuts in Lee County, Ala.,
after sundown on Wednesdays. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Custom colors: Among the multitude of special effects at Walt
Disney World's ``IllumiNations 2000: Reflections of Earth'' are
lasers in all colors, including four seen nowhere else: lagoon
blue, mint green, pumpkin orange, and lavender. The 13-minute
nighttime show takes place on and above World Showcase Lagoon at
Epcot and includes an Earth globe wrapped in 15,000 light-emitting
diodes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ah, romance: For the second year in a row, San Francisco was chosen
America's most romantic city in a survey by BedandBreakfast.com.
New York was second, New Orleans third, and Boston, Chicago, and
Las Vegas tied for fourth. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Wait a week: The winner of out contest, which asked for the
location of a certain statue, will be announced next week. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? The Bahamas are 30 miles closer to LA, according
to The Islands of the Bahamas (www.bahamas.com), which also notes
that pineapples made their way to Hawaii via the Bahamas. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Kalahari Desert is in South Africa, as we said in our Travel
Trivia answer last week, but also in Botswana and Namibia, so any
or all of those answers would have been correct. We thank alert
readers Robert Soli of Reading, who says justifiably that Botswana
or Namibia should have received top billing; Amy Bartlett of Salem,
N.H.; David Ives of Carlisle; and Eric Witt of Littleton, N.H. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In response to our description of the $5,600-a-night luxury
suite at the Churchill Inter-Continental in London, Thom McCabe of
Westborough writes about his room at the Bali Inter-Continental:
``I was brought into . . . a suite which I later measured at 66
feet long and 44 feet wide including a 10 x 66 foot balcony
overlooking the ocean and Bali's spectacular sunsets.'' The cost of
this magnificent suite: $225 US per night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our discussion of one-word state mottoes brought this comment
from Dan Kraft of Boston: ``I'm sure many of your readers guessed
that either New York or New Jersey would have four-letter words as
mottoes!'' (He's joking, folks. He notes that the two states that
actually have four-letter mottoes are Rhode Island (Hope) and
Washington (Al-ki, meaning ``by and by'').
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To the fan of Gillette Castle State Park in East Haddam, Conn.:
The historic castle will remain closed this year because of
continuing repair work. The park grounds and trails will remain
open to the public free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Schuster of Foxborough, Mass., a faithful contributor,
notes that not only does Orlando, Fla., claim the world's largest
McDonald's, as we mentioned, but also the world's largest Hard Rock
Cafe, at Universal Orlando's CityWalk.
</P>
