<HEADLINE>
`THE SHAKERS' PRIVATE ART' IS ON DISPLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first major museum exhibition to explore the spiritual
meaning and social context of Shaker gift drawings is on view at
Hancock Shaker Museum in Pittsfield, Mass. through April 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seen and Received: The Shakers' Private Art'' is notable for
the 25 inspired and little-understood body of drawings on view,
largely created by women, that in the mid-19th century captured on
paper a fervent outpouring of Shaker religious belief. The exhibit
is in Hancock Shaker Village's new $2.5 million Center for Shaker
Studies.
</P>
<P>
   The village, a living history museum on 1,200 acres in the
Berkshires, houses the largest collection of artifacts at an
original Shaker site. The Shakers are known for their simplicity in
life, music, and folk art.
</P>
<P>
   The community was active from 1783 to 1960, and visitors will
see not only some 20 historic buildings but also examples of
furniture, textiles, and tools. They will also learn of the life
and faith of the Shaker community through demonstrations, music,
and talks.
</P>
<P>
   For more information and directions, call 800-817-1137.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hospital Day
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for New England at its best, head for tiny
Townshend, Vt., Saturday for the 50th annual Hospital Fair Day.
It's a very special day for thousands, many traveling from hundreds
of miles away, who gather on the colorful town green to party,
dine, and seek out the bargains that annually benefit Grace Cottage
Hospital. It's a hometown festival like none other, complete with a
birthday parade (all the marchers were born at the hospital) led by
a 6-foot ``stork,'' also known at Dr. Tim Shafer, and the most
recent mother and child. (On one occasion the child was just four
hours old.) The day _ rain or shine _ includes free pony rides, an
art show, music and entertainment for all ages, an auction, a
sunset brass band concert, and a hole-in-one contest. Food ranges
from Belgian waffles and bisonburgers to a chicken barbecue.
Townsend is 17 miles northwest of Brattleboro, an easy 2 1/2-hour
drive from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Maine Festival
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For those looking for the creative spirit of Maine, head for
Thomas Point Beach in Brunswick for the 24th annual Maine Festival
Friday through Sunday. Events include seven performance stages with
a wide range of music from bluegrass to jazz and country and dance,
literary readings, and theater. Tents will be filled with
traditional Maine artistry including fiber arts and woodworking;
other activities range from kite flying and stilt dancing to a
Scottish bagpipe parade. Lots of food will be available. For more
information on activities, camping, and admission, call
800-639-4212 or visit www.mainearts.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Upcoming
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arts and all that Jazz comes to the Jackson, N.H., Village Park
Saturday from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m., rain or shine. The event features
fine arts, photography, sculpture, crafts, demonstrations, antique
autos, and, of course, jazz. For information, call 603-383-9356.
</P>
<P>
   The 33d Annual Originals Fine Art and Craft Show is Tuesday and
Wednesday at the Wellfleet Cinemas on Cape Cod. This annual benefit
features artists and craftspeople exhibiting everything from
watercolors to photography. Demonstrations will include wood
carving and watercolor techniques. The show is free, as is parking,
and there will be plenty of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire Music Festival continues Thursday and Friday,
featuring Michelle Kim performing Mendelssohn Violin Concerto at
the Silver Cultural Arts Center at Plymouth State College.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sand sculptures
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 27th annual Sandcastle and Sculpture Day on Nantucket will
be Aug. 12 (rain date, Aug. 13). This summer ritual should result
in more than 50 sculptures on Jetties Beach. The contest is open to
all ages, but pre-registration is necessary to guarantee space. The
rules are simple: Be creative. For complete details, call the
Chamber of Commerce at 508-228-1700.
</P>
</TEXT>
