<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9428 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-MIN-ART-BOS &LR;      08-01 1717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-MIN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 REVISING MADAME MAO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Do you know the difference between a traditional opera and a
Madame Mao opera?'' Anchee Min, addressing an audience packed into
the reading room at Boston bookstore, proceeds to demonstrate.
While singing the traditional Chinese opera, she stands still at
the lectern, smiling gently, her voice preternaturally high.
</P>
<P>
   Then she shifts gears, donning a military cap, a remnant of the
Shanghai native's Chinese film studio days. Min's petite body comes
alive as she launches into propaganda-spewing action. Her face
glows, her arms freeze in a variety of heroic poses, her voice
deepens as she determinedly sings:
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I fight for victory/
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't stop fighting until all my wishes come true.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance is Min's unique way of promoting her new book of
historical fiction, ``Becoming Madame Mao.'' The novel, which has
been popping up on bestseller lists in San Francisco, Los Angeles,
and Boston, tells the tale of Jiang Ching, the wife of Chinese
communist leader Mao Tze-tung.
</P>
<P>
   The book, which The New York Times Book Review praised as
``compelling and penetrating,'' is an intriguing profile of a
second-rate actress who molded herself into different characters to
please each of her four husbands (Mao was her last). Jiang finally
created her idealized self during the Cultural Revolution of
1966-76: a strong female protagonist who starred in the ballets and
operas she herself developed.
</P>
<P>
   After Mao's death in 1976, Jiang was imprisoned. Blamed for the
nation's suffering during the Cultural Revolution _ a topsy-turvy
time when intellectuals were vilified, traditional values were
attacked, and hundreds of thousands of people were killed _ Jiang
was denounced as a ``white-boned demon,'' a character from Chinese
history fingered for destroying powerful men.
</P>
<P>
   Although Min never met Jiang, the latter had Min plucked from a
labor camp to star in a film about Jiang's life. Before the
director had even shot a scene, Jiang was thrown in jail and Min
was denounced for her association with the fallen leader.
</P>
<P>
   In her best-selling 1994 memoir, ``Red Azalea,'' Min recounted
her journey from a Chinese film studio to a Chicago art school
(aided by her friend actress/director Joan Chen). With ``Becoming
Madame Mao,'' Min offers a revisionist view of the complicated
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, Mao's the god, Madame Mao is the demon,'' says
Min during an interview at a Boston hotel. ``Here you start to see
the complexity of this woman, an early feminist caught up in Mao's
personal political will.''
</P>
<P>
   To paint this new portrait, Min jumps from first person to third
person, separating historical fact from the fictitious tales woven
both by Jiang and by the Chinese government that sought to vilify
her. She humanizes Jiang by packing the tale with enough sex,
betrayal, and political intrigue that it could double as a
bodice-ripper.
</P>
<P>
   Min includes a reference list of 19 biographies about Jiang,
Mao, and their associates. ``She just wanted to make clear that
this book had stuck to the facts,'' explains the book's editor,
Anton Mueller of Houghton Mifflin. ``And that there were more
accurate psychological and sociological ways of looking at Madame
Mao.''
</P>
<P>
   Min's strong opinions in ``Madame Mao'' and ``Red Azalea'' have
angered many of her countrymen. When she appeared on a
Chinese-language talk show in the United States recently, callers
complained: You are not the only one who suffered during the
Cultural Revolution, one said. Who gave you the right to shame
China by telling your and Madame Mao's story?, another asked.
</P>
<P>
   The response to Min doesn't surprise Ross Terrill, an expert on
China who's written biographies about Mao and Jiang.
</P>
<P>
   Min is a ``resolute and passionate and maybe somewhat
egotistical person, the way she told her story of growing up and
suffering in the Shanghai area,'' says Terrill, who reviewed ``Red
Azalea'' but hasn't read ``Madame Mao.'' ``She is like Jiang Ching
in that controversy and strong opinions would attach to her like
iron filings to a magnet.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy has only helped make Min stronger than a Madame
Mao opera heroine. ``I'm not like Dr. Li (Zhi-Sui),'' says Min,
referring to Mao's personal doctor, who wrote the 1994 biography
``The Private Life of Chairman Man.'' ``He got criticized,
denounced by his country, (had a) heart attack, died _ paid his
life for it. They're not gonna kill me.''
</P>
<P>
   As Min says this, her wide-set eyes are fiery, her voice is
raised for emphasis. Her skin is the color of golden wheat, and she
mentions several times that she doesn't have the porcelain
complexion and almond-shaped eyes that pass for Chinese beauty
these days. ``I'm really considered ugly today,'' she says in
English that wavers between fluid and fractured.
</P>
<P>
   When Min gets excited or nervous, her native language suddenly
fills her head, she says, and her English falters. It's something
her 8-year-old daughter, Lauryann, teases her about, along with
Min's knack for getting lost on the highways of Los Angeles, where
she now lives with her second husband, Lloyd Lofthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Min credits Jiang for providing the women of her generation with
strong female role models, for helping them see that they weren't
blades of grass meant to be stepped on _ as Min's Madame Mao was
told growing up. But Min doesn't shirk from showing the negative
side of a desperate woman who fought for Mao's waning attention
through murder and deception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anyone to feel sorry for her,'' says Min, ``but I
demand an understanding so I can set the historical record
straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Such comprehension is necessary, Min believes, because many
Chinese are still living in denial when it comes to the Cultural
Revolution. Autobiography after autobiography has emerged, written
by people who blame Madame Mao for their woes. They ``don't have
the guts to say, `OK, I am a part of this criminal act,' '' says
Min. `` `I am guilty.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me eight years to reform myself, to say, `I am
responsible,' '' continues Min, who credits active ``Oprah''
watching while learning to speak English for helping her evolve.
``And I think we need that to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Min was 7 when the Cultural Revolution started. To evade the
beatings by neighborhood bullies that she received regularly
growing up in what she calls a ``middle lower class family'' _ both
her parents were teachers _ she embraced the ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to survive, you want to be the most powerful,'' Min
explains. ``To gain power is to be an ardent Maoist.''
</P>
<P>
   Min learned Mao's poems and won a district competition for her
efforts. Suddenly ``no one wants to beat me anymore,'' she says.
``Of course I chose society over my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   But Min's mother constantly shamed Min for her choices. ``She
would beat me until I passed out to set me right,'' says Min.
</P>
<P>
   The punishments didn't deter Min from causing great pain to
friends in the name of the Cultural Revolution. As a schoolgirl,
she denounced her teacher, causing the woman's exile.
</P>
<P>
   Min then volunteered to go to a labor camp in the distant
Chinese countryside, where hunger was a daily ordeal and the
bathroom was a maggot-filled outdoor pit. For Min the camp will
always be the place where she discovered the body of her friend,
Little Green, who had drowned. It is an experience she still speaks
of in a tremulous voice.
</P>
<P>
   Min says she and others had encountered the girl having sex with
her boyfriend at a time when relationships between men and women
were discouraged. The boyfriend was executed; Little Green, who
under political pressure had accused him of rape, went mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm living with the guilt all the time,'' says Min quietly.
``We were responsible for her death. There's no way you can repair
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories about such shattering experiences now help Min earn a
comfortable living in her adopted country. She does so with a
writing style that melds buttoned-down English with what her editor
Mueller describes as ``the flavor, some of the humor, and a lot of
the poetry of Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   One ``Madame Mao'' passage reads: ``She describes herself as a
radish pickled in the sauce of misery.'' Another goes, ``I am not
afraid of death if I know my spirit will live through the tip of
your fountain pen to the lips of the people, generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   But before writing her way into this sunny final chapter, Min
spent several dark years in Chicago with her first husband, a
Shanghai native. The family lived in a neighborhood where white
teenagers crudely propositioned Min and a black man threw a rock at
her husband. The couple ultimately divorced because of her
husband's Taoist religious views.
</P>
<P>
   ``He believes so deep that he thinks that to be born is a
tragedy,'' says Min, who yearned for a more positive life for
herself and her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Now ensconced in a suburban home writing full time, Min is
living her version of the American dream with Lofthouse, a Vietnam
veteran who works as a high school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I identify with Lloyd because he qualifies to be a communist,
he's so devoted,'' says Min warmly. ``I said, `Gee, you find this
American who suffered through war and . . . still has this idealism
and dreams of a better life, better society.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Min uses her pen to achieve her own idealistic dream of writing
Chinese history from a woman's point of view. A memoir about her
teenage years will soon be published. Then comes another historical
novel, this time about the empress dowager, another strong woman
whose 50-year rule in the 19th century has been maligned by some
historians who say she brought opium to China and murdered her
husband and son.
</P>
<P>
   Not true, says Min. And she'll prove it by using historical
documents, just as she did to re-tell Madame Mao's story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found there was no other way to do it as a woman,'' says
Min, leaning forward intently. ``I would be known as the
white-boned demon . . . if I did not have the documents backing me
up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
