u p BC-GOP-RDP-ART-(TRIM)-NY     08-01 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-RDP-ART-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE, OTHER TRADITIONAL GOP ISSUES TO TAKE CENTER STAGE AT
CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated by 9 p.m. EDT with a story
by Richard L. Berke.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ After projecting an image Monday evening of a
political party that welcomes women, minority groups and
immigrants, the Republicans were poised Tuesday to present a more
familiar focus at their convention, that of the party that embraces
and promotes military strength.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Asian-American, African-American and female
speakers were featured; on Tuesday evening, the podium will be
dominated by war heroes like retired Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf,
former Sen. Bob Dole and Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But the underlying message is the same: the Republican Party
under Gov. George W. Bush is united behind a single message and is
relentlessly disciplined and focused on taking the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The star attraction Tuesday evening will be McCain, who gave
Bush a strong run in the primaries. McCain faded after a few
initial victories, as Bush won over the party's base of
conservative voters. Still, McCain's maverick campaign captured the
attention of independent voters as he railed against moneyed
interests and pork barrel politics.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has been so relentlessly touting Bush's candidacy this
week that most observers expect him to hew to his announced theme
of military readiness and strength. McCain is expected to talk
about his grandfather, a World War II commander, linking his
service to the wartime service of former President George Bush,
Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   The convention has been so closely scripted that even the
mavericks have adhered to the party's message.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, retired Gen. Colin Powell spoke of his support
for abortion rights. But when he addressed the convention on
Monday, he dropped all references to abortion. He still spoke of
his support for affirmative action, although in the context of
praising Bush's attempts to find new ways to promote diversity in
higher education and Bush's decision to address the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People last month.
</P>
<P>
   That position put Powell at odds with most of the delegates and
alternates in the hall, a conservative group that opposes
affirmative action in education and hiring.
</P>
<P>
   But the conservative delegates cheered throughout Powell's
speech Monday, even as he took them to task for their opposition to
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On shuttle buses to and from the convention hall, some delegates
grumbled privately about attacks on the Confederate flag, a
cease-fire in the war to eliminate the Department of Education and
other attempts to moderate the party's image. But most appeared
enthusiastic about Powell, even if they did not agree with him.
</P>
<P>
   President Bill Clinton criticized the Republicans for what he
characterized as an attempt to change their party's packaging while
leaving the same product underneath.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're hoping if they wrap it tight enough, nobody will open
it before Christmas,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has ignored much Democratic criticism over the
last few days, on Tuesday he lashed back at the president. Bush
said Clinton was the one who was just playing politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome President Clinton's criticism,'' Bush said Tuesday
from Charleston, W.Va. ``He is so desperate to have his legacy
intact by getting Al Gore elected, he'll say anything, just like Al
Gore will.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although Monday's convention featured the most women and
minority speakers of the week, the Republicans are being careful to
continue showing a diverse face throughout the convention.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday evening, Condoleezza Rice, Bush's foreign policy
adviser, will speak. Elizabeth Dole, a former rival of Bush's for
the Republican nomination, is also scheduled to speak, as is Rep.
Jim Kolbe of Arizona, the only openly gay Republican in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's events will also include a tribute to past
Republican presidents. Former Presidents George Bush and Gerald
Ford will take the stage, while Nancy Reagan will represent her
husband, former President Ronald Reagan, who has Alzheimer's
disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
