<HEADER>
A9431 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     08-01 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAKING OF A MAN-EATER 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   As if we needed further evidence
that scientists are trying to kill us, a new robot has been
invented that runs on meat.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps because the name Dracula was already taken, the robot is
called Chew Chew. Whether this will be a source of comfort when the
thing begins gnawing on your leg remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Invented by Stuart Wilkinson of the University of South Florida,
Chew Chew looks more like a train of toy wagons than a heartless
man-eater, but looks can be deceiving as anyone who has seen the
movie ``Invasion of the Body Snatchers'' can attest. Right now,
Chew Chew runs on sugar cubes, but it could just as easily run on
haunch of humor columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson, who has the sense of humor one normally associates
with morticians, said he is reluctant to give robots a taste for
meat because ``they'll notice there's an awful lot of humans
running around and try to eat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ha-ha.
</P>
<P>
   In the journal New Scientist, Wilkinson said robots that are
powered by food are superior to those that run on batteries because
they don't have to be recharged. For example, a lawn-mowing robot
could power itself by eating grass clippings. (It could power
itself even more effectively by mowing over your dog, but let's not
get irresponsibly alarmist about this thing until it's absolutely
necessary.)
</P>
<P>
   I would not be overly concerned about this if it weren't for the
fact that robots are basically taking over the world. A 1998 report
by the United Nations Economic Commission said there are 720,000
robots in the world doing the work of 2 million people. Most robots
today are in factories, but as robots become more numerous in the
coming years, they will branch out into more people-oriented jobs
like nursing, elderly care and housecleaning, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   This might be bad news for the medical profession where, too
often, ``bedside manner'' consists of little more than jabbing a
needle in someone's arm and handing him a large bill. Robots could
(theoretically) be programmed to have pleasant personalities or, at
the very least, personalities somewhat warmer than Nurse Ratched's
in ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the warm, fuzzy glow that a patient receives from a
compassionate caregiver would be diminished somewhat if the
robot-nurse suddenly began gnawing on the patient's arm, but I am
willing to believe that `bugs` like this can be worked out, given
enough time.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, home of Godzilla and, more importantly, Mecha-Godzilla,
is even more gaga about robots than we are. Last year, Sony came
out with a $2,500 robot dog called Aibo that looks and acts just
like a real dog assuming your idea of a real dog is something with
titanium skin and an antenna sticking out of its butt.
</P>
<P>
   (Of course, my idea of a real dog is something that sleeps 21
hours a day and barks insanely at TV doorbells, so I am probably
not a good judge either.)
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Honda came out with a human-shaped robot with
the rather prosaic name of P3. (This would be a better name for a
robot dog, especially if it wasn't housebroken.) P3 walks on two
legs and can perform simple tasks with its two hands.
</P>
<P>
   Whether those simple tasks include dragging home unsuspecting
but well-marbled humans for dinner, I cannot say.
</P>
<P>
   All I know is if you see a train of three toy wagons staring
hungrily at that tender region just beneath your ribs, you may want
to walk quickly away.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
