<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO RED SOX DEALS _ FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The trading deadline may have passed Monday without
another peep from Yawkey Way (was it only a month ago that the
headlines were screaming Sammy Sosa's name?), but anyone who has
watched Dan Duquette operate knows that the Red Sox roster
shuffling is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Mercker, Rod Beck, Pete Schourek, Eric Gunderson, Dwayne
Hosey, plus the Matt Murrays, Jack Voigts, Greg Pirkls, and Chris
Snopeks of the world have all been August acquisitions made by
Duquette, who takes full advantage of that post-deadline window
known as the waiver deal to tinker further with his team.
</P>
<P>
   And this month promises to be no exception. First baseman Rico
Brogna, the Turners Falls (Mass.) native and Watertown (Conn.)
freshman basketball coach, could still wind up in a Boston uniform,
even though trade talks with the Phillies fell apart Monday when
the Sox balked at every prospect Philadelphia asked for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rico's extremely disappointed,'' Pat Gibbons, the player's New
York-based agent, said Monday. ``This morning, I would have said it
was 80-20 that the deal would get done. I was shocked that it
didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the players weren't enough for the Phillies to pull
the trigger. It would have been a perfect fit for all three
parties.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies, who have phenom Pat Burrell and just picked up
another first baseman/outfielder, Travis Lee, from Arizona in the
Curt Schilling deal, have no place for Brogna, who is a free agent
at the end of the year. They want to move him. Brogna would like to
come here and the Sox would like to have him, and Duquette may
figure he can get him dirt cheap if the Phillies opt to place
Brogna on waivers and no one claims him before Boston does.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman's troublesome left knee landed him on the 15-day
disabled list Monday, which would seem to make Brogna even more
desirable. But for now, at least, the Sox are content to go with
Brian Daubach at first. Second base was manned Monday night by Mike
Lansing, to whom the Sox owe a minimum of $7.25 million over the
next 18 months, a sum that may have given the Sox some pause about
Brogna, except as a rental.
</P>
<P>
   One source familiar with the Brogna talks said the sides never
really came close in the end but dismissed the suggestion that the
Sox had any concerns about the lingering effects of the fractured
forearm Brogna sustained back in May.
</P>
<P>
   The top hitters _ David Justice, Rondell White, B.J. Surhoff,
David Segui _ went elsewhere. Sammy stayed put. So did Juan
Gonzalez, though the Mariners came very close over the weekend to
swinging a deal for the Detroit slugger, one that reportedly was
quashed in the end by Tigers owner Mike Ilitch.
</P>
<P>
   The best pitchers _ Denny Neagle, Curt Schilling, Andy Ashby _
all wound up elsewhere, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees (Neagle, Justice, Glenallen Hill, Jose Vizcaino)
loaded up in the last month, as did the White Sox, who traded for
an All-Star-caliber catcher in Charles Johnson and a
still-dangerous bat off the bench in Harold Baines.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays added a starting pitcher, Steve Trachsel, who beat
both Pedro and El Duque by 1-0 scores in less than a month's time,
and another veteran in Esteban Loiaza from the Rangers. The A's
made a modest move, acquiring Jim Mecir, who briefly belonged to
the Red Sox, but he is a respected setup man who solidifies their
pen. Mecir, few will recall, was the player to be named later in
1997 for Duquette's first deal for Mike Stanley, then was claimed
by Tampa in the expansion draft six weeks later and never pitched
for the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians turned over 20 percent of their roster, but their
inability to land Schilling may outweigh everything else John Hart
did this summer, even as he replenished a pitching staff decimated
by injuries with Bob Wickman, Steve Woodard, and Jason Bere, none
of whom is likely to strike fear in the league's elite.
</P>
<P>
   And Mo's Angels, still lurking despite a paste-and-staple
starting rotation, picked up a veteran bat in Ron Gant.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox? Their big deal was Rolando Arrojo, the Cuban
righthander whose big-game pedigree dates back to when he was still
pitching for Fidel. Bret Saberhagen? ``We can't count on
Saberhagen,'' said Pedro Martinez, speaking the truth last week. At
best, he may give the Sox another five-inning pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette is confident that the resurgence of Troy O'Leary,
combined with Saturday's return of the suspended Carl Everett, will
compensate for the inability to land another hitter (yet), though
with Offerman first slumping and now hobbled, the team has been
functioning without an impact leadoff hitter all season.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, by the way, the Sox finally placed Stanley on waivers
after ignoring his request to be given an immediate release to give
him a better chance to land a job. Stanley, who won't clear waivers
until Wednessday, is taking swings with his son back in a batting
cage in Florida while teams in need of hitters have been looking
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully something will happen,'' Stanley said.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette was ripped by Nomar Garciaparra and especially Jeff
Frye, among others, for letting Stanley go. But Stanley dismisses
the idea that Frye was shipped out for speaking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, that deal had to have been in the works for a
while,'' Stanley said of the trade that sent Frye to the Rockies as
part of the Arrojo/Lansing exchange. ``I don't think this was a
`We'll get you type of thing,' not when they sent him to a place
where every hitter dreams of going.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some revisionist history going on, by the way, which
suggests that it was Jimy Williams, not Duquette, who wanted to
dump Stanley, and that it was Williams who politicked for Izzy
Alcantara's promotion before deciding not to play him.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley isn't buying it. Yes, he said, he agreed to go on the
disabled list even though there was nothing wrong with him because
Williams thought the two-week break might be good for him. And he
did so much hitting in the cages during that time that he strained
an abdominal muscle, which is why he didn't insist he be activated
immediately when the 15 days were up.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Williams) looked me in the eye and said he wanted me to be
part of the team,'' Stanley said. ``So if that's true, then what
Jimy told me face to face doesn't hold water.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I trust Jimy Williams to believe him when he looks you in
the eye. But in 14 years in this league, I've learned that there
are a lot of things that are out of a manager's control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
