<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9434 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-ART-     08-01 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MILLER HAD NO COSTLY FUMBLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not in recent memory has there been more hype surrounding a
broadcaster than the ado about Dennis Miller, who debuted as a
commentator on ABC's ``Monday Night Football'' this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Boston Channel 5's 6 p.m. newscast, Mike Lynch teased the
Hall of Fame Game between the 49ers and Patriots by suggesting that
while all eyes would be on Drew Bledsoe, ``all ears will be on
Dennis Miller.''
</P>
<P>
   Even venerable ABC sportscaster Al Michaels got into the hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have come to expect the unexpected, but this is off the
charts,'' Michaels said before introducing Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was true to form.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone in this stadium is more pumped up than me, they
won't be able to pass the league's standardized drug test,'' he
quipped.
</P>
<P>
   OK, he was excited.
</P>
<P>
   Funny? Well . . .
</P>
<P>
   He did use the word ``genitalia'' on national television. He was
talking about J.R. Redmond's groin injury, but who cares?
</P>
<P>
   Miller was able to mention drugs and sex within the first five
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But he was a little nervous at first. He said that Bledsoe was
sacked 55 times ``last night.'' Oops. That should have been ``last
year.'' Then Miller said a booming punt was a good example of the
``mile-high altitude here.'' Well, not exactly. The game was played
in Canton, Ohio, not Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is an acquired taste, and while executive producer Don
Ohlmeyer explained that he was not hired to be the court jester,
comedy is Miller's strong suit.
</P>
<P>
   As is star appeal. Tell the truth: You listened to every word
just to make sure you didn't miss a joke.
</P>
<P>
   When Lawyer Milloy roughed up the 49ers' punter, Michaels
wondered why Milloy was playing on the special teams in July.
Miller cracked, ``You know lawyers _ they get paid by the hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of his jokes fell flat. He said that Patriots coach Bill
Belichick was wrapped ``tighter than an expectant father's watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Miller needs a cable network to express himself more
freely.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, ABC is banking on the new Monday night crew to boost
sagging ratings. The opening promotional ad for the new lineup was
not subtle. It showed an old man, apparently near death, in a
hospital bed. A doctor placed headphones on the patient blaring the
theme song from ``Monday Night Football.'' All of a sudden, the
patient comes alive.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the once-popular showcase program is in need of
a resurrection. No one expects the new crew to erase the memory of
Frank Gifford, Don Meredith, and Howard Cosell; the television
industry has changed tremendously since their heyday in the '70s.
The emergence of cable, and the popularity in professional
wrestling _ as well as shows such as ``Ally McBeal'' and
``Everybody Loves Raymond'' _ have cost ``Monday Night Football''
precious ratings points. The show earned its lowest rating in
history last year, generating a 13.8 average, or nearly 14 million
households. It lost nearly 20 percent of its male viewers between
ages 18 and 34.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings are still good in comparison to other Monday night
prime-time programming but far off the show's glory days; for
instance, it generated an average rating of 21.7 _ or about 21
million households _ in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Monday's debut, Miller will be able to hold his own. He
was able to publicly articulate what many fans have thought in
private. In the first quarter, Miller questioned whether
quarterbacks actually make three, four, or even five ``reads''
before attempting a pass. Analyst Dan Fouts, the overlooked new
member of the crew, explained that when he played quarterback, he
usually counted ``one, four'' before releasing the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Football is, after all, entertainment, and for an exhibition
game _ one in which Bledsoe played only one series _ the new Monday
night crew made it fun. They were, for the most part, loose,
relaxed, and, well, entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Also making his debut was Belichick, who, when asked about
Miller, correctly answered, ``I got plenty else on my plate to
worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
