<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIONEER HAITIANS BACK IN THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jamaica's Reggae Boyz phenomenon has been an inspiration for the
hemisphere's island nations. The Jamaicans qualified for the France
'98 World Cup, and their performance helped promote the country's
sporting image as well as showcase players such as Ricardo Gardner
and Theodore Whitmore.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a precedent to Jamaica's successful campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, the Republic of Haiti became the first Caribbean nation
to qualify for the World Cup finals and threatened to become the
surprise team in Germany. In their opening match, the Haitians took
the lead against Italy as Emmanuel ``Manu'' Sanon scored in the
first minute of the second half, breaking goalkeeper Dino Zoff's
streak of 1,142 consecutive scoreless minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Sanon had predicted he would score twice in the game, saying,
``The Italian defense is too slow for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy recovered for a 3-1 victory, though, and Haiti began
self-destructing. Ernst Jean-Joseph, a commanding and elegant
central player who would later perform for the Chicago Sting,
tested positive for a banned substance after the match. The Tonton
Macoutes, the notorious enforcers of the Duvalier regime, then
began making their presence felt in the Haitian camp, leaving the
team in disarray. Even the spectacular goalkeeping of Henri
Francillon could not prevent Haiti's first-round elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was so excited because Haiti is a small country and
it was our first World Cup game ever,'' Francillon recalled Monday.
``But Italy is always one of the strongest teams in the World
Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Haiti's starters went on to professional careers.
Francillon was signed by TSV 1860 Munich. Sanon went to Belgium and
then to the San Diego Sockers.
</P>
<P>
   Francillon and Sanon will be reunited when Haiti's national
team, coached by Sanon, meets El Salvador in an exhibition at 4
p.m. Saturday at Foxboro Stadium. The Revolution and Columbus Crew
play in the second game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next four years, Haiti will be preparing a new
generation of players,'' said Francillon, now soccer coach at
Emerson College. ``When we were playing, the government paid a lot
of money to develop a strong team, and they got it. After that,
they didn't work with the young kids, and each generation went
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The importance of home-field advantage has been apparent in the
US' first two World Cup qualifiers this year. And Haiti was wise
enough to play host to the final round of the qualifying tournament
for West Germany '74. But playing before a home crowd of Haitians
can be a mixed blessing because of fans' tendency to be both
discerning and demonstrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We accomplished it by working hard,'' Francillon said. ``We
started playing together in 1965 and we were in last place in the
CONCACAF tournament. By 1971 we were second and in 1973 we were in
first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Haiti soon was submerged into two decades of what amounted to
soccer isolation, a victim of a chaotic economic and political
system. Hundreds of thousands fled the country, including the best
soccer players, mostly to Boston, Miami, Montreal, and New York.
The return of Sanon signified a commitment to the national team,
which reemerged in the 2000 CONCACAF tournament, now called the
Gold Cup. Haiti was eliminated quickly from the tournament and lost
to Trinidad and Tobago in World Cup qualifying, but several players
impressed, and Sebastian Vorbe signed with the Los Angeles Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haiti is a poor country and it is isolated as the only
French-speaking country around,'' Francillon said. ``The team needs
support from the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technically, this is a good team. The players have talent and
skills, and the more experience they get, the better they will
become. But it is difficult to play before a Haitian crowd because
they are like the French: Soccer is in their blood and they are
very critical. If you don't play well, you will have a problem with
them. The game is never over for them: They will stay around the
stadium talking about it until 1 or 2 o'clock in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Francillon moved to Boston from Florida after Hurricane Andrew
in the early 1990s and began coaching South Shore United in
Hingham. His Emerson coaching position is part-time and he works a
night shift as a supervisor at Gillette, a strange fate for the
area's only coach who has experience in both the Bundesliga and
World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might not be the right time for me, but it will happen
someday,'' Francillon said of potential coaching opportunities.
``It is the same for Haiti's players. The only way they are going
to get professional contracts is to go outside the country, because
no one comes to see us in Haiti. That is why the game Saturday is a
good idea for the Revolution to see some of our players.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A game of eight-ball
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Major League Soccer's three-division alignment has become
irrelevant. The division winners qualify for the playoffs, but the
true playoff race involves the competition to be among the top
eight, regardless of geography.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution play host to Central Division teams Dallas
Wednesday and Columbus Saturday, and these games could be as
crucial as the Aug. 12 visit to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our next two games will dictate where we will be at the end of
the season,'' Revolution coach Fernando Clavijo said. ``We have 21
points available in seven home games, and if we take 75 percent of
those points we should be in the playoffs with no worries. We would
be right on target for what we said we wanted to do at the
beginning of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Revolution midfielder Ted Chronopoulos, who sat out the
weekend's All-Star Game to rest a hamstring strain, is questionable
after damaging a right knee ligament in training Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
