<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9439 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-     08-01 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 DON'T CANONIZE BISHOP JUST YET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio _ Attention, talk radio denizens. Maybe it's a
little early to trade Drew Bledsoe, don't you think?
</P>
<P>
   This is not meant as a knock on the exuberant Michael Bishop,
who did well enough in his first moments of the summer facing real,
live (if you can call the defense the 49ers cobbled together in the
first half live) professional competition during New England's
exhibition opener against San Francisco in Monday night's Hall of
Fame Game.
</P>
<P>
   It is merely to point out that he had two wide-open guys (Rod
Rutledge and Tony Carter) on their way to the end zone and Terry
Glenn behind the defense early in the first half, when it counts
most, and he didn't put the passes where they needed to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I missed a couple of throws because I didn't get my feet
under me,'' Bishop said. ``Sometimes if I see a receiver wide open,
I tend to try and get him the ball (too quickly) rather than get my
feet set and throw it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is always good to hear a young player who not only
acknowledges mistakes but also seems to understand why they
happened; it bodes well for his future. But it must also be pointed
out that only four of the expected 49er defensive starters were in
the game when it began (six of their front seven and their strong
safety did not play at all), so even what Bishop did do early in
the game needs to be tempered by one simple fact: He isn't ready to
lead the Patriots against the best NFL competition despite his
obviously explosive athletic skills.
</P>
<P>
   Again, this is not to pummel Bishop, who made a spectacular
22-yard touchdown run on an option play in the third quarter, when
both teams played guys who may never wear a uniform again after
another week or two. And Bishop continued to do what he did last
year as a rookie in the exhibition season: make enough plays to get
his team a 20-0 lead by the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But it needs to be pointed out _ before the debate that raged so
often last year on talk radio begins anew _ that Bishop is a good
changeup, but a pitcher or a football team that tries to make a
living with changeups ends up living a lean existence.
</P>
<P>
   What Bishop showed was why he was runnerup for the Heisman
Trophy two years ago. He showed he can still make plays against the
kind of guys his Kansas State team would have manhandled. And he
showed he is more effective on the move than he is standing stock
still in the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   What he didn't show is that he should be playing ahead of Drew
Bledsoe, despite the fact that the talk radio fraternity in Boston
will be hollering about Bishop more often than Pope John Paul.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did some good things and he did some things that he could
have done better,'' Patriots head coach Bill Belichick said. ``Our
third-down conversion rate was not what you want to see (4 of 11,
36 percent). That wasn't all Michael's fault.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but he was the quarterback of record, so the
responsibility falls on his shoulders, as it does on Bledsoe's when
he is in charge of things. Bledsoe, for his part, played only one
series behind a makeshift offensive line and did what he had to do
in a game like this. He stayed in one piece.
</P>
<P>
   He'll probably be asked to do little more than that Friday night
in Detroit, when the Patriots travel to the Silverdome to play the
Lions. That means Bishop will have another chance to play his
entertaining brand of quarterback on the run, something he did well
enough Monday night to finish 9 of 13 for 101 yards, with a 25-yard
touchdown pass to Kevin Faulk, while also rushing four times for
another 50 yards, including a 22-yard score.
</P>
<P>
   Those are impressive numbers, but they are not the only numbers
that the wise talk-show caller should be looking at when it comes
to Bishop. There is also the number ``3'' that needs to be
addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Three, as in those three open receivers, none of whom got the
ball where they needed it. This is not to say Bledsoe hasn't
overthrown Glenn from time to time. And it is not to say he hasn't
put a ball behind a receiver as he broke wide open, as Bishop did
to Carter and Rutledge.
</P>
<P>
   It is just to point out what should be obvious to anyone but
those obsessively wanting a quarterback controversy in New England,
and that is that Bledsoe is a more proficient passer and far better
quarterback at the moment than Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   This should not come as a news bulletin to anyone who has been
paying attention, but the fact is you will hear that Bishop did
this and Bishop did that and how about using him on third down or
running the option on the goal line with him. Or, if the caller has
really been hitting the sauce, that he's even more dangerous than
the strong-armed but immobile Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   None of that was proven Monday night despite the numbers Bishop
put up. The reality that emerged was the same as a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bishop is a talented athlete with a future. Put into
certain situations _ as offensive coordinator Charlie Weis did when
he had him run the option in the third quarter for a touchdown _ he
is a kid who one day may make life uncomfortable for Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   But that day has not yet come.
</P>
<P>
   Not this week, and not any time soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
