<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9448 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-INSURANCE-COMMISSIONE     08-01 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-COMMISSIONER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW INSURANCE COMMISSIONER WON'T ROCK THE BOAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By ERIC BRAZIL and DIANA WALSH  
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In appointing retired Justice Harry W. Low as
California insurance commissioner, Gov. Davis chose a man seemingly
without enemies and a reputation for integrity and competence _ but
no boat rocker.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is banking on Low to restore public confidence in the
California Department of Insurance, in the wake of the scandal that
forced former insurance commissioner Chuck Quackenbush from office
last month.
</P>
<P>
   He is ``above reproach and, more importantly, above politics,''
Davis said at a press conference announcing Low's appointment
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In praising the former appellate court justice for his
character, intellect and judicial temperament, Davis tacitly
acknowledged that Low, unlike Quackenbush, is someone who would
find it unthinkable to use the insurance commissioner's office to
advance a personal political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe at the end of the day, if anyone on the planet can
restore integrity and credibility to the office of the Department
of Insurance, that person is Harry Low,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   low said he plans to apply an even hand to his new job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly intend to administer the law as fairly and
favorably as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding Justice J. Anthony Kline, who served with Low on the
1st District Court of Appeals and had been then-Gov. Jerry Brown's
screener of judicial nominations when Low was named to the
appellate bench, said Low is ``intelligent, principled and has no
political ambitions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He will approach this job with a level of objectivity and
experience that few people could.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 69, Low has been in public life for more than 40 years.
In addition to spending 1966 to 1992 on the bench _ the last decade
as an appellate justice _ Low also served as president of the San
Francisco Police Commission from 1992 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of California Insurance Companies said in a
prepared statement that Low's appointment is ``hopefully the first
major step toward restoring the department to an effective and
credible (industry) regulator.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harvey Rosenfeld, a consumer advocate who co-authored a 1988
ballot initiative that made the commissioner's job elective,
questioned whether Low can be an industry watchdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a balanced record as a judge (but) we're disappointed
that the governor didn't pick an aggressive advocate for
consumers,'' Rosenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   Low said he understood the protections the department must offer
Californians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The insurance department must protect consumers against unfair
practices, excessive or discriminatory insurance rates, and ensure
financial stability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Without offering specifics, Low said he plans to review
insurance claims from the 1994 Northridge quake that sparked the
scandal that forced Quackenbush's June 28 resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Low was born and reared and received his early education in the
Stanislaus County town of Oakdale, which is better known for
producing champion team ropers than judges. He attended Modesto
Junior College and graduated from UC-Berkeley in 1952. He
subsequently took his law degree from Boalt Hall School of Law and
went to work as a deputy state attorney general. He was first
appointed to the bench as a municipal court judge by then-Gov.
Edmund G. (Pat) Brown. He won election to the Superior Court in
1974 and in 1982 was named an appellate court justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Balance'' is the word that finds itself in virtually every
conversation about Low's performance on the bench. As a judge, he
considered a wide array of insurance cases before his retirement.
He has since been a member of the Judicial Arbitration and
Mediation Service's Alternate Dispute Resolution Panel, which
handles a number of insurance cases.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1999, Low has chaired San Francisco's Human Rights
Commission. He is also a past president of the California Judges
Association and a past national president of the Chinese American
Citizens Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Low married his wife Mayling in 1952, and they have three
children and four grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The new position will pay Low $132,000 a year. It requires
confirmation by a majority of both the Assembly and Senate. The
Legislature reconvenes Aug. 7 and is in session through the end of
the month.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush, a Republican and a former assemblyman, ran into
trouble in May with the disclosure that he had given a
multimillion-dollar break to several insurers of the victims of the
Northridge quake.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using his authority to require the insurers to
provide adequate settlements for earthquake-caused damages,
Quackenbush had forced them to contribute $12.5 million _ far less
than the potential fines they faced - to the California Research
and Assistance Fund, which he controlled.
</P>
<P>
   The fund financed political polls, minority outreach programs
and charitable grants that bore little if any relationship to the
quake. Some appeared to be vehicles to advance Quackenbush's
personal political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush resigned as legislative hearings into his
mishandling of insurance claims arising from the quake were about
to begin. He is now under investigation by a federal grand jury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
