<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TACO-TASTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REELIN' IN SOME TASTY TACOS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(With FISH-TACOS) 
By LARRY LIPSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's about as easy to find a tasty fish taco in the San Fernando
Valley these days as it is along the sandy beaches of Mexico. The
challenge is in finding the best ones.
</P>
<P>
   We randomly sampled these popular creations at a half a dozen
neighborhood purveyors, and here's how they stacked up from first
to last:
</P>
<P>
   1. Bronco Restaurant, 4378 Woodman Ave., Sherman Oaks, (818)
990-4961.
</P>
<P>
   Authentic, no-nonsense tacos at very reasonable prices. Corn
tortillas are soft, shrimp crunchy in larger-than-expected pieces;
battered pollock fish nicely presented. Pretty good salsa bar handy
for extras. Prices: Whitefish (pollock) $1.25, shrimp $1.75.
</P>
<P>
   2. Carrillo's Tortilleria &AMP; Mexican Delicatessen, 19744 Sherman
Way, Canoga Park, (818) 887-6118. (Also in San Fernando and Simi
Valley.)
</P>
<P>
   Very close second. Tacos look appealing. Also very Mexican
authentic. Cod tacos have good general flavor though a tad salty
for our gringo palates. Char-grilled shrimp tasted especially good
in fresh, house-produced tortillas. Prices: Cod $1.75, shrimp
$2.25.
</P>
<P>
   3. Poquito Mas, 3701 Cahuenga Blvd. West, near Universal City,
(818) 760-8226. (Also in Valencia, Burbank, North Hollywood, the
Sunset Strip and West L.A.)
</P>
<P>
   Lots of good, broiled shrimp. And upscale ahi tuna tacos come
with roasted red pepper sauce. One of the better-stocked salsa
bars. Prices: Shrimp $3.65, ahi tuna $5.10 (market price).
</P>
<P>
   4. Adobe Cantina, 29100 Agoura Road, Agoura Hills, (818)
991-3474.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly but good _ we spent the most on these tacos. Really more
like meals than snacks. More fish choices here than elsewhere. We
selected mahi mahi, cod and rock shrimp versions. Bonus: a load of
bright green, red and white chips, the national colors of Mexico.
Prices: Cod $7.95, tasty mahi mahi $8.95, rock shrimp $9.95, the
latter was ordered with rice and beans.
</P>
<P>
   5. Baja Fresh Mexican Grill, 19960 Ventura Blvd., Woodland
Hills, (818) 888-3976. (Also in Studio City, Burbank, Pasadena,
Beverly Hills and elsewhere.)
</P>
<P>
   Smoky, char-grilled shrimp for a dime more is a better buy than
breaded red snapper fish tacos. Both made with good and soft, but
small, corn tortillas. Looked attractive. Prices: Fish (Pacific red
snapper) $1.85, shrimp $1.95.
</P>
<P>
   6. Rubio's Baja Grill, 17200 Ventura Blvd., Encino, (818)
784-1497. (Also in Glendale, Northridge, Oxnard and elsewhere.)
</P>
<P>
   Though eaten in-house, tacos were delivered wrapped in paper.
Corn tortillas rubbery, rough and tough. Cheese overwhelms shrimp.
Batter-fried fish tacos on sale but impart little satisfaction.
Grilled mahi mahi tasty and worth the extra. Prices: Fish (Alaskan
pollock) 99 cents, shrimp $2.85, mahi mahi $2.55. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9491 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-FISH-SIDE-LADN &LR;      08-01 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISH-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTIN' FISHY WITH IT AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(With FISH TACOS) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you want to make a splash with fish tacos at home, here are
some tips for getting them on the table fast.
</P>
<P>
   -Do preliminary preparations before starting to cook the fish
and have ingredients organized assembly-line style. That means the
batter should be prepared if deep frying, fish cut into pieces, oil
in pot and tortillas wrapped in foil and ready to warm in oven or
toaster oven.
</P>
<P>
   -Choose a mild, firm-fleshed fish such as halibut or cod that
will hold up well. It's also possible to use mahi mahi, red snapper
or ahi tuna. Liven up, but don't overpower the batter (if using)
with seasonings such as garlic, ground cumin and chili powder.
</P>
<P>
   -When deep-frying, use a bland oil such as canola or vegetable
oil, and be sure it is heated to 375 degrees to avoid ending up
with soggy fish. Also, cook only a few batter-coated fish pieces at
time (don't overcrowd the pan); when golden, drain on paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   -If you plan to grill the fish, for best results, cook in large
pieces and cut into smaller pieces after cooking. Large shrimp are
the easiest to manage. Saute in a little butter and oil over high
heat _ or grill in a foil pan (with holes poked in bottom). The
foil pan will keep the shrimp from falling through the grid. You
can also broil the shrimp indoors.
</P>
<P>
   -Use thick, fresh corn tortillas, if available. Otherwise you'll
have to double the tortillas so diners can manage the tacos without
having them falling apart. Although a few quick-service food places
use flour tortillas, corn are preferred.
</P>
<P>
   -Feel free to dress the tacos with any kind of salsa
(store-bought or homemade) desired. If making pico de gallo (or
whatever other sauce you decide to use) from scratch, whip it up
before starting to cook the fish. -If you plan to dress the tacos
with a white sauce, whip up one with sour cream and a little lemon
juice _ or combine a mixture of mayonnaise and plain yogurt with a
few seasonings. A mild store-bought bottled ranch-type dressing or
sour cream dip could suffice if time is short.
</P>
<P>
   -Have finely shredded lettuce or cabbage (and finely chopped
fresh cilantro) ready to sprinkle on the tacos.
</P>
<P>
   -To heighten the flavor of the fish, offer cut-up lemon or lime
wedges so diners can add a squeeze, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   -Guacamole and shredded cheeses are optional. If you plan to
offer them, remember you can shortcut the work by using prepared
guacamole from the market and preshredded cheeses in a variety of
flavors and combinations.
</P>
<P>
   -Assemble tacos while fish and tortillas are hot _ and eat as
soon as possible to avoid ending up with soggy tacos.
</P>
<P>
   -For speed in assembly, you can tuck the fish (atop a little
sauce, if desired) in the tortillas and ask diners to top as
desired. Or you can assemble the tacos _ with everything _ and
simply pass the hot sauce. There seem to be no hard-and-fast rules
about the order of layering the sauces and greens atop the fish,
but keep in mind the finished tacos should be appealing to the eye.
In recent taco-sampling travels, we found the best and most
attractive-looking ones topped with pico de gallo, chopped
tomatoes, onions and cilantro, and colorful sauces.
</P>
<P>
   -Keep in mind that tacos lend themselves to serving both buffet
and sit-down style. For side dishes to accompany the tacos, offer
black or refried beans and Mexican-style rice (cooked with some
tomatoes, ground cumin and ground chili powder or diced green
chiles). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9492 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-FISH-TACOS-LADN-3rdTa     08-01 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISH-TACOS-LADN-3rdTake </SLUG>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRILLED SHRIMP TACOS WITH RADICCHIO AND AVOCADO SALSA &QL; 
1/4 cup olive oil &QL; 
2 cloves garlic, minced &QL; 
12 jumbo shrimp, peeled and deveined &QL; 
1 tablespoon coarse salt &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper &QL; 
6 (8-inch) flour tortillas &QL; 
12 small radicchio leaves &QL; 
3/4 cup Avocado Salsa (Recipe follows) &QL; 
6 wedges lime
</P>
<P>
   Combine olive oil with garlic and marinate shrimp 1 hour prior
to grilling. When ready to cook, season shrimp with salt and
pepper, and grill approximately 1 1/2 to 2 minutes on each side,
until center of shrimp is still barely opaque.
</P>
<P>
   Warm tortillas on grill; remove to a cutting board and cut in
half. Fold one edge of tortilla half toward the center, twisting
that edge inside and toward the rounded top, and roll so you have a
cone-shaped tortilla.
</P>
<P>
   Put 1 radicchio leaf, 1 tablespoon Avocado Salsa and 1 shrimp in
each cone and place, seam down, on a plate. Continue until all
tacos are complete. Serve with wedges of lime. Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Pacifica Blue Plates,'' by Neil Stuart, Ten Speed Press. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
AVOCADO SALSA &QL; 
2 medium avocados, peeled, seeded and diced &QL; 
1/2 cup seeded and diced tomatoes &QL; 
1/4 cup chopped cilantro &QL; 
3 tablespoons diced red onion &QL; 
1 clove garlic, minced &QL; 
1 tablespoon fresh lime juice &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon seeded and minced jalapeno pepper &QL; 
1 teaspoon coarse salt &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Combine and gently mix all ingredients in a bowl. Salsa is best
when used same day prepared. Makes 3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BAJA FISH TACOS &QL; 
Making a taco is no different than building a sandwich: pick your
bread, be it flour or corn tortillas, decide upon a filling and
then choose a suitable salsa.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is a reasonable facsimile of the fish tacos tasted
in Ensenada. For a variation, try grilling the fish on your
barbecue. Although the recipe specifies sea bass, any firm,
white-fleshed fish will do, as well as shark or swordfish. Don't
fail to give the fish a squeeze of fresh lime. &QL; 
BEER BATTER: &QL; 
1/2 cup flour &QL; 
1 1/2 tablespoons paprika &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper &QL; 
2 tablespoons cornstarch &QL; 
2 teaspoons coarse salt &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon granulated garlic &QL; 
1 cup beer, cold &QL; 
TACOS: &QL; 
Oil for frying &QL; 
3/4 pound sea bass fillet &QL; 
1/2 cup flour &QL; 
1 cup shredded green cabbage &QL; 
8 (6-inch) corn tortillas, warmed &QL; 
1/2 cup Cilantro Mayo (Recipe follows) &QL; 
1/2 cup Fresh Tomato Salsa (Recipe follows) &QL; 
8 wedges lime
</P>
<P>
   To make Beer Batter, sift all dry batter ingredients into a
small bowl and whisk in beer gradually until batter is smooth. Keep
refrigerated until ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   For Tacos, in a heavy skillet, heat 2 inches oil to 350 degrees
F. Cut sea bass into 8 strips, dredge in flour, cover completely
with beer batter and place carefully in hot oil, frying on both
sides until golden brown. Remove and drain excess oil on paper
towels.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble tacos, place equal amounts of cabbage down center of
each warm tortilla; then, put a tablespoon of Cilantro Mayo, a
strip of fried sea bass, and, finally, a tablespoon of Fresh Tomato
Salsa. Serve with lime wedges. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Pacifica Blue Plates,'' by Neil Stuart, Ten Speed Press. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CILANTRO MAYO &QL; 
3 large eggs &QL; 
1 teaspoon dry mustard &QL; 
2 bunches fresh cilantro, chopped &QL; 
1/4 cup rice wine vinegar &QL; 
1 clove garlic, minced &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper &QL; 
1 teaspoon coarse salt &QL; 
1 cup peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients except peanut oil in a blender or food
processor. Begin to process and add oil in a steady stream until
completely incorporated. Keeps refrigerated 2 weeks. Makes 2 cups. &QL; 
CAUTION: This recipe contains uncooked eggs. Because of the
possible threat of salmonella, U.S. Government officials recommend
that the very young, the elderly, pregnant women and people with
serious illnesses or weakened immune systems not eat raw or lightly
cooked eggs.
</P>
<P>
   If desired, doctor up store-bought mayonnaise with 2 bunches of
fresh chopped cilantro, minced garlic, pepper, dry mustard and a
little rice wine vinegar instead of making your own mayonnaise &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FRESH TOMATO SALSA &QL; 
!ital!There's just no reason to eat store-bought tomato salsa
anymore. Whether you call this ``salsa cruda,'' ``salsa fresca,''
or whatever else, when you use vine ripe tomatoes and serve it with
a basket of fresh, hot tortillas, nothing comes close to being this
good. You can spice the recipe up or down, as desired. If you can't
find tomatillos, you can eliminate them from the recipe. &QL; 
2 cups diced tomatoes &QL; 
1/2 cup diced tomatillos &QL; 
1/2 cup diced red onion &QL; 
1 clove garlic, minced &QL; 
1 small jalapeno pepper, seeded and minced &QL; 
1/2 cup chopped cilantro &QL; 
1 tablespoon fresh lime juice &QL; 
1/4 cup rice wine vinegar &QL; 
1 teaspoon sugar &QL; 
1 teaspoon coarse salt &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper Mix all ingredients in a
bowl. Allow salsa to set 1 hour before serving so flavors develop.
Serve at room temperature. Makes 3 cups. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
