<SLUG> BC-TACOS-FISH-LADN-3Takes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVE IN! FISH TACOS ARE DAY AT THE BEACH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(With TACO-SIDE, TACO-TASTE) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Move over, beef and chicken _ fish tacos are making a splash on
menus these days. If you aren't hooked already, now is a good time
to discover this trendy taco variation. There are plenty of options
at quick-service Mexican food stands and restaurants in the Valley
and beyond to explore _ or you can try your hand at making them at
home.
</P>
<P>
   The humble fish creation seems to have originated more than 25
years ago in San Felipe, a Mexican town on the Gulf of California,
where fresh fish was plentiful and the locals wrapped it up inside
their tortillas. And then surfers and college partiers found them
at stands along the beach in south-of-the-border towns when looking
for something cheap and satisfying to eat.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long before entrepreneurs capitalized on the idea,
brought it over the border and added their own style. Rubio's _
Home of the Fish Taco (opened in San Diego's Mission Bay in 1983
after Ralph Rubio discovered the fish taco while on a college
spring break in San Felipe) has to date sold more than 38 million
fish tacos and is now known as Rubio's Baja Grill.
</P>
<P>
   The company's signature Baja-style fish taco combines
beer-batter fried fish (pollock) fillets in warm corn tortillas
with mild salsa, tangy white sauce and shredded green cabbage. But
today Rubio's also offers grilled fish tacos, sauteed shrimp tacos
and fish tacos dressed up with a variety of toppings at its 95
outlets sprinkled throughout the western states (13 in Los Angeles
county).
</P>
<P>
   Depending on where you order them, fish tacos are cooked and
styled in a variety of ways.
</P>
<P>
   The creations are built around numerous varieties of fish,
ranging from cod and pollock to red snapper, ahi tuna, mahi mahi,
shrimp, lobster, salmon, swordfish, halibut and more. While some
versions feature batter- fried fish chunks, the fish in others is
grilled or charbroiled or even sauteed.
</P>
<P>
   Most often, the fish appears tucked into corn rather than flour
tortillas _ either a single thick one or two thinner ones _ ranging
from 3 to 8 inches in diameter. But be forewarned _ some tortillas
taste better than others. In some instances, the earthy flavor of
the tortillas (which can be rubbery) overpowers the fish; in
others, it blends deliciously with the ingredients. Some upscale
restaurants even use handmade blue or white corn tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   The tacos come sauced and topped in a variety of ways: some with
white sauce and a blanket of red sauce; others with fresh pico de
gallo (a mixture of chopped tomatoes, onions and cilantro); some
even with fruit salsas. Depending on where you eat them, you might
find shredded lettuce or cabbage, lots of chopped cilantro and even
a wedge of lime.
</P>
<P>
   Some come plain (diners are expected to dress them to taste with
toppings and salsas, from mild to explosive), while others are
pre-assembled with everything.
</P>
<P>
   It was evident in a recent tasting at stands and restaurants
that there are many variations on the theme.
</P>
<P>
   At the 7-year-old quick-service Bronco in Sherman Oaks, white
fish (pollock) and shrimp tacos, which were added to the menu about
8 months ago, are only available coated with batter and fried crisp
in vegetable oil. ``They're now as popular as beef and chicken
tacos,'' notes owner Jose Santos. But the shrimp outsells the white
fish version, both of which are assembled and presented in doubled
fresh corn tortillas, topped with chopped lettuce, tomatoes and
onions, then smothered with a layer of sour cream-based
dressing-like white sauce and a layer of special red sauce (with
tomato, garlic and chiles). At $1.25 (white fish) and $1.75
(shrimp), they're a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret to making a good fish taco depends on the quality
of the fish and the process (how it is prepared),'' says Santos. He
cuts the fresh fish into same-size pieces _ about 3 inches long and
3/4-inch wide _ and, prior to frying, coats them with a batter made
of flour, beer, egg and fish seasonings. Each taco comes with one
large fish piece or, in the case of shrimp, one large batter-coated
shrimp, which has been cut into two or three pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Poquito Mas, which specializes in fresh, healthy, Mexican
cuisine, has been making shrimp tacos since it opened in Studio
City in 1984 (locations now also in North Hollywood, Burbank,
Valencia and West Los Angeles), notes Kevin McCarney,
founder-owner. McCarney said they came about as the result of a
conversation with a woman who owned a taco stand in San Felipe
about 15 or 16 years ago. When he asked if she'd make shrimp tacos
without breading, she immediately whipped up something and asked
him if that was what he had in mind. It was _ and that was the
impetus for his business.
</P>
<P>
   At Poquito Mas, medium-size shrimp are broiled, then put in a
light tomato-based sauce (ranchera) and sauteed quickly. For best
results, use good-quality shrimp, advises McCarney. The wonderful
smoky flavor comes from the flame broiling. The shrimp are then
placed in doubled fresh corn tortillas (warmed on the grill about
20 to 30 seconds per side) to keep the taco from falling apart when
you eat it. Chopped onions and fresh cilantro and a piece of lime
top it off. Customers can then do their own thing and add their
choice of eight different salsas from the salsa bar. ``Chapina
salsa (cooked tomatoes, onions and celery) is my favorite sauce for
shrimp,'' adds McCarney.
</P>
<P>
   Grilled ahi tacos were introduced at Poquito Mas about four
years ago as another fresh, upscale presentation. The fish is
grilled and presented atop a single mini 3-inch flour tortilla. Two
come with a combination plate _ or you can order them a la carte.
The delicious roasted bell pepper-sour cream sauce, served
alongside, elevates them a notch above some others. The secret to
cooking the ahi, says McCarney, is to remove it from the broiler
when it is about 90 percent cooked because it will continue to
cook. Some customers prefer ordering it seared _ not cooked
through. ``We don't do batter-fried tacos,'' explains McCarney,
adding that ``our concept is clean and good-for-you food. A
batter-fried fish taco is tough to eat two or three times a week.''
Ahi and shrimp tacos are about equal in sales and popularity with
steak and chicken tacos in all locations except North Hollywood,
where fewer fish tacos are consumed, adds McCarney.
</P>
<P>
   Fish tacos can be made successfully at home, says McCarney.
``Ahi is one of the best fish for flavor and consistency.'' It
maintains its flavor without being overpowering and is better for
Mexican food with tortillas than sea bass or snapper, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Carrillo's in Canoga Park (other locations in San Fernando and
Simi Valley are owned by different family members) has been serving
batter- coated fried cod (white fish) tacos for two years and
grilled shrimp tacos for the last six months, says owner Larry
Luna.
</P>
<P>
   Both utilize a single, thick 7 1/2-inch corn tortilla, hot off
the grill, handmade daily on the premises. ``Thick corn tortillas
hold up better and are less likely to get soggy when salsa and
other toppings are added.'' The tacos are topped with finely
chopped lettuce (which is more popular than cabbage) and pico de
gallo (chopped tomatoes, onion, cilantro), making for an attractive
presentation. The white fish taco comes with sour cream mixed with
a little lemon juice _ and assorted salsas are included with all
orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife likes to make fish tacos at home,'' notes Luna. For
best results, ``Don't let the batter sit too long _ or it won't
stick to the fish.''
</P>
<P>
   When you want to give fish tacos a whirl at home, pick and
choose from the array of recipes that follow _ and adapt them to
suit yourself. Once you get the knack, you may turn them out often
for family and friends. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(RECIPES FOLLOW)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9499 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-COOKS-CORNER-LADN &LR;      08-01 1506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKS-CORNER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 MILKS, 3 VERSIONS, 1 GOOD CAKE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In response to Sue Mullins' request for a Tres Leche Cake,
several readers sent similar variations on the theme. The first
recipe, from the new ``Joy of Cooking,'' was shared by Marilyn
Kessler, who noted that she had made it several times _ and it has
always received rave reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Two recipes have a meringue topping, while the other has a
whipped cream frosting. &QL; 
TRES LECHES CAKE &QL; 
(Shared by Marilyn Kessler, Encino) &QL; 
CAKE: &QL; 
1 cup all-purpose flour &QL; 
2 teaspoons baking powder &QL; 
3 large egg whites &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon cream of tartar (optional) &QL; 
1 cup sugar &QL; 
3 large egg yolks &QL; 
1/4 cup milk &QL; 
MILK MIXTURE: &QL; 
1 cup heavy whipping cream &QL; 
1 (12-ounce) can evaporated milk &QL; 
1 (14-ounce) can sweetened condensed milk &QL; 
MERINGUE TOPPING: &QL; 
2/3 cup light corn syrup &QL; 
2 large egg whites
</P>
<P>
   Have all ingredients at room temperature. Preheat oven to 350
degrees F (325 degrees F if using glass). Grease 1 (9x9-inch) pan
or 1 (11x7-inch) pan.
</P>
<P>
   For Cake, sift together flour and baking powder.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, beat egg whites and cream of tartar on medium
speed until soft peaks form. Gradually add sugar, beating at high
speed. Beat in egg yolks, one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Add 1/4 of flour mixture at a time, beating on low speed or
stirring with a rubber spatula just until incorporated and scraping
the sides of the bowl as necessary. Add 1/4 cup milk and beat just
until mixture is smooth and evenly mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape batter into prepared pan and spread evenly. Bake at 350
degrees F until top springs back when lightly pressed and a
toothpick inserted into center comes out clean, 25 to 30 minutes.
Let cool in pan on a rack 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, make Milk Mixture by combining cream, evaporated milk
and sweetened condensed milk.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the cake in pan, prick with a toothpick at 1-inch
intervals. Pour milk mixture slowly over cake, including corners
and edges. Refrigerate at least 1 hour before serving or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   To make Meringue Topping, combine corn syrup and egg whites in a
2 1/2-quart heatproof bowl (preferably stainless steel).
</P>
<P>
   Bring about 1-inch water to a gentle simmer in a wide, deep
skillet. Set bowl of egg whites directly in hot water. Immediately
begin beating on low speed, moving mixer all around bowl, until
mixture reaches 140 degrees F. If you must stop beating for any
reason, remove bowl from hot water until you can resume to prevent
egg whites from scrambling. Beat on high speed 5 minutes; mixture
will be billowy and hold a stiff shape. Remove bowl from skillet
and beat 2 to 3 more minutes until meringue is cool.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, leave cake in pan or slide a slim knife around cake to
detach it from pan. Invert cake onto a large shallow serving
platter with enough of a rim to hold excess milk that will
gradually collect around cake like a sauce. Spread or pipe meringue
topping over cake. Cut into squares to serve. Makes 1 cake.
</P>
<P>
   From the new ``Joy of Cooking.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
LOS RANCHOS TRES LECHES &QL; 
(Shared by Steven Shunn, Glendale; and Ruth Nebron, Valley Glen)
</P>
<P>
   The recipe is from Los Ranchos Restaurant in Miami, which was
founded by a nephew of the late Nicaraguan President Anastasio
Somoza. &QL; 
CAKE: &QL; 
1 cup sugar &QL; 
5 large eggs, separated &QL; 
1/3 cup milk &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
1 cup all-purpose flour &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoons baking powder &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon cream of tartar &QL; 
MILK SYRUP: &QL; 
1 (12-ounce) can evaporated milk &QL; 
1 cup EACH sweetened condensed milk and whipping cream &QL; 
1 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
1 tablespoon light rum &QL; 
MERINGUE: &QL; 
1 cup sugar &QL; 
1/4 cup water &QL; 
3 egg whites &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   Generously butter a 13x9x2-inch baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   For Cake, beat 3/4 cup sugar and egg yolks until light and
fluffy, about 5 minutes. Fold in milk, vanilla, flour and baking
powder. In separate bowl, beat egg whites to stiff peaks, adding
cream of tartar after 20 seconds. Gradually add remaining 1/4 cup
sugar and continue beating until whites are glossy and firm, but
not dry. Gently fold whites into yolk mixture. Pour batter into
prepared pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake cake in preheated 350-degree oven about 40 to 50 minutes,
until it feels firm and an inserted toothpick comes out clean. Let
cake cool completely on a wire rack.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile make Milk Syrup: Combine evaporated milk, sweetened
condensed milk, whipping cream, vanilla and rum in a mixing bowl.
Whisk until well mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Unmold cake onto a deep, large platter. Pierce cake all over
with a fork. Pour Milk Syrup over cake. Spoon overflow back on top
until all is absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   Make Meringue: Place 3/4 cup plus 2 tablespoons sugar in a heavy
saucepan with water. Cover and cook over high heat 2 minutes.
Uncover pan and cook sugar to soft-ball stage, 239 degrees F on a
candy thermometer, 6 to 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, beat egg whites to soft peaks with cream of tartar in
electric mixer. Add remaining 2 tablespoons sugar gradually,
continuing beating to stiff peaks. Pour boiling sugar syrup in a
thin stream into whites and continue beating until mixture is cool
to the touch. The hot syrup ``cooks'' the whites.
</P>
<P>
   Using a wet spatula, spread top and sides of cake with a thick
layer of Meringue. Refrigerate cake, covered, at least 2 hours
before serving. Makes 8 to 10 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Miami Spice,'' by Steven Raichlen. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THREE-MILK CAKE &QL; 
(Shared by Ruth Nebron, Valley Glen) &QL; 
CAKE: &QL; 
1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
2 teaspoons baking powder &QL; 
4 eggs, separated &QL; 
1 1/2 cups sugar &QL; 
1/2 cup milk &QL; 
THREE-MILK TOPPING: &QL; 
1 (12-ounce) can evaporated milk &QL; 
1 (14-ounce) can sweetened condensed milk &QL; 
1 cup EACH milk and dairy sour cream (can use fat-free) &QL; 
WHIPPED CREAM TOPPING: &QL; 
2 cups whipping cream &QL; 
1 tablespoon sugar &QL; 
1 teaspoon vanilla OR almond extract
</P>
<P>
   Grease and flour a 13x9x2-inch baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   For Cake, sift flour with baking powder. In a large bowl with
clean beaters, beat egg whites until fluffy. Add sugar gradually,
beating to form stiff peaks. Add yolks, one at a time. Fold in
flour mixture and milk; mix well but don't beat. Pour batter into
prepared pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven until edges are golden brown,
about 30 to 35 minutes. Remove from oven, let cool on a rack.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare Three-Milk Topping: Combine milks and sour cream. Do not
beat. Pour Topping over cake and let sit until all mixture is
absorbed, 20 to 30 minutes (or refrigerate overnight).
</P>
<P>
   Prepare Whipped Cream Topping: Chill cream, bowl and beaters
thoroughly. Beat cream with electric mixer until it begins to
thicken. Gradually add sugar and vanilla and beat until stiff peaks
form. Refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Before serving, cover top and sides of cake with Whipped Cream
Topping, cut cake into squares and serve. Or spread Whipped Cream
Topping over squares of cake. Makes 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from a recipe from the Houston Chronicle. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Can you help &QL; 
If you have recipes that can help these readers, please send them
along to us at the address below to share in a future column. &QL; 
I am looking for a creamy garlic sauce recipe that is white, not
red in color. Does anyone know how to make this?
</P>
<P>
   _ Cheri Grady &QL;
</P>
<P>
   North Hollywood &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Does anyone have a recipe for the original chili _ or something
close _ that was served on the hot dogs at Cupid's in years past.
The chili served at Cupid's today doesn't taste the same.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lynette Duitsman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Canoga Park &QL; 
