<SLUG> BC-WALKPOLK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Food Lovers' Walks is a bi-weekly column that covers
neighborhoods in San Francisco and other Bay Area cities where a
casual stroll turns up culinary treasures. &HT;     
 Food Lovers' Walks: Strolling on Polk Street Offers a Big Slice 
 of Life   By Lesli Neilson  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Standing on the corner of California and Polk
streets in the heart of Polk Gulch, the neighborhood looks a little
scruffy. Liquor stores, 24-hour doughnut shops, hardware stores and
vintage gay bars (from the days when Polk Gulch was the center of
the gay community). But the strip also holds lots of culinary
discoveries.
<P>
   Just a couple of doors from the corner lies major sustenance for
an afternoon's walk _  &UR; Swan Oyster Depot &LR; , which has been feeding
locals and tourists fresh seafood since 1912. In May, Swan received
a prestigious James Beard award as a Regional Classic. The
Sanchimino family has been running the place since father Sal and
three cousins bought it from the original Danish owners in 1948.
Sal bought out his cousins in 1973 and added the clam chowder,
smoked salmon and take-out fish business. He died in 1989, and Swan
is now run by his children.
</P>
<P>
   Here are two tips _ arrive early to avoid a line winding out the
door and, if soft-shell crab ($12.50) is available, order it. The
28-seat marble bar holds evenly dispersed bowls of oyster crackers,
lemon wedges, Tabasco sauce and horseradish. Oysters on the half
shell ($13.90 a dozen) are as fresh as they come; the combo salad _
a large portion of crabmeat, bay shrimp and medium shrimp atop
crisp iceberg lettuce with Louis dressing ($14.25) _ is big enough
to share. Wash down the frutti di mare with one of the beers on tap
or a glass of white wine. Swan is open only during the day _
Monday-Saturday 8 a.m.-5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   For dessert, pop in to the oldest existing  &UR; See's Candies &LR;  store
in the country, right next to the graffiti-laden skeleton of the
Royal Theater. Opened in 1936, the black-and-white-tiled shop
offers the usual top-notch See's specialties.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't too many culinary destinations over the next four
blocks, but the reward for covering them is  &UR; Leonard's 2001 &LR; , on
the corner of Pacific Avenue and Polk Street. Owner Leonard Born
boasts over 275 domestic and imported cheeses, which are precut for
shoppers' convenience. Born not only will suggest interesting
products but will let you sample them and offer a recipe while he's
at it. He also carries worldly foodstuffs such as Callebaut
chocolate _ a favorite among bakers _ specialty dried pastas and
dried herbs, spices, fruit, nuts and legumes in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   Just off Polk on Pacific Avenue lies the  &UR; Jug Shop &LR; . Native San
Franciscan Phil Priolo opened the store 22 years ago, and stocks
more than 11,000 items, most of it wine. The shop offers wine
tastings every Thursday, Friday and Saturday for a $3 fee.
</P>
<P>
   Head back to Polk, then walk north toward Broadway, ducking into
 &UR; Cafe Aroma &LR;  for take-out. The rotisserie chicken ($7.95) is a
favorite among locals.
</P>
<P>
   Although the official demarcation line is further up Polk,
Russian Hill's influence on the street really begins at Broadway.
Here you'll find a variety of coffee houses, antique stores and
markets to explore, including  &UR; Real Food Co. &LR; , opened in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Another slice of San Francisco history is at  &UR; Mario's Bohemian &LR; 
 &UR; Cigar Store Cafe Ristorante &LR; , the newer sister to the original
North Beach Mario's, opened in 1972 by Trieste natives, Mario and
Lilliana Crismani. Son Paolo and daughter-in-law Debbie have been
running both locations since the early '80s, but Mario still comes
in occasionally to whip up a batch of his famed apple turnovers.
Lilliana's ricotta cheesecake is also a favorite. The Polk Street
location features live jazz Wednesday and Thursday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, you'll find Carol and Richard Martucci's
 &UR; Russian Hill Bookstore &LR; , with nearly 1,500 cookbooks. The
Martuccis' collection consists of recent editions, standard
classics, &LR;  and pre-1920 editions. The vintage volumes are a
particular hit among chefs, says Carol Martucci.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Andrew Rothstein Fine Foods &LR;  is a couple doors away. A former
private chef to Charles Schwab, Rothstein opened the store in 1997,
offering upscale entrees, side dishes and salads for take-out.
Dishes such as teriyaki flank steak, orange-glazed pork chops and
lemon-dill salmon with orzo salad are available by the pound or
sold by the meal.
</P>
<P>
   If you want something to drink with your take-out, head across
the street to  &UR; William Cross Wine Merchants &LR; . The array of wines
has a California focus but includes imports, as well. The store
also offers group wine tastings from 7-9 p.m. Wednesday-Saturday.
This week's tasting is David vs. Goliath _ boutique wines versus
the big boys.
</P>
<P>
   With the renowned  &UR; La Folie &LR;  and the new  &UR; La Boulange de Polk &LR; ,
this section of Polk Street may make you wonder if you've been
transported to France. La Boulange, with its outdoor tables,
authentic clafouti, Bordelais  &LR; canelles &LR;  and mini-quiches, is a
refreshing addition to the neighborhood. It's open 7 a.m.-7 p.m.
Wednesday-Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   If all this food has given you the urge to cook, make your last
stop  &UR; City Discounts &LR; . When Rita and Joe Paoli opened the place 15
years ago, they sold pots and pans from a single room. Over the
years, the minirestaurant-supply store has expanded to nearly five
rooms. The place is packed with kitchen utensils, gadgets,
appliances, baking equipment and glassware. There even are some
imported Italian foodstuffs like Genoa tuna packed in olive oil
(31/4-ounce tin, $1.35), dried porcini mushrooms (4-ounce bag,
$3.29) and Illy coffee (8.8 ounces, $8.49).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; POLK STREET &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The area code for the following businesses is (415).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STORES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Andrew Rothstein Fine Foods &LR; , 2238 Polk St. (near Green);
447-4094
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ City Discounts &LR; , 2436 Polk St. (near Union); 771-4649
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ The Jug Shop &LR; , 1567 Pacific Ave. (near Polk); 885-2922
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Leonard's 2001 &LR; , 2001 Polk St. (at Pacific); 921-2001
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Real Food Co. &LR; , 2140 Polk St. (between Broadway and Vallejo);
673-7420
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Russian Hill Bookstore &LR; , 2234 Polk St. (near Green); 929-0997
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ See's Candies &LR; , 1519 Polk St. (near California); 775-7049
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Wm. Cross Wine Merchants &LR; , 2253 Polk St. (near Green);
346-1314
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RESTAURANTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Acquerello &LR; , 1722 Sacramento St. (near Polk); 567-5432
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Cafe Aroma &LR; , 2032 Polk St. (near Pacific); 749-1478
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ La Boulange de Polk &LR; , 2310 Polk St. (near Green); 345-1107
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ La Folie &LR; , 2316 Polk St. (near Green); 776-5577
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Mario's Bohemian Cigar Store Cafe Ristorante &LR; , 2209 Polk St.
(near Vallejo); 776-8226
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Swan Oyster Depot &LR; , 1517 Polk St. (near California); 673-2757
</P>
