<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute Main
Dish takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast &AMP; Fresh
gives you dinner in about 20 minutes. 
 
 The Working Cook: Making the Most of Summer Produce  By Tara Duggan  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Head to the farmers' market or even the grocery
store during summer and it's easy to be seduced by the beautiful
array of tomatoes, squash, corn and peppers. Next thing you know,
you're carrying around 20 pounds of produce without a clue about
what to do with it all.
<P>
   When this happens, it never hurts to make a simple sauce and
then freeze it for later, when produce is not so abundant or at
least your refrigerator is not so full.
</P>
<P>
   The Summer Tomato &AMP; Eggplant Stew with Pasta &AMP; Toasted Pine Nuts
fits with this plan. Since this recipe serves 12, set aside some of
the stew to freeze and then prepare the pasta and toppings again
when you defrost it. Although freezing destroys some of the
vegetables' texture, it doesn't affect their wonderful fresh summer
flavor. There's only a little bit of extra liquid after defrosting,
and the pasta will help soak this up.
</P>
<P>
   Summer vegetables sometimes do need special treatment. The
tomatoes in this sauce, for example, must be peeled and seeded.
It's a little laborious, but you'll be glad you did it. The acidity
and liquid from the seeds can ruin the smoky, slow-roasted flavor
and firm texture of the eggplant.
</P>
<P>
   In the Black Pepper Beef &AMP; Cucumber Salad, this week's 30 Minute
Main Dish, I call for seeding and salting the cucumbers, which
removes some of their liquid. Not only does this help the dressing
adhere to the salad, it gives the cucumbers a crisp cool texture
that contrasts well with the savory beef.
</P>
<P>
   For this week's Fast &AMP; Fresh dish, Salmon with Spiced Green
Beans &AMP; Yogurt Sauce, steam the green beans and then shock them in
ice water to ensure a crisp texture. This method also gives you the
option of partially preparing the dish before everyone shows up for
dinner. If you blanch the beans and prepare the sauce ahead, it
will take only about five minutes to broil the salmon and saute the
beans with smoky cumin and mustard seeds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SALMON WITH SPICED GREEN BEANS &AMP; YOGURT SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   This recipe showcases both wild Pacific salmon and green beans,
which are in season now.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound green beans
</P>
<P>
   Handful cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plain nonfat yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 skinless salmon fillets (6 ounces each)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon yellow or black mustard seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler. Line a baking sheet with aluminum foil.
</P>
<P>
   Trim off the stem ends of the green beans. Prepare a large bowl
of ice water. Place the beans in a steamer and cook for 3 to 5
minutes, or until crisp-tender. Immediately plunge the beans into
the ice water. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Finely chop the cilantro (you should have about 2 tablespoons).
Mix with the yogurt and lemon juice and season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Season the salmon with salt and pepper. Place skin-side down on
the prepared baking sheet. Broil for about 5 minutes, or until the
salmon flakes but still is pink in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, drain the beans and shake off excess water.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a medium skillet over medium-low heat. Add the
mustard seeds, cumin and cayenne. Saute for about 5 minutes, or
until the mustard seeds just start to pop. Add the green beans and
cook, stirring, for 1 to 2 minutes, or until heated through. Season
with salt.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the salmon and beans among serving plates. Pass the sauce
at the table. There may be leftover sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING (without sauce): &LR;   &LR; 360 calories, &LR;   &LR; 36 g protein, 8
g &LR;   &LR; carbohydrate, 20 g fat (4 g saturated), 112 mg cholesterol, 86 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAUCE: PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 8 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 0 fat, 0 cholesterol, 11 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; 30-MINUTE MAIN DISH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BLACK PEPPER BEEF&AMP;CUCUMBER SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Seeding and salting the cucumbers improves their texture and
helps the dressing cling to the salad better.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups jasmine rice
</P>
<P>
   2 hothouse cucumbers
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt + salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oyster sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cracked black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds flank steak
</P>
<P>
   1-inch knob ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 red jalapeno or other fresh red chile pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black sesame seeds (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Begin cooking the rice according to package directions.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the cucumbers and cut in half lengthwise. To scrape out the
seeds, run a teaspoon down the seed cavity in each half. Cut the
cucumbers into thin half moons, then place in a bowl and sprinkle
with the 1 tablespoon salt; toss to combine. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the soy sauce, oyster sauce and peppercorns in a shallow
bowl. Place the meat in the soy-sauce mixture, turning to coat both
sides. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Peel and finely mince the ginger. Cut the jalapeno into quarters
lengthwise, discard seeds, then cut into strips and mince.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the ginger, jalapeno, vinegar and sesame oil. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large skillet over high heat. Remove the meat
from the marinade and place in the pan. Cook for about 5 minutes
per side, or until medium-rare. Transfer to a plate and tent with
foil; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Put the cucumbers in a colander and rinse well, then shake to
rid of excess water. Pat dry with paper towels. Combine the
cucumbers and the vinegar-oil mixture in a serving bowl and toss to
combine.
</P>
<P>
   Portion the rice onto heated serving plates; sprinkle with black
sesame seeds. Slice the meat and divide among plates. Pass the
cucumbers salad at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 600 calories, &LR;   &LR; 40 g protein, 59 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 22 g fat (8 g saturated), 84 mg cholesterol, 136 mg
sodium, 4 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; The calories and other nutrients absorbed from marinades vary &LR; 
 &LR; and are difficult to estimate. Variables include the type of &LR; 
 &LR; food, marinating time and amount of surface area. Therefore, &LR;   &LR; the
marinade is not included in this analysis. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER TOMATO &AMP; EGGPLANT STEW WITH PASTA &AMP; TOASTED PINE NUTS
</P>
<P>
   The stew may be frozen for later and then defrosted overnight in
the fridge. Prepare the pasta and toppings just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Stew
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil, plus olive oil to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 large globe eggplants, about 4 pounds, trimmed and cut into
1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   6 large ripe summer tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 large onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   10 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: (amounts are for full recipe)
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds penne or other short pasta
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces mild feta cheese, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1/4 bunch Italian parsley, minced
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the stew: &LR;  Preheat the oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Coat 2 large baking sheets with 4 tablespoons of the oil. Divide
the eggplant cubes between baking sheets, spreading them out in a
single layer. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Roast for about 15 minutes, or until the cubes begin to brown.
Using a spatula, stir the cubes, scraping the browned bits from the
pan. Return to the oven and roast for 10 minutes. Stir again, and
roast for 10 to 20 minutes longer, or until the eggplant is just
tender. Remove from the oven, scrape the pan again; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, bring a large pot of water to a boil over high heat.
Prepare large bowl of ice water.
</P>
<P>
   Using a paring knife, cut out the core of each tomato and score
the other end with a shallow ``X.'' Drop 1 or 2 tomatoes at a time
into the boiling water. Don't add too many; the water should remain
at a boil. Boil the tomatoes for 15 to 30 seconds, then remove with
a slotted spoon and plunge into the ice water to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the tomatoes. Cut them in half widthwise and gently squeeze
out the seeds. Cut the flesh into large dice.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining 2 tablespoons oil in large Dutch oven. Add
the onions and saute for 15 minutes, or until golden. Add the
garlic and saute for 5 minutes. Add the eggplant and cook,
stirring, until heated through. Add the tomatoes and cook for 2 to
3 minutes, or until just slightly softened. Season with salt and
pepper and a drizzle of olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble:  &LR; Preheat the broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil over high heat. Add
the pasta and cook according to package directions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, put the pine nuts in a small heavy skillet over
medium heat and saute, tossing occasionally, for about 10 minutes,
or until browned.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the pasta and combine it with the stew. Divide between two
9 x 13-inch baking dishes. Top with pine nuts and feta. Broil for
about 5 minutes, or until browned and bubbly. Sprinkle with
parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 395 calories, &LR;   &LR; 13 g protein, 59 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 13 g fat (3 g saturated), 13 mg cholesterol, 172 mg
sodium, 6 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
