<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 Wine Potpourri: Pet Provides Solace in a Cabernet-Free Zone   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Not long ago a ground swell movement began to gain
momentum, suggesting alternative wine choices to Chardonnay and
Cabernet Sauvignon. Someone tagged the mini-trend ``Learning Your
ABCs'` and suggestions began popping up for alternative wines from
Albarino to Viognier.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The smuggest of the anti-Chardonnay crowd defined ABC as
``Anything but Chardonnay (or Cabernet).'' Others, with less of a
problem about the dominance in the marketplace of Chardonnay and
Cabernet, took the more diplomatic road with ``Alternatives Beyond
Chardonnay.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how the term was defined, though, wine-industry types
were convinced that consumers wanted new tastes, new wines _
especially ones that would complement the highly flavored foods so
much in demand. Wineries began to look at ``new'' grapes like
Syrah, Sangiovese and Viognier. Most of these choices already had
firm reputations in France, Italy and other known wine regions, but
they were unknown to many American wine drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   As the list of alternative wines continued to mount, stalwart
varieties such as Petite Sirah (Petite Syrah in France), were all
but forgotten. Grown in California since the 1880s, Pet, as it's
affectionately known, was an important component in many red wines,
including California Burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, with the renaissance of Rhone-style wines, a
small group of California wineries began talking up Petite Sirah.
Dennis Fife, proprietor of Fife Vineyards in St. Helena, unhappy
with what he sees as ``confusing and/or misleading information
about (Petite Sirah),'' recently presented a paper on the varietal
at the Hospice du Rhone seminar.
</P>
<P>
   Fife and his fellow Pet producers want wine drinkers to know
that with all of the interest in Syrah and other Rhone varieties,
Petite Sirah has an important place as a varietal wine and as a
blending component in Rhone-style wines.
</P>
<P>
   According to Fife, the true origin of Petite Sirah was bandied
around for years with some experts, including viticulture
professors at the University of California at Davis, claiming that
Petite Sirah was one or a combination of French grapes, including
Syrah, Durifcq &LR;  and Peloursincq &LR; . Then, in the 1990s, UC Davis
professor Carole Meredith determined, using DNA, that the Petite
Sirah grown in California is related to Syrah and that ``Durif is
Peloursin fertilized by Syrah and thus shares the characteristics
of both varieties.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all still as cloudy as unfiltered wine, but what Fife wants
consumers to think about is that Syrah and Petite Sirah are very
close in flavor and texture, and even wine experts sometimes are
fooled. Using current winemaking techniques, winemakers are making
Petite Sirahs with reduced tannins and little bitterness. Rich in
fresh-berry flavors, Petite Sirah is a substantial red wine of
great character and length, the ideal accompaniment to meals
centered around red meats, stews and roasts.
</P>
<P>
   The well-matched flavors of Syrah and Petite Sirah come through
nicely in Fife Vineyards Max Cuvee, made from estate vineyards in
the Napa Valley. Among other good Petite Sirah choices are
Foppiano, Concannon, Louis M. Martini, Bogle Vineyard, Christopher
Creek Winery, Ridge Vineyard and Stags' Leap Winery.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; It's Beauzeaux, Bozo! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Beaulieu Vineyard director of winemaking, Joel Aiken,
conceived of an unorthodox blend of red varieties, based on
Zinfandel, that he named Beauzeaux (pronounced Bozo).
</P>
<P>
   Today, Beauzeaux is no joke. The contemporary blend from vintage
1998 starts with Zinfandel, then adds Primitivo (an Italian variety
similar to Zinfandel), Valdigue, Charbonocq &LR; , Grenache and _ Petite
Sirah. Beauzeaux is aged in oak, and at $20, is a great choice for
summer barbecues, especially if finger-lickin' ribs are on the
menu.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; German-Inspired Washington Riesling &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ernst Loosen, a leading winemaker from Germany's Middle Mosel
region, has teamed up with Washington's Chateau Ste. Michelle to
produce a Riesling called Eroica. Loosen worked with Ste.
Michelle's vineyard manager, then he and his winemaker teamed up
with Ste. Michelle white-winemaker, Erik Olsen, to produce a Eroica
Riesling from the Cold Creek Vineyard in the Columbia Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Lovers of steely, refreshing Mosel Rieslings will want to try
this unique joint-venture wine. Eroica, named with the Beethoven
symphony in mind, is priced at $20 and is widely available wherever
fine wines are sold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1521EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
