<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods. 
 
 Best Way: Cooking Corn on the Cob   By Amber Thompson 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; The last time I sped past a roadside corn stand, I
immediately slowed down and made the first U-turn I could. I picked
out a dozen fresh ears and raced home to indulge in a summer
classic _ corn on the cob.
<P>
   But what's the best way to cook it? Boiling is basic, but many
people swear that steaming or microwaving yields the best results.
</P>
<P>
   To find which method is best, we cooked fresh corn 10 ways.
Sacrificing the traditional accompaniments of butter and salt, we
ate our corn plain, searching for the truest corn taste and best
texture.
</P>
<P>
   We boiled, steamed and microwaved the ears, with and without the
husks, in plain water and in salted and sugared water.
</P>
<P>
   To boil the corn, we brought six pots of water to a rapid boil,
fully immersed the ears, covered the pots and cooked the corn for
three minutes. We boiled shucked and unshucked ears in plain water,
salted water and sugared water. The ratio of salt and sugar to
water was one tablespoon per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Food Department staffers liked the shucked ears boiled in salted
water the most. The corn had a lively crunch and true flavor.
However, because salt toughens the kernels of older cobs, adding
salt works only when the corn is very fresh.
</P>
<P>
   The corn boiled in sugared water drew mixed reviews. Two staff
members thought it enhanced the natural corn flavor, but others
felt it added an impurity that lessened the authentic corn taste.
</P>
<P>
   Most staffers did not like the corn boiled in the husk; it
tasted slightly raw and had a starchy texture. But, a few staff
members said that the husk protected the true corn taste.
</P>
<P>
   Shucked steamed corn was the department's overall favorite. When
the corn was done, its bright yellow color testified to the crisp,
sweet kernels. Steaming corn is also the quickest cooking method _
an inch of water boils faster than a full pot.
</P>
<P>
   Although steaming the corn in its husk also had its fans, it was
harder to prepare. Steaming greatly intensifies the heat of the
husk, and it is easy to burn yourself trying to remove it.
</P>
<P>
   Microwaving was the clear-cut loser. We microwaved corn in its
husk and also in plastic wrap for three minutes per ear. Once
removed, we let the corn rest for five minutes. Both tests produced
flabby ears of wrinkly corn kernels that lacked any true character.
</P>
<P>
   Once Food staffers decided they liked the steamed, shucked corn
the best, they began the classic epicurean debate. Should you eat
your corn in rows or around in circles? Divided on this question,
we abandoned the argument and went searching for floss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Remove the husks and silks from the ears of corn. Fill a large,
wide-mouth pot with one inch of cold water. Place the pot over high
heat and bring the water to a rapid boil. Lay the ears of corn in
the boiling water, stacking them on top of each other, if
necessary. Cover with a tight-fitting lid and steam over high heat
for seven minutes. Remove the corn from the pot and serve. Smear
with butter and sprinkle with salt, if you like.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1522EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0148 </DOCNO>
