 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 Taster's Choice: Knudsen Cottage Cheese Creams the Competition   By Robin Davis  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Some people equate cottage cheese with diet
plates, but others love the creamy freshness. Today's panel tasted
eight low-fat cottage cheeses and were surprised by the
differences.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The panel agreed that personal preference plays a large part in
what they liked. Some preferred cheese with a tangier flavor, while
others opted for a mild, milky taste. They also felt that what the
cheese would be used for was important in deciding which brand they
would choose.
</P>
<P>
   All of the cheeses were labeled low-fat, although the milk-fat
content varied from one to two percent. That means that a half-cup
serving has between one and 21/2 grams of fat.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming favorite was  &UR; Knudsen &LR;  (16 ounces, $2.49 at
many markets). Panelists liked the slightly tangy flavor and the
size of the curds. One panelist thought it would be particularly
good for using in dishes like cheesecake or as a topping for baked
potatoes. All would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Berkeley &LR;   &UR; Farms &LR;  (16 ounces, $2.09 at
Andronico's). Some panelists objected to the homogenous texture,
but most liked the creamy mouthfeel and tangy, fresh flavor. One
dissenter thought the curds were too dry and tough. Two would buy
it, one might buy it and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of TASTE 8- (71777 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &UR; Trader Joe's &LR;  (16 ounces, $1.49 at Trader Joe's) came in third.
One panelist described it as a ``classic'' cottage cheese, although
others thought it was bland. One would buy it; three might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth place went to  &UR; Lucerne &LR;  (16 ounces, $1.99 at Safeway).
Most panelists thought the curds were too large, lumpy and dry, but
two liked the milky flavor. Two would buy it, one might buy it and
one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nancy's Organic &LR;  (16 ounces, $2.39-$2.89 at many supermarkets)
was fifth. Two panelists thought it was too tart, but the others
thought it would work well combined with other ingredients. One
panelist &LR;  suggested adding herbs and spreading it on toasted
baguette slices.  &LR; One would buy it, one might buy it and two would
not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Sunny-side, Clover Stornetta and Nancy's
(not organic), but they ranked too low.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were Meryl Bennan, food writer and consultant; John P.
Carroll, cookbook author; Shelley Handler, food writer and
consultant; and Roland Passot, chef-owner of La Folie in San
Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur and Menlo Park. A perfect score
for any product would be 100. Because there were only four tasters
for this test, each panelist could score a product as high as 25
points. All products are tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
