<SLUG> BC-SECRET-TOMS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 Secrets Of Success: At Bistro Viola, Vegetables Are Stars  By Michael Bauer  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; I'm always pleasantly surprised when a restaurant
goes the extra mile and tries to do something special with
vegetables. Sure, lots of people are vegetarians or want to eat
lighter, but too many places think no further than grilled
vegetables or pasta primavera.
<P>
   At Bistro Viola in Berkeley, however, the vegetables can be the
stars, either on their own or as a side dish. One of my favorite
combinations created by Bistro Viola's former chef Mark Zeitouni is
the stuffed tomato, filled with haricots verts, potatoes and fresh
corn. The ingredients are cooked separately and then warmed in a
ripe tomato shell, under a creamy blanket of goat cheese.
</P>
<P>
   The stuffed tomato can stand alone as a simple vegetable main
course when served on a bed of frisee, or it can accompany roast
chicken as it does in the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Bistro Viola, which opened in 1999, has a cozy neighborhood feel
with polished birch plywood floors, an open kitchen and a sleek
stainless-steel bar that dresses up the 40-seat dining room.
There's also a 35-seat patio, one of the few places for outside
dining in Berkeley. The area is covered and, with the addition of
space heaters, it's possible to eat al fresco much of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Bistro Viola, 1428 San Pablo Ave. (at Page Street), Berkeley. &LR; 
 &LR; (510) 528-5030. Dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Individual cooking. &LR;  Cooking the vegetables separately and
then warming them in the tomato keeps them tasting fresh.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ The goat cheese. &LR;  Just a small amount helps to turn a
vegetable into a star, either as a side dish or a main course.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; STUFFED TOMATOES WITH GOAT CHEESE CRUST
</P>
<P>
   This simple mixture is seasoned only with salt and pepper.
However, don't be afraid to use fresh herbs such as tarragon, thyme
or parsley in the blend.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 large tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound haricots verts, or other thin young green beans
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   Kernels from 1 ear of fresh corn
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 fingerling potato, roasted or boiled and diced
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces fresh goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 head frisee
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 500 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Core the tomatoes and scoop out the inside of each, leaving the
walls about 1/2-inch-thick. Rub about 1 tablespoon of the oil over
the skin and around the inside of each tomato, then season
generously with salt and pepper inside and out.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the haricots verts in a large pot of boiling salted water
for about 4 minutes, or until just tender. Drain and rinse in cold
water. Cut into 1-inch lengths and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a medium saute pan over medium-high heat. Add
the green beans, corn and water and cook for 2 minutes. Add the
diced potato and cook for about 1 minute longer, or until the
liquid evaporates. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the tomatoes in an ovenproof pan or on a baking sheet.
Spoon the hot vegetables into the tomatoes. Top with the goat
cheese, pressing it gently into the vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for about 6 minutes, or until the tomatoes are hot.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, toss the frisee in a large bowl with the remaining 1
tablespoon oil. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the lettuce among serving plates, then top each with a
stuffed tomato.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 220 calories, &LR;   &LR; 8 g protein, 14 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 16 g fat (7 g saturated), 21 mg cholesterol, 151 mg sodium, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1523EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
