<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9518 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SOURCE-GOAT-SFCHRON &LR;      08-01 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-GOAT-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders. 
 
 At the Source: Nannies Know Best at Skyhill Farms  
 A herd of 700 goats do the work to make creamy goat-milk yogurt 
 and mild, rich cheeses  By Karola Saekel  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; NAPA, Calif. _  &LR; In political debates and labor negotiations,
hot-button topics always include maternity leave and retirement
benefits. But employees of Skyhill Napa Valley Farms, Inc., high
above the valley floor, don't have a problem with these issues.
They get a two-month leave every time they have a kid, and they are
well provided for when their working days come to an end.
<P>
   The employees in question, some 700 strong, are, however,
segregated by gender much of the time. They are goats, and if the
randy males are allowed anywhere near milking females, even if they
don't as much as brush coats with each other, the milk will take on
the males' overpowering scent _ what most humans would call a
stench.
</P>
<P>
   Skyhill started as an organic farm in the late 1980s. As a
hobby, co-owner/operator Amy Wend acquired three Nubian goats,
Emily, Natalie and Rose. Emily, Wend recalls fondly, had the finest
Nubian markings on her long, aristocratic face. So when Wend, with
partner Ted Connolly, started to sell her first goat cheese at
farmers' markets in 1993, Emily's face went on the label. Many
generations of goats later, Emily was still the poster girl for the
farm's products, including its outstanding yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   Skyhill's Nubian and Alpine LaMancha goats now produce enough
milk for an average of 700 gallons of yogurt a week, along with
about 3,000 pounds of handmade cheese: many kinds of chevre, fetas,
Rigoatta (a cousin to ricotta) and, the latest introductions, aged
jack and creamy fontina. Like the cheeses, the yogurt surprises
first-time buyers with its mild, rich flavor. The strong taste many
people expect from goat milk products just isn't there, thanks to
Wend's careful monitoring of her herd.
</P>
<P>
   Wend has great fondness for both her goats and their milk. Goat
milk, she asserts, has tiny fat globules and most closely resembles
human mothers' milk. Most people with lactose intolerance, she
says, can eat goat yogurt with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   Wend feels that goats deserve the good life they lead in
Skyhill's pastures since, she says, ``they are smart, and they have
an admirable social order.'' When they go to the milking shed twice
a day, they line up and take the same station every time _ no
shoving, pushing or trying to break away. (The fact that a little
granola treat awaits at the station may help just a bit.)
</P>
<P>
   When matriarch Emily got too old to reproduce or be milked, she
became something of a den mother, staying close to young females
giving birth and helping mind the kids. The other goats, Wend says,
always let old Emily get at food first, as though they respected
her senior status.
</P>
<P>
   During pregnancy and for their two-month maternity leave after
birth, the young mothers have separate pastures on the roughly
30-acre property.
</P>
<P>
   Wend is now the head honcho of Skyhill, though founding partner
Connolly, an all-pro guard with the 49ers from 1954 to 1963 and
later a major developer of shopping centers and other commercial
properties, still keeps a hand in. ``Ted does a little PR for us,''
she says, and right now he is helping her secure a different site
after the current lease expires. It will still be in Napa, but Wend
hopes to expand. Her dream farm would allow room for making blue
cheese, which needs a separate facility so the bacteria involved in
making it does not destroy the yogurt culture. Otherwise, she says,
``We'd end up with liquid yogurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Wend would also like to add a viewing area and retail shop,
which the current remote mountain location doesn't allow.
</P>
<P>
   She has no plans to raise kids for meat consumption. When people
call asking about buying a kid goat for a barbecue, they are told
Skyhill is not a meat farm. Wend does send surplus kids and
under-producing milk goats to auction, but she hopes that they find
homes on other farms, as pets or for 4-H projects.
</P>
<P>
   Some day, she would like to set up a system that would allow her
to monitor where these animals go. There is no question where the
goats who have passed beyond their useful milking time of about
eight years go. They retire to a Santa Rosa farm where they can
follow their proverbial taste for anything green by making a living
grazing for weed control.
</P>
<P>
   At Skyhill, it appears, it's not such a bad thing to be an old
goat.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Skyhill Napa Valley Farms is not open to the public. The &LR; 
 &LR; phone number is (707) 255-4800. Skyhill natural goat milk &LR; 
 &LR; yogurt, plain or flavored, is sold in quart containers at &LR;   &LR; Trader
Joe's. The farm's goat cheeses are available at most &LR;   &LR; upscale Bay
Area groceries and natural food stores but not in &LR;   &LR; supermarket
chains. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
