<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9525 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-MEXICOCOUNTRYSIDE-HNS     08-01 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO </SLUG>
 COUNTRYSIDE-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; REJECTED RULING PARTY FACES SEVERE TESTS IN MEXICAN
COUNTRYSIDE. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By DUDLEY ALTHAUS &QL; 
c. Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   MEDELLIN DE BRAVO, Mexico _ Hunched on a footstool in front of
his empty one-room store in this wilted community, Miguel Angel
Torres surveys the deserted main street and explains why Mexican
politics have changed forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past nine years, they've been promising pavement,
drainage and such,'' Torres, 36, says as he watches a few shoppers
shuffling home with loads of groceries down the street, which has
been closed off for 13 months. ``They haven't done anything.
Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'' are local and state officials who for seven decades
have been from the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, which
lost Mexico's presidency in historic elections July 2 to Vicente
Fox of the center-right National Action Party, or PAN.
</P>
<P>
   And ``they'' now confront local balloting Sept. 3, which many
here say promises to extend the PRI's stunning decline to towns and
villages across the Gulf Coast state of Veracruz, once considered
the party's impregnable heartland.
</P>
<P>
   While its national bosses wrangle over the PRI's future and
their role in it, the party's fate is playing out in backwaters
like Medellin de Bravo, a township of 30,000 people about 15 miles
outside the port city of Veracruz. And from all indications, the
party's future seems even less promising than its present.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the PRI's strategic reserve,'' Torres says of the
party's hold on Veracruz state politics for most of the past 70
years. ``Not anymore. If the PRI doesn't fulfill what it promises,
it's going to disappear from here as well.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mexico's next nationwide elections three years off, the PRI
enters a long season on the fringe in which most politics will be
decidedly local.
</P>
<P>
   Between now and Oct. 20, the PRI confronts crucial elections in
three states across Mexico's impoverished south, a region
considered by many to be the last redoubt of the ruling party's
once-formidable political machinery. But even here, the discipline
and arm-twisting that kept the party together and in power has
unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   In the south, PRI militants have been revisiting old feuds and
scrapping for what remains of the party's power.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate of a united opposition is favored to win the
governorship in southernmost Chiapas state. And in recent weeks,
fierce squabbling has broken out among local PRI politicos for
candidacies in Veracruz's municipal and state congressional
elections. As many as 13 people competed for the party's mayoral
nomination in some towns, because the PRI's state bosses proved
unable to impose their will.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the PRI is that everyone wants to be a
general; no one wants to be a soldier,'' complains Aquiles
Rodriguez, 35, a wealthy cattleman and University of Houston
graduate who is the outgoing PRI mayor of Medellin de Bravo. ``The
same people who have lived off the party don't want it to progress
because you take away their means for making a living.''
</P>
<P>
   The infighting in Medellin de Bravo was as fierce as anywhere,
with the daughter of a former PRI mayor leading a successful
rebellion against the candidate Rodriguez had tried to impose. The
woman, Norma Jacome, won the candidacy with the backing of the PRI
state president, an old friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that the PRI is a bad system but that the selection
of candidates has gone wrong,'' Jacome says. ``People are just
looking for power. But they must have ideals, conviction, values.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't political control,'' she says of the PRI's
internal conflicts. ``There is a lot of resentment. We don't have
the political maturity to work all this out.''
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, Jacome says, she now faces a tough race in a town
where most everyone is more than a little irritated with the
current mayor, with her father and with the PRI in general.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's hold on Mexican politics was fatally eroding even
before Fox's victory. The PAN and other opposition parties govern
55 percent of Mexicans at the state and local levels. For the past
three years, opposition parties have controlled 103 of Veracruz
state's 210 townships.
</P>
<P>
   The main street of El Tejar, Medellin de Bravo's shopping
district, has been closed off for more than a year now. After
contractors sent by the PRI-controlled state government tore up the
pavement to lay new sewer lines, funding evaporated and work
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The street remained closed for five months until new money was
found and a new contractor hired. Although Mayor Rodriguez promises
that the street will be open by Election Day, work continues at a
turtle's crawl.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, heavy buses, cargo trucks and family vehicles
detour through the village's residential backstreets, which have
never been paved.
</P>
<P>
   Chasms the size of swimming pools have been worn into the
once-smooth and bucolic lanes. Seasonal tropical downpours have
filled the pools with muddy water, making a drive across the
village seem like a back-country challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I go ask people for their vote with the streets like
this?'' Jacome asks. ``You have to work for people. If we don't
change, it's the party that is going to suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people in Medellin de Bravo would agree. Many work in
nearby Veracruz and Boca del Rio, increasingly prosperous cities
that have been governed by Fox's PAN for the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   The improvement has perhaps been most noticeable in Boca del
Rio, a shabby suburb of Veracruz until just a few years ago. Now it
sports a large mall with some of Mexico's best retailers and a
multiscreen theater as well as a hotel strip along the beach and
new streets and highways.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the townships where the PAN is and the quality of life
is better than where the PRI governs,'' says Cristobal Soto, 50,
another idle merchant on El Tejar's main street. ``The need for
changing parties is obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Others in town remain loyal to a former peasant leader who
defected from the PRI to the leftist Workers Party three years ago
when PRI state leaders selected Rodriguez for Medellin de Bravo's
mayor over him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are destroying the official party by putting in their
pals, their accomplices,'' says Julio Martinez, the 55-year-old
former PRI peasant boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are in the PRI just for themselves. That's why the
party is disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
