<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-MURRAY-CONSERV02-     08-01 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MURRAY-CONSERV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delegates attempt to define their version of a `compassionate
conservative`
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ ``Compassionate conservative'' _ Is it nature or
is it nurture?
</P>
<P>
   A lot depends on the way you were raised, say members of the
Texas Delegation polled for their definition of Gov. George W.
Bush's campaign catchphrase.
</P>
<P>
   Nurture? Well, yes, to a certain extent _ but with limits.
Indeed, ``but'' was a key word in most responses.
</P>
<P>
   Here are excerpts from interviews conducted at random.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``To help people to take care of themselves,'' said Carole
Ragland of League City. ``To be compassionate but not to make
people slaves to welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Mother raised me to be compassionate,'' said Jan Kennady of
New Braunsfels, president of the 2,500-member Texas Federation of
Republican Women. ``But she also liked people to be willing to help
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Charlie O'Reilly, 68, of Plano, owner of McDonald's
restaurants, understandably believes ``it's wrong to let people go
hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Conservatives can be very compassionate and very liberal in
some respects. I shouldn't use the word 'liberal,' but at least
have a sense of empathy toward other people.''
</P>
<P>
   _ For Bill Keating, 43, of Arlington, a Texas A&AMP;M graduate and
former Marine fighter pilot now flying for American Airlines, said
it involves caring about the ``whole person.'' ``Not just whether
they have a minimum wage job, but how's their life going and are
they doing OK. You can't throw money at that kind of problem.''
</P>
<P>
   _ For William Russell, 64, of Dallas, whose business is
investment and ranching, ``Ours really is the compassionate
party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in providing the best opportunity for everybody,
regardless of color or national origin.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell, who grew up on a Texas Panhandle ranch, said he was
raised ``to be self-sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something you learn from a video game.''
</P>
<P>
   _ William Fairbrother, 34, of Round Rock, a computer programmer,
said compassionate conservatives ``will help you but there has to
be an end-game to getting you out of government welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized ``faith-based initiatives, putting time limits on
welfare, going from welfare to workfare, holding down a job.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sue Evenwel of Mount Pleasant, a housewife whose husband is an
executive with a chicken-processing company, said compassion
``describes the heart of a conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have compassion for the poor and downtrodden, but we're
more interested in teaching them the skills to get ahead, not just
shoving programs to keep them where they are.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Roger O'Dell, 46, a utilities consultant from El Paso, said
his party realizes ``there are times when people have to be on
welfare, but not forever. Teach them how they can provide for their
families, start paying taxes and help pull the wagon for someone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Betty Anderson of Spring, a housewife and volunteer whose
husband is a pastor, had this advice for the poor:
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust in the Lord with all your heart and lean on Him and He
will direct your path. When you are really in need, a relationship
with God is something amazing to fall back on.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sue Hershey, an Amarillo homemaker whose husband is a grain
broker, put it simply:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's free enterprise, the opportunity to either succeed or
fail without interference from the government.''
</P>
<P>
   The button Hershey was wearing made a compassionate conservative
statement of its own: ``If it's not a baby, you're not pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; Website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Cl
</P>
