<HEADER>
A9536 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-CVN-MURRAY-CHARACTER0     08-01 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MURRAY-CHARACTER02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delegate says character is still the issue
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ For Bob Flournoy, 59, a delegate from Lufkin,
Texas, the Republican Party's ``determination to restore integrity,
truthfulness and decency to the presidency overshadows all the
other issues,'' including abortion rights and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally,'' he said, ``I don't think there's a more
important issue than the issue of life, but those of us who
disagree aren't being combative or angry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the GOP's desire for inclusiveness, said Flournoy, a
lawyer and lay preacher active in local and state GOP politics
since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge, but I believe it's in our heart to be
inclusive, to have more women and more minorities involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Flournoy contends that the Republican Party ``stands for what
the majority of minorities believe in ... faith, family, peace,
security and strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we haven't always done a good job of communicating what we
believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   He also concedes that ``many times we have been too quick to
criticize people for not standing for the same things we stand
for.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he added, ``It's like they say, 'If you don't stand for
something, you'll fall for anything.'''
</P>
<P>
   Flournoy says he doesn't want to see his party ``give up all our
standards and try to be all things to all people. I certainly hope
the GOP isn't going there.''
</P>
<P>
   For him, there's no problem in where to draw the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do it by drawing on the Bible,'' he said. ``That's the
standard that the Lord has set for us _ unity, caring, help and
hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all found in the very basic character of the Lord, in
love. Loving people covers a multitude of other shortcomings.''
</P>
<P>
   It's those characteristics that Flournoy said he finds in George
W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have worked with him for years, and I really believe that it
(love) is the motivation of George Bush's heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush's wife, Laura, and his parents, President and Mrs.
Bush, are all ``good honest folk,'' Flournoy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are consistent in what they stand for,'' he said. ``Their
moral code of ethics is what I want to see in my family and my
community. They're great.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Flournoy's first national convention, and he says he
``picked a good one to come to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are in the cradle of American history at one of the
most critical times in our nation's history,'' he said, ``and we
have a long way to go to restore the moral fiber of our country's
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; Website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
