<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9545 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-LIMPBIZKIT-REVI     08-01 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LIMPBIZKIT-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
`LIMP BIZKIT ROCKS THE NAPSTER DEBATE'(PHOTO) &HT;    By MICHAEL D. CLARK
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ This wasn't the biggest performance of Limp Bizkit's
career. It wasn't the longest and probably not even the loudest.
But for the 2,500 fans Monday night, it was the best for one simple
reason.
</P>
<P>
   It was free.
</P>
<P>
   Many Limp Bizkit fans spent their Sunday waiting, sleeping and
camping in line for the Monday morning distribution of entry
wristbands to the concerts Monday and Tuesday night. The shows were
underwritten by Napster, the online music download site temporarily
saved from shutdown by federal judges last week.
</P>
<P>
   (Other Napster-sponsored shows are scheduled for Aug. 2 in
Dallas, Aug. 4 in Denver, Aug. 6 in Salt Lake City, Aug. 8 in San
Francisco, Aug. 11 in San Diego and Aug. 12 in Los Angeles)
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of Napster's ultimate fate, Limp Bizkit stands to be
a winner for years to come. Its advocacy of Napster has moved the
band into national debates about e-commerce, the political and
legal ramifications of online music, and the future of music
distribution. And the band's free shows have made loyalists of a
nation of kids unable to afford the high cost of concert tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The hot and humid wait for wristbands sent at least 10 people to
the hospital to be treated for dehydration and heat exposure.
Shortly before showtime, the Houston Police Department reported
that seven arrests were made for public intoxication, indecent
exposure and theft.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday evening the fans had revived, returned and were ready
to thank the metal rappers for their generosity by tearing
themselves apart. The mosh pit was already in full force for stereo
music piped in before Limp Bizkit came on.
</P>
<P>
   Signs around the theater asked all to refrain from public
indecency, public exposure and violent or nonconsensual contact.
This crowd did everything it could to flagrantly break those rules.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 12-song, 80-minute set, guys slammed into each
other like football linemen and women lifted their shirts to catch
Bizkit frontman Fred Durst's attention.
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting that Limp Bizkit dressed its stage with a prison
yard-style chain-link fence, which separated the band from the
audience. As bodies surfed across the crowd and into the metal
barrier, the group thrashed like inmates behind it. It looked like
a steel cage wrestling match could break out at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   Durst stalked the stage dressed in black denim and a red
baseball cap flipped backward. His rhyme style can lapse into a
pleading whine reminiscent of Shaggy from ``Scooby Doo,'' but it
works best when he puffs out his chest and gets his throat dirty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just Like This'' had the entire room pogoing. ``Break Stuff''
was playful but turned the crowd fierce enough to jog memories of
the mayhem at Woodstock '99.
</P>
<P>
   The set rolled to a brief pop-rock pause while Durst sang a
cover of George Michael's ``Faith.'' A rendition of House of Pain's
early '90s East Coast rap jam ``Jump Around'' worked much better,
backed by the urban rave crash of guitarist Wes Borland and bassist
Sam Rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Highlighting the set was a breakdance beat approach to
``Counterfeit'' from Bizkit's first album, ``Three Dollar Bill
Y'All''. Overlaid with old-school vinyl scratches, a jeep-jumpin'
bass loop and guest shouts from Cypress Hill's Sen-Dog, the song
was a model for what once made smash-nose hard-core rap appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Limp Bizkit's contribution to this summer's ``Mission:
Impossible-2'' soundtrack, ``Take a Look Around,'' also transfers
well to the stage. Borland's dexterity mixing the original
``Mission Impossible'' theme into the track, combined with Durst's
solid blend of singing and shouting, made for a balanced output of
melody and lyrical content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a Look Around'' has to excite the Limp Bizkit fans
waiting for the band to come out with a new album. That won't
happen until its last release, ``Significant Other,'' leaves the
charts (57 weeks, 6 million copies sold and counting). With the
Napster-sponsored momentum Limp Bizkit has created, don't look for
that to happen anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
