r d BC-FOODCALENDAR-AUGUST08     08-01 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODCALENDAR-AUGUST0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As calendar turns, a day-by-day food fest for August
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - August is like a beauty who knows the clock is
ticking relentlessly. With tender youth past, she puts a touch of
color on her face and strides out, head high, flaunting her charms.
And she's got a lot to show off. Right now, but not for long.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who get to enjoy this sensual, passing show,
August is the most excessive part of summer. Think of the month,
like the lady, as dead ripe.
</P>
<P>
   Local farmers, blessed with the best growing season in years,
have bounteous crops of corn and tomatoes, zucchini and beans,
peaches and berries, including a second harvest of raspberries on
the horizon. And there's more to come, the melons and plums and red
bells by the bushels full.
</P>
<P>
   There's enough to fill each page of the calendar until September
signals that the extravagance of summer is fading.
</P>
<P>
   Today (Aug. 2) Buy local peaches at market. Let ripen fully and
make quick freezer jam. Have a package of Sure-Jell and sugar on
hand. The instructions are in the package.
</P>
<P>
   3. Layer slices of tomatoes, fresh mozzarella, and torn basil on
a platter. Drizzle with vinegar and olive oil, sprinkle with salt
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   4. Turn leftover corn on the cob into corn salsa with chopped
tomatoes, onion, garlic, minced jalapenos, cilantro, fresh lime,
and salt and pepper. Serve with grilled chicken or pork.
</P>
<P>
   5. Make pesto before the flavor of the basil plants get too
strong. Freeze some for later.
</P>
<P>
   6. Make a big batch a ratatouille with August tomatoes, bell
peppers, eggplant, zucchini, garlic and lots of fresh herbs.
</P>
<P>
   7. Make a quick vegetable soup with green beans and shell beans,
summer squash and tomatoes. Add a little pasta. Top the soup with
leftover basil pesto.
</P>
<P>
   8. Make old-fashioned succotash with lima beans or green beans
and corn off the cob.
</P>
<P>
   9. Vary the salad lineup with cucumber salad made with sour
cream thinned with olive oil. Add minced garlic.
</P>
<P>
   10. Make a modern variation on stuffed peppers by filling
roasted red bell peppers with smoked cheese. Bake them in light
tomato sauce .
</P>
<P>
   11. While chicken or pork chops are cooking, fix separate
skewers of vegetables on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   12: Take a few minutes to make tarragon or opal basil vinegar.
Stuff a quart jar half full of fresh herbs, bruising with your
fingers. Fill with rice wine vinegar, and let steep on a sunny
windowsill for 2 to 3 weeks. Bottle with fresh sprigs of herbs.
</P>
<P>
   13. Turn all those tomatoes and cucumbers into a cooling
gazpacho.
</P>
<P>
   14. Make an old-fashioned peach cobbler or crisp.
</P>
<P>
   15. Grilling zucchini is the best thing you can do to that
vegetable. Slice 6-inch squash in half lengthwise and salt it to
draw off juices. After a half hour, brush with oil and grill until
it is tender and the cut surfaces are brown.
</P>
<P>
   16. Try something different from the farm market, maybe orange
or striped beets. Toss the cooked beets with a vinaigrette made
with orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   17. Make a quick tomato sauce and toss with spaghetti squash
pasta and freshly grated Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   18. Make eggplant caviar _ also known as Texas caviar _ as a
dip.
</P>
<P>
   19. Company is coming so it's time to get fancy. Make a fresh
tomato tart for appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   21. Be the first on the block to grill brussels sprouts. Cut
them in half, thread on skewers, brush with olive oil and cook 5 to
10 minutes, until golden but not charred. Serve piping hot.
</P>
<P>
   22. Make a fruit salad with the bounty: watermelon, cantaloupe,
honeydew, peaches and plums.
</P>
<P>
   23. For a quick dessert using late summer' raspberries, pile 3
cups in a baking dish, spoon on a half cup of sour cream mixed with
2 tablespoons brown sugar and a tablespoon Chambord. Chill for an
hour then sprinkle with more brown sugar and broil 1 1/2 minutes
until the sauce begins to bubble.
</P>
<P>
   24. Don't forget the tomatoes margarita. Buy sweet cherry
tomatoes. Set them out with coarse salt mixed with minced cilantro
and a mix of tequila and lime juice for dipping.
</P>
<P>
   25. Make a sorbet or granita with pureed berries, cantaloupe,
watermelon or pear.
</P>
<P>
   26. Put up red bell peppers for winter. Core, seed and slice or
cube and freeze in a single layer on cookie trays. Store in freezer
bags.
</P>
<P>
   27. Grill new potatoes. Put them, single layer, in a
triple-strength packet of foil with salt, pepper, minced garlic and
a little water. Roast on hot coals 45 minutes to an hour.
</P>
<P>
   28. Make a plum pie.
</P>
<P>
   29. Make classic Pizza Margherita, a red, white and green
Italian favorite with nothing more than slices of fresh tomato,
mozzarella and fresh basil.
</P>
<P>
   30. Make the French vegetable sandwich called Pan Bagna, with
layers of salted tomatoes, cucumbers, bell pepper and hard -boiled
eggs on an olive-oil-drizzled baguette. Let it sit a half hour _
it's best a little soggy.
</P>
<P>
   31. Make pasta with roast tomatoes. Peel, core and season
tomatoes and place cored side down on a bed of basil leaves. Roast
for 1 1/2 hours in a 350-degree oven. Break up with a spoon and
serve over pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
