<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   August is canning season and if you need current information on
the safest procedures, check out www.homecanning.com, the new Web
site of Alltrista Consumer Products Co.
</P>
<P>
   The site provides step-by-step basics of home canning, equipment
selection, frequently asked questions, and online recipes from
tomato salsa to sweet and sour pepper relish and exotica such as
mulled blackberry vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  There's one month left for summer picnics. If you have a
picnic hamper packed with the basics ready to go at all times you
can pick up and go whenever the mood stripes. Include a tablecloth,
napkins, bottle opener, corkscrew, paper plates, plastic utensils
and at least one large plastic trash bag. Be sure there's a blue
ice pack in the freezer. All you have to do is stop at the
supermarket deli for quick picnic makings. See, life can be simple.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Anyone who has ever cut the kernels from an ear of corn knows
they can fly all over the kitchen. The most frequent suggestion is
to place the corn end down in a large mixing bowl and cut away, but
frankly that's awkward. Here's another suggestion: cut the cob in
half crosswise, then put cut end down on a plate with a lip. Cut
off kernels with the sharp edge of a knife. If the recipe also
calls for corn milk, turn knife and repeat with the dull edge to
free extra corn and corn milk.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
