<HEADER>
A9548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      08-01 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLENDER? WHAT'S A BLENDER? 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Too often, cucumber soup is made with no more thought than
``Let's throw it in the blender with some yogurt and salt.'' To me,
that's not soup but a kind of bizarre milkshake. A real cucumber
soup has backbone.
</P>
<P>
   The usual alternative is a cooked cucumber soup, and that's
fine, but I think the whole point is to avoid heat and effort while
making something cooling, soothing and perfectly refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   For years, I was stuck on cucumber soups, cooked or from the
blender, that had a smooth, creamy consistency. Then, I was served
a clear chunky ice-cold soup laced with soy and with the
characteristic sour, sweet, salty and spicy combination that is
characteristic of so much Southeast Asian and Korean cooking. The
base was chicken stock, and the very thinly sliced cucumbers were
mixed with scallions, watercress and fresh herbs.
</P>
<P>
   After I duplicated that, it occurred to me to make a similar
soup with coconut milk and the fish sauce nam pla. This variation
is equally spicy but wonderfully creamy.
</P>
<P>
   These soups showed me how to improve on the European-style
versions that I had always made. For those, I use yogurt or sour
cream, but the cucumbers are thinly sliced, not pureed, and the
soup has better texture. I doubt I'll ever use the blender to make
cucumber soups again.
</P>
<P>
   For either Asian or European cucumber soup, most of the time
involved lies in chilling. I refrigerate the seeded, sliced
cucumbers after they are seasoned, as their moisture is drawn out;
I refrigerate the stock, yogurt or sour cream that is the soup
base; and if time allows, I refrigerate the soup itself.
</P>
<P>
   The flavor of these soups is quite lively, not really from the
cucumbers but from the load of herbs with them. Both the Asian and
European variations can be augmented with other vegetables _
arugula is good _ and both work well with a few cooked shrimp or
some cooked shredded chicken tossed in.
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN-STYLE CUCUMBER SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 medium cucumbers
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons rice or white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 small chili, stemmed, seeded and minced, or \ teaspoon
cayenne, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chicken stock, chilled
</P>
<P>
   { cup minced scallions, both white and green parts
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped watercress or arugula (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup roughly chopped cilantro, mint, &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thai basil or a combination.
</P>
<P>
   1. Peel cucumbers, then cut them in half lengthwise. Scoop out
seeds. Slice cucumbers as thinly as possible (a mandoline is ideal
for this). Mix them in a bowl with soy sauce, vinegar, chili and
sugar, then refrigerate for about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add stock, scallions, watercress or arugula if you like, and
stir. Taste and adjust seasoning. Just before serving, garnish with
herb or herbs of your choice.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-STYLE CUCUMBER SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 medium cucumbers
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups chicken stock, chilled
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups yogurt, preferably full-fat
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, peeled and minced, or about \ cup minced red onion
or scallion
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped watercress (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup roughly chopped dill or mint.
</P>
<P>
   1. Peel cucumbers, then cut them in half lengthwise. Scoop out
seeds. Slice cucumbers as thinly as possible (a mandoline is ideal
for this). Mix them in a bowl with 2 teaspoons salt and refrigerate
for about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add stock, black pepper, yogurt, shallots and watercress if
you like, and stir. Taste and adjust seasoning. Just before serving
the soup, garnish with the herb of your choice.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
