<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SKEWERS-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      08-01 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKEWERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING GRILLED FLAVORS INSIDE OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN RAICHLEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to grilling, Americans achieve flavor through a
free-handed use of rubs, pastes and marinades. Asians take a more
internal approach. They grill their kebabs on skewers made of
flavorful grasses and herbs.
</P>
<P>
   I first encountered this practice in Bali, where roadside cooks
grill seafood mousse kebabs called sate lilit. An explosively
flavorful mix of pureed fish and spices is molded onto stalks of
fresh lemon grass, then grilled over coconut shell charcoal. The
lemon grass perfumes the sate from the inside out, and you get a
blast of flavor as you nibble the mousse off the skewer.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Vietnamese grill a delicately flavored shrimp
mousse on broad, flat lengths of sugar cane. These kebabs, called
chao tom, offer a stunning contrast of textures and flavors: the
refreshing crunch of the sugar cane versus the soft succulence of
the mousse, the briny tang of the seafood against the sweetness of
the cane juice. As with the lemon grass in sate lilit, you don't
really eat the sugar cane, but chew it a little to release the
juice.
</P>
<P>
   This dish made me think about other uses for sugar cane,
specifically the sugar cane swizzle sticks that are sold at
specialty shops. The thin, square-sided sticks make perfect
skewers; all you need to do is cut off one end sharply on the
diagonal to help ease the skewer through the food.
</P>
<P>
   Taking my inspiration from chao tom, I created a sort of
Caribbean dish by skewering whole shrimp on the cane and basting
them with a rum-mustard glaze. These offbeat kebabs make great
appetizers at a cookout, and assembling them is a snap. Just make a
starter hole with a metal or bamboo skewer in the item being
skewered. Sprigs of fresh rosemary also make excellent skewers,
with stems slender enough to pass through a small item like a
scallop, yet stiff enough to hold chunks of chicken or seafood. The
heat of the fire releases the rosemary oils, which infuse the kebab
with flavor. You can use fresh rosemary sprigs from a greengrocer,
but you'll get longer, stiffer skewers if you cut them from a
rosemary plant, which will keep growing. Once you start thinking
about flavorful skewers, there's no limit to where your imagination
will take you. Mine takes me to my spice rack. With fresh peaches
in season, I reckoned that whole cinnamon sticks would be just the
thing for skewering peaches or nectarines for grilling. For that
matter, you could use sections of vanilla bean as a flavorful
skewer for chunks of banana. Who ever said that you can't grill
dessert?
</P>
<P>
   ROSEMARY-GRILLED SCALLOPS  &QL; 
Time: 30 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds sea scallops (about 30)
</P>
<P>
   About 30 fresh rosemary sprigs (each 3 to 4 inches long)
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces prosciutto, sliced paper thin
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt and freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. Pull off and discard crescent-shaped muscle on side of each
scallop that has one. Strip leaves off bottom 2 inches of rosemary
sprigs (slide them off with your thumb and forefinger). Reserve
leaves, and set sprigs aside. Cut prosciutto into strips just large
enough to wrap around scallops (about 1 by 3 inches).
</P>
<P>
   2. Lay a scallop flat on a work surface. Wrap a piece of
prosciutto around it. Skewer a rosemary sprig through prosciutto
and scallop to other side. Repeat with remaining scallops. Arrange
scallops in a baking dish. Drizzle olive oil and lemon juice on
both sides, sprinkle with rosemary leaves and season with salt and
pepper. (Go easy on salt, as prosciutto is fairly salty.) Marinate
for 15 minutes, while you light grill.
</P>
<P>
   3. Set up grill for direct grilling, and preheat to high. Brush
and oil grate. Arrange scallops on grate, and grill until just
cooked, about 2 minutes a side. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 appetizer servings or 4 main course servings.  &QL; 
PEACH KEBABS ON CINNAMON STICKS  &QL; 
Time: 15 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 large ripe freestone peaches
</P>
<P>
   8 cinnamon sticks
</P>
<P>
   8 fresh mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons salted butter
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons bourbon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Peach or vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   1. Cut peaches in half, and remove stone. Cut each peach half in
half. Using a metal skewer, make a starter hole in center of each
peach quarter. Skewer two peach quarters on each cinnamon stick,
placing a mint leaf between each.
</P>
<P>
   2. Prepare bourbon butter glaze. Combine butter, sugar, bourbon
and lime juice in a saucepan, and boil until thick and syrupy, 3 to
5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Set up grill for direct grilling, and preheat to high. Brush
and oil grate. Grill peaches until nicely browned on both sides, 2
to 4 minutes a side, basting with glaze. Serve at once, with ice
cream.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   PLANTATION SHRIMP ON SUGAR CANE SKEWERS  &QL; 
Time: 40 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   24 extra-large shrimp (1{ pounds), peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper For the glaze: &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   { cup dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 stick (8 tablespoons) unsalted butter, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   { cup dark rum
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Dijon-style mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon distilled white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon each cinnamon, ground cloves and black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   12 sugar cane swizzle sticks (see note).
</P>
<P>
   1. Place shrimp in a mixing bowl and stir in oil, lime juice,
garlic, salt and pepper. Marinate 15 minutes while you prepare
glaze and skewers.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place ingredients for glaze in a saucepan, and bring to a
boil. Reduce heat to medium, and simmer until thick and syrupy, 4
to 6 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cut swizzle sticks in half widthwise, and cut one end off
each piece sharply on diagonal. Resulting skewers should be about 5
inches long and \ inch wide.
</P>
<P>
   4. Set up grill for direct grilling, and preheat to high. Using
a metal skewer, make two starter holes in each shrimp, one toward
head end, one toward tail. Insert a sugar cane skewer through
holes. Repeat with remaining shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   5. Brush and oil grill grate. Grill shrimp kebabs until cooked,
about 2 minutes a side, generously basting with glaze. Serve any
remaining glaze as a sauce on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 appetizer servings, 4 light main course servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Sugar cane swizzle sticks are sold at Citarella stores in
Manhattan for $3.99 for 10 to 12 sticks. Gourmet Garage stores also
carry them, in packages of eight to 10 sticks for $2.99.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   FISH MOUSSE GRILLED ON LEMON GRASS (SATE LILIT)  &QL; 
Time: 40 to 60 minutes, plus 2 hours' chilling  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 shallots, peeled and sliced ({ cup)
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 Thai or Serrano chilies, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon powdered turmeric
</P>
<P>
   5 macadamia nuts
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon shrimp paste or anchovy paste or 1 tablespoon Asian
fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces firm, fresh boneless white fish fillets, like snapper,
mahi-mahi, bass or catfish
</P>
<P>
   { pound shrimp, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   \ cup coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lime juice, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 kaffir lime leaves, cut into thin slivers (or { teaspoon
grated lime zest)
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   24 stalks lemon grass, leaves and roots trimmed off, each about
7 inches long.
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare spice paste. In a food processor finely grind
shallots, garlic, chilies, ginger, turmeric, macadamia nuts,
coriander, pepper, shrimp or anchovy paste (if using fish sauce,
add it in Step 2) and salt. Heat oil in a wok. Stir-fry mixture
over medium heat until dark and fragrant, 6 to 8 minutes. Transfer
to a bowl, and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   2. Prepare fish mousse. Puree fish and shrimp in food processor.
Add spice paste, and puree. Work in coconut milk, lime juice,
kaffir lime leaves and sugar. Taste mixture for seasoning, adding
salt or lime juice to taste. It should be highly seasoned. Chill
mixture for 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   3. Lightly wet your hands. Take about 3 tablespoons mousse
mixture in one hand, and mold it onto bulbous part of lemon grass
stalk about 3 inches long). Repeat with remaining stalks. Place
finished sates on a plate lined with plastic wrap. Cover with more
plastic wrap.
</P>
<P>
   4. Preheat grill to high. Brush and oil grate. Grill sates until
mousse is nicely browned and cooked through, 3 to 4 minutes a side.
If fish mixture sticks to grate, use a metal spatula to turn sates.
Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 appetizer servings, 2 to 3 main course servings.
</P>
