<HEADER>
A9576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SALMONELLA-EATING-WEL     08-01 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMONELLA-EATING-WELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORD OR TWO ABOUT RAW EGGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By   MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whenever the subject of raw eggs comes up, questions come
flowing in. Although the government says no one should eat raw
eggs, public health advice must be ``one size fits all,'' and the
risk is not the same for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood of getting salmonellosis from uncooked or lightly
cooked eggs, whether in mayonnaise or mousse, is quite small for
healthy adults. It has grown even smaller in the last three years.
In 1997, the chances of an egg being infected with salmonella were
one in 10,000. Today the chance is one in 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   But for certain groups, eating raw food like meat, fish or eggs
is much riskier than it is for a healthy adult. About 300 people in
the United States still die from salmonellosis every year. Raw or
lightly cooked eggs (soft-boiled, for example) should not be eaten
by children, the elderly, diabetics, pregnant women, those with
weak immune systems or liver disease, or those taking medication to
reduce stomach acid.
</P>
<P>
   In response to consumer pressure, the industry has assumed more
responsibility for ensuring safety. It produced a consumer
education campaign to raise awareness about safe food handling, and
egg producers have adopted measures that did not exist just a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until 1995 that the industry created a quality control
program encouraging farms to watch for rodent and pest infestations
and to wash and refrigerate eggs, controls most people assume have
always been in place. Though the program is voluntary, 93 percent
of large egg producers have adopted some version of it, according
to the American Egg Board, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Salmonella is transferred from the chicken to the egg, so a
vaccine is now being used on some farms. Food Animal Concerns
Trust, a nonprofit organization financed by private foundations and
individuals, which seeks to improve the safety of meat, poultry and
eggs, is using the vaccine on 13 small farms in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The trust also endorses a technique called competitive
exclusion, which introduces strains of beneficial bacteria in
day-old and 2-day-old chicks, which prevents salmonella from taking
hold. But the technique is relatively expensive, said Robert Wood,
the executive director of the trust, and is used only for broilers
and not for laying hens.
</P>
<P>
   Some supermarkets and specialty stores sell eggs pasteurized in
the shell, which means they are heated just long enough to kill the
germs without cooking the egg. Pasteurized eggs can be used in any
recipe that calls for raw eggs, including mayonnaise and Caesar
salad, though they must be cold in order to separate properly.
Pasteurized egg whites have been available for a few years. Beyond
these changes, Wood said the most promising innovation is the
testing of flocks and their environments at critical points, along
with the diversion of eggs to a pasteurization plant when
salmonella is found. The Food and Drug Administration wants to make
that system mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   Because the risk of salmonella poisoning rises with the age of
the egg, the Agriculture Department said Monday that it plans to
prohibit wholesalers from repackaging eggs that grocery stores
return like remaindered books. The department plans to require a
mandatory 30-day expiration date on all cartons. Currently, some
cartons carry sell-by dates, and some carry Julian dates, which
reveal when the eggs were packed, although in coded fashion: 001
means Jan. 1; 365 means Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration has also proposed requiring
safe handling instructions on cartons of eggs. They would be
similar to the labels on meat and poultry but would include a
statement saying eggs may contain harmful bacteria and warning that
certain people are most at risk. The Egg Board favors a label
without the warning.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, consumers should observe the following rules:
</P>
<P>
   Buy eggs only from refrigerated cases, and refrigerate them in
their cartons, which helps keep them fresh.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid repackaged eggs, buy only those that carry the
Agriculture Department shield.
</P>
<P>
   Look for Julian or sell-by dates on cartons, and buy the eggs
with the latest dates.
</P>
<P>
   Use only clean, unbroken eggs. Discard dirty or broken ones.
</P>
<P>
   Do not leave eggs in any form at room temperature for more than
two hours. For picnics, pack egg dishes with ice or commercial
coolant in an insulated cooler or bag.
</P>
<P>
   Wash your hands, utensils and work surfaces to prevent
cross-contamination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
