<HEADER>
A9577 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-     08-01 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE PLAN TO UPROOT HOMES FOR NATURE SANCTUARY IS FOR THE BIRDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, in a wooded setting between Weslaco and
Mercedes, bird fanciers and conservationists moved their mobile
homes into a park where they could enjoy the wonders of nature.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Lakeview Park became the winter home of nearly 270
annual visitors to the Texas Rio Grande Valley. An additional 40 or
so families made it their year-round home.
</P>
<P>
   Now they all have to move; tear up years of trees, plants and
shrubs that have grown around their mobile homes and leave the
park.
</P>
<P>
   Why would they destroy that kind of habitat? Because the local
development committee wants to hand the property over to the Texas
Parks and Wildlife Department for a bird sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Parks and Wildlife won't accept the land if anyone is
living on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a bird sanctuary for more than 30 years,'' said
George Hoffman. He and his wife, Kathryn, are serving as temporary
managers of the Lakeview Park. ``There are hundreds of species of
birds in this park, and a goodly number of small animals as well.
We have a man living here in this park who is a world-renowned
ornithologist. He moved here because he wanted to study the vast
number of species we have here.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Weslaco Development Committee, which recently purchased
the park, wants the property for the World Birding Center, to be
built by the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the center are readily obvious. They are not so
the birds can have sanctuary, but so thousands of visitors can come
to see them, spend money and go home.
</P>
<P>
   Nature tourism, as bird-watching is often called, is
economically important in the Rio Grande Valley. Last year, it
brought $21 million to the McAllen area, according to the chamber
of commerce there.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism is a $29 billion industry in Texas, and the Valley wants
a greater share.
</P>
<P>
   But at what cost? The vast majority of the people living in
Lakeview Park are senior citizens. The mobile homes they live in
are their only investments, and now those homes are being rendered
nearly worthless.
</P>
<P>
   They can't sell because no new residents are being allowed to
move to the park. They can't move because other mobile home parks
in the area don't take houses that are more than 10 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``And even if their homes are less than 10 years old, these
people still can't afford to move,'' Hoffman said. ``To tear
everything down, move and put it all back up again costs about
$4,000 to $5,000. These people don't have that kind of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said the original plans for the World Birding Center
didn't include the park, and now the plans only take in about 25
percent of it.
</P>
<P>
   There is no need to turn Lakeview Park into a bird sanctuary
because it already is one, Ben Basham, Lakeview's resident
ornithologist, told The Valley Morning Star in Harlingen. ``I've
got my own World Birding Center in the back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Basham went on to warn that many of the park's residents would
not leave without a fight. ``Nobody's going to turn over and play
dead,'' he said. ``There are veterans of World War II and the
Korean conflict in here. You don't kick people out of their
homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman says the battle all comes down to money and a callous
attitude by local officials. ``The Parks and Wildlife Department,''
he said, ``is more interested in woodpeckers than in people.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
