<SLUG> BC-CVN-YOUNG-DELEGATE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    YOUNGEST DELEGATE KNOWS WHAT SHE BELIEVES
 &HT;    By MIRIAM A. GARCIA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ ``Being the youngest, a lot of people feel the
need to protect me or guide me,'' said Karin Henninger.
</P>
<P>
   Henninger, 18, is apparently the youngest of the 4,132 delegates
and alternates to the Republican National Convention. But this
young Colorado alternate knows what she thinks.
</P>
<P>
   Raised by Republican parents, she is well acquainted with the
party. She immediately registered as a Republican voter the day
after her 18th birthday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Henninger said she firmly believes abortion ``should not be used
as a form of birth control'' and that young voters should be aware
of current legislation that will affect their future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security for my generation is very important. My
generation will probably not see a penny of it if something is not
done about it,'' Henninger said.
</P>
<P>
   At the convention, she has been rubbing shoulders with such
national and state luminaries as Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and
Gov. Bill Owens, R-Colo., and is already well-known among Colorado
politicos.
</P>
<P>
   Her daily schedule at the year's biggest political party
includes early morning breakfast with the Colorado delegation,
lunches with young politicians, workshop sessions on politics
during the day, and evening parties. But as exhausting as it may
seem, Henninger changes into comfortable shoes to continue
politicking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see more young people involved in politics,''
said Henninger, of Colorado Springs. ``My parents always told me
you can't exercise the right to complain if you don't exercise your
right to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Young people are only apolitical because no one is approaching
them, Henninger said. She encourages her peers and friends to go
out to vote regardless of what party they choose. She tells them
not to ``waste their vote by not voting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't encourage people while they are in high school
then you are not going to get them while they are in college,''
Henninger said. ``You need to start on them young.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado politicians are prepping her for a political career.
She would like to start off by running for a school board and
continue to change the face of politics to include more women.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she will take her experiences back to her local
organizations, including Colorado College Republicans, El Paso
County Young Republicans and Denver Metro Young Republicans. She
will be a freshman at Pikes Peak Community College in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Garcia can be reached by e-mail miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
