<P>
   SOMALIA-REVIVE (Arta, Djibouti) _ The Somalis originally thought
it could happen quickly, that their country could be resurrected
from its stripped bones in only three days. But they have been here
since March, talking their way down a wandering path of mobile
phones and free roasted camel that just may finally create a
central government for the only nation in the world without one.
There are good reasons to be skeptical about what is happening
here. This is the 13th attempt to remake Somalia since the state
collapsed in civil war in 1991. Some key players, notably major
warlords who keep Somalia in tatters, are not on board. But about
2,000 ordinary Somalis, along with the bulk of their leaders, have
come to the neighboring country of Djibouti, and without exception
they say they are determined to reverse the years of hatred that
made Somalia the No. 1 symbol for chaos in Africa. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
