<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9586 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-MAKING-MAYONNAISE-ART     08-01 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAKING-MAYONNAISE-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGGS, OIL AND SUNLIGHT: HOMEMADE MAYONNAISE, A GREAT SAUCE FOR
SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: Recipes at end of article)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was 1993, and I had my first kitchen job, at a restaurant in
Boston. I listened in as the sous-chef and a cook bent over a
blender, the sous-chef slowly giving instructions. With the machine
whirring, egg yolks were dropped in. Then oil, in an erratic,
drippy stream. A sunny yellow sauce rapidly formed. I asked what it
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayonnaise,'' the sous-chef said.
</P>
<P>
   I almost fell over.
</P>
<P>
   Although I grew up with a mother who baked bread, made her own
jam and never once bought a cake, I thought mayonnaise was
something from a jar. I knew what it should taste like, but I never
really knew what it was.
</P>
<P>
   What it is, is creamy, silky, sharpened with just a splash of
acid, enriched with egg yolk, thickened with oil and pretty much
the best thing that has come to cuisine since butter.
</P>
<P>
   Since I tasted that soft, buttery sauce, I have rarely gone back
to the commercial kind. Watching that mayonnaise whirl together in
what seemed seconds was one of those revelatory moments people new
to cooking have, and it changed me. If you could make something so
splendid from ingredients so ordinary, so unlikely, cooking must be
full of many more unearthed secrets. (It is.)
</P>
<P>
   And though most of America still depends on the stiff, oily
mayonnaise in jars, to serious cooks making their own has become as
fundamental as whisking together vinaigrette. As eggs have grown
safer in recent years, many home cooks have been emboldened to make
it a part of their regular repertory. Hellmann's is a fine product,
sweet and tangy as it is. But homemade mayonnaise is something
entirely different.
</P>
<P>
   It is perfectly divine spread on sandwiches or dressing a salad,
but you can also use it to build sauces. It is the foundation, for
instance, of rouille and tartar sauce.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, when I don't feel like cooking an entire meal, I
often gather a few vegetables from my neighborhood market, blanch
them in boiling salted water, whisk together a mayonnaise and break
a baguette into pieces. I dunk the artichokes, asparagus, carrots
or whatever into the mayonnaise and sop up whatever is left with
the bread. It is a perfect supper, easy, restorative and adequately
indulgent. In Provence, cooks have been doing that forever, but
they make the mayonnaise with garlic and call it aioli.
</P>
<P>
   Making mayonnaise is meditative. You can whip it up in a blender
or food processor _ and there are times, as with an herb
mayonnaise, when you need a machine to chop as well as to emulsify
_ but I always do it by hand.
</P>
<P>
   I have a small French whisk with many, many loosely layered wire
loops and a stainless steel bowl. The egg yolk falls into the bowl
like a thick drop of paint, and I loosen it with vinegar or lemon
juice, a pinch of coarse sea salt and a little Dijon mustard. It
smooths out with a few strokes of the whisk, and then I add the
oil, usually peanut or vegetable, whisking steadily, almost
frantically at first, to break up the oil. When it is incorporating
correctly, it seems to melt into the folds of the liquid,
disappearing until no drops of oil can be seen on the sides.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, I add the oil more quickly, whisking, whisking, until
the oil and mayonnaise are no longer at odds, blending as fluidly
as vermouth and gin in a martini. The smooth, yellow emulsion
clings to the sides of the bowl. I taste, add a little salt and
whisk again, and in a few minutes _ no more _ it is ready.
</P>
<P>
   You can do this faster in a blender or food processor, but I
have found I have more control with a whisk, and it is just as
easy.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason to improve basic mayonnaise, but there seem
to be an infinite number of ways to enhance it. Eggs and oil
welcome almost anything into their realm.
</P>
<P>
   I use a mildly flavored oil so that the richness of the egg
comes through. Many people use olive oil and are disappointed. The
result is often heavy and bitter. I use stronger, similar oils to
flavor the mayonnaise. I might whisk in a few tablespoons of extra
virgin olive oil, walnut oil or Asian sesame oil at the end. So
small an amount can scent the entire sauce without overwhelming it.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing a liquid is perhaps the most difficult decision. The
oil needs a liquid to emulsify and stabilize the sauce. You can use
just water. But some kind of acid is typically preferred. Almost
any will work: red wine vinegar, rice vinegar, champagne vinegar,
sherry vinegar, apple cider vinegar, lime juice, grapefruit juice,
lemon juice, Meyer lemon juice, too.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond these basic components you are free to roam, within
reason. Garlic in particular does good things to oil and eggs. I
add at least a sliver to most mayonnaise recipes as a gentle
background flavor.
</P>
<P>
   If you keep adding garlic, you'll get aioli. I have read recipes
for 16 cloves to a cup of oil. If you plan to carry on any
conversations in person for the rest of the week, three might be a
better start. But garlic is unpredictable. Some is wickedly strong,
and some is subtle. Crush it with the side of a knife, chop it to a
paste and add it at the beginning. If you want the aioli stronger,
whisk in more garlic later. Aioli, like most flavored mayonnaises,
needs to sit a few hours (in a refrigerator) before serving, to
mellow.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, I added a few crushed anchovy fillets with garlic
cloves to a mayonnaise. It became a decadent cousin to anchoide,
the French anchovy dressing, and seemed destined for a steak
sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   Then I charred a red pepper and pushed it into a blender with a
mayonnaise made with a whisk and a bowl. It turned a pretty salmon
pink and tasted sweet, smoky and only vaguely of red pepper.
Another time, I packed the blender with arugula and pureed the
fresh leaves into mayonnaise until it was smooth, pale green and
peppery. I spread it on day-old bread, rubbed with a tomato, and
covered it with a piece of serrano ham. You could substitute basil
and watercress for the arugula.
</P>
<P>
   Herbs can be added in the blender, or you can chop them up and
stir them in at the end. In the blender, you will get a delicate,
uniform sauce. By hand, you will get something more eventful. Some
tastes will be smooth as a pastry cream, others enlivened with
bursts of flavor from the herb.
</P>
<P>
   Mayonnaise, of course, is the basis of many salad dressings and
sauces. Tartar sauce is just mayonnaise loaded with salty bits of
gherkins, shallots or onion and capers. Sour cream is sometimes
added to mayonnaise to make a creamy and tangy dressing on wedges
of lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   I tried whole milk yogurt to see what would happen. The two
allied beautifully. The yogurt added a sharper tang and creaminess
without weighing down the sauce. A little heavy cream stirred into
a bowl of mayonnaise turned up a gentle, light sauce that could be
eaten by the spoonful. I folded it into a salad of smoked mackerel,
red potatoes and celery. The cream in the mayonnaise tempered the
smoke in the fish and thinly washed its flavor over everything as a
shadow softens a landscape.
</P>
<P>
   A standard mayonnaise would have been too thick for this salad.
The cream stretched it out and made it easier to pour. You can
loosen mayonnaise by adding things like cream, sour cream and
yogurt, but you can also simply add water. A tablespoon or so is
usually plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Once the egg yolk and oil emulsify into mayonnaise, it is a
fairly stable concoction. A little water, a little more acid or a
lot of mustard is not going to shake its foundation. Getting it to
coalesce in the beginning is the challenge. Sometimes a mayonnaise
will start thickening and then suddenly turn liquid, or break. It
could be caused by anything from the temperature of the ingredients
to the speed at which the oil is being added.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid this hazard, make sure all ingredients are at room
temperature, and when you first add oil, do it a few drops at a
time and no faster. If you add the oil too quickly, it is like
flooding an engine. The protein in the yolks is overwhelmed by the
oil.
</P>
<P>
   If your mayonnaise breaks, don't throw it out. Get a fresh bowl
and a new egg yolk. Begin mixing the yolk with the acid, salt and
whatever else you put in the first batch and then treat the broken
batch as if it were the oil, whisking it in drop by drop. Once this
emulsifies, you can add oil until the sauce is like your original
vision for the mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   By now, I have broken many mayonnaises. But I have yet to make
one that has disappointed me. One with lots of lemon juice and
lemon zest folded into chopped eggs changed my opinion of egg
salad. I used another, flecked with coriander and cumin, to dress
red and Savoy cabbage, but it made me consider roasting lamb, just
so I could make a sandwich with it.
</P>
<P>
   A lime mayonnaise with sieved avocado stirred in on a whim was
as green as a baby leaf and startlingly rich. It ended on chicken
and fennel. But it may end up with potatoes next time.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best consequences of making mayonnaise is that you
have to make more than you need for a meal. A cup is about the
least you can make, so there is always some left over.
</P>
<P>
   The next day when you pull it from the refrigerator, you can
congratulate yourself and choose its next fate. A basil mayonnaise
for burgers one day has renewed vitality in a chicken salad the
next.
</P>
<P>
   None of this means that I have turned my back on what I first
knew as mayonnaise. My mother makes a chicken salad with almonds,
grapes and celery. Commercial mayonnaise holds it together and
asserts itself sharply, sweetly. I would never try to make her
salad with homemade mayonnaise. Both have their place.
</P>
<P>
   STANDARD MAYONNAISE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   Sliver of a garlic clove, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon or English mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Sea salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peanut oil or vegetable oil.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, whisk together egg yolk, garlic, mustard, lemon
juice and a large pinch of salt. Beginning a drop at a time, whisk
in oil. As it emulsifies, add oil a little faster, in a slow steady
stream. When mixture is thick, taste and adjust seasoning. It
should be highly seasoned.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 1\ cups.
</P>
<P>
   Variation 1: Add \ cup walnut oil.
</P>
<P>
   Variation 2: Reduce lemon juice to one teaspoon, and add truffle
oil to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Variation 3: Add 3 tablespoons heavy cream.
</P>
<P>
   ARUGULA MAYONNAISE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Sea salt
</P>
<P>
   } cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2{ cups tightly packed arugula.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small bowl, whisk together egg yolk, mustard, vinegar
and large pinch of salt. Beginning a drop at a time, whisk in oils.
As it emulsifies, add oil a little faster in a slow, steady stream.
When mixture is thick, taste, and adjust seasoning. It should be
highly seasoned.
</P>
<P>
   2. Transfer mixture to a blender or food processor, add arugula,
and puree. (Add a tablespoon of water, if necessary, to get arugula
flowing.) Taste, and adjust seasoning before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 1\ cups.
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED RED PEPPER MAYONNAISE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 large red pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   { tablespoon white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Sea salt
</P>
<P>
   } cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup extra virgin olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat broiler. Place pepper under broiler, and roast until
blackened on all sides. Remove, and let cool. Peel away skin and
seeds, and discard. Pull pepper into 3 or 4 long pieces and set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a small bowl, whisk together egg yolk, mustard, vinegar
and a large pinch of salt. Beginning a drop at a time, whisk in
oils. As they emulsify, add oils a little faster, in a slow steady
stream. When mixture is thick, taste and adjust seasoning. It
should be highly seasoned.
</P>
<P>
   3. Transfer the mixture to a blender or a food processor, add
the pepper and puree. Taste, and adjust the seasoning before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 1\ cups.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POTATO AND SMOKED MACKEREL SALAD WITH CREAMY MAYONNAISE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 35 minutes, plus 1 hour's refrigeration  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1\ pounds (about 15) baby red-skinned potatoes, washed
</P>
<P>
   Sea salt and freshly ground grains of paradise or black pepper
</P>
<P>
   \ peeled red onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 stalk celery, thinly sliced on the diagonal
</P>
<P>
   1 smoked mackerel fillet, skin discarded
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   { tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red wine vinegar, more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons heavy cream.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place potatoes in a medium pan, cover with water and season
generously with salt. Bring to a boil, reduce to a simmer and cook
until tender, about 15 minutes. Drain. When cool enough, slice into
\-inch rounds.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a large bowl, combine potatoes, red onion and celery. By
hand, shred mackerel into pieces no larger than a raspberry; there
should be about 1 cup. Add to salad.
</P>
<P>
   3. Prepare mayonnaise: In a small bowl, whisk together the egg
yolk, mustard, vinegar and large pinches of salt and grains of
paradise. Beginning a drop at a time, whisk in oil. As it
emulsifies, add oil a little faster, in a slow, steady stream. When
mixture is thick, whisk in heavy cream.
</P>
<P>
   4. Fold 1/3 cup mayonnaise into potato mixture. There should be
just enough mayonnaise to coat ingredients; add more if necessary.
Cover, and refrigerate for at least an hour. Adjust seasonings
before serving, adding more salt or vinegar as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (Note: Grains of paradise are at Adriana's Caravan, in Grand
Central Terminal, 212-972-8804 ($6.50 for 2 ounces), and
Kalustyan's, 123 Lexington Ave., at 28th Street, 212-685-3451
($3.49 an ounce.)
</P>
<P>
   CABBAGE SALAD WITH TOASTED CORIANDER AND CUMIN MAYONNAISE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes, plus 1 hour's refrigeration  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon coriander seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cumin seeds
</P>
<P>
   3 cups thinly shredded savoy cabbage
</P>
<P>
   2 cups thinly shredded red cabbage
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons apple cider vinegar, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot lobe, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon thinly sliced chives
</P>
<P>
   Sea salt and ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups vegetable oil.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small skillet over high heat (or in a microwave oven at
full power), toast coriander seeds and cumin seeds just until
fragrant. Grind together using a mortar and pestle, and set aside.
In a large bowl, combine savoy cabbage and red cabbage, and set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Prepare mayonnaise: In a small bowl, whisk together egg yolk,
vinegar, shallot, chives, reserved coriander and cumin and large
pinches of salt and pepper. Beginning a drop at a time, whisk in
oil. As it emulsifies, add oil a little faster, in a slow steady
stream. When mixture is thick, whisk in more vinegar to taste;
mayonnaise should be highly seasoned.
</P>
<P>
   3. Fold 1/3 cup mayonnaise into cabbage. There should be enough
to coat cabbage generously; add more if necessary. Cover, and
refrigerate for at least an hour. Before serving, adjust
seasonings, adding more salt or vinegar as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN AND AVOCADO SALAD WITH LIME MAYONNAISE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 65 minutes, plus 1 hour's refrigeration  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 2} pound chicken, with neck, rinsed and patted dry
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   8 cloves of whole unpeeled garlic, plus { clove garlic, peeled
and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 medium bulb fennel, with leaves
</P>
<P>
   Coarse sea salt
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1{ avocados
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lime juice, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   } cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup, plus 2 tablespoons whole milk yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large soup pot, combine chicken, chicken neck,
peppercorns and whole garlic cloves. Cut fennel bulb into \-inch
dice, and reserve { cup; add remainder to pot. Chop fennel leaves,
and reserve 2 tablespoons; add remainder to pot. Add just enough
water to cover chicken, and season generously with sea salt. Bring
to a boil, then reduce to a simmer. Cook until chicken juices run
clear when sliced at a joint, 20 to 25 minutes. Transfer chicken to
a plate and allow to cool completely. Reserve broth for another
use.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove meat from chicken, discarding skin and bones. Cut meat
into {-inch pieces. Place in a large bowl with reserved fennel
bulb, reserved fennel leaves and scallions. Peel and cut one
avocado into {-inch cubes, and add to bowl. Sprinkle with 1
tablespoon lime juice, and toss gently to mix.
</P>
<P>
   3. Prepare mayonnaise: In a small bowl, whisk together egg yolk,
1 tablespoon lime juice, mustard, chopped garlic and a large pinch
of salt and pepper. Beginning a drop at a time, whisk in vegetable
oil. As it emulsifies, add oil a little faster in a slow, steady
stream. When all oil is incorporated and mixture is thick, press
remaining half of avocado through a sieve into mixture. Add
remaining tablespoon lime juice and yogurt, and whisk to blend.
Season to taste with salt and pepper; it should be highly seasoned.
</P>
<P>
   4. Fold 1/3 cup mayonnaise into chicken. There should be just
enough mayonnaise to coat ingredients; add more if necessary. Cover
and refrigerate for at least an hour. Adjust seasonings before
serving, adding more lime juice as desired.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
