<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9591 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-PERES-NYT &LR;      08-01 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PERES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK'S ENEMIES RENEW VOW TO TOPPLE ISRAELI GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By JOHN KIFNER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak's political problems
mounted Tuesday as his right-wing opponents, sensing blood after
their stunning defeat Monday of Shimon Peres, Barak's presidential
candidate, vowed new efforts to bring down the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak doesn't have a government,'' declared the Likud leader,
Ariel Sharon, calling for new elections. ``He has lost his majority
in the Knesset.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Moshe Katsav, the first Likud candidate ever elected
president _ a low-profile local politician and a Sephardi immigrant
who was given no chance by political commentators _ was sworn in
Tuesday evening, there was turmoil and consternation within the
remnants of Barak's battered coalition.
</P>
<P>
   One of Barak's closest associates, Deputy Defense Minister
Ephraim Sneh, a comrade from their days in Israel's most elite
secret commando unit and a former general, issued a frustrated call
for new elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, in the current political makeup of the Knesset, we could
not bring about the election of Peres, it is a sign that we will be
unable to pass other things,'' Sneh said on Israel radio.
``Therefore we must go directly to the nation, to present our path,
so that the nation can decide what it wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak is expected get through one more acrimonious session of
the Knesset, or parliament, Wednesday before it adjourns for its
regular three-month vacation. A preliminary bill calling for the
dissolution of parliament and new elections is to be referred to a
committee that his party controls.
</P>
<P>
   Barak hopes to use the coming months to strengthen his
coalition, which now has only a minority of 42 in the 120-seat
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But Sharon warned Tuesday that what he called his ``Jerusalem
Coalition'' would be ready to act should Barak ``sneak'' into any
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will stand on guard,'' the former general, a hero of tank
battles in the Sinai desert in two wars and the architect of
Israel's troubled 1982 invasion of Lebanon, said. ``We can call the
Knesset at any time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although it would be unusual, the Knesset could be called back
from vacation on a petition signed by 25 members, a number that
would be easy for Likud and its allies to gather. If the subject
was a vote of no confidence, the petition would need 61 signatures,
an absolute majority.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon made his remarks in a sometimes pugnacious appearance
before a group of foreign journalists, where he repeatedly returned
to his theme that Jerusalem is the rightful possession of the
Jewish people and must never be divided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerusalem is a symbol that kept the Jews together for
thousands of years,'' he thundered at one point, hammering his hand
on the lectern. ``Jerusalem is a symbol. You don't touch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Political commentators, many of them critical of the vote
against Peres in the Knesset and the role the ultra-Orthodox
parties played in his defeat, were unanimous on Tuesday in saying
that the vote had been a major blow to Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority in the Knesset voted not only against Shimon
Peres but first and foremost against Barak, and against what the
two of them represent,'' Nahum Barnea wrote in the newspaper
Yedioth Ahronoth. ``It is no wonder that the left wing in Israel
let out a painful cry yesterday: beyond the sorrow at Peres' bad
luck, people were afflicted by the same sense of self-pity that
seized them after Rabin's assassination.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same newspaper, Sima Kadmon wrote: ``The Likud chalked up
a tremendous political achievement yesterday. It succeeded where
failure appeared certain. And that success is going to accelerate
the collapse of Barak's coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Peres this was probably the last defeat,'' Kadmon
continued. ``For Barak it was probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Ma'ariv, Hami Shalev wrote: ``This is a Knesset which
acts in ways that are not only confrontational but also somewhat
perverse. This is a Knesset that will not pass a peace accord with
the Palestinians, that will not legislate a referendum under
conditions acceptable to the government, that will not let Barak
move another meter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
