<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9599 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-NAPSTER-COMMENTARY-TE     08-01 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAD ABOUT NAPSTER? YOU SHOULD BE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Funny, isn't it, how rebellion in rock 'n' roll has evolved?
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five years ago, it was going crazy over Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five years ago, it was growing your hair, dropping out,
turning on, going to Woodstock, marching against the Vietnam War
and arguing with Dad at the dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, it was safety pins, Ramones records,
pogoing and being one of a handful of people watching some punk
band while 12,000 worshipped at the feet of REO Speedwagon or
Journey.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, it was throwing away your Cinderella records,
getting a flannel shirt and moshing.
</P>
<P>
   And now, it's stealing music off the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   I refer, of course, to Napster, which allows people to download
songs off the Net and keep them, forever. For free. Right there on
your computer. For free. Sounding just like the originals. For,
once again, free.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, U.S. District Judge Marilyn Hall Patel
effectively shut down Napster, saying the company was infringing on
music copyrights to a massive degree. But on Friday, an appeals
court panel said Napster can continue to operate while it contests
the court order.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Patel injected a little sanity into this whole ugly
business, and it's nice to see that someone with some clout
recognizes Napster for what it is: Taking music without the
permission of those who made it, not paying royalties, not caring a
fig about little things like copyrights, and giving it away.
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association of America, which has sued
Napster, has estimated that more than $300 million worth of sales
have been lost due to the free trading, according to The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   The rift in the music community over Napster has been
polarizing. Millions of people have used the service and love it,
but musicians feel they're being ripped off.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Metallica have taken the most pro-active stance
against Napster: Drummer Lars Ulrich brought the e-mail addresses
of thousands of Napster users to the company's California
headquarters. Then the group sued Napster. And then, the day after
the band played Texas Stadium, Ulrich was on Capitol Hill,
testifying before the Senate Judiciary Committee on Napster.
</P>
<P>
   The whole Napster issue isn't going away _ company attorney
David Boies says there will be an appeal. In the meantime, reading
Ulrich's testimony should be mandatory for anyone interested in the
Napster debate; it's available at www.metallica.com.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Ulrich takes an honest, nearly comprehensive look at just
how far-reaching the effects of Napster could be _ on bands,
engineers and owners of recording studios, among others. All would
suffer if Napster were allowed to run rampant.
</P>
<P>
   The interesting thing about the whole debate, and Metallica's
stance, is that the band has somehow become ``the enemy'' to
thousands of music fans: To them, the band's members are sellouts,
money-grubbers, capitalist pigs. And now, most probably, even more
evil, as their point of view has, at least temporarily, prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, people think music should be free, maaaan _ the
argument being that if we can download the entire Metallica catalog
without paying for it, we should be able to.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the world doesn't work this way. I can go steal a
Metallica CD _ or at least attempt to _ from my local record store,
and food from my local supermarket and gas from the station I go.
</P>
<P>
   I can go eat dinner somewhere and then sneak out of the
restaurant and into a waiting car without paying for it _ walking
the check, we used to call it _ and I can do the same with a copy
of Rolling Stone down at 7-Eleven. You can take more than one copy
of your local newspaper from the rack.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is called theft: ``Can'' and ``should'' are not the
same thing. Nobody who wants to get Metallica's music for free
would take kindly to being asked to work for a week _ or a month,
or two _ for no pay, much less the many months it often takes
musicians to craft a CD.
</P>
<P>
   Metallica's crime, it seems, is being popular _ as if working
for years to build up a fan base and make a decent living means
they should then have to give up all rights and profits from their
music.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the cutoff point? Ten million CDs sold? Fifteen? Five
Top 5 singles? Eight?
</P>
<P>
   Most musicians, of course, are not wealthy. They're devoting
much of their lives to giving people music, and they should be paid
for their work, because it took time and money and effort and
creativity to produce it. We don't live in a society where
everything we want is free _ never has been the case, never will
be. Thanks again, Judge Patel.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
