<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CHAMBER-MUSIC-ART-     08-01 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHAMBER-MUSIC-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMBER MUSIC GROUPS ABOUND, PASSIONATE AND LITTLE PUBLICIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By DANIEL J. WAKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is a secret world of chance meetings between
strangers, of quietly arranged hookups, of one-time encounters that
can turn passionate or can even blossom into semipermanence.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the rave scene.
</P>
<P>
   This is the territory of Mozart and Brahms and Beethoven.
</P>
<P>
   Of the many social scenes that weave through New York's night
life, few are lesser known than the chamber music crowd. And few
have so many dedicated denizens.
</P>
<P>
   Piano trios, string quartets, wind quintets and other
permutations coalesce within apartment walls and then melt away, or
meet once for a reading, or grow old together. Many players find
one another through Amateur Chamber Music Players Inc., a worldwide
organization that lists some 500 members in New York City in a sort
of giant collective personal ad. Others navigate in small, informal
networks.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the amateur classical music world in this city extends
far beyond chamber groups.
</P>
<P>
   There are orchestras: the Doctors' Orchestra, the Lawyers'
Orchestra, the Brooklyn Heights Orchestra and ensembles at the
Bloomingdale School of Music and 92nd Street Y in Manhattan, among
others. Many of the city's more than 20 community music schools
have chamber music programs for amateurs. Around the country, there
are dozens of weekend or weeklong seminars for players willing to
travel, and to pay. One of the most popular seminars runs for a
weekend in March under the auspices of the Chamber Music Society of
Lincoln Center. And this is not to mention youth orchestras and
choruses.
</P>
<P>
   The most fervent devotees seem to be the chamber musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've no hesitation about calling absolute strangers, although
more and more you get to know people and have musical friends,''
said Joan Edelstein, a flutist and director of the physical therapy
program at Columbia University. ``In some cases they become
unqualified friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Edelstein plays weekly in a wind quintet, whose previous
incarnation lasted 12 years. Her husband, Haskell Edelstein, a
bassoonist and tax lawyer, plays in two other quintets and two
community orchestras. They play in frequent one-time gatherings and
a sometime nonet. When they travel, they always stop in on the
local music store, a practice that has swollen their sheet music
collection to four shelves' worth.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, amateur music-making has been around as long as
classical music. At first a province of the aristocracy, it
broadened into a bourgeois pursuit with the rise of the middle
class in the 19th century. Think of Schubertiade evenings in middle
Europe or parlor soirees in mid-Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In an age overwhelmed by electronic pursuits, this acoustic
world _ at least in New York _ seems to be flourishing.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is important for those who worry about the health of
classical music in America. Amateur musicians are the best sort of
audience, informed to the point that they have played the very
pieces on a night's concert program. Many serve on the boards of
musical institutions, or as arts administrators. Amateur dollars
provide income for professional teachers and chamber music coaches.
</P>
<P>
   And amateur music-making offers an avenue to the types of social
bonds and friendships that have declined as life has sped up, a
problem addressed by Robert D. Putnam in his recent book ``Bowling
Alone: The Collapse and Revival of American Community'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster). Putnam, a Harvard University political scientist, argues
that civic engagement and private networks have declined over the
past 30 years, to America's detriment.
</P>
<P>
   Although Putnam presents data in his book that shows a decrease
in the number of Americans in the last 25 years who play
instruments, the data does not break out classical music or chamber
music. There are, however, indications that these musical ranks
have been growing.
</P>
<P>
   The Amateur Chamber Music Players says its membership has
increased by about 800 since the mid-1990s, to 4,900. ``For every
member we have I am sure there are four or five who play quartets
with a member who just didn't join,'' said Daniel Nimetz, executive
director of the association. And the National Guild of Community
Schools of the Arts estimates there are 600 arts schools in the
country, and more than two-thirds of its members were founded in
the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Quantity is nice, but to many musicians, it is the quality that
counts. ``Chamber music by its very nature is a kind of analogue
for community,'' said Daniel Epstein, a New Yorker and the pianist
of the Raphael Trio. ``It requires cooperation, it requires
empathy, it requires listening to other people, all the things you
have to do in society to make society run successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   The devotion of some amateur musicians knows few bounds, judging
by the behavior at a chamber music workshop that the Raphael Trio
runs in Adamant, Vt., for adult amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get to camp and before they even unpack they pull out
their instruments and start playing,'' Epstein said. ``They'll play
far into the night. People tell us they look forward to this week
the whole year. It really gives meaning to the word amateur, in a
true sense of the word, somebody who loves something. It's not a
job to them. It's something that goes right to the heart of who
they are and what they love.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to overestimate the zeal of these amateurs. One
subject, Dr. Franz Alt, a retired mathematician at the Bureau of
Standards in Washington who fled the Nazi occupation of Austria in
1938, approaches people carrying string instruments on the subway
to his neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make it a habit of collecting people in Washington Heights
who play,'' said Alt, a violist who takes part in four or five
regular quartets at any one time. Alt is 89.
</P>
<P>
   At the Amateur Chamber Music Players association, joining simply
means gaining a place in a worldwide directory. Musicians grade
themselves. Members are encouraged to call one another. New members
are asked to volunteer a contribution of $20. A Web site,
www.acmp.net, allows members to search for players by instrument,
location and grade. In one way, the digital age helps. E-mailing
has made contacting players much easier.
</P>
<P>
   A typical evening of the chamber association took shape July 26.
</P>
<P>
   It was an eclectic mix, like a New York 2000 version of those
bomber crews in old World War II movies. There were the Edelsteins;
a music therapist; a synagogue caretaker for the Soslowitz Hasidic
sect; a federal prosecutor; an official of the city's Department of
Environmental Protection; a computer consultant; and a dot-com
employee. A reporter sat in. The ages ranged from late 20s to early
60s.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The evening was organized by Laurence Beckhardt, the
environmental official, who borrowed a sister-in-law's large living
room in Tribeca. The program: two wind octets by Mozart, and nonets
by Charles Gounod and Theodore Gouvy.
</P>
<P>
   Chitchat was minimal. There were deferential offers to play
second parts. Roles emerged. Barry Fader, the caretaker and an
oboist, revealed his former life as a professional musician by
occasionally calling for a chord or attack to be repeated, just to
get it right. Haskell, a true veteran of the amateur circuit,
assumed the mantle of raconteur and joke-teller. (``Did you hear
the one about the soprano standing outside her door in the rain?
She forgot her key and didn't know when to come in.'') Jennifer
Miller, French-horn player and music therapist and another former
pro, seemed the most assured on tempi.
</P>
<P>
   That, in fact, was the chief source of discussion _ how fast to
play a movement. ``Too bad this is a democracy,'' Fader said at one
point with a wry tone.
</P>
<P>
   There is a seamy side _ well, as far as it goes _ in the key and
fingerboard set.
</P>
<P>
   Some players refuse to play in a group that includes an
individual they do not like. Sessions can become a wedge between a
musician and a nonplaying spouse, or even the source of jealousy
when a spouse perceives a rival in the group.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Finley, a lawyer and violist, attends a lavish chamber
music party in Darien, Conn., every December. ``People bring their
spouses, but they group together and leave early,'' he said. ``Then
we switch around, go from group to group, room to room. It's almost
like a music orgy.''
</P>
<P>
   A recurrent theme among association members is frustration with
players who overrate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no fun to be in a group with people who play less well,''
said David Greenwald, the federal prosecutor and an oboist. ``And
in the long run, it's better not to play with people who are better
than you, because they will resent you. You want to find your own
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamber association sessions have a vague etiquette. An offering
of drinks is usually important. Don't criticize fellow musicians
unless you know them well enough to rib. Try not to be late. It's
hard enough getting a bunch of busy professionals together. Be
tactful.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be careful about not stepping on anybody's toes,''
Fader said. ``But musicians don't like to be superficial. It's an
art that requires great depth of expression.''
</P>
<P>
   English is not necessary. Finley says he once played string
quartets with an Italian, Japanese and German. Only the Italian
spoke English, to a degree. ``Who you end up playing with is
sometimes a complete mystery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that people generally regard that having a pleasant
evening and being hospitable and having something to eat and
telling good stories is almost as important as the music,'' Finley
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
