<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9607 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-DORM-MARKETING-ADV01-     08-01 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DORM-MARKETING-ADV01-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV01  
 IF IT'S HOT, IT'S SOON TO BE NOT IN FICKLE CAMPUS MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   ART ADVISORY: With illustration of a trendy dorm room, moving as a
photo (NNS1) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, August 1, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By DRU SEFTON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're a typical college student this fall, chances are
you'll buy something in an animal-print motif during your
back-to-school shopping.
</P>
<P>
   You just can't avoid it. Leopard, tiger and zebra prints are
lurking in store aisles on nearly everything: sheets, towels, rugs,
beanbag chairs, ironing-board covers, suitcases, inflatable
furniture, candles, bulletin boards, cosmetic bags, cell phone
covers -- even hair dryers.
</P>
<P>
   But now that animal prints are in, they're going out.
</P>
<P>
   That's the college market. If something is around long enough to
be hip, chances are it's not that hip anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it gets into the mainstream, then their parents go for it
and it's no longer cool,'' said Eric Weil, managing partner of
Student Monitor, a national collegiate market research service.
</P>
<P>
   So the campus set is a tricky market for retailers. Tricky but
temptingly lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   The latest census data shows that in 1998 a record 9.4 million
students under age 25 were enrolled in American colleges.
</P>
<P>
   During the fall 1999 semester, the average student spent around
$343 a month on various retail purchases, according to a Student
Monitor survey of 1,200 undergraduates. After food and
entertainment, top spending categories were toiletries and school
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, those students each spent about $23 a month on
toiletries. By region, that figure varies from a low of $22 in the
South and Midwest to a high of $27 in the West. For school
supplies, the average is $21 monthly, from a low of $18 in the
South to $28 in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 60 percent of students surveyed had a major credit card
in their own name.
</P>
<P>
   And they really like stuff.
</P>
<P>
   They are students like Amit Ray of Houston, a sophomore studying
computer science at Texas A&AMP;M University in College Station. His
dormitory essentials? ``I gotta have my microfridge, microwave, TV,
stereo system, computer, cordless telephone and digital answering
machine,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   To capture the attention of these young and enthusiastic
consumers, the manufacturers and retailers have to be -- and be
aware of what is -- cutting-edge cool.
</P>
<P>
   One store that has done a good job, in Weil's opinion, is the
discount chain Target.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is regarded as so hip in the student market,'' he said.
``It was the kids that first started calling it `TarJAY.' That has
a cache to it.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``hip factor'' must come from the kids themselves. ``Nobody
in the student market has more credibility than another student,''
Weil added. ``The power of buzz can build or destroy.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies look to the Ridgewood, N.J.-based Student Monitor and
The Gut, a trend publication in South Hadley, Mass., to tap into
the latest buzz on everything from shower accessories to room
decorations.
</P>
<P>
   And, in turn, The Gut turns to a network of trend spotters out
on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tap into people we call `style makers,' who are always
ahead of the mainstream,'' said Gut Editor Jennifer Grow. ``Like
those out on the fringe. The skateboarders and surfers in
California, for instance, they're the ones credited with starting
more than 50 percent of trends.''
</P>
<P>
   Animal prints probably were big with style makers as far back as
two years ago. ``Since that's hot right now, that's it for them,''
Grow said. ``They're not interested in that anymore, it's
overexposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, what's selling well with students is anything that
helps get more stuff into their small dorms, tiny apartments or
minuscule fraternity and sorority rooms, and keeps that stuff
organized.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a small, confined space, and they have nowhere else
to go,'' said Kate Danaj, research director at Teenage Research
Unlimited in Northbrook, Ill. ``They study, eat and sleep there.
They don't get to put much into it, so they cram in as much as they
can.''
</P>
<P>
   New this year at Bed, Bath &AMP; Beyond is a khaki-colored ``cargo
pocket'' for accessible storage that tucks under a mattress and
hangs down beside the bed.
</P>
<P>
   The national retailer also is partnering with MTV, the music
video cable giant. ``The MTV dorm towel has a Velcro pocket,'' said
Amy Susskind, a spokeswoman for Bed, Bath &AMP; Beyond. ``Students can
put their room keys or ID in the pocket on the way to the shower,
so they won't lose them.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers also must think differently to pitch products. One
approach is a technique called ``chalking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a big chunk of chalk and you write an ad or slogan on
sidewalks around campus,'' Weil said. ``Very low-tech but visceral.
Kids think that's very cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies attract student attention with elaborate
entertainment. During the spring 1999 semester, Hilfiger Toiletries
sponsored a Music Madness College Tour with bands Babe the Blue Ox,
the Interpreters and Trinket. While kids listened to tunes, they
snagged samples -- and purchased products.
</P>
<P>
   Just when a merchandiser manages to get the attention of
students, one-quarter of them graduate and a new bunch floods in --
each with their own ideas as to what's hip.
</P>
<P>
   Jane McCarthy, who coordinates The Gut's network of style makers
and trend spotters, predicts a likely trend: the marketing of
reality TV products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like MTV `Real World' accessories, those cool lamps and funky
bedspreads on the show,'' McCarthy said. ``Kids are talking about
those furnishings. They really like them.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest buzz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
