<HEADLINE>
`VIRTUA TENNIS' CAPTURES JUST ABOUT EVERY NUANCE OF THE GAME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aside from, like, pool and bowling, tennis is probably one of
the most difficult sports to reproduce for the video-game crowd _
namely because, like pool and bowling, the sport is so boring.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo is just about the only one to make a decent stab at
tennis, and you probably don't even remember it: ``Mario's 3D
Tennis'' for the company's now-defunct Virtual Boy system. The
three of you who bought it know what I'm talking about.
</P>
<P>
   But Sega, doing whatever it can to get you not to buy a
PlayStation 2, has successfully ported its ``Virtua Tennis'' arcade
title to its Dreamcast system, and it's gonna take a P2 title to
beat this thing.
</P>
<P>
   Right behind ``NFL 2K'' and ``NHL 2K,'' ``Virtua Tennis'' (Sega
for Dreamcast, all ages) is the latest Sega Dreamcast sports game
to perfectly capture just about every nuance of that particular
sport.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk this up to the graphics, which are so well-detailed, if
you walked into a room with this on, you'd swear you were watching
TV. Even the crowds, which are notoriously flat as wallpaper, have
depth and dimension to them.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the realism, there are eight players to choose from,
all of whom are based on real-life tennis athletes, such as Cedric
Pioline and Tommy Haas. Hopefully, someone's heard of these people.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing missing is John McEnroe throwing a tantrum and
cursing at the line judges. Maybe next time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evolution 2: Far Off Promise'' (UbiSoft for Dreamcast, ages 13
and up) is yet another game in an increasingly long line of titles
that look like they'd be cool for little kids but are more suited
for teens.
</P>
<P>
   In this role-playing game, players man Mag Launcher, who must
choose whether he wants to be the world's greatest adventurer or
save his best friend. Hmmmm _ world's greatest adventurer? Wouldn't
you get, like, free food and chicks? What friend?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Mag decides to save his friend. Which means you must
fight a bunch of bad people and get in all sorts of the usual RPG
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But ``E2'' is actually executed very well, and doesn't have that
right-traffic-lane-slow gameplay that dogs most RPGs. The graphics
are nicely illustrated, too, with two camera modes and a 3D-based
battle system.
</P>
<P>
   With alcohol consumption and tobacco use going on, though,
parents need to be wary. This isn't Mario.
</P>
<P>
   Parents will, however, undoubtedly love Disney's latest string
of education PC games, titled ``Disney Learning.'' There's three in
the series, aimed at different age levels: toddler, preschool and
kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   Players participate in a variety of skill-building games, from
finding hidden letters to creating and coloring objects. The games
enhance basic learning skills, like learning math and abstract
thinking. Shoot, ``I'' should be playing these games.
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713, or e-mail:
mmayhew(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
