<SLUG> BC-GOOD-COFFEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT TOUCH, AND TOP, FOR ESPRESSO
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Penn., Wash.)  By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nicholas O'Connell worked like a surgeon, his movements small,
precise. He reached for his tools, handled them like crystal and
was so quiet he barely seemed to breathe. His task complete, he
changed roles. He looked up, his suit still crisp, every blond hair
on his head in place. His inner host emerged. And he handed me his
masterpiece: a cappuccino.
</P>
<P>
   A real one, like those you can find in train stations in Italy.
Thick, creamy, so evolved that sipping is an impossibility. The
cappuccino goes down in a long, charged stream.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it different? Excellent beans and equipment, surely,
but also an acute sense of what a good cup of coffee should be. But
more on that later.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell, 29, works for La Colombe Torrefaction, a coffee
roasting company and cafe in Philadelphia. Dressed like a banker,
he travels to New York several times a week to visit restaurants
like Ducasse, Jean Georges and Daniel, among others. He makes sure
their coffee machines, which they buy from him, are in order and
meticulously clean, that the restaurants don't overgrind their
beans and that the staffs' technique stays honed.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell is a detail man. Since the flavor of the water used is
so important to good coffee, O'Connell also checks on the
restaurants' filtration systems. Likewise, he tests brands of milk
and recommends his favorites to the restaurants. (In New York, he
likes Marcus Dairy Inc.)
</P>
<P>
   Call him a technician or a consultant. But O'Connell is really
more a prophet, spreading the philosophy of his boss, Jean-Philippe
Iberti, who founded La Colombe in 1994 with Todd Carmichael.
</P>
<P>
   Iberti, 33, came to the United States from France in the late
1980s to study flight engineering in Seattle but ended up working
for a coffee roaster there. He liked the business and decided to go
out on his own. He chose Philadelphia because warehouse space could
be rented cheaply and because ... well, because there was no good
coffee there.
</P>
<P>
   He opened a small cafe on 19th Street near Rittenhouse Square.
It is a spare room with high ceilings and just a few tables and
wood chairs. The croissants are usually sold out before noon. Then
it is just coffee, Iberti's way. Double mocha skim lattes with no
foam are discouraged. But you can get an espresso whose flavor will
stay with you all day. ``The product is first,'' he said. ``The
customer is second.''
</P>
<P>
   The beans, which Iberti buys from growers all over the world,
are blended before being roasted gently, 15 minutes as opposed to
the typical five. The result, in an espresso, is a small shot that
is light and caramelly, with bitterness and acidity that are
deliberate but quiet.
</P>
<P>
   The company sells five varieties of beans by mail order for
$9.55 to $10.45 a pound. The minimum order is one pound, and
shipping is $4; (800) 563-0860.
</P>
<P>
   La Colombe cafe sells 1,500 cappuccinos and lattes a day, and
that is where the flair comes in. The milk is steamed so that it
becomes dense and creamy, with almost no distinction between foam
and milk. It is not merely poured on top of the espresso, but
fashioned to look like a feather, a leaf, a heart or a minimalist
grouping of lines.
</P>
<P>
   La Colombe only recently began taking on restaurant clients
outside Philadelphia. In addition to New York, they are in Boston
and San Francisco. That's where O'Connell steps in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest part,'' he said, ``is not the technique, but to
teach people to take their time and pay attention to their
senses.''
</P>
<P>
   And learn what a good cappuccino is. One must taste, taste,
taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we do is make them a great cup of coffee,'' he
said. ``If they can develop a taste, they can remember what it
should look like and the way it should be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
