<SLUG> BC-PETINSURANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE COULD BE A PET OWNER'S BEST FRIEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aja was a present to mark Candace Alley's first wedding
anniversary, so when the kitten became ill, no amount of money was
spared to restore her to health.
</P>
<P>
   Alley and her husband eventually spent nearly $1,000 on
treatment for Aja's liver and kidney ailments.
</P>
<P>
   The Arlington, Texas, couple has no regrets. But like many pet
owners _ and a growing number of employers _ they have become aware
of the money they could have saved if they had carried pet
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   As employers in North Texas and across the country take notice
of the emotional connection between employees and their four-legged
companions, a growing number are including pet insurance as part of
their benefits package.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a trend toward providing this type of
coverage to employees,'' said Bill Gorman, regional director of
business development at Veterinary Pet Insurance, which offers the
policies. ``We have now around 200 corporations from all over the
country, but the people that love us are the high-tech industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorman, who was in Phoenix recently to work out a pet-coverage
deal with Best Western International, said that with the economy in
such good shape, more companies are looking for extra benefits to
lure employees and keep the ones they have. ``It really doesn't
cost the corporations, except administrative work if they are going
to do payroll deduction,'' Gorman said.
</P>
<P>
   While Veterinary Pet Insurance has been around since 1982, it
only recently began expanding its client base to businesses.
</P>
<P>
   To date, clients are as varied and far away as Colle &AMP; McVoy, a
marketing and PR firm in Minneapolis and as close as Accor Economy
Lodging in Dallas and the Cancer Therapy and Research Center in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten a very good, positive response,'' said Lena
Morgan-Vega, human resources assistant at the cancer center, which
began offering the benefit about 10 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 percent of the center's 350 employees have taken
advantage of the coverage so far, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hettlinger, director of human resources at Colle &AMP; McVoy,
said his firm began offering the coverage in June, splitting annual
premium costs with employees who choose the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``About a half-dozen of our employees have signed up so far, but
I know that that's going to pick up,'' he said. ``We just
introduced it a few weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Both companies provide the coverage through Veterinary Pet
Insurance, which is based in Anaheim, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The coverage is primarily marketed through veterinary hospitals,
but pet owners can also sign up by calling toll-free at (800)
USA-PETS or enroll online at www.petinsurance.com, said Rebecca F.
Lewis, VPI's vice president of marketing and communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great features about our coverage is pet owners can
visit any vet worldwide; they can also go to vet specialists
without any pre-authorization,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As more and more pet owners are finding out that insurance is
available,'' Lewis said, ``they are taking advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   What's changed in recent years, she said, is the growing number
of employers who offer the coverage through benefits packages and
recognize the role a pet plays in a family and also the positive
effect pet ownership can have on employee morale.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to be competitive, corporations need to provide more
attractive, comprehensive benefit packages,'' said Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   That was the thinking at Colle &AMP; McVoy, said Hettlinger and Riff
Yeager, senior vice president at the integrated marketing
communications firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be a chicken-and-egg sort of thing, but we tend to
attract people who love and own pets because they know we're so
prominent in the category. Pets are near and dear to our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeager said that more than 70 percent of their employees own
pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pets are highly regarded as members of the family, and in some
instances even preferred over other members, and pet owners will go
into substantial debt to care for the health of their pets,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeager said that Colle &AMP; McVoy initially pursued Veterinary Pet
Insurance as a client. It was during talks between the companies,
he said, that the firm learned how relevant pet insurance was to
its own employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like a natural fit to sign up for it ourselves,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   VPI, which covers only cats and dogs, has more than 1 million
policyholders, including policies purchased through corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The premium is based on the pet's age and the plan selected.
Gold plan holders can insure their pet for $97 per year. Costs
start at $179 a year for the Advantage Plus plan, VPI's maximum
benefit plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two plans cover the same items,'' said Lewis. ``The only
difference is the premium and the level of reimbursement to owners.
For example, with the Gold Plan, we will pay up to $9,000 a year
and with the Advantage Plus plan, the maximum benefit is $14,000 a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The plans cover everything from accidental injury and illness to
vaccinations to routine care, skin rashes and ear infections.
</P>
<P>
   Alley recently purchased a plan for a second cat, Mia, but opted
not to cover Aja because of her age. Still the coverage, she said,
had to be purchased individually because her husband's employer
does not offer the benefit.
</P>
<P>
   If it did, she said, her family would jump at the chance to
cover their pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really important,'' said Alley. ``If you don't
have insurance, you can spend a lot of money to keep the pet
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Mia's coverage costs Alley about $11 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've only used it three time since signing up in March, but
they're really prompt in processing claims,'' said Alley. ``We've
probably saved $70 so far, but I expect to get virtually all of our
money back the first year.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
