<HEADER>
A9613 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-OPERA-RIGOLETTO-HNS &LR;      08-01 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-RIGOLETTO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
SANTA FE PRESENTS A CRAFTFUL `RIGOLETTO' &HT;    (Photos available from
http://www.santafeopera.org/PressPhotos/PressPhotos.htm.)
 &HT;    By CHARLES WARD
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ Two eras are intersecting _ seamlessly, it
appears _ at the Santa Fe Opera. That bodes well for the United
States' premier summer opera festival.
</P>
<P>
   General director John Crosby, who founded the company in 1957 in
the once serene desert hills outside the state capital, will pass
the reins to his long-groomed successor, Richard Gaddes, at the end
of the current season.
</P>
<P>
   The season is currently at its peak, with five operas playing in
repertoire through next week. They vividly illustrate the
exceptional variety that is this company's signature, from the
American premiere of Hans Werner Henze's ``Venus and Adonis'' to
Monday evening's crowd-pleasing ``Rigoletto'' of Giuseppe Verdi.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe gave Verdi's story of a court jester, his sheltered
daughter and a sex-addicted nobleman a strong new production. It
featured exquisite sets and direction by Danish designer Mikael
Melbye (cq) and first-class singing, capped by the Gilda of soprano
Elizabeth Futral.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic core of the opera is the way that a curse
insinuates itself into the mind and life of Rigoletto, jester in
the court of the Duke of Mantua.
</P>
<P>
   The Duke, a libertine par excellence, has seduced Count
Monterone's daughter. When Rigoletto mocks Monterone, the count
curses him.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Rigoletto sees evidence of the curse everywhere. Courtiers
kidnap his daughter, Gilda, believing she is his mistress, and take
her to the palace. After the Duke seduces her there, she tells her
father that, at church, she had previously met the Duke disguised
as a poor student and fallen for him.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Rigoletto seeks revenge, fate spoils his plan. He pays
Sparafucile to kill the Duke but the assassin's sister, Maddalena,
(cq) also falls under the ruler's spell. She persuades her brother
to kill someone else _ Gilda, who returns to the siblings' lair
determined to sacrifice herself for her lover.
</P>
<P>
   As a character, Rigoletto seethes. He deeply loves his daughter,
the only joy in his life, and desperately shelters her from the
Duke's lust. He grieves for his dead wife, refusing to talk about
her to Gilda. He hates the court for its disdain of the jester's
art.
</P>
<P>
   All this emotion is, of course, in the music for Verdi's first
masterpiece _ but it wasn't present in the portrayal by baritone
Kim Josephson. As with Eddie Carbone in last fall's Chicago
premiere of William Bolcom's ``A View From the Bridge,'' he created
Rigoletto through craft, not passion.
</P>
<P>
   His craft Monday was notable. He offered a handsome voice, a
richly detailed characterization and a thoroughly prepared
performance. Yet his Rigoletto never teetered on the dark edge of
blind emotion, as the character must.
</P>
<P>
   Futral's Gilda, by contrast, connected with the character's
inner life. The soprano used her light, almost silvery sound
virtuosically in ``Caro nome.'' But the famous aria was even more
memorable because Futral made Gilda's naivete and head-over-heels
love for the Duke so real.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when she emerged from the Duke's bedroom, Gilda was a
changed person _ her innocence gone, her hopes shattered. The shift
of mood was compelling, especially compared to the antiseptic ardor
of tenor Martin Thompson as the Duke.
</P>
<P>
   As Sparafucile, bass Raymond Aceto (cq) presented the
character's dark morals with the same emotional reality as Futral.
So did the evening's Maddalena, mezzo-soprano Beth Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   The last act, where the five major characters interact, was the
evening's highlight, with excellent singing and tense drama.
</P>
<P>
   Melbye's staging was consistently taut. His set, dominated by
arches and columns in a simple Italian Renaissance style, rotated
to show the court, Rigoletto's house and the street outside it, and
Sparafucile's inn. Though the playing areas were often small, he
used them well.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, conductor Richard Buckley's propulsive yet supple
accompaniment made the famous Act Three quartet _ Rigoletto, Gilda,
Maddalena, the Duke _ a top-notch ensemble piece.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the evening, the orchestra provided the musical
foundation for a fully gripping drama, no matter how familiar to
the seasoned listener. An emotionally ravaged Rigoletto might have
sparked it.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
