<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9614 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-0802-BEDRAILS-DEATHS-     08-01 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-0802-BEDRAILS-DEATHS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``DANGEROUS'' HOSPITAL BEDS LACK STANDARDS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) Lifestyle categories
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The death certificates have a grim sameness going
back a decade and a half.
</P>
<P>
   The victim, usually a woman over age 60, rolls over in a
hospital or nursing home bed and becomes entrapped in the space
between the side rail and mattress. Too frail or too disoriented to
free herself, she suffocates.
</P>
<P>
   For at least 200 people, and almost certainly many more, the
beds that were supposed to protect them turned into death traps.
Dozens more people have been seriously injured when they tried to
climb over the railings.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials, who first began to recognize the problem in the
early 1990s, have issued warnings and advisories to the nation's
health care facilities. But they have yet to establish safety
standards for the beds and railings.
</P>
<P>
   Much to the frustration of experts in the field, deaths and
injuries have continued.
</P>
<P>
   In the period between the first safety alert issued by the Food
and Drug Administration in August 1995 and late May of this year,
federal records show at least 28 deaths across the country. Florida
and Minnesota had the most, with four reported deaths each.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Consumer Product Safety commission has also recorded
dozens of injuries, including more than 30 cases during the first
five months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The actual numbers are thought to be much higher, since federal
reporting rules are laxly enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Among those that were reported, a 74-year-old woman in Sunrise,
Fla., became wedged between the bed rail and mattress and was
asphyxiated in June of last year. A 78-year-old man in Minneapolis
died after his head became trapped between the mattress and side
rail last December. And in 1997, a 29-year-old woman in Lubbock,
Texas, was found suffocated in her home after she became stuck
between the mattress and rail of a hospital-type bed.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the alarm over hospital beds and side rails is
perplexing to families of patients, said Sarah Burger, an advocate
for nursing home residents. ``There's been an acceptance that bed
rails were there for safety,'' she said. ``There's been a lot of
rethinking.''
</P>
<P>
   But not enough, according to Burger, who works with the private
National Citizens' Coalition for Nursing Home Reform. She noted
that the federal government set standards more than 25 years ago
for cribs to keep infants from trapping their heads between the
side rails.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a decade after problems surfaced for the elderly,
government agencies are still debating what to do about hospital
beds and even who bears the responsibility for them.
</P>
<P>
   Because the bed frame and rails are labeled ``medical devices,''
they are under the jurisdiction of the Food and Drug Administration
(FDA).
</P>
<P>
   However, the mattresses are often the major contributing factor
in these tragedies. Facilities often buy replacement mattresses
that are too small for the bed frames, leaving a gap where patients
can become trapped and asphyxiated. And because mattresses are not
considered to be medical devices, they fall into the domain of the
Consumer Product Safety Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating the issue, an inter-agency federal working
group was set up 15 months ago that includes FDA officials, Health
and Human Services Department officials, and private experts as
well as industry representatives. No members from the safety
commission were included.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we've mostly been focused on the bed and bed
design,'' said Joan Todd, an FDA consultant who is working with the
working group. She said that ``it is our intention'' to seek help
from the safety commission later.
</P>
<P>
   The working group has no target date for proposing new safety
standards, Todd said. She blamed the slow progress on a lack of
funding and added, ``I think they're doing a great job, because all
these people are volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   A former member was more critical. ``The FDA panel was supposed
to come out with a final report in December of last year,'' said
Dr. Steven H. Miles, a geriatrics professor at the University of
Minnesota, who is credited for being one of the first to spot the
dangers of hospital beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's eight months later, and these deaths have been occurring
for a very, very long time,'' he said. Miles, who left the panel
for an unsuccessful race for the U.S. Senate, accused manufacturers
of ``having an undue influence'' in delaying action.
</P>
<P>
   ``One would be hard pressed to identify another device that has
caused (as many) deaths where the industry has not been forced to
come up with a design modification,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Miles said many facilities are taking more precautions, but he
traced the improvement more to recent lawsuits by angry families
than to government efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Among the pioneering attorneys in this area, Jeff E. Rusk of
Austin, Texas, four years ago won a $900,000 award and promises of
reform from a New Mexico nursing home, plus $4.5 million from the
bed manufacturer, Everest &AMP; Jennings of Earth City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Rusk later reached a settlement that reduced the bed maker's
payment in exchange for a promise to send out thousands of warning
letters to customers detailing the potential dangers of using rails
for weak or confused patients and urging the use of more padding.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas attorney has also taken the case of 71-year-old Sarah
Hitz, who died at Boca Raton's Manor Care nursing home in November
of 1996. The lawsuit in Palm Beach County's Circuit Court charges
the nursing home with ``gross negligence'' for allowing her to
become trapped in her bed rails.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, brought by her son, Alexander Hitz of West Palm
Beach, cites two prior such incidents in the chain of more than 300
facilities run by HCR-Manor Care Inc. of Toledo, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokeswoman declined to comment on the case but said
that the company's current policy is to perform ``an assessment on
all patients'' and use side rails only when ordered by a physician.
</P>
<P>
   On the web: National Citizens' Coalition for Nursing Home
Reform: www.nccnhr.org
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
