<SLUG> BC-CVN-JOE-GUERRA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
JOE GUERRA LEAVES HIS GAS STATION TO LEAD THE GOP IN PLEDGE OF
ALLEGIANCE &HT;    By SUSANNA McBEE
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Joe A. Guerra, 66, of Laredo, Texas, still can't
believe it, but on Wednesday night he will lead some 22,000 people
at the Republican National Convention here in reciting the Pledge
of Allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   Guerra, a gas station operator, a city councilman and a
Republican in an overwhelmingly Democratic city on the Texas-Mexico
border, said in an interview that being chosen by his party to lead
the flag salute ``is an awesome thing for me. I've never been
before such a big crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of how Guerra, known in Laredo for his strongly held
views against big government, was chosen to lead the Pledge began
with the patriotic festivals he and his family hold each July 4 for
close friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're cookouts,'' he said. ``We sing patriotic songs, raise
the flag and give speeches about the sacrifices of the Founding
Fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerra said that Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-Texas, whose district
includes Laredo, heard about the cookouts last year and asked if he
could send a camera crew to the family's 1999 July the Fourth
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing Guerra knew, the Republican National Committee
had used the footage from the cookout in an ad ``that ran on all
major TV networks several months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The point of the ad, said Guerra, ``was to portray the party as
being more inclusive, to show that it is reaching out to
Hispanics.''
</P>
<P>
   Then party officials asked him to appear at the convention and
help open the Wednesday night session. The national committee flew
him to Philadelphia Tuesday and agreed to put him up for two nights
in a downtown hotel before he returns to Texas on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Guerra said he won't mind missing a few days of work at his
Exxon station, where he takes pride in getting car windshields
spotless and making sure the tires and oil and transmission fluid
levels are OK.
</P>
<P>
   Operating a service station wasn't his father's first choice of
a career for him.
</P>
<P>
   Guerra recalled that after he graduated from St. Mary's
University in San Antonio, his father wanted him to be a dentist.
``But I just couldn't do it,'' he said. Instead, he went into
business, supported his eight children, and saw them succeed.
``Thirty years after I graduated, my daughter Maya graduated from
St. Mary's, and now she is a dentist,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Guerra said he and his family share a number of beliefs promoted
by the Republican Party, including personal responsibility, self
reliance, and the idea that the federal government should be used
as a last, not a first, resort.
</P>
<P>
   Of his night in the GOP spotlight here, he said, ``I feel very
proud to have been chosen. I'm thrilled and excited. But it's kind
of humbling. I don't think I deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
