<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9621 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-RESTAURANT-RESTROOMS-     08-01 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANT-RESTROOMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTAURANT RESTROOMS: BEHIND THE `M' AND THE `W,' A NEW STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK MARIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To Stephen Lyle, fixing up the bathrooms at his new
restaurant, Village, was less a chore than an archaeological dig.
The chef and his aides carefully stripped and chipped away layers
of plaster and drywall to unearth the ancient subway tile, dating
from the 1920s or '30s. The phone-booth-size marble stalls were so
small that they had to be expanded in the women's room. A tiny
window in the men's room, looking down from the building's second
story onto Ninth Street, had been boarded up. They restored it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was choosing the space, one of the things that sold me
on it was these funky old bathrooms,'' said Lyle, who had been at
Odeon for many years before opening Village this summer. It is no
longer enough for bathrooms to be ``just functional.'' Like
restaurateurs all over the city, Lyle believes that bathrooms ``are
definitely a kind of definer.'' They are, he said, ``a statement
about your personality, about who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Stern, the manager at Village, offered a more basic
assessment: ``The urinals are pretty incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Polite dinner conversation now includes such observations. You
go to a new place to eat, you talk about the food, the service, the
decor . . . the bathroom. The loo experience has become as
important to the people who design restaurants in New York as
gleaming, steaming open kitchens were in the '80s. No building
material is too obscure, no plumbing detail below notice. Not
terribly long ago, a conversation pissoir was still a novelty. You
had Phillipe Starck's men's room waterfall in the Royalton. You had
Bar 89 in Soho, where the glass doors shift from transparent to
opaque _ as long as the user remembers to turn the lock.
</P>
<P>
   Now, no new restaurateur dares to opt for cheap generic tile or
unimpressively domestic fixtures. Porter's New York in Chelsea has
shoe-polishing machines. At Fun, in Chinatown, you can see what's
going on at the opposite sex's sink on a little video monitor.
Communal sinks outside the men's and women's rooms are part of the
scene at restaurants like Commune. Attendants are also back in
action, directing diners to door No. 1, 2 or 3 at Thalia,
Guastavino's and, more surprisingly, Vandam downtown _ or wearing
black tie and offering mints and towels at Shelly's New York.
</P>
<P>
   It's gotten so that a good bathroom could be an incentive to
return to a restaurant, a bad one a reason never to darken its
stalls again. The Zagat Survey's ``New York City Nightlife 2000''
guide includes a listing of ``cool loos.'' Even a Lower East Side
boite like Oliva has compact, design-conscious bathrooms: walls
done in a blue wash, oval mirrors, original tile on the floor, lily
in a vase filled with green grapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did them in blue because of the seafood,'' said Eduardo
Fontan, an owner. ``The idea was that the inside would contrast
with the outside.'' The dining room is as spare as the bathroom is
ornate.
</P>
<P>
   The food is Basque, but the woodwork on the bathroom doors has a
Moroccan flavor. Fontan, who is from Madrid, used to own a
furniture repair shop on Orchard Street, so the work was not
difficult for him. Still, when was the last time you saw custom
woodwork on a bathroom door?
</P>
<P>
   Roy Klein, the general manager of AZ in the Flatiron district,
said, ``I'm a big bathroom guy, and I think ours are pretty cool.''
They were designed by Grant Koerner of Untitled Inc. in the
building that once housed the club-restaurant Flowers. The big,
pitched skylight over the center of the dining room is echoed by a
smaller one in the bathroom. The sink is a transparent glass bowl
with metal trim. And the glass mosaic tile on the floor seems to
change color from every angle. The door is marked with a
gender-progressive ``U.''
</P>
<P>
   New York bathrooms used to be characterized by their cramped
confines and malodorous atmosphere. Larry Bogdanow, of Bogdanow
Partners Architects, traces the expanded notion of bathroom space
to the Americans With Disabilities Act. Passed a decade ago, it
requires new restaurants to provide at least one bathroom large
enough for a wheelchair's turning radius.
</P>
<P>
   ``Restaurant bathrooms were really tight 10 years ago,''
Bogdanow said. ``I find that the extra space is also useful.'' In
the women's room at the Tribeca Grand Hotel, he put a lounge with a
banquette. In both the men's and the women's rooms, the handicapped
stall contains a changing table and a sink, making it almost a
private bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most avant-garde toilettes around are at the
Brasserie. Designed by Diller &AMP; Scofidio, a firm known for
breathing only the most rarefied air of high architectural theory,
the Brasserie bathrooms were as rigorously conceptualized as the
rest of the supermodern space. The men's and women's rooms are
divided by a wall made of Panelite, a translucent plastic. But they
share a sink, an amber-hued, cast-resin trough that runs through
the wall. On the mirror above the sink in the men's room it says,
``WASHISTOPURGEISTODENYIS-TOWASHIS.'' The women's side has a
similar message.
</P>
<P>
   You might think that ``purge'' is not a desirable word to
display above a sink in a New York bathroom. But Liz Diller, one of
the partners of the firm, explained the thinking: ``It has to do
with different aspects of cleaning oneself,'' she said. ``And the
relationship between sin and dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   How much time did she and her colleagues spend worrying about
the bathroom? ``A lot,'' Diller said. ``It's one of the most
potentially interesting spaces in any kind of public space. There
is all kinds of shame associated with bathrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   David Rockwell, never shy about calling attention to his
restaurant designs, thinks of himself as a pioneer in the bathroom
department. His most recent creation is New York Strip, a
steakhouse opening next week where Asti used to be, at 13 E. 12th
St. Previously, the room's major decor feature had been 8-by-10
glossies of opera singers. Many of them will survive, but the
overall look has been revised to Euro bordello.
</P>
<P>
   In the conference room of his Union Square offices, Rockwell
showed off the materials used in the bathroom: red glazed subway
tile, red glass balls for the sconces, shaded with red
leopard-print fabric.
</P>
<P>
   There was also a black-and-white photograph of a naked woman,
who did not resemble an opera singer. Rockwell said mildly naughty
pictures like it would adorn the stalls in both men's and women's
rooms. He promised that their subjects were authentic French and
German women from the 1930s and '40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to have one or two memorable things in the
bathrooms,'' Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is that diners notice these things during their rest
stops. Laureen Barber designed Blue Hill, the small ground-level
restaurant on Washington Place, for her brother-in-law, Dan Barber,
the chef. She is a graphic designer, and this was her first
restaurant. She was surprised to find that ``when people heard I
was doing Blue Hill, all they wanted to talk about was the
bathrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the overall design, the unisex bathroom is a
haven of warm, dark tones, with one deep red wall and a greenish
slate countertop, on top of which sit two low-wattage lamps and a
few candles deployed to achieve maximum flattery.
</P>
<P>
   Practical concerns have been dealt with, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 comment was that the wastebasket should be in close
proximity to the door,'' Ms. Barber said. That was from the women.
Men, she said, wanted a hook for their jackets.
</P>
<P>
   The wastebasket-by-the-door thing is a hygiene issue. Some
diners evidently want to be able to turn the door handle with the
towel, then do the germ-phobe's version of a slam dunk, tossing the
prophylactic paper or cloth on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   Hygiene is also Shelly Fireman's reason for having attendants in
his large, busy restaurants. At Shelly's New York, which replaced
the Motown Cafe on 57th Street, men and women he calls bathroom
valets solicitously offer towels, mints and combs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a believer in pathologically clean bathrooms,'' Fireman
said. ``I don't know any other way.''
</P>
<P>
   What kind of response does he get to his omnipresent valets?
``It's a subliminal response,'' he said. ``Nobody finishes a meal
and says: `Wow! You've got a great bathroom!'''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they do now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
