<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9623 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-GAMER0802-COX     08-01 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMER0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Screenshot from Earth 2150
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   The one-dimension charm of Armorines: Project S.W.A.R.M ($30;
www.armorines .net; for the PlayStation) is this: Kill 'em all.
You're a soldier, soldier, and bugs are the bad, bad enemy. When
they come at you, blast them. First-person shooters live and die by
the level of adrenaline they deliver, and this one is just
unpardonably dull. If the model for the game was the film
``Starship Troopers,'' Acclaim failed to notice that things get
more interesting when you're battling hundreds or thousands of bugs
rather than two or three. The graphics are pretty crummy, too.
</P>
<P>
   Playing the role of a hero who roams a magical fairyland in
search of artifacts that enable him to rebuild an entire world from
scratch is not as easy as it sounds. In Legend of Mana ($50;
www.squaresoft.com; for the PlayStation), the sequel to Secret of
Mana, the feat is almost impossible unless you have all afternoon
to get set up. Then, and only then, does the game become even
mildly coherent. Persist and soon enough you'll find yourself
enthralled, travelling from land to land, fighting monsters,
collecting goodies, conversing with strange creatures. The graphics
are strikingly beautiful and make up for the mind-bending drone of
repetitive scene-based theme music. All in all, if you have plenty
of time and an open mind, Legend of Mana will keep you pleasantly
occupied.
</P>
<P>
   Atmospheric, gorgeous and dense almost to a fault, SquareSoft's
Vagrant Story; for the PlayStation), is an RPG fan's dream _
``Final Fantasy'' devotees won't play this one so much as inhale
it. There's ample action amid all the skullduggery and deception in
this medieval tale and you, lucky boy or girl, get to target
specific body parts when facing opponents. Climbing a fairly steep
learning curve is rewarded by plenty of replayability _ you can't
even get into all areas in the game unless you've run through the
whole thing several times.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   An epic Real Time Strategy game that sold like hotcakes in
Germany, Earth 2150 ($40; www.mattel.com; for the PC) comes to
North America with a bang. Boasting superior graphics and sound, as
well as intricate but flowing ``all-terrain'' gameplay with an
eight-person online multiplayer component, even those not fond of
meticulous resource-hoarding and management of traditional RTS
games can get sucked into this one. A global warfare premise
ranging across air, land and sea _ plus the ability to take the
fight underground with an innovative ``subterranean warfare''
feature _ makes Earth 2150 a thing of vision and scope. The
``potentially'' possible scenario offers insanely aggressive
science fiction elements blended with traditional war machine
mobilization (robots and ray guns, tanks and helicopters). This is
Armageddon-is-nigh-so-let's-move-to-Mars gaming at its finest.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
