<SLUG> BC-TECH-HOMEGEAR0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New iMac edition is truly Special
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Bearing in mind that Apple veritably coined the
phrase ``user friendly,'' it follows that the iMac DV Special
Edition (SE) ($1,500; www.apple.com) offers everyperson home
computing at its finest. Bundled with an easy, yet detailed
tutorial and a formidable suite of basic computing tools (Internet
browser, e-mail, desktop publishing, graphics editing), the iMac DV
SE's crowning feature is it DVD-ROM drive and the immensely popular
iMovie software, a video editing/moviemaking application for the
home movie enthusiast. Complete with trademark ``FireWire,''
digital video transfer hardware normally sold separately (and at
notable cost) for Windows-based PCs, the SE is a forward-thinking
computer in that it does not accommodate analog video, the more
familiar camcorder format fast on its way to becoming obsolete.
iMacs are inherently less expandable than PCs, though more
adaptable in these later incarnations, yet with specific users and
hobbyists tackling specific home computer tasks, the iMac DV SE is
just what a great many new-to-the-modern-era folks are looking for:
scaled down, professional-caliber computing that brings the
``friendliness'' back to user-friendly personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S HIP TO BE FLAT
</P>
<P>
   I've been using the new IBM T54 flat panel monitor ($979;
www.ibm.com) for the past two months and it's going to be hard to
give it up. The color quality is so close to a conventional, boxy
monitor that I often forget the thing is only two inches thick.
Most impressive, the color is just as vibrant when viewed from an
angle. IBM says it consumes less power, generates less heat and
produces fewer magnetic emissions than a standard monitor. It also
takes up far less space. All of those tangible benefits
notwithstanding, the biggest reason I like the 15-inch T54, the
least expensive of IBM's new flat panel line, is that it simply
looks cool. It's entirely black, with sharp edges and a sleek
stand. But you've still got to pay more to be techno-hip. The price
may make it tempting for some (retail prices of flat panels are
finally dipping below $1,000 this year), but it's still a little
too rich for my blood. I can probably stand to cope with my boxy,
if decidedly 1990s-looking, monitor, for a little while longer.
</P>
<P>
   BARBECUER'S DECK HAND
</P>
<P>
   Does your grill drool grease or sputter sparks? At one time or
another most grills become the source of a deck-top mess. Instead
of pressure washing wood or stone after every cookout, why not buy
a bib for the barbie? The ``Original'' Grill Pad ($25 to $40
depending on size; www.diversitech.com) is little more than a pad
of thick, felt-like material coated in colored concrete. But it's
big enough (30-by-42-inch rectangles or 30-inch rounds) to protect
the deck and can be cleaned off with a shot from the garden hose.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
