<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-AMERICAN-REVIEW-NY     08-01 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AMERICAN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN HIGH': GENUINE, UNENHANCED TEEN-AGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Broadcast notes appear at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their puppyish faces alone are enough to show that the students
in ``American High'' are not actors. In television dramas the
supposed teenagers (especially the boys) have the chiseled features
of professional actors in their 20s, a fact conspicuous everywhere
from ``Dawson's Creek'' to the summer series ``Young Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   But in ``American High,'' the 14 seniors who were filmed
throughout their last year of high school have the
out-of-proportion features of adolescents. It's not baby fat we're
seeing but the soft, unformed look of people who have not quite
grown into their faces.
</P>
<P>
   That is only part of what makes this documentary series the
least contrived and most realistic of reality programs. When camera
crews weren't following the students, their self-made video diaries
took over (the two forms blend fluently on screen). These
middle-class suburban students, from Highland Park High outside
Chicago, were not dealing with explosive issues of crime or
survival but with the inner turmoil of working out relationships
and getting into college. ``American High'' is serious, expertly
crafted, often poignant, yet disappointingly predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Its flatness may be the most illuminating aspect of all: on the
realistic side, it demonstrates that we already know a lot about
the inner lives of teenagers; on the dramatic side, it suggests how
expectations have been shaped and inflated by movies and series
targeted at teenagers and by other so-called reality shows.
</P>
<P>
   The series was made by R.J. Cutler, a producer of ``The War
Room,'' about behind-the-scenes maneuvers in the 1992 Clinton
presidential campaign, and a co-director of ``A Perfect
Candidate,'' about Oliver L. North's campaign for the Senate. In
theory the same pulling-back-the-curtain aspect should inform
``American High,'' but there is not much to surprise teenagers or
their parents here.
</P>
<P>
   These students are self-aware and articulate as they confront
their typical problems. Robby and Sarah have been dating for two
years, and she is terrified of what will happen when he goes away
to college. With a poignant mix of self-awareness and naivete, she
says, ``I'm scared for myself 'cause I'm a kid still. I've just
turned 17 and I've already found the love of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   In a couple of scenes she and Robby lie on a bed (clothed), in
intimate yet hardly shocking moments. In this high school version
of pillow talk, they discuss his going away. ``I'll have to teach
you how to do laundry,'' she says. In the most dramatic scene,
Robby's friend Brad reveals that he is gay. Robby is surprised,
though quickly accepting. Brad is later seen at a group meeting for
gay and lesbian students. These are not trivial issues, but in our
confessional culture they are familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, the most outrageous of the students, begins the series
with a rant to the camera (with one word bleeped out): ``These are
the years when you're supposed to be wild, blame it all on your
parents or society, not have to suffer consequences, have
unprotected sex, go do drugs, smoke cigarettes, drink alcohol.''
His mother interrupts to tell him to quiet down, but he goes on:
``These are your teen years but what are you sitting at home having
to do? Homework.''
</P>
<P>
   The raucous, attention-seeking opening does not truly set the
series' tone. By the end of Wednesday night's two back-to-back
episodes, Morgan has gotten a part-time job helping to coach
gymnastics for disabled young people. He thinks he may want to
teach them as a career.
</P>
<P>
   No one would wish him to be more self-destructive, but it would
have made a livelier story. That's what we have come to expect from
both fiction and reality shows. ``Dawson's Creek'' has included an
ex-convict, drug-dealing father; the entertaining ``Young
Americans'' is even more melodramatic. (Now halfway through its
eight-week summer run, it will be shown Wednesday night at 9 on WB,
directly competing against ``American High.'') The setting is an
exclusive boys' school near a working-class New England town. In
the first episode, the rich, handsome and preposterously named
Scout Calhoun (Mark Famiglietti) falls for the local girl who works
at the gas station, Bella Banks (Kate Bosworth), only to find that
she is his father's illegitimate daughter. That puts a nasty crimp
in the romance. As Scout's roommate wryly says, ``It's socially
unacceptable to date your sister.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oedipal tangle makes the major subplot seem tame: a girl
masquerades as a boy to enroll at Rawley Boys' Academy. ``Young
Americans'' is fun in a soapy way, but it has struggled in the
ratings. Maybe viewers want a bit more attachment to reality than
this.
</P>
<P>
   But they don't want a lack of drama. MTV's flourishing ``Real
World'' may feature real-life players, yet they are cast by the
show's producers and placed in a situation _ living and working
together _ contrived for maximum volatility. It's not quite the
real world; it's reality enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   In this summer overloaded with shows that turn fake ``reality''
into a game, from the insanely popular physical challenges on
``Survivor'' to the already annoying mind games on ``Big Brother,''
``American High'' is more genuine. But that is not enough to make
it scintillating. The show may inadvertently point out that
pseudorealism and explosive emotions are the kind of escapist
entertainment viewers really want.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN HIGH'
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday at 9 p.m. on Fox &QL; 
Created, produced and directed by R.J. Cutler. Dan Partland,
supervising producer; Ted Skillman, coordinating producer. Produced
by Actual Reality Pictures in association with 20th Century Fox
Television. Cutler, Erwin More, Brian Medavoy and Cheryl Stanley,
executive producers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
