<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9631 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JEWISH-TV-$ADV06-NYT &LR;      08-01 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWISH-TV-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S A TALMUDIST DOING IN A PLACE LIKE THIS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 6)  
 By FRANZ LIDZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's a scene in Barry Levinson's 1987 film ``Tin
Men'' in which a bunch of aluminum-siding schleppers sit around a
diner, ``Broadway Danny Rose''-style, talking television westerns.
One salesman complains that ``Bonanza'' is not an accurate
depiction of the Old West.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ever see the show?'' he asks. ``It's a 50-year-old father
and three 47-year-old sons. You know why they get along so good?
'Cause they're all the same age.''
</P>
<P>
   A second salesman demurs. ``I'm not an authority like you are,''
he grumbles, ``but I occasionally watch `Bonanza' and I think it's,
like, how can you believe there's a man who got three kids by three
different wives and they all died at childbirth?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Musta been a hell of a man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Musta been the kiss of death.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't get much breakfast-booth banter in the four Hebrew
horse operas being screened Tuesday night at the Jewish Museum in
Manhattan. Billed as ``Wild Wild West: The Jewish Experience,'' the
program comprises hourlong TV oaters with Jewish themes, including
a 1963 episode of the historically dubious ``Bonanza.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want audiences to look critically at the way Jewish
ethnicity has been represented on TV,'' said Andrew Ingall, the
museum's broadcasting archivist. ``The Jewish characters on these
shows are basically stereotypes. But then, all four teleplays are
products of their time.''
</P>
<P>
   Though these gunfights at the Oy Vey Corral address every
nonsecular issue from anti-Semitism (``Gunsmoke'') to intermarriage
(``Little House on the Prairie''), their leaden lyricism (``She
awaits us, our farm, like the Sabbath bride, scented and
anointed'') is leavened by very little Jewish humor.
</P>
<P>
   You hope the episode of ``Gunsmoke'' will show Marshal Dillon
conducting a Seder in the Dodge City jail, or Doc performing a
barroom bris, or Kitty getting bat mitzvahed in the Long Branch
Saloon. What you get is a stilted story line about the clash
between frontier justice and Talmudic law, which makes no
allowances for circumstantial evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Marshal Dillon (incredulously): Three men are running around
loose that murdered your boy and you're standing here playing with
words?
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Gorofsky (pedagogically): Words! Some we live by, and some
we must die for.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the Jewish TV families facing these problems is ruled by
a bearded Yiddisher with an accent as thick as pumpernickel and
syntax as twisted as kugel noodles. ``A man tell me the ground in
Dakota is black like swamp and fat like grease and there are no
bosses,'' says Papa Kleinfeld in a 1954 Philco Television Playhouse
production. ``There are not enough people for there to have
bosses.''
</P>
<P>
   Each patriarch is a stern, intractable scholar who knows God on
a first-name basis. ``He's a wise sage trying to preserve Jewish
values _ honesty, devotion, compassion _ while surrounded by
immoral outlaws,'' observes the comic Jackie Mason, an expert on
Jewish Westerns by virtue of numerous appearances on ``The Ed
Sullivan Show,'' a CBS neighbor of ``Gunsmoke.'' ``Today, it would
be like an Old World rabbi arguing with Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   These Jewish fathers have brought their familes to the New West
to escape the pogroms and harassment of the Old East. Exodus
parallels are drawn so freely, you feel like you're in a Leon Uris
novel. The Philco Playhouse narrator intones: ``Papa led us out of
Chicago like Moses freeing the children of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   As with Moses, a little blood is spilled _ in this case, Papa's.
Shamed by his wife's reluctance to assimilate with other
``greenhorns'' of the 1850s, Papa Kleinfeld stomps out of the
homestead and beds down on the plains, where he promptly burns to
death in a brush fire.
</P>
<P>
   What Papa's hard work didn't accomplish, his sacrifice does.
Mama embraces the idea of 1950s ecumenicalism and holds a prairie
Passover service. Among the guests are a Norwegian and a Native
American in full headdress _ a sight only slightly less incongruous
than the appearance of a Yiddish-speaking Indian chief in Mel
Brook's ``Blazing Saddles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After World War II, multiculturalism was valued by the liberal
Jewish community,'' Ingall said. ``Jews wanted to participate in
the same rituals with some boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonanzologists still debate the boundaries of the Ponderosa,
though most agree Ben Cartwright's ranch must have been roughly the
size of Mesopotamia. In the episode under consideration, the
traveling salesman Aaron Kaufman and his Jewish mother of a
daughter camp at the spread for the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Papa, you always do nothing,'' scolds his daughter. ``The
world spills scalding hot soup all over you, and you stick out your
tongue and lick it and say, `Thank you.'''
</P>
<P>
   When the wandering Jews are held up by outlaws, Papa holds his
tongue. Defying his Old Testament teachings, he becomes a kind of
Billy the Kibbitzer, popping off the bandits as easily as if he
were shooting lox in a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got 'em both, Kaufman,'' Adam Cartwright says. ``That's
pretty good shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good shooting?'' says the angst-ridden peddler. ``I killed two
men!''
</P>
<P>
   No such moral qualms afflict the avenging farm boy Richard
Dreyfuss played a decade later on ``Gunsmoke.'' Gershon Gorofsky
confronts his brother's killers with a shotgun and threatens to
blow them away. ``The show was filmed shortly after Israel won the
Six Day War,'' Ingall said. ``Dreyfuss' feisty farmer reflected the
New Jew _ the young, macho Israeli filled with ethnic pride and
willing to take the law into his own hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason does not argue this point. He does dispute the farmer
part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jews in the Wild West did not generally own farms or
ranches,'' he contends. ``Jews have never been into that line of
work. OK, so there used to be some Jewish chicken farmers in
Jersey. Maybe because they didn't have to lift nothin' heavy or get
dirty. But very seldom did you see Jewish ranchers or Jewish
cowboys. It was almost always a Gentile riding the horse or poking
the cow or flying from the trees. As soon as a Jew got dirt on
himself, he sold the ranch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9633 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MODERN-DESIGN-$ADV06-     08-01 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODERN-DESIGN-$ADV06-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW MODERN DESIGN REMAINS FAITHFUL TO ITS CONTEXT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 6)  
 By   HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  NEW YORK _ In the absence of alternatives, there may be no more
important project under way in New York right now than David
Childs' restoration of Lever House, the International Style
skyscraper on Park Avenue at 54th Street. Designed by Gordon
Bunshaft and completed in 1952, Lever House was the first glass
curtain wall tower to rise in New York. It remains among the 20th
century's major landmarks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lever House established Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill as the most
progressive firm in the postwar United States. Along with the
Seagram Building, the Guggenheim Museum, the CBS Building and the
United Nations headquarters, it helped make New York the leading
city for architectural innovation in those years. Childs became
chairman of SOM in 1990. His homage to Bunshaft is no mere
sentimental journey. The restoration, due for completion this fall,
is uncovering qualities that are becoming valued in architecture
once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uncommon Ground,'' a book by Thomas Leatherbarrow, should help
admirers of modern architecture to form a more precisely analytic
appreciation of those qualities. Leatherbarrow, a professor of
architecture at the University of Pennsylvania, also provides a key
for interpreting contemporary work, including recent projects by
Childs, Rafael Vinoly and Peter Eisenman.
</P>
<P>
   The book, due in October from M.I.T. Press, is a revisionist
work. It corrects the distorted view that modern architects were
insensitive to the physical context of their buildings. Focusing on
projects by Richard Neutra and two less well-known figures, Antonin
Raymond and Aris Konstantinidis, Leatherbarrow shows that
modernists did not regard building sites simply as blank slates for
inscribing their fantasies of a uniform, technological society.
</P>
<P>
   Further, he contests the notion that modern architects were
latter-day Vandals, intent on shattering the cultural continuity of
regional and urban life. Rather, the best of them adapted
industrial building techniques to the lay of the land. Modern
design mediated between prefabricated construction and local
topography. It reconciled the homogenizing nature of modernity with
regional differences. Its aim was to prevent the shattering of
continuity in the industrialized world, not to accelerate it.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Frank Lloyd Wright and Luis Barragan were not
the only architects who took landscape into account. Architects
like Neutra regarded the city as an evolving topography in which
landscape and successive layers of built form intersected over
time.
</P>
<P>
   But why use past tense? The International Research Institute for
Climate Prediction at Columbia University's Lamont-Doherty Earth
Observatory, completed earlier this year, perfectly illustrates
Leatherbarrow's ideas. Designed by Vinoly, the institute is the
most sensitively sited building I've visited since Tod Williams and
Billie Tsien's Neurosciences Institute in La Jolla, Calif. Both are
science buildings. Both command impressive natural, partially
urbanized sites. Both embody a conception of science as the culture
of nature.
</P>
<P>
   Vinoly's project is in Palisades, N.Y., on a cliff-top site on
the west side of the Hudson. The institute's design is as serenely
elegant as its name is clunky. Almost Wrightian in its relationship
to the landscape, the institute is composed of two arc-shaped wings
that overlap at the center, forming a double-width lobby area at
the building's entrance. The roof is also designed as two pairs of
overlapping arcs. A clerestory between the arcs illuminates the
corridor that bisects the full length of the building's interior.
</P>
<P>
   Leatherbarrow writes that the modern relationship between
construction and topography is best seen in section (a cutaway
drawing), rather than in plan (from above) or elevation (from
outside). The institute's central corridor offers a walk through
this idea. The ground on which the building sits slopes gradually
down toward the north. The land has not been leveled off. This is
translated into the interior by flights of steps that break the
corridor into segments.
</P>
<P>
   Materials and exposed structure further integrate construction
and site. The corridor runs beneath an arcade of wood bow trusses
that support the roof and create an outside-in impression of trees.
Internal office windows, facing into the corridor, pull light and
views into the core. Bearing walls are made from the same local
stone that erupts in boulders from the ground outside. The arcs of
the wings and the metal roof echo contours of land and water.
</P>
<P>
   According to Leatherbarrow, the conflict between technological
progress and cultural continuity exists only in theory, not in the
real world of architecture. Vinoly's building proves the point. The
Palisades were formed 200 million years ago. One of the functions
of the climate research institute is to monitor the global warming
that could result in their submersion. Try that on for continuity.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, in a review of Peter Eisenman's design for
the Staten Island Institute of Arts and Sciences, I wrote that
Eisenman's buildings should be seen as links between the history of
places and the history of ideas. At the site of a recent design for
a hotel on the Friedrichstrasse in Berlin, these two histories
already run closely parallel. The Hotel am Spree Dreieck is a
homage to two unbuilt Berlin projects designed by Mies van der Rohe
in 1921 and 1922. The two projects were Mies' first explorations of
the glass tower, a type that culminated in the completion of the
Seagram Building 37 years later. Eisenman's plan, situated on the
exact spot of Mies' 1921 project (no site was designated for the
1922 project), takes the International Style tower back to its
Expressionist roots.
</P>
<P>
   In 1921, Mies had yet to rationally integrate steel construction
into his skyscraper aesthetic. His Berlin towers were as much
Expressionist as they were modern. Eisenman has essentially
reversed the course of Mies' later development. His design uses a
scientific technique to arrive at an Expressionist result. The
design was generated by computer. Mies' two Berlin designs were
loaded into the software and morphed into a single, composite
structure.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel combines the three-pointed star configuration of Mies'
1921 ground plan with the biomorphic contours of his 1922 scheme.
The result is indescribably sexy. As with Mies' projects, the
hotel's most prominent feature is the floor planes, stacked one
above the other like a theatrical multiplex of urban stages. It's
peek-a-boo time, not only for the hotel guests, but also for Berlin
and for Mies, its greatest 20th-century architect. The irrational
within the rationalist stands exposed. Eisenman's siteis the
history of modern architecture and of the role Berlin played in it
before Hitler came to power. (MORE)
</P>
<P>
   The most conspicuous feature of the Lever House restoration is
the repair of the glass curtain wall. The spandrel glass,
originally a uniform green, had become a random two-tone mix. But
the restoration should also open our eyes to the fact that
Bunshaft's design involved more than wrapping a pretty skin around
some steel and concrete. The building's importance lies with the
integral relationship between skin, structure and site. At Lever
House, skin and section are one.
</P>
<P>
   The stretch of International Style towers along Park Avenue
south of 59th Street has been criticized for destroying Park
Avenue's sense of place. Precisely the opposite is true. The towers
revealed a deeper sense of place than the masonry buildings that
preceded them. Park Avenue is a feat of engineering: a viaduct for
cars suspended over the train tracks that run beneath. The machine
aesthetic of the towers raises this infrastructural dimension above
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The exposed columns of Lever House punch through the thin crust
of sidewalk and convey the impression of stilts straddling the
subterranean tracks. The window mullions extend that vertical
thrust to the skyline. The tower's floating base and stacked floor
planes reveal that New York is a horizontal as well as a vertical
city. Each floor replicates the slice of ground beneath it.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the advantage it takes of sunlight, Lever House does
not reflect the natural topography of Manhattan. Rather, the design
adapts construction to the artificial topography of a city that has
evolved over time. Lever House itself is part of the city's
accretive nature. So is its restoration. Half a century after its
completion, we see the building with fresh eyes.
</P>
<P>
   When new, Lever House was received as a sign of progress,
socially and aesthetically. Office workers benefited from the
natural light and the clear, open spaces. The city gained from
being among the first to realize the utopian ideal visualized by
Mies and other modernists. These qualities are still evident. But
they are enriched by our awareness of a psychological dimension
underlying the modern forms. Park Avenue is a CAT scan of New
York's collective brain: our ambition, our exhibitionism, our
compulsion to build platforms for our ideas. The city is more
upfront about these urges than it was 50 years ago. In that sense,
Lever House can stand for progress still.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
