<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-MEDIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIANS BUZZ OVER POSSIBLE SHIFT TO LEFT IN NEWSPAPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ A new media colossus rose north of the
border this week as Israel ``Izzy'' Asper _ a Manitoba entrepreneur
who already controls a hefty percentage of Canada's television and
radio stations _ acquired most of the country's leading newspapers
from Conrad Black, the Canadian-born, British-based press baron.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.3 billion takeover, the biggest media deal in Canadian
history, leaves Asper's CanWest Global Communications Corp., in
control of 148 newspapers from St. John's, Newfoundland, to
Victoria, British Columbia, including 13 high-profile dailies such
as the Ottawa Citizen, Montreal Gazette and Vancouver Sun.
Moreover, Asper and Black will split control of Black's Canadian
flagship, the Toronto-based National Post.
</P>
<P>
   The deal hatched between two of Canada's most colorful and
ideologically contrasting moguls leaves Asper in control the
country's biggest multimedia empire, one marrying Black's
newspapers, trade magazines and Internet companies to Asper's slew
of broadcast outlets, telecommunications outfits and entertainment
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``CanWest has all but cornered the market on the gathering and
dissemination of news in this country,'' Christopher Dornan,
director of the Carleton University School of Journalism and
Communication in Ottawa, wrote in the Globe and Mail newspaper, one
of the very few front-rank Canadian papers left without ties to
Black or CanWest.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction was seen by financial analysts as the first step
by Black's company, Hollinger Inc., to sell nearly all of its 350
newspapers across North America to boost its dormant stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   But the buzz across Canada Tuesday focused less on the
long-range implications of the megamerger of print, broadcast,
entertainment, and cyberspace media than on the outsized
personalities at the heart of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Asper and Black are Canada's two most flamboyantly recognizable
media tycoons, and both are passionate aficionados of politics with
nearly opposite views. So it seemed a strange twist that the
takeover deal stipulates that Asper and Black's Hollinger Inc. will
share control of the National Post, launched only in 1998 yet
already one of Canada's most influential newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Asper, 67, is a brash, chain-smoking jazz lover who grew up in a
community of Russian Jewish immigrants in Manitoba and whose first
job was scraping gum from under the seats of his father's movie
theater. He's known for his left-of-center political views as well
as an almost eccentric devotion to his home city of Winnipeg. He's
kept CanWest based in the gritty, much-faded former railroad hub
while nearly every other major Canadian corporation maintains head
offices in Toronto, Montreal, Calgary or Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Black, 56, raised a child of privilege in an English-speaking
enclave of Montreal, is an urbane Anglophile who makes his home in
London, hangs out with Margaret Thatcher and William F. Buckley,
rules his print fiefdoms from a chair that once belonged to his
greatest hero, Napoleon, and has never hestitated to use his
newspapers to flog his conservative views.
</P>
<P>
   If the upstart National Post _ Black's proudest creation _ has
gained a reputation for aggressive reporting, sleek design and
stylish writing, it is even better known as the nation's most
prominent trumpet of the political right.
</P>
<P>
   Sparring over the Post's future editorial stands seemed to start
almost instantly, with Asper pointedly telling a news conference
Tuesday that the newspaper will express ``a balanced point of view
on issues.''
</P>
<P>
   For some journalists, the departure of Black comes as a relief.
``The heavy hand of Conrad Black will not be felt as much as it has
over the years,'' said Alexander Norris, a veteran reporter with
the Montreal Gazette.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the surprise takeover appeared to signal the end of
an era in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Along with archrival Rupert Murdoch, Black is the last of the
old-style press barons whose newspapers were inseparable from their
own swaggering personalities. Inspired by a biography of William
Randolph Hearst, Black purchased a stake in a tiny Quebec newspaper
after being expelled from university in the early 1960s, and has
since stuck to newspapering _ obviously relishing the power and
punch of controlling his own presses.
</P>
<P>
   Asper is undoubtedly a character, but his corporation, CanWest,
is basically just another colorless media conglomerate and it's
certain that he sees newspapers as just another product, not a
passion. The main focus of the company will remain television and
radio; it controls dozens of stations not just in Canada but in
Ireland, Australia and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Black will retain newspapers around the world, including the
London's Daily Telegraph, the Jerusalem Post and the Chicago
Sun-Times. But the sell-off to Asper represents a dramatic
eclipsing of his empire.
</P>
<P>
   While Asper and his son, Leonard Asper, president and chief
executive officer of CanWest, held jubilant news conferences, Black
uncharacteristically disappeared from public view _ on vacation,
according to a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   His only public thoughts, so far, on the deal were expressed in
an interview with the National Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it a retreat, but it is substantially a
departure,'' Black told the paper. ``We have said for a long time
we had an overexposure in Canada. You'll hear less of me, but I am
not leaving and I will not go completely silent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
