<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S SOFTBANK CANCELS PLAN TO SELL SHARES IN 5 SUBSIDIARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Softbank Corp., one of the world's largest investors in
Internet start-up companies, abandoned a plan Tuesday to sell
shares in five of its subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Softbank said it made the decision because of potentially costly
tax consequences from such sales. But there was speculation that
Softbank abandoned the plan partly because its own share price has
fallen more than 70 percent this year, and that a spinoff might
have made the company even less attractive to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The plan had been criticized by investors and analysts, who
argued that it would further muddy Softbank's accounting, confuse
investors and create conflicts of interest between the company and
the subsidiaries. ``I think they realized they were going to have
trouble selling these companies, especially for the price they were
looking for,'' said Thomas Rhodes, an Internet analyst at Nikko
Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   The subsidiaries are basically clusters of Softbank investments
in electronic commerce, publishing, online financial services and
software.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation was that Softbank had intended to use the proceeds
of the sale to finance its portion of the purchase of Nippon Credit
Bank, an insolvent bank taken over by the government during the
height of the Japanese financial crisis of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Softbank, together with Orix Corp. and Tokio Marine &AMP; Fire
Insurance Co., plans to spend 80 billion yen, or $730.6 million at
current exchange rates, for an 80 percent stake in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Softbank must sell some piece of its Internet empire, which
spans investments in 400 companies, to finance its part of the
purchase. Largely a giant venture capital fund, it has almost no
revenue. In the past, it has sold bits of investments in Yahoo,
Trend Micro and Softbank Technology to raise money to finance its
operations and make further investments.
</P>
<P>
   The bank deal has come under heavy criticism from politicians,
who object to what they consider overly favorable terms for the
buyers. Last week, the government postponed the sale of the bank,
which was to have been concluded Tuesday, by one month in hopes of
increasing political and public support. Softbank and its partners
had threatened to walk away if the government tried to renegotiate
the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Hideyuki Aizawa, the newly appointed head of the
Financial Reconstruction Commission, the agency responsible for
overhauling the banking system, said the deal would go through as
originally planned. ``It's better to keep the existing policy
toward the NCB deal,'' he said. ``We basically won't change the
contract.''
</P>
<P>
   His comment may have contributed to the first rise in the
benchmark Nikkei stock index in five sessions. Investors have been
worried that the Japanese government has lost its appetite for
financial reform, but Aizawa's commitment to completing the sale of
Nippon Credit Bank under the original terms, despite his personal
objections to allowing companies other than banks into the banking
industry, seemed aimed at alleviating those concerns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1740EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9645 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-DREAMHOUSE-900(2Takes     08-01 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAMHOUSE-900(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAZZLING FORT WORTH HOME WITH A HOLLYWOOD PAST IS UP FOR SALE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By GAILE ROBINSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The long, low, white house on Ridgehaven
Road stretches out along the property like a Matisse odalisque.
There is no overt recognition of the street, no porch, 2-story
front door or flowered sidewalk. Yet, there is something special
about this house. It is different from the neighbors', more
glamorous, more secretive.
</P>
<P>
   The house has a history that features William Haines, the
notorious Hollywood designer, actress Joan Crawford and the Kimbell
Art Museum. It is a beautiful example of mid-20th century
architecture. The street facade only hints at the glories that can
be seen from the 15th green of the Ridglea Country Club golf
course.
</P>
<P>
   Polly Scheneker is the reason this houses exists.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Edmund, built it in 1952, but it was Polly
who had the vision and the Hollywood connections. During the
Depression, Polly came to Texas from California, where she had been
the private secretary for Laura La Plante, one of the goddesses of
the silent screen. Polly was friends with many in the film colony,
and she ran with the fast crowd.
</P>
<P>
   After Edmund made his fortune in oil transportation, it came
time to build Polly's dream house. She called on Haines, a friend
from her Hollywood days, and together with Fort Worth architect
Jack Schutts, they created the sleek contemporary house.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thought about building that house for a long time. She
knew what she wanted,'' says Schutts, who was fresh out of the Army
and architecture school at the University of Texas. Polly's house
``was one of the first things I ever did.'' Now he is a principal
at the Fort Worth-based firm Schutts Magee and Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Haines, though, had been around. He was a silent film star.
</P>
<P>
   In 1929, he was the major money-making star for MGM, and one of
the few who could insist that his name precede the movie's title.
By 1931, Louis B. Mayer, coming under increased pressure from
critics, was tightening the reins on his sexually wayward stars.
Haines, who was openly gay, was always in Mayer's sights. In 1933,
Mayer began issuing ultimatums: If Haines didn't give up his
significant other, Jimmy Shields, Mayer would terminate his
contract. Haines, who refused to play the Hollywood game of
arranged marriages and publicity dating, said no. His career as a
star was over, but his relationship with Shields lasted 47 years
until Haines' death in 1973. Shields passed away soon after in
1974.
</P>
<P>
   Haines was not schooled in interior design, but he had an innate
sense of style, a luxurious, exclusive, expensive one. When roles
ceased to come his way, his former leading ladies began
commissioning him to do their homes. Joan Crawford was one of the
first. Constance Bennett, Claudette Colbert and Carole Lombard
became clients. So did director George Cukor and studio head Jack
Warner.
</P>
<P>
   The Haines look was eclectic. He liked combining European
antiques and chinoiserie, pale colors and leather walls. He was the
first designer to champion the placement of telephones in
bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   He found the trick to pleasing actors was to place mirrors
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   He was also cruel. He put bad lighting in the dressing areas.
Crawford would fix her hair and makeup under ghoulish lighting
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Haines said, ``I told her if she can make herself look good in
that light, she'll look good anywhere,'' reports William J. Mann,
author of ``Wisecracker; The Life and Time of William Haines,
Hollywood's First Openly Gay Star.''
</P>
<P>
   By the 1950s, when Polly Scheneker imported Haines to Fort
Worth, Haines' sphere of influence had moved beyond the film
community, and he was coaching Betsy Bloomingdale and Nancy Reagan
in the niceties of California social climbing and power decorating.
</P>
<P>
   Haines created magic for Polly. Entering the house is a dynamic
experience. The modest, dark front door pushes open to reveal a
light-drenched room that seems to swoop toward the golf course,
plainly visible from the back wall of glass. The room grows
lighter, brighter and bigger as you enter.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   This animation of space is enhanced by the blurring of outside
and in. There is indoor landscaping. Huge tropical plants that
scrape the ceiling are growing from rectangular planters in the
floor. The plants seem to have bullied their way inside from the
golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The indoor sprinkler system is built in, so is the radiant
heat under the marble floor. Everything about the house was ahead
of its time,'' says the Schenekers' daughter, Courtney Edwards, who
lives in Dallas. ``Mother was always ahead of her time.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the living room walls is upholstered in a rough-textured
ivory silk, and it forms the background for the low built-in sofa
and shelves, still there, exactly as Haines envisioned them. Like a
Frank Lloyd Wright house, there is little need for furniture _ what
is not built-in seems superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   The room is a stage. It is no accident that the fourth wall is
glass. Haines knew his clients expected to be the center of
attention. They are the players, and they are as important as the
view.
</P>
<P>
   During the Schenekers' reign, it was certainly true. ``Polly was
always good fun. She was always planning something. There were a
lot of parties,'' reminisces Annette Potts, a member of Polly's
circle of friends.
</P>
<P>
   The Scheneker guest list encompassed both coasts. Joan Crawford
was often their house guest. Edwards remembers Brooke Astor and the
Douglas MacArthurs coming to party with her parents.
</P>
<P>
   It was during a stay with the Schenekers that Crawford left her
mark on Fort Worth lore. Local designer Terry Crane remembers
``the'' incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew she was coming to the deb party at the River
Crest Country Club,'' he says. ``Tout le'' Fort Worth was in
attendance. ``It was when The Assembly ball was the big event,''
Crane continues, ``everyone was waiting for Joan, and the hours
ticked by and she didn't come and she didn't come.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, a white moving van pulls up to the front door
of the club. A moving van! The back rolls up and there is Joan,
standing in the middle of the van holding on to a strap connected
to the ceiling. Her dress was too big for the limousine, so she had
herself delivered to the club.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford stayed with the Schenekers, until, according to Crane,
an unfortunate name-calling incident took place on the dance floor,
and Crawford moved out of the Scheneker house and into the Western
Hills Hotel. She dated Sid Richardson for about a month after that,
says Crane.
</P>
<P>
   After the Schenekers died in 1968, the house was sold to Jim
Meeker.
</P>
<P>
   It had a colorful run as a major party pad, then the Kimbell Art
Museum foundation bought the house for Ric Brown, the museum's
first director. Ted Pillsbury moved his family in when he took over
as director of the Kimbell in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fell in love with the house, but I was uncomfortable being
a ward of the foundation, so I arranged to purchase the property,''
says Pillsbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were there until 1987 or 1988. I thought it was beautiful,
architecturally, the space, the materials, the shell stone. It was
striking, a simple but striking design.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pillsburys added the family room, connecting the kitchen to
the garage, swallowing up a side courtyard. The next owners, the
Richards, added a second-story master suite over the family room.
Crane was very hands-on with that project.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen was updated, and the wing and second story were
added, but very little about the original house has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is as it was, no one has abused it. All the owners
left it better than they found it, especially the Richards,'' says
Crane.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the house is for sale again, by Henry S. Miller Realtors,
for just shy of a cool million. But for the money, you get four
bedrooms, music room, sauna, wine cellar, a guest suite and
Hollywood history.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
