<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9648 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-LATIN-ROCK-MUSIC-$ADV     08-01 1471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-ROCK-MUSIC-$ADV06-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK EN ESPANOL REACHES ITS FINAL BOUNDARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 6)  
 (Eds: 3rd take may be used as a sidebar.)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ Rock may have been born as American music,
but at middle age it is also the music of the Americas, as quickly
becomes apparent during an afternoon spent in a recording studio
here with Aterciopelados, Colombia's most popular rock band. The
duo is rushing to finish mixing tracks for its new compact disc
before heading off for a summer tour of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Echeverri and Hector Buitrago, the group's founders, are
putting the finishing touches on a song called ``El Album,'' which
has just the sort of mixed-salad of a sound that has made the band
so successful throughout Latin America. The tune features a twangy
rockabilly guitar, a repetitive piano pattern that would sound at
home on any salsa record, the scratching of a hip-hop D.J., and a
chorus in the accordion-driven Colombian folk style known as
vallenato.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are rockers at heart, but we are Latin American rockers,
and that means that our music feeds on a lot of different
sources,'' Echeverri, who sings and writes for Aterciopelados
(pronounced ah-TARE-see-oh-pay-LAH-dos), which means ``the
Velvets,'' said after the session was over. ``We like to mix things
from outside with what is indigenous because that is what makes the
music so cool and unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   In studios and on stages all over Latin America these days,
similar scenes are unfolding as a new generation of musicians,
raised on rock in all its various permutations, topples the
traditional stereotypes of what Latin music ought to be. If only
for lack of a better name, the movement, which has been developing
since the mid-1980s, has come to be known as rock en espanol _ and
to be seen by its adherents as a powerful and energizing global
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock 'n' roll was born out of a cultural clash in the United
States between black and white,'' said Gustavo Santaolalla, an
Argentine who is the leading producer of rock en espanol records.
``Now a new cultural clash is taking place worldwide between
American culture and our indigenous cultures and the result, at a
time when so much mainstream pop music sounds like it has been
rehashed or recycled, is something that is new and fresh and
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The term rock en espanol is all-purpose and all-inclusive,
grouping musicians whose only real points in common are that they
grew up admiring Anglo-American rock bands and that they sing in
Spanish. Indeed, the movement is so wide-ranging that it
comfortably embraces everything from Mexican rappers like Molotov,
Control Machete and El Gran Silencio to melodic singer-songwriters
like the Argentines Fito Paez, Charly Garcia and Andres Calamaro.
</P>
<P>
   But as record companies have discovered in recent years, rock en
espanol is a phenomenon that is as much commercial as aesthetic,
which has created an interesting quandary for many Latin American
rockers about their future directions as their music moves beyond
their borders. Bands like the Mexican power-pop quartet Mana, to
take the most prominent example, routinely fill soccer and baseball
stadiums, arenas and bull rings with audiences of 25,000 or more
and sell millions of records to Spanish-speaking teen-agers all
over Latin America and, increasingly, the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The movement has been slower to make an impact in New York,
whose Spanish-speaking population is predominantly Caribbean and
thus more accustomed to tropical rhythms, than in Latin America or
in cities like Los Angeles, Miami and Chicago. But over the next
three weeks that situation may change, as a result of the Latin
Alternative Music Conference, a three-day industry forum scheduled
to begin next Sunday, and a series of showcase concerts sandwiched
around it.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Chilean pop quartet La Ley, the dance
specialists Los Amigos Invisibles from Venezuela and the Argentine
funk band Ilya Kuryaki and the Valderramas will be performing in a
free open-air concert at Central Park Summerstage. Then on Aug. 23
the Watcha Tour, a package show that has become Latin rock's
equivalent of Lollapalooza, arrives in New York for the first time,
with Cafe Tacuba, Aterciopelados, Molotov and Animal playing at the
Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   What is most striking about these and other popular rock en
espanol bands is their eclecticism and flexibility. Like Latin
American musicians from earlier generations, they have grown up
listening to the whole gamut of styles that make up the region's
common musical heritage: salsa, tango, merengue, bolero, cumbia,
mariachi, samba, ranchera, mambo and so on.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to improved communications and economic conditions,
they have also had more opportunities than their predecessors to
become familiar and comfortable with the popular music of the
English-speaking world. From Jimi Hendrix, Led Zeppelin and Bob
Dylan to Nirvana, Oasis and Nine Inch Nails, they have heard _ and
absorbed _ it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are amphibious,'' said Ivan Benavides, leader of the
Colombian group Bloque, whose eponymous debut album made the top 10
lists of several New York Times critics in 1998. ``We can play the
music of the cultures we were born into, but it also feels natural
to play the music of the broader cosmopolitan culture. That gives
us an advantage over people who are ethnocentric, whether they are
Anglo-, Euro- or Latino-centric.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time that Latin rockers, most of whom are in their 30s,
were growing up, cultural discourse in Latin America was dominated
by doctrinaire leftists who argued that rock was a decadent
manifestation of American imperialism and that only folk-based
indigenous music could be a valid form of expression. Given what
they saw as a false dichotomy between Silvio Rodriguez and David
Bowie, or Victor Jara and Kiss, the rockers quite deliberately
chose both.
</P>
<P>
   ``People on the left tend to have very closed opinions and not
to be very farsighted,'' said Flavio Cianciarulo, the bass player
and a songwriter for Los Fabulosos Cadillacs, Argentina's most
innovative band. ``Rock is essentially pure rebellion, and always
has been, but they couldn't understand that, so we just wrote them
off and continued to do our own thing, always with honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   In their early days, admittedly, many rock en espanol performers
sounded like copies of whatever Anglo-American bands first inspired
them to pick up their instruments or sing. Mana drew heavily on the
Police, La Ley emerged as a cross between Depeche Mode and Duran
Duran, Los Fabulosos Cadillacs seemed like an Argentine version of
the Specials and the Colombian singer-songwriter Shakira found
herself being compared to Alanis Morissette.
</P>
<P>
   But as bands and singers have gradually gained experience and
confidence, that tendency has changed, and Latin American rock
today can be just as adventurous and stylistically promiscuous as
North American pop. One of the biggest hits in Latin America during
the past year, for example, has been Shakira's ``Ojos Asi,'' which
fuses a Spanish-language lyric with a Middle Eastern melody and
rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in Barranquilla, which is a Caribbean port city
where you heard every kind of music you could imagine, from cumbia
and vallenato to rhythm-and-blues,'' recalled Shakira, a member of
a Lebanese immigrant family whose full name is Shakira Mebarak.
``Some of the first records I remember hearing as a little girl
were Donna Summer and the Arab singers that my parents liked,''
such as the Egyptian singer Oum Kalsoum.
</P>
<P>
   But if one place has been most influential in the development of
the movement, it is Mexico. Even in the 1960s, Mexican bands were
listening to the ``border blasters,'' high-wattage radio stations
broadcasting to the United States from Mexican territory and
recording Spanish-language cover versions of American rock 'n' roll
hits. By the mid 1980s, Mexican record labels were slowly waking to
the commercial possibilities of home-grown rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock en tu idioma,'' or ``rock in your language,'' was the way
they marketed the new sound. Based in Mexico City, bands like Cafe
Tacuba, Maldita Vecindad, Caifanes, Santa Sabina and La Castaneda
found small clubs in bohemian neighborhoods that were willing to
let them play, developed followings that soon grew from the local
to the national, and signed contracts with the Mexican branches of
the main multinational record companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important as an affirmation to sing in Spanish,'' said
Ruben Albarran of Cafe Tacuba, the pioneering band whose recent
activities have included a tour of the United States with Beck and
recordings with the Kronos Quartet. ``We had to define ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
