</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9650 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-LATIN-ROCK-MUSIC-$ADV     08-01 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-ROCK-MUSIC-$ADV06-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BOGOTA, Colombia: define ourselves.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Argentina, a similar process was under way. A flourishing
rock 'n' roll scene had emerged in Buenos Aires during the 1960s,
but when a right-wing military junta seized power in the mid 1970s,
the music was forced to retreat and only began to re-emerge after
the collapse of the dictatorship following the Falklands War of
1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no accident that we began around 1984,'' Cianciarulo
said. Once civilian rule was restored, he said, ``everything that
had gone underground came out into the light of day, and freedom
became the order of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Though isolated from the rest of Latin America by language,
Brazil saw its pop music evolve along the same lines. The
tropicalists who first came to prominence in the late 1960s
continue to flourish there, but groups like Paralamas do Suceso,
Legiao Urbana, Titas, Skank, Charlie Brown Jr., Jota Quest, Barao
Vermelho, Kid Abelha, Planet Hemp and Chico Science have forged an
equally catholic, Portuguese-language variant of Latin rock.
</P>
<P>
   Yet each nation's burgeoning rock scene might have continued in
insularity were it not for recent advances in technology and more
contacts between the local affiliates of multinational record
companies. Perhaps the biggest factor in breaking down barriers,
artists and managers agree, has been the explosive growth of cable
television in Latin America during the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``MTV Latino and CNN en Espanol have been fundamental'' in
spreading rock en espanol, said Beto Cuevas, lead singer of the
Chilean band La Ley, whose base is in Mexico. ``They not only
showed us what was happening in the United States at the same time
it was happening, but also allowed us to see what was going on in
Argentina or Colombia, countries that had their own rock tradition
but hadn't been heard elsewhere because of a lack of
communication.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, because of its very success, the movement, rebaptized
Latin Alternative to make it more palatable to North American
audiences, may be approaching a crossroads. Stimulated by the
recent crossover success of home-grown Hispanic performers like
Ricky Martin and Jennifer Lopez, interest in Latin American rock is
growing in the United States, both among audiences hungry for new
sounds and record companies eager for new profits.
</P>
<P>
   There is now a Grammy award for best Latin Rock/Alternative
performance, for instance, and several Latin rock songs have turned
up in Hollywood films seeking an edgy tone, ``Grosse Pointe Blank''
and various Quentin Tarantino movies among them. College radio
stations are adding rock en espanol to their playlists, Web sites
and publications like Spin have begun to pay attention to the
genre, and booking agencies like Creative Artists Agency have
signed leading rock en espanol bands and sent them out on tour with
established American pop artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I don't get calls from EMI Latino or Sony Discos
anymore,'' said Tomas Cookman, manager of Los Fabulosos Cadillacs,
Aterciopelados and other top groups, referring to the traditional
Latin music departments of two big labels. ``Now I'm more likely to
be dealing with Maverick Records or Atlantic or Warners or Chris
Blackwell. This is a wonderful moment, like the beginning of
hip-hop, when Russell Simmons was just getting Def Jam together.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, however, many of Latin America's most popular rock
bands are facing a dilemma. Do they continue to focus on their
loyal Spanish-speaking audience back home or do they shift more of
their attention and energy to a potentially futile quest to break
into the promising but unknown American market, at the risk of
sacrificing what makes them authentic and perhaps alienating their
original fans?
</P>
<P>
   A hilariously sly new video by Los Fabulosos Cadillacs that has
been in heavy rotation on MTV Latino in recent weeks makes it clear
that at least one band recognizes the problem. The clip
accompanying ``La Vida'' features an American image consultant,
unable to speak Spanish and completely unattuned to the band's
proudly grungy image and sound, trying to repackage them into a
slick, dancing ensemble, a la 'N Sync or Ricky Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Some artists, like Shakira, are convinced they can have it both
ways. She recently signed a contract with the same management team
that long guided Madonna's career and has spent much of the summer
in the Bahamas, working on new material and translating some of her
older songs for a projected English-language album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the chance to expand as an artist, and I'm curious,''
she said. ``I want to know what's on the other side, how far I can
take this thing. It's a challenge to sing in another language, but
it's also an opportunity, and if I can have success in both
languages, of course that will also bring credit to Colombia.''
</P>
<P>
   Julieta Venegas, in contrast, is a 29-year-old Mexican
singer-songwriter who grew up in Tijuana, listening to California
radio stations ``with more a chance of seeing Iggy Pop or Oingo
Boingo in San Diego'' than hearing rock in Spanish. Though she
speaks perfect English, the only suggestion of an accent being that
of a Valley Girl, and recorded her latest disc in Los Angeles with
American studio musicians, she insisted ``it never occurred to me
to write in English.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like having access to American music, but writing in Spanish
is a big part of what I am and what makes my music interesting,
even to someone who might not understand the language,'' she said.
``We've been watching you people all the time, and now you're
watching us. It's sort of funny, but it's true, and I think that's
the way it's going to stay from now on, with everybody on both
sides of the border exposed to a broader, richer range of
influences.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
