NYT-08-01-00 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9651 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-LATIN-ROCK-MUSIC-$ADV     08-01 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-ROCK-MUSIC-$ADV06-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BOGOTA, Colombia: of influences.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the idea of Latin American rock and pop seems utterly
foreign, here are a dozen records, chosen to display the diversity
of the movement, that offer a good starting point for the beginner:
</P>
<P>
   ATERCIOPELADOS: ``Caribe Atomico'' (BMG 1998). Tropical punk?
Psychedelic folk? It is hard to classify this eclectic collection
from Colombia other than to say it never stops swinging, surprising
or satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   BLOQUE: ``Bloque de Busqueda'' (Luaka Bop 1998). The group
started as the back-up band for the vallenato star Carlos Vives,
then made this record showing the darker side of Colombian pop,
with acerbic lyrics and harsh heavy metal guitars over a driving
Afro-Caribbean percussion section.
</P>
<P>
   LOS FABULOSOS CADILLACS: ``Vasos Vacios'' (Sony 1994). This
Argentine ensemble has shown jazz leanings on its most recent
records, but this early best-of compilation highlights its
reggae-ska-dub-punk origins and includes the Brazilian-influenced
``Matador,'' still its signature song.
</P>
<P>
   CAIFANES: ``La Historia'' (BMG/Ariola 1997). A two-disc set that
traces the evolution of one of Mexico's most important groups from
a clone of the Cure to a tight and deft ensemble proud of its Latin
American origins.
</P>
<P>
   CHARLY GARCIA: ``Obras Cumbres'' (Sony 2000). A two-volume
career retrospective from Latin America's foremost
singer-songwriter, a disciple of Bob Dylan and the Beatles who has
inspired a generation of younger artists. It includes ``No Voy en
Tren,'' perhaps the first rock en espanol anthem.
</P>
<P>
   LOS AMIGOS INVISIBLES: ``The New Sound of the Venezuelan
Gozadera'' (Luaka Bop 1998). Dance music as self-referentially
playful and goofy as anything the B-52's have ever recorded.
</P>
<P>
   JAGUARES: ``El Equilibrio de los Jaguares'' (BMG 1996). If rock
en espanol has a guitar virtuoso, Mexico's Saul Hernandez is the
man, and this brooding but beautiful collection of songs allows him
to show off all his chops.
</P>
<P>
   MANA: ``Suenos Liquidos'' (WEA Latina 1997). The best-selling
rock en espanol record ever, by a Guadalajara-based quartet that
has parlayed a melodic, power-pop sound into unparalleled
commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   MOLOTOV: ``Donde Jugaran Las Ninas?'' (Surco/Universal 1998).
Bilingual rap from a binational quartet (three Mexicans and one
gringo) that is by turns angry, scatological and humorous.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKIRA: ``Donde Estan Los Ladrones?'' (Sony 1998). At 23, this
Colombian singer and songwriter has barely entered adulthood but
already shows a striking talent for the polished, well-made pop
tune, the most appealing of which here is probably the
Arab-influenced ``Ojos Asi.''
</P>
<P>
   CAFE TACUBA: ``Reves/Yo Soy'' (WEA Latina 1999). A challenging
two-disc collection (one of quirky instrumentals, the other of more
conventional but stylistically diverse songs) that may be the
crowning achievement of Mexico's most consistently adventurous and
experimental rock band.
</P>
<P>
   VARIOUS ARTISTS: ``Reconquista! The Latin Rock Invasion'' (Rhino
1996). A chronicle of rock en espanol's early, punk-inspired years,
with an emphasis on the Mexican pioneers of the movement but also
including a pair of key cuts by Los Fabulosos Cadillacs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
