<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9656 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-GOP-BUSH-0802-COX     08-01 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GOP-BUSH-0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH SIDESTEPS QUESTIONS ABOUT POWELL'S CONVENTION SPEECH
 &HT;    By JENA HEATH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Gov. George W. Bush sidestepped questions on
Tuesday about the blunt criticism retired Gen. Colin L. Powell
handed the GOP in the speech he delivered during the opening night
of the 37th Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday if he agreed with Powell's criticism of the GOP's
stand on affirmative action, Bush declined to say one way or the
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with Colin Powell that Republicans need to do more to
reach out to minorities,'' Bush told reporters traveling with him
to Charleston, W.Va. ``We've got a lot of work to do. And I agree
with him that I'm the man to do it for the Republican party.''
</P>
<P>
   In an impassioned speech Monday night, Powell praised Bush for
improving the educational performance of students in Texas,
particularly minorities, and said that Bush can help ``bridge our
racial divides'' if he wins the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But Powell had some sharp criticism for their party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some in our party miss no opportunity to roundly condemn
affirmative action that helped a few thousand black kids get an
education, but you hardly hear a whimper from them over affirmative
action for lobbyists who load our federal tax code with preferences
for special interests,'' Powell told delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he had not seen Powell's speech in advance but that
Powell called him Monday to tell him that he would ``talk about
these issues.'' Powell, the only African-American to serve as
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, is one of the speakers
helping the GOP convey Bush's ``compassionate conservative''
campaign theme during the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what specific policies he had in mind,'' Bush
said. ``In my state of Texas we took a very positive step toward
ensuring (that) the racial mix of Texas universities reflected the
nature of our population.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Texas's 10 percent plan, students of any race who graduate
in the top 10 percent of their classes are automatically admitted
to state colleges and universities. Bush signed the plan into law
after a federal appeals court disallowed the use of race or
ethnicity as a factor for admittance to Texas colleges and
universities.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign spokeswoman Karen Hughes said Bush supports what he
calls ``affirmative access.'' He opposes race-based quotas because
``he believes quotas divide and Balkanize our society,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he thought his delegates and the large, enthusiastic
crowds that have greeted him on his six-state pre-convention tour
are mostly white, Bush said: ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember the makeup of the crowds in Texas but I got
nearly 50% of the Hispanic vote and I'm not so sure the nature of
the crowd necessarily is going to reflect the nature of the vote,''
he said. ``But we've got a lot of work to do, no question about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, Bush may have won as much as 40 percent of
the Hispanic vote during his 1998 gubernatorial re-election,
although some voting groups have cast doubts that he did that well.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was nuanced in his response to Powell's speech, Bush
was loud and clear about recent criticism from President Clinton.
At a fund-raiser late last week, Clinton mocked the Bush campaign
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, how bad could I be?'' Clinton, playing the role of
Bush, told Democrats in Rhode Island. `` I've been governor of
Texas. My daddy was president. I own a baseball team. They like me
down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has been stepping up his criticism of Clinton
throughout his pre-convention tour, reminding audiences almost
daily that his running mate, former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney,
``knows what the meaning of the word 'is' is,'' _ a reference to
Clinton's deposition in the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In her speech before the convention Monday, Laura Bush promised
that her husband would renew a time when children could respect the
president of the United States. Traveling with her husband to West
Virginia Tuesday, Mrs. Bush said she was not referring to Clinton,
and Bush added: ``I don't think I've ever mentioned President
Clinton's name on the stump recently.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that he has been talking about the president
when he uses the ``is is'' line. Almost daily, Bush recounts
stories of people coming to him with pictures of their children,
imploring him to restore respect to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was talking about him then,'' Bush said. ``I sure was,
but in the context of having somebody who's going to shoot straight
with the American people...When people walk up and hold pictures of
their children, they're the ones doing that. And we're just
reflecting what we see. ``
</P>
<P>
   Jena Heath can be e-mailed at: jenah(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
