<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-POET-LAUREATE-ART-NYT     08-01 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POET-LAUREATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAUREATE DISTILLED, TO AN EAU DE VIE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(editors: excerpted poem passages should be italicized) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I don't expect to be very kinetic,'' Stanley Kunitz
said, with a dry little laugh. A reporter was asking Kunitz what he
would be doing in his new appointment as the United States' 10th
poet laureate, which was announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nor do I expect to traipse around the country,'' Kunitz said.
Understandable perhaps, for he is 95 years old. ``I feel the best
service that I can do is to continue to function as a poet.'' He is
certainly doing that. There aren't many poets who sign three book
contracts at age 92, as Kunitz did with his publisher, W.W. Norton.
</P>
<P>
   And in October, when his appointment as poet laureate begins,
Norton is to publish Kunitz's 12th book of poetry, a volume of
``Collected Poems.'' He would like to think there will be at least
one book after that, ``in this millennium,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Jay Parini, a poet, novelist and critic, was told about
Kuntiz's appointment, he said: ``Every poet I know with any sense
looks to Stanley Kunitz and says that's the way to think about a
poetic career. In other words, total devotion to the craft itself,
not the slightest degree of affectation, a complete humility in his
work. There's never a moment when you say, `He's faking it,' or
`He's doing this to impress me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kunitz succeeds Robert Pinsky, and this is actually his second
time round as the nation's top poet. From 1974 to 1976, he was
Consultant in Poetry at the Library of Congress, before the words
poet laureate were added to the job title. He has also won just
about every other honor possible for a poet, including a Pulitzer
Prize, the National Book Award and the Bollingen Prize. But for
many years, he was overlooked in favor of more famous
contemporaries, like W.H. Auden and Robert Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are critics who believe that Kunitz's work has
gotten better over time. ``I've learned to strip the water out of
my poems,'' he has said. In recent years, his writing has become
sparer, less formal, more direct, in a sense, purer. There are no
rhyme schemes, no complicated metrical designs. In one typical
poem, ``The Wellfleet Whale,'' he describes the cries of a whale
lying stranded on the beach, as ``an eerie medley of clicks/and
hoots and trills,/location-notes and love calls,/whistles and
grunts. Occasionally,/ it's like furniture being smashed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Kunitz's work is lyrical and sensuous too, as in
``Touch Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer is late, my heart.
</P>
<P>
   Words plucked out of the air
</P>
<P>
   some forty years ago
</P>
<P>
   when I was wild with love.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the poem he asks,
</P>
<P>
   Darling, do you remember
</P>
<P>
   The man you married? Touch me,
</P>
<P>
   remind me who I am.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Worcester, Mass., the son of a manufacturer who
killed himself before Kunitz was born. He has written about the
anguish the suicide caused his family. He went on to graduate from
Harvard, served in the military and was briefly a newspaper man.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my primary thoughts through the years has been that I
am living and dying at once,'' he said. ``It began long before I
was an aging man. It's continuing. Perhaps the mix gets a bit
different.'' He cites his poem, ``The Layers,'' as an example:
</P>
<P>
   In a rising wind
</P>
<P>
   the manic dust of my friends,
</P>
<P>
   those who fell along the way,
</P>
<P>
   bitterly stings my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Kunitz is married to Elise Asher, 88, his third wife, an artist
and poet. Each has a child from a previous marriage, and ``a
bowlful of grandchildren and even great-grandchildren,'' he said.
``They're all going to be up here soon,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The couple gets by without a housekeeper. ``We work together and
manage our lives as best we can.'' They have homes in Greenwich
Village and Provincetown, Mass., where Kunitz enjoys his other
passion, gardening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in writing every day,'' he said, ``though I'm
at my desk every day. So much of writing is thinking before you
write, reading or simply brooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a night worker,'' he said. ``I love the sense of solitude
and the silence. ``I love to think that here I am alive and burning
and the rest of the world is asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Kunitz, who is slender and fit-looking, said he had no special
prescription for good health or longevity. ``I don't pay much
attention to exercise or diet,'' he said, though ``I'm famous for
my martinis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what keeps me going is my caring about being alive and
caring about the world. And the fact that I love being here, that's
all.''
</P>
<P>
   His poem ``The Long Boat,'' expresses it all, he said. In the
poem, he imagines lying down in a cradle with the family ghosts,
``buffeted by the storm, endlessly drifting.''
</P>
<P>
   And at the end, he writes, it is ``As if it didn't matter/ which
way was home;/ as if he didn't know/ he loved the earth so much/ he
wanted to stay forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9658 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER0802-COX     08-01 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT THE BECK AND CALL
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Retired Gen. Colin Powell, mentioned as a possible secretary of
state if George W. Bush wins in November, said Monday he also would
entertain a job offer from Al Gore if the Democrat wins the
presidential election. ``If he were the president, I would have to
take it under serious consideration,'' Powell said after being
asked on ABC's ``Good Morning America'' if he could work for Gore.
Powell added: ``I've had conversations with President Clinton like
this. I elected not to accept some of the offers that were out
there, but you always have to listen when a president comes to you
...'' Bush hinted Monday that Powell, the only black to serve as
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, would be offered a top job
in his administration. ``I hope his greatest service to America
might still lie ahead,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ALSO ON THE LINEUP . . .
</P>
<P>
   Hewing to the carefully calculated script of moderation,
tolerance and outreach, speakers on the second night of the
convention will also include Rep. Jim Kolbe of Arizona, the only
openly gay Republican in Congress, Condoleezza Rice, the black
woman who is Bush's chief foreign policy adviser, and Elizabeth
Dole, the former Cabinet member who briefly ran for the GOP
nomination. Former Presidents Bush and Ford will take the spotlight
in a convention tribute to former Republican presidents. Nancy
Reagan was flying in from California to stand in for her husband,
Ronald, who has Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT WAS THAT ABOUT STRANGE BEDFELLOWS?
</P>
<P>
   A dozen prominent Republicans spent two hours trying to woo
Teamsters President James P. Hoffa at a reception, hoping to win an
endorsement or at least prevent the labor organization from backing
Al Gore. It was the first time in 20 years a GOP convention has
hosted the union. The 1.5 million-strong International Brotherhood
of Teamsters and the United Auto Workers abstained when the AFL-CIO
labor federation endorsed Gore. Hoffa said he plans to make a
decision about an endorsement - if any - around Labor Day, after
also attending the Democratic Convention. Republicans said when
Teamsters see the pictures of Republicans with Hoffa, that alone
will convince some members who were on the fence to vote for Bush.
``That picture is what it's all about,'' said Scott Reed, the man
who put the meeting together.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT WAS THAT ABOUT STRANGE BEDFELLOWS, PART II
</P>
<P>
   Outspoken civil rights activist and Democrat, the Rev. Al
Sharpton, is attending the convention today not as a protester but
as a guest of conservative commentator Armstrong Williams. Williams
said Sharpton will spend most of the day with him, including taping
Williams' syndicated radio show from inside the convention hall.
``We're just trying to show that people of different political
persuasions can try to come together and talk about their
differences,'' Williams said. In exchange for his attendance here,
the Republican Armstrong said he'll go to Los Angeles for the
Democratic convention, Aug. 14-17.
</P>
<P>
   NO CLINTON-BASHING AT THIS BASH
</P>
<P>
   When the New York Republican delegation takes the floor at the
convention this week, the Republican running in the state's most
important race will be nowhere to be seen. Rep. Rick Lazio decided
to skip most of the convention to stay in New York and continue his
Senate campaign against Hillary Clinton. He made a cameo appearance
with New York delegates today, speaking at their breakfast and then
raising some money at a private event. Rep. Peter King, a fellow
Long Island Republican, said Lazio wouldn't be addressing the
convention because, ``The feeling is that if (he) got up to speak,
that would be looked upon as an anti-Clinton speech and the crowd
would obviously respond, maybe too enthusiastically, to Rick
because of their dislike of Mrs. Clinton. And the Bush people don't
want to make this an anti-Clinton convention.''
</P>
<P>
   SO MUCH FOR THE SPIRIT OF HARMONY
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate Alan Keyes may have dropped
out of the race, but he apparently won't give up any of his
hard-won delegates. Keyes received five of the 288 votes cast
during the roll call of the states at the convention. George W.
Bush, the presumptive nominee, got the remaining votes. Keyes
earned the five Arkansas delegates in the state's May 23
presidential primary. Because they were never released after Keyes
quit the race in July, the delegates technically remain pledged to
him _ even though only one of the five delegates supports him,
according to Arkansas Gov. Mike Huckabee. Anne Britton, head of
Keyes's campaign in Arkansas, said Keyes probably would have
released his delegates if he had been given a chance to speak at
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR BEEF'S WITH ME
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton says he is more nervous about the outcome of
his wife's New York Senate race than he ever was about any of his
own elections, and he worries that people who ``always hated me''
have ``transferred all their anger to her.'' In an interview with
Fox television broadcast Tuesday, Clinton said, ``It's almost as if
they've got one last chance to beat me. I feel like I just wake up
every day wishing I could do something else to help.'' Recent polls
have shown Hillary Clinton and opponent Rick Lazio in a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   THAT'S IT, I'VE HAD IT
</P>
<P>
   While George W. Bush has generally refrained from mentioning
either President Clinton or rival Al Gore by name, he did so twice
Tuesday, responding sharply to criticism from Clinton, who he said
is ``so desperate to have his legacy intact by getting Al Gore
elected, he'll say anything, just like Gore will.'' Bush later said
on his plane that he had ignored his self-imposed ban on mentioning
names because he was ``riled up'' by Clinton's remarks at a
fund-raiser last Friday. At the event, Clinton suggested Bush's
campaign message was: ``How bad can I be? I've been governor of
Texas. My daddy was president. I owned a baseball team. They like
me down there. ... Everything is rocking along hunky dory. Their
fraternity had it for eight years, give it to ours for eight
years.'
</P>
<P>
   MAKING ITS LIST AND CHECKING IT TWICE
</P>
<P>
   With control of Congress up for grabs this fall, Republicans are
sending an unmistakable message to political action committees who
are thinking about hedging their bets by writing checks to both
parties. The GOP fund-raising arm for House candidates has created
a 75 Percent Club for special interests to find out who's been
giving too much money to Democrats. What is the 75 percent? A
requirement that political action committees give three-quarters of
their contributions to Republican candidates _ or they might not
get their calls returned. ``They've got to make a decision of how
they are going to help their friends and who their friends are,''
said Rep. Thomas Reynolds of New York, one of the committee's key
fund-raisers. Fred Werthheimer, head of Democracy 21 and an
advocate of reducing the influence of money in politics, criticized
the tactic, saying, ``This is taking it to a new level, from the
selling and buying of access to the political extortion level where
your access may be cut off if you don't pay up.''
</P>
<P>
   A TEMPEST BREWING
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Cheney's discomfort with the media's interest in her
lesbian daughter, Mary, televised nationally over the weekend,
threatens to ignite the first firestorm of the so-far superbly
scripted Republican convention. On Sunday, when ABC's Cokie Roberts
started to ask the GOP vice-presidential candidate's wife about
having a daughter who has ``declared she's openly gay,'' an irate
Lynne Cheney shot back: ``Mary has never declared such a thing.''
The controversy could bubble over this week, since friends of Mary
Cheney - who has publicly declared herself a lesbian and has worked
as the gay and lesbian corporate relations manager for Coors
Brewing Co. - say she's planning to bring her life partner to the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Saeed Ahmed from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
