<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Aug. 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dreary conditions that have enveloped much of the Northeast
since late last week will yield to weather more like summer as a
warm front plods northward into Maine. Fog will shroud the New
England coast, but some sunshine will break through by afternoon
from Boston southward. It will turn sultry in the New York area as
breezes from the southwest develop.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical air gliding northward around the Bermuda high will pass
over the heated land of the Southeast, leading to widespread
thunderstorms in the afternoon. Flooding is possible as storms move
slowly along the same path in the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   A cool front pushing southward into the Great Lakes will promote
thundershowers. Cooler, less humid air will cover the northeast
Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Torrid weather will persist in the Rockies and interior West,
though the Northwest will turn cooler. Afternoon storms will
develop in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TOTALLY MARINE
</P>
<P>
   The enormous capacity of the ocean to temper the climate along
the coast was most evident from New York to Boston on Monday. The
temperature there varied by no more than 3 degrees during that
24-hour period. While thick clouds and some rain helped to reduce
the temperature variation, a persistent wind from the North
Atlantic drove ocean-cooled air into the region. It is remarkable
that in late July, with nearly 15 hours of daylight and the sun
high in the sky, the ocean overwhelmed the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
