<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9665 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ART-EXPLORATORIUM-$AD     08-01 0184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-EXPLORATORIUM-$ADV06-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
SAN FRANCISCO: over either.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following Oppenheimer's death in 1985, his successors have
struggled to keep his vision alive while coping with sometimes
rancorous internal disagreements about future directions. What to
some looks like greater professionalism to others looks perilously
close to selling out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a new emphasis on making everything clean and
organized,'' said Joe Ansel, an exhibition designer who worked at
the Exploratorium from 1972 to 1992. ``I think they see that as the
better way, but it's really the more conventional way.''
</P>
<P>
   But McLean is confident that ``Revealing Bodies'' marks a step
forward rather than a retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm planning to install more of these kinds of shows so that
we can offer a variety of experiences, from wild, crazy, chaotic,
open spaces to quiet, reflective spaces,'' she said. ``At the
Exploratorium we're so fixed on the kinds of experiences we've done
in the past, which were so powerful, that it's hard for some people
to see how inventive and experimental a show like `Revealing
Bodies' is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
