<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for the
Wednesday, Aug. 2, Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   GOP-RDP (Philadelphia) _ A convention roundup: After an evening
projecting an image of a party that welcomes women, minority groups
and immigrants, the Republicans are poised to present a more
familiar focus at their convention, that of the party that embraces
and promotes military strength. On Tuesday night, the podium will
be dominated by war heroes: Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf, former Sen.
Bob Dole and Sen. John McCain. But the underlying message is the
same: The Republican Party under George W. Bush is united behind a
single message, relentlessly disciplined and focused on taking the
White House. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-FUNDRAISING _ Who is raising money for George Bush and how?
By Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FUEL-COST-IMPACT (Brooklyn, Iowa) _ Middle class Americans,
flush with prosperity, are grumbling about high fuel prices, but
rising gas and heating costs are inflicting catastrophic burdens on
the working poor. For low-income families in small towns and
suburbs, where long distances and the lack of public transportation
make driving a necessity, filling gas tanks is coming at the
expense of proper nutrition and medicine. One study suggests that
higher heating bills this winter could even compel low-income
consumers to do without health care, phones and electricity. By
Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   OPERA-DUO (Aix-en-Provence, France) _ At the summer opera
festival here, two promising young singers whose lives are the
stuff of operatic drama. They are a real-life Romeo and Juliet: She
is a Serb and he is a Croat. By John Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GLOBAL-WARMING (Undated) _ Preparing for a new round of
negotiations over how to reduce levels of heat-trapping greenhouse
gases that may be warming the climate, the United States has taken
the stance that using forests and farmer's fields to sop up carbon
dioxide, the chief warming gas, is just as important as cutting
emissions from smoke stacks and tail pipes. The position was stated
in documents filed before a deadline with a U.N. office that is
overseeing talks aimed at implementing the 1997 Kyoto Protocol, an
international agreement among industrialized nations aimed at
averting any dangerous climate warming. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
</TEXT>
