u p BC-CVN-CHENEY02-COX     08-01 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CHENEY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHENEY TO JOIN BUSH ON POST-CONVENTION TRAIL
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Dick Cheney said Tuesday he would join George W.
Bush on a post-convention barnstorming tour targeting battleground
states in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to take the battle to the heart of Democratic
territory,'' Cheney said. ``After the convention, George W. Bush
and I will be taking a train to campaign in states such as Illinois
and Michigan.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's comments came at a luncheon to honor House Speaker J.
Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   As he continued a round of meetings at the Republican National
Convention, Cheney also held an impromptu reunion with former
President Gerald Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, a chief of staff in the Ford White House, said afterward
that he was very happy to get the chance to meet with Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to recognize what he meant to me, because I wouldn't be
here if it wasn't for Jerry Ford,'' Cheney said at a luncheon
Tuesday to honor House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who addresses the convention Wednesday night to accept
the vice-presidential nomination, said Bush has the exuberance
needed for the long fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``George's greatest strength is the ability to get others to
support his policies for the greater good,'' Cheney said. ``He is a
very persuasive man _ I did not volunteer for this job _ I said no
to him several times before I finally said yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert called Cheney a seasoned and honorable political veteran
who has the experience and intelligence to represent the country
with Bush. He cited Cheney's experience in Congress, as White House
chief of staff, and as defense secretary under President Bush
during the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said that he was pleased to see a Republican majority in
Congress, something he never experience in his 10 years serving as
a representative from Wyoming. He also praised Republicans for the
``robust'' surplus that was he said was due to the Republican
majority in both the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's e-mail address is rodell(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
