<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      08-01 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS PLEASED WITH BALANCE, DISCIPLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio _ Michael Bishop was exciting, Raymont Harris was
surprising, and the Patriots defense was virtually flawless, but
standing out most in their 20-0 win over the San Francisco 49ers
Monday night was the team's discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Even the best of teams incur penalties. There are messed-up
substitutions that leave 12 or 10 men on the field. Guys might jump
offside once or twice. Maybe there's a blown coverage or a receiver
runs the wrong route.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the teams that limit those snafus that are usually the
best prepared _ and the ones that win.
</P>
<P>
   In game management, the Patriots couldn't have been better
Monday night for a team playing its first game in a new system with
a new coach and 17 players out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Belichick did allude to a few problems with
``communication,'' but that was just coachspeak.
</P>
<P>
   On the sideline, Belichick was a stark contrast to the excitable
Pete Carroll. It's not that one style is better than the other, but
in this case the style fit the philosophy: no nonsense. Notice that
players weren't celebrating after big plays as much. Notice that
Belichick's mood changed little.
</P>
<P>
   Those things have not gone without notice from the players, who
agree that the timing and execution displayed on the field was at
times better than what was seen during regular-season games last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a well-balanced game,'' said safety Lawyer Milloy.
``There was a lot of enthusiasm. We have runng backs who aren't
afraid to stick it in the hole. There were people making plays.
Belichick has done a good job with our talent. He's bringing that
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy also made the comment that Belichick had prepared the
Patriots better for this game than the team had been prepared for
playoff games in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously bringing out all of the little things that win
games,'' said Milloy. ``I think we were on the same page out there.
Sometimes that doesn't happen so early in the season. We can get
better, and that's the exciting thing _ that we can take this as a
positive experience but know we can execute even better than what
we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The preparation applied to all three units.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were tagged with only three penalties, one of them
a roughing-the-kicker call on Milloy, who tried to block a punt but
missed by a split second. That 15-yard penalty came with about four
minutes remaining in the first quarter after the defense had
stopped the 49ers on three plays. After the penalty, Willie
McGinest made three superb plays over a five-play span, two of them
resulting in sacks of quarterback Jeff Garcia. McGinest likes to
anticipate the snap count, and to do that with such precision so
early in the exhibition season was another sign of preparation.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' patchwork offensive line had only one holding
penalty, that by Jason Andersen in the third quarter. And the only
other penalty was on third-string safety Reggie Rideau for holding
in the fourth quarter. Unless it was simply a case of the officials
letting a lot of things go, the youngsters on the Patriots
offensive line were in step and certainly got the messages that
line coach Dante Scarnecchia and offensive coordinator Charlie Weis
have hammered home about technique and avoiding bad penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question Coach Belichick had us well-prepared for
the first game,'' said running back Raymont Harris, who ran hard
inside as well as he did in training camp. ``We thought it was
important to get off on the right foot. It's a preseason game, but
this is our first under Coach Belichick and we wanted to make it a
good debut for him and our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering that Harris (58 yards on nine carries) didn't play
at all last season, and considering that he was running behind an
unfamiliar line, his timing and reads were top-shelf.
</P>
<P>
   There were other things done well, too. Adam Vinatieri made both
of his field goal attempts (21 and 39 yards), with good snaps from
Derrick Fletcher and flawless holds by Lee Johnson, who also punted
for a 47-yard average. The cover teams did allow one 32-yard
kickoff return, which is about 12 yards too much, and one 12-yard
punt return, which is also more than the coaching staff would like.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots did not turn the ball over, another sign of
strong preparation. Meanwhile, Troy Brown did force one 49er
fumble.
</P>
<P>
   There are problems, familiar ones, that Belichick will likely
harp on in limited practice sessions this week, namely third-down
conversions. This was a huge problem last season, when the Patriots
converted 35.4 percent. On Monday night, they were 4 for 11 (36
percent) on third down and 0 for 1 on fourth down.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest thing the Patriots can gloat about is their running
game, which produced 193 yards for a 5.1-yard average. The Patriots
averaged only 89.1 yards per game last season, which severely
reduced their time of possession and put the defense on the field
for too long. While optimistic about the running game, the Patriots
haven't yet seen third-round pick J.R. Redmond, who is still
recovering from groin surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what the next four exhibition games will bring? Maybe
all of the problems of the previous regime may reemerge. But for an
exhibition debut, it was tight and efficient.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
