<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9678 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-CONGRESS-VISITORS-CTR     08-01 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-VISITORS-CTR-0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR SUNDAY, AUG. 6
 &HT;    SECURE VISITORS CENTER TO BE READY FOR INAUGURATION -- IN 2005
 &HT;    By Rob O'Dell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two years after the fatal shooting of two U.S.
Capitol police officers, designs are being completed for a $265
million Capitol Visitors Center that will boost security and allow
police to better manage the flow of more than 2 million visitors a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The center will be the first planned addition to the Capitol
building since 1959, but you won't be able to see it from ground
level. The 500,000 square foot center will be built underground,
between the Capitol and the U.S. Supreme Court building.
</P>
<P>
   Construction is scheduled to begin in 18 months and be completed
in time for the Presidential inauguration in January 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, visitors enter the Capitol through several entrances
near the central staircase. Tour staging areas are held outdoors in
the east plaza.
</P>
<P>
   When the center is completed, most visitors will enter through
the center. A sloped entry way would be carved from First Street,
east of the Capitol, to a point in the east plaza about 100 yards
from the building. The entrance would be cut from stone in keeping
with the character of the building.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors would pass through a security screening area and enter
the Capitol underground through a connection to the rotunda. Tour
staging areas would be held in the center instead of outdoors,
providing a protected entrance and enabling police to better manage
the flow of visitors by screening them outside the building.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of outside screening was heightened on July 24,
1998, when a lone gunman bypassed the metal detectors at an
entrance used by tourists, killing the officer at the checkpoint
and another guarding the office of House Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, before being apprehended.
</P>
<P>
   The center will also offer auditoriums and exhibits designed to
enhance the educational experience of Capitol visitors, in addition
to providing more restrooms, gift shops, and a cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Groundbreaking for the visitors center occurred on June 20, as
Capitol Preservation Commission members, with commemorative
shovels, turned soil and unveiled a plaque that will be laid
commemorating the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly an historic occasion, because this is the first
time since the East front extension in 1959 that we have had a
groundbreaking ceremony on Capitol grounds,'' said House Speaker J.
Dennis Hastert, co-chair of the CPC. ``We have begun the process of
constructing a facility that will enable us to take better care of
those who come to visit the 'People's House'.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the center will be shared by public and private
sources. Congress has appropriated $100 million for construction.
Private support from U.S. foundations, individuals, and
corporations is expected to raise another $100 million. More than
$35 million has been received to date from private donations.
</P>
<P>
   A series of environmental and archeological tests are being done
underneath the east plaza to determine the condition of the site
where the Visitors Center will ultimately be located. A final
design report will be issued to the commission in early fall, and a
final vote on the design will occur then.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitol Preservation Commission consists of 19 members, nine
members from both the House and Senate, and the Architect of the
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the web: Architect of the Capitol: www.aoc.gov
</P>
