<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9679 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-01 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ROUTINE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    HILL SHOULD STAY GOP, BUSH SAYS SOFTLY
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ No off-message dissent is being brooked at the
lock-step love-in that is the Republican National Convention, but
the careful listener can pick up faint murmurs of trouble ahead.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the charitable can write it off as merely ``different
emphases.'' But over the next three months, it could blow up into a
storm.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are divergent notions of the Bush campaign and the
national Republican Party leadership about how to fight at the same
time to regain the White House and to keep control of Congress.
It's a classic question that's almost always decided in favor of
the presidential candidate doing whatever is necessary to win. If
the House and Senate elections break the party's way, fine; if not,
too bad.
</P>
<P>
   That may be a bit cavalier for Republicans this year, given that
partisan control of the House really does hang in the balance. A
shift of six seats out of 435 to the Democrats would end the GOP
interregnum that began only in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, of course, would rather become president with
Republican majorities in both houses of Congress. Unified campaigns
will be run in many states to that end. But as long as the
presidential race remains fairly tight and public dissatisfaction
with the national legislature remains fairly strong, Bush is
unlikely to make retaining Republican control of Congress a major
issue in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Republican National Committee and the
House and Senate Republican campaign operations will be spending
millions of dollars on generic ads seeking to boost the chances of
the GOP remaining in power on both sides of Capitol Hill. More will
be laid out in individual races.
</P>
<P>
   The differing views of the Bush campaign and the institutional
Republican hierarchy in Washington on this point was evident in
comments to reporters here by Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist,
and Jim Nicholson, RNC &QL; 
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   For Nicholson, Armageddon seems to be approaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an historic election,'' the chairman said. ``It's really
a parliamentary election'' because the fate of all three branches
of government is at stake. Not since the days of Herbert Hoover
have Republicans controlled the White House and Congress, and had a
majority of Republican-appointed justices on the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Given the ages and health of some members of the Supreme Court,
it seems likely that the next president will fill enough vacancies
to alter the precarious 5-4 split on such fractious social issues
as abortion and gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that's how much we have riding on this thing,'' Nicholson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats share Nicholson's cataclysmic view, and the threat
that they see implicit in a GOP takeover of the entire government
is already a central theme of the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise then that Rove was less apocalyptic than
Nicholson in assessing the importance of the congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   ``All things being equal, we'd like to win,'' Rove said,
sounding like he was discussing a $2 ticket at a dog track.
</P>
<P>
   Rove pledged that the Bush folks will ``do our part'' to
maintain Republican majorities in the House and Senate, but he made
clear that was not the be-all, end-all for the high command in &QL; 
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, Rove said, would be ``prepared to deal with whatever kind
of circumstances face him'' on the congressional front.
</P>
<P>
   Rove, in fact, spent more time laying out how Bush had worked
with a divided government in Texas and explaining how the governor
``understood the prerogatives of the Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   This flows from Bush's theme about returning a bipartisan spirit
of cooperation to Washington, which flows from public disgust at
incessant bickering and &QL; 
gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have developed a perverse affection for divided
government but also an aversion to the constant clashes it seems
destined to produce. So for a presidential candidate to make a
strong, sustained pitch to give his party all the reins of
government could be risky.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has even shown he can light into congressional Republicans,
criticizing them last fall for trying to ``balance their budget on
the backs of the poor.'' It was a shrewd bid to distinguish his
``compassionate conservatism'' from the sledgehammer oafishness of
Tom DeLay &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton-Gore engineers the budget train wreck in September or
October that some skeptics foresee and seeks to blame the
Republicans, don't be surprised if Bush's attitude is ``a pox on
both.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes kicking two dogs is as easy as kicking one.
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
