<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GIULIANI-BOOK-REVIEW-     08-01 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-BOOK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CANDIDATE FOR NOTHING BUT UNDER 2 MICROSCOPES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
  Here are two ambitious books on the same subject, and almost a
single theme. The subject is Rudolph Giuliani, the most famous
mayor in the world and a surprise noncandidate for Senate. And the
theme is the depth of his flaws, despite the magnitude of his
accomplishments as a mayor. The fact is that voters will not be
using the information disclosed in these works to inform any
electoral decisions in the very near future. Still, the books tell
a great deal about recent local history and the role played in it
by one of the more compelling and energetic protagonists in
contemporary politics.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The books are Wayne Barrett's ``Rudy! An Investigative Biography
of Rudolph Giuliani,'' which is a major work of political
biography, and Andrew Kirtzman's ``Rudy Giuliani: Emperor of the
City,'' which is merely good.
</P>
<P>
   Kirtzman, who covers city politics for New York 1, focuses
entirely on Giuliani's career as an elected official, with little
about his background or even his earlier career as the U.S.
attorney for the Southern District in Manhattan. If his book were
the only one available about Giuliani, it would seem a competent,
informed, fair-minded though generally critical account of
Giuliani's life in city government.
</P>
<P>
   But Barrett, a veteran reporter for The Village Voice, has
written a book with broader shoulders and a deeper reach than
Kirtzman's. It is also an indefatigable accumulation of facts and
anecdotes about Giuliani guided by a muckraker's impulse to find an
unsavory maximum about him.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett unearths numerous details about Giuliani's family
background that, he contends, the mayor has assiduously tried to
keep secret, specifically that several of his close relatives,
including his father, were criminals. He analyzes his record as
U.S. attorney and finds a sizable gap between the record and the
Great Prosecutor's reputation. He goes back to Giuliani's career as
the youngest-ever associate attorney general in the Justice
Department and finds that he played a major role in devising the
Reagan administration's contradictory policy of interdicting
Haitian refugees while providing asylum for Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   Both Barrett and Kirtzman aver early on that New York has become
vastly better off in the years Giuliani has been mayor. ``It is
hard to overstate the degree to which the culture of the city
changed under his mayoralty,'' Kirtzman writes. By culture he means
such matters as the extent of homelessness, the sense of lurking
danger that New Yorkers used to live with on a daily basis, the
neighborhood pornography stores that Giuliani closed down.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett makes a similar overall judgment. ``There is little
question but that New York City has become a better place to live
on Rudy Giuliani's watch,'' he writes. ``It got dramatically safer
and cleaner. The tax load dipped and the budget surplus soared.''
But one senses a pro forma quality to that remark, which is
followed by nearly 500 pages portraying Giuliani as not just a
zealot, but so driven by his zeal that he is unaware of his own
corruptibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arrogance that is like body odor to Rudy,'' he writes in
his concluding chapter, ``repellent to others but undetectable to
him, is rooted, strangely enough, in his concept of clean hands. He
is never wrong, his swagger says, because he has spent his life
uncovering and combating wrong, a knight besieged but undaunted by
the compromised, confused and corrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't necessarily the case, contrary to an underlying
assumption in both of these books, that a flawed man can't make an
excellent mayor, but both authors do show direct connections
between the flaws _ an unwillingness to share public credit chief
among them _ and the city's problems. One important item in the
bill of indictment in this sense was City Hall's effort to push the
city's highly successful police commissioner, William Bratton, to
resign, mainly because Bratton was getting too much credit in the
press. Barrett contends that all the initiatives in the dramatic
reduction in crime that occurred in New York came from within the
Police Department. Still, he argues, Giuliani ``dumped Bratton when
polls showed that 60 percent of New Yorkers credited him, while
only 18 percent cited the mayor, for the two-year, 26.3 percent
drop in felonies.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is a relentlessness to Barrett's effort to discredit
Giuliani that gives the impression of a journalistic vendetta, and
yet there is much too much evidence in his book to ignore. (One
minor mystery is that Barrett provides footnote references for only
three of his 21 fact-packed chapters.) He details Giuliani's
unfaithfulness to two wives _ his first marriage, to his second
cousin Regina Peruggi, was annulled after 14 years. He mentions
about every sighting on the record of Giuliani and his chief press
aide, Cristyne Lategano, with whom he maintained an unseemly
closeness. ( Barrett, like other writers on this well-covered
subject, provides no hard proof of just how intimate the two were.)
He practically counts the failures of Giuliani to spend quality
time with his children.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett argues strenuously that Giuliani's record as U.S.
attorney was actually not as good as his predecessor's in that job
or as good as his rival's in the Eastern District in Brooklyn,
although he does allow that Giuliani won his share of major cases,
against organized crime and against corrupt Democratic politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of Rudy's term as U.S. Attorney, he had ushered in
the end of an era: the demise of Democratic machine politics in New
York City,'' he writes. Both Kirtzman and Barrett bring the
Giuliani story up to date _ to his withdrawal from the Senate race
after announcing almost simultaneously that he had prostate cancer
and that he and his wife, Donna Hanover, were separating.
</P>
<P>
   Kirtzman's book, while not as complete as Barrett's, is modestly
more generous in some ways. He is willing, for example, to
attribute to Giuliani sincerely held values and honest convictions
even while assiduously chronicling his faults. ``Giuliani believed
that his predecessors had gotten themselves and the city into
trouble by blurring the distinction between right and wrong,'' he
writes. ``His strategy was to stake out a principle, send a
consistent message, and refuse to compromise.'' Still, Kirtzman's
detailed account of Giuliani's pained relationship with Ramon
Cortines, the former schools chancellor, is a study in manipulative
unreasonableness.
</P>
<P>
   One has the sense that there is a degree of zeal in these books
_ more in Barrett's than in Kirtzman's _ that mirrors the Giuliani
zeal and that therefore leads the authors to miss a point. The
steady listing of personal and political flaws makes one wonder how
it is that, as both authors acknowledge, New York got so much
cleaner, safer and more prosperous with Giuliani in charge. One
reads these books with interest for their huge compilations of
facts and details, and yet one reads feeling also that the answer
to that question is missing in both.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `RUDY!: An Investigative Biography of Rudolph Giuliani'
</P>
<P>
   By Wayne Barrett
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 498 pages. Basic Books. $26. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `RUDY GIULIANI: Emperor of the City'
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Kirtzman
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 333 pages. William Morrow. $25. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
