reality show with a twist: This one followed a group of teens
through a Chicago-area high school during the '99-'00 school year.
Airs in two half-hour segments Wednesday against ``Big Brother's''
weekly life show on CBS. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   BILLBOARD-COMPILATION _ For the first time in Billboard magazine
history a non-soundtrack, multi-artist album debuted at the top of
the charts this week, ``Now That's What I Call Music 4.'' It's a
compilation of hits, but not of the old, K-Tel variety we used to
see advertised on late-night television. This series has pretty
recent hits, some of which are on current albums. The appeal is
obvious: It's pop radio without the commercial. But what does a
record label get out of cooperating with a project like this? After
all, it could take away from its own artists' sales. What does
Billboard think about a CD of already-proven hits charting? And
what's the chance of this U.S. phenom going the way of the
long-going British originals, which now are banned from the charts?
(SoMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
