<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9685 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-CVN-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-01 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
A RARE LEADER &HT;    By MARIANNE MEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Only rarely in history does a public figure come
along with great stature and popularity _ and no ambition to become
president.
</P>
<P>
   In retired Gen. Colin Powell, the country has such a remarkable
personage, a worthy successor to two other generals content to let
their fame speak for them _ George C. Marshall and Douglas
MacArthur.
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, part of their charm that although they could
not entirely escape the tentacles of presidential politics, they
never sought the office for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Why would Powell want the presidency anyway? He's already more
widely respected than President Clinton or this year's two main
presidential contenders. Some other fellows who build national
reputations look good until they let the public adulation go to
their heads, start to pick and choose among controversial issues
and stoop to name-calling. Suddenly, they make enemies and don't
seem so perfect any more. That happened to Ralph Nader, once a
greatly admired consumer advocate and now just a millionaire
egotist running for president as a spoiler.
</P>
<P>
   But it is difficult to find other leaders to compare Powell
with. Alas, he is one of a kind. Democratic guru Robert Strauss,
former ambassador to the old Soviet Union, comes close. So do
former Armed Services Chairman Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the late House
Speaker Sam Rayburn and the late Senate Republican Leader Everett
Dirksen.
</P>
<P>
   All giants, none White House occupants. But there aren't many
more.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's rare position at the pinnacle of public life was
dramatized at the Republican National Convention when no less than
Gov. George W. Bush himself, speaking via satellite, delivered a
lavish introduction to Powell's speech, an unprecedented compliment
from a future presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Powell went on to demonstrate his talent for words of wisdom,
urging greater national efforts to improve education, expand
opportunities for racial minorities and apply common sense to
foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The speech was clearly a warm-up for a role as Bush's secretary
of state, a job Powell does want.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who was President Bush's chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff and a central strategist in Operation Desert Storm that
forced Iraq out of Kuwait, is so universally popular that President
Clinton tried to lure him into the Democratic Party, and Dubya, as
his campaign heated up, repeatedly dangled the vice presidential
nomination. But Powell had promised his wife Alma _ who worried
that as the first African American on a major national political
ticket he might be assassinated _ that he would neither run for
president nor vice president. The Cabinet, however, is a different
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's performance was a dandy. It fit neatly into the
convention theme of kindly inclusiveness but it demanded that
Republicans really mean it . He didn't spare his audience of mostly
white delegates,
</P>
<P>
   reminding them forcefully that giving minorities a competitive
chance is an everyday task, not just a campaign-year slogan. ``Some
in our party roundly and loudly condemn affirmative action that
helped a few thousand black kids get an education, but hardly a
whimper is heard from them over affirmative action for lobbyists
who load our federal tax codes with preferences for special
interests,''' he thundered. Ouch. A painful truth.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knew that Powell was a loyal Bush backer. He could get
away with dumping a little rain on Bush's sunny parade here. In
fact, there's not much he can't get away with. Nobody can accuse
him of not being his own man.
</P>
<P>
   He also lectured the Republicans on the proper uses of military
power, warning that our armed strength cannot serve just ``the
well-to-do, the comfortable, the privileged.'' He talked about
national education initiatives that go further than the GOP
platform proposals. He is on the team, but not singing by rote from
the party script.
</P>
<P>
   Powell arrived at his invincible position the hard way _ he
earned it. He rose steadily through the military ranks before he
became a White House fellow in 1972. There, he was discovered by
Reagan and Bush administration officials who were excited to find
an articulate, discreet, intelligent and conservative black officer
capable of leading armies. Given their trust, Powell delivered. And
so did they.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years of our republic, career military men often
made it to the White House. But since World War II a uniform has
seldom been a boost to a political career. Powell is so exceptional
it is difficult to compare him with past heroes.
</P>
<P>
   When he retired as a four-star general in 1993, he wrote a
memoir that sold like Pennsylvania pretzels and further enhanced
his reputation. Recently, he has directed a national project to
encourage community volunteerism to help children _ an effort that
has bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   His selfless service ranks up there with that of the great Gen.
George C. Marshall, a World War II hero who served as President
Harry Truman's secretary of state and initiated the massive postwar
aid program that rebuilt Europe and became known as the Marshall
Plan. Marshall, who had his hands full with conservatives who
feared he was wasting money overseas, had no interest in seeking
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Another great general was Douglas MacArthur, who was so popular
in his day that when Truman fired him in 1951 for refusing to
follow orders in Korea, MacArthur was greeted by cheering crowds
and a ticker-tape parade in New York City. A week after he was
fired, he addressed a joint session of Congress and delivered his
famous line that ``old soldiers never die; they just fade away.''
In 1952, some Republicans launched a boomlet for him for president,
but MacArthur discouraged it. Besides, Gen. Dwight Eisenhower and
Sen. Robert Taft had the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Powell doesn't have any delegates either. He doesn't need them.
He has himself, which is quite enough.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
