<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMS-MAGIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TEAM FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAT WILLIAMS   (Pat Williams is senior vice president of the
National Basketball Association's Orlando Magic; this was written
with Geoffrey Brewer.)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My first wife, Jill, and I adopted 14 children between 1983 and
1993. We had been married 11 years and already had three birth
children.
</P>
<P>
   At first, I resisted adopting; I couldn't fathom it. Jill was
initially the driving force, but then I became the aggressor. I
learned everything I could about adoption and threw myself into it.
</P>
<P>
   In our first adoptions, we brought home two little girls, Sarah
and Andrea, from South Korea in September of 1983. After that, the
floodgates started opening. Over the next 10 years, as we heard of
children who needed homes, we would adopt them. We also had another
birth child, Michael. We brought home children from the
Philippines, Romania, Brazil and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Many images stay with me from our visits to orphanages. I
remember going to Brazil in the summer of 1992, the same summer the
Magic drafted Shaquille O'Neal, and we were just flabbergasted by
the living conditions. There were countless numbers of children of
every size, shape and color, all longing for a home. They were like
goldfish, with wide eyes, like they were swimming in a bowl. Their
physical needs were being met, but they needed more.
</P>
<P>
   We came out of there wanting to adopt every kid we saw. We
brought home two from Brazil in February of 1993, Richie and
Daniela, who were both 11. Later that year, on Christmas night, we
brought home two more, Caroline, who was 10, and Alan, who was 8.
At that age, they are basically unadoptable. Most families want
infants.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, I've had wonderful help in raising these children.
We've always had a great nanny, and we have had people come in and
cook. You can learn a lot about management from managing 18 kids. I
have tried to give them each special attention, but it's a daily
struggle. I have breakfast with them, drive them to school and go
to their sporting events. But my life is demanding, and it's been
challenging to keep the thing afloat financially. Also, I usually
travel three or four times a month.
</P>
<P>
   Things certainly didn't get easier when Jill filed for divorce
after 23 years of marriage. July 5, 1995, the day I got the divorce
papers from her lawyer, was the worst day of my life. I was
flabbergasted, devastated.
</P>
<P>
   We had had many long discussions. All I can say is, she wasn't
happy. She wanted to go in another direction and start a new life.
I felt like I had tumbled into a black hole, and never felt so
helpless. Since Jill didn't get custody of the kids, I was left to
raise 18 of them by myself. This was never part of the game plan
when we had talked about adoption.
</P>
<P>
   That September, at a seminar on time management and
organizational skills, I met Ruth. I was in my mid-50s, and the
odds of a woman falling in love with me knowing that I had 18 kids?
Well, that kind of narrows the field, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   We married in April 1997. At one point last year, there were 16
teen-agers in our family at the same time. The pressures on
teen-agers are enormous today, with alcohol, drugs, rock music and
the media. It's an era of almost-anything-goes. But Little Ruth,
who has a grown daughter of her own, has helped me raise those
children, even while she has continued working and traveling. She
came to me like some kind of miracle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
