<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-SPENDING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMERS SPEND HEARTILY, ECONOMISTS WORRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   US consumer spending rose at its fastest pace in three months,
providing new evidence for economists who argue interest rate hikes
have failed to slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Commerce said Tuesday that personal spending
on goods and services in June outpaced growth in personal incomes,
as it has during much of an expansion. Record employment levels
have kept consumers flush and eager to spend all _ even more than _
they earn.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending, which accounts for about two-thirds of the
economy, rose last month by 0.5 percent, compared with a 0.4
percent increase in personal incomes in June. Spending was driven
in part by a rebound in auto sales, which drove spending on durable
goods.
</P>
<P>
   The latest data shows an acceleration of May's activity, when
spending and incomes stayed even, each rising at a revised pace of
0.3 percent. Consumer spending rose only 0.2 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   The June spending jump was one detail embedded in a broader
report, issued last week by the Commerce Department, which showed
that US gross domestic product expanded 5.2 percent in the second
quarter, outperforming first-quarter growth of 4.8 percent.
Economists seized on that report to argue that the Federal Reserve
has not brought growth down to a more sustainable pace _ one that
would not cause an acceleration in inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised interest rates six times since June and will
meet again on Aug. 22 to consider another rate increase. Richard
Yamarone, economist for Argus Research Corp., a private firm in New
York, believes the Fed may be forced to raise rates again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty apparent that we never got a soft landing,''
Yamarone said. ``In fact, we never got a landing at all. the
economy continues to soar unfettered.''
</P>
<P>
   Most observers agree the economy needs to slow from its
breakneck pace of growth. But, in truth, the signals are more
mixed, as is often the case in a maturing expansion. There is
heated debate among economists about whether the economy has cooled
and whether the Fed believes a seventh rate hike is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   For example, analysts noted the jump in spending last month was
due to an oil-driven spike in inflation. The higher prices tended
to inflate what consumers paid for the goods they purchased, from
gasoline to plastic razors, economists said. The Commerce
Department's consumer spending figures, adjusted for inflation,
increased only 0.2 percent in June _ far less than a 0.5 percent
rate, unadjusted for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Personal spending ``wasn't strong,'' said Nicholas Perna, an
economist and consultant in Richfield, Conn., citing the ``big
pickup in inflation'' in June.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a mix of signals that also include a softer housing market,
analysts agreed that the government's report on July job growth, to
be released Friday, would be a significant indicator of the
economy's strength and would be watched closely by the Federal.
</P>
<P>
   In June, total government and private employment grew only by
11,000 jobs, a tepid comeback from May, when private payrolls had
plunged. Nevertheless, economists said the job market remains very
strong, putting upward pressure on spending _ and inflation _ in
the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The central issue facing Fed policy makers, as explained by
Richard Rippe, managing director and chief economist for Prudential
Securities Inc.: ``The economy is at full employment already, so if
we continue to grow at a pace faster than supply is growing _ now
that we're at full employment _ there's likely to be inflationary
pressure down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing activity remained steady in July, ending a
four-month decline, according to the National Association of
Purchasing Managers, which surveys executives who buy raw materials
and other supplies for industry. The association said its
production index was unchanged from 51.8 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
   William Cheney, chief economist for John Hancock Financial
Services Inc., said the purchasing manager's number ``was a little
weaker than expected. That's the kind of number the Fed would be
reassured by.''
</P>
<P>
   But he explained that data often conflict when an economy is in
transition, hence a strong rise in spending and second-quarter
growth at the same time there is a slowing in housing sales due to
the Fed rate hikes.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said the data is ``confusing,'' and economists ``have
been misled before.'' In the fall of 1998, however, the economy
began to slow but then picked up again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the economy was slowing down before and it's turned
out not to. It's come steaming right back,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9698 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-GOP-JACKSON-BOS &LR;      08-01 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-JACKSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REV. JACKSON URGES TREATMENT, NOT JAIL, FOR DRUG ABUSERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Rev. Jesse L. Jackson Tuesday demanded that
Republican and Democratic leaders start sending nonviolent drug
abusers to treatment centers rather than to the nation's crowded
prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 2 million people in prison. That is an international
scandal,'' said Jackson, leader of the Rainbow Coalition. Inmates
``come to prison sicker . . . and come out slicker,'' he said. ``We
have to wipe out recidivism.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was the main attraction at the Shadow Convention, an
alternative event organized by Common Cause, conservative
commentator Arianna Huffington, and a host of public interest
groups to focus on issues they say are being ignored by the
Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jackson, 80 percent of the inmates in prison for
drug arrests have been charged with nonviolent crimes. He also said
most of the people crowding the prisons are either African-American
or Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Jackson, a recovering addict who attended the
standing-room only speech, agreed with the civil right's leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sending drug addicts to prison really doesn't do anything but
hardens a person,'' said Jackson, of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   While the civil rights leader's fire-and-brimstone speech
contrasted to the scholarly but emotional address of retired
General Colin Powell the previous night at the GOP convention,
their messages were similar.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson echoed Powell, the Republican Party's most prominent
African-American figure, who told the delegates that blacks are
cynical about the party's opposition to affirmative action.
Jackson, who in 1984 was the first African-American to make a
serious run for the White House, said building schools not prisons
would help curb crime and violence in the country's urban
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Colin Powell was a statesman . . . I think he is
correct to stand on the platform and preach moral values,'' Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson said Powell's compassionate appeal for inclusiveness
does not reflect the conservative ideologies of the party's
leaders, such as Senators Trent Lott of Mississippi and Strom
Thurmond of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, another high-profile civil right's leader
criticized the Republican's strategic appeal to minorities and
women at the convention. Sharpton, who talked to reporters as he
walked through the media pavillion Tuesday, said he was invited to
the GOP convention by Armstrong Williams, a black Republican and
radio commentator. Sharpton said Republicans were using blacks and
Hispanics to show a moderate face when most party members and
delegates are wealthy white men.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Sharpton also said Governor George W. Bush's
decision to chose Dick Cheney, a former Wyoming congressman and
former defense secretary, as a running mate is proof that the party
is not changing its views.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say let's have a new game when you are playing
with your same old teammates on the field,'' Sharpton said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, however, Cheney said he would now vote in
favor of the Equal Rights Amendment, Head Start funding, as well as
a ban on ``cop killer'' bullets, issues he voted against in the
1980s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
