<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-DEBT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH KOREAN CONGLOMERATES STILL HAVE DEBT PROBLEMS, NEW DATA
SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ It has been nearly three years since the
South Korean government ordered the nation's largest business
conglomerates to reduce their staggering debts. But official
statistics released Tuesday showed that the debt levels of most of
the conglomerates remained significantly higher than what the
government considers acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the major conglomerates reported their debt
levels in consolidated financial statements, which bring together
all the assets and liabilities of a parent company and its
subsidiaries. Under an earlier accounting system, the true extent
of a conglomerate's debt was hard to determine, obscured by the
ability of subsidiaries to finance each other's loans.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Samsung, South Korea's second-largest business
conglomerate, and Lotte, a hotel, food and beverage group, the
nation's largest conglomerates failed to lower their debt-to-equity
ratios below 200 percent. That level, which means that a company's
long-term debts are twice as high as the vale of its stock, was
imposed by the government last year under new methods of evaluating
the size of liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Lowering the huge amounts of debt held by the conglomerates has
been a focus of the Seoul government's financial and economic
reform plans since the nation was forced to seek a $58 billion
bailout package from the International Monetary Fund late in 1997.
The debts of these conglomerates have been cited as one of the main
causes of the financial crisis and the recession that followed.
</P>
<P>
   The average corporate debt-to-equity ratio stood at 225 percent,
according to the Financial Supervisory Commission, which has been
overseeing the restructuring of the conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   Among the top four business groups, the debt-to-equity ratio of
Hyundai was 229.7 percent, LG 273.2 percent, SK 227.6 percent and
Samsung 194.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the average debt-to-equity ratio rose to 349 percent when
the highly leveraged financial units of the conglomerates were
included, with Hyundai's rising to 296 percent and Samsung's to 443
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the statistics, government officials expressed optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debt levels were a lot lower than we had expected,'' said
Lee Suk Jun, a manager at the commission's corporate accounting
division. ``In fact, the debt ratios, excluding financial units,
have actually gone down _ a sign we consider as a significant
improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were also optimistic that the new system of accounting
for debts would lead to more effective ways to reduce them. ``It's
what we were expecting from a fully consolidated balance sheet,''
said Paulo Rhee, deputy head of chief at HSBC in Seoul. ``I'm
positive that we're seeing more transparent numbers. Now we know
more clearly what the problem areas are and the magnitude of the
debt levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, said that financial support among the
subsidiaries of a conglomerate remained a problem. Jang Ha-sung, a
campaigner for minority shareholder rights and professor of
business administration at Korea University, said the level of
transactions between the same conglomerate's subsidiaries is ``a
lot higher than I thought.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
