<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALTERING STEPS OF A NEW SITCOM; LOOKING FOR A BOOST FROM
`SURVIVOR' 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Richards, who played Kramer on ``Seinfeld,'' has not had
an easy time producing his new sitcom. Called ``The Michael
Richards Show,'' the comedy is about a bumbling private detective,
played by Richards. It will make its debut on NBC this fall.
</P>
<P>
   NBC executives considered the show's pilot episode so lacking in
hilarity that they refused to show it to critics who gathered last
month in Pasadena, Calif., to learn more about the network's fall
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   With production scheduled to begin next week, the show has been
retooled. The pilot was shot by a single camera, but new episodes
will be filmed with four cameras on a traditional sitcom set and
before a studio audience. Also, Richards will be joined by new cast
members, an apparent ``Seinfeld''-like ensemble, including Tim
Meadows of ``Saturday Night Live,'' William Devane of ``Knots
Landing'' and Amy Farrington, who was most recently a guest star on
``E.R.''
</P>
<P>
   Several people close to the production have said that the script
for the first episode also had some major problems and needed
reworking.
</P>
<P>
   But Spike Feresten, one of the show's creators, said that
despite having ``some problems with some jokes here or there,''
Richards was now quite happy with his first episode. Still, to
ensure that everything goes smoothly, Richards has ``been in the
room writing with us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the project did not have Richards as its star, all of this
retooling could be very worrisome for NBC, which, like the other
networks, is struggling to develop a new hit comedy and has high
hopes for the program. But executives there have repeatedly said
that even the original, junked pilot scored high marks with test
audiences, which are apparently still quite fond of Richards from
his ``Seinfeld'' days.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to see him on television and they're excited that
he's coming back,'' said Shirley Powell, an NBC spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said that executives were optimistic about the show's
future and that any changes in the scripts were a normal part of
the process of producing a new TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Feresten said that the first episode was to be shot on Aug. 18.
After that, he said, the producers will show outlines for future
episodes to network executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our hope they'll see the comedy in there,'' he said.
``But there are talented writers in  &UR; that room,  &LR; too.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be plenty of time to fix any problems that may arise.
The show is not scheduled to make its debut until Oct. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Richards was not available for comment. But when he was asked
about the state of his new show last month by the critics in
Pasadena, he said, ``There's no trouble here.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jim Rutenberg
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a `Survivor' Lift
</P>
<P>
   Is everybody at CBS happy to finally have a breakthrough hit
like ``Survivor?''
</P>
<P>
   Not if you include David Letterman, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman expressed a bit of unhappiness on the air on Monday
night during some joking cross-talk with his band leader, Paul
Shaffer, suggesting that CBS was not helping ``the whole CBS
family'' as much as it could with ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   When Shaffer asked several times what he meant, Letterman was
not specific but did agree that his discontent had something to do
with the show's scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Letterman has called some CBS executives in Hollywood
wondering _ in what one executive called a mostly humorous way _ if
perhaps the hit show might be moved to a place that would prove
more advantageous to his ``Late Show,'' say 9 p.m. or 10 p.m,
instead of 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' has set ratings records this summer, reaching close
to 30 million people on Wednesday nights from 8 to 9, including
more young adult viewers than any other show on CBS by a huge
margin.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman has long suffered from not being able to promote his
show to many young adult viewers because so few of them watch CBS,
and his producers have long pointed out that he is at a distinct
disadvantage against his main rival, Jay Leno at NBC because of
CBS's 10 o'clock weeknight shows.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has ``E.R.'' and two editions of ``Law and Order,'' while
CBS has ``Judging Amy'' as its only real 10 p.m. hit.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with ``Survivor,'' from Letterman's point of view,
is that many of the viewers it has been attracting in droves have
drifted away from CBS by 11 p.m. On several nights Letterman made a
particular comic target of ``Falcone,'' which CBS was using at 10
p.m for a while, for driving away the remnants of that big
``Survivor'' audience.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Pope, the show's executive producer, said Tuesday, ``We
have not asked formally that the show be moved to 9 p.m.,'' though
she acknowledged that she had ``made a pitch for `Survivor II' to
be moved to 9.'' She said, ``I don't know if Dave has called
himself about it.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS plans a second round of castaway adventures _ this time in
the Australian outback _ to start in January. The network has not
committed itself to a time period for ``Survivor II,'' but
Wednesday Leslie Moonves, the president of CBS Television, said,
``It could definitely go at 9 next time.''
</P>
<P>
   He ruled out starting the show at 10 because it has a
significant audience of children.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves noted that the ratings for ``Survivor'' had always been
bigger from 8:30 to 9 than from 8 to 8:30, suggesting that the show
might be even a bigger hit if it started at 9 p.m., when more
viewers overall are available to watch television.
</P>
<P>
   But Moonves pointed out that ``Survivor'' had already helped
Letterman considerably. ``We had our biggest Wednesday night in
months for Dave last week,'' he said. On that occasion CBS followed
``Survivor'' with its other summer reality show, ``Big Brother,''
and far more of the audience was carried over.
</P>
<P>
   That Letterman show scored a 4.3 overnight rating, well above
the 3.6 the show is averaging for the summer. For the weeks since
``Survivor'' started, Letterman is up about 25 percent in total
viewers over the comparable weeks last year, to about 4.35 million
from about 3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly we're delighted that `Survivor' is on CBS,'' Pope
said. ``I wish we had more shows like that.'' She acknowledged that
promotions for Letterman's show run regularly on `Survivor' and
``it's very helpful to reach that young audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Pope said that the Letterman team was looking forward to the
night of the finale of ``Survivor'' on Aug. 23, which CBS has
turned into a three-hour ``Survivor'' extravaganza: two hours to
settle which contestant wins the $1 million prize followed by an
hourlong ``town meeting'' with the 16 original participants.
</P>
<P>
   That will lead directly into the local newscasts and then to
Letterman.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Carter
</P>
</TEXT>
