<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASHMIR-ATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRORISTS FIRE ON HINDU PILGRIMS IN KASHMIR 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI _ Apparently in an effort to subvert the budding peace
effort in Kashmir, terrorists opened fire Tuesday on an area
crowded with Hindu pilgrims. They killed at least 20 people in
Pahalgam, 60 miles south of Srinagar, the summer capital of the
Indian state of Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The attack occurred around sundown, the authorities said. The
target appeared to be both Indian security forces and the pilgrims
whom they were guarding. Thousands of people were in the area, on
their way to the holy cave at Amaranth, where the Lord Shiva is
worshiped in the form of a lingam-shaped ice block.
</P>
<P>
   Early reports from the police indicated that the dead included
pilgrims, Indian soldiers and two heavily armed militants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, groups who do not like peace restored _ peace to
come back _ will do these things,'' said Ashok Bhan, the inspector
general of police in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Hizbul Mujahideen, the largest anti-India
militant group operating in the state, declared a unilateral
three-month cease-fire, setting the stage for talks with the Indian
government and the possible end to more than a decade of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Other militant groups have objected to the peace overture,
condemned the Hizbul as traitors and pledged to step up their
attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9706 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-AFRIQUE-DANCE-ADV06-2     08-01 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRIQUE-DANCE-ADV06-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTNERS IN DANCE MEET AT THE INTERSECTION OF TWO CULTURES
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: For release Sunday, Aug. 6) 
By CHRISTOPHER REARDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Germaine Acogny was sitting in a Viennese cafe four summers ago,
smoking her pipe, when a blond woman with a broad, animated face
sauntered in. Acogny recognized her as Susanne Linke, the gutsy
German dancer she had once seen on television performing an
anguished duet with a claw-foot bathtub.
</P>
<P>
   Acogny took the liberty of introducing herself, for she, too,
was a dancer of some renown. Maurice Bejart, calling her ``my
African double,'' had enlisted her in 1977 to open a branch of his
modernist dance school in Senegal, the former French colony where
she grew up.
</P>
<P>
   The school, known as Mudra Afrique, ran out of money within five
years, but Acogny was ready to try again. After more than a dozen
years in France, she had decided to start a new school for
traditional and contemporary African dance in Senegal. Perhaps
Linke, she suggested, would like to come teach a workshop.
</P>
<P>
   Their chance encounter ultimately gave rise to ``Le Coq Est
Mort,'' an earnest but problematic production that will open on
August 9 at the Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival in Becket, Mass.
Choreographed by Linke, the 70-minute piece centers on eight
African men who cast off the trappings of Western culture and renew
their connection with nature.
</P>
<P>
   Some spectators questioned Linke's artistic vision when
Compagnie Jant-Bi, the fledgling troupe affiliated with Acogny's
school of the same name, performed it last year in Senegal, France,
Germany, Italy and Canada. The flash point was a scene in which the
dancers, who are black, cavort like apes. Linke, who is white, has
maintained that the scene is being crudely misread.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, ``Le Coq Est Mort'' sheds light on some of the
tensions inherent in working with people from other cultures, a
practice that is gaining favor among performing artists. At the
Lincoln Center Festival, for example, the French choreographer
Mathilde Monnier recently presented ``Pour Antigone,'' her 1991-93
collaboration with dancers and a drummer from Burkina Faso and
Mali. In October the Brooklyn Academy of Music will stage ``Tree,''
Ralph Lemon's joint venture with artists from India, China, Taiwan,
Japan, Ivory Coast and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Acogny and Linke, both 56, saw their partnership as an
opportunity to forge a new alloy of West African physicality and
European expressionism. In a recent telephone interview from
Germany, Linke traced her affinity for dance _ and expressionist
movement in particular _ to her childhood. As an infant she had
meningitis, and it kept her from speaking until she was 6. Out of
necessity, she learned to communicate with hand gestures. ``That
had a great influence on my life,'' she said. ``Even now, body
language is closer to me, more natural to me, than speaking with
words. I prefer to move.''
</P>
<P>
   To develop her talent, she sought out some of the most inventive
figures in German dance _ from Mary Wigman, the pioneering
expressionist, to Hans Zullig, a successor to Kurt Jooss at the
Folkwang School, an influential dance academy in Essen. She also
danced briefly for Pina Bausch, who attended the school a decade
ahead of her.
</P>
<P>
   Although Linke directed the Folkwang Dance Studio for 10 years,
and the Bremen Theater for another 6, she is best known for her
solos. Typically, they are stark portraits of women in distress,
but instead of passing off tired archetypes she achieves a
psychological depth that is eerily persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   Acogny abides by a more earthy aesthetic. Speaking on the phone
from France, she likened her dancing to ``a big tree, with deep
roots and branches that reach to the sky.'' (She offers the same
metaphor in ``Danse Africaine,'' a book on technique that she
published in Germany and Senegal in 1980.) ``I'm trying to make a
connection between tradition and modernity,'' she said. ``I take
pride in my personal heritage, but still I want to go in a
contemporary direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Her first break came, oddly enough, when she was asked to help
``Africanize'' a platoon of drum majorettes in Dakar, the
Senegalese capital. Her fusion of stately marching and polyrhythmic
stamping caught the eye of Leopold Senghor, Senegal's first
president. A poet as well, Senghor became famous before
independence for expressing Africa's social and political mood in
lyrical French, spawning the literary movement known as Negritude.
</P>
<P>
   It was Senghor who introduced her to Bejart and marshaled the
funds for Mudra Afrique. Like Mudra (a Sanskrit term for gesture),
Bejart's school in Brussels, it took a cosmopolitan approach, with
classes in ballet, modern dance, traditional African dance,
drumming and singing.
</P>
<P>
   Money was always tight, but after Senghor left office the school
was hard pressed to continue. Acogny soon moved to France, opening
a school for Euro-African dance outside Toulouse and creating solos
for herself. Her signature piece, ``Ye'ou, the Awakening,'' won a
Time Out London Dance and Performance Award in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Senegal a few years later, she bought some land in
Toubab Dialaw, a fishing village 30 miles south of Dakar. When
Linke arrived there in 1998 for the inaugural session of the new
school, she found 28 dancers _ most of them Senegalese men _ but no
studio. The dancers stayed with local families and shared meals
prepared by some of the village women. Classes were held on the
beach or under a large baobab tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a pioneer project,'' said Helmut Vogt, a German
entrepreneur who met _ and then married _ Acogny after reading her
book 18 years ago. ``When we bought this land there was no water,
no electricity. There was only sand and stone.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by ``the energy and power'' of the dancers, Linke
returned last year to create a new work. With Acogny, she assembled
a troupe of eight male students _ six from Senegal, one from
Nigeria and one from the Congo Republic. The new company took its
name from the school; Jant-Bi means sun in Wolof, the Senegalese
dancers' native tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I make a dance, I always have a strong concept and
meaning in mind when I start,'' said Linke, who had never been to
Africa before she met Acogny. ``But this time I went without any
idea. Only the energy was important to me.''  &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Linke and her assistant, an Israeli choreographer named Avi
Kaiser, spent the first few weeks guiding the dancers in a series
of improvisations. For example, they experimented with leaping and
falling to get around the difficulty of turning in the sand. (Sand
became so integral to the dance that Jacob's Pillow will truck in
nearly 10 tons of it this week to blanket the stage of the Ted
Shawn Theater.)
</P>
<P>
   As themes of power, competition and war began to emerge, Linke
fashioned a narrative about a community that rediscovers its
cultural identity. The title, she said, expresses a desire to be
free of French domination, male swagger and the roosters that woke
the dancers each morning in Toubab Dialaw. (``We wanted to kill
them,'' she said.)
</P>
<P>
   The dance begins with eight men, dressed as diplomats or
businessmen, who traverse the sand in complex patterns, stopping
occasionally to shake hands or exchange briefcases. Eventually they
grow frustrated and, as the shrill sound of Shostakovich gives way
to spirited drumming, their stiff formal abstractions take on spry,
demonstrative quality.
</P>
<P>
   Shirtless, the men later scamper about like gorillas, with tight
shoulders, bent wrists and a bounding gait. Their reverie is
shattered by the sound of gunfire, and most of them fall to they
ground. Returning to human form, they rise and sing an anthem
associated with traditional Senegalese wrestling matches. Linke
said she used it as an exhortation to resist the homogenizing
forces of modern society.
</P>
<P>
   At first the monkey scene troubled Acogny, who feared that
audiences might take it the wrong way, and she suggested that Linke
cut it. But when they consulted the troupe, the dancers insisted on
keeping the sequence, which they liked for its technical challenges
and intrinsic beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers in Toubab Dialaw voiced no complaints, Acogny said,
when ``Le Coq Est Mort'' had its premiere last year in the school's
new outdoor performance space. She said the only criticism came
from ``black and white intellectuals'' who view the dance through
the lens of colonialism.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying question is whether any motive can justify a
white choreographer's decision to have black dancers mimic animals.
Can an artist reasonably expect the audience to view such images
without recalling the painful narrative of slavery, colonialism and
racism?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my opinion that blacks are closer to monkeys than
whites,'' said Linke. ``To me, it's a symbol of an ancestor that we
all share.''
</P>
<P>
   To some critics, though, it doesn't matter whether the dancers
move like apes or angels; as long as a white person is calling the
shots, some exploitation is inevitable. Indeed, many artists who
have forged international creative partnerships have found the
dynamics of power far more daunting than language barriers, the
logistics of overseas travel or aesthetic differences.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Acogny attested to Linke's equitable relationship with
the troupe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Susanne never imposed things on the dancers,'' she said. ``She
always spoke with them first. And the dancers gave the
improvisations, they gave the movement phrases, and they created
the work together.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
