<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9709 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-LATIN-MUSIC-ADV06-2TA     08-01 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-MUSIC-ADV06-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUCH OF LATIN POP, AGING AND STERILE, ISN'T KEEPING PACE
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: for release Sunday, August 6) 
 By PETER WATROUS     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year was a great year for Latin music, and by extension
Latin culture, in the United States, if one accepts that the
enthusiastic reception of Latin music by non-Latinos was a true
indication of the music's health. What happened, in fact, was that
some of Latin music's most popular artists _ Ricky Martin in Latin
pop and Marc Anthony in salsa _ made records in English that were
huge sellers in the United States. As might be expected, the
English-speaking press took notice.
</P>
<P>
   The attendant articles and discussions promoted the idea of a
flowering of Latin culture. The news media were discovering what
had long been obvious to marketers, advertisers and venture
capitalists: The Spanish-speaking population in the United States
was growing and asserting itself culturally through its buying
habits.
</P>
<P>
   Optimists saw a rosy, multicultural future, in which the Anglo
majority gave up some cultural room to the Hispanic minority,
slapping them on the back and inviting them over to dinner.
Meanwhile, pessimists grumbled and waited. In their view, Latin
music in the United States was in big trouble, facing internal and
external conflicts that were largely ignored by the commentators.
And now, a year later, the fault lines have grown wider. As the
pessimists predicted, the non-Hispanic media have lost interest in
the story, and Latin music in the United States continues its
tumble toward a state of crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Salsa, the dance music from Puerto Rico and New York, offers a
case in point. It is virtually dead both in terms of sales and the
paucity of promising new artists. Where Marc Anthony, at the peak
of his success three years ago, sold 400,000 copies of his album
``Contra la Corriente,'' the newest pretender to his throne, George
Lamond, sold 41,000 copies of his album ``Entrega'' last year,
putting him in the league of a good-selling jazz artist. (By
comparison, Keith Jarrett's solo piano record ``The Melody at
Night, With You'' was a hit last year, selling 84,000 copies.)
</P>
<P>
   Latin record distributors along 10th Avenue in Manhattan are
clamoring for new records to push to stores _ and not finding any.
What is showing up, from labels large and small, is dreadful, badly
produced and profoundly out of step with the times. To appeal to
young consumers, salsa, like all pop music, must reflect their
concerns. But there are few salsa singers under 30, and none
showing much more than modest promise.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't the artists' fault. The problems are systemic. In New
York, where there had been hundreds of clubs in the 1960s and
1970s, places where artists could learn how to play and the art of
dominating a room, there are now only a handful. Much the same
thing is happening in Puerto Rico. And salsa record companies are a
generation or two behind the time, selling salsa's elders, dressed
in coat and tie, to teenagers who are just as much a product of
hip-hop as they are of classic salsa. In a grave misstep, record
companies have stifled innovation in salsa, and as a result the
music has suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Radio, once the music's lifeblood, has become a major part of
the problem, sticking to imitations of years-old hits and ignoring
new, youth-oriented trends, most notably timba, the dance music
coming out of Cuba. Mega (WSKQ, 97.9 FM), the tropical station in
New York, which was in the No. 2 spot last fall, fell to No. 6 this
spring, according to the latest Arbitron ratings. Its programming
has become lackluster, the music has grown stale and,
unsurprisingly, listeners have tuned out.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening in salsa is symptomatic of the difficulties
facing all Latin music in the United States, and the reasons are
many. Latin teen-agers flex their bicultural muscles, moving
through all the musical genres available on the radio and among
their peers. It's entirely possible for a Latin teen-ager in New
York to listen to the rapper Jay-Z one minute, the rock group
Matchbox 20 the next and the reggae singer Sean Paul a moment
later. All of it is well-made pop, tailored to the dance floor. It
sounds good, translates well to radio and is on the receiving end
of lots of promotional money from record companies, much of it
aimed at the teen-age market. Teen-agers are buying the comfort of
mass success.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists, advertisers and marketers are now hedging
their bets, revising investments in the Latin market on the
assumption that assimilation may rob the market of its uniform
buying power. Experience has shown them that the influence of
national loyalty lasts one generation, then shows up only
occasionally thereafter. Latin teen-agers act just like any other
American teen-agers, voting their aesthetic preference every time
they buy music or turn on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible for salsa, and Latin pop more generally, to be a
part of teen-agers' listening habits, but it has to meet their
definition of hipness (which more than ever means blackness),
danceability and both songwriting and technological sophistication.
In its current state, it comes with none of these elements. When
two second-generation New York Spanish-speaking teen-agers were
asked to name the top three salsa stars a few weeks ago, they
shrugged and said: ``There aren't any. Maybe DLG'' _ a reference to
Dark Latin Groove, a salsa group with an urban sound.
</P>
<P>
   But something else profound is happening in the world of Latin
music: It's exploding with creativity, with uncountable genres
mutating and spawning across the Americas, virtually none of which
have had commercial success in the United States. Mainstream Latin
music companies are pinning their hopes on an astoundingly narrow
group of artists, mostly pop crooners and smooth salsa singers.
This isn't to argue that pop music from elsewhere in the world has
produced an abundance of personalities, but Latin pop simply hasn't
kept pace.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, an audience for different forms of Latin music
exists in the United States, and it needs cultivation. Unlike the
United States, many of the countries of Latin America, until
recently, never developed an audience large enough to sustain the
kind of intelligent experimentalism now taking place in Latin pop
under the rubric of rock en espanol. But Latin music has failed to
develop an infrastructure to support anything but the most obvious
music like classic salsa. The success of Latin pop, for example,
depends, like much of popular culture in Latin countries, on its
relationship to telenovelas, the Spanish- and Portuguese-language
soap operas that promote glamour and escapism. An alternative
rocker doesn't stand much of a chance of using that medium, nor
does a salsa singer, especially one with dark skin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Radio could help, but it hasn't. Rock en espanol, which over the
last several years has produced a slew of exceptional albums aimed
at a sophisticated, young audience, doesn't get played on Latin
radio, and the few commercial radio stations in the United States
that do, only do so occasionally. Without radio airplay,
disseminating the music is almost impossible. Worse, the Latin
major labels are run by people whose strengths are in marketing pop
or tropical music, and they don't really know how to market music
outside those genres. Consider ``Caribe Atomico,'' a 1998 album by
the Colombian group Aterciopelados that is a beautiful experimental
rock record and one of the genre's best. It was released by the
Latin affiliate of a major American label and sold just under
10,000 copies in the United States. Notwithstanding such failures,
bands and record labels are looking for ways to break with past
practice: The next albums by Titan, an experimental hip-hop and pop
hybrid from Mexico, and Manu Chao, a French and Spanish group, will
be released through the non-Latino side of Virgin Records and
treated as priorities.
</P>
<P>
   So as the second generation of Latins in the United States
continues to grow and develop more sophisticated tastes, the
appetite for less mainstream music is likely to expand beyond
artists in the Ricky Martin or Marc Anthony mold. Shows by bands
from Cuba in the United States used to draw predominantly Cuban
audiences; now they attract fans from across Latin America, along
with others looking for new rhythms to dance to. Ditto for
performances by rock en espanol bands. A recent show at Mercury
Lounge in Manhattan by the band Sergeant Garcia drew listeners from
France, Cuba, Puerto Rico and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   This is the music of the future, with audiences that can be
cultivated. While the cracks in the Latin music industry are
getting bigger, there are encouraging signs for the music's
eventual viability in the United States. Yet the question remains:
Can an audience be found for it? If not, the marketplace will
decide and listeners will simply go elsewhere, exercising their
right to exist in several cultures at the same time, and derailing,
at least in the United States, the possibility of a real surge in
creativity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
