<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9711 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-BUSH-HNS &LR;      08-01 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
BUSH STAGES RAID ON DEMOCRATIC WEST VIRGINIA &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)
 &HT;    By STEWART M. POWELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, W.Va. With a promise to bolster the nation's
defenses, Republican George W. Bush made a pitch Tuesday to the
voters of West Virginia, a state that has a long tradition of
preferring Democrats for president.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential nominee touted his edge over
Democrat Al Gore in the latest statewide poll and outlined plans
that could attract a hard-bitten state of 1.8 million people where
coal mining and related industries employ nearly 150,000 and
account for more than one-third of the state's economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   A welcoming crowd of several thousand on the grounds of the
state capitol failed to diminish Bush's apparent sense of awe that
he could be within striking distance of becoming the first
Republican outside the White House to capture the Democratic
stronghold in 72 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, jovially feigning disbelief, recalled the improbable
invitation by Republican Gov. Cecil Underwood to add West Virginia
to the list of swing states Bush is visiting en route to the GOP
convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait a minute West Virginia hasn't voted Republican for a
while,'' Bush recalled telling the West Virginia governor, a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Bush scanned the enthusiastic audience on the state house lawn
and declared: ``Gov. Underwood produces,'' adding: ``You know what?
I like our chances in West Virginia.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest statewide survey in West Virginia shows Bush leading
Gore, 47 percent to 38 percent an astonishing margin in a state
that has voted Democratic in 14 of the 17 presidential elections
since the onset of the Great Depression in the early 1930s. Ohio
State University's Center for Survey Research released the survey
May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bush hopes to repeat the feat of Republican Herbert Hoover, who
swept West Virginia in 1928 on his way to a 444-electoral vote
landslide over Democrat Al Smith, a New Yorker whose Roman
Catholicism alarmed Protestant descendents of Scot-Irish settlers
who settled this remote, rugged territory in the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   Underwood set the tone for Bush's remarks, which were crafted to
mesh with the national security theme at the GOP convention in
Philadelphia Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to get Al Gore to pay attention to veterans and
national defense is to tell him that Navy SEALS are on the
endangered species' list,'' quipped Underwood to the delight of the
crowd, which included veterans. ``
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a president who waves the Star Spangled Banner more
proudly than he waves the flag of Greenpeace.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not directly attack Gore but rather echoed the theme of
national defense, telling his audience that he would revive armed
forces' ``dangerously low morale'' by hiking military pay,
modernizing military housing and strengthening American defenses.
He also promised to end the partisan backbiting in the nation's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would be ``a uniter, not a divider'' with an
administration ``that appeals to our better angels and not our
darker impulses,'' adding: ``This nation is sick and tired of the
politics of personal destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia has been more elusive for Republicans than the
four other swing states visited by Bush before arriving in
Harrisburg, Pa., Tuesday, en route to the GOP convention on
Wednesday. Those states Arkansas, Missouri, Kentucky and Ohio last
voted Republican in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginians who took part in Tuesday's pre-convention rally
and a historian at nearby West Virginia University Institute of
Technology said state residents are drawn to Bush by his ``common
man'' manner, his willingness to ease environmental restrictions on
coal mining operations and his reputation as ``a family man.''
</P>
<P>
   Former three-term Republican Gov. Arch Moore said West
Virginians ``do not trust Al Gore because he represents himself too
many different ways'' and they feel ``taken for granted'' by
Democrats. The state's two senators and three House members are all
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   James W. Teets, chief of staff to the state's GOP governor, said
West Virginians ``feel more at home with Bush who, coming from an
oil state understands you need a balanced approach that offers jobs
as well as protecting the environment.'' Joe Rigney, 31, a
mechanical engineer from Hurricane, W.Va., who was wearing a Bush
sticker, liked Bush's plans for ending the ``thermonuclear partisan
warfare in Washington,'' adding: ``People here are just sick of all
those verbal bombs being thrown.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wilkerson, 71, a teenage member of the once powerful United
Mine Workers Union who later attended law school and became a
lawyer, says voters are alarmed that ``Gore wants to shut down the
mining industry with his environmental regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Brown, a historian at 2,600-student West Virginia
University Institute of Technology for 27 years, said Bush is
reaping the benefits of West Virginians' readiness to punish Gore
for Clinton's lapses of morality.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here have a strong work ethic, a strong faith in their
religion and are attracted to Bush's reputation as a family man,''
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewarthearstdc.com )
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
