<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9715 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-AFFAIR-OF-LOVE-FILM-$     08-01 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFAIR-OF-LOVE-FILM-$ADV06-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACING AN AFFAIR FROM END TO BEGINNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: for release Sunday, August 6) 
 By LAURA WINTERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I lived a powerful love story, I understood nothing
about it, and I needed to delve into my questions in a film,'' said
the Belgian director Frederic Fonteyne, by way of explaining his
tender, unconventional and emotionally charged movie about
middle-aged romance, ``An Affair of Love.''
</P>
<P>
   But he says the film, which has been acclaimed in Europe and
which opens here on Friday, is not autobiographical. Written by his
longtime friend and collaborator Philippe Blasband, it depicts a
40-something woman and a slightly younger man who meet in Paris
through a personals ad that the woman has placed in order to
fulfill a particular sexual fantasy. The characters never tell each
other their names, nor do they (or we) have any information about
their respective backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   We also never see the enactment of the fantasy that brings them
together: for the most part, the camera stops outside their
hotel-room door.
</P>
<P>
   During the course of their encounters, the couple fall in love.
But we are not allowed to hope that their relationship will work
out: interspersed with the flashbacks of their affair are
interviews in which each character, alone, talks about the
now-ended liaison. Each tells a slightly different story.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which was called ``A Pornographic Affair'' in its
European release, stars the French actress Nathalie Baye and the
Spanish actor Sergi Lopez. Baye was named best actress at the 1999
Venice Film Festival and the film earned the distinction of opening
the New Directors/New Films series this spring at the Museum of
Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film has a lot of interesting levels,'' said Richard Pena,
program director of the Film Society of Lincoln Center, which
presents New Directors with the museum. ``What is going on, what
the characters say is going on, and then what we think is  &UR; really
 &LR; going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Fonteyne, a quiet 32-year-old with the burly build of a
lumberjack, looks as if he would be more at home directing a buddy
film (which he did for his first feature) than delivering a
mysterious, intimate take on a thwarted midlife love affair. Part
of a Belgian cinematic flowering that began in the early 1990s with
offbeat films like ``Man Bites Dog'' and culminated in the first
Belgian Palme d'Or at the 1999 Cannes International Film Festival
(for Luc and Jean-Pierre Dardenne's ``Rosetta''), Fonteyne shares
the ironic bent of his compatriots Benoit Mariage (``The Carriers
Are Waiting'') and Alain Berliner (``Ma Vie en Rose'').
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their movies, ``An Affair of Love'' is an out-and-out
love story, springing from Fonteyne's fascination with the
unresolved romance in his own past. ``The film asks questions about
what love is, but also explores how you talk about a love story
once it's finished,'' he said, speaking in French, while in New
York for the New Directors series. ``I wanted to film the pain and
pleasure of recollection _ like a jewel in a box that you peek at
before you close it again.''
</P>
<P>
   For him, the greatest irony in ``Affair'' is that the couple
separate not from loss of love but because they fatally
second-guess each other. ``I'm interested in how people talk to
each other, and how do they  &UR; not  &LR; talk to each other,'' he said.
``When you explore communication, you also have to explore the
moments when it breaks down.''
</P>
<P>
   By starting with the end, and by withholding background details,
the film does away with many of the usual hooks of narrative.
Instead, it focuses on the poignant contrast between experience and
memory, and on the shifting sands of truth.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why the characters he wrote remain anonymous,
Blasband said he ``wanted to make this story as pure and elemental
as possible.'' He chose Paris as a setting, he said with a laugh,
because ``Brussels is such a small town that it would be difficult
to have an affair here anonymously.''
</P>
<P>
   Blasband's original title, ``A Pornographic Affair,'' was a
reference to the sexual nature of the couple's tryst. But the title
proved troublesome for some European audiences, who stayed away
thinking the film might be porn. Those who have seen the film
sometimes have the opposite reaction, Fonteyne said. They ask him
why he did not show (or tell) the couple's sexual fantasy outright.
His reasons have nothing to do with coyness.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fantasy is a completely private thing,'' he said. ``The
strongest way to convey it is by a closed door. We wanted to do an
erotic film where the eroticism exists not just in the sex scenes
but also when the characters look at each other and think of their
fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when we finally see the couple make love _ without the
fantasy _ the impact comes from everything we haven't seen before.
Fonteyne's approach to eroticism is clearly different from the
explicitness of such filmmakers as Catherine Breillat (who directed
the recent French film ``Romance''). But, as a Belgian filmmaker,
he said, ``I did not want to do a typical French film about love.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what distinguishes the Belgian point of view, he
responded: ``I think it's in our slightly skewed sense of humor.
Belgium is such a strange country, with its two languages and
cultures; we're always at the point of the absurd. I also think
that there's a realist side to our films, the opposite of
glamour.''
</P>
<P>
   This gritty humor surfaces in scenes like the one where the
characters first meet. In a painfully funny moment, Baye's
character, who is nervous, starts talking about her longtime quest
for a hairy man. As she recounts her saga in great detail to the
astonished Lopez (who, fortunately, fits the bill), it becomes
clear that we are far from a chic, Gallic-style first encounter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That human tone is one of the things I really liked about this
script,'' Lopez said from Madrid. ``So often, the man feels he must
take the initiative. But in this film, there is no power struggle:
the man accepts and enjoys the woman's strong personality.''
 &UR;  &LR;  Fonteyne had long wanted to work with Baye, who is one of
France's most famous actresses and who has starred in such films as
``The Return of Martin Guerre.'' Baye, in turn, loved the
character. ``It's rare to have a role of that beauty when you've
passed 40,'' she said, on the telephone from Paris.
</P>
<P>
   But Fonteyne surprised everyone by casting Lopez as his leading
man. The Spanish-born Lopez (who speaks French in the film) was
well-respected for films like ``Western'' but was not widely known
for romantic roles. ``I wanted to put together these two people who
seem to have nothing to do with each other, and see what happens,''
Fonteyne said. ``Sergi didn't even know who Nathalie was, but there
was a real curiosity and openness between them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the film was scripted, Fonteyne had Baye and
Lopez improvise some of the interviews. Since the two actors did
not know their characters' backgrounds, what became important to
them was, as Lopez said, ``playing people caught entirely by
surprise by love.'' In their duet-like scenes, they relied upon
Fonteyne's sense of balance. ``The three of us had a real
complicity,'' Baye said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Frederic may be young, but he has a powerful emotional
gauge,'' she added. ``He would listen intently until what we were
playing rang true inside him.''
</P>
<P>
   According to his friends, Fonteyne has always combined his
ability to listen with a quiet stubbornness. As an introverted
teen-ager, he thought about becoming an artist. His father was at
that time the artistic director of an advertising agency; his
mother, who is Hungarian, had fled to Belgium as a young girl
during the Hungarian uprising of 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Fonteyne ended up going to film school (at the Institut des Arts
de Diffusion in Louvain-la-Neuve), where he met Blasband and,
through him, Patrick Quinet, who is his producer and who founded
the Brussels company Artemis Productions.
</P>
<P>
   The trio are like a youthful Three Musketeers of Belgian cinema
_ and, indeed, soldierly grit is needed to get a film produced in
Belgium. Even now, the paucity of domestic financing for cinema
restricts the production of Belgian films to a handful a year, and
requires most films to be international co-productions. In 1997,
Fonteyne finally managed to direct his first feature, ``Max and
Bobo,'' about the tormented friendship between a hairdresser and a
hobo. ``Max'' flopped at the box office, but Fonteyne hardly
blinked before embarking on ``An Affair of Love.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of his second film, he is pausing for breath. ``I
did my first two films so fast,'' he said. ``I've said to myself
that I will stop for one year and think about things, and just
live. And I'm sure that my next film will be completely different.
I've done my version of a love story now; I don't need to continue
to do love stories all the time.'' He laughed. ``I still may not
understand love, but at least I can now talk of other things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
