<HEADER>
A9719 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-SOLDIER-1STLD-     08-01 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SOLDIER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SOLDIER SENTENCED TO LIFE WITHOUT PAROLE FOR KILLING KOSOVAR
GIRL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (SUBS to restore `Ms.' to 2nd graf before optional trim) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ A U.S. military court in Germany sentenced a U.S.
soldier to life in prison without parole Tuesday for the murder of
an 11-year-old Kosovar Albanian girl.
</P>
<P>
   The soldier, Staff Sgt. Frank J. Ronghi, 36, who was sent to
Kosovo last summer with the 3rd Battalion of the 504th Parachute
Infantry, pleaded guilty last week to sodomizing and murdering the
young girl, Merita Shabiu, while he was on peacekeeping duty in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   His sentence is the most severe available to a U.S. military
court holding a trial in Germany, where the death penalty does not
exist. It was handed down after the girl's father and mother had
provided moving testimony about their own suffering and their
daughter's.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter welcomed the peacekeepers,'' the father, Hamdi
Shabiu, said. ``She was very happy because she thought they had
come to protect us. How do you do this to someone? He massacred my
daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Her bruised and slashed body was found in the snow on Jan. 13
outside Vitina, where Ronghi's company was based. Ronghi has said
he sodomized and murdered Merita in an abandoned building in
Vitina, before stuffing her corpse in a plastic bag and dumping it
in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what went wrong that day,'' he said in court
Tuesday, standing before a jury of six uniformed Army officers. ``I
am still trying to look for answers myself to that question.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronghi had a previously impeccable record.
</P>
<P>
   Until shortly before the trial _ and despite compelling evidence
against him from another soldier in the company who witnessed his
removing the body _ Ronghi had insisted that he was not guilty and
was being framed as ``a bad guy.'' But on Friday, he abruptly
changed his plea to guilty.
</P>
<P>
   There was also evidence that he had planned the killing. Citing
testimony from a fellow soldier, Capt. Alton Gwaltney, a prosecutor
said Ronghi had told fellow soldiers that he had a plan to ``grab a
little girl and rape her, but would have to kill her to get away
with it and would blame the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl's mother, Remize Shabiu, wept as details of the murder
were read out in court. ``Merita is not the only one that died,''
Ms. Shabiu said. ``We all died. We are half-people now.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple have five other children.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In its sentence, the panel accepted the prosecution's argument
that the crime amounted to cold-blooded murder and an ignoble
betrayal of a mission to maintain security in a province bitterly
divided between Serbs and Albanians. The panel ignored defense
arguments that the sergeant should be granted some leniency because
his unit was under extreme psychological pressure in Vitina.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Kosovo, where U.S. soldiers are situated, was supposed
to be relatively safe, far from the traditional front lines between
the Serbs and the Kosovo Liberation Army, the insurgent Albanian
movement. But the area proved to be as unstable as the rest of the
province and quickly became a haven for smuggling and drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Ronghi was born in Niles, Ohio, the third of four children. He
is divorced. He joined the Army in 1988, serving in Egypt, Haiti
and during the Gulf War. By the time he arrived in Kosovo in late
summer 1999, he had risen to staff sergeant in Company A of his
infantry regiment. In Kosovo, he commanded about 12 soldiers
responsible for controlling checkpoints and patrolling streets.
</P>
<P>
   His company earned a reputation for aggressiveness. In late
March, after their return home to Fort Bragg, N.C., five of its
soldiers were disciplined for mistreating civilians on Jan. 9 and
10, a few days before Merita's murder.
</P>
<P>
   The defense for Ronghi alluded to those incidents, suggesting
that a ``negative command climate'' had developed in a highly
unstable situation. But the evidence that he had carefully planned
the killing proved more compelling than those arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Ronghi, who said he regretted what he had done and the disgrace
that he had brought on the Army, is to serve his sentence in the
United States. Under the terms of the sentence, he has no
possibility of obtaining parole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
