<HEADER>
A9721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GUNS-CRIME-555&AMP;ADD-NY     08-01 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-CRIME-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADY GUN-CONTROL ACT HAS NOT REDUCED MURDER RATES, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no evidence that the Brady law requiring background
checks of handgun buyers reduced homicide rates after it went into
effect in 1994, according to a study published Wednesday in The
Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of the study, Philip Cook, a professor of public
policy at Duke University, and Jens Ludwig, a professor of public
policy at Georgetown University, suggested that the reason the
Brady law did not reduce homicides, most of which are committed
with guns, was because it did not go far enough. The law requires
background checks only for those who bought handguns from federally
licensed firearms dealers, and does not cover the large unregulated
market involving an estimated 30 percent to 40 percent of all
sales, like gun shows and private transactions, where criminals and
juveniles often buy handguns.
</P>
<P>
   But the study's conclusion was immediately challenged by the
Clinton administration, the Center to Prevent Handgun Violence, the
gun control group that helped push for the Brady law, and by other
researchers who said the study was misleading and inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Johnson, the undersecretary for enforcement at the
Treasury Department, said Justice Department figures have shown
that crimes committed with handguns fell 52 percent between 1993
and 1998, which is twice the rate of crimes overall. The Brady law,
new uses of crime gun tracing by the Bureau of Alcohol Tobacco and
Firearms and other efforts directed at guns all led to the drop,
Johnson said. ``We think there has been a significant contribution
by Brady,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Weil, director of research at the Center to Prevent
Handgun Violence, said the new study was flawed because it only
measured whether homicide rates in the 32 states that did not have
background checks and waiting periods to purchase handguns before
the passage of the Brady law showed a greater decline than the 18
states that already had such requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Weil said, this did not allow the authors to
measure how big an impact the Brady law had on interstate gun
trafficking, in which states that previously had no background
checks or waiting periods had long provided a ready source of
supply for traffickers who illegally resold guns in states that did
have such restrictions. For example, after the implementation of
the Brady law, Weil said, he found that some states with lax gun
laws, like Virginia, Georgia, South Carolina and Ohio, were as much
as 86 percent less likely to be the sources of guns used in crimes
in states like New York, New Jersey or Illinois that already had
restrictive laws.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore this point, Johnson said that 44 percent of the
ATF's investigations of gun trafficking cases involved guns being
sold illegally from one state into another. Therefore to gauge how
much the Brady law reduced homicide, a study would have to look
nationwide, not just compare those states that already had
background checks before 1994 with those that had to implement them
under the Brady act, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Weil said, there has been a sharp reduction in the
percentage of robberies and assaults committed with guns since the
Brady law went into effect, saving an estimated 9,368 lives from
1994 to 1998.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Separately, two studies by Dr. Garen Wintemute, director of the
Violence Prevention Research Program at the University of
California at Davis, have found that California laws requiring
background checks of convicted felons and criminals who committed
violent misdemeanors reduced crimes committed with guns by 25
percent to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wintemute, in another study, also published in Wednesday's
Journal of the American Medical Association, found strong new
evidence that a small number of federally licensed firearms dealers
are responsible for a disproportionate number of handguns that end
up being used in crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The ATF has reported that of the 83,272 federally licensed
dealers in 1998, 1.2 percent, or 1,020, sold 57 percent of the guns
used in crimes that the agency was able to trace. The gun industry
has complained that this finding is unfair, because the ATF was not
able to distinguish between large stores, with high sales volumes,
and dealers who were knowingly selling to traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   But Wintemute found that 8.6 percent of dealers in California
sold 82.7 percent of all handguns used in crimes there in 1998,
though these same dealers accounted for only 33.2 percent of all
handgun sales during the period from 1996 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Delfay, president of the National Shooting Sports
Foundation, the gun industry trade association, said the gun
industry ``absolutely supports'' more tracing of guns if there are
corrupt dealers selling to criminals. But he cautioned that there
might be other explanations for so many guns being traced back to a
dealer. For instance, Delfay said, some cities still do not trace
all guns used in crimes, so the existing data may be misleading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
