<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SLUG-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      08-01 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLUG-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: corporate quarter. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of course, the venture still had to be economically feasible.
Honest Tea is expensive _ $2.50 for 16 fluid ounces in one
Manhattan deli, compared with $1.50 for the same size Snapple iced
tea _ but the founders' efforts to sell it through health food
stores, gourmet food shops and restaurants seem to be catching on.
Large supermarket chains like Shaw's, Wegmans and Grand Union also
now carry Honest Tea.
</P>
<P>
   The expense provokes another puzzle for the professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many stores use rules like, we have to have 100 percent markup
on everything we sell,'' Nalebuff noted. ``And that rule doesn't
take into account the cost of making the product. If our drink
costs 75 cents to make and someone else's costs 50 cents, they will
sell ours for $1.50 and theirs for $1. Interestingly, the store
makes 50 percent more on our product than on the other, but they
don't always see the advantage of selling our product.''
</P>
<P>
   Honest Tea had its origins in a question Nalebuff posed to a
class one day in 1995, when Goldman was among the students sitting
in the lecture hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked, `Why isn't there a normal product for the rest of
us?''' recalled Nalebuff, a longtime drinker of iced tea. ``You can
have 200 calories, or you can have zero calories with NutraSweet.
But if you believe in declining margin utility, why isn't there a
product out there with 10 to 20 calories? Anyone can handle that.
It's fewer calories than a carrot.'' A teaspoon of sugar enhances
the flavor of tea, he believes, ``but by the time you put 16
spoonfuls of sugar in, it's worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   For Goldman, the point reverberated one afternoon about two
years later, after a hot, sweaty run in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into one of these cafes, and there was nothing to drink
that quenched my thirst,'' he said. ``I sort of banged on the table
and said: `That's it. We have to do something about this.'''
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, he sent Nalebuff an e-mail message asking if he
was still interested in that soft drink idea he had mentioned in
class. Coincidentally, Nalebuff had just returned from India, where
he had tried unsuccessfully to sell the owners of Tata Tea Ltd. on
the idea of starting a line called Honest Tea. It was not
Nalebuff's first global business concept that failed to catch on.
Earlier, he had wanted to sell fortune cookies to the Chinese, with
each cookie containing an English lesson.
</P>
<P>
   What flopped in India, however, received the red carpet
treatment back in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he told me the name Honest Tea, I felt like that was it,
the angels singing,'' Goldman said. ``It was a product I wanted to
create.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea, of course, was the easy part. The partners _ Nalebuff
is chairman of the company, Goldman the chief executive, although
Nalebuff insists on referring to him as the ``TEO'' _ struggled to
find a plant that would produce their product their way. They
eventually set up their headquarters in Bethesda, Md., where
Goldman is a daily presence and Nalebuff is on call from New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   They tried making tea in a giant tea bag, which was actually a
laundry bag converted for the purpose. In one of the early rounds,
the bag burst and spattered wet tea leaves all over the factory.
Eventually they settled on a custom-made tea ball, an
industrial-strength sphere of stainless steel that allows the tea
to be steeped as long as necessary, to get the desired flavor.
</P>
<P>
   They developed partnerships with suppliers like the Crow Nation,
which provides the Montana-grown peppermint leaves that are used in
one flavor. They flirted briefly with using other names for the
company _ Perspicaci-Tea and Golf Tea were among the possibilities,
Nalebuff said _ and at one point got a mildly threatening letter
from lawyers for Nestle, which owns the Nestea brand and thought
that Honest Tea might be misread as ``Ho Nestea.'' (Making the
product's name into one word for trademark purposes, although it
appears as two words in the marketplace, seems to have eliminated
the problem.)
</P>
<P>
   Some industry experts have speculated that Honest Tea will have
a hard time building the kind of market share that will keep it
viable for the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to have to convince distributors who already
have trucks filled with strong products to make room for another
product, and that's not easy,'' Sicher said. Still, he noted, some
small companies do figure out a way to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The Honest Tea founders are optimistic, pointing to anecdotal
evidence that their product has appeal beyond the obvious health
food store and gourmet-deli circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Kurtis and I am a truck driver,'' read an e-mail
Goldman recently received from a man who called himself ``a
completely addicted iced tea junkie.'' The message continued: ``I
stopped at the T/A truck stop at Antioch, Ill., and found your tea
in the cooler. The info on the label caused me to buy three
different bottles. It was mind blowing different.'' He closed by
informing the company that its products could not be found in
central Illinois, and begged to have his hometown become a test
market.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of tests, the Honest Tea partners leaped at the chance
to grade each other's performance in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   Nalebuff, the professor, said he would give Goldman an A+ for
his work on the company.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, describing Nalebuff's role as ``more analytical on a
day-to-day basis,'' awarded him an A. ``The ideas are always
creative,'' the former pupil said. ``Barry is an out-of-the-box
thinker. Of course, some ideas are in the box for a reason.''
</P>
</TEXT>
