<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HONEST-TEA-2TAKES-NYT     08-01 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONEST-TEA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YALE MANAGEMENT PROFESSOR AND FORMER STUDENT TACKLE REAL WORLD
BEVERAGE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It hardly seems the stuff consumer thrills are made of: a weak,
watery tea, brewed the old-fashioned way, with hardly any sugar and
even less caffeine. Marketing? There is almost none. Edgy
television ads and celebrity endorsements? Zero.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Seth Goldman and Barry Nalebuff started Honest Tea
two years ago, in part to fill what they saw as a neglected market
niche and in part to make a point, they were well aware that they
would be competing against mass-marketed sweetened iced teas made
by the Coca-Colas, PepsiCos and Snapples of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Beverages mixed up to address a specific target market are
nothing new: Microbreweries making specialty beers ran long and
hard with the concept. But the beverage industry is especially
tough on new brands; even Coke and Pepsi have stumbled over the
years while trying to induce consumers to try something new.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably hundreds of beverages introduced around the
country every year, and most do not succeed,'' said John Sicher,
publisher of Beverage Digest, a trade newsletter. ``This is a huge
market that requires a great tasting product, good marketing, lots
of money and good distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   As luck, or insight, would have it, when Honest Tea started
landing on store shelves, consumers were showing a distinct
preference for bottled water and other beverages perceived to be
more healthful. And for all it did not have, the founders saw their
product is distinct enough from established brands to attract a
different customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to compete against the big companies on their
terms, unless we won the lottery, we would be finished,'' said
Nalebuff, a professor of game theory at the Yale School of
Management.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he and Goldman, a former pupil of his and an alumnus of
the Calvert Group, the largest sponsor of ``socially responsible''
mutual funds, decided to set their own terms. They would make an
iced tea that promoted the tea flavor and would be naturally low in
calories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funniest thing was, why hadn't anyone else done this?''
Nalebuff (pronounced NAIL-buff) said. ``It wasn't rocket science.''
</P>
<P>
   They steered clear of artificial sweeteners; and their
philosophy on sugar was that less was more. Their tea leaves had to
be of high quality, and therefore costly. They promoted the teas
through trade shows and presentations to supermarket chains. They
included a Web site, of course (www.honesttea.com), and printed a
toll-free number, (800) 865-4736, on labels for consumer feedback.
</P>
<P>
   The two partners used their own money, as well as financing from
friends and family, to amass the $507,000 needed to get the company
going in early 1998. Since the product went on the market that
year, $2.7 million more in financing has been raised, mostly from
passionate consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Distribution, always tricky in the beverage business, has been a
patchwork arrangement, encompassing everything from driving their
own U-Hauls to piggybacking the product onto delivery trucks
belonging to a corned beef company with lots of deli connections.
Offering samples has been a cornerstone of the marketing strategy,
as it is with many small companies. With sales expected to reach
$3.5 million this year, the company anticipates its first brush
with profitability.
</P>
<P>
   For Nalebuff, 41, the development of Honest Tea has been an
eye-opening foray into the real world of supply and demand, a world
that few academics experience day in and day out. For Goldman, 34,
whose role in the company may have been presaged in childhood (his
parents are scholars of Russia and China, two cultures that
appreciate a properly made cup of tea), it has been an opportunity
to apply what he learned in graduate school. It has also been a
chance to see his former teacher in a new light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry's reputation at Yale was as a very hard-nosed,
cold-calling professor,'' Goldman said. ``You'd walk into the room,
there would be a case study, and someone would be called on and put
in the hot seat for most of the class.''
</P>
<P>
   He now sees Nalebuff as a supportive colleague. ``A lot of
students, when they heard that I was going to partner with Barry,
said, `What is it like to have to go through that every day?' For
me, he has been only affirming and encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``A lot of professors are getting involved in start-up
companies. But how many of them really put money into them? And
when Barry goes to bed at night and when he wakes up in the
morning, he's thinking Honest Tea.''
</P>
<P>
   Nalebuff said he had been surprised to learn how hard it was to
put some of his own theories to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've written a book on cooperating with the people you compete
with, and it's easy to say that,'' he said, ``but in practice it's
much more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a competing brand wanted to make tea at the same
bottling plant Honest Tea uses, and even wanted to try the same
technology, the brainchild of Nalebuff and Goldman. ``We decided
that eventually they would figure out how to do this on their own,
and we would be willing to help speed up the process for the right
amount of money,'' Nalebuff said.
</P>
<P>
   They made a deal.
</P>
<P>
   To create a product consistent with their vision, the partners
insisted on a specific manufacturing process, on applying socially
responsible principles to how and where they bought their raw
materials wherever possible, and on emphasizing quality over
quantity. Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade, the ice cream company that
Unilever PLC agreed in April to buy for $326 million, is their
corporate role model _ not for the takeover, but for the business
principles, which include encouraging minority businesses to become
suppliers and finding other ways to enhance society from the
corporate quarter.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
