<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9727 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MERRILL-LYNCH-SCHOLAR     08-01 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-LYNCH-SCHOLARS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS BENEFIT FROM INVESTMENT MADE BY MERRILL LYNCH 12 YEARS
AGO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: GA., Mass., Ill., Mich., Texas, Calif., Fla., Pa., D.C.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twelve years ago, Merrill Lynch chose 251
first-graders at random from some of the toughest neighborhoods in
10 cities and made them a pledge: graduate from high school by
2000, and we will pay all your college expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The company saw the pledge as the kind of transaction a
financial services firm understood: investing money. It would be
pretty straightforward: throw a few community events, collect
report cards from the schools, and send out the checks.
</P>
<P>
   It quickly became apparent that it was not that easy. Getting
the students through school took more hours and people than anyone
predicted. Not least, it took the dedication of students and
families. But now, as the deadline arrives, ScholarshipBuilder
stands out as the longest and one of the most successful of these
kinds of programs, with 93 percent of students _ not counting two
who died _ heading to college in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Following celebrations in the 10 cities _ Atlanta, Boston,
Chicago, Detroit, Houston, Los Angeles, Miami, New York,
Philadelphia and Washington _ 149 of the students gathered in New
York City this week to meet one another for the first time and to
collect some last-minute advice on how to make the transition to
college. Merrill Lynch, meanwhile, was reflecting on the major
lesson of any program of its kind: it's about much more than money.
</P>
<P>
   ``A full scholarship was a big deal,'' said Eddy Bayardelle,
director of the company's philanthropic programs. ``But for urban
kids it's not good enough. Not when you're starting in the first
grade. So many things will happen in 12 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ScholarshipBuilder, which its founders estimated will cost $16
million at the program's end, came on the heels of other programs
started by philanthropists, universities and companies in the 1980s
as dropout rates soared.
</P>
<P>
   But while others held out the financial carrot to sixth-graders
_ along the model established by New York philanthropist Eugene M.
Lang in a speech to his former Harlem elementary school in 1981 _
Merrill Lynch started earlier. It invested $2,000 for each first
grader every year through 12th grade, and enlisted the Urban League
to be the more human side of the program, offering mentors and
running after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, the students say they did not really understand
what was happening to them. They remember they were given bright
yellow book bags and a letter announcing the gift. ``I remember we
had an assembly, we all had to stand on the stage and wave our
letters, look cute for the cameras,'' said Nicole Brown, 18, who
was in a class of first graders chosen at PS 30/31 in Harlem. She
will head to Howard University next month. But in first grade, she
and others were not sure they would go to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of celebrities don't graduate from high school,'' she
said, ``I thought maybe it didn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Some began to realize the benefit as early as middle school, as
people they knew started to go to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you find out how much school costs, and your mother
doesn't make that much in a year, you know it's a blessing,'' said
Travis McKinnon, 17, a recipient from Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   But most said they did not realize what they had been given
until high school _ and often, not until they had risked losing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realizing that if you don't graduate in 2000 you don't get the
full scholarship, that makes you get your grades up fast,'' said
Ashley Lightborn, another of the Harlem students.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch always planned to offer tutoring, and that
continued throughout. But the needs grew as students got older.
Simply tracking students as they moved between family members and
foster parents proved a huge challenge. By sixth grade, Merrill
Lynch decided to hire full-time coordinators for each city to help
the students and their families. Those people became like parents
in some cases, going to teacher conferences, finding medical help,
arranging summer camps.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch found jobs for some parents, helped siblings with
tutoring, and took the students on college tours as senior year
approached. In each city, the Urban League arranged a place for
students to go after school, where they could bring homework or see
friends. When one girl in Detroit moved out of town, Chris Gaitley,
the assistant to a Merrill Lynch district director, phoned
different cab companies until she found one that would be willing
to drive the girl back and forth to the center for her tutoring
each day.
</P>
<P>
   Gaitley was involved from the inception of the program, working
with the students despite the demands placed on her by her own
three children. ``I never felt I had a choice not to,'' she
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Bayardelle said starting in the first grade was crucial to the
program's success. One ScholarshipBuilder student drowned, another
committed suicide. But programs that started in the sixth grade
have seen more dropouts, more deaths from gang violence, and slower
high school completion rates.
</P>
<P>
   The students left New York this week with a new laptop computer
from Merrill Lynch, which will allow them to keep in e-mail contact
with their mentors and their fellow students.
</P>
<P>
   The program organizers, meanwhile, are recruiting mentors from
within the firm to advise the students as they go through the next
four years. That, too, was not part of the original program. But
Bayardelle said it would be irresponsible to leave the students at
this stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned a lot over the last 12 years,'' he said.
``There's no magic to this, but there's a lot, a lot of caring, by
a lot of caring adults.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
