<HEADLINE>
WOMEN TO HOLD TWO KEY POSTS AT UMASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICK HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A businesswoman and an administrator are becoming the
first women to hold two key posts overseeing the University of
Massachusetts and the state colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Grace K. Fey, executive vice president of the Frontier Capital
Management Co., is expected to be elected chairwoman of the
university's Board of Trustees Wednesday. Tuesday, Judith I. Gill
was appointed the state's chancellor of higher education, who makes
tuition and academic policy for state campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Women make up about 30 percent of the trustees of public schools
nationwide. There is no data on the profile of board leaders, but
governance experts estimate that only a small number are female.
</P>
<P>
   Fey, who will succeed Robert S. Karam, said she plans to work
with UMass President William Bulger to raise more private funds and
develop joint programs _ such as online classes _ among the
university's five campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Distance learning has so many wonderful implications for
teaching, learning, the people we can touch, and the revenue we can
generate,'' Fey said. ``We want to attract great faculty and give
students all they need for their education.''
</P>
<P>
   Karam said Fey has already made connections between UMass and
the Boston business community as a university trustee, and that she
has helped the university's efforts to turn intellectual property
and research into profit-making ventures. Among other roles, Fey is
chairwoman of Zoo New England, earning credit for some improvements
to the Franklin Park Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been like a rainmaker,'' Karam said.
</P>
<P>
   For the 2000 fiscal year, the university raised an estimated $80
million in private funds, up from $69.7 million the year before.
Fey said she would like to break the $100 million mark during her
time as chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Gill as chancellor was expected, and the
Massachusetts Board of Higher Education made it official Tuesday.
She replaces Stanley Z. Koplik, who died in January.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next year, Gill said, she will work with Department of
Education officials on programs to help students pass the MCAS
test.
</P>
<P>
   Passing scores on MCAS will be required for high school
graduation in 2003, and some UMass officials say the test could cut
sharply into their enrollments, especially among minority students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a responsibility to public education, and I don't
think it has been our first priority,'' Gill said. ``There's a very
selfish reason for our involvement _ these will be our students.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
