<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9730 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DIESKAU-MUSIC-$ADV06-     08-01 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIESKAU-MUSIC-$ADV06-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHANCE TO HEAR A LEGEND'S DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 6) 
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who would have suspected, this late in the game, that there were
any crucial gaps left to fill in the discography of the German
baritone Dietrich Fischer-Dieskau? The very model of the serious
postwar vocal artist, Fischer-Dieskau turned 75 in May. From the
very dawn of his career, microphones seemed to spring up where'er
he walked. For him as for legions of other performers
``legendary,'' honorable or merely retired from the scene, the
opening of the archival floodgates in the CD era has brought an all
but engulfing tidal wave of documentation, much of it previously
impossible for any but the most resourceful, connected and
determined fanatic to find.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here comes Myto Records of Milan, upstaging a flurry of new
Fischer-Dieskau offerings on other labels with what is advertised
as the premiere release of Fischer-Dieskau's first operatic
appearance. The assignment is no novice's walk-on, either, but
Rodrigo, freethinking confidant of royalty, a principal in Verdi's
``Don Carlos'' (001.H038; three CD's). Where on earth did Myto turn
up the source tape? And how is it possible no one got there before?
</P>
<P>
   Quite apart from the interest Fischer-Dieskau's debut gives the
evening in retrospect, this was an occasion. The company was the
Staedtische Oper Berlin (now the Deutsche Oper). Its previous
efforts to raise itself from the postwar ashes had failed
ingloriously. With the premiere of a new ``Don Carlos'' on Nov. 18,
1948, Heinz Tietjen, who had run the operation to acclaim in the
late 1920s, was back in charge. In the pit stood his discovery
Ferenc Fricsay, a Hungarian conductor of remarkable gifts, then 34.
</P>
<P>
   Typically for Fischer-Dieskau, his debut in opera was early and
auspicious. An ex-prisoner of war of the British in Italy, he made
his first concert appearance, in the brief (though crucial)
baritone solo of Brahms' ``German Requiem,'' in Freiburg in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1948, at 22, he was heard on Berlin radio in
Schubert's agonized song cycle ``Winterreise.'' That broadcast has
been on CD at least since the late '80s, evidence of his
preternaturally precocious interpretive maturity. True, in later
years he would develop a leaner sound, a broader palette of colors
and greater variety and swiftness of utterance. (This
``Winterreise'' clocks in at a lugubrious 78-plus minutes, some
seven minutes more than later readings of his.) By comparison with
his subsequent work, this performance has a slightly
presentational, old-fashioned cast. Still, no one familiar with the
artist Fischer-Dieskau was to become could fail to recognize the
timbre, musicianship or personality.
</P>
<P>
   With the Myto ``Don Carlos,'' sung in German, as was the local
custom of the time, we are already in the presence of the
``modern'' Fischer-Dieskau. (Perhaps Fricsay's extremes of tempo,
especially the fast ones, have something to do with it.) At his
first appearance, an unexpected reunion with Don Carlos, to whom
Rodrigo is devoted, Fischer-Dieskau's taut rhythms and mercurial
reactions bring not only his own character but also the whole
dramatic predicament sharply to life. What he hears is dire. The
young prince is in love with his stepmother. Fischer-Dieskau gives
Rodrigo's thunderstruck exclamation in a smothered, almost
asthmatic voice but quickly recovers to suggest, with lofty
solemnity and a trace of Mephistophelean insinuation, that Carlos
take up the cause of oppressed Flanders.
</P>
<P>
   The famous duet that ensues goes painfully awry, and the tenor,
Boris Greverus, must bear the blame. (Such from-the-heart,
pitch-approximate bawling as is heard from him throughout the
performance is quite exciting at a visceral level here and there
but catastrophic where voices must blend, twisting Verdi into
Ives.) When Rodrigo reappears, bearing a letter to the queen from
her mother and a whispered message from the prince, Fischer-Dieskau
is urbane, smooth and youthful, his precise diction charged with
the sense of detailed motivation one hopes for in a spoken play.
Once again, he is rhythmically scrupulous; a detractor might say
pedantic.
</P>
<P>
   In his big paragraph of melody describing the prince's
suffering, Fischer-Dieskau conveys tremendous compassion,
emphasizing emotional detail rather than the allure of his own
sound. Italians do not sing this way. And for many,
Fischer-Dieskau's vocal character has always been intrinsically
incompatible with Verdi. ``Che fa, questo Discher-Fieskau?,''
Renata Tebaldi, the quintessential Italian soprano, is said to have
asked when he showed up to sing Rodrigo on Georg Solti's recording
in 1965: ``What is he doing, this Discher-Fieskau?'' No doubt she
scrambled his name perfectly innocently. Why would she have known
it? He was not of her world.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Fischer-Dieskau could reveal potentialities in Verdi
Italians are apt to overlook. On Myto, face to face with Josef
Greindl's King Philip _ a colder, harsher portrait than one might
think possible, snarly and granitic, as withholding of voice as of
tenderness _ Fischer-Dieskau starts out rather cool and stiff. As
their wide-ranging dialogue proceeds, he grows mysterious,
strangely tentative, before breaking out with wild horror at the
evils he has seen abroad. Thanking the king for his favor,
Fischer-Dieskau at first seems dazed, almost catatonic.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with a single word left to go (``Sire''), the light
changes, and Rodrigo seems transfigured, off in his own radiant
world. By the end of the opera, the character will have dealt
double with the king, sacrificing himself for Carlos and the cause
of liberty. Verdi gives the dying man an aria in which the beauty
of the melody expresses the nobility of his ideals. In
Fischer-Dieskau's performance, the arc toward transcendence already
begins many scenes before.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The Myto ``Don Carlos'' merits comment on other counts. Verdi's
score is long, and it underwent significant revisions. Different
editions solve the resulting problems in different ways, and the
choices of Julius Kapp, the director of the Berlin production, are
unusual, at times ingenious. Fricsay's highly individual sense of
pace and texture serves the drama excellently, and the cast forms a
remarkably coherent ensemble. As an acting singer, Fischer-Dieskau
was very much among his kind. The practice of speaking in song _
and of speaking as clearly and expressively as actors at the
playhouse _ is common to the entire cast. Myto provides no
libretto, but if you understand German, you will not need one.
(Super-titles? Was ist das?)
</P>
<P>
   But rather than dwell on these matters, let's turn to other
noteworthy recent additions to Fischer-Dieskau's immense
discography. Aribert Reimann's ``Lear,'' adapted from Shakespeare's
tragedy, was composed _ slowly, and against powerful internal
resistance _ at the singer's suggestion. Fischer-Dieskau made
specific dramatic suggestions, too, but these were ignored. Nor was
he consulted about the vocal writing. The score that resulted _
replete with 12-tone rows, quarter tones and other equally
singer-friendly attributes _ received its premiere in Munich,
conducted by Gerd Albrecht, in a production by Jean-Pierre
Ponnelle. Long out of print on LP, Deutsche Grammophon's live
recording of 1978 now returns to the catalog (463 480-2; two CD's).
</P>
<P>
   Verdi, as is well known, dreamed of setting ``Lear'' as an opera
but gave up. He cannot have been thinking of anything like this.
Though the vocal writing, notably for the three sopranos as Lear's
daughters, is in spots jagged and stratospheric, the singers
operate fundamentally within a domain of declamatory recitative
unrelieved by melody. The instrumental writing _ particularly for
percussion, strings (divided into as many as 48 parts) and solo
flute _ creates a bleak yet mesmerizing soundscape within which the
terrors of the action unfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``A work charged with meaning that must be grasped in its
totality and is far removed from the sensationalism so customary
today,'' Fischer-Dieskau calls Reimann's ``Lear'' in an
introductory note. ``Seldom _ perhaps only in Alban Berg's
`Wozzeck' _ has the loneliness of man been so convincingly
portrayed as the consequence of his blindness to his fellow man.''
</P>
<P>
   At a poignant moment on the hard road to self-knowledge,
Shakespeare's mad, outcast monarch calls himself ``a man more
sinned against than sinning.'' Fischer-Dieskau has the courage to
go beyond the partly justified self-pity, taking his character to
the extremes. Whether the voice is writhing through little
serpentine melismas or oscillating in anguished jungle cries,
whether he is shouting or growling, cracking or letting the sound
fade and flare like the last exhalations of a dying candle, he
surrenders unconditionally to the truth of the moment. The
extraordinary supporting cast is with him every step of the way.
</P>
<P>
   This journey into the heart of darkness, though one of the
artist's supreme achievements, is surely not for all travelers. As
a happier tribute for his 75th year, Deutsche Grammophon has issued
the Fischer-Dieskau Edition. This boxed set of reissues (463 500-2)
consists of 20 CD's, some also to be sold individually at a later
date, plus a bonus disc of folk-song settings by Haydn, Beethoven
and Weber, recorded in 1961 and 1970: A jewel, demonstrating how
light and unaffected this obsessively detail-oriented interpreter
could be.
</P>
<P>
   Exploring the treasure chest in full will take devotion. (The
cover story of International Record Review in June consisted of
nearly three pages of repertory listings from the set and just over
two pages of commentary.) The selection represents most of the
breadth of the artist's repertory, from Buxtehude, Bach and Handel
to Debussy, Ravel and Ives by way of an extremely comprehensive
canon of the German lied (not only Schubert, Schumann, Brahms,
Wolf, Mahler and Strauss but also Liszt, Schoeck, Reger, Busoni and
Pfitzner). A disc of opera arias recorded between 1949 and 1964
includes forays into Bizet (not only the ``Toreador Song'' from
``Carmen'' but also ``O Nadir, tendre ami'' from ``Les Pecheurs de
Perles''), Rossini (``Sois immobile'' from ``Guillaume Tell,'' sung
in Italian), Leoncavallo (the prologue to ``I Pagliacci'') and
Puccini (the quartet from Act III of ``La Boheme'').
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, complete operas are absent, and symphonic repertory
is scarce. On these grounds alone, the Fischer-Dieskau Edition must
be accounted only the tip of an iceberg. (A recent Web search for
the artist turned up 163 record listings, a total that gives a very
false impression. His great Schubert sets, recorded from 1966 to
1972 and originally issued as 29 LP's, include no fewer than 463
songs and appear in discographies as only three items.) Still,
Deutsche Grammophon has struck a perfect balance: The
Fischer-Dieskau whose portrait emerges from the new edition is the
artist who defined an era.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even now, there are addenda. Since 1992, when
Fischer-Dieskau quietly discontinued his singing career, he has
taken engagements reciting poetry and texts with music. Thus, in
1994, for Hyperion's Schubert Edition, he recorded the Wilhelm
Mueller poems omitted by Schubert in his setting of the cycle ``Die
Schoene Muellerin,'' adding a rare perspective to Ian Bostridge and
Graham Johnson's febrile account of the songs. (That Bostridge's
volatile, psychologically searching performance style is scarcely
imaginable without Fischer-Dieskau's example makes the linkage all
the more meaningful.)
</P>
<P>
   And last year, for ECM New Series, Fischer-Dieskau lent his
voice to Peter Ruzicka's 21-minute ``Sich Verlierend''
(``Vanishing''). It is the final track on a CD of string quartets
by Ruzicka, performed by the Arditti String Quartet. Between sharp
gestures that hang in air like the strokes of a Chinese master
calligrapher and pools of silence, the speaker is heard in snippets
of text in several languages by a handful of mandarins of modern
prose, Handke, Adorno and Celan among them.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, is Paul Valery, whose bit begins, ``Die Musik ist
in mir'' (``The music is within me''): A pregnant beginning, spoken
from the soul. And last is the oracular Proposition No. 7 with
which Wittgenstein ends his ``Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus'':
``Wovon man nicht sprechen kann, darueber muss man schweigen''
(``Of things whereof one cannot speak, one must be silent'').
Awkward as this sounds in translation, the original German has the
elegance that arises where accuracy of thought and economy of
expression intersect. If this is not the master's last recorded
word, it deserves to be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1912EDT &QL; 
