u f BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      08-01 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: CASH REFUNDS FOR DELAYED FLIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication warning: also sent with `t' code) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Delayed four hours in Boston. Flight canceled
abruptly in Atlanta. Stuck overnight in Dallas. Left Sunday
morning, got here Monday. Still waiting for the sales team to roll
in from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 corporate travel managers and travel industry
suppliers milled around the trade show floor Tuesday at the annual
convention of the National Business Travel Association at the Los
Angeles Convention Center. An impressive number of these hard-core
travel professionals seemed to have tales of woe, just like the
rest of us, in this summer of the worst air traffic delays ever.
</P>
<P>
   A good time, then, to check back in with Hal Rosenbluth, the
iconoclastic boss of the worldwide Rosenbluth International travel
management company who gave a case of the vapors to the cozy travel
agency world in May with an audacious offer to pay cash refunds to
customers whose flights were delayed. The offer, which is still in
effect, was for those buying tickets on Rosenbluth's Biztravel.com
Web site for flights on five major airlines. The basic terms: $100
for a flight arriving more than 30 minutes late and $200 for a
flight more an hour late; if a flight is more than two hours late,
the full ticket price is refunded.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbluth said at the time that he had confidence that the
airlines ``are doing their best to get their planes off on time.''
He said he did not think the offer, which generated tons of
publicity, would break the bank. But that was before the air system
screeched down into near-gridlock in June, with 50,000 delayed
flights, the most ever.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Rosenbluth, himself a frequent business traveler,
might sound like a man singing the blues. ``I've been stuck; I've
been grounded; I've been canceled; I've been overnighted against my
will,'' he said. Just in the past two weeks, he probably would have
gotten about $5,000 back if he'd taken advantage of his own
company's flight-delay refunds, he added. Biztravel.com's total
payout for its money-back offer as of last week: $298,832.33,
according to Rosenbluth. About two thirds of that total was for
flights that were more than two hours late, or were canceled
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put out more money than we thought we were going to put
out,'' he said. I thought we were going to average somewhere around
$10,000 to $15,000 a week. But in June and July, and especially in
June with horrendous kinds of delays caused by weather, we were
experiencing about $30,000 to $35,000 a week in payments.''
</P>
<P>
   So why is this man smiling?  &UR; Volume &LR; , as the old joke goes.
Thanks to the delays and the word of mouth about the refunds,
ticket sales on the site are up 40 percent, Rosenbluth said. In the
fiercely competitive and rapidly consolidating world of online
travel booking, where establishing a brand name is crucial, the
outlays have been worth it even when they went through the roof, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we struck a nerve,'' said Rosenbluth, whose company
announced on Monday that it had started Rosenbluth Everywhere, a
new Web portal for corporate intranets that will enable corporate
travel managers and travelers to link to a variety of custom online
and wireless booking services, e-mail and corporate
travel-management services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perversely, the delays have been great for us, though I'm
hoping that as we get out of the summer and into the fall, the
weather improves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   TOURISTS DISCOVER LOS ANGELES' NEW SUBWAY
</P>
<P>
   The newly completed 17-mile-long Los Angeles subway has been
ridiculed by mass-transit planners as a $4.5 billion pork-barrel
extravaganza. But it does have its virtues. The line runs from
downtown Los Angeles to Hollywood, where it bores through the hills
and emerges six miles later into the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists are only beginning to find their way onto the subway,
which is called the Metro Red Line. Here's a tip for business
travelers to Los Angeles, many of whom stay not in the more famous
western precincts of town, but in the big new hotels clustered
among the skyscrapers far away in the downtown part of the city:
Try out the subway, which is fast, with clean, comfortable cars and
beautifully designed _ if eerily noncrowded _ stations.
</P>
<P>
   It's especially useful for the increasing numbers of business
travelers who are bringing families along on trips to popular
tourist destinations like Los Angeles. According to industry
statistics, 20 percent of business travelers take spouses or
partners along, and the number of children going along on business
trips tripled in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   From downtown, you can board the subway near the Convention
Center, at Metro Center on Seventh Street, at Pershing Square, at
the Civic Center and at Union Station. The ride to Hollywood takes
about 20 minutes. It's a seedy but requisite stop, if only to
wonder what Nathanael West would make of today's slack-jawed
tourists wandering with their cameras over the faded sidewalk slabs
of movie-star handprints and footprints in front of the decrepit
old Chinese Theater.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the last _ and by far most expensive _ link of the line
was completed under the Hollywood Hills and into the Valley. It's
now just a 25-minute subway ride from downtown to Universal City,
home of the popular Universal Studios theme park. By automobile,
that same ride can take several hours on some days.
</P>
<P>
   And the price is right. Round-trip tickets cost $2.70, and are
good all day long, with unlimited stops. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
