<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9735 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FAUST-THEATER-$ADV06-     08-01 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAUST-THEATER-$ADV06-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY'S CLASSIC OF CLASSICS, ALL 21 HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 6)  
 By ANNE MIDGETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, Germany _ ``Two souls do dwell, alas!, within my
breast,'' cries the title character of Johann Wolfgang von Goethe's
``Faust.'' Struggling between his thirst for pure knowledge and his
desire for earthly pleasures, he finally chooses youth over
embittered old age, signs a pact with the devil and embarks on the
epic drama that is the cornerstone of German literature _ a text,
some say, that is a key to understanding the German soul.
</P>
<P>
   There are also two souls within ``Faust.'' ``Faust,'' Part 1,
published in 1808 and a work of both Goethe's youth and maturity,
contains the well-known plot _ the bargain of the learned Doctor
Faust with Mephistopheles, the seduction of the innocent Gretchen _
that has been echoed in novels, movies, puppet shows and several
operas. ``Faust,'' Part 2, written in Goethe's old age and
published shortly after his death in 1832, is more abstract,
disjunct _ Faust travels from the court of the Emperor Maximilian
to the shores of classical antiquity _ and downright difficult. It
is seldom read and hardly ever staged.
</P>
<P>
   So when one of Germany's most celebrated theatrical directors,
Peter Stein, determined to mount a production of the complete uncut
``Faust,'' Parts 1 and 2, it became an event of national magnitude.
Asserting that no one has ever presented an unedited staging of the
work, Stein calls his ``Faust'' a world premiere, and it has
certainly gained the equivalent attention. Tickets for the
production, which opened on July 22 at Expo 2000 in this
northwestern German city, sold out within hours when sales began in
January. The premiere was front-page news in every paper in the
country. And this even though the full play lasts a total of 21
hours, including intermissions. The production is being presented
in Hall 23 at the world's fair here in two formats: in two-day
marathons on Saturdays (7 hours) and Sundays (14 hours), and on six
consecutive nights.
</P>
<P>
   For Stein, 62, staging ``Faust'' was a longtime dream that
somehow had never been realized: not at the Berlin Schaubuehne,
which he took over in 1970 and where he made his reputation as a
revolutionary during a 15-year tenure, nor at the Salzburg
Festival, where he was the head of the spoken theater branch from
1991 to 1997 under Gerard Mortier. During those years, Stein
developed a reputation for seeking an ever-larger canvas as well as
complete control over his projects. The size and scale on which he
prefers to work were evident in an earlier project in 1994 in
Moscow: a staging of the ``Oresteia'' trilogy, a theater marathon
in its own right.
</P>
<P>
   The director had not forgotten his dream; he had been trying to
find sponsors for ``Faust'' all along. Expo was the first
organization to make him a concrete offer of $2 million. But that
wasn't nearly enough to finance the kind of staging the director
had in mind. The 33 actors in ``Faust,'' including the Swiss-born
star Bruno Ganz _ one of the leads in Wim Wenders' film ``Wings of
Desire'' _ started rehearsals a year before the premiere. The cast
is committed to the production through December 2001, going on,
after Expo ends in October, to a 37-week run in Berlin and a
15-week run in Vienna. With healthy subsidies from DaimlerChrysler,
Deutsche Bank and the German federal government, the project has
ended up costing about $15 million. ``Wonderful,'' say some
Germans; ``megalomania,'' say others.
</P>
<P>
   Stein's ``Faust'' was to be a highlight of another project with
megalomaniacal aspects: Expo 2000 in Hanover. The first world's
fair held in Germany, Expo was forecast as Europe's biggest event
of the new century, with an expected 40 million visitors thronging
to see elaborate new national pavilions and an extensive theme park
with exhibits devoted to Expo 2000's theme:
``Humankind-Nature-Technology: A New World Arising.''
</P>
<P>
   But walking through the grounds of the fair is a reminder that
there are also two souls in the breast of Germany. One is the
spirit of culture or learning that makes the staging of a work as
challenging as ``Faust'' the talk of the entire country. The other
is the more earthly spirit responsible for the ``economic miracle''
of fat-cat postwar Germany: a spirit that tends to express itself
in a kind of earnest, dull didacticism and in huge trade fairs.
</P>
<P>
   These characteristics are prominent at Expo 2000, which is also
making headlines _ as a flop. People are staying away in droves,
put off by high prices, negative assessments in the press and a
geographical location that nobody is interested in visiting. As the
arts pages of Germany's newspapers were filled with articles about
``Faust'' in the days leading up to the premiere, the financial
pages were devoted to stories about Expo 2000's lack of visitors, a
desperate new advertising campaign and the question of whether the
government would step in and bail the fair out of a debt that
Germany's education minister fears could exceed $900 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faust'' is hardly going to affect the financial fate of Expo
2000, since there are only 460 seats available on any given night.
But the work itself does echo Expo's stated theme, exploring the
relationship of man and technology. Stein's staging of it also
represents a huge endeavor, comparable to the scale on which Expo
2000 was conceived.
</P>
<P>
   Stein's goal was to create a monument to Goethe's masterpiece,
and to do so in a spirit of reverence rather than reinterpretation.
His main concern, he has emphasized, was to reproduce the text as
faithfully as possible. ``I don't want to reinvent theater,'' he
said in a recent telephone interview from his home in Rome. ``I
want to bring the experience I have amassed in 35 years of working
in the theater and place it at the disposal of this piece.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His intention to follow Goethe's stage directions and vision to
the letter, changing not a word of the original poem, aroused
skepticism from those who believe a director's job is not merely to
present a piece but to interpret it as well: to create, in other
words, the kind of Regietheater, or directors' theater, that Stein
and his peers have helped to define.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stein was one of the great revitalizers of German theater in
the 1960s and 1970s,'' said Andreas Mury, the theater critic for
the weekly newsmagazine Fokus. ``But now he has turned away from
the principles that made him famous. He has become reactionary.
Simply taking a text and putting it onstage _ that's not
artistic.''
</P>
<P>
   A certain amount of theatrical artistry is required to get
Goethe's text _ with its witches, Greek gods and startling
metamorphoses _ on the stage in any form. ``In the 20th century,''
Stein said, ``artistic forms developed that allow this piece to be
performed.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a choppy, episodic presentation is not as foreign to
a modern audience as it might have been to one in Goethe's time;
Stein likens Part 2, in particular, to cabaret. At the same time,
he said: ``We have developed theatrical structures akin to the ones
Goethe uses. The idea of a circle, of something coming up again and
again, was a formal principle of Goethe's.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, in Stein's view, it is only now possible, in the
early 21st century, to stage the piece at all. He paid tribute to
the idea of the circle by using a spiral to represent the approach
to heaven. In the first scene, a circular metal construction was
suspended from the flies overhead with a few actors representing
angels aboard; in the very last scene, the circle unwound into a
spiral path along which the angels led Faust, now redeemed, to the
Almighty.
</P>
<P>
   In general, however, the most avant-garde element in the work of
Stein's two set designers (Ferdinand Woegerbauer for Part 1 and
Stefan Mayer for Part 2) and the costume designer (Moidele Bickel)
is the juxtaposition of elements both traditional and modern in the
service of illustrating the story. Some sets are as conventionally
representative as Faust's messy, manuscript-lined study, erected on
a proscenium-style stage; others as abstract as the geometric
contours of a forbidding, fortress-like mountain in the fourth act
of Part 2. The witch's kitchen where Mephistopheles takes Faust for
the potion he needs to regain his youth is inhabited by marvelous,
``Planet of the Apes''-style monkeys and a witch who looks like
something out of a Halloween decoration, warts and all. By
contrast, the centaur Chiron is a man fastened to a wheeled metal
contraption that forms his horsey hindquarters and back legs: a
more modern, if no less literal, representation of a mythological
creature.
</P>
<P>
   Another modern element is the way Stein involves the audience.
There are two separate performance spaces in Hall 23, each fitted
out with bleacherlike seating that is continually reconfigured to
create various arenas for the different scenes. The audience is
kept moving between these spaces, each time taking a different
place, sometimes in regular seats, sometimes standing on risers,
and even, at the Emperor Maximilian's court, sitting at banquet
tables set with glasses of real wine.
</P>
<P>
   Moving from one space to another creates a kind of theatrical
democracy: no one is guaranteed a better seat than anyone else. An
unfortunate by-product of this concept, at least during the
premiere, was a kind of cattle-stampede effect every time the doors
opened, as elegantly clad, presumably sophisticated men and women
practically mowed one another down in their efforts to get a good
spot. But at least it kept everyone awake.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of duality was also present in the casting: Stein
divided each of the two leading parts _ Faust and Mephistopheles _
between two actors. This meant that the younger version of Bruno
Ganz's Faust was to be played by Christian Nickel, 31. But the
concept ran into some problems.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Mephistopheles, one of the devils, Robert
Hunger-Buehler, another Swiss actor, was much better than the
other, Johann Adam Oest. Oest tended to bluster ineffectively,
while Hunger-Buehler was at once suave and earthy, understated yet
in perfect control. The contrast between the two performers gave
the character a regrettable disjointedness.
</P>
<P>
   Far worse was the news, five weeks before the premiere, that
Ganz had fallen from a ladder in rehearsal and broken his wrist and
pelvis. After speculation about whether the premiere would be
called off, Nickel took over the entire role, a speaking part that
adds up to about six hours. He did remarkably well under the
circumstances, but his performance was, naturally, uneven.
Surprisingly, he was more convincing as the older Faust than as the
hot-headed young seducer of Gretchen, the role in which he was
originally cast. As a young man, he lacked the sense of making up
for lost time that motivates Faust's disregard for Gretchen's
feelings and her future.
</P>
<P>
   Faust's actions were all the harder to understand because the
Gretchen, Dorothee Hartinger, was so excellent: believable but
never cloying in her innocence, a bit saucy, and heartbreaking in
her final madness.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of the absence of Ganz, Stein said, he regards
the performances on July 22 and 23 as a phase in a continuing
process rather than a premiere. ``The real premiere will take place
in December,'' he said, when ``Faust'' opens in Berlin; by then,
Ganz should have resumed his role.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Stein himself sustained physical injury in the
pursuit of his dream. During a rehearsal, he closed a rusted metal
door on one of his index fingers, and half the finger had to be
amputated. Of course there were comments that Stein had made his
own pact with the devil, sealed, literally, with flesh and blood.
</P>
<P>
   Intentionally or no, it was just this kind of literal-mindedness
that characterized the whole production.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Goethe's text, Mephistopheles first appears to Faust in the
guise of a black poodle: so there, onstage, was a real black
poodle, too cute and well trained to evoke anything very diabolical
and greeted with affectionate titters by the audience. When
Goethe's stage direction reads that Mephistopheles enters by
emerging from a pair of seven-league boots (an image from German
fairy tales), Stein has him come out from behind a pair of huge red
boots. When Faust's former student, Wagner, creates his own hominid
in a glass beaker in his laboratory, Stein had a little boy in a
glowing glass ball suspended over the stage, an original test-tube
baby.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this kind of literalness can approach caricature.
In Part 1, it seemed that Stein might have been deliberately
working tongue in cheek; after all, he had been quoted before the
premiere as saying that ``any idiot can stage Part 1.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Part 2, he followed the text as literally as he had done
in Part 1 _ and it fell flat. The actors declaimed each and every
line and wore costumes Goethe might have recognized: the sea gods
``swam,'' miming the freedom of moving through the water with the
help of invisible roller blades; carnival figures danced, strutted
and expostulated from beneath their comic masks between the ranks
of standing audience members. But it was hard to tell what was
going on. At moments, when a foreign critic might struggle to
follow the words, perhaps during what is called the Classical
Walpurgisnacht section in Part 2, many of the native Germans in the
audience seemed to be asleep.
</P>
<P>
   Stein has spent years trying to understand Part 2 of ``Faust,''
and now that he has finally come to terms with it _ to the envy of
many of his compatriots _ he talks about it with unconcealed
excitement. ``Goethe is trying to deal with the subject of the
genetic program of the human race,'' he said. ``Man does whatever
he is able to, even if it's harmful to nature, or to himself. He
won't refrain from doing something he's able to do just because
it's bad for the environment. That's the Mephistophelean element of
the human race. With the help of the devil, Faust can do everything
he wants to; at the end, he's draining the ocean, creating a new
society. And he fails. But all of this happens in a very humorous
way. Goethe described it as very serious jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   If only more of that excitement, and humor, had come across.
Flushed with discovery, Stein may have forgotten how much of the
text still needs to be explained to others. On the page, the words
seem livelier and funnier than they do in the stentorian readings
of Stein's actors. Which brings to mind another observation that
Goethe made about Part 2, to wit, that it is unstageable.
</P>
<P>
   For once, the critics were virtually unanimous. ``A
disappointment,'' said the Sueddeutsche Zeitung of Munich. ``Too
much Goethe, too little Stein,'' said Die Welt. The Frankfurter
Allgemeine Zeitung compared Stein's pursuit of ``Faust'' to that of
a young man who spends his life running after a young woman,
finally gets together with her in old age for a night of passion,
and has no idea what to do with her, ultimately stripping off her
clothes and leaving her, naked but untouched, on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Stein's description of Man doing something simply because he can
applies (as he well knows) especially to himself, embarking on this
seemingly impossible theatrical project simply because he could.
The consensus after the first round is that he, like Faust, has
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it may not be that simple. In his goal of creating a
monument to the greatest work of German literature, Stein may have
succeeded. For monuments are also for the general public; and in
avoiding interpretive excess, the director may have won over a
wider popular audience to his vision. However flawed the
production, there is something undeniably exhilarating about
experiencing this whole text in two days.
</P>
<P>
   It may emerge that there are two souls within the German
audience as well. The critical one has had its say, but the popular
one raised its voice at the end of the premiere in jubilant
ovation. An account of the dress rehearsal in Die Welt am Sonntag,
one of Germany's less intellectual newspapers, was ecstatic.
Furthermore, plenty of people will be able to see some of ``Faust''
without sitting through the entire 21 hours, if they choose single
evenings from the six-consecutive-night format.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Does Faust really fail? At the start of Part 1, the doctor, sick
of words, demands deeds. Nonetheless, he remains more a man of
letters than of action. In translating Goethe's text from page to
stage, Stein is also moving from word to deed. The complete
``Faust'' may remain more successful as a literary creation than as
a work for the theater. But for Peter Stein, as for Doctor Faust,
the act of striving for deeds is what makes it a story in the first
place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
