<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9740 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAV-OZARKS-HNS &LR;      08-01 2030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAV-OZARKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MISSOURI'S LAKE OF THE OZARKS OFFERS LAID-BACK PACE &HT;    (WITH OPTIONAL TRIMS)
 &HT;    By HARRY SHATTUCK
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE OF THE OZARKS, Mo. _ Here's a tip for those who make
regular pilgrimages to Branson, mid-America's most popular parking
lot:
</P>
<P>
   Next visit, once you've seen all the Osmonds and Lennons _ no
small accomplishment _ and escaped the traffic gridlock on 76
Country Boulevard, mosey up the road about 2{ hours and into a
different world.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find a place where you can dock your boat beside the
Three Pigs Barbecue for lunch _ are the Pig Wings for real? _ and
feast on exquisite Chilean sea bass at Andre's French restaurant
come evening.
</P>
<P>
   A place where millionaires from St. Louis and Kansas City mingle
with tourists on the tightest of budgets.
</P>
<P>
   A place for underground weddings. No, nothing subversive; just
ceremonies in a lakeside cave, where brides and grooms have been
known to arrive and depart on water skis.
</P>
<P>
   A place to explore the ruins of an authentic Scottish castle.
Well, almost authentic.
</P>
<P>
   A place with a lake that covers 54,000 acres _ paradise for
boaters and fishing enthusiasts _ and with 1,150 miles of shoreline
dotted by 13 golf courses, whose terrain humans share with
white-tail deer, wild turkeys and eagles.
</P>
<P>
   A place to unwind on a houseboat, in a campground or at a
first-class, family-oriented resort.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the relaxed pace and diversity of enticements at Lake of
the Ozarks, Missourians' favorite summer playground, make it an
ideal vacation companion to bustling Branson.
</P>
<P>
   Like Branson, a trip here fits easily within most budgets. And
leave those fancy duds at home; casual attire is the rule even at
Andre's.
</P>
<P>
   An orientation:
</P>
<P>
   Lake of the Ozarks carries two connotations: (1) a region in
central Missouri, southwest of Jefferson City (the state capital)
and almost equal distances from Kansas City (165 miles to the west)
and St. Louis (175 miles to the east); and (2) a large body of
water.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by thick forests and rolling hills and guarded by
towering bluffs, the lake reminds one of a river. It meanders for
92 miles, from Bagnell Dam to Truman Dam, with three major
tributaries spreading 10-15 miles from the main water mass.
</P>
<P>
   The lake was created during the Great Depression; with almost
5,000 laborers working on it from 1929 to 1931. Bagnell Dam was
hailed as the most skillful engineering feat of its era, impounding
the Osage River and resulting in the world's largest man-made lake
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Perspective on this enormous undertaking is provided at Willmore
Lodge, a log structure about a mile north of Bagnell Dam. It served
as administrative headquarters during construction and is now a
visitor center and historical museum _ and a recommended first stop
for maps and brochures.
</P>
<P>
   The three-county area contains two state parks, Lake of the
Ozarks and Ha Ha Tonka, and 16 communities of varying size and
appeal. Most resorts, restaurants and golf courses are to the east
of the lake, along or near U.S. 54, but a new toll bridge has
hastened development on the opposite bank.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Recent growth is described as ``explosive'' by Joel Pottinger,
executive director of the Lake of the Ozarks Convention and Visitor
Bureau. Not only is tourism up, but the average home price has
increased by about $40,000 in three years. Sixty percent are
weekend or summer homes, and some overlooking the lake cost as much
as $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Growth creates challenges, however, and Pottinger says, ``The
biggest will be the use of the water _ not the quality, but the
use. I can take you to a place on the Fourth of July where you'll
be all alone; that's because we have so many coves. But the main
channel of the lake can get really crowded.:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Luxury yachts vie for space with speedboats, fishing vessels,
jet-skiers and wave-runners. About 100 marinas provide rentals or
offer parking and services for travelers who bring boats from home.
</P>
<P>
   Not inclined to pilot a craft on uncharted waters? Omer and
Jacquie Clark operate daily tours from the Lodge of Four Seasons
resort (no relation to the Four Seasons chain) aboard their
150-passenger Tropic Island II yacht, pointing out the newest
mansions _ one built for a Dallas Cowboys physician _ and providing
insight into lake traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over here you'll see what we call Party Cove, Omer Clark says.
''People park their boats on Saturday and party all day. Next to it
is Worship Cove. On Sunday, after all the partying, boats move into
this cove, and the same people turn on the radio and listen to
church services.``
</P>
<P>
   Lake fishing can be spectacular, with targets ranging from
largemouth and white bass to crappie, strikers, catfish and _ but
only March 15-April 30 _ the rare paddlefish or spoonbill, said to
be a remnant of the dinosaur age and weighing up to 130 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Just off the water, golf rivals boating as a recreational
pursuit, with courses designed to satisfy all skill levels and
budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most renowned course architects are represented,
including Robert Trent Jones and Jack Nicklaus at Lodge of Four
Seasons courses; Arnold Palmer at Osage National, near the town of
Osage Beach; Tom Weiskopf at Old Kinderhook near Camdenton; and
Bruce Devlin and Robert von Hagge at the Oaks Course at Marriott's
Tan-Tar-A Resort.
</P>
<P>
   High-season greens fees are about $40-$100; packages booked
through resorts can provide savings.
</P>
<P>
   Birders, too, find ample rewards. The area is home to the great
blue heron and, from November into March, concentrations of bald
eagles, especially just below Bagnell Dam on the Osage River. More
than 100 species of songbirds nest during summer in the Missouri
Ozarks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, about Bridal Cave and the Scottish castle:
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, boasting more than 5,700 caves, is steeped in
underground lore. One legend holds that an Osage Indian maiden and
her prince were wed almost 200 years ago in a sacred chamber
beneath Thunder Mountain, a bluff overlooking the lake two miles
north of Camdenton.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of primitive exploration, the cavern became
accessible in 1948, and a couple asked to take exchange their vows
within.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of snowballed from there,'' says Steve Thompson, a
co-owner of Bridal Cave.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 1,800 marriages have been performed in an underground
chapel adorned with stalactites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are as nice as any church wedding,'' Thompson says.
``Others border on the ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Some wedding parties arrive by boat, disembarking at a dock near
the cave's entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``And once the ceremony is completed, we've had them ski right
off our deck into the water,'' Thompson says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There was one occasion, he says, when the bride arrived in a a
hoop skirt that wouldn't fit through the narrow entrance to the
chapel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the wedding party was asked to leave,'' Thompson
says. ``Then she removed her clothes, squeezed into the chapel and
dressed again before the others returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another time, a couple wanted to get married on Harley
Davidsons. They worked all day taking the motorcycles apart and
trying to fit the pieces into the chapel where they would
reassemble them for the wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Portions of the cave are believed to be 40 million years old.
Tours are conducted several times daily. Some passageways create a
tight fit even for people not wearing hoop skirts, and these
caverns are not recommended for anyone who has difficulty walking
or who becomes claustrophobic.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-minute drive to the east, within Ha Ha Tonka State Park,
stands another intriguing attraction. Or what's left of it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1903, wealthy Kansas City businessman Robert Snyder bought
more than 5,000 acres here, and two years later he hired 60
stonemasons from Scotland to build a castle much like those in
their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Snyder was killed in 1906, in what is believed to be
Missouri's first automobile accident. His sons finished his dream
house, though less elaborately than Snyder had envisioned. It
opened first as a home, then as a 60-room hotel.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, a fire gutted the interior and a nearby carriage house.
For almost three decades, the site was abandoned. Then the state
bought it, and the ruins became an integral part of Ha Ha Tonka
State Park.
</P>
<P>
   Ha Ha Tonka is notable, too, for its geological formations,
including a natural bridge, a 150-foot sinkhole and bluffs that
rise to 250 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Lake of the Ozarks State Park, to the north, has more of a
marine emphasis, with 90 miles of shoreline, two public beaches and
boat-launching areas. Another cave system, Ozark Caverns, is within
its boundaries, and naturalists present summer programs in an
open-air pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   A third cave system, Jacob's Cave, lies to the northeast. It is
fully accessible to people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Other diversions in towns and along roadways include six small
amusement parks, seven go-kart tracks, seven miniature-golf
courses, more than 50 antiques shops and the 110-store Osage Beach
Factory Outlet Village.
</P>
<P>
   But where do you hang your hat for the night?
</P>
<P>
   For those who can't get too much of the lake, a company called
Forever Resorts, headquartered near Camdenton, rents houseboats
that accommodate 10 people, with bedrooms, a living area, a kitchen
and a sun deck.
</P>
<P>
   Campgrounds abound. So do bed-and-breakfasts, motels and
condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   Or splurge _ it's not a serious splurge either, given the
reasonable rates _ at one of several full-service resorts.
</P>
<P>
   With 930 rooms and suites, Marriott's Tan-Tar-A is the largest
property. Its accommodations range from standard rooms with
balconies overlooking the lake to five-bedroom houses. Features
include 27 holes of golf, a marina, swimming pools, a health club,
a miniature-golf course, tennis and racquetball courts, a bowling
center and, for winter guests, an ice-skating rink. Room rates
start at $69.
</P>
<P>
   The Lodge of Four Seasons has 300 rooms, 13 suites and 85 two-
and three-bedroom condominiums, with rates starting at $99. Guests
have access to 45 holes of golf, a marina, a spa and swimming
pools.
</P>
<P>
   More intimate is the Country Club Hotel and Spa, home to 63
suites, 16 villas and 20 deluxe rooms, plus a health and fitness
center, a tennis academy with indoor and outdoor courts, and live
jazz five nights a week. Rates are $159-$179.
</P>
<P>
   All these resorts deliver high-quality dining. Try brandied
lobster bisque with lobster ravioli and pecan-encrusted salmon at
Tan-Tar-A's Windrose Restaurant, or savor prime rib or turkey steak
at HK's, one of several eateries associated with the Lodge of Four
Seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Andre's, overlooking the water near the town of Lake Ozark,
provides a special culinary treat _ and marvelous views at sunset.
Parisian onion soup and a carpaccio of beef tease the palate, and
chef-owner Andre Torres' perfectly seasoned entrees even include
Catfish Provencale.
</P>
<P>
   Prefer something less formal? Kenilworth Bakery and Grill in
Lake Ozark and Kenilworth Restaurant in Osage Beach serve soup of
the day in a sourdough bread bowl and tempt with delicious
sandwiches, salads and pastas.
</P>
<P>
   Well off the beaten path, at Mill Creek Cove near the town of
Gravois Mills at the lake's northern extreme, Three Pigs Barbecue &AMP;
Marina welcomes customers who arrive by car or boat. Pork ribs and
onion rings are addictive. But the Pig Wings _ served spicy or mild
_ sure do resemble chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, no visit is complete without a stop at Randy's Frozen
Custard _ ``made fresh every hour'' _ along U.S. 54. Choose vanilla
or chocolate, then mix in key lime, raspberry or any of 26 other
flavorings. Or sample an Ozark Turtle: vanilla custard with hot
fudge and cream caramel fudge, topped with pecans and cherries.
</P>
<P>
   Pick a bench in the open air. Linger for a spell. There is no
rush. The only show is the custard dribbling down your chin. You're
a long way from Branson.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
