<SLUG> BC-TRAV-FREE-STLOUIS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
TEN FREE ATTRACTIONS FOR VISITORS TO ST. LOUIS. &HT;    By SYD KEARNEY
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the United States was young, St. Louis was the starting
point for pioneers searching for adventure and fortune in the West.
Today, the city still draws explorers, but they are more likely to
be wearing Cardinals, not coonskin, caps.
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 sites to explore _ all at no charge _ in the city
that is best known for its big arch and big hitter Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   See the world's biggest pickup truck at Bigfoot 4x4, Inc, home
of the original monster truck. Memorabilia, videos and photographs
illustrate the evolution of the super-sized truck industry. Located
at 6311 N. Lindbergh Blvd. Closed Sundays. Call 314-731-2822 or
access www.bigfoot4x4.com.
</P>
<P>
   The attractive domed Old Courthouse is one of the city's most
distinctive landmarks. Its galleries present exhibits that trace
the history of St. Louis. The courthouse was the site of two
important trials: The Dred Scott trial, which eventually upheld the
rights of slave owners, hastened the beginning of the Civil War;
Virginia Minor's unsuccessful 1870s suit for the right to vote
pushed the women's suffrage movement into the national spotlight.
The Old Courthouse is located at 11 N. 4th St. Open daily, except
holidays. Call 314-655-1600 or access www.nps.gov/jeff.
</P>
<P>
   Polar bears, penguins and a passel of primates are among more
than 6,000 animals that make their home at the St. Louis Zoo.
Located in the beautiful 1,370-acre Forest Park, the zoo owes its
formation to the 1904 World's Fair Bird Cage, which at the time was
the largest bird cage ever built. The free-flight aviary is 228
feet long, 84 feet wide and 50 feet high. The zoo's latest
attraction is the River's Edge, home to Raja, the Asian elephant.
Open daily, except Christmas and New Year's Day. Call 314-781-0900
or access www.stlzoo.org.
</P>
<P>
   Also located in Forest Park is the St. Louis Art Museum. The
museum is housed in the Palace of Fine Arts, a tremendous
beaux-arts building constructed for the 1904 World's Fair. The
museum's 30,000 pieces are showcased in more than 100 galleries and
range from ancient Egyptian mummies to modern art. Open Tuesday
through Sunday. Closed Mondays and holidays. Call 314-721-0072 or
access www.slam.org.
</P>
<P>
   Home to hundreds of exotic animals, delightful Grant's Farm is
the Busch (as in Anheuser-Busch) family's gift to the city. A tram
ride takes visitors through a wildlife preserve. Guests also can
glimpse Clydesdale colts at the stables and an antique carriage
collection. And there is free beer for visitors age 21 or older.
Parking fee. Located at 10501 Gravois. Call 314-843-1700 or access
www.grantsfarm.com.
</P>
<P>
   Explore military history at Jefferson Barracks Historic Park,
which was a U.S. Army post from 1826 to 1946. Robert E. Lee and
Ulysses S. Grant were among the many men who served at Jefferson
Barracks, located at 533 Grant Road. Closed Mondays. Call
314-544-5714.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of fun and hands-on experiments await inquisitive
visitors at the St. Louis Science Center, located in Forest Park.
The center also boasts an OMNIMAX theater and planetarium that
require a fee. Open daily, except Thanksgiving and Christmas. Call
800-456-7572 or access www.slsc.org.
</P>
<P>
   Shop more than 140 stalls filled with fresh produce, fish, meats
and herbs at the Soulard Farmer's Market. The market, located at
the corner of Seventh and Lafayette streets, was founded in 1779.
Open Wednesday-Saturday. Call 314-622-4180.
</P>
<P>
   Play in the hay, milk a cow or learn dog obedience tips at the
1,500-acre Purina Farms. The family attraction boasts a barn-full
of animals and plenty of hands-on activities. Located at Gray
Summit, about 40 miles west of St. Louis. Open Memorial Day through
Labor Day. Reservations required. Call 314-982-3232 or access
www.purina.com.
</P>
<P>
   Discover some of the city's shining stars when you take a stroll
along the St. Louis Walk of Fame, located beside Delmar Boulevard.
Among the 80 inductees: Chuck Berry, Maya Angelou, Buddy Ebsen,
Kevin Kline, Charles Lindbergh, Vincent Price, Bob Costas and
Tennessee Williams. Call 314-727-7827 or access
www.stlouiswalkoffame.org.
</P>
<P>
   Call 800-916-0092 for a free St. Louis visitors guide or go
online at www.explorestlouis.com.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
