<HEADER>
A9742 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAV-FREE-SANFRANCISC     08-01 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAV-FREE-SANFRANCISCO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEN FREE ATTRACTIONS FOR VISITORS TO SAN FRANCISCO &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By SYD KEARNEY
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Francisco visitors bureau reports that out-of-towners
spent $6.55 billion in the city during 1999. That's a lot of sour
dough. Here are 10 free attractions to enjoy when you visit the
city by the bay.
</P>
<P>
   Clang, clang, clang. All aboard for a visit to the Cable Car
Museum and a fascinating look at the history of San Francisco's
favorite form of transportation. A trolley ride costs $2, but a
visit to the museum is free. Vibrant artifacts, video and vintage
cars enhance the experience. Located at 1201 Mason St., the museum
is open daily except for holidays. Call 415-474-1887 or access
www.cablecarmuseum.com.
</P>
<P>
   Asian art and artifacts are the focus of the Chinese Cultural
Center. Exhibits, ranging from antique snuff bottles to
contemporary photography, change frequently. The cultural center is
located at 750 Kearny St. and is open Tuesday through Saturday.
Call 415-986-1822 or access www.c-c-c.org.
</P>
<P>
   Tickle your taste buds with a free tour of the Jelly Belly jelly
bean factory in nearby Fairfield. Visitors see the whole process,
which includes polishing the sugary beans and stamping the Jelly
Belly logo on each tiny treat. Tours are offered daily, except on
holidays and when the factory is undergoing maintenance. It's
located an hour's drive east of San Francisco. Call 707-428-2838 or
access www.jellybelly.com.
</P>
<P>
   Learn about 19th-century military life as you explore the Fort
Point National Historic Site at the Presidio. Rangers lead guided
tours and re-enact cannon drills at this brick fort constructed by
the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers between 1853 and 1861. It's
located under the south anchorage of the Golden Gate Bridge and
open daily. Call 415-556-1693 for information or access
www.nps.gov/fopo/index.htm.
</P>
<P>
   You could spend an entire day roaming the 1,017-acre Golden Gate
Park. Weekends are particularly pleasant because cars are banned
and skaters and cyclists own Kennedy Drive, which slices from east
to west through the park. A few attractions within the park, such
as the Asian Art Museum and the California Academy of Sciences,
charge admission, but even those institutions are gratis one day
each month. Every day the Friends of Recreation and Parks offer
free, guided walking tours of the park, designed in 1871 by William
Hall. Call 415-263-0991 or access www.frp.org.
</P>
<P>
   See an authentic stagecoach and a 2-pound gold nugget at the
Wells Fargo History Museum. The museum also displays bank notes,
vintage photographs and prospecting equipment related to the
history of the bank, founded in 1852. Located at 420 Montgomery
St., the museum is open weekdays except for bank holidays. Call
415-396-2619.
</P>
<P>
   Batman, Uncle Sam, Scrooge McDuck, Garfield, Betsy Ross. They
are all here at the Burlingame Museum of Pez Memorabilia, the
world's largest public display of the flip-top candy dispensers.
Located about 20 miles south of San Francisco in Burlingame, the
museum is open daily except Sundays and Mondays. Call 650-347-2301
or access www.spectrumnet.com/pez.
</P>
<P>
   City Guides' army of volunteers lead free walking tours of the
most historic districts and neighborhoods. Topics include churches
and cathedrals, the 1906 earthquake and the haunts of the original
49ers. Supported by the San Francisco Public Library, tours depart
daily. Call 415-557-4266 or access www.hooked.net/users/jhum.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy a classical music concert each Wednesday at St. Patrick's
Church. Concerts start at 12:30 p.m. The church is located at 756
Mission St. near Yerba Buena Gardens. Call 415-421-3730.
</P>
<P>
   The colorful entertainment, shopping and dining district known
as Pier 39 has many ways to part a tourist from his or her money,
but it also offers attractions that are free. Most famous are the
sea lions that have made the pier their home since 1989. Each
winter, more than 900 sea lions congregate at the pier. Numbers
dwindle in the summer, but there are always a handful around to
provide a photo opportunity. Pier 39 also stages free entertainment
daily in the form of magicians, jugglers, comedians and mimes.
</P>
<P>
   Call 415-391-2000 for a free San Francisco visitors guide or go
online at www.sfvisitor.org.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
