<HEADER>
A9743 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-BUSH-ART-NYT &LR;      08-01 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUSH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S GLOVES STARTING TO COME OFF AS CLINTON PRESSES VOCAL JABS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Pa., W.Va.) (ART ADV: Photo NYT 11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. _ After four days of subtle digs at President
Clinton, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas took him on directly Tuesday
and said the president was ``so desperate to have his legacy intact
by getting Al Gore elected, he'll say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's remarks on his campaign plane came as he stopped in two
more battleground states _ West Virginia and Pennsylvania _ on his
way to a triumphant coronation at the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor was prompted by a stream of verbal broadsides
from Clinton, who said at a recent Democratic fund-raiser that
Bush's message amounts to the following: ``How bad can I be? I'm
governor of Texas. My daddy was president. I own a baseball team.
They like me down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Bush said he welcomed the jabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to me that the president of the United States
would spend time trying to be a political pundit,'' he said. ``He's
so desperate to have his legacy intact by getting Al Gore elected,
he'll say anything just like Al Gore will. And I welcome him to the
arena.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at his first rally of the day at the West Virginia war
memorial at the foot of the state Capitol, Bush stepped up his
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to win the state of West Virginia,'' he told
several thousand people gathered on the humid morning, ``and we're
going to do so because this nation is sick and tired of the
politics of personal destruction.'' He added, ``This nation is
looking for an administration that will appeal to our better
angels, not our darker impulses. This nation does not want four
more years of Clinton-Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in days that he had mentioned the two
Democrats by name in a speech; until now he only implied criticism
at President Clinton for his affair with Monica Lewinsky and his
evasions about it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's wife, Laura, made a similar dig on Monday in her
convention speech about education when she that said her husband
hears pleas from people to bring back an era when children can
``respect the president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush escorted his wife down the aisle of a new, red, white and
blue campaign plane Tuesday morning to celebrate her speech, and
she protested when a reporter suggested she had criticized Clinton:
``I wasn't talking about President Clinton,'' she said, ``I was
talking about my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush jumped in and said their comments simply reflected public
sentiment. ``When people walk up and say `don't let us down,' we're
just reporting what's happening,'' he said. ``I don't think I've
ever mentioned President Clinton's name on the stump recently.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Honor and dignity in the White House is an issue in
this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was talking about Clinton when he introduced
his new running mate, Dick Cheney, as a man ``who knows what the
meaning of is is,'' Bush said, ``Yeah. I was talking about him
then. I sure was. But in the context of having somebody who's going
to shoot straight with the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's rally in West Virginia was followed by one in Harrisburg
late Tuesday, as he completed a trip through six swing states and
prepared to make his entrance in Philadelphia on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Like all the crowds Bush has drawn during the last five days,
the audiences Tuesday were overwhelmingly white, despite the
careful choreography of the convention, which has been featuring
minorities as speakers to moderate the Republican Party's image and
to appeal to suburban voters. The largest group of black voters to
appear at any of Bush's rallies was a cluster of union members who
showed up to protest against him on Thursday in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the lack of diversity showed that his appeals were not
resonating with minority voters, Bush said, ``We'll see on Election
Day, won't we.'' He added: ``I can't remember the makeup of the
crowds in Texas, but I got nearly 50 percent of the Hispanic vote,
and I'm not so sure the nature of the crowd necessarily reflects
the nature of the vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush praised retired Gen. Colin Powell for his prime-time
challenge to the Republican Party on Monday to reach out to black
voters and ``not just during an election-year campaign.'' Bush
said, ``He's right and we have a lot of work to do and I'm going to
go out and try to do the best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   But asked about Powell's criticism that some in the party
condemn affirmative action to help ``black kids get an education''
but do not protest ``affirmative action'' for lobbyists, Bush
sidestepped the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what specific policies he had in mind,'' Bush
said. ``Children not getting into places of higher education? In my
state of Texas we took a very positive step toward ensuring the
racial mix of Texas universities reflect the nature of the
population.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was referring to legislation he signed in Texas after a
federal court threw out an affirmative action plan for higher
education. The legislation guarantees that the top 10 percent of
graduates from every high school in the state will be ensured a
place in a Texas college or university.
</P>
</TEXT>
