 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
TEN FREE ATTRACTIONS FOR VISITORS TO THE ORLANDO AREA &HT;    By SYD KEARNEY
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   With theme park ticket prices inching toward the $50 per day
mark, vacationers to central Florida could use some inexpensive
diversions. Here are 10 free Orlando-area attractions that can help
stretch the family travel budget:
</P>
<P>
   Explore pioneer life at Fort Christmas Historical Park, which
features a restored 1837 fort built during the Second Seminole War.
The site, in the tiny town of Christmas, also includes a museum and
several pioneer homes. It's closed Mondays. Call 407-568-4149.
</P>
<P>
   Admire the nation's largest bald cypress tree in Big Tree Park
near Longwood. More than 3,500 years old, 138 feet tall and 18 feet
in diameter, the tree is known as ``the Senator,'' a tribute to
Sen. M.O. Overstreet, who donated the park to Seminole County. It's
open daily. Call 407-788-0405.
</P>
<P>
   Called a cottage when it was built in 1885, the Bradlee-McIntyre
House is a three-story Victorian featuring an octagonal tower and
gingerbread-trimmed verandah. Located in Longwood and maintained by
the Central Florida Society for Historical Preservation, the house
features a grand salon, a ``Blue Parlor'' and library. The house is
open several times each month for tours. Call 407-332-0225.
</P>
<P>
   Each Saturday morning, Winter Park residents and visitors turn
out for a colorful farmers' market in Central Park near the town's
tree-shaded rail station. Shop for fresh fruit and vegetables,
breads and pastries, flowers, herbs and spices. Call 407-623-3200.
</P>
<P>
   One of the country's finest small museums is on the campus of
Rollins College in Winter Park. The Cornell Fine Arts Museum
collection features more than 6,000 works ranging from the
Renaissance to the 20th century. It's closed Mondays and major
holidays. Call 407-646-2526.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage Florida wines can be found at Lakeridge Winery in
Clermont. The winery, which boasts the largest vineyard in the
state, offers tours and wine tastings, and frequently hosts
festivals and concerts on its grounds. It's open daily. Call
800-768-9463.
</P>
<P>
   The Crealde School of Art, a nonprofit organization formed in
1975, is known for its affordable painting, drawing and photography
courses. For visitors, its Winter Park galleries offer a pleasant
diversion. Changing exhibits spotlight local, regional and national
artists, as well as student works. Call 407-671-1886; access
www.crealde.org.
</P>
<P>
   Stop by Eatonville, America's oldest African-American
municipality. The tiny town is home to the Zora Neale Hurston
National Museum of Fine Arts and hosts a popular black heritage
festival each year. Call 407-647-3307.
</P>
<P>
   Budget some time to hike the Sandhill Nature Trail or paddle a
canoe along the black waters of the Lower Wekiva River State
Preserve near Sanford. The preserve is home to black bears,
sandhill cranes, river otters and alligators. Call 407-884-2008.
</P>
<P>
   Finding anything free in Mickeyland is a challenge, but check
out the Marketplace and West End shopping/entertainment district at
Walt Disney World. It's fun to browse in stores such as Toys
Fantastic, Guitar Gallery and Pooh Corner. And kids enjoy splashing
in the dancing fountains and romping in the outdoor LEGO
playground.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about these and other Orlando attractions,
call 407-363-5800 or access www.go2orlando.com.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
