 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
PLAIN TALK FROM CARLOS MENCIA &HT;    (ADV for release Thursday)
 &HT;    By SHERRY THOMAS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carlos Mencia isn't on the telephone _ half-awake _ to talk
about Ted Nugent. In this long-distance call from a hotel room in
Denver, he's supposed to be plugging his ``Take a Joke America 2000
tour.''
</P>
<P>
   But when did Mencia ever follow the rules?
</P>
<P>
   The half-Honduran, half-Mexican comic has risen to the top by
calling it like he sees it. Bottom line? He thinks everybody should
wake up, speak up and stop complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mexico was such a great place _ or Honduras _ my parents
wouldn't have come here,'' he said during one of his hilarious,
stream-of-consciousness rants. ``I don't understand why everybody
moves to America and (dumps) on it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Nuge came up:
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Mencia believes everybody should speak English:
``People who come to this country who don't learn English end up
paying the price for it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   But when a guy like Nugent insults Mexicans onstage, at a KISS
concert in Houston of all places _ and then gets national media
attention out of it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is he?'' Mencia said, half-laughing into the phone. ``He's
an (idiot).''
</P>
<P>
   Later he continued: ``What he doesn't understand is, immigrants
who come to this country are going to do jobs that he would never
do and his kid would never do. When you go to Taco Bell at 3 a.m.
and the guy doesn't speak English very well, you get mad. But think
about this: How (much of an idiot) is Ted Nugent's son who just
lost his job to a kid named Julio _ who can't speak English _ from
Nicaragua?''
</P>
<P>
   Mencia has been called an equal-opportunity offender (his
publicist makes it nice-nice by describing Mencia's observations
``equal-opportunity frankness.'') But Mencia says comedy should
never be offensive: His job is to make people laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Take a Joke America 2000'' tour has been billed as one of
the most ``ethnically diverse'' comedy shows on the circuit.
Mencia, however, says that while he appreciates the absence of
color lines in the show, it wasn't really intentional. He asked Guy
Torry (who's black), Dave Attell (who's white) and Bobby Lee (who's
Korean) to join him on the road because he thought they were funny
_ not because he was trying to compete with the Rainbow Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tour is me,'' Mencia said. ``You're getting these guys for
free. It's like, `But wait, there's more.' That's who they are.
They are the set of steak knives that don't break.''
</P>
<P>
   On his debut album with Warner Bros., ``Take a Joke America,''
Mencia skewers many of life's hypocrisies and absurdities while
addressing a proverbial rainbow of subjects, including ethnic
stereotypes (don't get him started), racism, people's inability to
laugh at themselves, and a certain president's, um, sexual needs.
</P>
<P>
   Since much of his material plays off the news, it's always
changing. Last week, one day after the Concorde jet crash, Mencia
was already thinking of a way to work it into his act.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm in a plane and the captain comes out and says there's
a mechanical problem and we're going to have to fix it, I don't
stay on that plane, personally,'' he said. ``People are so afraid
to say what they feel. I guarantee you that somebody on that plane
is dead right now when their initial thought was, `I want to get
off this flight.'''
</P>
<P>
   Raised in an East Los Angeles housing project, Mencia is fast
becoming one of hottest comedians in Hollywood. Just don't call him
the ``hottest Hispanic comedian.'' He doesn't want any racial
labels, thank you very much. He just wants to be the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that if I don't get a TV show or if I don't get into
movies, as my predecessors have, then I wasn't good enough,''' he
said. ``That's the way I look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. It you can't make it to the Aerial, check out Mencia in
cyberspace at www.carlosmencia.com.
</P>
<P>
   Details: &UR;  &LR; The ``Take a Joke America 2000'' tour: Dallas, Aug. 5;
El Paso, Aug. 11; Riverside, CA, Aug. 12; Corpus Christi, Aug. 25;
Tucson, Aug. 26.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1919EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9747 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-TICCODE-HNS &LR;      08-01 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TICCODE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
``THE TIC CODE'' HITS HOME (PHOTO) &HT;    By LOUIS B. PARKS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ How many strikes can one film have against it and
survive?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tic Code'' _ the title is strike one _ may supply this
season's definitive answer. It's had enough strikes to retire the
side at your local ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   That audiences are even getting to see the movie _ it opens
Friday in Houston, New York and Los Angeles _ testifies to the
determination of former ``thirtysomething'' actress Polly Draper
and the movie's surprisingly strong emotional story.
</P>
<P>
   Draper wrote the screenplay and stars in the movie, which she
also produced with her husband, Michael Wolff. Wolff also did the
film's jazz-rich score.
</P>
<P>
   Draper and Wolff, who met when he was band leader on ``The
Arsenio Hall Show'' and she was a guest, were in Houston recently
for a screening of ``The Tic Code.''
</P>
<P>
   They were having so much fun cutting up, laughing, talking on
top of each other's sentences and, frankly, snuggling, that you'd
never suspect the seven years of hassles they had getting the movie
made and released. Maybe they were giddy during their visit because
the process had come to a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the vague title, ``The Tic Code'' sounds like a check
list of things screenwriters are told to avoid:
</P>
<P>
   It's about jazz and the jazz world.
</P>
<P>
   One of the three central characters is a 10-year-old boy, and
yet the film, rated R for language, is meant for adults, not
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   It features an interracial love story, between Draper, as the
boy's mother, and a jazz musician played by Gregory Hines.
</P>
<P>
   Though the film was made for theatrical release, it was first
shown on the cable network Starz.
</P>
<P>
   While Draper is well-known onstage (``Closer,'' ``Trudy Blue'')
she's not a name known to film audiences.
</P>
<P>
   And _ this may be the toughest strike _ the story deals with the
neurological disorder called Tourette's Syndrome, making many
people immediately think, ``Uh-oh, disease-of-the-month movie.''
</P>
<P>
   We won't even go into the financial problems or the death of the
original director.
</P>
<P>
   How did ``The Tic Code'' even get made, much less released?
</P>
<P>
   For starters it has a solid, emotional, but not mushy plot about
a mother seeking a strong male role model for her troubled son, a
jazz prodigy who has Tourette's. She falls in love with a musician
(Hines) who is still unwilling to admit that he also has
Tourette's.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the film offers some cool jazz, both on the soundtrack and
played by the characters.
</P>
<P>
   If the story is believable and free from the usual ``disease
movie'' sentiment, it's because Draper knew what she was writing
about: Wolff has Tourette's Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Tourette's is a disorder that causes involuntary behavior, which
can include repetitive, compulsive movements, facial or body tics,
coughing or, in some cases, cursing.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff had never admitted he had Tourette's, even to himself,
until he was 35. When he started dating the outspoken Draper, she
mentioned it right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``What she said,'' Wolff recalled, ``was, `What's the matter
with you anyway?'''
</P>
<P>
   Draper, all but elbowing Wolff in the ribs, insisted she was not
so harsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I said it in a kind, gentle manner,'' she insisted.
``I was the only person, apparently _ according to him _ that was
rude enough to ask him.''
</P>
<P>
   During the interview, Wolff, who manifests the disorder through
tics, not the more publicized but less common cursing, displayed no
obvious sign of Tourette's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expended a lot of my life learning to suppress and repress
it,'' Wolff said. ``It gets better and worse, but you master
yourself better.''
</P>
<P>
   After ``The Tic Code'' was shown on cable _ due to a deal made
by the bank to cover the movie's outstanding bills _ the film won
audience-popularity awards at a number of film festivals, including
Berlin, the Hamptons and Montreal. That was enough to make small
distributor Lion's Gate decide to give it a chance in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   But the real story of ``The Tic Code'''s survival is Draper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polly gets the credit because she decided she wanted the movie
to be made the way she wanted or not at all, not going with what
the studios wanted to change,'' Wolff said.
</P>
<P>
   When she first wrote the script for ``The Tic Code,'' several
studios showed interest but wanted changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marketing people would say, `Are you crazy? It's got an
interracial romance; it's got this kid with tics. It's got jazz,
and who cares about jazz?'''
</P>
<P>
   Draper just kept saying no to changes. To her, all the elements
tied together: an African-American with Tourette's who is unwilling
to admit it, finding safety in the world of jazz, which readily
accepts both blacks and abnormal behavior; a mother trying to find
a role model for her Tourette's-afflicted son.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a story that needed to be told a certain way,'' she
said. ``I don't care if I'm the only one seeing the movie in some
screening room somewhere. I have to see it the way I'm proud of it.
Otherwise, I can't live with myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple regard Tourette's in the film as a metaphor for
people outside of society's comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart of this movie is people accepting who they are,''
Wolff said, ``not having to be the ideal of normal. Whether it's
being a black person, having Tourette's _ whatever it is _ we feel
everyone, underneath, has something they feel is wrong with them,
something where they feel they don't quit fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   Jazz was the movie's glue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the main character of the movie,'' Draper said. ``It's
the fabric that ties the three people together. It's the thing that
allows them to talk about their Tourette's.''
</P>
<P>
   How well ``The Tic Code'' does in its initial release will
determine its future in national release. Whatever its fate, Draper
and Wolff said, they feel they have succeeded in what they set out
to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just so happy it's coming out at all,'' Draper said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
