<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9750 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-COX-CVN-BUDGET02     08-01 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CVN-BUDGET02 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These stories from the Republican National Convention in
Philadelphia are moving to all points.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-MAIN _ In an evening where the themes of strength and
compassion intertwine, the main speakers are Sen. John McCain and
former Gen. Norman Schwartzkopf on defense policy, Bush foreign
affairs adviser Condoleeza Rice on foreign affairs, and Elizabeth
Dole. (Herman).
</P>
<P>
   CVN-PROTESTS _ PHILADELPHIA _ Protests turned violent Tuesday as
demonstrators and police battled with fists and clubs in the heart
of the city. More than 90 arrests were reported, and delegates were
delayed arriving at the Republican National Convention. (Galloway)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-BUSH _ CHARLESTON, W.Va. _ George W. Bush continues his
march to the convention with appearances here and in Harrisburg,
Pa. (Heath).
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GAY _ PHILADELPHIA _ Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., becomes the
first openly gay official to address a Republican National
Convention, though his topic Tuesday night is trade. There are
reports that the head of the Texas delegation was trying to head
off a walkout by some members when Kolbe speaks. That would mar the
convention theme of tolerance and diversity, exemplified by a
reception Tuesday honoring Republican gay and lesbian elected
officials. (Dart).
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-MONEY _ PHILADELPHIA _ Like most coventions, this one is
awash in corporate sponorship, in various forms. Companies like
BellSouth with interests before the Commerce Department are
shelling out big bucks to sponsor lavish parties for Reps. Mike
Oxley and Billy Tauzin, who are vying for the committee chair.
Lobbyists pushing private Social Security accounts have supplied
1,000 beach balls to be released on the convention floor Wednesday
with slogans like ``Don't float more debt'' and ``Don't inflate the
trust fund.'' And Kraft is continuing its tradition of supplying
elephant-shaped macoroni to delegates and media. (Sherman).
</P>
<P>
   CVN-CHENEY _ PHILADELPHIA _ Dick Cheney said Tuesday he would
join George W. Bush on a post-convention barnstorming tour
targeting battleground states in the Midwest. ``We are going to
take the battle to the heart of Democratic territory,'' Cheney
said. ``After the convention, George W. Bush and I will be taking a
train to campaign in states such as Illinois and Michigan.''
(O'Dell)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GEORGEP _ PHILADELPHIA _ An interview with George Prescott
Bush, the 25-year-old nephew of the nominee seen as one of the
GOP's strongest forces to attract young and Hispanic voters.
(Crowley)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-YOUNG-DELEGATE _ PHILADELPHIA _ ``Being the youngest, a lot
of people feel the need to protect me or guide me,'' said Karin
Henninger, 18, apparently the youngest delegate to the Republican
National Convention. But this Colorado alternate knows what she
thinks. (Garcia).
</P>
<P>
   CVN-NOTEBOOK _ PHILADELPHIA _ Tidbits from the Republican
National Convention. (Staff).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
