<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9752 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-VIDEO-NOTES-HNS &LR;      08-01 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-NOTES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
REVIEWS OF NEW VIDEO &AMP; DVD RELEASES &HT;    By BRUCE WESTBROOK
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Romeo Must Die''
</P>
<P>
   If ``Titanic'' was ``Romeo and Juliet on a sinking ship,'' this
is ``Romeo and Juliet in a modern American gang war.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea worked better in ``West Side Story,'' not to mention
``Romeo + Juliet.'' Here, mundane mechanics are melded to fierce
ethnic stereotyping to create a cultural melting pot simmering with
too few action scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romeo'' was intended as a breakthrough vehicle for Hong Kong
action star Jet Li after his strong supporting turn in the
unsatisfying ``Lethal Weapon 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Here he plays a Hong Kong cop heading to the United States with
Motivation No. 1 (and only) for far too many action films: revenge.
His brother was killed in a conflict between organized crime groups
_ one black, the other Asian.
</P>
<P>
   Via absurd coincidence, Li instantly meets Trish (singer
Aaliyah), daughter of the black crime boss, and they, of course,
fall in love. You figure out the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The drama is dreary, especially with so many flat supporting
performances (not counting Delroy Lindo's fine work as the black
godfather).
</P>
<P>
   But Li is likable enough, and he makes the most of his chances
to cut loose.
</P>
<P>
   If you enjoyed the high-flying stunts of ``X-Men,'' you can find
some of the same thrills here, thanks to Corey Yuen. For ``X-Men,''
Yeun was ``action director.'' For ``Romeo Must Die,'' he was
``martial-arts coordinator.`` Either way, his work is a kick, and
Li delivers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this is largely an exploitation flick you wish would get
busy and exploit. Instead, it tries to tell an ambitious yet
ultimately tired tale and sputters badly while its engine idles
between action scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romeo'' has one extra for both VHS and DVD: Aaliyah's music
video for her contribution to the soundtrack, ``Try Again.'' The
DVD also adds several featurettes and trailers. &QL; 
Grade: C &QL; 
2000, R, Warner, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever It Takes''
</P>
<P>
   For yet another teen romantic comedy, boy-girl maneuvers are
patterned after a classic tale, this time that of ``Cyrano de
Bergerac.''
</P>
<P>
   At least there's a fine cast. Playing high school seniors are
``The Practice'''s Marla Sokoloff and ``Once and Again'''s Shane
West. They're next-door neighbors, a la Melissa Joan Hart and
Adrian Grenier in ``Drive Me Crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   He craves an unattainable girl, while his jock friend eyes
Marla. Together the boys scheme to fulfill each other's dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a fine array of pop songs, the film provides the usual
youth-market pandering, including wealth fantasies and a strange
absence of parents.
</P>
<P>
   These high schoolers live like they're in their early 20s (which
the actors are) and are financially independent. In one scene, they
have free rein in a mansion for an alcohol-soaked party.
</P>
<P>
   The characters are witlessly overstated and unlikable. The
script isn't smart, and it lacks a heart. For a John Hughes flick
wannabe, there's also an aimlessly edgy slant. ``Whatever It
Takes'' is coarse but not comical, with some gross-out gags that
just don't fit.
</P>
<P>
   But at least we can't blame Freddy Prinze Jr. for this one. &QL; 
Grade: D+ &QL; 
2000, PG-13, Columbia TriStar, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD
$24.95
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   Also due this week are ``NBA Finals 2000 Official Championship
Video and Second Heaven: The Official NHL 2000 Stanley Cup
Championship Home Video.'' Each is on tape only, available from USA
Home Entertainment. Each runs one hour and costs $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   Due next week: ``Reindeer Games,'' ``Dragonheart: A New
Beginning,'' ``Supergirl,'' ``The Grandfather,'' ``Holy Smoke'' and
``Jerry and Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   Nanny bonanza
</P>
<P>
   If a Julie Andrews nanny movie is among your favorite things, a
double dose awaits you on video.
</P>
<P>
   New in stores is a ``Gold Collection'' edition of ``Mary
Poppins'' ($22.99 on VHS, $29.99 on DVD). Due Aug. 29 is a
35th-anniversary edition of ``The Sound of Music'' ($14.98 on tape,
$29.98 on disc).
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Poppins'' has been on tape since the '80s and had an
earlier DVD release. But the new ``Sound of Music'' is big news.
This marks the beloved film's debut on the booming DVD market.
Also, Fox is loading the two-disc sets with more than six hours of
bonus material, much of it never seen.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among extras will be ``The Sound of Music'': From Fact to
Phenomenon,`` a new 87-minute documentary on Austria's singing Von
Trapp family, as it is in real life and as it is portrayed on the
screen. Narrated by Claire Bloom, it will have interviews with Von
Trapp family members, as well as ''Sound of Music`` stars Andrews
and Christopher Plummer, director Robert Wise and others in the
cast and crew.
</P>
<P>
   Also shown will be rare footage from the set. Many ``home
movies'' shot on location by the cast and crew in Salzburg,
Austria, were uncovered recently, lending themselves to this
feature.
</P>
<P>
   Discs also will offer trailers, TV and radio spots, audio
interviews, storyboards, production stills, sketches and a
production diary. Still more interviews, photos, clips and music
will arise, along with audio tracks by Wise and screenwriter Ernest
Lehman.
</P>
<P>
   Also shown will be ``Salzburg Sight and Sound,'' a theatrical
featurette from 1965, with cast member Charmian Carr hosting a
Salzburg travelog. (It previously appeared on laserdisc.)
</P>
<P>
   For tech-heads, Fox says the film has a ``breathtaking new
hi-definition video transfer created from the original 65mm film
source,'' with Wise's approval. The soundtrack has been restored
and presented ``in discrete 4.1 Dolby Digital.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Poppins'' has far fewer spoonfuls of sugar. Its first DVD
had no extras, and this one adds only a few _ chiefly, a 16-minute
documentary, ``The Making of `Mary Poppins,''' hosted by star Dick
Van Dyke.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's not new.`` Making of'' was produced for a previous VHS
edition in 1997. (Oddly, ``Poppins' '' new tapes don't have the
featurette.)
</P>
<P>
   Other extras for DVD: a 16-question trivia game (geared to young
kids); a theatrical trailer; and ``Hollywood Goes to a World
Premiere,'' a 10-minute featurette documenting the film's premiere
in August 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Some of its footage overlaps the making-of material, and its
sustained film clips are more superfluous than supercali _ well,
you know.
</P>
<P>
   But it's interesting to see fresh young stars of the era make
their glittering arrivals, from Mary Tyler Moore and ``enchanting
Angie Dickinson'' to Andrews _ beaming while wrapped in fur _ and
Van Dyke with his wife and kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Poppins'' is shown in the wide-screen format, with a
1.85-to-1 aspect ratio on DVD. As for the transfer, it looks
exquisite.
</P>
<P>
   If you already own the film on tape or disc, Disney feels your
pain. The studio is offering a $5 ``upgrade'' rebate when you send
in the proof-of-purchase tab or UPC symbol from your original copy.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   Clint's Warner link
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Cowboys'' (opening Friday) isn't Clint Eastwood's first
film for Warner Bros.; it's just his latest. In fact, the actor's
longtime link to Warner has enabled that studio to issue a new
``Clint Eastwood Collection'' spanning 27 films.
</P>
<P>
   All are on VHS, but only 10 are on DVD: ``Unforgiven,''
``Absolute Power,'' ``The Bridges of Madison County,'' ``Dirty
Harry,'' ``The Gauntlet,'' ``Pale Rider,'' ``The Outlaw Josey
Wales,'' ``True Crime,'' ``Bronco Billy'' and ``Kelly's Heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   The last two are making their DVD debuts.
</P>
<P>
   Only on VHS are ``Magnum Force,'' ``The Enforcer,'' ``Sudden
Impact,'' ``The Dead Pool,'' ``Any Which Way You Can,'' ``City
Heat,'' ``Every Which Way But Loose,'' ``Firefox,'' ``Heartbreak
Ridge,'' ``Honkytonk Man,'' ``A Perfect World,'' ``Pink Cadillac,''
``The Rookie,'' ``Tightrope,'' ``Where Eagles Dare,'' ``White
Hunter,'' ``Black Heart'' and ``Eastwood on Eastwood.''
</P>
<P>
   Tapes are $14.95 each, while discs are $24.98.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
