<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9755 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-GOP-INSIDE-BOS &LR;      08-01 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-INSIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST SHOW AT THE CONVENTION: PSEUDO.COM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It may go down in history with Kittyhawk and
Marconi's first transatlantic message. Then again, it may be
remembered for its distinctive blend of Wayne's World and Animal
House in a skybox the size of Elizabeth Taylor's bathroom. Either
way, Day One of pseudo.com at the Republican convention was the
best show in this undazzling spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   All day Monday, print and network reporters wandered into the
cramped space to witness history or, at the very least, hide from
their editors. No one was quite sure what was happening except
that, for the first time, they could peek at any part of the hall
on a computer screen while following the live video interplay
between chatroom addicts and talking heads.
</P>
<P>
   This was not controlled chaos; it was the real thing. Pseudo was
playing without a net. Guests either appeared or they didn't. ``We
have no idea who will show up from those we asked,'' said pseudo
editorial director Gersh Kuntzman, who rather liked the
arrangement. ``Then there are others here we didn't ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Just who invited Philadelphia City Comptroller Jonathan Seidel,
for example, remains unclear. But there he was, with the look of a
man who had just made a huge mistake, waiting next to the stale
crackers and grape stems to be an online guest in the pseudo
skybox. He proved to be game, though, and declared the experience
``amazing'' as he left.
</P>
<P>
   The on-air talent was an eclectic bunch. Some appeared on
pseudo, while others were guests on Salon.com's hour-long show that
runs in the pseudo skybox each evening of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Among the talking heads during a two-hour stretch were 90
year-old CBS legend Robert Trout; the formidable arriviste and
Shadow Convention doyenne Arianna Huffington; New York Congressman
Jerry Nadler; Log Cabin Republicans head Rich Tafel; and The New
Republic scribe and Princeton history professor Sean Wilentz, who
favored a Jimmy Buffett look in a Hawaiian shirt with a beer in his
hand.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere was decidedly Margaritaville. ``Rock on,
gentlemen,'' producer Sam Hollander exorted the group. He was kind
enough to add, ``You can bring the beer with you,'' as Wilentz
prepared to join the online fray. During the breaks, pseudo piped
``Green Onions'' by Booker T and the MGs through its speakers.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, pseudo CEO David Bohrman, who reigns as skybox
impresario, gazed at the dead food littering the floor and
announced, ``I'm going to get the garbage out of here before we do
anything else. The Internet should be neat.''
</P>
<P>
   On a good day, the pseudo experience works something like this:
an EJ, pseudo's version of a DJ, monitors a chatroom whose members
receive a live audio feed from the skybox discussion. Monday's EJ,
a woman with the online moniker of Jaxx, took questions from the
chatroom off of her computer screen and gleefully interrupted the
on-air guests with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to be obnoxious,'' she said. ``If people in the
chatrooms don't believe what they're hearing, I'll let the online
people know about it.'' Jaxx gives new meaning to the talk show
dictum, ``Feel free to jump in at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Pseudo's fanciest gizmos are its five 360-degree web cameras
that continually pan the convention hall, day and night. A user of
its web site can control the view with a computer mouse and stop
the camera at any point to focus on interesting turf.
</P>
<P>
   It's not much as voyeurism goes. Republican delegates, after
all, don't provide many steamy scenes. And the visuals are
worthless until the technology improves. For now, they occupy a
small piece of real estate on a computer screen and are all but
impossible to decipher without 3-D glasses and a microscope. Pseudo
spokeswoman Jeanne Meyer conceded as much when she called the look
``chunky pointillism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not there yet,'' admits Bohrman, a former CBS producer.
``But from these feeble beginnings we see a glimpse of things to
come. The technology is too early now and it will be too late four
years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuntzman adds that the pseudo package poses no threat to
reporting. ``We will never affect serious journalism,'' he says.
``We're the window dressing around it. Fortunately for us, there is
so little real reporting going on here that the question for us is,
did we book good guests?''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear: interactive explorations of medicare funding
are just as deadly as similar exercises on cable or at the Shadow
Convention, which continues to lose altitude daily. Pseudo's best
chance for survival is its mix of sponaneity and rudeness. If it
ever gets polite, it's in real trouble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9756 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-BOARDGAMES-HNS &LR;      08-01 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOARDGAMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GA-GA OVER GAMES: BOARD GAMES HAVEN'T LOST THEIR APPEAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos; w/Boardgame-Tips) &HT;    By DANIEL J. VARGAS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just got paid. It's Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The radio is tuned to a station spinning the best from the '70s
and '80s. Chocolate chip cookies are baking to a golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Come inside the Rodriguez household, where Fridays are family
board game night around the kitchen table.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, it's Monopoly _ Bass Fishing edition-style.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Rodriguez, the matriarch of this game-loving family, is
the trustworthy one. That's why she's always the designated banker.
</P>
<P>
   Dad _ Dave Rodriguez _ is resident comedian. More on that later.
</P>
<P>
   Maripat, 13, is the forgetful one who's more worried about the
layout of her money than who lands on her property.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen-year-old Dan wears his emotions on his sleeve and has a
noticeable allergic reaction to losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling lucky tonight,'' Mom proclaims.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you said that the last 10 games,'' her husband quips. The
kids laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, this is the Bass Fishing version where Bassmaster's
Classic is the equivalent of Boardwalk and houses and hotels become
bait shops and marinas. So Mom's game piece is the tackle box,
daughter the hat, Dad is the open-mouthed bass and son the fishing
boat.
</P>
<P>
   About 45 minutes into the game, things are getting a little
cutthroat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys, we need to think about some alliances here,'' Dad says.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't `Survivor','' the son responds.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet, anyway. (FYI: A board game version of CBS' hit
voyeuristic show is expected on shelves by November. Rats _ we hope
_ not included.)
</P>
<P>
   The simplistic, yet mind-stimulating, board game is thriving
despite the fact we live in a high-tech, computer-driven world
where most traditional board games such as Monopoly and Scrabble
are now available to play on computer with snazzy graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Avid players say, however, there's nothing like cracking open a
board game, spreading it out on the floor or table, and hanging
with friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The board game) Risk is fun, and Risk is fun to play against
a computer but nowhere near as fun as playing with a neighbor or
your best friend,'' says Erik Arneson, board game guide for
About.com. ``It's that face-to-face social aspect. Board games are
a nice way to get away from a computer monitor and use your brain
in a different way.''
</P>
<P>
   To say board games go way back is an understatement. The
precursor to checkers, Arneson says, dates back to 600 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us probably remember the more recent classics such as
Clue, the Game of Life, Stratego, Candy Land, Scrabble and Risk.
</P>
<P>
   Who can forget the characters of Mr. Green, Professor Plum and
Col. Mustard? Or the metal game pieces of Monopoly: Scotty, the
Scottish terrier; the tiny thimble; and the old-school racing car.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the computer and the Internet have opened the doors
to new games around the world, especially in Germany where games
such as Diplomacy, Settlers of Catan and Torres are made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm totally immersed in board games,'' says Arneson, who owns
about 150 board games. ``I buy imported games from Germany. There
are great games out there for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   And great places to play them: among them coffee houses and
cafes.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday and Saturday nights, board gamers practically rule the
Dessert Gallery in central Houston.
</P>
<P>
   For the past five years, board game fans have packed the place
to play Scrabble, Yahtzee and Backgammon, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are just crazy about playing games,'' owner Sara Brook
says. ``I've seen people crowded around a table to look at a hot
game of Trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she isn't a board game enthusiast herself, Brook
purchased more games to keep her clientele happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got more games now, and we branched out to Pictionary,''
she says. ``We even have Barrel of Monkeys for the young kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Morris, spokesman for Hasbro Games, which owns Milton
Bradley and Parker Brothers, says board games are not just
surviving, they're growing in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   He says more than 600 people will compete at the
Hasbro-sponsored Scrabble national championship to be held next
week in Providence, R.I. _ that's a threefold increase since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in 1999, sales of the company's 30 most popular classic
games such as Monopoly were up 6 percent from the previous year.
Children's games such as Trouble were up 14 percent. Hasbro does
not release sales figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the very mature games to get a 6 percent increase is
almost amazing,'' Morris says. ``People are finding that they want
to come back to board games. They're vital because they provide
social interaction like no other form of entertainment can.''
</P>
<P>
   When just mere inches separate you from the next player, you're
bound to learn a few things about them beyond personal hygiene
habits. And not all of it is nice.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Nice Guy suddenly becomes Mr. Know-It-All. The quiet one
transforms into an ear-bursting Chatty Cathy. The soft-spoken one
becomes a ruthless assassin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy for people to hide their faults, but it's harder for
them to do it when they're playing a board game,'' Arneson says.
``You simply have more interaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the presence of games and competition mean sore
losers aren't far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can get pretty nasty,'' Arneson says. ``I've seen people
curse at the board, other players. They'll knock off the pieces
from the board, abruptly leave or accuse someone of cheating. It's
amazing how serious people take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the inevitable cheater who likes to swipe money
from the bank or move pieces when there's a bathroom break.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you do?'' Arneson asks. ``You have to ask youself if
you want to play with them again. You can't stop it the first time
around, but you can the second.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing games on Fridays has been a tradition for the Rodriguez
family for about 15 years. The family has two other sons, Bob, 18,
and Michael, 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sons will come home from college and want a Monopoly night,
and that's wonderful,'' Janet Rodriguez says. ``It's an opportunity
for them to bring up things going on in their lives in a relaxed
atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez says family game night is a priority, especially as
their children get older and begin to start their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is they're family, and we have to know each
other,'' she says. ``And to do that, we have to be together.''
</P>
<P>
   Togetherness seems to be a common theme among board game
players.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Haseltine, a 61-year-old teacher from Pearland, Texas,
plays Parcheesi nightly. It's not that she has a particular
fondness for the game. She enjoys watching her 87-year-old mother,
Novella Myers, play.
</P>
<P>
   Myers suffers from mild memory loss, and to see her mentally
active is a beautiful sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see more sparkle in her eyes when she plays,'' Haseltine
says, adding that she's lost interest in needlework and
conversation as she's gotten older. ``It's enjoyable to just watch
her strategize and plan ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers' love for Parcheesi stems from childhood when she played
Parcheesi on her family's farm in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Now, every night Haseltine breaks out the game on top of a
wooden, folding food tray. They'll play three games a night.
</P>
<P>
   Mother and daughter don't talk much unless it's about the game.
Not even the lack of conversation can spoil these moments,
Haseltine says.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's just a whiz at this game,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   At times like this, it doesn't matter who wins.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
