<HEADER>
A9763 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILMPRESERVATION-1100     08-01 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMPRESERVATION-1100(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD IS FINALLY FOCUSING ON SAVING ITS CELLUOID PAST
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by PRESERVATION-LOST FILMS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW MARTON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hugh Hefner, yes he of the silk pajamas, rotating bed and that
little social bombshell he launched nearly 50 years ago, is on the
phone from ``the mansion'' and is mildly fulminating. Hefner is a
self-anointed defender of Hollywood celluloid history. He's got the
letter ``Y'' from the original ``Hollywood'' sign as a badge of his
film protector credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me that the entire Hollywood community has been so
completely unaware of its own heritage,'' says Hefner, who admits
to a sentimental attachment to those melodramatic yarns involving
William Powell, or Basil Rathbone as the tweedy Sherlock Holmes.
``In terms of film preservation and recognition of film as a
universal art form, and one of the most important parts of this
country's past, there has been a real lack of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The level of Hefner's high dudgeon seems justified. Although the
last decade has revealed a sudden awareness by mainstream Hollywood
studios of the need to preserve and resurrect a number of classic
films, this is more an 11th-hour Band-Aid gesture than anything
else. It barely masks Hollywood's startlingly cavalier neglect
toward its own product. The studios' passivity stands in marked
contrast to the actions of graying moguls like Hefner who regularly
pony up tens of thousands of dollars to preserve their childhood
screen favorites in the name of posterity.
</P>
<P>
   Pounding home the crying need for greater film preservation
awareness was June's American Movie Classics eighth annual
``Preservation Festival.'' This year, AMC trumpeted its message by
showcasing the films of Alfred Hitchcock and the glossy restoration
of ``Rear Window,'' whose original negative was reportedly so
damaged that it almost resisted resuscitation.
</P>
<P>
   AMC could easily have bandied about statistics that point to a
disturbing film mortality rate. About half of the 21,000 shorts and
feature films shot before 1950 are lost, that is to say,
unviewable. For films made before 1921, including numerous silent
era chestnuts, the number of perished films rises to 90 percent. At
Paramount studios alone, only 37 of 1,014 silent films survive. And
most of the color films produced on Eastman Color stock between
1950 and 1975 will likely fade into pink obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, in the Hollywood community, there have been
accounts of tins of film stock and negatives converted into
Wilshire Boulevard landfill or Pacific Ocean chum, images that
perhaps best sum up the movie industry's malign neglect of its
archival riches.
</P>
<P>
   For a vain community so eager to elevate its work to near mythic
status, film artists have historically yielded to the hard-core
business decision of jettisoning their films as soon as they
exhausted a screening run. ``For Hollywood, it has always been the
shortsighted approach of what can you do for me today or
tomorrow,'' says Ken Weissman, head of the motion picture
conservation center of the Library of Congress' facility at
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Almost none of Hollywood's most beloved films has been
inoculated from the Chinese water torture of gradual deterioration.
While working on the re-release of ``Star Wars,'' George Lucas
discovered an original negative so decomposed that he had to resort
to outtakes to complete the restoration. Universal Pictures
reportedly no longer has a single original print of its
Oscar-garlanded ``The Sting.'' The original negative for John
Ford's ``Stagecoach'' is gone. And until a recent restoration
supervised by the late Stanley Kubrick himself, ``2001: A Space
Odyssey'' was shaded like a smoked salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Putting a human face on that kind of deterioration reveals whole
film careers reduced to celluloid dust. ``Take someone like Theda
Bara who was the Madonna and Sharon Stone of her silent-film day,''
says Margaret Bodde, director of The Film Foundation. ``Of the more
than 40 films she made, only one of them has survived.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety, not heritage, was the prime incentive for most studios'
systematic destruction of many films made prior to 1950. Old film
stock was composed of silver cellulose nitrate, a substance that
put the ``silver'' luminousness onto the silver screen. The only
catch is that nitrate film made prior to 1950 possessed properties
alarmingly similar to gunpowder. As it ages, cellulose nitrate
breaks down, turns to jelly or dust, and runs a good risk of
exploding _ as happened during nitrate fires consuming the original
negatives of ``Singin' in the Rain'' and ``Citizen Kane.'' So the
studios pre-emptively destroyed the silver nitrate powder keg they
had inadvertently created.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many of silver nitrate's replacements weren't
improvements in preservation. One brand of ``safety'' film, a
popular replacement stock, suffered from the ``vinegar syndrome,''
whereby extreme changes in temperature would trigger an instability
in the film while emitting a pungent, vinegar odor. And even
without this odoriferous demise, a film's surface area could show
scratches, brittleness, tearing and/or massive fading, known as the
shrimp effect, ``where facial highlights become a lovely shade of
crustacean,'' says Robert Harris, an archivist with The Film
Preserve, one of the country's leading film restoration firms.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
