A9765 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AIRFRANCE-CRASH-NYT &LR;      08-01 0290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFRANCE-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ENGINE PARTS IN CONCORDE DEBRIS TRAIL, SAY INVESTIGATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   French investigators said Tuesday that they had not found any
engine parts in the trail of debris shed by an Air France Concorde
on its brief flight before crashing near Charles de Gaulle Airport
outside Paris on July 25.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Bureau of Accident Investigations also said
that it had found no evidence of any ``particular problem before
the departure of the flight.''
</P>
<P>
   The crew had radioed shortly before the crash that two engines
were not working properly, raising the possibility that an engine
had broken up in flight and thrown off parts that punctured a fuel
tank or a fuel line; in that case, engine parts would have dropped
on the ground. Some work had been done on an engine part, a thrust
reverser, shortly before takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators are focusing on the possibility that tires
burst and sent debris flying up into the fuel tanks or other parts,
releasing fuel that allowed a spectacular fire to begin even before
the plane had lifted off the runway.
</P>
<P>
   The French authorities reiterated Tuesday that Air France's five
remaining Concordes would stay grounded for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways, which had continued flying its seven Concordes,
had to take one out of service Tuesday, shortly before it was due
to leave Heathrow Airport in London for New York, because more work
was needed on an engine that had been replaced over the weekend.
That plane had suffered an engine surge while landing at Heathrow
from New York on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways put the 33 passengers on another Concorde, which
took off more than two hours late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9767 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-GOP-MINORITIES-C     08-01 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-GOP-MINORITIES-CHAIT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FALSE FACE OF THE GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Wednesday, Aug. 2, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By JONATHAN CHAIT    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ You might mistake the Republican convention for an
ethnic festival or a forum on women's rights,'' The New York Times
said in a description that seems to capture the scene in
Philadelphia this week. Except this dispatch didn't come from the
convention that is nominating George W. Bush, but the one that
nominated his father 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The image of diverse Republican speakers is so at odds with the
usual portrayal of the party that some people have concluded that
something radical and significant must be going on. Last week, a
Times story said the convention would ``showcase women and people
from minority groups, faces that are not usually highlighted at
Republican conventions.'' Actually, the last convention, in 1996,
gave prominent roles to Susan Molinari, Colin Powell and Elizabeth
Dole. And GOP conventions have been showcasing women and minorities
since at least the time of Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans held their 1980 convention in Detroit, a heavily
unionized city with a majority of black residents. In 1984, women
received the two longest speakers' slots at the Dallas convention.
And in 1988, trying to close the gender gap and appear ``kinder and
gentler,'' Republicans gave over their podium to a parade of women
and members of minority groups. Even the 1992 convention, now often
characterized as a right-wing hate fest, featured an event called
``Black America Salutes the First Family'' and forced white male
luminaries like Alfonse D'Amato and Howard Baker to surrender their
credentials to make room for more female delegates.
</P>
<P>
   A convention is a television commercial, and the decision to
feature black or female faces has barely any deeper philosophical
import than the decision to feature balloons or confetti. In
February, when Bush needed the support of conservative whites in
South Carolina, he visited Bob Jones University and refused to
denounce the Confederate flag. This doesn't mean that Bush is a
secret racist; it simply reflected expediency in the choice of
racial symbolism at that moment. Now the moment and the symbolism
have changed.
</P>
<P>
   The best evidence that Bush has not fundamentally altered the
direction of his party is reaction of the GOP's right wing.
Conservatives are so vigilant against creeping moderation that they
have denounced Newt Gingrich and Trent Lott for ideological
deviation. Not only is this group not barking out any complaints
now, but it is nuzzled lovingly in Bush's lap. And no wonder. His
positions on economics and judicial appointments hew firmly to the
conservative line.
</P>
<P>
   Party diehards understand that it doesn't much matter if a blind
mountain climber gets to speak in prime time while Lott is shunted
to 11 a.m. Come next year, it is Lott, not the mountain climber or
the gospel singers, who will be helping to set the legislative
agenda for the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   (Jonathan Chait is an associate editor of The New Republic.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
