<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9768 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-CHENEY-RECORD-SI     08-01 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-CHENEY-RECORD-SIMPSON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY'S NOT EXTREME, HE'S FROM WYOMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Wednesday, Aug. 2, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By ALAN K. SIMPSON    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Since he became the Republican vice presidential
nominee, Dick Cheney has been depicted as some kind of right-wing
kook. His detractors have scoured his record in Congress and
plucked out a few votes with no reference to their context. They
toss out conclusions about him that have no relation to his
splendid reputation among his former colleagues, Republican and
Democrat alike. But if his detractors continue to focus on only a
few of his thousands of votes, let's at least be upfront with the
facts.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA SANCTIONS: Dick Cheney opposed sanctions against
South Africa under apartheid and voted against a resolution calling
for the release of Nelson Mandela. But the issues then were not so
simple.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, there was a consensus to end apartheid. The debate
was whether sanctions should be imposed or whether we should follow
President Ronald Reagan's policy of free trade and open dialogue.
Reagan believed the American companies could best help black South
Africans by giving them jobs. Sanctions, the thinking went, would
only hurt black South Africans, because these companies would have
to pull out.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the resolution to free Mandela contained language
requiring official recognition of the African National Congress as
the legitimate representative of the black majority. But the South
African government was then our ally in stemming communism in
Africa, particularly in Angola, and the leaders of the ANC included
admitted communists.
</P>
<P>
   When Dick Cheney cast his votes, neither he nor anyone else knew
when the Cold War would end. Nor could we know that sanctions would
ultimately help create a free South Africa. Members of the House
are issued voting cards, not crystal balls.
</P>
<P>
   EQUAL RIGHTS AMENDMENT: It is not easy being a minority member
of the House. The majority party can use procedures that deprive
the minority of offering amendments. That's what happened when
Democrats brought the equal rights amendment to the House for
consideration under ``Suspension of the Rules,'' which doesn't
allow debate or amendments _ even though this legislation would
have amended the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has always supported the equal rights amendment. He voted
no because he believed that a proposed amendment to the
Constitution should be subject to full debate. But this vote was
not about equal rights for women. This was about the Democrats'
hardball efforts to create an issue during a campaign year.
</P>
<P>
   HEAD START: If Dick Cheney were voting today on whether to
expand this program, or any other social program, he would first
ask whether it was worthwhile. If the answer was yes, the next
question would be, ``Can we afford it?'' The answer today, with the
surpluses piling up, is likely yes. But Cheney served in Congress
during the days of huge deficits. It's never easy for politicians
to say no to worthwhile programs, but if we hadn't had members of
Congress like him to cast these tough votes, we might not have the
luxury of surpluses we wallow in today.
</P>
<P>
   GUN CONTROL: In Wyoming, gun control means holding your rifle
steady. We have a different lifestyle; we learn to use firearms for
hunting or target practice responsibly at an early age. The way for
a guy to be ``outside the mainstream'' _ or out of office _ is to
vote for gun control. The last time I checked, members of Congress
are encouraged to represent their constituency. But things change,
and the Columbine shootings and other tragedies have haunted us
all. I personally know that Dick Cheney would almost surely support
tough laws to keep guns out of the hands of juveniles and
criminals. He would also support child safety locks and raising the
age of handgun possession to 21.
</P>
<P>
   THE ENVIRONMENT: Cheney is an avid outdoorsman, committed to
conservation and a clean environment. I remember his steady efforts
on behalf of an act that set aside thousands of acres of Wyoming
for special protection. No one fought harder for it than he did,
despite the powerful economic interests and many Republicans
fighting against the designation.
</P>
<P>
   To evaluate his record fairly, one must look at the 1980s, with
its deficits and Cold War antagonisms. And one must remember that
he represented a very conservative state, and ask whether these
votes are relevant to judging his qualifications. As vice
president, he would take a broader view than his role of
congressman from Wyoming required. After all, we know that as
defense secretary during the Gulf War, Cheney was calm and cool
under pressure _ thoughtful, competent and trustworthy. What he is
not is an extremist. Those who know him will tell you this,
including honest Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   (Alan K. Simpson, a Wyoming Republican, served in the Senate
from 1979 to 1997.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
