<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following financial
story for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, Aug. 2, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Stewart Slavin at the Daily News, (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   ACTORS-STRIKE (Burbank, Calif.) _ Talk about starving actors.
Five actors began a hunger strike in Burbank on Tuesday to draw
attention to the stalled talks between the advertising industry and
the unions that represent advertisement actors. By Jesse Hiestand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9770 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILMPRESERVATION-2ndT     08-01 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMPRESERVATION-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: restoration firms. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even worse has been the sheer abuse or careless cataloging of
many great film negatives. Consider 1954's ``Rear Window,'' whose
original negative was in tatters thanks to the churning out of 389
prints of the film. And ``Stagecoach,'' John Ford's cornerstone
western and collaboration with John Wayne, had to be repaired
without the benefit of its original negative as only a 16mm print
was thought to exist. Eventually a 35mm version was found, rumored
to belong to Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studios' record on preservation is unspeakable,'' says
Kevin Brownlow, director of London-based Photoplay Productions, one
of the world's pre-eminent restoration firms, ``Frankly, I think
that executives are much more interested in their lunch than in
looking after their pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that each studio doles out between $2 million
and $5 million per year to their preservation and restoration
programs. That seems a tad stingy when considering that for $50
million, roughly the average cost of a feature film, 30,000 reels
of silent-era film could be saved.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Columbia Pictures lacked a film-preservation
program. But thanks to its merger with high-definition TV-minded
Sony, Columbia created a whole department devoted to restoration.
Universal, MGM and Warner Bros. maintain their film libraries
collection with some care. However, The Walt Disney Company,
insiders say, seems to pay the greatest attention to preserving its
cache of classic animation. Witness ``Fantasia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People in these companies really treat films like selling
black rubber combs,'' Harris says. ``They aren't passionate about
film, so when it comes to restoration, they feel no one will care
if you start messing with the color of `Lawrence of Arabia.' Now
with that attitude, where does that leave America's art form?''
</P>
<P>
   In a gesture that amounts to the path of least resistance,
Hollywood's studios have allowed several outside organizations to
compensate for their lax preservation effort. Pitching in are the
National Endowment for the Arts, The Pew Charitable Trusts and The
Film Foundation, co-created by Martin Scorsese, George Lucas and
Steven Spielberg, among others. Many of the oldest, frailest films
are drawn from the extensive archives held at UCLA, the Library of
Congress (among its 120,000 film cans in its Ohio storage area is
``The Great Train Robbery''), New York's Museum of Modern Art, the
Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, and George Eastman
House.
</P>
<P>
   Where the main Hollywood studios have most clearly dropped the
ball is in their preservation of silent films. The main object of
the National Film Preservation Foundation's ``Saving the Silents''
effort, fueled by a $1 million federal support fund, is to
preserve, usually on a modern, 35mm master copy, some 67 shorts and
serials. In addition, the foundation has salvaged thousands of
minority-made films, avant-garde reels and other so-called
``orphans'' that lack real commercial viability.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, a $500,000 grant from the National Endowment
for the Arts has helped a fascinating selection of rare films
remain alive. They include ``Blacksmithing Scene,'' the nation's
first commercial film (made in 1893), several ``one-reelers'' from
Thomas Edison in his laboratory, and home movies from Ernest
Hemingway and Groucho Marx.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad truth is that there are very few marketplace
incentives to protect so many of these orphan films,'' says Annette
Melville, director of the National Film Preservation Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps shamed by these vigorous efforts at film preservation
outside the Hollywood studios, the moviemaking community has
invested the last decade in improving its halfhearted conservation
efforts. ``With the value of film having become more obvious in the
last 10 years, many of the studios are finally practicing what they
had only preached before,'' says Roger Mayer, president of Turner
Entertainment Co. and chairman of the National Film Preservation
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's creative and media elite have attached themselves to
idiosyncratic restoration projects. Scorsese took such a shine to
the 1965 Polish film ``The Saragossa Manuscript'' that he helped
defray the $36,000 cost of its renovation. And Ted Turner has taken
a passionate interest in a British restoration company's bid to
rescue a 1925 silent film version of ``Ben Hur.''
</P>
<P>
   When the major studios have launched themselves into the
preservation and the restoration game, it has produced very highly
publicized cosmetic surgeries on such marquee titles as
``Vertigo,'' ``Gone With the Wind,'' ``Casablanca,'' ``Lawrence of
Arabia'' and ``Citizen Kane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's certainly an improvement over the days when the only
ones in the community interested in preservation were just a few
archivists,'' says Arthur Hiller, former president of the Academy
of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   But the studios' critics still scoff at their attempts to buff
up only the best-known titles. ``What the studios do now is all
about public relations,'' says Brownlow. ``They will bring out the
obvious stuff like `Casablanca' and let the other stuff perish.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The ideal film preservation formula involves maintaining prints
at a steady temperature of 32 to 50 degrees, and 35 percent
humidity. Warner Bros. has six cold storage vaults (many of them
earthquake-proof) and has maintained films in old salt mines in
Kansas. Warner's separate areas contain a total of 650,000 video
and audio reels. Paramount has two storage plants including one
buried in a limestone mine. ``Everyone knows that the proper
storage for a huge film library is nowhere near the cost of even
the marketing campaign of one major film,'' admits Gray Ainsworth,
vice president of technical services at MGM.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9772 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILMPRESERVATION-3rdT     08-01 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMPRESERVATION-3rdTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: services at MGM. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The studios' better-late-than-never motivation for preservation
is the explosion of ancillary markets eager for the overhauled
classic. From television to video, cable networks (such as American
Movie Classics), pay-per-view, laserdisc, DVD and the Internet, the
number of new outlets for these musty favorites has grown
exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   The studios don't deny the new incentive. ``Quite frankly, not
only do we recognize the new need to sell into these new markets,
but DVD in particular sets a very high standard for quality so
everyone is having to clean up all the pops and crackles on their
material,'' says Grover Crisp, vice president for asset management
and film restoration at Sony Pictures Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not every aging film will qualify for a digital
afterlife. ``Films will fall through the cracks; do you really see
the studios spending $1.5 million to restore 1959's `Porgy and
Bess' or rather let it rot, losing those performances by Sidney
Poitier and Pearl Bailey?'' Harris says.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to restoration, the only certainty is how
time-consuming and costly it can be. A typical black-and-white film
can run between $20,000 to $50,000 to preserve and restore, while a
color film costs between $50,000 and $300,000. The rescue of
``Lawrence of Arabia'' ate up more than a year and cost $1 million.
That's a bargain compared with the $15 million for the re-release
of the original ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every restoration effort reveals either blatant film
neglect or the painstaking effort to revive the film. This year's
USA Film Festival in Dallas showed a fully restored version of
1967's ``In Cold Blood,'' whose original negative was torn in more
than 30 places. In the reconstruction of ``Spartacus,'' not only
were Kirk Douglas and Stanley Kubrick heavily involved, but the
film specialists took two years to comb through 1,600 cans of audio
and visual materials. And The American Film Institute in Los
Angeles recalls how it had to recover the missing 10-minute first
part of its ``Our Gang-Lil' Rascals'' film series through an 8.5mm
home movie in Australia and a film restoration expert in Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Now, digital technology is playing a key role in all of these
far-flung restoration tales. Digital scanning and adjusting is
helping erase the surface scratches that pock older prints in
addition to smoothing over the nagging pops and hisses from aging
sound tracks. MGM's restoration department used a digital comb to
remove the rain of green specks that had formed on Sidney Poitier's
face in part of ``In the Heat of the Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet some warn that digital's facility in erasing a film's
time-worn glitches can lead to enslavement to what might be the
accelerating obsolescence of the DVD player. ``It won't last
forever, and if ever there is a problem with a digital copy, there
might not be anything to fall back on,'' Bodde says. ``Putting a
film in digital form is akin to (having) a really good color laser
copy of the Mona Lisa.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday night, Hugh Hefner wanted to screen the Errol
Flynn classic ``Gentleman Jim'' with one of Katharine Hepburn and
Spencer Tracy's great collaborations, ``State of the Union.'' He
was finding it virtually impossible to track down clean, 35mm
versions of either film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because a film is regularly seen on television doesn't
mean that there is a theatrically viable, 35mm print available
anymore,'' Hefner says. ``This bothers me, because other than my
family, movies were the major influence on my life, setting the
dreams of my childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Hefner's concern is one of many familiar to the Hollywood's old
guard. But does it bother the new breed? Apparently yes, at least
according to the Directors Guild of America, whose preservation
committee is filled with such young-buck talent as directors M.
Night Shyamalan, Bill Duke and Steven Soderbergh. And a review of
the donor list of The Film Foundation reveals that such young
mega-stars as Leonardo DiCaprio and Winona Ryder have contributed
anywhere from $20,000 to $50,000 to the preservation effort.
</P>
<P>
   Ryder's generous donation explains why the actress recently
remarked that a perfect day for her would include her cellphone
suddenly ringing with Scorsese on the line: He ``calls me to tell
me that scientists have discovered an inexpensive way to restore
old movies.''
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew Marton is arts critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7679, or e-mail:
amarton(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
