<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-SOUTH-SWITCHERS-N     08-01 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-SOUTH-SWITCHERS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CONVERTS LEAVE THEIR YELLOW DOG DAYS BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., La.)   By CARL HULSE   
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Sen. Richard Shelby of Alabama is the co-chair of
his state's delegation to the Republican National Convention. Rep.
Billy Tauzin of Louisiana is among the GOP congressional elite on
hand. But not so many years ago, they wouldn't have been let
through the door here.
</P>
<P>
   They were Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   It is an oddity of modern Southern politics that many of the
die-hard, rock-solid conservatives who comprise the bulwark of the
GOP across Dixie got their political start in the opposing camp.
There were no Republicans in the Solid South, not many anyway, an
antipathy directly linked to the vestiges of the Civil War. People
interested in holding office or voting in primaries that were the
true elections had to call themselves Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP converts are quick to point out that though they
might have worn the Democratic label, they never shared the ideals
of what they saw as an increasingly liberal national Democratic
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never voted for a Democrat for president,'' boasted Shelby,
who conspicuously switched parties the day after Republicans seized
control of Congress in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one better illustrates how the Southern political
tide has shifted than Alabama GOP delegate George Wallace Jr., the
son of the fire-breathing governor and presidential candidate who
personified the Southern Democrat for many in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Elected twice statewide as a Democrat, the younger Wallace said
that in 1995 he broke the news to his ailing father that if the son
were to run for office again, it would be as a Republican. He said
his father had already shown his own sympathy for Republican causes
and candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made it clear publicly where he was,'' said Wallace, who
was elected to the state Public Service Commission shortly after
his father's death in 1998. ``He understood my change.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, in fact, credits his father with playing a major role
in shaping the current GOP philosophy of states' rights and a
reduced role of federal government, a view espoused by such
contemporary Southern political figures as Sen. Trent Lott of
Mississippi and Newt Gingrich of Georgia as well as Shelby and
Tauzin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was the architect of the modern conservative
movement,'' said Wallace. ``I think what he represented so well
when he ran for president across the country were Alabama values.''
</P>
<P>
   The torrent of party switching that occurred in the 1990s began
in the 1980s with a nudge from President Ronald Reagan, who was
known to be effective in persuading conservative Democrats that
they should make the jump to the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Democrats were easy targets, unhappy as they were with
a party they saw as falling under the control of labor, minorities
and other activist groups, the same interests that made Walter
Mondale the presidential nominee in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   One of those who took the plunge is delegate and veteran
Louisiana legislator John Hainkel of New Orleans, who recalls he
flew to Washington to switch parties in a high-profile ceremony
with Reagan and Vice President George Bush looking on approvingly.
Like many who left the Democrats, Hainkel said he didn't change _
the national Democratic agenda did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kept going to the left and I sort of stayed where I was,''
said Hainkel, the current state Senate president who noted that
when he joined the legislature in 1968 there was not a single
Republican in either the House or Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin switched in 1995, one of five conservative House
Democrats from the South to do so that year after Republicans
gained control. He had struggled with his allegiance since
President Clinton took office in 1993. Now he is line to be
chairman of the Commerce Committee, one of the top jobs in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt whatsoever he is truly Republican,'' said
state party leader Pat Brister.
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't just well-known delegates who made the switch.
Alabama GOP chairman Winton Blount estimates that about half of the
state's delegation has at some point has worked on behalf of
Democratic candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9774 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-LUCENT-CISCO-BOS &LR;      08-01 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-CISCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE WON'T BLOCK LUCENT WORKERS' DEFECTION TO CISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Cisco Systems won a round Tuesday in its nasty battle
with Lucent Technologies over Cisco's new optical plant in Salem,
N.H., with a federal judge declining to issue an injunction
blocking 10 former Lucent employees from moving to Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   US District Court judge Edward F. Harrington ruled that ``there
is no evidence'' that any of the 10 defectors from Lucent's big
plant in North Andover had disclosed ``any proprietary or
confidential information. . . . There is no evidence that
defendants have caused (Lucent) any actual harm.''
</P>
<P>
   In language that had Cisco executives privately gloating,
Harrington also said in his ruling that the technology Cisco will
manufacture at its new Salem plant ``is a much more highly
developed and complex product than the plaintiff's,'' suggesting
there were few valuable Lucent secrets to divulge anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco will use the new Salem plant to build dense wave division
multiplexing systems that put multiple data streams over a single
fiber line by transmitting in several colors of light. Much of the
Cisco technology came through an acquisition from Pirelli Optical
Systems.
</P>
<P>
   In what has become an increasingly common practice in the
bitterly competitive telecom sector, Lucent in June sued 10 former
employees who left its 6,000-person North Andover plant to work for
Cisco. Among them was 18-year Lucent veteran Daniel B. Tymann, who
is now plant manager for the Cisco optical equipment factory.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, the 10 employees, whose defense is being funded
by Cisco, charged Lucent with sex discrimination, ``abusive and
oppressive management tactics,'' and toleration of shoddy work to
speed sales. Lucent denied all these charges.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington's ruling only blocks Lucent from getting an immediate
order stopping the employees from working for Cisco but preserves
its right to pursue its suit against them.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said Lucent ``still has a viable cause of action
against the defendants'' if it can prove in a trial they are
revealing trade secrets or violating terms of their employment
contracts at Lucent. Harrington said he would entertain future
motions for injunctions from Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent spokesman John Skalko said the Murray Hill, N.J., company
was pleased that Harrington ``recognized our right to protect our
proprietary information. We're encouraged that our former employees
are clearly prohibited from disclosing Lucent trade secrets or
other proprietary information'' while the case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview, Tymann said he was relieved and happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our jobs and livelihood were at stake, and our integrity was
questioned and so was that of our peers,'' Tymann said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a message to people that you have a right to change
jobs and careers,'' Tymann said, but added that he had no comment
on whether he thinks other Lucent employees at its Merrimack Valley
site plan to jump over to Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, which has spent more than $8 billion buying local
start-ups in recent years, has faced challenges keeping top talent
from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco is renovating a former Digital Equipment Corp. factory in
Salem for use as a 2,500-person optical equipment plant that will
be one of its flagship properties in New England. It expects to
formally open the plant in October.
</P>
<P>
   With the market for fiber-optic telecommunications gear
exploding, Lucent, for years the dominant US telecom gear maker and
still the world's largest, has been in a dogfight with rivals such
as Cisco and Nortel Networks to maintain market leadership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
