<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9775 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BILLBOARD-COMPILATION     08-01 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLBOARD-COMPILATION02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's a first: Pop compilation tops the charts
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time in Billboard magazine history, a multi-artist
album that isn't a soundtrack made its debut at the top of the pop
charts this week, ``Now That's What I Call Music! 4.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a collection of hits, but not of the old K-Tel variety seen
on late-night TV. The 18-single compilation CD that dethroned
embattled rapper Eminem after an eight-week reign ironically
contains some of the recent singles of acts he most likes to
criticize _ boy band the Backstreet Boys' ``Larger Than Life,''
teen siren Britney Spears' ``(You Drive Me) Crazy'' and blonde
Britney-in-training Mandy Moore's ``Candy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Richter, manager of HMV Records in Lenox Square, said,
``from what I hear and what I see, this is something that's selling
on all of the racks'' _ both at record shops and at such
mass-market retailers as Target and Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now's'' appeal is obvious: It's pop radio without the
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But doesn't the 320,000 ``Now'' sold during its first week
detract from the sales of its artists' own CDs?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not, says Bob Mercer, senior vice president of UTV
Records, the label that released ``Now.'' UTV claims that more than
half of those who buy a ``Now'' album will go on to purchase an
album by one of the participating artists. The record labels
partnering on this project, Universal Music Group, the EMI Group,
Sony Music and Zomba, ``get a considerable amount of income as
indeed do the artists,'' Mercer says.
</P>
<P>
   Plus the labels get to introduce their artists to an audience
that may have bought ``Now'' because of another performer, Mercer
says.
</P>
<P>
   UTV is the arm of Universal Music Enterprises set up three years
ago to put out such TV-marketed compilations as ``Now,'' ``Pure
Funk'' and ``Jamming Grooves.''
</P>
<P>
   For the ``Now'' compilation, ``we are heavily focused toward
MTV, and particularly Nickelodeon, because it is incredibly
influential,'' Mercer says. ``And `Now' records tend to skew
young.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-year-old U.S. version of the ``Now'' series is an
offshoot of the ``Now'' brand that started 15 years ago overseas,
and has sold more than 55 million copies across the world. It's so
popular, in fact, that compilations were given their own chart in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   No chance of that here, says Billboard's Geoff Mayfield,
director of charts. ``We like to see, on one chart, how everything
out there in the marketplace fares,'' he says. ``And surprise,
surprise _ a collection of hit songs sells like a hit album.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Mayfield was surprised by ``Now's' chart-topping
appearance. But his 12-year-old wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on ``Now That's What I Call Music! 4
'': www.nowmusic4.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
