<HEADER>
A9776 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-AMERICANHIGH02-COX     08-01 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AMERICANHIGH02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Documentary a serious study of kids
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Right away, ``American High'' slaps down its manifesto, courtesy
of a kid named Morgan in a Korn T-shirt: ``These are the years
where you're supposed to go (bleeping) wild, blame it all on your
parents, not have to suffer consequences, have unprotected sex, do
drugs, drink alcohol, watch porno, porno, porno, go pick fights, be
reckless. ... And instead, you're stuck at home, doing homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are sentiments guaranteed to give serious palpitations to
any parents of teenagers watching this new Fox documentary series,
not that many parents are likely to be watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``American High'' is of, for and, more or less, by today's
adolescents in all their troubled, contradictory glory.
</P>
<P>
   Although some viewers will want to lump it in with the summer's
Voyeur-Vision trend, ``AH'' is really just a straight,
old-fashioned documentary; with no tribal councils or votes of
expulsion. The filmmakers hung out with 14 students last school
year at mostly white, mostly affluent Highland Park High School in
suburban Chicago and gave the kids camcorders to keep their own
video diaries.
</P>
<P>
   Fox is running half-hour episodes for 13 weeks, with the first
two back-to-back tonight.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Morgan, who has more interesting layers to him
than that opening talking-id barrage would indicate, there's Robby
and Sarah, so hopelessly in goo-goo love that it's almost painful
to watch; Brad, an out gay kid whose parents are textbook-accepting
of who he is; Kaytee, a budding musician-songwriter who may not be
threatening Ani di Franco yet, but whose wicked perceptiveness
makes her a joy to listen to; and Kiwi, a football player who seems
oblivious that his best platonic friend, the Latina Anna, may have
a secret crush on him.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the ones we meet in the first two episodes; presumably
the remainder of the 14 will follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``AH'' is wise in not making us keep track of too many people at
first, so that despite having to wade through some standard
adolescent ``Who am I?'' navel-gazing, we get to know the kids at
something more than a superficial level.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments here that can just break your heart, whatever
your age. ``It's very lonely at my house,'' Sarah says, and with no
further explanation, she conjures up a world of hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, who has attention deficit disorder, visits his doctor
and blinks vacantly as he listens to a discussion about changing
his Ritalin dosage.
</P>
<P>
   Will these kids become Warholian celebs, a la the casts of
``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother''? It's doubtful, but these days,
anything is possible. They themselves obviously aren't sure what
they want. They only know they want it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``American High''
</P>
<P>
   9, 9:30 tonight
</P>
<P>
   on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
