<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9778 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-SPEECHWORKS-IPO-BOS &LR;      08-01 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEECHWORKS-IPO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEECHWORKS' IPO BUCKS MARKET, GAINS 184 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SpeechWorks International Tuesday continued a trend of
telecommunications firms bucking the choppy market for
technology-sector initial public offerings. Its shares nearly
tripled on their opening day of trading to give the company a Wall
Street valuation of over $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The 250-person Boston-based company makes speech-recognition
systems that allow people to use their voice _ instead of telephone
touch-tone buttons _ to get information and conduct business over
the phone. Tuesday, its shares soared from a $20 offering price to
as high as $67.25 before closing at $56.75, for a 184 percent
first-day gain.
</P>
<P>
   While Wall Street has had mixed reactions to this summer's crop
of technology IPOs, the booming Greater Boston telecom sector has
fared well, with SpeechWorks following Sonus Networks of Westford
and Avici Systems of North Billerica in big first-day ``pops'' for
their IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   As Internet-connected wireless phones have boomed in popularity
over the last six months, so have complaints about the hassle of
using tiny phone screens and keypads to read information or
transact requests.
</P>
<P>
   SpeechWorks systems, already in use at three airlines, Amtrak
and the E(star)Trade brokerage house, are seen as a potentially
popular way for cell phone users to get information from the Net by
using their voices instead of fumbling around a telephone keypad.
</P>
<P>
   For example, guided by prerecorded voice prompts on the other
end, people can use SpeechWorks products to execute commands such
as ``buy 100 shares of Gillette'' or get answers to questions such
as ``What is the weather forecast for Boston?'' or ``When does
Flight 404 arrive in Atlanta?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet over the telephone is a hot space,'' Michael Dubrow,
a senior analyst at Jacob Asset Management, told Bloomberg Business
News. ``A lot of people see (the phone) as the ultimate Internet
appliance.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, AT&AMP;T agreed to take an undisclosed stake in SpeechWorks
as part of a deal giving the Boston company access to a trove of
speech recognition technology developed at AT&AMP;T's labs. SpeechWorks
has also formed an alliance with America OnLine.
</P>
<P>
   The offering of a 16 percent stake in the company gave
SpeechWorks $95 million for growth and product development.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the huge value attached to SpeechWorks, it last year
posted sales of only $14 million and a net loss of $15.4 million,
with both numbers about triple what they were in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The company also faces intense competition from IBM, Lucent
Technologies and Microsoft as well as local speech-recognition
giant Lernout &AMP; Hauspie, whose North American offices are in
Burlington.
</P>
<P>
   However, SpeechWorks has earned considerable praise from
industry analysts for developing friendly, efficient voice prompts
to speed people through information requests and transactions.
Earlier this summer, it offered to share its software with other
companies to speed the growth of Internet ``voice portals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9780 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-AIMEE&AMP;JAGUAR-$ADV06-2     08-01 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIMEE&AMP;JAGUAR-$ADV06-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HIGH-PITCHED DANCE OF LOVE AND DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 6) 
 By NANCY RAMSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Felice Schragenheim was a high-spirited, educated, sensual,
witty and wily young woman, whose dangerous misfortune was to have
been born Jewish in pre-World War II Germany. During the war she
lived in Berlin under an assumed name and worked at a Nazi
newspaper, feeding information to the underground resistance. She
was involved with a circle of sophisticated Jewish lesbians whose
dancing-on-the-volcano lives flouted convention, and sometimes
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly Wust, the young wife of an SS soldier, was the mother of
four boys, and for her effort in producing such strapping young
specimens of Aryan youth, she was awarded the Nazi's Maternal Cross
in bronze. Yet, seeking excitement, she had an affair with an
officer while her husband was fighting on the Russian front. She
had reportedly once said that she could ``smell Jews,'' a comment
that, when it reached Felice via a mutual friend, challenged the
playful Felice to arrange a meeting with such a person.
</P>
<P>
   When they were introduced in late 1942, Lilly's fascination
turned to attraction and fear and then to an all-consuming, erotic
love. It wasn't until well into their relationship that Felice told
Lilly she was Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aimee and Jaguar,'' which opens August 11 and is based on the
true story of Felice Schragenheim (nicknamed Jaguar; played by
Maria Schrader) and Lilly Wust (nicknamed Aimee; played by Juliane
Koehler), is a film that the director Max Faerberboeck initially
resisted making. ``I had a sack full of reasons not to do it,'' he
said about his first feature, speaking by telephone from his home
in Hamburg, Germany. Creating solid female characters was familiar
ground for Faerberboeck; ``Bella Block,'' a television show he
wrote and directed, was about an intelligent, stubborn policewoman
and won the German equivalent of an Emmy. And he knew that the
well-publicized story of Aimee and Jaguar _ a best-selling book of
the same title, by Erica Fischer, was published in Germany in 1994
_ would surely be made into a movie. But he had written another
love story he wanted to film, that of two women from highly
bourgeois Hamburg families who admit their love for each other
while on holiday in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognized `Aimee and Jaguar' was a movie of love and
passion,'' he said. ``If I love it, I thought, I will do it
strongly, and it won't be commercial enough. There would be that
element of German romanticism, with the characters going into deep
sentiment, high feelings and destruction. The only one who had the
courage to play all those cards was Fassbinder.'' But as he was on
his way to Berlin to meet with a producer and turn down the
project, Beethoven's Ninth Symphony, conducted by Wilhelm
Furtwaengler, came over the car radio. ``Furtwaengler went for a
very strong emotional dynamic,'' Faerberboeck said. ``You have very
destructive moments and, within half a second, the most tender
violin you can hear. Filmmaking is a question of rhythm, and as I
listened to the symphony's clash of feelings, so many images came
into my mind. The film chose me.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-pitched life of wartime Berlin provided the perfect
backdrop to the remarkable story of Felice and Lilly. ``People who
had lost family one day would dance until morning the next,''
Faerberboeck said. ``They lived for the moment. I used Cuban music,
the rumba, which has the feeling of those days. There were lots of
sexual relationships, people betrayed each other much more than the
Germans like to admit. And the Nazis hated Berlin women; they
didn't want to work in the factories, and they loved pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's elements of tension are found less in the air raids
than in small, everyday moments, and Faerberboeck uses long,
lingering close-ups of his characters to bring the war home. In a
Berlin hotel one day, some young German soldiers send a round of
drinks to Felice and her friends; the soldiers may be unaware the
women are Jewish, or perhaps they are just too young and libidinous
to care. Later in the film, this sinister undercurrent is magnified
when the women, to make money, pose for semi-nude pictures to be
sent to soldiers on the front. Leaving the photographer's studio,
one of them is stopped by two officials, who demand to see her
papers. The camera alternates between the tense, brief
interrogation to close-ups of her friends, walking briskly, as they
grow increasingly terrified: Should they keep walking? Pretend they
don't know her? Seconds count. Look back? Go back?
</P>
<P>
   ``Aimee and Jaguar'' opened the 1999 Berlin Film Festival.
Schrader (``The Giraffe,'' ``Nobody Loves Me'') and Koehler (a
theater actress making her film debut) shared the Silver Bear award
for best actress. Alan Riding wrote in The New York Times that ``a
German film has for the first time dared use the Nazi regime simply
as the context for a human drama.'' The Times of London noted that
it ``seems likely to follow Steven Spielberg's epic `Schindler's
List' as a cinematic example of an individual German's struggle to
defy the inhumanity of the Hitler era against all the odds.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's theatrical release in Germany was a commercial
success; the critical reception was mixed. Peter Koerte, the film
critic for the daily Frankfurter Rundschau, said recently that he
found ``Aimee and Jaguar'' too arty, too perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my review I wrote about Rubens' skies, a Rembrandt
chiaroscuro and a glimpse of Caravaggio,'' he added. ``But what
makes it different is the whole angle, which hasn't existed in
German cinema. Films on that period were usually based on
resistance people or on German soldiers as innocent victims of a
big propaganda machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabine Hake, a professor of German literature and film at the
University of Pittsburgh, said that ``Aimee and Jaguar'' is part of
a ``new phase'' in German cinema brought on by both the unification
of Germany and the fact that the last Holocaust survivors are
dying. ``It's an effort at the normalization of the German past.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Films about the Nazi period ``used to be very moral and very
austere,'' Hake continued. ``Now there will be more individual
stories. But is it one of the historical periods that you can set a
love story to, like the Civil War or World War I? The risk is that
you trivialize things.''
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the ``minefields'' he was encountering, Faerberboeck
considered various approaches. A boulevard comedy a la Ernst
Lubitsch was one, no doubt drawing on the success of Roberto
Benigni's ``Life Is Beautiful,'' with Felice's circle of friends
descending upon the Wust household, ``all those girls coming
through different doors into the apartment with this kind of free
living; it was a Nazi house, after all,'' Faerberboeck said. ``But
that would have been a superficial trick. You would have lost that
inner tension of the story, the passion and eroticism. I was more
interested to get the feeling of those two women. For each it was
love for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before she met Lilly, Felice was living like a pirate,'' he
continued. ``She had a warm heart, but she was conquering life. She
wanted every day to steal life away from the Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   Schrader said: ``When Felice first meets Lilly, she uses her as
a hideaway. She's also trying herself out, playing games, to see if
she can get hurt. One of the beautiful things about `Aimee and
Jaguar' is that when it starts out, it's mixing up conventional
roles of perpetrators and victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Lilly, Koehler said, ``was afraid that Felice and her friends
were more intelligent, more sophisticated. Lilly was, in a way,
simple compared to Felice, but that's what Felice loved about
her.'' It was Felice who called herself Jaguar and gave Lilly the
pet name Aimee.
</P>
<P>
   Faerberboeck and his co-writer, Rona Munro, extended this nuance
and complexity to their supporting characters as well. For the
newspaper editor, Felice's boss (Peter Weck), Faerberboeck, who was
born in 1950, looked to his father's generation. ``Today it's too
easy to say it would have been impossible to go along with what was
happening,'' he said. ``This editor was a very human, highly
educated man. He's a man you could sit down and talk with today.
But he was 100 percent Nazi. He wrote the most perverted things in
his newspaper. It is too easy to create Nazi characters with
stupid, violent faces, or have them wearing a mask.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 21, 1944, Lilly and Felice spent an idyllic afternoon
along Berlin's Havel River swimming, picnicking and taking
photographs and arrived home to discover Nazi officials in their
apartment. They were questioned incessantly, and Felice was taken
away. ``By that point, Felice had fallen in love deeply,''
Faerberboeck said. ``And she got into terrible danger, because she
stayed with Lilly. If she hadn't fallen in love, maybe she would
have been more attentive to danger, maybe she would have escaped
Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Felice was transported to the Theresienstadt concentration camp,
and Lilly actually journeyed to the camp to try to see her, an act
that may have put Felice's life in further danger. ``Lilly was
completely out of her mind,'' Faerberboeck said. ``And this scene
at the camp, of course, is a scene you normally would like to see.
But what I did instead was to film the scene when Lilly returns and
tells their friend Ilse what she did. I wanted the horror on Ilse's
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Felice died toward war's end, probably on one of the death
marches. Lilly Wust, 86, is still alive in Berlin; in 1981 she was
awarded the Federal Service Cross, one of West Germany's highest
service medals awarded to civilians, for hiding Felice and three
other Jewish women. She remarried briefly after the war, to support
her children, but Felice remains her one true love. In June Wust
came to New York for the film's screening at the New York Lesbian
and Gay Film Festival; she finds its ``essence very truthful'' and,
in conversation, readily transports herself back to her days with
the ``radiant and elegant'' Felice.
</P>
<P>
   Faerberboeck did shoot a scene with a pile of corpses, Felice's
body among them. But he chose not to use it. ``The atmosphere of
Felice being taken away is much stronger than showing her as a
corpse,'' he said. ``The movie, until that moment, is told the
other way around, it's not showing the primary images.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have broken the law of that narration, it would have
been too obviously dramatic. This is a film that lives in the
faces.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
