<HEADER>
A9783 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-SHOSHONE-CLAIMS-NEWHO     08-01 1487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOSHONE-CLAIMS-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBE'S HOPES FOR HOMELAND STIR RESIDENTS' FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, Aug. 1, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With two photos, of Rod Ariwite (NNS2) and Robert Cope
(NNS3). 
 By PETER SLEETH  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALMON, Idaho _ Rod Ariwite was the last of the Shoshones to
graduate from the high school here as a ``Salmon Savage.'' It was a
place where he excelled at playing football, while shrugging at the
school mascot in the war bonnet.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Salmon Savages remain, while Ariwite, 45, and the
rest of the Lemhi Shoshone tribe are gone. They live on a
reservation in the bleak desert country of southern Idaho, 201
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was here in this scenic mountain valley that the legend
of the Shoshone girl Sacagawea came to be. It was here in August
1805 that the fate of the Lewis and Clark expedition was decided by
Sacagawea's brother in one of the most startling tales of the
expedition.
</P>
<P>
   And it is here, today, that Ariwite is working as a Shoshone
Moses, trying to bring his people home in what many view as a
quixotic attempt at restoring a tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend millions of dollars on wolf, grizzly and fish
recovery. What are we doing for the Lemhis?'' said Ariwite, an
education specialist with the U.S. Bureau of Indian Affairs. ``What
I am asking for is something that is morally and ethically right.''
</P>
<P>
   Ariwite said he hopes the upcoming bicentennial of the Lewis and
Clark expedition will be a springboard to a return of the Lemhis'
reservation, one they lost in 1907.
</P>
<P>
   Ariwite said he will appeal this year to President Clinton for
restoration of the Lemhis as a tribe with treaty rights, while
plying other federal agencies for land grants and money to purchase
private land.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is, few residents seem to want the Lemhis and
their proposed reservation.
</P>
<P>
   The Lemhis are not a federally recognized tribe; instead, they
are considered part of the Shoshone-Bannock tribe on the Fort Hall
Reservation, located 243 miles east of Boise. Although they once
had a 100-square-mile reservation of their own in the Lemhi River
Valley, and de facto if not legal tribal status, today they are
recognized only by themselves as a unique people.
</P>
<P>
   And many would like to keep it that way.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government is slow to recognize tribes in a process
that can take decades, and many people in Salmon River country fear
a return of the Lemhi Shoshones could threaten everything from
water rights to employment in a valley where both water and jobs
are scarce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody cares if they want to come up and settle, but where are
you going to put them?'' asked Robert Cope, a veterinarian and
candidate for the Lemhi County Commission. ``What isn't already
cultivated isn't any good.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Shoshone lash out at that attitude, saying the white
residents of the valley want only the legends of Sacagawea and
their Shoshone ancestors, not real human beings. A proposed $12
million Sacagawea Interpretive &AMP; Educational Center in Salmon --
meant to draw tourists during the bicentennial -- is a focal point
for their anger.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewis and Clark Bicentennial runs from 2003 to 2006.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want her as a museum, as an icon to stabilize their
economy, but they don't want her people back,'' said Leo T.
Ariwite, 41, a cousin of Rod Ariwite.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, said Tom Chaffin, a Lemhi County commissioner. No
proposal has even been put before the county government for it to
consider. He said the Lemhi would be welcome back in the valley,
away from the Fort Hall Indian Reservation. But valley residents
fear establishment of a casino or depletion of natural resources,
from water to fish, if they came back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't doubt they have been neglected or abused down there.
My heart goes out to them,'' he said. But, ``personally, I don't
want to see a reservation.''
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, the mountains that ring this remote ranching
community served as a fortress for the Lemhi Shoshone.
</P>
<P>
   Sacagawea captured the American imagination largely for her role
in the valley where her people lived. Although she is often
portrayed as a guide for the expedition, in truth she knew almost
none of the country they crossed. But she knew the land near the
Salmon River and, more importantly, the people.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1805, the Corps of Discovery was badly behind schedule
in crossing the mountains of what is now Idaho. They had no horses,
no guide and no clear idea of how to reach the Pacific Ocean.
Meriwether Lewis had hoped to cross the Continental Divide into
this valley and find a clear path down the Columbia River.
</P>
<P>
   What he found were seemingly endless rows of snowcapped
mountains blocking his path.
</P>
<P>
   Sacagawea had been in the area before. Kidnapped by a raiding
party of plains Indians as a teen-ager, she became the property of
French Canadian fur trader Touissant Charbonneau after he won her
in a wager.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the expedition came upon her, she was Charbonneau's
second wife. Lewis and Clark hired Charbonneau as an interpreter.
They saw her as a bonus -- she could speak Shoshone and knew the
uncharted lands of present-day western Montana and eastern Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   A fairy tale is more believable than what happened next.
</P>
<P>
   After encountering a band of some 60 Shoshone warriors near
present-day Salmon, a war party that could easily have wiped them
out, Lewis persuaded them to come back over Lemhi Pass and meet
with his party to trade for horses. With great suspicion, Chief
Cameahwait agreed. Then, in a magical episode, Sacagawea recognized
the chief as her long-lost brother.
</P>
<P>
   The expedition got its horses, a guide over the Bitterroot
Mountains and a life-saving chance to make the Pacific Ocean before
winter.
</P>
<P>
   The Lemhi lived largely undisturbed in the valley until 1855,
when Mormon missionaries established a post near Tendoy, Idaho.
Within three years, the tribe sent the Mormons scurrying back to
Utah, but it was a short-lived reprieve. Settlers led by miners and
ranchers began pouring into the valley.
</P>
<P>
   By 1875, President Ulysses S. Grant had allotted a
100-square-mile reservation for the Lemhi Shoshone, said Orlan
Svingen, an associate professor of history at Washington State
University.
</P>
<P>
   But the reservation, like the rest of their territorial claims,
would not last. Almost from the outset, the government and settlers
began to whittle away at Lemhi territory, Svingen said.
</P>
<P>
   Svingen is writing a book about the Lemhi and helping them seek
federal restoration as a tribe.
</P>
<P>
   The settlers ultimately succeeded in 1907, with what Svingen
calls the ``Lemhi Trail of Tears,'' and had them relocated to Fort
Hall. There, they moved in with tribes of Shoshone-Bannock.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   It was a move disparaged among the Lemhi as much for the arrival
at Fort Hall as the leaving of the Salmon River country, Ariwite
said. The Lemhi have been ``hostages'' of the Sho-Bans, he said,
the foster children on a reservation where they never felt they
belonged. The Shoshone-Bannock tribe is composed of bands the Lemhi
often fought.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that way then. Why in the hell would it be any
different now?'' Ariwite said.
</P>
<P>
   Leroy Boyer, Shoshone-Bannock Tribal Council chief, did not
return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   The Lemhis believe that they are losing their identity with each
passing year, as their culture, their language and their history
fade as the elders die.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Ariwite and some tribal elders are trying to use the momentum of
the bicentennial to gain tribal status and land to return north. No
one knows the exact number of Lemhi Shoshones, but about 400 to 500
exist, according to tribal members. About one-half of those might
want to return to the Lemhi Valley, Ariwite said.
</P>
<P>
   Their hopes hinge on public sentiment and the celebration of a
conquering nation that displaced the Lemhis from their native
homeland. The Salmon School District has removed the Native
American in a war bonnet as its mascot, although school officials
will continue with the name Savages.
</P>
<P>
   That, Ariwite said, is not a major issue to him. The land and a
return home is the issue.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw what happened 200 years ago. The Corps of Discovery
brought back one of our stolen daughters,'' Ariwite said. ``Now,
200 years later, with the bicentennial of the Corps of Discovery,
maybe the Corps of Discovery can bring us home.''
</P>
<P>
   (Peter Sleeth is a staff writer with The Oregonian of Portland,
Ore.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
