<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9785 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-GOP-IMMIGRATION-ART-1     08-01 1418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-IMMIGRATION-ART-1,100&AMP;ADD-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTER LINE MAY HELP LURE LATINOS, BUT HOW MANY? 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, Aug. 1, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With photo of protester posing as Lady Liberty (NNS4). 
 By JONATHAN TILOVE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Bearing signs reading, ``Stop the Racism'' and
``Stop the Greed,'' a small band of immigration restrictionists
called Project USA marched Tuesday on a Republican National
Convention they believe has caved on immigration policy in a craven
bid for business money and Hispanic votes.
</P>
<P>
   Marching the prescribed protest route past boarded-up homes to
the huge, empty park that has been designated for ``free speech''
here, they were out of earshot and eyeshot of everybody but
themselves. At that, the protest was the closest anyone at this
convention is likely to come to hearing a discouraging word about
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   In four years, Republicans have been transformed from a party
that fretted about immigration to one that celebrates it. To
Hispanic Republicans, that transformation under the leadership of
Texas Gov. George W. Bush enables them to finally competctively against Democratic domination of the growing Latino
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredibly helpful,'' said California Assemblyman Rod
Pacheco, a leading figure in California Republican politics. ``This
is really different.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal wing of the Republican Party has always
supported high levels of immigration as good for business. But
increasingly, consideration of immigration policy has been
intertwined with the politics of America's changing political
demography.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high, and, some observers warn, a gamble the
Republicans in the long term cannot afford to lose. If Democrats
continue to win Latino votes at anything like their current rate,
Republican support for high immigration levels may ultimately prove
their party's undoing.
</P>
<P>
   It is a point that has been made by unabashed immigration
restrictionists like Patrick J. Buchanan, who may bring the issue
of immigration to the fall campaign as the Reform Party nominee.
When he was still a Republican, Buchanan warned that absent a
moratorium on immigration, Republicans were facing a ``demographic
death sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Manza, a political sociologist at Northwestern University,
said Buchanan has a point. ``How long do you allow immigration to
continue at very high rates at the same time that these new voters
mostly vote Democratic?'' asked Manza.
</P>
<P>
   Latinos are now 12 percent of the population and it is estimated
they will be close to 15 percent of the population by 2010,
surpassing the African-American population. With the exception of
the large Cuban-American population in Florida, which tends to vote
Republican, most Hispanics lean heavily Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma deepens, Manza noted, because if the Republicans
were to reverse course, they will also reverse whatever headway
they make with Latinos who are a growing electoral force in
important states like California, Texas, Florida, New York and New
Jersey. ``If you try to stop immigration,'' Manza said, ``it will
generate a powerful backlash.''
</P>
<P>
   That has certainly been proven out in recent history. When Pete
Wilson ran for California governor in 1990, Pacheco said, he won
nearly half the Latino vote. But by the time Wilson got through
supporting Proposition 187, the 1994 California ballot initiative
to deny public benefits to illegal immigrants and their children,
Latino support for Republican candidates in California had been
decimated.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Republicans who took over Congress in 1994
were voting to exclude legal immigrants who were not yet citizens
from some categories of public assistance. The result was a rush
among Hispanics to become citizens, and vote Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Republican nominee Bob Dole, running on a platform that
backed Proposition 187 and the elimination of birthright
citizenship for children of those in the country illegally, got
only about 15 percent of the Latino vote in California, Pacheco
said.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Right now, according to Pacheco, internal GOP polls in
California indicate Bush support is around 25 percent among
California Latinos, and only a few points behind Gore altogether.
If he can get 30 percent of the Hispanic vote, Pacheco said, Bush
will win California.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Guerra, a San Antonio public relations specialist who is
doing work for the Republican National Committee, said that any
time a Texas Republican wins 30 percent of the Latino vote, victory
is certain. If Republicans are not able to do the same in
California, ``California will be lost forever,'' said Guerra.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was crushed among Hispanics by Democrat Ann Richards
when he first ran, won up to half that vote in his landslide
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is, in many ways, the candidate from central GOP casting
when it comes to appealing to Latino voters. He speaks Spanish. As
governor of Texas, he was the un-Wilson, welcoming immigration and
praising immigrants. And his brother is married to a woman from
Mexico, and their son George P. Bush, who has made an ad for his
uncle, has Ricky Martin quality charisma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexican blood runs in the Bush family,'' said Rosario Marin, a
member of the city council in Huntington Park, Calif. ``Blood,''
Marin said emphatically. ``Blood is stronger than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Marin said it is ``a humbling experience'' to be a delegate to
this convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an immigrant,'' said Marin. ``I was born in Mexico City.
Now, I'm one of 2,000 delegates who will nominate the next
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Marin used to work for Pete Wilson, her last job being his
liaison to the Latino community. ``I earned my money,'' she said,
noting that she did not agree with her boss on 187.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is much better,'' she said of Bush. She believes that
Hispanic voters are ready to discard their Democratic habits for
him, just as they did in electing her in a city that is 99 percent
Latino.
</P>
<P>
   Manza, however, believes there has been ``an insane misreading
of Bush's appeal to Hispanics.'' He may have won nearly half the
Hispanic vote in Texas when he ran for re-election, but that was
against a weak, underfunded opponent whom Bush trounced among white
voters. There remained, Manza said, ``a huge gap'' in his appeal to
Hispanic and white voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' new approach to immigration comes at a time
when polls indicate immigration is still an issue on which
Americans are very divided. And yet, it has dropped off the
political map, thanks in large measure to a broad alliance between
those on the civil rights left and the leadership of the Hispanic
and Asian communities, which are heavily immigrant, and the
business community, which wants both skilled workers for the
high-tech industry and unskilled workers for those jobs that, as it
is commonly put, ``Americans won't do.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   One political contest where it has emerged as an issue is in
Michigan. There the Federation for American Immigration Reform has
been running ads attacking Spencer Abraham, the architect of
Republican immigration policy in the Senate. But Abraham, who is in
a tough re-election battle, dismisses the ads as the work of ``hate
groups.''
</P>
<P>
   ProjectUSA, which has raised immigration restricton billboards
in various states, has also been attacked as racist, even though
its founder, Craig Nelsen of Queens, N.Y., said he is only
motivated by concerns about population growth and immigration is
the single biggest contributor.
</P>
<P>
   The recent history of the immigration debate has been that it is
almost impossible to talk about in non-racial terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's a huge insult to those citizens of Latino and
Asian ancestry who feel themselves capable of hyphen-less voting,
who feel themselves as good and loyal Americans rather than a
narrow ethnic group,'' said Nelson. ``It is nakedly racist in
itself that race somehow determines our policy ... . It's
particularly dangerous if immigraton policy becomes a tussle
between the races.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
