<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9791 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-LINKTEL0802-COX     08-01 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-LINKTEL0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta firm sees potential in e-mail access similar to pay
phones
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - With e-mail increasingly vital, with the nation ever
more mobile, maybe the pay phone of the future is an Internet
connection.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, LinkTel Communications of Atlanta is banking
on the idea that people on the move will happily drop a few dollars
into a machine that gives them access to e-mail in places they
would otherwise be wasting time.
</P>
<P>
   Under the name Pay2Linc, the company has installed about 100
devices in Georgia, Florida and Texas, including 40 in metro
Atlanta. LinkTel offers a service that lets people access the Net
and get e-mail while they are otherwise stuck: Their car is being
serviced, they are in a hotel or waiting for a table at a
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``These really work when you've got somebody captive,'' said
Chief Executive Marty Whirl. ``The machine will be your best
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, he is encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   The average machine does about $450 to $600 per month, and the
average user spends seven minutes on Pay2Linc, he said. The company
also receives revenue from billboard ads bought on the service. ``I
am looking to put up 5,000 of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Using Whirl's math, that would produce a business of more than
$30 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   But will it fly? The main purpose of the machines is to provide
access to e-mail accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Pay2Linc adds a wrinkle that the company hopes will help it
catch on in tourist areas: A user can take a photo on the spot and
send it via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Among Pay2Linc spots in Atlanta are the Ramada Inn in Conyers,
the Windy Hill Car Spa in Marietta and the Best Western hotel at
Hartsfield airport. In most cases, the Pay2Linc machine is owned by
LinkTel and the owners of the premises receive a portion of the
take _ up to 50 percent, Whirl said.
</P>
<P>
   Pay2Linc charges $1 for three minutes. For $5, the user gets 25
minutes, with the clock in all cases starting only when the Net
connection is made, Whirl said.
</P>
<P>
   Whirl, whose background is as a stockbroker, said the company
started out installing and managing pay phones. LinkTel now has
2,500 pay phones _ a device that is increasingly lonely in affluent
areas where people carry wireless phones. While seeing the Pay2Link
concept as parallel to pay phones, the target market is very
different, he said. ``The people who use pay phones are
predominantly in urban areas or very rural areas.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's a different market from the Palm Pilot, too, he said.
It's cheaper, for one thing. And _ whatever the Palm Pilot's charms
_ it is not as simple to use, Whirl insists. As for laptop
connections _ wireless and otherwise _ Whirl said Pay2Linc is much
quicker. ``I'll have you on the Internet before you could unpack
the laptop.''
</P>
<P>
   Pay2Linc is not alone in the market. Among competitors is Darwin
Networks, which makes what it calls ``public Internet kiosks.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
