<HEADER>
A9797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-VOICES-NYT &LR;      08-01 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-VOICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CONVENTION NOT EDGE-OF-THE-SEAT FARE, TV VIEWERS SAY _
THANKFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT LEBANON, Pa. _ Some faithful Republican homes here glow
with the blue light of faithful Republican television-watching
these convention nights. But no one can say that even the most
stalwart of stalwarts are sitting on the edges of their leather
couches.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect scripting, it seems, comes with a price: lukewarm
attention, and minimal effect.
</P>
<P>
   Four sets of neighbors on White Oak Circle, a sloping cul-de-sac
in this gracious, Republican-leaning suburb of Pittsburgh, shared
their reactions as the convention unfolded and largely concurred
that for them, it held little excitement, less suspense and an
infinitesimal chance of changing their minds about anything.
</P>
<P>
   Some viewers described, rather, a sense of watching as a
precaution, on the off chance that something could muddle George W.
Bush's momentum. It would have been more riveting if the choice of
running mate had remained unclear, they said, or differing opinions
on platform issues were expressed. But no such luck; so somehow,
even on the 48- and 50-inch TV sets that fill whole den walls here,
the convention seems a small event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm watching to make sure he doesn't mess up,'' Dr. Dick
Lewis, a surgeon, said of Bush. ``His single most outstanding
characteristic is that he's got the ability to beat Gore. That's
more important than this platform or anything else as far as I'm
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a bit, Lewis said, like a golf tournament ending on
Sunday: ``You can't win the tournament on Saturday, but you can
lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the street, Diane Goldschmidt, community service
coordinator at Mt. Lebanon's award-winning high school, said she
had explained to her 18-year-old son that ``if some major trauma
occurred, if Bush had a heart attack or we found out he's a spy, if
something occurred that would prevent him being a candidate, this
is when it would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Short of that, she said, she has read enough about Bush in
recent years that ``I know my opinion won't be altered.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Jack, a financial consultant, noted that this time
around, he has no real questions lingering in his mind about
candidates or issues, which was by no means the case when Bush's
father ran against Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   And in general, he said, the convention ``is like the State of
the Union address: It's a feel-good thing. Could we do without it?
Sure we could. It's a chance to get together and toot your horn;
it's a media show and I don't think it's ever going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Such awareness of the convention's limitations did not prevent
the White Oak Circle viewers from enjoying Monday night's top
speeches, though, and forming a few new impressions.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush garnered high marks: ``She's much better than I
expected her to be, she's very natural,'' said Jeff Lammert, vice
president of a company that makes steel-cutting shears.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Teri, responded particularly when Mrs. Bush talked
about returning respect to the presidency: ``That's a powerful
comment,'' she said. ``That brings up a lot of memories of what
happened. I think we have to make the presidency respectable again,
and I think he can do it and she can help.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Lewis, a nurse and mother of three, said she felt as if
she could relate to Laura Bush: ``She is foremost a mom before
anything else,'' she said, ``and in the baby boom generation, I
think that a lot of people can relate to her _ at least, I can. She
mentioned the empty nest syndrome she's facing this fall, which is
something we're facing; and she seemed so down to earth, I loved
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Colin Powell's speech brought praise as well, although
here, the convention organizers' strategy of scheduling the
highest-profile speeches after 10 p.m., when there would be network
air-time, seemed to backfire a bit.
</P>
<P>
   At the Lammerts' house, some visiting friends listened to the
beginning of the speech, then jumped off into a long, loud tangent
about testing teachers for competency; at the Lewises, Charlene had
to run out for car-pool duty; and Lea Smith, a lawyer who was
watching at home with her husband, Temp, also a lawyer, dropped off
to sleep at about 10:30, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had watched much of the evening, she said, and felt no
shift in her opinions: ``Every time they talked about streamlining
federal government, reducing bureaucracy, I felt energized,'' she
said, ``and then they talked about his education initiative and
requiring reading literacy at third grade level by third grade, and
I thought, `That's all well and good, but that seems like as much
or more federal involvement.'''
</P>
<P>
   Smith was also struck, she said, by how all the earlier speakers
followed the same pattern: They would talk about what they had
managed to achieve because America was a land of opportunity,
``then education, then what good Bush was going to do and then God
Bless America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little comical,'' she said. ``It made it seem less of
a usual convention and more scripted, more planned and executed
according to a common plan. But I guess when I look at the whole _
the running mate already named, the platform already being passed _
what else is there to do?''
</P>
<P>
   She and most of her neighbors said they would continue watching
the convention in dribs and drabs, and certainly try to tune in
when Bush spoke. But with little expectation of bombshells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine anything that George Bush would say that would
make me vote for his opponent,'' Temp Smith said. Rather, he said,
he and Lea, who are active in local Republican politics, are
waiting to see whether they get excited enough about him to put any
effort into his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said nostalgically that he missed ``the goofy bowler hats
they used to wear, and noisemaker horns.'' Somehow, he said, ``it
doesn't seem like there's quite the party atmosphere you used to
get,'' at least, to viewers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
