<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9798 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-SHEEP-RULING-BOS &LR;      08-01 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEEP-RULING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEEP HERD SHOULD BE DESTROYED, JUDGE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAPHAEL LEWIS AND STACEY CHASE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRATTLEBORO, Vt. _ In a decision likely to damage the nation's
small but growing sheep-farming industry, a federal judge Tuesday
ruled that 355 imported sheep in Vermont should be killed because
they may have contracted a version of mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
   Judge J. Garvan Murtha's ruling, which supported an earlier
order by the US Department of Agriculture, came as fears increase
worldwide that the brain-wasting ailment responsible for more than
50 human deaths in Europe is no longer confined to cows.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of the two flocks have until Monday to appeal the
decision, but attorneys for both said Tuesday no decision has been
made yet on whether they will do that. The Lydonville owner of a
third flock voluntarily sold his 21 imported sheep to the USDA last
month.
</P>
<P>
   On July 14 Secretary of Agriculture Dan Glickman ordered the
sheep execution after eight animals tested positive for TSE, or
transmissable spongiform encephalopathy, confirming the
government's worst fears about the animals. Glickman contended that
the sheep _ most of which are East Friesians imported from Belgium
_ were likely exposed to feed contaminated with the always-fatal
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Mad cow disease caused a panic in the British beef market a few
years ago and prompted strict import bans on this side of the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court's decision was in the best interests of the
country's human and animal health,'' said Patrick Collins, a USDA
spokesman. ``But I think we have to keep in mind that these three
flocks have shown a unique set of signs that there's a potential
problem there. The real message is: We're taking science-based,
prudent action to control a potential threat before it has the
chance to evlove into something much larger.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners of the two flocks, philanthropist Houghton Freeman of
Stowe and farmers Linda and Larry Faillace of East Warren, appealed
the USDA's order to Murtha, saying the government's tests were
flawed and inconclusive at best. They also asserted that the USDA
was merely working to protect domestic farmers, whose sheep produce
about one-tenth the milk of the Belgian sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, as supporters of the farmers continued their
``Save the Sheep'' campaign _ which portayed government as a
shadowy band of thugs protecting domestic trade interests and not
public health, the two sides squared-off in Murtha's courtroom.
Meanwhile, friends and supporters made pilgrimages to the Faillace
farm in the unfortunately named Mad River valley, making a point of
eating the family's cheese products and petting the long-earred
grazers in the pasture.
</P>
<P>
   Well before Murtha's ruling, though, the USDA's order had begun
to hurt operations that produce or sell sheep's milk and cheese _
in Vermont and beyond. Whether or not Murtha ruled in favor of the
USDA, some said, the damage was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a no-win situation for us,'' said Ruth Flore,
president of the American Cheese Society, a trade group with about
500 members nationwide, only a fraction of whom produce sheep's
milk products. `` We're only talking about two farms, and I know
several of our farms around the country have been called and asked
questions. ... Right now, we're already seeing a drop-off. People
are concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   David Major, who produces cheese made from sheep's milk on a
farm in Westminster West in southern Vermont, said half of his
buyers have canceled their orders. Orders for his specialty cheese,
marketed under the name Vermont Shepherd, have dropped off so
sharply that he said he might have to cut production or sell some
of his flock if the anxiety surrounding the industry doesn't die
down within three or four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be eating lots of cheese,'' Major said.
</P>
<P>
   Most sheep farmers say they have always kept their flocks under
strict watch to protect them from any kind of contamination.
Despite that, many consumers are starting to see all Vermont sheep
goods as tainted.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Squier, owner of Sage Sheep Farm in Stowe, said
destroying the sheep on the two farms won't solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that would still leave a lot of questions in people's
minds,'' said Squier, who sells meat and wool. ``I don't see why
they can't be retested so that everybody can see whether they have
the disease or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, nearly 67,000 sheep farms raise about 7.2 million
sheep, according to Peter Orwick, executive director of the
American Sheep Industry Association _ but he added that only a
small fraction raise the animals for milk production.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: Most breeds of American sheep produce about 100
gallons of milk a year, making them relatively unprofitable by
comparison with dairy cows.
</P>
<P>
   The sheep imported by Freeman and the Faillaces are capable of
producing more than 1,000 gallons annually, making them
particularly valuable for breeding rights. The sheep came into the
United States during a brief period in the spring of 1996, when the
importation of foreign sheep was legal, but their owners have been
barred from breeding their flocks since then. Such importations
have since been made illegal, thanks in large part to the risks of
infecting the nation's cows and sheep with mad cow disease and
scrapie, another form of TSE that entered the nation's sheep
population in 1946, from imported animals.
</P>
<P>
   Orwick has applauded the judgment of the USDA from the outset,
saying the sheep posed an unnecessary risk to the health and
reputation of the rest of America's sheep farms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those importers in Vermont are portrayed as farmers just
trying to make it, but let's face it, they brought them to the US
to establish a profit-making breeding operation, to sell those
animals nationwide,'' Orwick said. ``The USDA, they don't just pick
on different flocks for the fun of it. ... It seems reasonable to
us that you make sure it does not spread.''
</P>
<P>
   Reasonable or not, fears that mad cow disease is now running
rampant in the brains of sheep have begun to gain a larger audience
of late, prompting speculation in Europe that a repeat of the mad
cow panic may be at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Times of London reported that Nobel Prize-winning
scientist Stanley Prusiner has found preliminary evidence that BSE
is endemic in Britain's sheep population.
</P>
<P>
   And this week the Belgian newspaper De Morgen reported that
European Union scientists are looking into the possibility that a
mad cow disease epidemic may afflict the continent's sheep flocks
as well. One scientist told Reuters the situation was ``a timebomb
that continues to tick.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, no proof has emerged that sheep are in fact capable of
contracting the disease, let alone if humans could be affected by
eating sheep meat or milk products.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, shortly after the USDA ordered the Vermont sheep
killed, the Vermont Department of Health issued an alert for
consumers to avoid eating any cheese produced by the Freeman and
Faillace flocks. The department did not issue a recall of the
cheese, however, and one spokesperson said no such recall was in
the offing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of Vermont simply issued a recommendation in a tone
of a precaution for people,'' spokesperson Nancy Erickson said.
``There is no state or national recall for those products, and I
don't foresee a change in that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
