<HEADLINE>
LOST FILMS: HOLES IN HOLLYWOOD'S HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Accompanies FILM PRESERVATION)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to the combined efforts of film scholars, acclaimed
directors, private film buffs and professional archivists, great
films from John Ford's ``Stagecoach'' to George Lucas' ``Star
Wars'' have been lovingly restored. Sadly, the same cannot be said
for a handful of historically significant movies that have been
irretrievably lost. They include:
</P>
<P>
   ``That Royle Girl'' _ a 1926 silent film starring W.C. Fields
and directed by the great D.W. Griffith
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rogue Song'' _ a 1930 work directed by Lionel Barrymore
and starring Laurel &AMP; Hardy
</P>
<P>
   ``Camille'' _ a 1927 version featuring a star turn by Norma
Talmadge
</P>
<P>
   ``Remodeling Her Husband'' _ a 1920 work, the only film ever
directed by Lillian Gish
</P>
<P>
   ``Convention City'' _ a 1933 slapsticky comedy featuring the
brassy Joan Blondell
</P>
<P>
   ``London After Midnight'' _ a 1927 film featuring one of the
era's distinctive stars, Lon Chaney
</P>
<P>
   ``The Magnificent Ambersons'' _ the original version of Orson
Welles' 1942 masterpiece
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Red Riding Hood'' _ a 1922 cartoon by Walt Disney, made
before he attained his fame and fortune in Hollywood
</P>
<P>
   _ Andrew Marton
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
