r l BC-HUMOR-MEDICINE-TEX     08-01 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMOR-MEDICINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL COMICS PRESCRIBE LAUGHTER TO BUOY PATIENTS' SPIRITS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CAROLYN POIROT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Quackers, a hand puppet in a nurse's uniform
and a long curly blond wig, sneaks up on Horace Owen, 86, and
smacks him with a big duck kiss. Owen's face lights up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you can tell everybody a blond nurse crawled into bed
with you and gave you kisses,'' says Nurse Ducky, the mischiefmaker
who speaks for Quackers.
</P>
<P>
   Owen's smile turns to laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts to laugh, but they keep me medicated to contain my
pain so I can enjoy the show,'' he says, adding that he has been in
Harris Methodist Southwest hospital in Fort Worth ``eight weeks too
long,'' while undergoing three surgeries for an intestinal
blockage.
</P>
<P>
   Hazel White, 93, was in the hospital with complications from
surgery for a broken hip when her room was invaded by Nurse Ducky
and Quackers; Dr. Cat Scan, who checks for funny bones; Ima Green
Frog, who's ready to make anything that's ``bugging'' you disappear
with her magic scarf; Smiley Bubbles, who started carrying a
battery-powered bubble gun because her large nose interfered with
her bubble-blowing; and other clowns.
</P>
<P>
   White's beautiful laugh filled the hospital room and shook her
whole body when they sang ``Happy Ha Ha to You,'' then announced
that they had been practicing real hard and could now sing it
backward just for her. They turned their backs to her and repeated
the song.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was wonderful of those ladies, and they all work here,''
White says as the caravan moves on to the next room where they sing
the same song ``under water,'' with flower vases, pitchers and
drinking glasses held over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Nurse Ducky is Marcy Graves, and she says that clowning around
is her calling from God. It just happens to complement her real job
as director of cardiopulmonary and extended-care services at Harris
Methodist Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Every Wednesday afternoon, she slips on her ``old-fashioned''
white nurse's cap and uniform (trimmed in red hearts, rainbows and
rickrack), packs her ``Mirth Aid Kit,'' glues on a pair of huge
fake eyelashes, adds a red clown's nose, paints on her pouty lips
and grabs up Quackers to make hospital rounds with her crew of
merrymakers _ the HaHaS.
</P>
<P>
   Short for Health and Healing at Southwest, the HaHaS are
respiratory therapists, nurses, technicians and other hospital
staffers who are convinced that sometimes laughter is the best
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one of my eyelashes catches a wind, I might just fly off,''
Graves says while putting on her makeup. She admits that she once
attached the lashes with her nose glue and couldn't open her eyes
until she ``melted'' the lashes with glue remover.
</P>
<P>
   Often a doctor or hospital administrator will drop by the
pulmonary department while the HaHaS are getting ready and say,
``I've got an hour, do you have an extra nose?''
</P>
<P>
   The HaHaS are always happy to expand the troupe that Graves
organized in February 1999, soon after seeing the movie ``Patch
Adams.''
</P>
<P>
   Graves couldn't believe it, though, when Dr. Patch Adams called
her and invited her to join his clown tour of China.
</P>
<P>
   She and the legendary physician have a lot in common when it
comes to using humor in healing. She knew all about him from the
movie starring Robin Williams, but how did Adams know about her?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was my husband, Mark,'' she says. ``I said, `OK,
honey, but I don't have time to talk with you right now. I'm in the
middle of some paperwork on a patient.'''
</P>
<P>
   Adams asked if she had caller ID, which she didn't, then
requested her fax number and told her to go check out the fax
machine as soon as she had a minute to spare.
</P>
<P>
   The message she received was printed on stationery from Adams'
Gesundheit Institute, inviting Graves to join the doctor and 30
other medical clowns for a 12-day trip to China, beginning Sept.
17. They will be spreading laughter, love and good health through
hospitals, orphanages, schools and retirement centers. She has
accepted the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he learned about Graves by reading the abstract of a
paper Graves presented in full Nurse Ducky costume at a recent
meeting of the American Association for Respiratory Care in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The paper, ``Is Laughter the Best Medicine?,'' reports on a
study examining the immune response of patients with pneumonia to
therapeutic humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called him back, and he said, `I'd love it if you would come
along with us to China.' I was blubbering so bad I could hardly
talk. All I could think was, `Oh my God, this is so cool,' ''
Graves says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always believed that since I'm the only theater/pre-med
major to ever come out of the University of North Texas, this is
probably my calling from God.''
</P>
<P>
   She has been clowning around at Harris Fort Worth and Harris
Southwest for 20 years. ``I got the idea for the HaHaS and talked
to people in administration at the hospital. They supported the
idea as long as it would not cost the hospital any money,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Graves set up protocols that include stopping at the nursing
station on each floor that is visited and checking to see if there
are any patients who should not be disturbed. The HaHaS also knock
at each door and ask permission to enter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We assume everybody will want to see us, but we check to be
sure,'' Graves says. ``Sometimes women in labor don't respond well,
and people on ventilators we leave alone.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Wednesday afternoon, they also avoided the emergency
room. A doctor told the HaHaS it was already a circus in there.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on medical issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7687, or e-mail:
cpoirot(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
