<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON WEDNESDAY, CHENEY GETS CHANCE TO SAY WHO HE REALLY IS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BOB RAY SANDERS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ During the first two nights of the 37th
Republican National Convention, two retired generals _ both heroes
of Operation Desert Storm _ sang the praises of the vice
presidential pick and former defense secretary, Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night Cheney gets a chance to toot his own horn, and
more than likely he will try to smooth out some of the sour notes
produced by his very conservative voting record when he served in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. Colin Powell, whose mission on Monday night
included reaching out to minority voters on behalf of candidate
George W. Bush and the GOP, chided his fellow Republicans for not
always embodying the spirit of the ``party of Lincoln.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell warned that Republicans can't just talk about inclusion
and diversity, especially only at election time; they must show
they mean it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be every day,'' he said. ``It must be for real.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Cheney's speech Wednesday night, and his appearances
over the next three months as the party's vice presidential
nominee, must tell us who he really is, and what he really thinks.
</P>
<P>
   Is he a hard-nosed right-wing businessman who doesn't care much
about equal rights, the environment, the education of poor children
or rising oil prices? Or is he an astute public servant who will
not be bullied into supporting flawed ideas or legislation?
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who already have launched a series of television ads
targeting Cheney's voting record, want us to believe the former.
Republicans would have us believe the latter.
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Cheney is not a great speaker, but great
oratory is not what is needed or expected here. He must give a
speech that is convincing, and one that he can live with once it
comes under attack during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Just after his congressional voting record came under attack,
the presumptive VP candidate refused to run away from it. He did
try to explain some of those votes, noting that, once any vote was
put into context, even critics could see there was more to his
though processes than simply being against the Head Start program,
the Department of Education, the school lunch program, the
environment or the release of Nelson Mandela from a South African
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on TV talk shows last weekend, Cheney indicated that
he might vote differently today on some of those issues of two
decades ago because some circumstances have changed.
</P>
<P>
   But he's got to be careful when he talks about changing his
votes or his mind. That's what the Republicans accuse Vice
President Al Gore of doing too much.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Republican ticket's significant bump in the polls
since Cheney's selection as Bush's running mate, Democrats still
believe they can make the voting record of the vice presidential
nominee an issue in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans will have to keep reminding themselves, and their
nominees, what Powell told them Monday night: You can't just talk
it, you must demonstrate these principles of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Republicans have put plenty of ethnic minorities,
women and an openly gay congressman on the platform this week,
small things suggest there is still exclusion in the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   In his long, sometimes scolding benediction Monday night, a son
of famed evangelist Billy Graham ended the closing prayer in ``the
name of your son, Jesus.'' Afterward, I watched a delegate wearing
a yarmulke as he left the hall, and wondered if he really felt
included.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ray Sanders is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7775, or e-mail:
bobray(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
