<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9811 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-GEORGEP02-COX     08-01 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GEORGEP02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'P' USES LATIN SIZZLE TO HEAT UP BUSH'S CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    By BRIAN E. CROWLEY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The ``little brown one'' has become a hunk. A
real hunk. The guy who has ``it,'' whatever ``it'' is. No less an
authority than People magazine _ the folks who know all about
``it'' _ named George P. Bush fourth in its list of America's 100
most eligible bachelors.
</P>
<P>
   Behind George Clooney, Derek Jeter and Matt Damon.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, there's a Bush with sizzle, and no one is more
astonished by the attention than the 24-year Mexican-American who
is being called the Ricky Martin of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   He's so hot that the Philadelphia Daily News is running a ``hunk
watch'' column this week giving George's adoring fans daily tidbits
about the strikingly handsome son of Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida and
his wife, Columba.
</P>
<P>
   He's so hot that he has been picked to address the Republican
National Convention here Thursday, shortly before his uncle accepts
the party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   At this moment, though, coming in a side door of the Loew's
Hotel in downtown Philadelphia, the soft-spoken former high school
teacher is feeling nothing like a hunk. Exhausted with the
attention and the demands on his time, George P. _ or just P., as
his family and friends sometimes call him _ would like nothing more
than a little time to himself.
</P>
<P>
   But he is on a mission. His uncle is running for president and
long before People discovered him, George was quietly working last
year in New Hampshire stuffing envelopes and helping put up yard
signs. He also spoke to high school students, trying to excite them
about politics.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign moved him to California after the New Hampshire
primary, and it was there that George P. became a star.
</P>
<P>
   Watching him speak to Mexican-Americans, a key voting group in
that important state, his uncle's aides were astounded by how much
Latinos loved the young man. ``People would come up to him with
tears in their eyes and tell him that someday he will be the first
Mexican-American president,'' said a Bush adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Serious, athletic and intensely proud of his Mexican heritage,
George Prescott Bush, grandson of a former president, thinks of
himself as ``someone of color.'' While his father's side of the
family is blue-blooded Yankee transplanted to Texas and Florida,
his mother was born and raised in Mexico and frequently visits
friends and relatives there. George P., who is fluent in Spanish.
grew up in Miami while his father was building a business and
political career.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, George, his sister, Noele, and brother, Jeb, got
unwelcome national attention when their grandfather, then the vice
president, introduced the grandkids to President Reagan as ``the
little brown ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people were shocked by the statement, but the family knew
it was a loving remark. George P. is especially close to his
grandfather. He has spent summers with him, and between fishing and
palling around, his grandfather taught him the family's code of
conduct: Don't show off. Work hard. Stay close to friends and
family.
</P>
<P>
   While being the grandson and son of politically successful
people has its own rewards and difficulties, George P. has not been
able to escape the prejudice that comes from being a ``brown one.''
</P>
<P>
   There are times, he says, when he goes into stores and ``the
attendant comes out from behind the counter and follows me
around.'' And he has gotten stares, not always friendly, in some
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   He's been called a ``tar baby'' and a ``wetback.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a bicultural experience and I'm very proud of
being a Mexican-American,'' he said. ``Our society makes
distinctions based on outward appearances. There are perceptions
made about people based on what they look like and how they
dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Without getting specific, he acknowledges that the Republican
Party still has a way to go before it will feel like a party that
welcomes everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my uncle is going a long way to show people that this
is party of inclusion,'' he said. ``I don't agree with everything
that the Republican Party has ever done, but I see a lot of
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   George P. lives in California and travels wherever his uncle's
campaign sends him. When the campaign is over, he is off to law
school at the University of Texas. After that, he wants to be
involved in politics, but he's not sure whether that will
ultimately mean becoming a candidate himself.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb, the proud dad, beams when talking about his son. He
compares his son's experience working for the presidential campaign
as similar to his own experience giving speeches as a young man for
his father's presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while you lose the fear of humiliation. You realize
that, yes, I can get up before a large crowd and give a speech
without humiliating myself,'' Jeb Bush said. ``I can see the joy he
gets from being involved in a process that we all hope will make
people's lives better.''
</P>
<P>
   The comparisons stop at ``hunk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not even close,'' Jeb laughs loudly. ``He's a lot
handsomer than I was, and I was already married.''
</P>
<P>
   With his family and friends constantly tormenting George P.
about his newly found hunkdom, dad is not worried about his son
taking himself too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can keep him under control,'' he laughs. ``Besides,
when he goes to law school he's going to hit the wall with
studying.''
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with George P. who hopes that once the campaign is
over and he's in law school the intense interest in his every move
will quiet down.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, that doesn't seem likely.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Crowley's e-mail address is
brian(underscore)crowley(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
