<HEADLINE>
MILLIONS CLICK AWAY FROM GOP FESTIVITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (p and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though the Republican National Convention has been tailored
for television, viewers are so unimpressed that they tuned out by
the millions Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, a certain dropoff was inevitable this year because
one of the three leading broadcast networks, NBC, chose not to
carry the first night of the GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   But this was supposed to be the year when the all-news cable
networks _ CNN, Fox News Channel, and MSNBC _ stepped into the
broadcast breach and played the convention-coverage role the old
Big Three _ NBC, ABC, and CBS _ are no longer willing to play. Yet
the three cable channels drew a combined audience Monday that was
less than half the 6 million viewers NBC did in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the prime-time audience in 1996 for ABC, CBS, NBC, PBS
and CNN was around 20 million viewers. On Monday, the combined
audience in prime-time was just over 16 million for the networks
that aired any coverage at all: ABC (which devoted just an hour),
CBS (whose coverage was limited to a half-hour portion of its
newsmagazine), PBS, CNN, Fox News and MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, meanwhile, viewers voted thunderously with their
clickers: When ``Monday Night Football'' ended on WCVB-TV (Channel
5) and ABC's convention coverage began, two-thirds of the audience,
or 200,000 households, either changed the channel or turned off
their TVs.
</P>
<P>
   Commentators have noted the absence of drama at the Republican
convention, with the nominee and his running mate already known and
intraparty squabbling kept under wraps. Even the much-anticipated
speeches Monday night by retired General Colin Powell and Laura
Bush, wife of GOP candidate George W. Bush, couldn't pull in
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, to judge by the ratings for Monday night, viewers have
not yet made the transition from broadcast to cable for the
quadrennial display of political pageantry.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the combined audience for ABC, CBS and NBC on the first
night of the GOP convention was just under 17 million viewers. On
Monday, ABC was the only broadcast network to devote a full hour to
coverage, drawing 5.9 million viewers for the speeches by Powell
and Mrs. Bush that began at 10 p.m. That was a slight increase for
ABC from 1996, even though the network's ratings were actually down
a bit (the TV audience on which ratings are based is larger than it
was four years ago).
</P>
<P>
   CBS limited its convention coverage Monday to a portion of of
its newsmagazine ``48 Hours'': The program drew 6.3 million
viewers, an increase from four years ago. But, in the head-to-head
competition at 10 p.m., the decisive victor was NBC with a rerun of
a drama called ``Third Watch,'' which pulled in 10 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, over on the all-news cable networks, CNN drew 1.2
million viewers Monday, enough to win the cable contest, but down
from 1.3 million four years ago. Partly, that was due to inroads
made by newcomers Fox News (676,000 viewers) and MSNBC (516,000).
</P>
<P>
   The Public Broadcasting Service Tuesday was reveling in the fact
that its coverage Monday night drew more viewers than all three
all-news cable networks combined. But even PBS's ratings were down
slightly from four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   So where did all the viewers go? Perhaps yet another number
offers a clue: In 1995, the average American home had 41 channels
to choose from; by this year, that number had climbed to 62. Or
viewers may have chosen to take their convention coverage with a
dash of satire, as on Comedy Central's ``The Daily Show,'' which
drew 480,000 viewers Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-area viewers proved far more interested in the
Patriots-49ers matchup on ``Monday Night Football'' (and the debut
of comedian-turned-analyst Dennis Miller) than the GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   More than 331,000 households were tuned in to Channel 5 for the
last 15 minutes of the football broadcast, even though the Patriots
had the game well in hand. But when convention coverage began at 10
p.m., Channel 5's audience dropped to barely 130,000 households.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
