<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHILE-PINOCHET-NYT &LR;      08-01 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-PINOCHET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET REPORTEDLY STRIPPED OF IMMUNITY IN SECRET COURT VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ The Chilean Supreme Court reportedly voted in
secret on Tuesday to strip Gen. Augusto Pinochet of his senatorial
immunity, according to local radio and Web site accounts. The
decision would remove the last legal obstacle to a full-scale
criminal investigation of the former dictator and would permit his
trial on charges of kidnapping, murder and torture.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the court, Hernan Alvarez, said the justices
would release their opinion formally sometime next week. ``We are
not going to make any statements,'' said Alvarez, after the 20
justices consulted for four hours on Tuesday. ``The Supreme Court
has instructed me merely to say an agreement was reached.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither he nor any other court or government official
disputed the reports, all attributed to anonymous sources close to
the Supreme Court and the presidential palace, and all widely
disseminated among Chileans.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, reported as 11-9, had been expected after the court's
11-9 rejection last week of a defense motion to proceed with
medical tests of the former dictator before ruling on his immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very content,'' said Juan Bustos, a lawyer for human
rights victims involved in the case against Pinochet. ``The report
surging through the courthouse is that we have won and General
Pinochet no longer has immunity from prosecution.'' There were no
public reactions from Pinochet's lawyers or family.
</P>
<P>
   With the decision, the Supreme Court has apparently upheld a
ruling made in May by the Chilean Court of Appeals, which was also
revealed to many of the same news organizations more than a week
before it became official. Observers have theorized that the courts
and government are using the technique to try to soften reactions
and control the size of demonstrations supporting and opposing
Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers arguing the case against Pinochet maintained that there
was enough evidence linking him to disappearances and other crimes
that he should be stripped of his senatorial immunity. Never
elected to the Senate, Pinochet took his life-time seat in 1998
under a constitutional provision written during his 17-year
dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Pinochet gathered momentum here after he was
arrested in London in 1998 on a Spanish warrant for many serious
rights violations. He was freed for health reasons four months ago
and allowed to return to Chile, but his standing in society and
even among the military leaders and right-wing parties has
suffered.
</P>
<P>
   During the proceedings, no evidence ever linked the general
definitively to any single crime. But prosecutors are hoping that
his deteriorating legal status will encourage several retired
officers who are already imprisoned to testify that the former
dictator was aware of their crimes or helped cover them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the beginning of the legal process and there will
need to be a long investigation to gather proof,'' said Ricardo
Israel, a political scientist at the University of Chile. ``For a
conviction, some eyewitness or document has to come forward,
otherwise the evidence is all circumstantial.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel and many other experts say Pinochet, who is 84 and
suffers a variety of health problems, will probably die before he
can be convicted. But for many critics of his regime, the fact that
he could face justice in Chilean courts at all is a giant step
toward a full civilian-based democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Sebastian Brett, the Human Rights Watch representative in Chile,
said the court's stripping of Pinochet's immunity would signify
``the most important decision in Chilean judicial history.'' He
added, ``It would show that dictators are not above the law in
their country.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Juan Guzman, who is prosecuting the Pinochet case, is now
expected to force the general to answer a long series of questions
meant to link him to a case involving 19 people who disappeared
soon after the 1973 coup that brought him to power. The 19 are
believed to have been executed on the orders of top Pinochet aides.
</P>
<P>
   The general's lawyers say he is not guilty in the executions and
disappearances of more than 3,000 people. But during the Supreme
Court hearings last month they argued that he was not healthy
enough to stand trial because he was unable to direct his lawyers
adequately.
</P>
<P>
   However, they said any tests of the former ruler for mental
illness would be humiliating and unacceptable. That claim will
probably set up the next legal test, since under Chilean law all
criminal defendants over 70 must receive a medical examination
before trial, and mental illness may prevent legal proceedings to
go forward.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's legal maneuverings appear designed to broaden
defendants' due-process protections to include physical illnesses
as well as mental health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Despite earlier rumblings from senior military officers, the
armed forces have remained silent on the Pinochet case since the
Court of Appeals ruling in May. Demonstrations that were fierce
after his arrest two years ago in London have gradually subsided.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
