<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-MAIN (Philadelphia) _ Republicans gathering in
Philadelphia focus on foreign policy and national security in a
evening headlined by former prisoner of war Sen. John McCain of
Arizona. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-NATIONAL-SECURITY (Philadelphia) _ Republicans devote the
second evening of their convention to drawing sharp distinctions
between their party and the Democrats on national security and
foreign policy. Scheduled speakers include Sen. John McCain of
Arizona; retired Army Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf, commander of
allied forces in the Persian Gulf War; 1996 GOP presidential
nominee Bob Dole; and Condoleeza Rice, a senior adviser to Texas
Gov. George W. Bush. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-GAYS (Philadelphia) _ If it weren't for the fact that
he's an openly gay Republican, Rep. Jim Kolbe of Arizona would be
giving just another forgettable speech on international trade
tonight. But the fact that he's speaking at all at this convention
reflects the divisions within the GOP on gay rights and other
controversial social issues. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-McCAIN (Philadelphia) _ George W Bush's vanquished foe, Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., takes the stage to talk about military
readiness instead of his favorite issue, campaign finance reform.
BY GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-UNORTHODOX (Philadelphia) _ So far, the Republicans really
have deviated from the party line, especially with Colin Powell's
support for affirmative action and with the convention's broader
focus on women and minorities. More than one person on the
convention floor has remarked that it sounds more like a Democratic
convention than a Republican convention. By R.G. RATCLIFFE and CLAY
ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOD (Philadelphia)_ A look at how religious conservatives
are reacting to many Republican leaders' willingness to accept gays
and lesbians in the party. By ALAN BERNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-JOE-GUERRA (Philadelphia) _ Joe A. Guerra, 66, who operates
a gas station in Laredo, Texas, will lead the Republican National
Convention delegates in reciting the Pledge of Allegiance Wednesday
night. The story of how he got from Laredo to Philadelphia started
with family cookouts on the Fourth of July. By SUSANNA McBEE.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-BUSH (Charleston, W. Va.) _ Expressing a fervent commitment
to veterans and to ``rebuilding national defense,'' Republican
George W. Bush seeks to stage a raid for votes in the Democrats'
craggy bastion of West Virginia. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-RULING-PARTY (Medellin de Bravo, Mexico) _ A month after
losing the presidential election, the elder statesmen of Mexico's
recently defeated governing party are struggling to find a way to
win back power. But judging from the mood of voters in Mexico's
towns and cities, the Institutional Revolutionary Party has a long
way to go. By DUDLEY ALTHAUS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-MEANS-COLUMN (Philadelphia) _ Only rarely does a public
figure come along with great stature and popularity and no ambition
to become president. In Gen. Colin Powell the country has such an
admirable personage. His speech before the Republican convention _
introduced by no less than Gov. George W. Bush himself _ was a
warm-up for a new role as secretary of state, a job he does want.
And he demonstrated the great power of words of wisdom. By MARIANNE
MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-HINES-COLUMN (Philadelphia) _ There are faint early notes of
disharmony between George W. Bush's camp and the party that can be
seen at the convention if one looks carefully. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-ELY-COLUMN (Philadelphia) _ Why party platforms mean so
little. By JANE ELY.
</P>
