<SLUG> BC-CVN-KENNEDY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP STAGING THE WORLD'S FIRST 4-DAY-LONG HALFTIME SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BUD KENNEDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Republicans aren't throwing a convention.
</P>
<P>
   They're throwing a Super Bowl halftime show.
</P>
<P>
   From Monday's gospel choir songfest to Wednesday's Brooks and
Dunn country hoedown, the Republican Party's national convention is
more of a spectacle than a campaign kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   All it needs is the Kilgore Rangerettes.
</P>
<P>
   This show even has two quarterbacks. U.S. Rep. J.C. Watts, who
played QB for Oklahoma, may never live down singing ``My Girl''
with the Temptations at a party Sunday night. Steve Young, formerly
the leader of the San Francisco 49ers, will lead the prayer
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, Americans were urged to play strong safety and put
up a tough defense.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure whether anybody paid attention to the speeches. But
it was tough not to pay attention when bluesman Jimmie Vaughan of
Austin cranked up his Fender Stratocaster guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be paying attention when I come on stage,'' Vaughan
said yesterday, laughing as he came off stage after a sound check
in the First Union Center arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be blasting them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' idea of convention entertainment used to be Lee
Greenwood singing ``God Bless the U.S.A.'' This week, the party
bands have included Blues Traveler (for U.S. Rep. Dick Armey) and
Earth, Wind and Fire. The arena has been rocked by the Greater
Exodus Baptist Church gospel choir and, now, blasted with Oak Cliff
blues.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan is part of the convention's not-your-father's-GOP
marketing, but he also has played before for Gov. George W. Bush.
He and his younger brother, the late Stevie Ray Vaughan, played the
1989 inaugural ball for Bush's father, President George Bush,
invited by the late Republican Party Chairman Lee Atwater.
</P>
<P>
   It's that boomer thing. Vaughan is 49. Bush is 54.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think George W. likes my music,'' Vaughan said. He denied
any political interest, saying he ``won't talk politics. If you
want to talk about Jimmy Reed, I'll be there.''
</P>
<P>
   He flew from Austin to perform one song, so he made it one of
his best: ``Boom-Bapa-Boom,'' a rocking number from a 1994 album.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan said he isn't surprised that musicians from the heavily
Democratic entertainment industry are playing for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible exposure for anybody,'' he said. ``Millions of
people see you.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not political. They called me, and this is what I do _ I
play guitar.''
</P>
<P>
   Even comedians get in on this Republican show. Comedy Central
host Ben Stein staged a skit Monday night. Later, the network
hosted a party, turning the Drexel University Grand Hall
administration building into a wild dance club filled with 12 bars,
eight food tables and a lighted dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, former Miami Hurricanes football player Dwayne
``The Rock'' Johnson of the World Wrestling Federation is supposed
to introduce the speaker of the House.
</P>
<P>
   It's the world's first 4-day-long halftime show.
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7538, or e-mail:
budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
