<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9818 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-LAZIO-NYT     08-01 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-LAZIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO'S VISIT TO GOP CONVENTION SHORT, BUT NOT VERY SWEET 
</HEADLINE>
  By   RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Rep. Rick Lazio stopped by his party's convention
for a few brief hours on Tuesday, seizing the chance to raise money
for his Senate campaign and to rally supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican congressman from Long Island also managed to try
to increase his visibility against his high-profile opponent,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, by giving interviews on local and national
television at several events.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day, he seemed unrestrained by the national
Republican efforts to steer clear of criticism of Clinton and her
husband. Instead, Lazio told New York delegates at a brunch several
miles from the convention hall that ``we've been here about a day,
probably longer than Hillary Clinton has been in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Lazio was far more guarded, telling a mass of journalists
that he was taking the high road toward what he considered the
negativity of his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   And he attracted people curious to see the man who is in
political combat with the first lady, though more than a smattering
still were unsure who he was. ``Is that Lazio?'' asked one delegate
as he passed near the First Union Center. He did venture inside the
hall, though far from the podium, where some Republicans felt Lazio
belonged. He said he was ``excited to be here,'' but would stay
just a short while before doing more interviews and then attending
fund-raisers in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Republican party's platform, Lazio said, ``I
think the platform, frankly, has become largely obsolete.'' He did
cite the GOP's opposition to abortion as problematic (he opposes
public financing for abortions and late-term procedures).
</P>
<P>
   Dan McLagan, a spokesman for Lazio, later explained that Lazio
considered the concept of platforms obsolete, not the content.
McLagan was not sure what else in the platform Lazio opposed. Lazio
faced a long line of questions about the brevity of his visit, and
he reiterated that he would not be here Thursday for Gov. George W.
Bush's acceptance speech. Some have suggested that the Lazio
campaign was irritated that he was not offered a greater role,
especially given the prominence the first lady will have at the
Democratic convention in Los Angeles. Others, though, including his
aides, said that he wanted to avoid such a spectacle. Asked about
his lack of a speaking role, he said: ``My job is to get back to
New York. That's where the votes are. I'm not running for national
office here.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of his prominent Republican allies said they were
disappointed, including House Majority Leader Dick Armey, who
warmly hugged Lazio and called him ``one of my one or two best
friends in the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey, a conservative Texas Republican, said that despite his
occasional political differences with the more moderate Lazio, he
would have liked to see Lazio play a more high-profile role at the
convention. Organizers, Armey said, ``tried to allocate spots to
guys who needed the exposure. Rick doesn't really need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio told reporters he spent Monday in New York at seven or
eight events that aides later said were private fund-raisers, like
the one Tuesday night at a restaurant in Veterans Stadium, where he
was joined by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, Clinton's campaign spokesman, said Lazio was
``trying to run away from his party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Washington, Rick Lazio is proud to be a member of the
Republican leadership,'' Wolfson said, ``but in New York he tries
to hide the fact that he's a Republican at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
