<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9820 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-RESEARCH-EARNINGS-ART     08-01 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEARCH-EARNINGS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITIES SEEKING NEW WAYS TO REAP PROFITS FROM THEIR
INTELLECTUAL CAPITAL
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo _
NYT 28 _ was sent on 7-26 to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Fredric D. Price, the president of a
nutritional-supplements company, sought a partner to create an
online information company, NutritionU.com, he approached a
Columbia University professor, Dr. Richard J. Deckelbaum.
</P>
<P>
   He hit pay dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Some academics might have run the other way, concerned about the
motives and standards in the emerging commercial market for
cybereducation. But Deckelbaum, director of Columbia's Institute of
Human Nutrition, was not especially worried; he viewed the Internet
as a way to reach a wider population.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia was interested, too. The venture fit neatly into its
strategy to turn more of its intellectual capital _ the knowledge,
research and teaching of its professors _ into financial capital.
It quickly forged an agreement with Price for fees and a share of
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia's eagerness to join forces with a start-up Internet
venture reflects a significant shift in an academic culture that
once saw itself driven only by intellectual curiosity and far
removed from commerce. While the change is occurring throughout the
academic world, few universities have moved to try to cash in as
aggressively as Columbia, which has a research capacity similar to
that of Harvard and Yale but without their endowments.
</P>
<P>
   As Columbia ventures further and faster than its peer
institutions _ it is collecting more in patents and royalties than
any other university _ it is the focus of both concern and envy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a paradigm shift,'' said Cornelius W. Sullivan,
the vice provost for research at the University of Southern
California, who is trying to point his own university in a similar
direction. ``There was a time that this kind of work _ and the idea
of making money from your research _ was not acceptable at
universities, including ours. That has changed dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Columbia earned nearly $100 million of its $1.5
billion budget from patents and royalties. This year it will
collect more than $160 million on products, like one technique that
allows animal cells to be used to manufacture proteins used as
drugs, and another that paved the way for eye drops used in
treating glaucoma. It is reinvesting much of that money in further
research to expand scientific discoveries and the money it makes
from them.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the faculty has not raised a fuss. The benefits to
them of collecting more money from research and other academic
activities are clear: more money to advance their work and less
dependence on the government. But there are concerns as well.
</P>
<P>
   Dimitris Anastassiou, a professor of electrical engineering at
Columbia, worries about the perception among some faculty members
that the university increasingly ``appears to be a for-profit
enterprise.'' He would like it to put more of a wall between
decisions about how the campus can make money, and decisions about
what research the university should support. Currently, both sets
of decisions are vested in the executive vice provost, Michael M.
Crow, who receives the university's income from patents and
royalties and decides how to spend it.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Krimsky, a science policy specialist at Tufts
University, worries about the impact on research when professors or
universities have a stake in the outcome of work they are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more involvement you have by faculty, administrators and
students, the more likely you are to have conflicts,'' he said.
``It is a question not just of how many relationships you have with
business, but the nature of those relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Eli M. Noam, a Columbia business professor who believes that
generating more revenue from intellectual property is legitimate,
still worries that ``long term, it will reduce the credibility of
universities and will probably reduce the willingness of society to
take care of these institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Universities have benefited from the perception that they are
outside the marketplace and have credibility because they are seen
as disinterested parties,'' Noam said.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia's provost, Jonathan R. Cole, acknowledges that there is
a revolution taking place in what he calls the ``means and modes''
of producing knowledge, but argues that it will be possible to
safeguard the underlying values of the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the dominant values are predominantly the same as they
used to be,'' he said. ``The income is only a means to continue to
pursue our mission.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our motivation is to be entrepreneurial,'' Cole said. ``We've
been giving it away for generations. Now we want to get a fair
return, always so we can reinvest it. That is changing the
relationship of universities to the outside world.''
</P>
<P>
   The change began two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   To spur technological progress, the Bayh-Dole Act of 1980
encouraged universities to commercialize the research they
conducted with support from the federal government. Columbia, like
other research universities, set up a technology licensing office.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Spinning academic discoveries into commercial riches, however,
turned out to be a slow, uncertain process. Even if a university
can find a company willing to license its discoveries, the odds are
only one in 20 that the company will make it pay off commercially,
said Lita Nelsen, director of the Technology Licensing Office at
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. She said that MIT
typically earns $15 million to $20 million a year in patent and
royalty fees, and that most university licensing offices do not
break even.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet, which traffics in information, has jolted
university officials into action. They see the Net as a gold mine _
providing a faster, larger payback than traditional research in
areas like biology _ if only they can figure out how to package
what their professors know.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies with deep pockets are already buzzing around
campuses, eager to enlist professors like Deckelbaum or Arthur R.
Miller, a widely known Harvard law professor who agreed to work
with a new online law school while he remained at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the competition, universities are trying to create
their own opportunities that will allow professors to expand their
reach and their incomes, and permit the universities to share in
the bounty.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia has been well ahead of the pack. The partnership with
NutritionU.com is just one of the deals it has announced in recent
months. In April, it announced the creation of Fathom.com, a
commercial online partnership with other prestigious institutions,
including the New York Public Library, the British Library and the
Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of Natural History. These
institutions and others will offer information and classes on the
Web site. In May, the university announced that it was teaming up
with Cognitive Arts, a software designer, to offer continuing
education on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia was also the first university to join forces with
UNext.com, a start-up backed by Michael Milken, the former
junk-bond king, that is offering Internet college courses created
by elite universities. Columbia has already collected $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Crow, Columbia's executive vice provost, has been quarterbacking
the university's efforts to cash in on its intellectual property.
He has easy access to the provost and the president. And he has a
hefty bankroll: more than $40 million this year, money not subject
to the normal budget process or any faculty oversight.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of the university's seriousness was its decision seven
years ago to give Crow the income from the university's research
royalties as his budget, rather than contribute it to the
university's general fund. At the time, the amount was small, about
$1 million. Today, it is about $42 million.
</P>
<P>
   Crow thinks of the money as venture capital to be spent both on
academically promising projects and economically promising ones. In
recent years, his office has contributed $800,000 in seed money for
a child and family policy center, and $600,000 into the development
of an urban extension service. ``On the academic side, we are not
after economic return,'' he said. ``We are after academic or social
return.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, he said, about $10 million went into various academic
initiatives. An additional $20 million went into building new
institutions, like a campus connected with Biosphere 2 in Arizona,
and the rest into miscellaneous projects, including digital media.
</P>
<P>
   The university has created a new structure, Columbia Media
Enterprises, to nurture digital projects. Although modeled on
Columbia's technology licensing office, Columbia Innovation
Enterprise, there is a key difference: it is a profit-making
company, albeit one wholly owned by Columbia. Columbia Media
Enterprises started last fall with one employee; today there are
15, including seven student ``sweepers'' who comb the university
for content to put on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of increased activity over the Internet,
Columbia pushed its faculty to consider how their interests should
be treated. Professors traditionally own the rights to the books
and articles they write, and their royalties represent perhaps 10
to 15 percent of book sales. Universities typically own patents
from research, and professors may get a quarter of the revenue.
(Each university's policy differs.)
</P>
<P>
   Columbia's Senate approved a new intellectual property policy in
June that gives the university rights to Internet projects that are
supported by university money or commissioned by the university, or
that make ``substantial'' use of university equipment and labor. In
these cases, professors share in the revenue, receiving anywhere
from a quarter to a half of the revenue after expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia says it has no plans to compel faculty members to
cooperate with its own ventures, but hopes to offer them as an
alternative to working with outside companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The faculty are independent spirits, and we can't make them do
anything,'' Crow said. ``Their primary benefit is to create new
knowledge. The secondary benefit is to collect licensing income.
But it's a wondrous secondary benefit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
