<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9824 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-WOMEN-JOCKS-CO     08-01 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-WOMEN-JOCKS-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN ATHLETES SELL MAGAZINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, Aug. 1, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The August issues of Esquire and GQ magazines have dueling babes
on their covers_ each model provocatively posed in a tight, white,
breast-hugging, belly-baring T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   That's no surprise. The publishers of men's magazines often use
actresses or models as cover subjects, knowing that men are
drooling idiots who are influenced by that sort of thing. We like
power tools, but we like chicks even more. (Hence the Rigid Tool
Calendar.)
</P>
<P>
   This time around, though, the cover subjects aren't models or
actresses _ they're jocks.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis tart Anna Kournikova, the most downloaded female athlete
in the history of the Internet (literally thousands of Web sites in
dozens of languages are dedicated to worshipping her), is on the
cover of GQ, along with the caption, ``Don't Call Me Lolita.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. We'll call you ``Professor'' instead.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Kournikova doesn't mind parlaying the Lolita routine
into $10 million in endorsement deals per annum, including a
billboard campaign with her in a sports bra and the caption, ``Only
the ball should bounce.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympic pentathlete Mary Beth Larsen is the Esquire cover woman,
in honor of ``Strength &AMP; Beauty, A Portfolio of America's 10
Sexiest Athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Larsen is on the cover of only some issues. Others
feature high jumper Amy Acuff, doing a Fosbury Flop while wearing a
black, shiny, Calvin Klein bikini, which I'm pretty sure is not her
usual high-jumping attire-though if it was the ratings for track
and field on TV would IMPROVE TREMENDOUSLY.
</P>
<P>
   I've also seen Esquire covers starring triathlete Lokelani
McMichael, jogging in a wet T-shirt; and kayaker Tamara Jenkins in
white shorts so tight you can see all the way to Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Not all 10 of the athletes in the pictorial feature are at the
absolute top of their profession; however, all of them are
fabulously attractive, e.g., surfer Malia Jones, who could easily
slip into a Sports Illustrated swimsuit issue as a model without
anyone blinking.
</P>
<P>
   For an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The same standard applies to Ms. Kournikova, by far the most
talked-about, written-about and lusted-after female athlete on the
planet. The 19-year-old Kournikova ain't on the cover of GQ because
she's the best player on the women's tour _ in fact, she's more
like the 15th or 16th best, a good but not great performer who has
never won a WTA event in her career.
</P>
<P>
   She is, however, like that neighborhood girl who flounces about
in tight outfits and then complains when the guy across the street
runs his power mower into a tree because he's so distracted by her.
She wears sexy outfits and she dates NHL players and she says
provocative things the boys love hear _ which leads to
embarrassments like the GQ story, with its cringe-inducing lead of,
``I am deeply in love with Anna Kournikova.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the GQ story is the most egregious example of a
magazine being bowled over by Kournikova's looks. That dubious
distinction belongs to the aforementioned SI, which caused a furor
earlier this year by putting Kournikova on the cover in a pouty
pose touting a story that had another 11 pictures, including two in
which she's actually playing tennis.
</P>
<P>
   As for the article itself, the normally level-headed Frank
Deford called called her ``Pornikova,'' ``Ground Strokin' Goddess''
and, believe it or not, ``Jezebel of Sweat.''
</P>
<P>
   Well at least he didn't call her ``Lolita.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's sports organizations complained about the article and
op-ed columns ragged on SI for highlighting Kournikova over more
deserving players such as Martina Hingis, Lindsay Davenport or the
Williams sisters. At around the same time, 32-year-old Nathalie
Tauziat, the No. 6 player in the world, released a book (in French)
in which she referred to Kournikova as, yep, ``Lolita,'' and ``a
blond cash machine'' and mocks Kournikova's abilities.
</P>
<P>
   But don't cry for Kournikova; after all, it's her choice to pose
for GQ, a-posin' and a-poutin.'
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I think Larsen, Acuff and company are more
impressive physical specimens. More grownup, more mature, less
bimbo-y.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I could make the politically correct claim that it's
a shame any of these great athletes have to dampen their T-shirts
and wear tight shorts just to get some play in national mainstream
magazines, but come on, who's using whom?
</P>
<P>
   Whether we're talking about the U.S. women's soccer team calling
themselves ``booters with hooters,'' American and Australian female
track and field stars doing nude calendars, volleyballer Gabrielle
Reece doing pinup posters or ice skating legend Katarina Witt
baring all for Playboy, an awful lot of top-level gal jocks are
celebrating their attractiveness on their own terms. If they want
to do stuff like that, who am I to get in their way?
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper &AMP; the
Movies.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
