<HEADER>
A9826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-PROFILES-NYT &LR;      08-01 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-PROFILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEDNESDAY'S SPEAKERS AT THE GOP CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trent Lott
</P>
<P>
   Republican Senator from Mississippi
</P>
<P>
   Combining firebrand conservatism and polished tactical skills,
Trent Lott, the majority leader in the Senate, has climbed the
ranks of the Republican Party. Lott, 58, a gregarious lawyer who
was once the party's House whip, vaulted over other, more senior
members to the party's top job in the Senate in 1994. His smooth
television performances and openly partisan manner won over many
young Republicans, as he shifted from the House to the Senate. He
is the first person to hold whip positions in both houses of
Congress. Lott, the son of a cotton farmer turned shipyard worker
and a teacher from Grenada County, Miss., began his political
career on the other side of the aisle, working for Rep. William
Colmer, D-Miss., in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   James S. Gilmore III
</P>
<P>
   Governor of Virginia
</P>
<P>
   James S. Gilmore III is at the epicenter of a Republican Party
in Virginia that had been left for dead just five years ago. But
for the first time in a century, Republicans now hold all three of
the top statewide elected offices. In 1997, Gilmore, 50,
orchestrated something of a tour de force, turning an underdog run
for governor into a rout. He picked a clear message _ cut the tax
on personal cars and trucks _ and he never waivered. Exit polling
indicated that this message, and his steadfastness, won over
voters. Gilmore, who was born in Richmond, Va., and still lives
there, served in the Army as a counterintelligence specialist in
Germany before receiving a law degree from the University of
Virginia. Along the road to the governor's mansion, he practiced
law, served as county attorney and was elected attorney general in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Richard J. Riordan
</P>
<P>
   Mayor of Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   The first Republican mayor in more than 30 years of the largely
Democratic and liberal Los Angeles, Richard J. Riordan is known for
fighting crime and municipal inefficiency. He won his race in 1993
largely on the strength of white voters in the San Fernando Valley
and elsewhere in the city as fears of a surging crime rate swept
the city and the race riots that followed the acquittal of four
white police officers who were accused of beating Rodney King were
a recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Before winning his first term, he made millions as a venture
capitalist and investment banker, and was a philanthropist and Los
Angeles power broker. He is comfortable with politicians from both
parties and worked tirelessly to ensure that the Democratic
National Convention would be held in Los Angeles later this month _
often against the Democratically-controlled City Council. ``The
Democratic convention is a huge plus for the city of Los Angeles,
and that's my first love,'' he said recently. ``My first love is
not the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Raul J. Fernandez
</P>
<P>
   Technology Company Owner
</P>
<P>
   Raul J. Fernandez, 34, is one of the wealthiest men in the
country under 40. A former aide to Jack Kemp in Congress, he is now
chairman and chief executive of Proxicom, an Internet consulting
company based in Reston, Va. With $40,000 in savings, Fernandez
founded the company in 1991, three years after leaving Kemp's
office. The company reported revenue of $50.9 million for the
second quarter of 2000. The firm was founded as a systems
integration company called Proxima, but Fernandez changed the name
to Proxicom and the emphasis on Internet consulting in the
mid-1990s. As a young aide to Kemp, Fernandez researched tax
legislation and debated financing for rebels in Nicaragua while
working on the office's computer system. (As of November, Kemp
owned more than $2.3 million in Proxicom stock.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
