<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MIPS-MARKETPLACE-ART-     08-01 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIPS-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: CLASS WARFARE VS. RATIONALITY ON MIPS STOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an irrational world, a rational investor may be at a severe
disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with MIPS Technologies, a semiconductor equipment
company whose share price has gyrated wildly this year. It fell
from a high of more than $111 on March 14 to a low under $17 on May
24 and has since rebounded to more than $46.
</P>
<P>
   Such swings are not all that unusual in this year's technology
yo-yo, in which companies go from beloved to hated and back faster
than a teen-ager can develop a crush. But MIPS stands out because
it has two classes of stock. What is amazing is not the absolute
prices of these shares, but their relative prices.
</P>
<P>
   Since the second class of shares began trading in late June,
they have traded at an inexplicable discount to the original
shares. More than a few clever investors, seeing that spread, have
tried to take advantage of it. Their strategy has been completely
rational. It has also been very unsuccessful. Against all reason,
the discount has widened. Rational investors who thought they saw a
sure profit now have substantial losses.
</P>
<P>
   Before getting to the details, here are the basic facts: MIPS
used to be a subsidiary of Silicon Graphics, which took the
subsidiary public through a 1998 initial public offering, and then
sold more shares to the public in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For tax reasons, Silicon Graphics wanted to keep 80 percent
voting control even though it owned only about 65 percent of the
stock after that second offering. So it put through a
reclassification that allowed its Class B shares to elect 80
percent of the board members, while Class A shares _ the ones in
public hands _ could elect only 20 percent of the board. Other than
votes, however, the shares were equal. They have equal rights to
dividends and to any other distributions by the company.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Silicon Graphics got out of MIPS entirely by spinning
off the Class B shares to its shareholders. Beginning June 21,
there were 25.1 million shares of Class B, trading under the Nasdaq
symbol MIPSB, and 13.4 million shares of Class A, trading under the
symbol MIPS.
</P>
<P>
   Logically, the MIPSB shares ought to be worth the same _ or
perhaps a bit more _ than the Class A shares, reflecting the
additional voting rights and the fact that more of them are in
public hands and available for trading. But when the shares began
trading in June, the Class B shares were trading at a small
discount of about $1 a share to the original shares.
</P>
<P>
   Such discounts are not unusual in the early days of a spinoff.
Shareholders of a parent company often sell the spunoff shares soon
after they arrive, particularly if they wound up with only a few
shares of the new company. That clearly could have happened in this
case _ only 13.86 shares of MIPS B were distributed for each 100
shares of Silicon Graphics.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that some investors tried to take advantage of the
discrepancy in the prices of the two shares by borrowing Class A
shares and selling them short while buying Class B shares. That
strategy guaranteed a profit if the price differential were
eliminated, as a rational investor would expect.
</P>
<P>
   But instead it widened. On June 27, the gap between the two
shares suddenly leaped to more than $3. It soon settled at $2 to
$3, but then grew again on July 12 to more than $5.
</P>
<P>
   With some fluctuation, the difference has remained about that
ever since. Yesterday, the gap stood at $5.625, or 12 percent, as
the MIPS shares closed at $46.6875 and the MIPSB shares ended the
day at $41.0625.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Eichler, the chief financial officer of MIPS, said in an
interview that he was puzzled by the discrepancy. But he said one
possibility was that many individual investors had not yet grasped
that there are two shares of stock available. ``Without question,
there is more retail focus on'' the old shares, he said. ``They
just type in the symbol MIPS and don't know MIPSB.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some evidence to support that view, since MIPS tends to
have more small trades than MIPSB.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more at work here than uninformed retail investors.
Nasdaq reports short interest _ the number of shares that have been
borrowed and sold short _ monthly, and those figures indicate that
the short interest in MIPS has soared. On June 12, shortly before
the spinoff, the reported short interest was about 1.7 million
shares. But by July 11, it had leaped to 3.1 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Class B shares would seem to offer greater liquidity, since
nearly twice as many of them are outstanding as are Class A shares.
But in fact they have traded at lower volume. Total volume for the
month of July in Class B shares came to 8.5 million shares, or
about a third of the shares outstanding. Total volume for Class A
shares came to 20 million shares, or about 1.5 times the number of
shares outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   What may have happened is that some of the investors who
received Class B shares in the distribution from Silicon Graphics
were reluctant to sell them at the discount. Instead, they sold
Class A shares short.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gordon, the president of 21st Securities, a firm that
specializes in various forms of arbitrage, said he considered
shorting the Class A shares and buying the Class B ones but
concluded that the risk of a short squeeze was too great. In such a
squeeze, an investor who has sold a stock short is forced to buy it
back, often because it has become difficult or impossible to borrow
the shares.
</P>
<P>
   But Gordon added that ``Anyone who owns MIPS Class A should
certainly sell it and buy MIPS Class B.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that is the rational thing to do. But so
far being rational has not been the same thing as being right in
MIPS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
