   &UR; Off-lead: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-AIDS (Beijing) _ With the AIDS virus moving silently
through China, a number of China's leading medical experts have
begun to angrily complain that the government has done too little
define the epidemic and to prevent the virus' spread. Official
inattention and the lack of a national public education program
have already allowed HIV to transform from an fairly rare condition
among intravenous drug users in 1990, to a rapidly growing problem
that now effects an estimated 600,000 Chinese, the scientists say.
And in another 10 years, they warn, China will have one of the
world's largest populations of HIV carriers, unless the government
takes action. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `i' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOLD: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GOP-FUNDRAISING _ Who is raising money for George Bush and how?
By Don Van Natta Jr.
