<HEADER>
A9834 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-GOP-MONEY02-COX     08-01 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GOP-MONEY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CORPORATE INTERESTS FUEL PARTY BOOM AT CONVENTION
 &HT;    500&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By MARK SHERMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ You won't see any television commercials in this
particular campaign, but the race between Michael Oxley of Ohio and
Billy Tauzin of Louisiana is shaping up as one of the year's
fiercest _ and most entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   The two congressional Republicans are vying to be chairman of
the House Commerce Committee next year, but their competition is
playing out at the Republican National Convention. Companies with
interests before the powerful panel have flocked to be sponsors of
parties in their honor, part of a tide of corporate money sweeping
over the convention.
</P>
<P>
   And these are no run-of-the-mill receptions.
</P>
<P>
   Oxley's party featured the ageless Dick Clark, Frankie Avalon
and Chubby Checker. The entertainment harkened back to another era,
but the interests of the more than dozen companies that footed the
bill are firmly in the 21st century, including telecommunications
and electricity deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the same companies were among the three dozen or so that
paid for the Tauzin party, a Mardi Gras bash Tuesday night at the
old Philadelphia Navy yard. Members of the Neville family provided
the entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Company, the parent company of Georgia Power and other
southern utilities, and Atlanta-based BellSouth are studiously
neutral in the race for chairman, and willing sponsors of both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the politicians are and it's the job of our
lobbyists to establish relationships with politicians,'' said Bill
McCloskey, BellSouth's director of media relations.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is running a lounge with free refreshments for
reporters covering the convention, McCloskey said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyndall, a Southern Co. spokesman, said, ``They are both
well-respected individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has made $1.5 million in contributions to candidates,
political action committees and political parties in 1999 and 2000,
according to the Center for Responsive Politics. The Southern
Company has given $732,000 so far, the center said.
</P>
<P>
   These convention parties fall within House ethics rules, which
otherwise place strict limits on what lawmakers may accept from
lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   But the parties and the avalanche of political money at the
convention raises the ire of good government groups, which argue
that special interests get unparalleled access to politicians and
that the politicians are sure to remember their patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system's broken. We are addicted to soft money,'' Sen.
John McCain told reporters Tuesday in criticizing both the parties
and contributions. Soft money technically refers only to the
unlimited contributions to political parties, but McCain was
speaking more broadly.
</P>
<P>
   McCain added, ``The fact is, it's a bipartisan issue.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, McCloskey said that BellSouth is one of many
companies from many industries that have paid to rent Dodger
Stadium for a day during the Democratic convention later this
month. Delegates will have the chance to take batting practice and
shag fly balls, just like the big leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The Oxley and Tauzin parties were just two of hundreds of
receptions and parties at the Republican convention. At the same
time that Tauzin was the guest of honor at his party, Speaker
Dennis Hastert of Illinois, Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas and
Majority Whip Tom DeLay of Texas were the stars of a party that
featured the band Blues Traveler. Coca-Cola, Continental Airlines
and Union Pacific Corp. were among the sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Other sponsors of the Oxley event included: Philip Morris, which
has given $1.8 million; Merrill Lynch, $1.1 million; and the Edison
Electric Institute, $486,000.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies who paid for Tauzin's party included: Philip
Morris; SBC Communications, $2 million; Joseph E Seagram &AMP; Sons,
$1.2 million; Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co., $1 million; America Online,
$737,000; Walt Disney, $692,000; United Airlines, $604,000; Viacom,
$402,391; and News Corp., $401,000.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to parties, corporations and industry trade groups
have seized numerous opportunities to get their names and issues in
front of candidates, delegates and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, television viewers may see beach balls being
batted around the convention hall. The balls are being provided by
the National Association of Manufacturers and the Alliance for
Worker Retirement Security to push private Social Security savings
accounts. The balls bear slogans like ``Don't inflate the Trust
Fund.''
</P>
<P>
   US Airways, the official airline of the GOP convention, has a
hospitality suite in the First Union Center for big Republican
contributors. A pilot in uniform greets visitors at the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Many reporters have placed their convention credentials in a
plastic holder supplied by the Lexis-Nexis research and information
service.
</P>
<P>
   And, as it has for many years, Kraft has given delegates and the
media boxes of macaroni and cheese in which the pasta is shaped
like an elephant, the Republican party mascot.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman's e-mail address is marks(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
