<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9839 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-LILEKS-CONVENTIONS-NE     08-01 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILEKS-CONVENTIONS-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A TALE OF TWO CONVENTIONS, STAGED FOR CONTRAST 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, Aug. 1, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By JAMES LILEKS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tightly scripted coronation, some call the Republican
convention; other commentators, looking for a unique angle, have
called it a coronation, tightly scripted. As one pundit said:
``There's a script for this coronation, and it's tight.''
</P>
<P>
   When the GOP convention sticks to a single theme, it's a
ham-fisted suppression of diversity. But when every member of the
media sings the same song, it's an amiable consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Ahhh, but who needs spontaneity? The French Revolution consisted
of 10 years of spontaneity, and they're still washing the blood off
the Place de la Concorde. Spontaneity gets you events such as the
Shadow Convention, where a group of political infants was stunned
to hear John McCain endorse George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   They heckled, threatened, barked and generally expressed dismay
that a pillar of the Republican establishment did not announce his
support for the Ralph Nader/Jello Biafra ticket. Ridiculous, yes --
but spontaneous!
</P>
<P>
   Over at the GOP convention, of course, spontaneity and diversity
have been banished in favor of a soulless parade of blow-dried
robots. A yahoo.com headline summed up the general nature of the
horror: ``Average GOP Delegate White Male, Married,'' it said, and
only the ``married'' part kept them from writing, ``Like Tim
McVeigh, Average GOP Delegate White, Male.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, black people somehow sneaked into the event. A
black gospel choir serenaded the delegates on the first night,
prompting an ABC radio news anchor to note that ``it's not the sort
of sound you expect to hear in this place.'' It's not expected, you
see, because the GOP delegates are all RACISTS who no doubt get
nervous when they see black people who aren't either tap-dancing,
shuffling along the road in shackles, or dressed up like the Cream
of Wheat mascot. Republicans, according to liberals, only attract
strange, damaged, self-hating black people.
</P>
<P>
   Let's review, then: Colin Powell, Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Al Sharpton, Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   If the GOP convention had featured a Lutheran choir singing
room-temperature hymns, commentators would have warned darkly about
the role of the religious right. But a black gospel choir, exultant
in the throes of religious ecstasy, strikes the liberal ear as a
safe form of devotion. Gospel singers occupy the Good End of
demonstrative religion, the polar opposite of pale, eye-rolling,
buzz-cutted snake-handlers in short-sleeved shirts. Surely any God
who enjoys gospel music is pro-choice and anti-school-vouchers,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Since lack of spontaneity and unity are traits of the nasty old
GOP, we can expect that the script for the Democratic convention's
opening night looks like the following:
</P>
<P>
   ``FYI -- this is a rough draft, people, since unlike the other
guys, we are spontaneous and diverse!! Note to pyrotechnicians --
fireworks are usually left for the closing moments of the last
night, but feel free to shoot them off when you like. Likewise all
marching bands, floor demonstrations, etc. Follow your bliss!
Anyway, here's the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   ''7:00-7:05 -- Welcoming address by Dr. Laura. Working title is,
`You thumb your nose at God and I hold my nose at you.' Be nice.
Show our tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ''7:06 -- Dr. Laura's body dragged offstage (exact time subject
to change, but the cameramen need a window so they can set up
shots).
</P>
<P>
   ''7:07 -- Keynote speech by Hillary Rodham Clinton: `Tevye and
Me,' about her recollections of playing a czarist agent in a high
school production of `Fiddler on the Roof.'
</P>
<P>
   ''7:30-10:00 -- To Be Announced. Possible speeches include Bill
Bradley, whose two-hour slide show has an algebraic proof of his
superiority over Al Gore; Mario Cuomo might speak in Latin for two
hours (applause lines will be signaled by a wry waggle of his
eyebrows -- pay attention!!!); OR Miami Cubans might take the
podium to bitterly denounce us as tools of a homophobic, fascist
tobacco merchant named Fidel. Hey, it's anything goes at OUR
convention!''
</P>
<P>
   So that's the first night.
</P>
<P>
   And how will their convention end? Why, in the interests of
spontaneity and diversity, FDR's old wheelchair is nominated for
the presidency. ``From the Great State of Despair,'' a delegate
says, ``we nominate his empty wheelchair. Better the great man's
seat unfilled than warmed by the butt of that callow satyr's
vice-apologist!''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, such a delegate would probably be a Republican -- but
no one would wonder how he got into the convention. In the
interests of spontaneity and diversity, anyone's welcome at the
Democratic convention. Unless, of course, you're not a Democrat.
Tsk, tsk: And here we thought they were the party of inclusion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
