r p BC-GORE0802-COX     08-01 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore spending vacation time at home of sporting goods
entrepreneur
 &HT;    By Bobby Burns
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. - Vice President Al Gore is making a habit of
spending his
</P>
<P>
   vacation at the beach home of a North Carolina sporting goods
entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who will accept the Democratic Party's presidential
nomination
</P>
<P>
   later this month, arrived Thursday at the home of Parker
Overton,
</P>
<P>
   founder of Overton's water sports mail order company based in
</P>
<P>
   Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   It's the third summer in four years that Gore, his wife, Tipper,
and
</P>
<P>
   family members have stayed at the home located on Figure Eight
Island, a
</P>
<P>
   private residential enclave north of Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Overton's is a leading retailer of skis, sportswear and water
sports
</P>
<P>
   equipment. Overton's daughter, Kristi, is a world champion water
skier.
</P>
<P>
   The Gores first stayed at the four-story, six-bedroom,
seven-bath home in
</P>
<P>
   1997 after a mutual acquaintance recommended Figure Eight to the
Gores and
</P>
<P>
   helped make arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Overton, who charges the second family nothing for the stay,
said Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   he expects no return favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the vice president of the United States calls and he's used
your house
</P>
<P>
   and he enjoyed himself, you'd open your house up to him again,''
Overton said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenville lawyer Tom Taft, a Gore supporter and former
Democratic
</P>
<P>
   representative in the North Carolina House, sold the Gores on
Figure Eight. He said they enjoy the North Carolina coast and
Figure Eight's privacy is appealing.
</P>
<P>
   The island is a ``gated'' community, Taft said. Security guards
man the
</P>
<P>
   single bridge that connects it to the mainland. Secret Service
agents
</P>
<P>
   augment the existing security contingent when Gore visits, Taft
said.
</P>
<P>
   Taft's home on the island was too small to accommodate the
Gores, so he
</P>
<P>
   arranged the family's initial stay at the Overtons. The Gores
have called the Overtons
</P>
<P>
   directly since.
</P>
<P>
   Taft and the Overtons were invited to an official party at the
vice
</P>
<P>
   president's last Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The Gores are expected to leave Thursday, said Gore spokesman
Jim Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was expected to spend a short time mulling his
vice-presidential pick,
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said. Two potential choices, Sens. Evan Bayh of Indiana
and John
</P>
<P>
   Edwards of North Carolina, also have been vacationing on the
island at a
</P>
<P>
   home owned by Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   The Gores' children, Kristen, Sarah and Albert, all have spent
time there
</P>
<P>
   during the week, Kennedy said. The couple's other daughter,
Karenna, also visited
</P>
<P>
   with her husband, Drew Schiff and their son, Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are having a great time here together,'' Kennedy said
Tuesday. They
</P>
<P>
   have been body-surfing, taking walks along the beach, playing
board games,
</P>
<P>
   reading books, watching videos and working a jigsaw puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Overton and his wife, Becky, took the Gores boating on Friday,
allowing
</P>
<P>
   both to steer their 38-foot, high performance vessel
</P>
<P>
   through the Intracoastal Waterway.
</P>
<P>
   Overton is not active in the Democratic Party. In the past, he
has
</P>
<P>
   supported candidates from both major parties, including North
Carolina's
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Jesse Helms and Democratic Gov. Jim Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   He has contributed to neither the Gore campaign nor that of GOP
candidate
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, according to the Center for Responsive Politics,
a
</P>
<P>
   nonpartisan group that tabulates federal election reports.
Overton would not
</P>
<P>
   say if he supports Gore's bid for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy calling myself friends with him, but I'm not a
political person. I'm a businessman,'' Overton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Greenville native started Overton's Sporting Goods about 25
years ago
</P>
<P>
   in his father's grocery store. He began selling water skis
</P>
<P>
   and equipment while cutting meat at the store.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has built the business into a multimillion dollar
catalog
</P>
<P>
   and Internet company. In addition to its corporate headquarters
in
</P>
<P>
   Greenville, the company has a showroom and warehouse facility
here.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's office also said the Overton friendship is not
</P>
<P>
   political.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president is deeply appreciative of the hospitality
shown by the
</P>
<P>
   Overtons and he enjoyed the time he spent with them, but it's
strictly a
</P>
<P>
   private matter,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gores are constantly in the public eye, Overton said, so
he's glad to
</P>
<P>
   let them use the home if it grants them some respite. He said he
will allow
</P>
<P>
   them to use the house again if they want to, whether or not Gore
is president.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good people,'' Overton said. ``And like you, me or
anybody else,
</P>
<P>
   they need to get away and have some time to enjoy themselves. If
they
</P>
<P>
   want to come back, they're welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
