<HEADER>
A9841 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-UGAFOOT0802-COX     08-01 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGAFOOT0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ It might not be the biggest or best recruiting
class that Georgia coach Jim Donnan has signed in his five seasons
in Athens, but several newcomers could make a significant impact
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is expected to welcome 14 freshmen to campus today,
including three quarterbacks and a pair of highly regarded running
backs. The group includes three players _ receivers Reggie Brown
and Tavarus Morgan and defensive lineman Johnathan Sullivan _ who
signed with the Bulldogs in 1999, but failed to qualify
academically.
</P>
<P>
   Three more junior college transfers could join the Bulldogs as
early as next week. Georgia Military College defensive end Nic
Clemons and defensive backs Demetric Moore and Horace Willis are
completing final exams this week. The players must pass their
required core courses to transfer to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Georgia's more decorated freshmen are running backs
Albert Hollis of Sacramento, Calif., and Musa Smith of
Elliottsburg, Pa. Hollis, a Parade All-American this year, rushed
for 2,053 yards and 31 touchdowns as a senior. He also was one of
the nation's top prep sprinters.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who at 6 feet 2 and 210 pounds is bigger than Hollis,
rushed for 2,041 yards and 32 touchdowns as a senior. Hollis and
Smith will challenge junior Jasper Sanks and redshirt freshman
Bruce Thornton for the starting tailback spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a feeling I'll be playing this season for sure,''
Hollis said. ``I think they'll be able to use my speed in the
backfield.''
</P>
<P>
   The newcomers also include quarterbacks David Greene of South
Gwinnett High School, Sean Jones of Westlake and Matt Redding of
Madison, Fla. One of those new signal-callers should emerge as
starter Quincy Carter's backup during preseason camp.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a Parade All-American at Carrollton High in 1999, will
give Georgia much-needed speed in its receiver corps. Brown, who
had 62 catches and 10 touchdowns as a senior, enrolled at Georgia
in January, but couldn't participate in spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan has called Sullivan ``the best (defensive) lineman we've
signed at Georgia.'' Sullivan, a graduate of Griffin High, spent
last year at Hargrave Military Academy in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia lost tight end Andre Zellner of Mary Persons High to
academics. Zellner will enroll at Hargrave and said he'll sign with
the Bulldogs in February.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
