<HEADER>
A9843 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-POLITICAL-SURFING     08-01 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-POLITICAL-SURFING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE MAY BE NOTHING TO SEE, BUT YOU CAN CATCH IT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the start, Republican officials said it would be a
different sort of affair. They would offer up a new, moderate face
for the party, appeal more energetically to independent voters and
present the most fully wired, Internet-capable political convention
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Fine.
</P>
<P>
   Unplug the television. Turn off the radio. Pull down the shades.
Let's crank up that computer and see what it was actually like
Tuesday to experience Day Two of the 2000 Republican National
Convention solely as a surfer on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Pseudo.com was offering continuous streaming video from the
convention, as was c-span.org (basically, a Web version of what was
showing at around the same time on the cable channel, maybe a
minute delayed), so you didn't have to miss a minute. Be warned,
special plug-ins are often required to view some of this material,
and it can take a half-hour or more to download. As always, plan
ahead. The reward: A small, talking postage stamp of a screen with
a continuous, herky-jerky view of ebullient Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the Web, it was a grab bag of smart-aleck
commentary, quizzes, bogus polls, Web cams, sarcastic features,
chat rooms and live talk-backs.
</P>
<P>
   CNN.com thoughtfully provided users with a list of ``things to
watch'' during the day's events, basically an attempt to inject
some drama into a convention that has been proudly lacking in it.
One should watch for ``party poopers,'' it said, particularly to
see if Sen. John McCain of Arizona said some intemperate things
during his evening speech. Or keep an eye out for ``negativity,''
to see if the teeth-clenched Republican activists could keep
themselves from bashing President Clinton for another full day.
</P>
<P>
   The National Journal's Web site, in keeping with its more
serious, inside-the-Beltway bent, offered up-to-the-minute rundowns
of the day's national polls, which seemed to agree that Bush was
ahead of Vice President Gore by 5 to 8 percentage points. There was
also a poll, commissioned by the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, that showed that Sen. Zell Miller, D-Ga., who has been
on the job for exactly one week, is rated as doing an ``excellent''
or ``good'' job by 68 percent of his constituents.
</P>
<P>
   In its daily convention commentary, ``A Crowd Bored to Cheers,''
the Journal decided that ``there is utterly no tension at the
convention in Philadelphia, no drama, no sideshows at all.''
</P>
<P>
   No sideshows? How about Johnny Rotten's visit to a march in
downtown Philadelphia in support of the homeless? ``Hello, poor
people!,'' said John Lydon, who was known as Johnny Rotten when he
sang with the punk rock band, the Sex Pistols, and who now has a
Web talk show on eYada.com. The meeting of Lydon and the homeless
was recorded on salon.com. ``I'm Mr. Rotten and I'm here because
I'm amused by American politics,'' he told them.
</P>
<P>
   Speakout.com and MSNBC were offering a real-time rating of each
convention speaker. Web users could sign up and then manipulate a
little bar on the screen to show how they were rating each speaker
at each moment in the speech. The verdict from Monday night's
speeches? ``Messages aimed at female voters appear to have hit
their target.''
</P>
<P>
   C-Span, incidentally, also had a helpful chart showing how many
hours and minutes of the official convention proceedings had been
shown on the various broadcast and cable networks, to give some
idea of who was providing the most fulsome coverage. And the winner
was ... C-Span! Yes, out of seven hours and 49 minutes of official
proceedings on Monday, C-Span showed seven hours and 49 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Slate offered a diary from a Philadelphia caterer about how
difficult it was to stage Speaker Dennis Hastert's Fishing
Tournament on Tuesday morning. It seems the invited guests were
roused from their beds at 5 a.m. and stuffed onto a bus where they
were fed ``a teeny fruit salad and croissant'' to keep them quiet
while they were bused to Valley Forge National Park in the
Philadelphia suburbs. There, a ``full buffet in the middle of a
field'' awaited them. The problem was that it had rained buckets
for hours and so the whole thing was a little soggy.
</P>
<P>
   The National Journal, in a piece headlined, ``Fat's Where it's
At,'' detailed every single morsel of food that one Maryland
alternate delegate put in his mouth in one day at the convention, a
truly awesome stream of saturated fats and raging cholesterol. They
quoted another caterer, Susan Lacz, as noting that Republicans
``traditionally spend more and have higher taste buds.''
</P>
<P>
   And there were plenty of chat rooms and talk-backs Tuesday,
featuring such prominent characters as Bush domestic adviser Steve
Goldsmith and ABC's Sam Donaldson (who is threatening to talk back
every single night of the convention). Tuesday morning, Fox News
offered up their own anchor, Brit Hume, who didn't seem to have
such a high opinion of his colleagues. ``The media in general, and
the broadcast media in particular, don't have much use for
Republicans,'' Hume wrote in response to a user's question.
``That's not news, of course. But there it is.''
</P>
<P>
   But what did he eat yesterday?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
