<SLUG> BC-CVN-NATIONAL-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
BUSH LAUDED BY FORMER WAR HEROES AS IDEAL COMMANDER-IN-CHIEF &HT;    (EDS: Quotes from Sen. McCain are embargoed until delivery,
expected around 10:30 EDT)
 &HT;    By ERIC ROSENBERG
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ A triumvirate of war heroes praised Texas Gov.
George W. Bush's qualifications to be commander-in-chief Tuesday
night, with former POW John McCain telling the Republican National
Convention: ``I support him. I am grateful to him. And I am proud
of him.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who defeated Bush in seven GOP primaries earlier this
year before bowing out of the race, sought to reassure voters that
the untested Bush ``will confidently defend our interests and
values wherever they are threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain noted that former President George Bush served as a naval
aviator in World War II under McCain's grandfather, an admiral who
commanded aircraft carriers in the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it is my turn to serve under the son of my grandfather's
brave subordinate,'' McCain said, adding that Bush was a leader of
``courage and character.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Navy carrier pilot, McCain was shot down in 1967 during the
Vietnam War and spent five and a half years as a prisoner of war.
He was introduced by Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., another decorated
veteran of the Vietnam War and a McCain ally on campaign finance
reform legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of Tuesday night's convention session was national
security and foreign policy and allowed Bush to bask in the
reflected glow of some of the nation's most well-known decorated
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to McCain, former Sen. Bob Dole and retired Gen. H.
Norman Schwarzkopf, the commander of allied forces in the Persian
Gulf War, praised Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, a decorated World War II veteran and the 1996 GOP
presidential nominee, told the delegates that the nation looks to
Bush and Dick Cheney, Bush's choice for the vice presidential
nomination, ``to raise our sights and to restore honor and civility
to public life.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwarzkopf, speaking via satellite from the USS New Jersey
battleship docked in the nearby Delaware River, , said the Clinton
administration had allowed U.S. military readiness to dip. He cited
enlistment and re-enlistment shortfalls, the declining preparedness
of Army divisions and the increasing number of military personnel
who receive food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarzkopf praised the governor's father for his leadership
during the 1990-1991 Gulf War, then asked, ``Wouldn't it be great
for our armed forces and for America if we could have another
commander-in-chief named George Bush with Dick Cheney on his
team?'' Cheney was Bush's secretary of defense during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarzkopf, who retired from the U.S. Army in 1991 as a
four-star general, is active with numerous charitable activities
and conservation issues.
</P>
<P>
   Another speaker, Condoleeza Rice, a former national security
specialist in President Bush's administration and now a senior
advisor to Gov. Bush, told the convention that the younger Bush
already has a deep understanding of when _ and when not _ to employ
the military.
</P>
<P>
   In a reference to the numerous peacekeeping missions that
Clinton has committed U.S. troops to, Rice said Bush does not view
the military as ``a global police force. They are not the world's
911,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As governor of Texas for the last five years, Bush has met with
leaders from Russia, South Africa and Mexico, she said. ``I know
that he understands the complexities of our relationship with
China,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said that Bush would make good on Republican efforts to
deploy a missile defense shield, known as National Missile Defense.
</P>
<P>
   Two recent polls indicated the voters believe Bush would do the
better job handling defense and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In a poll released Monday by the Los Angeles Times, Bush led
Vice President Al Gore 61 percent to 24 percent on the question of
who would do a better job of handling national defense. And an
ABC-Washington Post poll had Bush leading Gore 45 percent to 40
percent on the question of who would best handle foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, speaking to a rally in Charleston, W.Va., on his way to
the convention, sounded the same defense theme and criticized
Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This nation does not want four more years of Clinton-Gore,''
he told a rally in Charleston, W.Va. ``This nation wants somebody
who will restore the military strength of the United States of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail:
eric(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
