<HEADER>
A9866 &Cx1f; tta-z
u e BC-OPERA-DUO-NYT &LR;      08-01 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-DUO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALENT _ AND ROMANCE _ CATAPULTING EUROPEAN OPERA DUO INTO
LIMELIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN ROCKWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIX-EN-PROVENCE, France _ Until last month, the names of the
young opera singers Marijana Mijanovic and Kresimir Spicer were
virtually unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they are ``the couple of the summer,'' according to the
Marseille newspaper La Provence. That is partly because of their
performances as Penelope and Ulysses in the new production of
Monteverdi's ``Ritorno d'Ulisse in Patria'' at the noted opera
festival here.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also because they are a real-life Romeo and Juliet:
she is Serbian, he is Croatian, and they live together in
Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Beaune, France, where they had
gone to sing in a concert performance of the opera, they seemed
determined not to exploit the drama of their relationship. Nor,
since they still must present their formal graduation recital this
fall at the Sweelinck Conservatory in Amsterdam, do they wish to be
prematurely compared to a better-known opera couple, the Romanian
soprano Angela Gheorghiu and the French tenor Roberto Alagna. Yet
their gifts may be comparable, and their lives are the stuff of
high operatic drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a great story,'' said Spicer, 24, with boyish
enthusiasm. Through different routes, both arrived in Amsterdam in
1994: he from Slavonski Brod via Zagreb, a mid-size Croatian
industrial city, she from Valjevo via Belgrade, a smaller,
central-Serbian town. They came to study with Cora Canne-Meijer, a
respected Dutch teacher.
</P>
<P>
   He is the son of a mid-level factory worker, although he added
that his family was rich until World War II. Her father is a highly
placed engineer and inventor.
</P>
<P>
   They met at the height of the tension, not to say outright
hatred, between Serbs and Croats. The Serbs had seized control of
30 percent of Croatia in 1991, and it was not until 1995 that the
Croats could drive them out. Interethnic romantic relationships,
common enough before the hostilities, had become nearly
unthinkable, although Spicer and Mijanovic (his name is pronounced
KRE-shi-meer SHPIT-zer; hers, Mar-YAN-a Mee-YAN-o-vich) said that
in their circles at home, casual relations were not quite so
fraught. Each came to Amsterdam separately: he with the aid of a
Dutchman who visited Croatia, bringing humanitarian aid; she after
an aunt in the Netherlands said she could live at her house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before our first group class in the fall,'' Spicer recalled,
``our teacher called up and said, `There is student in the class,
and there may be a problem: she is Serbian.' I said, `There is no
problem.' She had called Marijana and warned her, too. We spoke
English in class, but I greeted her in our language. We were
friends right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, the Romeo and Juliet parallel developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was quite a bad time in our country, a strange time,''
Mijanovic, now 28, recalled in an understatement. ``Both Kresha and
I were different then. Your minds are closed; you're constantly
bombarded with media. Then you come outside, and you realize there
is something else. This boy opened the door and he spoke my own
language.''
</P>
<P>
   Their friendship did not flower into love at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took time, for both of us,'' Mijanovic explained. ``In that
first year, there was no question that I was even going to think
about him as a boyfriend.'' The two began living together in 1996,
but marriage is still difficult to contemplate. While they each
visit their families regularly, they have not traveled home
together, let alone sung in Croatia or Yugoslavia. ``Until this
year, it was not quite safe,'' she said simply.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had quite a few problems and crises at first,'' Mijanovic
continued. ``The two families have still not met. But they accepted
our relationship. Now, if we broke up, both families would be
surprised. But marriage _ it's still a bit too complicated at this
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not just their personal drama, but also their professional
artistry that has captivated the operatic world. Le Monde called
them ``revelations.''
</P>
<P>
   Mijanovic is a commanding low mezzo with a spectral stage
presence that made the sometimes mopey Penelope, waiting for years
for the return of her husband from the Trojan War, into the
haunting figure Monteverdi intended: the Frankfurter Allgemeine
Zeitung praised her ``secret, strange, distant aura.''
</P>
<P>
   Spicer is a heroic tenor in the making _ a young Jon Vickers,
said Eva Wagner-Pasquier, the festival's artistic adviser and a
leading candidate to take over her great-grandfather's Bayreuth
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner-Pasquier added that the couple had been inundated with
offers from agents and opera-house managers, but that Mijanovic and
Spicer seemed sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a big fuss now,'' Mijanovic said. ``We are already
overburdened by offers. They say this role is good for you, and
that role is good for you. But we are very realistic people. When
you come from our country and have lived what we've lived through,
you become very down to earth.''
</P>
<P>
   As the elder of the pair, Mijanovic seems the more fully formed
artist, one whose rich low mezzo is likely to grow in strength and
assertion over the years. Right know, she is concentrating on the
Baroque and Handel, although she and Spicer recently sang Mahler's
Romantic ``Das Klagende Lied'' in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult, for a young singer,'' she said. ``We love
different kinds of music; we don't like to put ourselves in a
Fach,'' she added, using the operatic term for vocal category.
Although she and Spicer have undertaken a joint recital tour, her
heart is clearly set on opera. ``It's not just voice and
musicianship, but something else: you can share yourself with your
audience, and I love that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner-Pasquier was not alone in noting a kinship between Spicer
and Vickers in his youth. Like Vickers, the great Canadian tenor of
the 1960s and '70s, Spicer has a voice that is baritonally
anchored, with ringing high notes that drop to soft (yet always
tonally sustained) quiet passages, and a complex, even
idiosyncratic way of phrasing. But while Spicer is being offered
parts like the title role in ``The Tales of Hoffmann'' and Rodolfo
in ``La Boheme,'' with maybe Wagner down the line, he is proceeding
almost as cautiously as the notoriously cautious Vickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voice grows all the time,'' he said, objectifying his
instrument in the time-honored manner of singers. ``When I sing an
aria now after singing it a year ago, it's completely different. My
brother bought the first Three Tenors record for me, and I could
always sing all the top notes. When I first started with Cora
Canne-Meijer, though, she wondered if I was really a heroic
baritone. But every year, I get one more high note.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the couple said they look forward to pairings like
Carmen and Don Jose or even Kundry and Parsifal, they are prepared
for separate engagements as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would love to sing together, but we know it will not always
be possible,'' Spicer said. The ``Ulisse'' production here is
finished for the summer, and the couple have no recordings (a duet
CD may be in the works), but curious opera lovers will be able to
hear them in several productions of ``Ulisse'' in Europe next
season, and most likely at the Brooklyn Academy of Music next
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as their career opportunities abound, attention keeps
circling back to the drama of their personal relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand why people look at us in this way,'' Mijanovic
said. ``But it doesn't say on our foreheads, `Serb,' and `Croat.'
If people like the fact that we are together, I don't have anything
against that. But after this interview, we don't want to speak
about it. I look at Kresha not as a Croat but as the man I love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
