<HEADER>
A9870 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHINA-AIDS-1030(2TAKE     08-01 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-AIDS-1030(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT INATTENTION FURTHERS SPREAD OF AIDS IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ During all the years that Yang Zhiyin was selling his
blood, he had never heard of AIDS. All he knew was that he was
desperately poor, and selling blood on the black market was what
farmers did in his village when they needed cash. For much of a
decade, Yang said, he rolled up his sleeve to the blood dealer's
needle ``many, many times.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those times, Yang, now 37, became infected with HIV, the
virus that causes AIDS. Because illegal blood rings often use
unsterile collection methods, poor peasants like Yang are routinely
exposed to blood-borne diseases, scientists say. And after Yang
contracted the virus, he presumably spread it unwittingly to dozens
of others, who for the most part still do not know that they are
infected _ or even that HIV exists.
</P>
<P>
   With the AIDS virus skipping silently through China, a number of
China's leading medical experts have begun to complain angrily that
the government has done too little to define the epidemic and to
prevent the virus' spread. Official inattention and the lack of a
national public education program have already allowed HIV to go
from a fairly rare condition among intravenous drug users in 1990,
to a rapidly growing problem that now infects as many as 600,000
Chinese, the scientists say. And in another 10 years, they warn,
China will have one of the world's largest populations of HIV
carriers, unless the government takes action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spread of AIDS is accelerating rapidly and we face the
prospect of remaining inert against the threat,'' states an
extraordinarily blunt report by a committee of eminent experts that
was sent to China's leaders earlier this year. ``Owing to
government indifference, AIDS prevention and control is gravely
ineffective.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, there has been no national screening for HIV, so that
the government has little idea of how and where the disease is
spreading, for example. The total budget for AIDS prevention last
year was under $2 million _ far less than those of much smaller
countries like Vietnam and Thailand. Local officials often refuse
to screen for the virus, for fear high rates will reflect badly on
their governance. In many cities, billboards promoting AIDS
awareness or prevention through condoms have lasted only days
before they were declared ``indecent'' and destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've reached the point that if we don't wake up, it will be a
national disaster,'' said Zeng Yi, a leading AIDS researcher who
was on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over how China should handle AIDS generally pits
government scientists concerned with a simmering health epidemic
against socially conservative propaganda, education and health
officials, guardians of China's image and its moral values. The
scientists protest that these conservatives have stymied their
efforts to confront the disease, preventing frank discussions of
sex and drug addiction, for example, and even attempting to
camouflage China's HIV problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central government doesn't seem to realize how serious
this is,'' said Qiu Renzong, a bioethicist at the Chinese Academy
of Social Sciences, with clear exasperation. ``We have not yet had
an effective risk-reduction strategy, because some departments are
very conservative. They think chastity is more important than
condom use. They say that the only way to prevent HIV transmission
is to rely on China's traditional values.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee members like professor Qiu say they intended their
report to be a jarring wake-up call _ arguing for national AIDS
education, condom use and needle exchanges for drugs addicts, for
example. And some have been encouraged by the government's initial
response: appointing Deputy Prime Minister Li Lanqing to oversee
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the government attitude is changing,'' said Zeng,
hopefully.
</P>
<P>
   But others remain skeptical: ``Yes, there's been big progress,
but compared to the speed at which HIV is spreading it's not
enough,'' said Wan Yanhai, a former government health worker, who
said he was fired in the mid-1990s for speaking too frankly about
HIV. ``Part of the reason there hasn't been a survey is that they
don't want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there are now 17,000 people known to carry the AIDS
virus in China, government officials say that the real figure is
probably closer to 500,000 or 600,000. The number is still small
compared to China's overall population, which exceeds 1.2 billion,
but scientists say rates are extraordinarily high in some groups
and in some locations. They add that the number of cases is now
growing by 30 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials say that intravenous drug users probably
account for more than 70 percent of the HIV in the country. Zeng
and many other experts believe that blood sellers like Yang may
well be the second-largest group.
</P>
<P>
   But the first estimate may be skewed because it is based on the
forced testing of drug addicts under arrest. And there is almost no
hard information on blood sales, which are officially banned.
Prostitutes and gay men are also considered at high risk.
</P>
<P>
   These limited surveys have found extremely high rates in some
localized populations: In the early 1990s more than 80 percent of
drug addicts arrested near the Myanmar border were infected, Zeng
said. More recently, a survey in Henan found rates as high as 16
per cent in locales where illegal blood selling was common _ until
local officials blocked further testing.
</P>
<P>
   But it is difficult to extrapolate from these pockets of high
infection to the larger population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we haven't done the screening that needs to be done,
we don't really know the size of the problem,'' said Zeng. ``That
means that when the government confronts it, they think the
problem's not too big.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wan said, some of the more worrisome data are often
kept secret. He noted that outbreaks of HIV in the countryside are
not publicized and that drug addicts are not always told that they
are HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people still feel quite safe _ they think HIV is a
disease of foreigners,'' said Wan, who now runs a Web site about
HIV.
</P>
<P>
   The true picture will never be clear without very aggressive
government intervention, experts said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Individuals from high-risk groups have little incentive to be
tested since there is no treatment for the disease in China.
Western treatments for AIDS are expensive and not licensed for use
in China, and traditional medicines have not proved effective.
</P>
<P>
   Also, although laws prohibit discrimination against people with
HIV, harassment is the rule, prompting most to hide their disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``HIV is like having leprosy in the 1930s,'' said Yang, the
former blood seller who contracted the virus, and who said he would
only speak if his home province was not identified. ``I have only
told my immediate family.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the greatest obstacle is that local officials do not
want to admit that prostitution, drug abuse or blood selling are
occurring on their watch. ``Even many provincial officials have no
idea how many HIV-infected individuals are in their province _ and
they don't want doctors to come and do the tests'' said Qiu.
</P>
<P>
   They are particularly resistant to surveys of blood sellers,
scientists say, since the practice was outlawed in 1997. Still,
blood sales continue and government scientists estimate there are 5
million Chinese who regularly provide blood for pay.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say that HIV in this group is probably very high because
of the collection methods commonly used by the blood gangs, who buy
the blood from farmers and then sell it to individual patients or
small-town doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, blood is collected from a number of peasants with the
same blood type at one time. The blood is then pooled and spun down
to separate out the components needed for medical use, and the
remainder is divided up and re-infused into the original donors. In
this way, people like Yang are exposed to the blood of six to 12
others every time they sell, experts say. Wan said that in one
preliminary survey in Shanxi Province, 132 of 134 people with HIV
were found to be blood sellers.
</P>
<P>
   The risk to hospitalized patients is probably not great, Zeng
said, because hospitals generally screen blood products for the
virus _ although in emergencies or in rural hospitals and clinics,
there is evidence that the system can break down.
</P>
<P>
   Song Pengfei, 18, one of the few AIDS patients in China who has
spoken out about the difficulties of living with the disease, was
infected during emergency surgery at a rural hospital after his
family purchased a transfusion from a blood gang in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   While a number of researchers and even government bureaus have
attempted projects to educate Chinese about HIV, these are often
privately funded and nationwide efforts have been hampered by lack
of money and a strong puritanical streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``When HIV became a problem in the West, there were huge
education campaigns,'' said Zeng, who has himself paid for and
organized a large traveling scientific exhibition on HIV. ``We talk
about it one day a year _ on Dec. 1 _ International AIDS Day. That
is not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Dec. 1, for example, the State Family Planning Commission
unveiled new television advertisements promoting the use of condoms
to thwart HIV. By the next day they were ordered off the air by the
State Administration for Industry and Commerce, which said they
violated a law against advertising sex-related products.
</P>
<P>
   In June, a billboard advocating condom use in Wuhan was ordered
removed just 22 hours after it was posted. Bus ads in Guangzhou
last year met with a similar fate. And although condoms are widely
available in drug stores in Beijing and Shanghai, an effort to
install machines on university campuses was abandoned after intense
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you promote condoms among youth, it would lead to a great
deal of sexual license and abandonment of sexual morality,'' said
Zhu Qi, a government consultant who believes that the best answer
to HIV is chastity. ``So this is not just about AIDS, it's about
our overall cultural and spiritual development.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an attitude that exasperates Qiu.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an old Chinese saying,'' he said. ``People don't shed
tears until they see the coffin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
