u a BC-CALIF-POWER-CRISIS-NY     08-01 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POWER-CRISIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT WAVE IN CALIFORNIA BRINGS STATE CLOSE TO DECLARING POWER
EMERGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A lingering heat wave throughout the West drove
demand for electric power in California to near-record levels on
Tuesday and brought the state close to a full-scale power emergency
that could have prompted rolling blackouts as power administrators
sought to keep the state's giant, overburdened electricity grid
from crashing completely.
</P>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, the California Independent System
Operator, which controls about 75 percent of the state's electric
power grid on behalf of private utilities, declared a statewide
Stage Two emergency at midday. In a Stage Two emergency, power is
curtailed to commercial and industrial users who receive discounted
power rates in exchange for agreeing to shut down when asked to do
so in times of high demand.
</P>
<P>
   Officials warned that a Stage Three emergency, which has never
before been declared, was possible because a stubborn high-pressure
system stretching from Mexico to Canada had kept temperatures so
high that air-conditioning systems were working harder and longer
throughout the entire region. In a Stage Three alert, ``rotating
blackouts'' to small portions of communities are imposed to keep
the overall system up and running.
</P>
<P>
   In California, which began deregulating the electric power
industry four years ago, and around the nation, a decade of
economic growth and under-investment in new power plants has left
power reserves at the lowest levels in decades. Early on Tuesday,
officials warned that overall demand in California was expected to
exceed 46,245 megawatts, breaking the previous record of 45,884
megawatts set just last year.
</P>
<P>
   But at 3:30 p.m., the system was handling 43,400 megawatts, and
had already cut off about 1,800 megawatts to industrial users as
part of the Stage Two alert. That left the system with a reserve
capacity of about 3 percent more power than the demands on the
system. A Stage Three alert is automatically called if reserves
fall below 1.5 percent. Because the heat wave is so widespread,
California has been unable to import enough power from other
states.
</P>
<P>
   If a Stage Three event works as planned, ``We'd have to impose
rotating outages to small portions of communities across all our
service area,'' said Tom Boyd, a spokesman for Southern California
Edison, which supplies power over 50,000 square miles in Central
and Southern California, including much of suburban Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles itself, the city's municipal utility, the
venerable Department of Water and Power, which built the Owens
Valley aqueduct that allowed the growth of the modern city,
controls its own independent electric power source and was not
expected to be affected by the statewide alert.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
