<HEADER>
A9880 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-CHENEY-ART-NYT     08-01 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CHENEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY, A VETERAN OF PUBLIC LIFE, SEEMS UNEASY AT CENTER STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo  NYT13  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By   ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ At a breakfast on Monday for Wyoming's delegates
to the Republican National Convention here, Dick Cheney looked
uneasy when it came time to pose for a photograph with the crowd
from his home state.
</P>
<P>
   When the group burst into a rousing rendition of ``Ragtime
Cowboy Joe,'' the University of Wyoming fight song, everyone
reveled in the pageantry. Everyone, that is, except Cheney, who sat
stiff and silent in the front row, a pained smile fixed on his
face.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, 59, has lived in the bubble of public life for more than
a quarter-century, as White House chief of staff, congressman and
secretary of defense. He presided over the military in the Persian
Gulf war in 1991. But he has not run for office since 1988, in his
last bid for re-election as Wyoming's lone House member. As Gov.
George W. Bush's running mate, he is in many ways a neophyte on the
national campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   He seems utterly at ease giving short, serious speeches to
crowds, and fielding searing political line drives from Sunday
television talk show hosts. But give him a crowd and a rope line,
and Cheney rushes through, visibly relieved when he's finished.
Give him a bank of television cameras at a campaign rally, and he
looks the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick did fine tonight, and he'll get better,'' Gov. Tom Ridge
of Pennsylvania said after Cheney's four-minute speech at his debut
rally on Sunday, a well-received, if sober, recitation of his
conservative record and the campaign's central themes. ``Remember,
Dick has not been on the political stump in a long, long time, and
like everything else, he'll get into a rhythm,'' Ridge said.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates here, who like Cheney are more conservative than most
registered Republicans, almost universally applaud his selection,
more for bringing sure-footed experience to the ticket than any
campaign sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not bouncing up and down about Cheney, but sometimes
substance is better than show,'' said Bill Caster, a commissioner
in New Hanover County, N.C., and Republican delegate.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bush has gently poked fun at his partner's dry campaign
style, but he continues to praise Cheney and brags that picking him
as a running mate was a ``presidential decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bush campaign advisers argue that vice presidents don't
need to be galvanizing campaign figures. Jack Kemp, for example,
was supposed to jazz up Sen. Bob Dole's lagging campaign in 1996,
but it made no difference. So with The Secretary _ as many campaign
aides call Cheney _ preparing to give the speech of his life to the
convention on Wednesday night, the Bush camp's strategy has been to
let Cheney be Cheney, with a few tweaks here and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man of Secretary Cheney's stature and experience came here
prepared,'' said a Bush campaign spokesman, Ari Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush advisers conceded that no one planned or anticipated
that Cheney would spend much of his week defending his voting
record in Congress after appearing on last Sunday's talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the Cheney quotes raised some eyebrows among swing
voters,'' said Frank Luntz, a Republican pollster. ``Votes that
played well in the West didn't go over well in the Philadelphia
suburbs.''
</P>
<P>
   The same concerns about Cheney's votes against the Head Start
education program and a ban on armor-piercing bullets gave other
Republicans pause. ``There are a number of votes that seem strange,
but I try to put them in perspective with the times and the
circumstances,'' said Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart, one of Miami's two
Cuban-American House members.
</P>
<P>
   Bush advisers played down the controversy. Tom Rath, a
Republican National committee member from New Hampshire who advises
the campaign, said: ``The Democrats' attempts to make Cheney a
scary figure are not going to work, because he's not a scary
figure. The base is very content with him, and if the base is
content, then you can work on the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, the lone black Republican in
Congress, urged Cheney not to appear to pander to individual
groups. ``My advice to Dick Cheney is just to continue doing what
he's been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegates agree that Cheney's seriousness is his biggest asset.
``He isn't a snake-charmer by any means, but he'll bring a
stabilizing force,'' said Pat Cross, 68, a Republican delegate from
La Quinta, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Cheney hasn't said much about any of this. Since
arriving here on Sunday, he has kept a low profile and has seemed a
little uneasy with all the adulation that is stock fare at a
political convention. He allowed himself to beam just a bit on
Monday night when his old friend and ally, Gen. Colin L. Powell,
the former chairman of the joint chiefs of staff, praised him
lavishly from the speaker's podium.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney paid a private visit today to former President Gerald
Ford, who brought him to the White House, and his wife, Betty. He
later attended a lunch honoring House Speaker Dennis Hastert, where
he told the 1,000 attendees that running for vice president ``was
not an assignment I volunteered for'' but one that he accepted
because ``it was an important thing to do for the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
