<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9885 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-ELECTRICPOWER0802-COX     08-01 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRICPOWER0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FPL competitors unfazed by word of Entergy mega-deal
 &HT;    By Deborah Circelli
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Two out-of-state electric companies
expect heightened competition from the goliath utility that would
result from FPL Group's deal for Entergy Corp., but that isn't
dissuading them from wanting to set up shop in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't change our mind to come there. We are still very
interested in meeting the needs of Florida,'' said Rick Rhodes,
spokesman for Duke Energy of Charlotte, N.C., which along with
Dallas-based Panda Energy has unsuccessfully tried to build power
plants in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger is just an example of how quickly things are
moving in our industry,'' Rhodes said. ``Competition is going to
increase as there continues to be a need for additional electricity
capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   Juno Beach-based FPL Group announced Monday that it intends to
buy New Orleans-based Entergy in a $13.9 billion deal that would
create the nation's largest utility, serving 6.3 million retail
customers in Florida, Arkansas, Louisiana, Mississippi and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is subject to shareholder, regional and federal
approvals.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say FPL would benefit from Entergy's skills dealing
with deregulated retail environments in Texas and Arkansas. In
those states, power companies compete for customers. FPL and other
Florida power companies are government-regulated monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be able to learn from their experiences, and they will
be able to learn from ours,'' said Bill Swank, a spokesman for FPL.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush has appointed a commission to study the power
business in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Panda Energy officials hope FPL's deal will make it more
receptive to opening Florida to competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, this will bring further deregulation enlightenment
to the state,'' said Peggy Striegel, spokeswoman for Panda.
</P>
<P>
   Panda and Duke want to build so-called wholesale plants near
Fort Pierce and Port St. Lucie. Such plants sell power to other
utilities. But they have been blocked by FPL and other Florida
utilities. Panda and Duke, as well as other interested companies,
are waiting to see whether the state Supreme Court will grant a
rehearing on its April decision that state law doesn't allow
wholesale plants.
</P>
<P>
   The FPL-Entergy combination, valued at $27 billion, with more
than 48,000 megawatts of capacity, would be a strong competitor to
Atlanta-based Southern Co., which serves 3.9 million retail
customers in Georgia, Alabama, Mississippi and the Florida
Panhandle. But a Southern spokesman said Tuesday that FPL's deal
isn't costing the company any sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see it as a threat,'' said Mike Tyndall. ``We have a
very focused growth strategy we are implementing. This doesn't
change that strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but Southern's territory would be flanked by the
combined FPL-Entergy.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its size, the combined company, which has not been
named, would have more leverage to keep its suppliers' prices down
_ which could help keep customer rates low and make it attractive
in competitive markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This combination will definitely make them one of the big
players in the South,'' said Marybeth Flater, vice president of
utility research at Dresdner Kleinwort Benson in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   William Liggett, an analyst with the U.S. Energy Information
Administration, said increased competition has spurred utilities to
cut costs and consolidate. Since 1992, investor-owned electric
utilities have been involved in 26 consolidations, and 16 more are
pending, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   FPL's stock (NYSE: FPL) rebounded Tuesday, to close up $2.06 to
$50.31 a share. After the deal was announced Monday, the stock
dropped to $48.25, down from Friday's close of $52.81. Entergy's
stock (NYSE: ETR) also rebounded Tuesday, gaining $2.88 to close at
$30.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of uncertainty whether it will get approved, so
as long as this merger is pending, FPL will probably be a flat
stock,'' said Zach Wagner, energy analyst for Edward Jones in St.
Louis, which has downgraded the stock to a hold.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's Investors Service announced Tuesday it placed the
securities of FPL Group Capital and FPL under review for possible
downgrade while it determines whether FPL's Florida Power &AMP; Light
subsidiary will be able to maintain ``strong cash flow'' under the
new company. The service also said it was changing the ratings
outlook for Entergy's six subsidiaries to positive from stable.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
