r s BC-FBC-DUKE0802-COX     08-01 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-DUKE0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duke bedeviled by a lack of depth
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. - Carl Franks saw life from the other side of the
tracks last year, and he didn't like it.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, an assistant to Steve Spurrier since 1987, helped coach
winning football teams 12 years in a row. He was offensive
coordinator at Florida for four years before taking the head job at
his alma mater, Duke, last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blue Devils stumbled to a 3-8 record in Franks' debut
season as a head coach. Franks' brought his own version of
Florida's fun-and-gun offense to Duke, but it didn't turn out being
much fun.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils threw for 2,584 yards but completed only 46.6
percent of their passes. Meanwhile, the rushing game was pathetic,
just 811 yards in 11 games, an average of 73.7 per game.
</P>
<P>
   But Franks isn't complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew exactly what I was getting into,'' he said. ``If
everything was perfect, the job wouldn't have been available. As I
remember, Ohio State and Michigan weren't offering. This was my
shot, and I took it.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks is upbeat about the 2000 season. He will have seven
starters returning on offense, led by senior quarterback Spencer
Romine. When Romine, a medical student with a 3.9 grade-point
average, was healthy, he was outstanding. He threw for 1,638 yards
and six touchdowns in seven games. The trouble was, he missed four
games because of injury. Romine has yet to make it through a season
without injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have a very good track record of staying healthy,''
Franks said. ``I just hope we don't have to play three quarterbacks
again this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils lost both of their starting wide receivers from
last year. Scottie Montgomery and Richmond Flowers caught 93 passes
between them, so Duke will be inexperienced at wideout. ``It's
tough to run a passing game with question marks at receivers,''
Franks said.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Moore, who caught 11 passes last year for 113 yards, is
listed as one starter, and Ben Erdeljac, who had 19 receptions for
268 yards, is the other. Duane Epperson, the Devils' leading rusher
with 324 yards in nine games, returns at tailback.
</P>
<P>
   Duke finished last in the ACC in total defense and last in
scoring defense, allowing 422.3 yards and 33.0 points per game.
Eight starters from that unit graduated and, of the 11 starters on
the depth chart, eight are underclassmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the mistakes we made last year is we didn't play enough
guys on defense,'' Franks said. ``This year, everybody knows
they're going to get to play more.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks points to the fact that the Blue Devils had a chance to
win several other games. They lost two in overtime and played a
potent Georgia Tech team well in losing 38-31. Their three wins
were all conferenc they beat Maryland, Virginia and Wake Forest,
and the latter two were bowl teams.
</P>
<P>
   But with an out-of-conference schedule that features East
Carolina, Northwestern and Vanderbilt, Duke might have a tough time
winning three this season.
</P>
<P>
   DUKE
</P>
<P>
   -Location: Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   -Enrollment: 6,264.
</P>
<P>
   -Coach: Carl Franks, 3-8 in one year at Duke.
</P>
<P>
   -Nickname: Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   -Stadium (capacity): Wallace Wade Stadium (33,941).
</P>
<P>
   -All-time record: 434-368-31.
</P>
<P>
   -Conference championships (number of titles, title years): Seven
_ 1953, 1954, 1955, 1960, 1961, 1962, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   -1999 record (overall, conference): 3-8 overall, 3-5 ACC
</P>
<P>
   -Schedule: Sept. 2: East Carolina; Sept. 9: at Northwestern;
Sept. 16: Virginia; Sept. 23: at Vanderbilt; Sept. 30: Clemson;
Oct. 14: at Florida State; Oct. 21: at Georgia Tech; Oct. 28:
Maryland; Nov. 4: at Wake Forest; Nov. 11: at N.C. State; Nov. 18:
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
