<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9891 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-BUSH-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      08-01 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUSH-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: THE CAMPAIGN GETS PERSONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The former president had been biting his tongue,
sacrificing his anger to his heir's ambitions. The current
president had been rocking on his heels, letting his disciple fight
his own battles.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with a volley of words that unearthed genuine emotion
amid a contrived spectacle, two leaders who had pledged to let the
2000 election be about the future are demonstrating how much of it
is about the past _ about lingering animosities, dueling legacies,
competing claims to vindication and rivals with the names Bush and
Clinton, not Bush and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview broadcast on NBC's ``Today'' show Tuesday
morning, former President Bush put President Clinton on warning,
telling him that if he persisted in belittling Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, the former president's eldest son, he would be sorry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tempted to get off the reservation,'' Bush told Jamie
Gangel, as he took at least a half-step across the line. ``But I'll
tell you what I'm going to do: I'm going to wait a month. Now, you
give me a call; I'll give you the home number.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And if he continues that,'' he went on, referring to the
president who usurped him, ``I'm going to tell the nation what I
think about him as a human being and a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was responding to a swipe that Clinton had taken at the
Texas governor last week, when Clinton said that ``the message of
the Bush campaign is just that, `How bad could I be? I've been
governor of Texas, my daddy was president.'''
</P>
<P>
   But President Bush was also proving how thoroughly he had come
to hover over this race in the last few weeks, pulled back into it
by those who think his memory will do them good and by those who
think his memory will do their opponent harm.
</P>
<P>
   His son's choice of Dick Cheney, the former defense secretary,
as a running mate seemed to mark a kind of turning point in the
Texas governor's campaign. While Gov. Bush had for months kept his
father at a political distance, he now seems to be hugging him
tight. In interviews and conversations with reporters in the days
after he formally announced the selection of Cheney, Gov. Bush
gushed and gushed about Dad.
</P>
<P>
   And Dad himself loped back into the picture, sitting down with
Gangel and sitting front and center at the convention on Monday
night. Nearby was Cheney, who served in his administration. Up on
stage was retired Gen. Colin Powell, another member of the Beltway
brigade who waged the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, too, has unleashed himself. To rally the Democratic
faithful at fund-raisers over the last few weeks, he has repeatedly
denigrated the man who not only preceded him in the Oval Office
but, as Clinton tells it, left America in shambles in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country was in the ditch,'' Clinton said in Boston on
Friday. ``And the politics of Washington, D.C., was like watching,
I don't know, `Wayne's World' or something to most of us who lived
out here in the world, the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   This is precisely the juncture in a presidential election when
each man's heir is supposed to be coming into his own. But the two
presidents are overshadowing the process by giving newly candid,
newly bracing glimpses into how much they dislike each other, an
antipathy that frames how their would-be successors see each other
and sell themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the prime-time hour of the first night of the
Republican convention here was largely about Clinton, even though
no one uttered his name.
</P>
<P>
   When Laura Bush, the Texas governor's wife, talked about all the
parents who tell her husband that they want their children to be
able ``to respect the president of the United States,'' the ghost
in that sentence was Clinton, and he was plenty visible to members
of the audience, who cheered wildly.
</P>
<P>
   When Powell said that Gov. Bush ``comes from a family with a
generations-long tradition of public service'' and would ``bring
character and integrity to the Oval Office,'' the obvious point of
contrast was Clinton, not Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Texas governor, campaigning in West Virginia and
Pennsylvania, went further and, like his father, took Clinton on
directly, saying that the president's recent insults showed that he
was ``so desperate to have his legacy intact by getting Al Gore
elected, he'll say anything.'' The subject, yet again, was not a
would-be president's agenda but a will-have-been president's
self-conscious place in history.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides expressed delight at the turn of events, saying
that President Bush's Today show interview rooted out the
bitterness beneath all the sweetness of the convention, disrupted
the intricate choreography and cast the Texas governor as too
feeble to fend for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, the whole thing tells people a lot about George
Jr.,'' said Mark Fabiani, a spokesman for the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush's advisers and supporters agree that the elder Bush is
a window into the younger one, but they have a different take on
what it shows: carefully nurtured values of honesty and integrity.
</P>
<P>
   And they seem to be betting, more and more, that voters will
share that vision: The convention Tuesday night featured a video
tribute to the former president, prominently showcasing his face
and voice. Not so long ago, his eldest son's stump speeches had
only the most oblique reference to him, a line about the Texas
governor being the beneficiary of ``some pretty good training'' for
the office he was seeking.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican strategist said that as soon as the Texas
governor hooked up with Cheney, there could no longer be any
pretense that President Bush was not a part of his political
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican official who sometimes advises the Bush campaign
said that the Texas governor had reached a point in his campaign
where he had proved his mettle, and that he could now acknowledge
his parents more openly. Polls have shown that a sizable majority
of voters have favorable opinions of the former president and the
former first lady.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
