<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9892 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-AMERICAN-REVIEW-SF     08-01 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AMERICAN-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOLERS GET THE REALITY TREATMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At this rate, we'll all end up living in little TV communes,
videotaping ourselves and hoping we're good enough for an audience.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's ``American High'' serves up the latest batch of
common-folk stars Wednesday, this time high school kids in suburban
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar-nominated filmmaker R.J. Cutler (``The War Room'') spent
the 1999-2000 school year supervising two film crews at Highland
Park High School as they chronicled the tumultuous lives of 14
teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   The kids also got a chance to be auteurs, taping themselves in
``video diaries'' to supplement Cutler's footage.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the first and most pungent impression is made by
the most outspoken and troubled teen in the group, Morgan Moss.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, 17 when the school year began, has bedeviled his parents
since infancy _ he calls them ``pricks'' after one family flareup _
and he opens Wednesday night's premiere with a provocative,
profanity-laced tirade.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are years that you are supposed to go (bleeping) wild,
blame it all on your parents or society, not have to suffer
consequences, have unprotected sex, go do drugs, drink alcohol,
watch porno, rent porno movies, get porno magazines,'' he riffs
into his camcorder.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly Andy Hardy planning a backyard carnival and
struggling to please his stern ol' dad, Judge James Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Porno, porno, porno,'' Morgan continues. ``Do whatever the
hell you want. Go pick fights, stay out all night ...''
</P>
<P>
   And then: ``These are your teen years. And what are you sitting
at home having to do? Homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Aha. After busting out of the opening credits like a runaway
truck, Morgan reveals a softer side by night's end. He finds
contentment working with disabled children. Maybe he won't become a
comedian or movie star after all; maybe he'll end up a
special-education teacher and ``become the people that I dread _ a
teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutler's early focus is also on a gay senior, Brad, awash in a
heterosexual world on Chicago's North Shore; Brad's best friend
Robby, the quiet and reassuringly sensitive captain of the lacrosse
and soccer teams; Robby's younger girlfriend Sarah, who muses that
``I just turned 17 and I've already found the love of my life'';
and Kaytee, a sparrowish senior who writes and trills humorous love
songs.
</P>
<P>
   It's mostly a get-acquainted premiere. But Wednesday's hour, the
first show in a seven-week run, does eventually revolve around
eternal teenage themes _ fears, fun and the urgent quest for
identity.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan fears he'll fail to make a splash in the larger world.
Sarah fears she'll lose Robby when he leaves for college. Brad
fears sexual isolation. Anna, a dark-haired beauty, fears she'll
never find a boyfriend. Mike, who calls himself ``Kiwi,'' is a
football star who fears missing field goals.
</P>
<P>
   So ``American High'' pulsates with the painful self-awareness of
late adolescence. Morgan's ``porno, porno, porno'' outburst may
shock, but some things don't change. It's Kiwi, I think, who
reviews his countenance in the mirror one morning and mutters that
``a pimple ruins the day in a teenager's life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American High'' probably won't get the buzz that attends CBS'
contrived ``reality'' contests this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But after succumbing to the TV temptation to smack viewers in
the face to capture their attention, Cutler seems to be on course
to remind us that teenagers think big within confined
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Also that they feel big, aspire big, and are sometimes
dreadfully alone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
