<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-THROTTLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHIS DEATHS PROMPT NASCAR KILL-SWITCH RULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the deaths of Adam Petty and Kenny Irwin Jr. in similar
accidents eight weeks apart at New Hamsphire International
Speedway, NASCAR officials announced rule changes Tuesday to help
drivers avoid stuck throttles.
</P>
<P>
   While NASCAR has not found any conclusive evidence of the cause
of the two accidents, it was widely thought in the garage area that
Irwin's fatal crash July 7 was the result of a stuck throttle.
Likewise, that was thought to have been the problem in Petty's May
12 crash.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials instructed Winston Cup teams to install a stop
on the throttle assembly of their cars plus an engine-kill switch
on the steering wheel within reach of a driver's thumb.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are changes I can't see anybody disagreeing with,'' said
driver Jeremy Mayfield. ``They don't take anything away from the
race cars, they don't affect competition, but they can save you
from a pretty hard crash. You have to applaud NASCAR for taking
steps like these.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will this totally solve the problem of a throttle sticking?
Probably not, but this will give the driver something he can do to
help make it less of a problem if it comes up. I'd just as soon
never have it happen, but I feel a little better about the
consequences if it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Triplett, NASCAR's director of operations, said the safety
measures will take effect Thursday, when teams begin preparations
for Saturday's Brickyard 400 at Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to look at things, to go through things and talk
to people,'' said Triplett. ``It's a difficult thing to re-create
following an accident what happened because of damage to this piece
of the car and that piece of the car.''
</P>
<P>
   However, said Triplett, discussions with drivers, crew chiefs,
and owners brought a consensus on what changes to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``In trying to find something that was effective across the
board and comfortable across the board, these were the two areas
that could be done, and easily be done, before this weekend,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Petty, the 19-year-old son of Winston Cup driver Kyle Petty and
grandson of stock car legend Richard Petty, was killed during a
Busch Series practice at Loudon.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, 30, of Indianapolis, was killed during a Winston Cup
practice at the 1.058-mile oval, striking the wall in the same
corner where Petty died.
</P>
<P>
   Both drivers were said to have been traveling in excess of 150
miles per hour when they entered Turn 3 and were unable to
negotiate it.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Andrews, crew chief for driver Steve Park, said at the time
of Irwin's crash that a stuck throttle could have resulted from any
number of circumstances:
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be something on the floorboard, it could be from a
malfunction on the carburetor, it could be something in the air
cleaner. Several things could make a throttle stick; it doesn't
matter where you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Driver Ricky Rudd said he once experienced a similar problem _
but not at NHIS, where the track's configuration (long
straightaways that funnel into tight corners) leaves little room to
react to a stuck throttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had 'em stick before and it's not like there's a whole
lot a driver can do about it,'' Rudd said. ``If you get off the
gas, you might get the car settled, but it's still going wide open.
You've got to get your foot on the brake, and that's about all you
can do. But when the motor is wide open and you get on the brakes,
though, it doesn't slow you down a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mayfield, ``Let's face it, it's not how fast you go, it's
how fast you stop. If you can hit something at a slower speed,
that's got to be good. If you have more time when you're having
problems _ say you're aimed at the wall or something like that _ to
correct it a little bit, then this is a good thing. Even if you hit
at a better angle, then that's got to be good, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
