<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-NEGATIVE-CAMPAIGN     08-01 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-NEGATIVE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SAYS THEY'RE ABOVE NEGATIVE CAMPAIGNING, BUT NOT ABOVE
COMPLAINING ABOUT IT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ For all its focus on a nicer, blander image,
there is one thing the Bush campaign wants to be negative about _
negative campaigning from the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush complained about attacks on
Republican vice presidential nominee Dick Cheney ``coming out of
the bowels of the Democratic National Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   In Columbus, Ohio, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the prospective
Republican presidential nominee, said, ``Americans are sick and
tired of the politics of tearing people down.''
</P>
<P>
   In Charleston, W.Va., the governor said, ``This nation is
looking for an administration that will appeal to our better
angels, not our darker impulses. This nation does not want four
more years of Clinton-Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi told a youth
group at the Republican National Convention, ``We're not trashing
our opponents, we're not looking back.''
</P>
<P>
   And Monday night the prospective nominee's wife, Laura Bush,
told the convention her husband ``sets a tone that's positive and
constructive, a tone that is very different from the bitterness and
division that too often characterizes Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said this
consistent message was not derived from polls or focus groups, but
from the candidate's ``heart.''
</P>
<P>
   But a prominent Republican operative, Frank Luntz, said it
matched the strategy his focus groups dictated.
</P>
<P>
   Luntz said, ``Voters don't like political attack dogs, and they
have complained for two decades about the negativity of politics.''
Only now, he said, were they beginning to vote against sponsors of
negative ads. So, he added, ``Once you destroy the messenger, you
destroy his message.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged, however, that the first Democratic ad attacking
Cheney's voting record in the House over Head Start, the school
lunch program and the Clean Water Act seemed to work against Cheney
among independents.
</P>
<P>
   But Kathleen Hall Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg School for
Communication here at the University of Pennsylvania, said, ``I
think they misunderstand what the electorate believes to be
appropriate campaigning.'' She added, ``If the public believes it's
accurate, the likelihood is that because it's a low-key ad, the
public is likely to accept it as legitimate campaigning.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hart, a Democratic pollster, said the tactic of negative
campaigning against negative campaigning depended on the original
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes back to the charge. If you prove the charge is false,
then negative campaign against negative campaign is fine. But if
the charge is true and relevant, all the bellyaching and all the
campaigning cannot hide one's voting record.'' In this case, he
said, ``they are a squealing extra loud on something they have no
way of refuting.''
</P>
<P>
   But while his arguments matched the general line, there was a
singular intensity to former President Bush's comments, made on
NBC's Today show in an interview that was tape recorded late on
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He called the criticism of Cheney, his former secretary of
defense ``crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you going to say when you get a great, outstanding
choice like Cheney, who's widely respected?'' he continued.
``They've got a carping _ they've got a little minion sitting there
with their dark glasses, you know, digging up dirt on someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want that anymore. But let them try. Cheney's
much bigger than all that, more proven than all that. And if
something ever happened to George when they were elected, he'd make
an outstanding president of the United States. So I don't worry
about that opposition research crowd digging. `Hey, look what I
found,' some little nerd sitting there in the Democratic National
Committee. It doesn't make any difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fabiani, a spokesman for the Gore campaign, responded, ``It
tells you a lot about George junior that he has to send his father
out to defend himself.'' He said, ``Someone's record is a
legitimate issue. It's hardly improper to criticize someone's
record.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said that Bush was no innocent when it came to negative
campaigning, noting that his first defense of Cheney, was a hostile
comparison to President Clinton. Bush said of Cheney, ``He's a man
who understands what the definition of `is' is.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to Clinton's evasive testimony in August
1999, when prosecutors asked him whether he was lying in January of
that year when he denied there was any sex in his relationship with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   And while Bush's campaigning against what he calls
``Clinton-Gore'' is not blunt _ or as direct as the advertisements
about Cheney's votes or Bush's record on health care in Texas _
there is nothing deeply subtle about the governor's constant
pledge: ``When I put my hand on the Bible, I will swear to not only
uphold the laws of the land, I will swear to uphold the honor and
the dignity of the office to which I have been elected, so help me
God.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
