<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9898 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-DIARY-NYT &LR;      08-01 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DIARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVENTION DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX KUCZINSKY AND MATTHEW PURDY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the convention podium, Colin Powell launched a salvo at
monied special interests. On the street, the police massed loudly
in expectation of protesters against all manner of capitalistic
evils.
</P>
<P>
   But in elegant Rittenhouse Square, where lobbyists and
politicians gathered Tuesday afternoon, an eight-piece swing band
drowned out the noise, and white tents insured that the business of
business could carry on uninterrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of you can vote for me,'' a Senate candidate from Nevada
announced to the crowd during a break in the music, ``but your
checks will surely be welcomed.''
</P>
<P>
   Compassionate conservatism by night, liberal lobbying by day.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA-Palooza! was thrown by the financial services industry
to honor members of Congress who helped win a vote on increasing
retirement account limits. But it was like scads of other parties
and receptions given by those with policy interest (and money) and
those who seeking policy advice (and money).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give you six words why you should back me with your faith
and your financial support,'' Paul Rappaport announced confidently.
``I'm running against Paul Sarbanes.'' No rolls of coins came
flying his way, but he said his appeal to help defeat Maryland's
veteran Democratic senator has struck a chord at other receptions
he's gone to this week. ``People are just handing me checks,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In his convention speech Monday night, Powell contrasted some
Republicans' criticism of affirmative action ``that helped a few
thousands black kids'' with their silence on ``affirmative action
for lobbyists who load our federal tax codes with preferences for
special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists bravely brushed off the flesh wounds. ``It was a nice
rhetorical flourish,'' said Steve Bartlett, the president of the
Financial Services Roundtable. ``But it's mixing two issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Various business representatives pointed out that raising IRA
limits was supported by legislators in both parties and by millions
of working people around the country. ``I don't believe I represent
a special interest,'' said Bruce Thompson, a Merrill Lynch vice
president for government relations. His company did sponsor a few
other parties this week, not to mention its contribution to the
Philadelphia host committee organizing the convention.
</P>
<P>
   One of those parties it helped organize honored the House
commerce committee ``which just happens to have jurisdiction over
the financial services industry,'' he said. ``Just as an aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Asides aside, none of the lobbyists were willing to take on
Powell, by name. ``I'm not here to get any glory,'' explained one
lobbyist. Not that any was going around.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Schlafly, the high priestess of the right wing and the
anti-abortion movement, has been to every Republican convention
since the last one in Philadelphia in 1952. Boy, were they a sight
better in the old days, she says. This one is a snoozefest,
according to Schlafly, looking trim and ready for action at 75,
wearing plastic pearls the size of gumballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is boring, boring, boring,'' she complained over coffee
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1952, Eisenhower was seven or eight votes away from the
nomination. No one knew who the vice president was going to be. It
was terribly exciting. There were floor fights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This ... '' she sighed, waving her hands dismissively.
</P>
<P>
   As that was not bad enough, she said, convention hall security
confiscated a set of knitting needles two days ago from Gail
Ruzicka, a staff member for Schlafly's Republican National
Committee For Life, had her knitting confiscated two days ago.
Security guards worried the needles were dangerous, Schlafly said.
``So they snapped them in half and ruined her knitting,'' Schlafly
complained.
</P>
<P>
   Dissent is so rarely heard among the Republican delegates that
you would think it's barred by local ordinance, both inside and
outside the convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates have each been given written instructions to stick
to happy talk when speaking to reporters. The mandate is not to
attack anyone, even Al Gore, and to relentlessly praise George W.
Bush's talents as a unifier.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephanie Bonner, an alternate delegate from East Hartford,
Conn., just couldn't help herself.
</P>
<P>
   Although she dutifully hopped on the Bush bandwagon, Bonner said
she wished her man, John McCain, were giving the acceptance speech
on Thursday night instead of Tuesday night's defense policy
address.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner said that if he were the nominee the convention would
surely have a different feel. ``We'd have so much more of a
cross-section of people in terms of race and class,'' she said,
looking out over a sea of delegates that is 98 percent white.
</P>
<P>
   The attack-free zone also extends to the booths selling
convention memorabilia. In Houston in 1992 and San Diego in 1996,
the hottest-sellers were anti-Clinton buttons, books and T-shirts.
In Philadelphia, these items are hard to come by. One of the only
negative buttons on display at the Pennsylvania Convention Center's
political bazaar, where most delegates are buying their convention
goodies, was a 1952 ``Let's Clean House With Ike and Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the tables were covered with sedate, black Bush-Cheney
buttons, emblazoned with American flags. Way in the back, there
were a few lonely anti-Hillary T-shirts and stop Gore buttons.
</P>
<P>
   A 1960 thank-you note from Mamie Eisenhower, priced at $300,
drew a larger crowd of shoppers on Tuesday afternoon than a booth
filled with copies of Barbara Olsen's ``Hell to Pay,'' one of
several recently published anti-Hillary tracts.
</P>
<P>
   What happens in the Republican afterlife? Whatever it is, it
must have something to do with steak and cable television.
</P>
<P>
   Or so Tuesday's birthday lunch for Alfonse D'Amato, the
loquacious former senator from New York, seemed to prove.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato celebrated his 63rd birthday at Mortons steak house
Tuesday, on Philadelphia's Walnut Street. Among the first guests to
arrive was Bob Dole, the former Republican presidential candidate,
who has parlayed his presidential bid into a career touting
treatment for erectile dysfunction and who Tuesday night was
scheduled to begin his career as a political commentator on Comedy
Central.
</P>
<P>
   After giving D'Amato a manly hug, Dole asked: Have you broken
any furniture yet?
</P>
<P>
   A passel of D'Amato's former senatorial colleagues were on hand
to fete him, as well as New York Gov. George Pataki, who was once
D'Amato's protege.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Alaska Sen. Frank Murkowski shouted from the back
of the room: ``We miss you, Al!'' It looked for a moment as if
D'Amato might burst into tears. Murkowski shouted again: ``And we
miss Mama D'Amato! D'Amato's mother is known for her terrific
Italian cooking. D'Amato brightened. Then he shot back: I'll send
her down with Lazio!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
