<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9901 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-GOPSENATE0802-COX     08-01 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOPSENATE0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Jim Galloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA - In a ballroom, in a museum and behind the closed
doors of hotel rooms, two Georgia Republicans with senatorial
ambitions began a Southern game of ``chicken'' on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. senator and ambassador Mack Mattingly and aviation
entrepreneur Lewis Jordan met face-to-face, then sent lieutenants
to work in efforts to persuade the other guy to drop out of a Nov.
7 special election to challenge newly named U.S. Sen. Zell Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``In four days, we'll have a decision. Anybody can run. But all
of us know if we're going to hold the Senate seat, it's going to be
one of us. It can't be five of us. It can't even be _ possibly _
two,'' said U.S. Rep. Charlie Norwood.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood introduced Jordan, a political neophyte and founder of
ValuJet Airlines, to Georgia delegates at the Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan told them he would bring two essential qualities to the
race: a fresh face and $3 million of his own money. ``You need to
know that I'm prepared to do things in a big way,'' said the
56-year-old major shareholder in AirTran Airways.
</P>
<P>
   The race, officially nonpartisan, will determine who will fill
out the term of the late Sen. Paul Coverdell. A tribute to the GOP
leader, who died of a stroke last month, was held at a downtown
Philadelphia art museum on Tuesday, amid jazz, wine and full-length
portraits of George Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Both Republican contenders for Coverdell's seat attended the
tribute Tuesday afternoon and huddled in a backroom in a meeting
arranged by Mattingly. It was his third conversation with Jordan
about the race, Mattingly said, but he was not successful in
persuading the newcomer to leave the field.
</P>
<P>
   State Republican chairman Chuck Clay confirmed he had polled
some of the party's executive committee by phone, and they
indicated a preference for ``the fresh face'' _ Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   After the Jordan-Mattingly meeting, Clay appeared increasingly
resigned to the fact that he might not be able to accomplish the
difficult task of unifying the party behind one candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're not going to have just one Republican, why not have
four or five?'' the state chairman said. Some Republicans have
argued that a larger field increases the likelihood of a runoff, in
which it might be easier for a survivor to pick off Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying starts today and ends Friday. Jordan intends to be
among the first to sign up, said delegate John Sours of Smyrna, a
Jordan supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly said he plans to remain in Philadelphia at least one
more day.
</P>
<P>
   While Mattingly and Jordan say they're in the race to stay, core
supporters say the ballot isn't big enough for both, if Miller, a
Democrat, is to be beaten.
</P>
<P>
   So the Philadelphia gathering of Georgians has become an
unofficial primary for a ``unity candidate'' _ one of the few
unscripted stories arising from the presidential nominating
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Just how much support that one candidate will receive from the
national party is somewhat in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the race against Miller an uphill fight, Sen. Mitch
McConnell , chairman of the National Republican Senatorial
Committee, said, ``I'm not committed to funding any race that's not
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's morning appearance was for many Republicans their first
look at the businessman, and his reception was not as hearty as the
one given Mattingly a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan brought with him the endorsement of half of Georgia's
Republican congressional delegation. In addition to Norwood, Reps.
John Linder, Saxby Chambliss and Mac Collins have lined up behind
Jordan. Norwood said they would make the case for their favorite
over the next four days.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Bob Barr and Jack Kingston have declared their support for
Mattingly, who stood in the back of the hotel ballroom as Jordan
spoke.
</P>
<P>
   After approaching Jordan to shake hands, Mattingly, 69, spent
most of his day speaking one-on-one to delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Nathan Deal and Johnny Isakson have not publicly backed
either candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was met by a crush of reporters and TV cameras when he
left the delegation meeting. The former airline executive was
circumspect when it came to discussing issues and asked for a
two-day grace period before he laid out specific positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be sure when I first articulate to you my positions,
what I believe in, that I state it precisely,'' he said. Jordan
briefly described himself as a ``Coverdell'' Republican and a major
fund-raiser for the presidential campaign of Sen. John McCain
(R-Ariz.). But he readily acknowledged that he has given financial
support to Democrats as well, including U.S. Sen. Max Cleland of
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only one who can claim to be a real, no-kidding, fresh
face in politics who can bring some new electricity to this, and a
willingness to significantly fund my campaign,'' Jordan said.
``I've seen nothing in the last few days that tell me that I should
do anything other than (run).''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
