<HEADER>
A9903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-TV-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      08-01 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-TV-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NON-NEWS EVENT MAY BACKFIRE ON REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARYN JAMES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The broadcast networks have not given the Republican Convention
one minute more than they have to, and they are absolutely right.
The most telling television image, after all, has been that of
Peter Jennings against a blank blue screen. As he has several times
during ABC's coverage, Tuesday night Jennings gave audiences full
disclosure that whenever he looks as if he is in a skybox, he is
really in a small room on the convention floor, projected against
video of the crowd outside the room.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's head of special news events, Marc Burstein, explained that
this not only saved the network several hundred thousand dollars,
by not converting their skybox to an anchor booth; it also allowed
their anchor to report from the convention floor, then scoot
quickly to a more peaceful interview space.
</P>
<P>
   But the blue background conveys more than anyone intended. The
void behind the anchorman is the perfect symbol for the nothingness
that the networks have been embarrassed into dropping by to cover,
and that the all-news cable channels have blanketed, with deadly
dullness. Even for those of us fascinated by politics, Tuesday
night was the perfect time to catch up on that rerun of ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic and Republican Conventions are such acknowledged
non-news circuses that Dan Rather on CBS, using a popular cliche
attached to this convention, called it an ``infomercial.'' Politics
has become show business, so the networks are reviewing the show,
and analyzing message it means to send. Tuesday, Jennings, in his
daily e-mail to viewers of ``World News Tonight,'' defended the
coverage in just those terms: ``The challenge is to see the way the
party presents itself, and try to get you at home to match the
image with the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever scraps of enlightenment there were came from poking
holes in the slick packaging. Most conspicuously, every channel and
nightly newscast contrasted Monday's minority-loaded Republican
show with the overwhelmingly white make-up of the convention
itself. And Tuesday night, planned by the Republicans as National
Security Night (there's a catchy show title) was full of women,
offsetting any possible macho tone. The speakers included
Condoleeza Rice, the African-American woman who is George W. Bush's
foreign policy adviser, Elizabeth Dole and a ``surprise''
appearance (widely reported in advance) by Barbara Bush. On cable,
there was enough hot air to knock a viewer unconscious. Tim
Russert, on MSNBC, heralded the importance of Tuesday night's
speakers by speculating that if Bush wins, Rice might be his
national security adviser. (Or not.) This is surely the
find-the-silver-lining approach to an non-event. PBS, the only
broadcast network to offer full evenings of the convention this
week, was just as soporific.
</P>
<P>
   The dullness of the Republican show may justify the networks'
near absence, but that doesn't let them off the hook. Viewers are
being shortchanged, not because they are missing the convention,
but because no one replacing that lost prime time with more
substantial, inventive ways to report on the campaign. NBC,
offering less broadcast time than the other networks because it has
complete coverage on its cable channel, MSNBC, is pointing to the
future. But that idea is a bit premature; networks still reach a
far larger audience than cable and the much-hyped internet
combined. Campaign coverage on the network evening news programs is
down 33 per cent from the 1996 campaign, according to a study
released this week by the Center for Media and Public Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   What is left has been shunted to the margins, to the morning
news and Sunday talk programs. In fact, look beyond prime time and
you see how the Republicans' careful convention planning has
backfired. John McCain may have lost the nomination but he has
gotten a victor's share of air time, almost dominating the past
three days as he gave interviews (NBC's ``Today,'' CNN's ``Larry
King Live'' and the ``CBS Evening News'' only begin the long list)
leading up to his prime-time speech Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But speeches themselves seem backward looking in this age of the
soundbite. Many anchors expressed nostalgia for the old days (four
years ago) when the roll call of states voting for the nominee took
place in one long session. In a quaint way, the roll call was fun
to watch, but it belongs to a time when there was such a thing as a
captive television audience. Today, a flick of the remote can send
viewers from a Schwarzkopf speech to ``Seinfeld,'' which means no
one has to sit still for silver-lining coverage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
