<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9904 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      08-01 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS BUSH'S CAMPAIGN FOR BLACK VOTES A SUBTLE APPEAL TO WHITE
SUBURBANITES? 
</HEADLINE>
   By R.W. APPLE Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Tuesday night, for the second night in a row, one
of the principal speakers at the Republican National Convention was
a black person. Tuesday night, it was Condoleezza Rice, the chief
national security adviser to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas; on
Monday night, it was Colin Powell, who may be secretary of state if
Bush is elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this was no happenstance. In this convention, whose
sole mission is the glorification of Bush, happenstance just
doesn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Equally obviously, neither Rice nor Powell was on the dais as
window-dressing. Both are eminent figures, whose success in the
academic and military worlds speaks volumes about the achievements
of black Americans in the last couple of decades. But there was
window-dressing as well, in the form of black singers, black
choirs, black candidates for lesser offices and black children
seated at school desks in the rather contrived backdrop to the
speech of the prospective nominee's wife, Laura, a former
schoolteacher.
</P>
<P>
   The question occurs, what is all this about? Granting that Bush
has demonstrated in his brief political career a considerably
greater sensitivity to minority concerns than the average
Republican, what political purpose lies behind the image-making?
</P>
<P>
   Does he really think he can do better among blacks than his
father, who took 12 percent and 10 percent of the black vote in
1988 and 1992, respectively, and better than Bob Dole, who took 12
percent in 1996? Or is it a three-cushion shot, a subtle play for
the votes of white suburbanites, a pivotal voting block that
includes many voters for whom civil rights remains a high priority?
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no chance of getting any significant African-American
vote,'' said David Bositis of the nonpartisan Joint Center for
Political and Economic Studies. ``This is not even about that. It's
about the suburbs, and about moderate swing voters all across the
country. There's no better way to distance himself from Tom DeLay
and Dick Armey and the other hard-liners in Congress than showing
that he's friendly to blacks and Hispanics.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the cold facts are these: The Democrats are a
multiracial party, with large numbers of blacks in leadership
positions. The Republicans are largely a monoracial party. Since
World War II, only three African-American Republicans have been
elected to Congress, including Sen. Edward Brooke of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said bluntly that there was widespread ``cynicism in the
black community'' towards the Republican party, based in part on
its opposition to affirmative action, reaffirmed in this year'
platform. He challenged the Republicans to reach out to blacks and
other minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``And not just during an election-year campaign,'' he continued.
``It must be a sustained effort. It must be every day. It must be
real.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he thought Powell was right and acknowledged that ``we
have a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats expressed skepticism that it would ever get done.
Speaking at the Shadow Convention here in Philadelphia, the Rev.
Jesse Jackson praised Powell but said that his speech was part of a
``sham.'' Noting that this is a largely white convention _ only 4
percent of the delegates are black, about the same as in 1972 _
Jackson added, ``You got Powell making speeches but you got Trent
Lott making policy'' _ a reference to the Senate majority leader, a
conservative from Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   According to exit polls conducted by Voter News Service, a
consortium of television networks and The Associated Press, Bush
took 27 percent of the black vote in his re-election contest in
1998. That may have been a exaggeration of his true strength,
because his Democratic opponent, Tony Mauro, was never seen as a
viable alternative. Bush did much less well against Ann Richards in
1994, winning 15 percent of the black vote then.
</P>
<P>
   During this year's campaign, he made a point of appearing before
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People,
something Dole declined to do four years ago. But in the South
Carolina primary, when Sen. John McCain of Arizona was pressing him
hard, Bush was unwilling to condemn the flying of the Confederate
battle flag on the statehouse in Columbia, and he campaigned at Bob
Jones University in Greenville, which banned interracial dating at
the time of his speech there.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has also described Clarence Thomas and Antonin Scalia,
dyed-in-the-wool conservatives whose very names are anathema to
many blacks, as model Supreme Court justices, even though Thomas is
himself black.
</P>
<P>
   To many African-Americans, those actions seemed of a piece with
Richard Nixon's southern strategy, which built a lasting base for
the Republicans among Southern white voters. It was not explicitly
anti-black, but it was grounded in racial apprehensions. Ever
since, the GOP has had, to a greater or lesser degree, a white
southern core, and its leadership on Capitol Hill has been and
still is largely southern.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, meanwhile, has emerged as the most popular
president among African-Americans since Lyndon Johnson, who signed
the Voting Rights Act, and Franklin D. Roosevelt, who espoused
their cause in the depths of the Depression. When Clinton's
fortunes were at their nadir, during the acrimonious impeachment
battle in the House, blacks were among his staunchest advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my friends see him as a kind of God,'' said a black
Republican delegate here, who asked that his name not be used.
``Some of that rubs off on Al Gore, and it makes Bush's job in
November terribly difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest New York Times/CBS News poll, taken between July 20
and 22, suggested how difficult a job the governor faces in
courting black votes. In a two-way race, Gore won the support of 84
percent of African-Americans to Bush's 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush signaled Tuesday that he was confident of doing better
than that. As he wended his way toward Philadelphia, he was asked
whether he was discouraged to see so few black faces in the crowds
at his rallies, even after Monday night's multiracial television
production. He answered, ``We'll see on Election Day, won't we?''
</P>
<P>
   At a first glance, blacks would seem to be ripe for conversion
to Republicanism. In nationwide telephone surveys conducted by The
Times and CBS News since 1976, between a quarter and a third of
black voters have described themselves as conservatives, but only 6
percent to 11 percent have described themselves as Republicans.
Even making allowances for those who use the word ``conservative''
in its social rather than political sense, and apply it to
themselves because they are regular churchgoers, for example, the
Republicans should have an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, moreover, more and more blacks have reached the
middle class, have moved into prosperous suburbs and have joined
the professions. According to a new study called Black America
2000, the income levels of black households have tripled in the
past 24 years, and the number of black-owned businesses more than
doubled in number between 1987 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When other groups have undergone such changes, significant
numbers among them have migrated to the Republican party. But so
far, that pattern has not held for African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, things are going well for Bush among white
suburbanites. The same Times/CBS poll showed him well ahead of the
vice president among that group, 52 percent to 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If, as Bositis and a number of Republican tacticians suggested,
Bush's real aim in appealing to blacks is to solidify his support
among white moderates, he would not be the first Republican nominee
to try that ploy. In 1980, Ronald Reagan made much of his
endorsement by the civil rights leaders Ralph David Abernathy and
Hosea Williams. His black support barely budged; but that was not
the point, as one of his strategists, Richard Wirthlin, later
explained. The target, Wirthlin said, was white suburbanites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
