<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BOSNIA-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVIL SUIT AGAINST EX-LEADER OF BOSNIAN SERBS UNDER WAY IN NEW
YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The trial of a civil lawsuit against the former
leader of the Bosnian Serbs began in a federal courtroom in
Manhattan on Tuesday with a witness fainting on the stand as she
described her captivity, rape and torture during the Balkans
conflict in the summer and fall of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, a Bosnian Muslim, told of being dragged from her
house by soldiers, including a former neighbor from her town in
northern Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   She said the men, who wore photographs of the Bosnian leader,
Dr. Radovan Karadzic, told her she was being singled out because
she was a Muslim. They took her and her two young children to a
mountainside shack, she said, where they locked her inside and
repeatedly raped her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not resist, I could not fight against them,'' the
witness, a woman identified as N.S., testified. ``I could not
resist because the others were holding me while my children were
watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Karadzic has been indicted for genocide by the international war
crimes tribunal in The Hague but has not been apprehended and is
believed to be in hiding in Bosnia. Although neither he nor his
lawyers appeared in the courtroom Tuesday, they submitted documents
vigorously contesting the right to hold a civil trial in the United
States for offenses the plaintiffs claim were committed overseas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The woman testified that her abductors ``started slapping me in
the face, saying there was nothing and no one to save me, ever.''
She added: ``It was their state and they could do as they pleased.
There was no way for me to escape.''
</P>
<P>
   While tales of atrocities have become familiar in accounts of
the conflicts during the disintegration of Yugoslavia, the
testimony Tuesday was among the first heard on the subject by
American jurors.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which was filed in 1993 on behalf of a group of
women and children, seeks millions of dollars in damages from
Karadzic, who the plaintiffs say masterminded a campaign of
genocide, rape and torture in the area in the early 1990s. Lawyers
for the women said that in addition to experts and witnesses to
more widespread violence, 11 witnesses were expected to testify to
attacks made against them.
</P>
<P>
   In the last seven years, the case has moved from the U.S.
District Court to the 2nd Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, as lawyers
for both sides argued whether U.S. courts could exercise
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   The courts ruled that the case could be brought in the United
States under federal laws against torture, and under a 1789 law
allowing damage claims made for offenses against ``the law of
nations or a treaty of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, Judge Peter K. Leisure of the U.S. District Court
entered a default judgment in the women's favor.
</P>
<P>
   Maria T. Vullo, one of the lawyers representing the women, said
Tuesday that although ``the case obviously has an important message
in it,'' her clients fully intended to collect damages from
Karadzic's assets.
</P>
<P>
   The trial in Manhattan, which is expected to last about two
weeks, will determine the amount of money he will be ordered to
pay.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Karadzic did not return telephone calls. But in a
letter to the court written in 1997, Karadzic rejected the U.S.
courts' ability to sit in judgment on his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you really hope to find truth, or do justice, or protect
rights of people in distant nations?'' Karadzic wrote. ``Do you
really believe that attaching a U.S. dollar sign to human tragedy
around the world by empty judgments in uncontested lawsuits is a
step toward peace or justice?''
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Karadzic said he would ``have to look to history,
or to courts with real access to the events, the witnesses,
documents and the parties for my vindication.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has offered $5 million for information on
the whereabouts of Karadzic and several other wartime leaders
accused by the war crimes tribunal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
