u f BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT &LR;      08-01 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR SALES RISE, EXCEPT AT GM AND CHRYSLER 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ General Motors and DaimlerChrysler said on Tuesday
that their sales fell in July, leaving both automakers unable to
reduce their bloated inventories of unsold minivans, pickup trucks
and sport utility vehicles. But Ford and foreign automakers
announced strong sales last month and balanced inventories.
</P>
<P>
   Overall industry sales were very strong. While they did not
quite match the torrid pace early this year, they were still brisk
enough to suggest that consumer spending remained a powerful force
in the American economy during July.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some signs of moderation, although the industry is
running at a healthy pace,'' said Bill Lovejoy, GM's group vice
president for North American vehicle sales, service and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Mark M. Cornelius, an auto statistician in West Olive, Mich.,
calculated on Tuesday evening that sales rose 2.1 percent from a
year ago, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 17.2 million cars
and light trucks. He used estimates for sales of Mazda, the only
automaker not reporting Tuesday. The auto industry sold 17 million
vehicles last year, its best ever.
</P>
<P>
   GM posted a 2.6 percent drop in sales for July from its record
level a year ago, as a 22.8 percent jump in sales of small Saturn
cars failed to offset weak sales of minivans, small pickup trucks
and large sport utility vehicles. Paul Ballew, GM's sales analysis
director, blamed inadequate factory production for the weaker sales
of large sport utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Chrysler unit of DaimlerChrysler said sales fell 12.2
percent in July, dragged heavily by a 29 percent plunge in sales of
minivan sales, a market segment that Chrysler essentially invented
in 1983 and has dominated ever since. Chrysler will unveil
redesigned minivans later this month and in early September, and
customers have proved loath to buy the older models, despite
increasingly lavish rebates.
</P>
<P>
   Jeep sales dropped 15 percent and sales of Dodge Durango large
sport utility truck fell 3 percent. But Americans continued to snap
up Chrysler PT Cruiser small vans as fast as the company could
build them.
</P>
<P>
   During most of the year, automakers seek to keep a 60-day
inventory of vehicles at dealerships and on the way to dealerships.
But at the end of July, when they are phasing out old models, they
would prefer somewhat smaller inventories of 55 to 58 days.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, GM said late Tuesday afternoon that its supply of
unsold cars and light trucks equaled 68 days of sales. Chrysler
said that it had a 78-day supply. Both automakers said that they
did not have separate inventory figures Tuesday for cars and for
light trucks, which encompasses minivans, sport utilities and
pickups.
</P>
<P>
   GM and Chrysler both had very large inventories of light trucks
and small numbers of cars at the end of June. Nicholas Lobaccaro,
an auto analyst at Lehman Brothers, said that the two companies'
sales and production figures in July suggested that this pattern
had persisted, particularly at GM, and that the companies' overall
inventory figures masked huge backlogs of minivans, sport utilities
and pickups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their car inventory is too low, but you don't make any money
on cars, and their light truck inventory is too high, and you make
money on light trucks,'' he said. ``You just can't go forever
building more than you sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler officials acknowledged that their large inventories
reflected an enormous supply of minivans. That situation stems at
least partly from the company's determination not to run out of
minivans this year as it did in 1995 when it shut its two minivan
factories for nearly three months to retool them for a new
generation. Chrysler ran short of minivans, posted a huge quarterly
loss and watched as many loyal customers deserted to rival brands.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Chrysler built lots of extra minivans in the spring
and figured out a way to convert one factory over to the new model
in two weeks this summer and the other in seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The first factory is now in production and cranking out the new
minivans quickly while the old models are selling slowly. James
Holden, Chrysler's chief executive, said last week that discounts
would be needed to dispose of the older models.
</P>
<P>
   GM's inventory is more complicated. In a telephone conference
call with reporters Tuesday afternoon, Ballew, the sales analysis
director, dismissed widespread rumors in Detroit that GM was about
to slow output at some factories because of excessive inventories.
The automaker's supply of vehicles looks large only in comparison
with last summer, when the company was short of many models, he
said. He added that the industry's sales might slow slightly next
year with weaker economic growth. Gas prices have had little affect
on sales, Ballew said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford announced on Tuesday that its sales inched up six-tenths of
1 percent from an extremely strong performance a year ago. The
company had roughly a 50-day supply of cars and about a 60-day
supply of light trucks at the end of July, said George Pipas, a
market analyst at Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Some foreign automakers fared better in July. Honda had its best
month ever in the American market as sales rose 11.6 percent, led
by strong results for the Civic compact car, the Odyssey minivan
and the CR-V small sport utility vehicle. Mitsubishi's sales jumped
28.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen's sales climbed 4.8 percent, while Toyota's sales
crept up 1 percent and Nissan's sales edged up by two-tenths of 1
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
