<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9908 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-NYT     08-01 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR RECORD LABELS MOVE TO OFFER THEIR MUSIC ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  By   MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At least three major record labels plan to begin
selling songs over the Internet in a subscription format by the end
of the year, enabling users to listen to or download a range of
tracks for a flat fee, a move which may fundamentally change the
way recorded music is packaged.
</P>
<P>
   An executive from EMI Recorded Music said on Tuesday that the
label expects to have a subscription service available by the end
of September. Universal Music Group and Sony Music Entertainment
should have a similar service in place by the end of the year, said
Bruce Hack, vice chairman at Universal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be getting in with a subscription model by the end of
the year,'' Hack said.
</P>
<P>
   The executives' statements came on the same day Universal
announced it will begin selling individual songs online for
downloading. Starting later this week, the label will make 60 songs
available on a dozen affiliate Web sites for $1.99, a price that
includes the song, images of the artists and text of the lyrics.
The songs are sold in an encrypted format that Universal says will
prevent anyone but the purchaser from listening to them.
</P>
<P>
   Other major labels are involved in similar trials, including
EMI, which recently began selling 100 albums for downloading on
July 18 from music retail sites. But critics of the industry
consider the efforts an insufficient, desperate scramble to catch
up with an underground Internet music economy they say threatens to
pass the record labels by.
</P>
<P>
   The labels, critics point out, are selling a handful of titles
online for $2 or so a song, while some 20 million people who have
downloaded the software of Napster, the embattled online music
start-up, are exchanging hundreds of thousands of songs free. Last
week, a federal judge issued a temporary injunction ordering the
effective shutdown of Napster, which the recording industry accuses
of contributory copyright infringement. But an appeals court panel
on Friday stayed the injunction pending trial.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, record companies have suggested a
subscription service might borrow heavily from the look and feel of
Napster, offering Internet users a search engine to find songs to
download, but effectively adding a cash register, and with the
songs encrypted to prevent their free and unfettered exchange.
</P>
<P>
   This would be distinct from a pay-per-song model in which users
pay to download or listen to tracks on an individual basis.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Sony Music Entertainment and Universal said they were
exploring a subscription model. Hack said the subscription service
planned to launch by the end of the year will be a product of that
joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many issues are unresolved, Samit said. For example,
he said the labels need to go back to artists and rewrite their
contacts to permit their music to be included in a
subscription-based service.
</P>
<P>
   One record industry executive said the contractual issues aside,
the labels would likely only have to make 5,000 to 10,000 of their
200,000 title libraries available to meet consumer demand, which is
concentrated among a few artists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9909 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT &LR;      08-01 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR SALES RISE, EXCEPT AT GM AND CHRYSLER 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
