u i BC-VENEZUELA-POLITICS-NY     08-01 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELA PRESIDENT SAYS HE WILL CRUSH POLITICAL FOES 
</HEADLINE>
   By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ President Hugo Chavez said Tuesday that he
would use troops to crush street protests and to remove an
opposition party governor who has accused the governing party of
fraudulently altering the outcome of elections last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be nothing more than a little spat, but we
are obliged to guarantee order and prevent these groups from
spoiling the beautiful process that we have concluded,'' Chavez
said Tuesday afternoon, referring to the vote held across Venezuela
on Sunday. ``If they lost, they lost,'' he added dismissively.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary results from the national and local balloting, in
which Chavez and 165 members of a new National Assembly were also
elected, gave victory to the incumbent governor in the western
state of Merida, William Davila, a leading opposition figure. But
6,000 ballots, most cast for Davila, were declared invalid for
reasons that are still not clear, and the pro-Chavez candidate was
declared the winner Tuesday, by a margin of less than 1,800 votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that there was a fraud, which the people of Merida
reject,'' Davila said in remarks broadcast on national television
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition candidates in five other states also made similar
accusations about fraud in their races. Preliminary results had
given Chavez's leftist Patriotic Pole coalition 12 of the 23
governorships at stake in the election in this oil-rich nation of
23 million people, but Tuesday afternoon Chavez said that his
candidates had actually triumphed in 16 states and warned that he
would not tolerate ``anarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are consolidating our victory, and as in any battle, you
have to fight for every inch of territory,'' he said. He minimized
the protests as ``a mob with a few rocks and sticks'' and said that
``four or five canisters of tear gas ought to get them out of
there,'' referring to the government offices where Davila has taken
refuge.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, two international observer groups, one led by former
President Jimmy Carter and the other sent by the Organization of
American States, had pronounced the balloting here clean and fair.
Sustained opposition complaints of fraud in the tabulation of votes
began in earnest only Tuesday, though, after the observer groups
had begun to close down operations here.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, a former army colonel who led an unsuccessful coup
attempt in 1992, announced the dispatch of troops Tuesday afternoon
during a three-hour news conference at which he also discussed
issues ranging from his government's foreign policy to his plans to
reactivate the Venezuelan economy. His most significant comments,
though, came in a response to a question about oil prices, which
have recently soared to near-record highs.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Venezuela has been the leading supplier of the
oil imported by the United States, and the country's energy
minister, Ali Rodriguez Araque, was designated president of the
Organization of Oil Exporting Countries, or OPEC, this spring.
Chavez made it clear that he was delighted with the jump in oil
prices and reiterated his position that he sees no reason to take
any action to bring them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just defending our position,'' Chavez said. ``It's not
that prices are high. They are fair and just.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the oil bonanza, Venezuela's economy contracted by more
than 7 percent last year, and now that the election is over, Chavez
is under pressure to take steps to end that recession.
</P>
<P>
   He also reiterated his admiration for the Cuban and Chinese
revolutions, saying those countries' economies ``have good things''
and have produced social benefits. But he then added that it is not
his intention to ``try to import models from abroad,'' and said
that his own revolutionary government welcomes foreign investment,
so long as it is ``productive, not speculative.''
</P>
<P>
   Long a skeptic about U.S. policies in the region, Chavez
expressed concern about the $1.3 billion emergency aid package for
neighboring Colombia that President Clinton approved last month. He
said that while his government is ``willing to cooperate'' with
Colombia and the United States, he hoped that the military aid
would ``not be used to Vietnamize the Colombia conflict'' or
contribute to an increase in the fighting there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hope this doesn't happen,'' he said. ``We are paying
close attention.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chavez reserved his most critical comments for his domestic
opposition, saying that some of his adversaries ``refuse to
recognize Chavez as president'' and warning that he will not
hesitate to use his expanded powers to bring them to heel. ``If
they don't understand that or don't cooperate, we will apply the
constitution to them,'' he warned.
</P>
</TEXT>
