<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRICELINE-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICELINE IS SELLING $190 MILLION STAKE TO INVESTORS  
</HEADLINE>
   By SAUL HANSELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a deal as complex as his patented method of selling airplane
tickets, Jay S. Walker, the founder of Priceline.com, agreed
Tuesday to sell $190 million of his shares to Paul G. Allen's
Vulcan Ventures and John C. Malone's Liberty Media Group.
</P>
<P>
   The sale can be seen as quite a loss for Walker. Last November,
he bought 2.1 million Priceline shares from Delta Air Lines for
$59.93 a share. Now he has agreed to sell 8 million shares at
$23.75 each. After taxes, he said, he will wind up with about $125
million, which he will invest in Priceline's WebHouse Club, its
affiliate that sells groceries and gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   After this sale, Walker will still own some 50 million shares,
worth about $1.2 billion. But those shares were worth six times
that in April 1999, about a month after Priceline's initial public
offering. And the stock has been in free fall since March _ sliding
from $104, to $23.625 Monday. On Tuesday, however, the share price
rose $1.31, to $24.94, as investors considered the deal a vote of
confidence by Liberty and Vulcan rather than as a bearish signal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not taking the money and running,'' said Mark J. Rowen,
an analyst with Prudential Securities. ``He's putting it back into
WebHouse.'' Rowen had downgraded Priceline's stock last week
because he was concerned that the company's grocery business was
not growing fast enough to compensate for the slowing growth in its
travel sales.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline, notable for its ubiquitous advertising featuring the
labored crooning of William Shatner, allows customers to name their
own price for airline tickets, hotel rooms and an increasing number
of other products.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said he was reluctant to sell his shares at this low
price and that he had held off completing the deal with Vulcan and
Liberty in hopes that the market would be buoyed by Priceline's
second-quarter earnings, which were released last week. Despite an
operating loss that was only a penny a share better than analysts
had expected, the company's shares continued their decline.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase by Liberty and Vulcan is organized as a forward
sale in that Walker receives the payment now, but he does not
deliver the shares to Liberty or Vulcan for a year or two. That
way, investors can be assured that the shares will not be sold in
the market the moment that Priceline's stock ticks up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want the market to feel I was putting pressure on
Priceline's shares,'' Walker said. ``The last thing that
Priceline's stock needs is more pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The effective price Walker is receiving is less than $23.75,
because he also granted Liberty and Vulcan an option to buy an
undisclosed portion of his share in Walker Digital, a company that
is devoted to thinking up and patenting new ideas for businesses.
The options give Liberty and Vulcan the right to buy the shares
from him at a price that values Walker Digital at $1.5 billion to
$1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, a co-founder of Microsoft who has accumulated a portfolio
of companies involved in the Internet and cable television, already
owns about 5 percent of Priceline.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty, a tracking stock of AT&AMP;T, is an independent investment
vehicle of Malone's that owns interests in a number of media and
technology companies, including smaller stakes in Priceline and
WebHouse.
</P>
<P>
   While WebHouse appears to be an integral part of Priceline,
linked to its Web site and using Shatner as a spokesman, it is
owned by Walker, Walker Digital and a group of investors. Priceline
owns no shares in WebHouse, but has an option to buy a controlling
interest.
</P>
<P>
   WebHouse, in many ways, is far more elaborate and expensive to
build than Priceline itself, because customers bid for products on
the Internet, pay for them with a credit card, then pick them up at
stores and gas stations with a special card.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as complicated as Visa,'' Walker said. ``We are
building a system that connects 80,000 cash registers in 7,000
stores. Last week we priced 2 million grocery items. I'll do that
for 100 million transactions next year.''
</P>
<P>
   WebHouse has already raised $200 million from a group of
investors and is currently raising another $145 million, including
Walker's $125 million. Walker said that the company would need to
raise more money before the system was complete.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, WebHouse is meant to offer manufacturers an
alternative to paper coupons to get potential customers to try
their products. But while it has many of the biggest supermarket
chains participating, leading manufacturers like Procter &AMP; Gamble
and Lever Brothers have not. As a result, WebHouse is selling goods
for less than it pays for them.
</P>
<P>
   But even Rowen, the analyst who downgraded Priceline's stock,
argues that selling $2 jars of peanut butter for $1.50 may just be
smart. ``Priceline is not a typical consumer business,'' he said.
``Their model is they first have to get the consumer demand. Then
they sell the demand, in essence, to the highest bidder.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
