<SLUG> BC-GOP-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S GIULIANI ENDORSES RICK LAZIO FOR SENATE AT REPUBLICAN
CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani behaved like a good
Republican Tuesday as he went to a fund-raiser for Rep. Rick Lazio,
held a joint news conference with Lazio and gave interviews to two
networks _ all while attending his first national political
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very strongly support Rick Lazio and urge everyone that at
least wants to listen to me to vote for him,'' Giuliani said at the
joint news conference, which lasted 10 minutes. Later, at the
fund-raiser, which the mayor attended with his friend, Judith
Nathan, Giuliani thanked the crowd for ``supporting Rick and for
making certain that I don't have to spend the last year that I'm
the mayor of New York City with Hillary as the senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, the mayor who had endorsed a Democrat for
governor _ Mario Cuomo _ and then barely endorsed a Republican for
president _ Bob Dole _ showed such disdain for his party's national
convention in San Diego that he was not even invited.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't allow Gov. Wilson to speak, haven't allowed Gov.
Weld to speak, and they tried to constrict Pataki's remarks to such
a degree that he didn't want to speak,'' Giuliani told reporters at
the time, referring to the Republican governors Pete Wilson of
California, William Weld of Massachusetts and George E. Pataki of
New York. ``So I think I made the right choice in terms of sticking
to my job and trying to do the best I can to be really a mayor that
reaches out to both political parties.''
</P>
<P>
   How times have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Although Giuliani withdrew from his Senate race against Hillary
Rodham Clinton in May after announcing that he had prostate cancer
and was seeking a separation from his wife, his appearance here
Tuesday _ as a New York delegate _ suggests that he has not ruled
out running for office again. And although he is still distrusted
by many in the New York state Republican party, he has nonetheless
spent the last two and a half years traveling across the United
States to raise his political profile in the national party.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his advisers have said he has always had his eye on the
presidency, while others say that what he really wants is to run
for governor of New York in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, Giuliani said he believed his place in the
world of Republicans had changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1996, I didn't know an awful lot of people,'' he said at
New York City Hall on Monday. ``Now I probably know people from at
least more than half the states that I've worked with, done things
with, that I've helped, that have helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the Republican convention allowed him to ``get
them all in one place'' to say thank you to such helpers, and that
``several of these events allow you to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what events Giuliani was talking about was unclear,
since his aides at City Hall have declined to say when the mayor
arrived at the convention Tuesday, whether he will be staying
overnight and what events he may be attending.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was expected late this afternoon at a party given by
the dress designer Nicole Miller at her boutique in central
Philadelphia, but had not turned up by 5 p.m., although his former
communications director, Cristyne Lategano-Nicholas, had. Miller is
a political supporter of Giuliani and a friend of both him and his
estranged wife, Donna Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani grew testy when reporters asked on Monday about his
plans for the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to enjoy myself, have fun, and I'm going to have you
leave me alone as much as possible,'' he said. ``And you'll see me
when I want you to see me, and not when I don't want you to see
me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
