<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9923 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-DEWINE0802-COX     08-01 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEWINE0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain, Ohio's DeWine foster support for Bush
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Republican National Convention belongs to
George W. Bush, but Tuesday provided one final opportunity for
Ohio's Mike DeWine and thousands of other John McCain supporters to
cheer on the Arizona senator who, however briefly, rocked both the
Republican establishment and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any doubt that John McCain's running
made George Bush a better candidate, a stronger candidate. We get
tougher, we get stronger usually when we deal with adversity,''
DeWine, Ohio's senior U.S. senator, said as he prepared to hear
McCain address the convention Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has urged his followers to fall in line behind Bush.
Americans don't like sore losers, McCain has said.
</P>
<P>
   DeWine, from Cedarville in Greene County, has taken McCain's
advice with a vengeance. He campaigned this week with Bush both in
Cincinnati and Dayton as the Texas governor made his way to the
convention through battleground states he will need to carry in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush is the kind of person who should be in the White
House. He is a man of integrity and a man of honor,'' said DeWine.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, of course, did not always shower Bush with such
accolades as they battled through New Hampshire, South Carolina,
Michigan, Ohio and other states in pursuit of the nomination Bush
will claim this week.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not the harsh rhetoric that remains with DeWine, one
of only four Republican senators to endorse McCain.
</P>
<P>
   What remains is the reception that McCain _ the Navy pilot who
was shot down in the Vietnam war and survived brutal beatings in
prison to emerge as a political leader _ received from other
veterans who thronged to see him along the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most memorable scene was watching the older
veterans. They came up to him and they had tears in their eyes,''
said DeWine. ``They really connected. They connected in a very
nonpolitical way.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other scenes worth remembering, too, said DeWine. At
a bookstore in the suburban Cincinnati, hundreds of McCain fans
lined up for McCain to sign copies of his book, ``Faith of Our
Fathers.'' McCain signed them all, DeWine remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance reform, McCain's signature issue, is not part
of the Republican platform. DeWine did not even support the McCain
version of finance reform. McCain's effort, however, provided the
party with a needed reminder, said DeWine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the messages that people got from all of this
is that our party should stand for reform, should stand for change.
That's not a bad thing to say, that you're the party of Theodore
Roosevelt,'' DeWine said.
</P>
<P>
   DeWine, the loyal political soldier, has joined other
Republicans in heaping praise on Dick Cheney, the former Wyoming
congressman and defense secretary, whom Bush picked as his running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, however, also would have been a good choice for that
job, said DeWine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would have been a good idea,'' DeWine said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
