<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9924 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-GOD-HNS &LR;      08-01 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    CHRISTIAN COALITION CHEERS PAT ROBERTSON WHO BLASTS EDUCATION
DEPARTMENT, CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By ALAN BERNSTEIN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Countering the conciliatory mood of the
Republican National Convention, speakers at a Christian Coalition
of America rally here Tuesday denounced pop culture, the U.S.
Department of Education and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelist and commentator Pat Robertson, founder of the
coalition, also asserted that the organization has been wrongly
written off as a force in national politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of reading stories saying the Christian Coalition is
dead,'' Robertson said. ``We're just warming up, folks.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Sam Brownback of Kansas, one of several Republican
officeholders who addressed the audience as warm-up acts for
Robertson, revived a phrase that often fills GOP strategists with
regret.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback, stoked by applause from about 1,800 people packed
into a hotel ballroom, criticized violence in the mass media and
urged religious voters ``to engage in the great cultural battle for
the soul of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the 1992 Republican convention in Houston,
conservative commentator Pat Buchanan declared ``a religious war .
. . for the soul of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said Buchanan's rhetoric was so corrosive
that it damaged efforts by President Bush and the Republican Party
to win over moderate voters. The 1992 speech is being cited here
this week as the type of approach the GOP has abandoned in its push
for Texas Gov. George W. Bush's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said the 2000 election is no time to be dainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a convention of sweetness and light,'' he said.
``Nobody wants to rock the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Robertson said, he wants the nation to know that, for
example, he doesn't want his tax money spent on ``dirty pictures or
Planned Parenthood.'' It was an apparent reference to federal
funding for the arts and for sex education.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson called for the dismantling of the Education
department, saying he could do a better job with the agency's money
by educating children through private, religious projects.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Bush made sure that the party dropped its
long-running call for the department to be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I frankly agree with Ronald Reagan,'' Robertson said. ``I
think they should do away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky rocked another boat
Tuesday in his role as the Senate's leading foe of legislation that
would place further limits on the way candidates and parties
finance their campaigns with contributions from individuals and
special interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hear the three words `campaign finance reform,' some
liberal is trying to shut you up,'' McConnell said. ``No matter how
you dress up that turkey, it still won't fly.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the legislation would blunt the Christian Coalition from
pooling its financial resources to ``amplify'' its messages.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. John McCain's advocacy of campaign finance reform
boosted him into the runner-up position in the Republican
presidential primary won by Bush. The issue is getting sparse
mention, if any, from the podium of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond discussion of their favorite issues, the ``Faith &AMP;
Freedom Celebration,'' which featured patriotic music, was the
Christian Coalition's assertion that it remains relevant to the
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Bush is a born-again Christian who opposes
abortion and is running on a ``pro-family'' agenda shows that the
coalition is on the verge of its goal to have such a person in the
White House, Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating told the audience that the media
have declared the death of groups such as the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think there was any more religious right, if you read
the press,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not it has weakened, the coalition has faded from the
scene partly because Robertson, a 1988 candidate for the GOP
presidential nomination, has taken a relatively quiet approach to
this year's election.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than get behind a single candidate for this year's
nomination, such as conservative Gary Bauer, Robertson told
reporters in early 1999 that Bush, Elizabeth Dole and several other
candidates all seemed acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, he also agreed with Bush's effort to soften the GOP
image by applying the ``compassionate conservative'' label.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought conservatism had to have a hard edge,'' he
said then.
</P>
<P>
   Rice University professor William Martin, author of a book on
the evolution of the religious right, said groups such as the
coalition have become pragmatic and less raucous while continuing
to represent about a sixth of the national electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power of the religious right was overestimated, and now it
is being underestimated,'' he said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   The rally conducted by the Christian Coalition during the 1996
Republican convention in San Diego was a roomier, outdoor event
that drew about 1,000 more people than Tuesday's gathering.
</P>
<P>
   A Texas convention delegate at the rally, Myrna McElroy of
Gonzales, said this year's convention has not muted the voices of
religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Citing religious-oriented musical entertainment and video
presentations at the convention, McElroy remarked, ``I think this
convention is showing me that godly people are going to be involved
in the selection of our leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
