u p BC-GOP-FUNDRAISING-2TAKE     08-01 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-FUNDRAISING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL GROUP PROVIDING BIGGEST GOP DONATIONS _ TWO-THIRDS OF SOFT
MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Exclusive) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Republican officials insist that their financial
base is primarily small donors, but the party has received more
than $90 million from a relatively small pool of wealthy
individuals and corporations, some of whom have shielded their
generosity from public view.
</P>
<P>
   An elite cadre of 739 contributors, writing much larger checks
than in the past, has provided two-thirds of the party's $137
million in so-called soft money, the unrestricted party gifts. Some
of these donors have been directed by party officials to make their
gifts in ways that disguise their identity and the degree of their
largess, according to a top Republican fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   The party's top-level sponsors are the Republican Regents, a
group of 139 people and corporations that party officials say have
each given at least $250,000 to the party since January 1999.
Two-thirds of the Regents are individuals, the rest are
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   According to Federal Election Commission records, the membership
includes Lawrence Kadish, a New York real estate developer; Kenneth
Lay, the chairman of Enron Corp.; Jerrold Perenchio, the chairman
of the Univision television network; and Alex Spanos, a developer
and investor based in Stockton, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But Federal Election Commission records show only 54
corporations and individuals as having given that much to the party
because some donors have split their donations into smaller checks,
at the suggestion of party officials. That effectively makes the
donors' contribution totals harder to trace.
</P>
<P>
   Some contributors have also written checks to state party
committees, the records of which are not filed with the Federal
Election Commission and are difficult to obtain. Several party
fund-raisers also acknowledged that some donors have been told by
finance officials to make their contributions in the name of more
obscure corporate subsidiaries that cannot always be easily linked
to individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Pascoe, the Republican Party press secretary, said he was
not aware that there was a deliberate plan to direct large
contributors to send checks to state party committees as a way of
disguising the size of their gifts.
</P>
<P>
   But fund-raisers said big-dollar political donors were willing
to write numerous checks to different party committees in an effort
to preserve their privacy. Some have asked for suggestions from
party officials for ways to disguise the level of their
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's broken up,'' said a longtime Republican fund-raiser who
asked not to be identified. ``A man gives some, a spouse gives, an
investment company gives, a subsidiary gives. People want
anonymity. The party doesn't care; they're getting their money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0400 </DOCNO>
