<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9932 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-MEXICO-FOX-HNS &LR;      08-01 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FOX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S PRESIDENT-ELECT MAY CREATE OFFICE OF BORDER CZAR  
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL RILEY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ President-elect Vicente Fox's foreign policy
experts said Tuesday that his transition team is considering
creating an office of a border czar that would deal with
drug-trafficking, immigration, pollution and other issues along
Mexico's international boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   They indicated that Fox, who defeated Francisco Labastida of the
long-ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party on July 2, would
discuss his ideas for the office and other issues when he meets
with President Clinton during a two-day visit to Washington on Aug.
24
</P>
<P>
   Fox also will confer with Vice President Al Gore, the presumed
Democratic presidential nominee, said the aides, Adolfo Aguilar
Zinser and Jorge Castaneda. The Mexican leader will travel to
Dallas where he will meet with Gore's Republican opponent, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, and with state business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The officials disclosed few details about a border czar office.
But they said that while it would deal with Mexico's southern
border with Guatemala as well as with its northern border, the
priority would be Mexico's 2,000-mile boundary with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The officials reiterated Fox's commitment for an open
U.S.-Mexican border, the free-flow of labor between Mexico and the
United States, and the reshaping of the North American Free Trade
Agreement with the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, they said, wants to transform NAFTA, which will tightly
link the economies of the three nations, into a sweeping political
and economic partnership modeled after the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Mexican leader will ask Clinton to scrap the
U.S. drug certification program, which is widely unpopular among
Mexican and other Latin American politicians. U.S. law requires the
administration to annually certify whether countries have taken
measures to control the flow of narcotics to the United States.
Nations that fail to be certified as drug-war allies face loss of
U.S. aid and other economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Fox's proposals are not likely to be greeted with
enthusiasm in Washington. But others may get a warmer response,
including hints by the Fox transition team that the president-elect
would be willing to trade a crackdown by Mexican law enforcement on
illegal immigration for more of so-called ``guest worker'' visas
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the U.S. economy continues to grow, there is a real
possibility a deal like that could happen,'' said Delal Baer, of
Washington's Center for International and Strategic Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``American industry is growing at a rapid enough rate that we
clearly have high demand for unskilled labor,'' she said. ``It's
just a matter of how you regulate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's overseas trip will also include two days in Canada, where
he will meet with Prime Minister Jean Chretien. The North American
visit is part of series of foreign trips Fox will make before
taking office Dec 1. The president-elect also will travel to South
and Central America and Europe, meeting with leaders of the
countries important to Mexico's political and economic interests.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
