<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     08-01 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHY WAS THIS DOC SMILING? 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trade deadline was over Monday. If you counted all the
relieved Yankees, you came up with a plethora, a whole bunch, a
minyan, a veritable majority:
</P>
<P>
   Six or eight left fielders. A passel of spare infielders. A few
no-name pitchers camping out in pup tents in the bullpen. Even Tino
Martinez, whom Joe Torre felt the need to sedate on Sunday with the
parting words, ``I'll see you Tuesday.'' Tino Martinez, for
goodness' sakes.
</P>
<P>
   Amidst all this rampant job insecurity, there was one guy who
hadn't really sweated it out. The Yankees need arms _ particularly
arms with functional heads in the vicinity _ and for the moment,
Dwight Gooden fits that description.
</P>
<P>
   The improbable Yankee, the accidental tourist, Gooden was on the
mound Tuesday night at Yankee Stadium against Kansas City, holding
the fort as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   While some Yankees reported to the stately old castle in the
Bronx with a sense of relief, Gooden showed up with the same huge
smile he sported in days of old. It was summertime and the living
was easy, at least until game time. Doc started with a perfect 3-0
record and an earned run average of 2.05 in his four appearances in
his astonishing return from the edge. He pitched seven innings
Tuesday night, after giving up one earned run on four hits. He
walked one and struck out four _ not vintage Doc, but good enough
to give the Yankees a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted to get imaginative about it, Doc's grin was so
all-encompassing that it included a bit of a smirk at the
ludicrousness of it. He was putting something over on the world,
which is always fun for a powerball pitcher who suddenly discovers
it is just as cool to see hitters splat one into the ground as it
is to see them strike out lustily.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was more surprised than Joe Torre, who, when presented
with Gooden last month, said he had been told by Tampa (the
nearer-my-Steinbrenner-to-thee bunker in Florida) that Gooden was
the best pitcher available, not exactly strong praise.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Gooden had bought time for the Yankees to regain first
place, Torre was seeing the humor in Gooden's emergence as a
pitcher of poise and control.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no pressure,'' Torre was saying Tuesday night. ``This
is a lark for him. It's like it was for me when I got fired from my
last job.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre recalled being let go by St. Louis in the summer of 1995
and being hired, somewhat surprisingly, by the Yankees for the 1996
season, and how he was in Cincinnati, his wife's hometown, and his
friends _ his friends, mind you _ were faxing him the ravings in
the tabloids calling him Clueless Joe and other niceties. What the
heck, Torre was back in the major leagues, the way Doc Gooden is
now back in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got released by his last club, a club under us,'' Torre
said. ``That's got to make you stop and think. He's going to enjoy
this ride as long as he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre admitted he was ``as surprised as anybody else'' when he
was handed Gooden to start the Queens portion of that eccentric
bicounty doubleheader with the Mets on July 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doc has to thank his lucky stars we were rained out,'' Torre
said. ``If it wasn't for that doubleheader. ... It gave him a
chance to have an adrenaline rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could have envisioned Gooden's being so cerebral in
his major league comeback, Torre responded with an emphatic ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched for Cleveland last year, he pitched for Houston and
Tampa Bay this year,'' Torre recited. ``It was the same. He'd get
deep into the pitch count. He kept trying to have you not hit the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if you're throwing 86 or 106,'' the manager
said, alluding to velocity. ``You still have to throw strikes. It
really works against you if you're always 2-1 or 3-1 instead of 1-2
or 0-2. Now the hitter has to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to elaborate on why he was so surprised at Gooden's
transformation, Torre said: ``I'd watched him pitch. I knew he had
the ability to change, but I didn't know if he would. I'm pleased
for him. Baseball is still big in what he does. It's great to see a
smile on his face.''
</P>
<P>
   There will probably be other starts for Gooden. David Cone is
still in Florida on his Boss-mandated sabbatical, studying at the
feet of the guru, Billy Connors. El Duque Hernandez started in the
minors last night and may be back soon, or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice for a manager to be faced with six starters,'' Torre
said, knowing he needs four at most for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that Doc has the capability to come out of the bullpen, it
gives us more flexibility,'' said Torre, smiling quite a bit, but
not nearly as much as Dwight Gooden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
