<SLUG> BC-ACTORS-STRIKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKING ACTORS GO ON FAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Hoping to up the ante in the 14-week-old
commercial actors strike, five union actors went on a ``rolling
fast'' Tuesday, swearing off solid food indefinitely to publicize
their cause.
</P>
<P>
   Screen Actors Guild officials said union members, through
persistence or substitutions, would keep up the fast until a new
contract is reached with the advertising industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about martyrdom or starvation, it's about
education and inspiration for all members of the union,'' said
union member James Arone, who relocated his wife and three children
from their Burbank house so it could be used for ``ACT FAST.''
</P>
<P>
   The longest commercial actors strike in union history is nowhere
near resolution; both sides refuse to budge from their positions
and no new talks are scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are deadly serious about this,'' strike
coordinator Michael Brennan said on behalf of the SAG and the
American Federation of Television and Radio Artists. ``They see no
other way to resolve this, considering that the other side made it
painfully clear in the last two attempts at negotiation that they
don't want to talk to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the advertising industry did not return
repeated calls seeking comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Actors want to be paid residuals for ads on cable television, as
they are now paid for network spots. They also want jurisdiction
over commercials shot for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers want to eliminate the residual system and instead
pay actors a flat fee for all commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The strike has cost the Los Angeles County economy an estimated
$70 million in lost wages and support services, according to county
economic experts.
</P>
<P>
   Arone is being joined in the fast by S.A. Griffin, Peaches
Johnson, Raymond O'Connor and Jeri Zucchi.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Day One,'' Arone said, while refusing to say how long
he would go without food. ``I plan on personally going more than
one day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
