<SLUG> BC-GOP-TV-RATINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FIRST NIGHT: FEW WATCHED, AND NOT FOR VERY LONG 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television ratings for the first night of the Republican
National Convention indicated that only a small fraction of the
total television audience watched the prime-time portion of the
event.
</P>
<P>
   On ABC and CBS, the two broadcast networks that offered just an
hour of prime-time coverage each on Monday, only about 13 million
total viewers tuned in, or about 15 percent of the total television
audience. And on CBS, which interrupted its convention coverage for
a repeat of a segment of its newsmagazine ``48 Hours,'' on the
subject of medical experiments on human patients, about half the
audience left when the network shifted to pure convention coverage
at 10:30 p.m. The convention coverage on both ABC and CBS was
beaten by a repeat episode of the show ``Third Watch'' on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.5 million watched PBS, which had three hours of
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   On the three all-news cable channels, a total of 2.4 million
viewers watched the evening convention events. CNN had the biggest
audience, 1.2 million, compared with 676,000 for Fox News and
516,000 for MSNBC.
</P>
</TEXT>
