<SLUG> BC-CNV-GOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERTSON SAYS CHRISTIAN COALITION `JUST WARMING UP' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Countering the conciliatory mood of the
Republican National Convention, speakers at a Christian Coalition
of America rally here Tuesday denounced pop culture, the U.S.
Department of Education and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelist and commentator Pat Robertson, founder of the
coalition, asserted that the organization has been wrongly written
off as a force in national politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of reading stories saying the Christian Coalition is
dead,'' Robertson said. ``We're just warming up, folks.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Sam Brownback of Kansas, one of several Republican
officeholders who addressed the audience as warm-up acts for
Robertson, revived a phrase that often fills GOP strategists with
regret.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback, stoked by applause from about 1,800 people packed
into a hotel ballroom, criticized violence in the mass media and
urged religious voters ``to engage in the great cultural battle for
the soul of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said the 2000 election is no time to be dainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a convention of sweetness and light,'' he said.
``Nobody wants to rock the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson called for dismantling the U.S. Department of
Education, saying he could do a better job with the agency's money
by educating children through private, religious projects.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Bush made sure that the party dropped its
long-running call for the department to be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I frankly agree with Ronald Reagan,'' Robertson said. ``I
think they should do away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky rocked another boat
Tuesday in his role as the Senate's leading foe of legislation that
would place further limits on the way candidates and parties
finance their campaigns with contributions from individuals and
special interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hear the three words `campaign finance reform,' some
liberal is trying to shut you up,'' McConnell said. ``No matter how
you dress up that turkey, it still won't fly.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the legislation would blunt the Christian Coalition from
pooling its financial resources to ``amplify'' its messages.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond discussion of their favorite issues, the ``Faith &AMP;
Freedom Celebration'' was the Christian Coalition's assertion that
it remains relevant to the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   That Bush is a born-again Christian who opposes abortion and is
running on a ``pro-family'' agenda shows that the coalition is on
the cusp of its goal to have such a person in the White House,
Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Rice University Professor William Martin, author of a book on
the evolution of the religious right, said groups such as the
coalition have become pragmatic and less raucous while continuing
to represent about a sixth of the national electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power of the religious right was overestimated, and now it
is being underestimated,'' he said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
