<SLUG> BC-COKE-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK EMPLOYEES AT COKE MAY FILE SEPARATE DISCRIMINATION SUITS 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Exclusive)  By   CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A former Coca-Cola benefits manager who has criticized the
company's treatment of black workers said on Tuesday that he would
urge those workers to retain lawyers to help them determine whether
they should accept a settlement reached in June between Coke and
four black employees who sued the company or file their own suits.
The terms of the settlement have not yet been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The manager, Larry Jones, plans to hold a news conference on
Friday in Atlanta. He said on Tuesday that he would tell his former
colleagues not to wait until October, when the terms of the
settlement are scheduled to be announced, to assess whether they
would be better off as part of the agreement, which covers all
black salaried employees from 1995 to the present. Jones said he
was arranging to have lawyers, other than those already involved,
help employees decide what action to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawyers would look at their individual cases and talk to
them about the pros and cons of going after individual claims,''
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in April 1999 in federal court in Atlanta,
contends that black employees at Coke were denied promotions,
raises and other benefits because of their skin color. Coke has
denied that any discrimination took place. Many of the employees
say they are unsure of how to proceed, particularly because the
specifics of the settlement are still secret. ``I'm very
frustrated,'' said Yvette Frierson, a former employee. ``They're
telling us, `Oh, we've reached a decision,' but they aren't giving
us any details. As far as I'm concerned, they haven't reached a
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Since March, the lawsuit has taken a complicated turn, resulting
in confusion for many of the employees who would be affected by the
settlement. After a dispute over the settlement's financial terms,
four of the eight plaintiffs split off from the original legal
team, led by Cyrus Mehri, a Washington lawyer. They signed on with
Willie E. Gary, a Florida personal-injury specialist who became
involved with the case in early April.
</P>
<P>
   Gary, who is chairman of a cable television channel that
recently signed a large advertising contract with Coke, filed a
$1.5 billion lawsuit in Georgia state court in June, the day the
settlement of the federal suit was announced. His clients in that
lawsuit are four black women who formerly worked at Coke. Gary has
said that he has no conflict of interest despite Coke's business
dealings with his cable channel. His co-counsel on the lawsuit is
Johnnie L. Cochran, who defended O.J. Simpson at his murder trial
in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
