<HEADER>
A9938 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-CAR-GASPEDALS0802-COX     08-01 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GASPEDALS0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR sets two safety rules in wake of fatal crashes
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Winston Cup teams support NASCAR's new safety rules,
calling them ``a step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The sport's governing body issued technical bulletins Tuesday
that mandate two safety devices: an independent stop on a car's
throttle assembly and an ignition on-off switch within the reach of
the driver's thumb. The changes will take effect immediately,
beginning with Saturday's Brickyard 400 at Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The two modifications are NASCAR's initial technical reactions
to the recent deaths of drivers Kenny Irwin and Adam Petty at New
Hampshire International Speedway. The investigations are
incomplete, but both drivers appeared to be hindered by stuck
throttles that sent their cars smashing into the outside-retainer
wall at high speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are changes I can't see anybody disagreeing with,''
driver Jeremy Mayfield said. ``They don't take anything away from
the race cars, they don't affect competition but they can save you
from a pretty hard crash. You have to applaud NASCAR for taking
steps like these.''
</P>
<P>
   Several teams, including the No. 36 Pontiac of Atlanta-owned MB2
Motorsports, had already been using the safety devices for the past
two races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a great move by NASCAR _ just another step
they are taking to make the sport safer,'' said Sammy Johns, crew
chief for Ken Schrader. ``(But) we're still looking for other ways
to make it even safer for our driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Makar, who works for Winston Cup points leader Bobby
Labonte and is considered a dean of the crew chiefs, said the
modifications are ``definitely a move in the right direction'' and
``certainly, any action that can be taken is better than nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Makar, and Tommy Baldwin, crew chief for Ward Burton, are among
many teams studying the automatic throttle-kill systems used in
NASCAR's modified series. The system, which is sensor-based and in
the engine's linkage, already has been approved for Winston Cup
teams to use voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things out there to go a step further than (the two
new changes) that we're looking at right now, even though they
aren't quite ready to use in our cars,'' Makar said. ``We're
getting them worked on and tested. If it works, we'll put it in the
car.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty was killed in May and Irwin in July at the Loudon, N.H.,
oval.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
