<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPEFULLY, HUGGINS VETO WILL LEAD TO PROTESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm heartened to read that as many as 50,000 demonstrators are
expected to converge on the Staples Center at mid-month to protest
the goings-on inside.
</P>
<P>
   It's about time somebody turned up the heat on the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Clippers owner Donald Sterling hit a new low this week. The most
humiliating of his many humiliations unfolded in two stages: He
offered $2 million a year for four years to a college coach without
a national championship to gloss up the resume; then the college
coach said no thanks, you can keep your $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   This was reality slapping Sterling in the face. With any luck
Sterling was taking a look in the mirror at the time. It might take
such a combination of metaphors to show this guy what's wrong with
the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   If they can't attract a ``name'' coach like Bob Huggins this
summer, they'll never do it.
</P>
<P>
   Things have been looking up: The Clippers are out of the
despised Sports Arena and comfortably ensconced in the Staples
Center, where they are no worse than the third-ranking tenant. They
are teeming with talented rookies after their smartest draft in
years, and the innocents are pledging to stay together and build a
contender. Their top free agent, Maurice Taylor, is as good as
gone, but you take the bad with the good in this franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The arena and the rookie class are the positives that would
cause somebody like Huggins, the University of Cincinnati coach, to
give the Clippers a look.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Sterling still has those midcourt owners' seats,
which is the kind of negative that would cause somebody like
Huggins to give the Clippers the brush-off.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins announced his decision to stay in Cincinnati by saying:
``I took a lot of things into consideration and I think the thing
for me to do at this point in time is to stay here and continue
what we started.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice arena, improving roster, same old owner. Let's see: Reading
Huggins' mind, which of the things he took into consideration might
have dissuaded him?
</P>
<P>
   There's simply no future in the Clippers as long as Sterling is
signing the checks.
</P>
<P>
   This week the Clippers' search for a head coach to replace the
fired Chris Ford will stretch into a seventh month. Closer to the
start of next season than the end of last season, they are the only
NBA team without a coach.
</P>
<P>
   They'll likely end up hiring somebody like Alvin Gentry, John
Lucas or Dennis Johnson, and it'll be a return to the glorious eras
of Don Casey, Mike Schuler and Bob Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling and the Clippers have been late-night monologue jokes
for so long _ 19 seasons, of which one was a winning season and one
was a .500 season _ that you wonder if the owner realizes the team
has fans who are seriously disappointed in its lack of improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any hope of persuading the businessman who never sells
anything to sell the Clippers to somebody who won't scare coaches
and players away? Let's consider how this might be accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   A public boycott of Clippers home games? Not likely to be
effective, since for most Clippers home games the difference would
be undetectable.
</P>
<P>
   A public boycott of Sterling property? Not likely to be adhered
to because if half of Beverly Hills is declared off-limits, where
would we purchase our mink coats?
</P>
<P>
   No, it appears a full-scale demonstration is the best solution.
So as long as thousands of activists are massing at the borders in
preparation for nonviolent protests during a political party's
convention the week after next, perhaps we can persuade a few to
carry placards for a new cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sterling Must Go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Down With the Clippers' Oppressor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice for All, Not Only Lakers Fans.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a week.
He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
