<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOUR-GREENSCENE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PGA PRO DOESN'T ALWAYS MEAN WOODS, DUVAL OR ELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a daily source of confusion in an industry that employs
more than 25,000 nationwide and nearly 1,500 in Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Greatswing is introduced as a PGA professional and almost
immediately will be asked something about play on the pro tour.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Gunn, teaching professional at Moorpark's Tierra Rejada
Golf Course, has the bottom-line answer for that one. It's an old
joke in the industry but also way too accurate for too many of the
golf professionals who make up the world's largest working sports
organization:
</P>
<P>
   ``The old saying among PGA professionals is PGA stands for `Put
your Golf clubs Away,''' said Gunn, one of the fortunate few in his
profession who gets to occasionally sample life at the tip of the
pro golf iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the PGA Tour, which represents less than two
percent of the golf professionals in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion stems from the names: the PGA of America, founded
in 1916, and the PGA Tour, which began in 1968 when the Tournament
Players Division split off from the PGA of America and took charge
of tour play.
</P>
<P>
   ``PGA Tour players have one job and that's trying to get the
most out of their golf game, period,'' said Gunn. ``A PGA golf
professional for the most part is running a pro shop _ making sure
the carts are running, the merchandise is ordered, the food and tee
times and greens superintendent and course is set up, and it goes
on and on and on. The PGA professional wears many hats.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, it's not one he's seen wearing on weekend television.
But there have been notable exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman, a former assistant pro at Wood Ranch in Simi Valley,
went from teaching golf to ruling it in less than a decade,
advancing from club instructor to winning the British Open
championship and being named PGA Tour Player of the Year in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom was a classic case, and there are a few of them,'' Gunn
said, ``where you look at a guy and say, `What's wrong with him _
why isn't he on tour?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And the answer is, not a thing is wrong. He's good enough to
be out there doing great. Jeff Freeman (the SCPGA champion who won
last year's national club pro championship and nearly won this
year's Nissan Open) is another. Whatever life circumstances bring _
maybe they missed a cut in tour school or whatever _ they're off
the tour when they might actually have the ability to be on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it comes down to job security. Brad Gallagher, who
once recorded eight consecutive birdies to set a Canadian Tour
record but also failed PGA Tour qualifying school nine times, has
settled for a full-time job at Robinson Ranch. The tour might have
its allure, but steady pay has its own benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be the big difference,'' Gunn said. ``If a
professional player doesn't play well, he basically doesn't get
paid. It's a much more stable existence for a PGA professional. I
couldn't believe the first time I started getting paid for lessons
whether I thought the lessons went well or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunn, who formerly instructed at Lake Lindero Country Club in
Agoura, is accomplished enough as a golfer to have played in two
U.S. Opens _ most recently the 1997 national championship at
Congressional Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   He was wandering outside the ropes at this year's centennial
Open at Pebble Beach, wishing he were inside playing but also
remembering his thought process during a reality check practice
round with Lehman at Congressional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took ten bucks from him,'' Gunn said, ``and the whole time
I'm thinking, `Thank God I'm not playing this guy for my
mortgage.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's that consistency of quality that keeps PGA Tour players in
golf's top league, Gunn said. The club pros might be able to
compete with a touring pro on any given day, but only the best can
do it consistently _ in which case they generally move on to the
tour. Other notable club pros to make that switch with great
success were Sam Snead and Ralph Guldahl, the 1939 Masters winner
and two-time U.S. Open champion who concluded his golf career at
Tarzana's Braemar Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some wonderful success stories out there,'' Jeff
Johnson, director of golf operations at the PGA of Southern
California Golf Club at Oak Valley, said of club pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly is a distinction (between PGA Tour players and
PGA professionals),'' Johnson said, ``but it's an allied
association. We're looking after the business of the game of golf
and growing the game of golf, and those great players on tour are
inspiring more people to take up the game. It's really a win-win
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   And while a PGA professional deals with issues ranging from
event planning to merchandising to agronomics to fund-raising to
rules arbitration and much, much more, the most-rewarding part of
the job _ apart from a steady paycheck _ might be the instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Gunn, who does only that at Tierra Rejada, cites golf newcomer
Beau Gooliak as an example. Gooliak took up the game only a year
ago and shot 80 in his first tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The satisfaction of that accomplishment left both of them
beaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always fun to see when it happens to a friend, if you
will,'' Gunn said, ``because they become friends after a while.
That's about as good as it gets.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
