<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-PROTESTS-0802-COX     08-01 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-PROTESTS-0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MASS ARRESTS AS PROTESTERS DISRUPT PHILADELPHIA
 &HT;    By JIM GALLOWAY and ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Roving crowds of protesters clashed violently
with police Tuesday, paralyzing large sections of the city's
downtown as delegates tried to make their way to the second night
of the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The skirmishes were the first large-scale confrontations of the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   By 9 p.m. (ET), more than 300 protesters had been arrested or
detained, and traffic had resumed to something close to normal.
Republican officials reported a number of state delegations
delayed, but none were prevented from making it to the GOP meeting
several miles away at the First Union Center.
</P>
<P>
   Reports on injuries to protesters weren't immediately available.
Lt. Dennis Konczyk of the Philadelphia Police Department said one
female police officer was injured when an unidentified liquid was
thrown in her face.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators, some wearing black bandanas or ski masks over
their faces, were protesting a wide variety of issues ranging from
the death penalty to U.S. involvement in a ``drug war'' in Colombia
to the expense of AIDS medication.
</P>
<P>
   Police acknowledged that the protesters were marginally
successful in their effort to disrupt both delegates and local
rush-hour commuters. ``I call today a wash,'' Konczyk said.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of mostly peaceful demonstrations, protesters had
promised there would be disruptions on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Many protesters were demonstrating against what they said was
corporate influence on the major political parties and the
government. Some chanted: ``Capitalist pigs go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Stacey Falls, a 23-year-old who traveled to Philadelphia from
Michigan, said that she was protesting ``everything''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our government is dominated by corporations. We are the
richest country in the world and still cannot provide health care
or good education for the poor,'' Falls said. ``I'm not protesting
just about the Republicans, I'm protesting against both parties
since they are run by the same corporate sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   Several protesters dressed up in costumes with goats as heads,
calling themselves ``the goats with the votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Fitzpatrick, 29, from Philadelphia, said that the
``goats'' were protesting ``the two party system that is backed by
the same corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country is run by just one party _ the corporations,''
said 21-year-old student Justin Leto, who lives near Philadelphia,
shortly before he was arrested for blocking a downtown street.
</P>
<P>
   There were even a group of protesters dressed up as clowns who
claimed to be protesting the protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the protesting clowns,'' said Melanie, an 18-year-old
from Philadelphia, who did not give her last name but insisted on
being called Snogg. ``We are protesting about protest, but us
clowns are protesters at heart.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the clowns, other protesters wore cardboard horse
heads.
</P>
<P>
   The worst exchanges came near the Wyndham Franklin Plaza Hotel
where Texas Gov. George W. Bush will be staying Wednesday and
Thursday. Protesters began slashing the tires of police vehicles,
dumping orange paint on other police cars and spray-painting
obscenities on others. A short time later, police responded with
batons after protesters hit them.
</P>
<P>
   But the largest crowds gathered around City Hall, where police
responded with phalanxes of horses and squads of officers on
bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   Over city blocks that spanned miles, demonstrators and police
played a rush-hour game of cat-and-mouse. Demonstrators would often
sit or stand in the street, their arms inter-linked and their hands
clasped in plastic pipes.
</P>
<P>
   Once lines of police horses began to push them back, the
demonstrators would retreat to another location.
</P>
<P>
   Spectators and homeward-bound workers outnumbered protesters at
some locations. Sometimes they found their routes home blocked by
police lines and demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to get home on the R-7,'' Winifred Simmons complained
to police, pointing to her subway stop.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, 58, was loaded with 72 rolls of toilet paper. ``These
people making the demonstrations need to cool out.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
