<SLUG> BC-BKN-FREE-AGENTS0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA's Day 1 big deal lands Eddie Jones in Miami
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - A funny thing happened to Tuesday's Day 1 gold rush in
the NBA: not as much as expected.
</P>
<P>
   The news was that Pat Riley obtained Charlotte's Eddie Jones in
a nine-player deal that could give the coach his first trip to the
Finals with the Miami Heat.
</P>
<P>
   Going to Miami with Jones were Anthony Mason, Ricky Davis and
Dale Ellis. The Hornets got Jamal Mashburn, P.J. Brown, Tim James,
Otis Thorpe and Rodney Buford.
</P>
<P>
   But the free-agent news Tuesday mainly centered on second-tier
players.
</P>
<P>
   The reason was that the Orlando Magic convinced Grant Hill and
Tracy McGrady that it would be best to hold off signing until
today. Either way, the players get deals worth about $9.6 million
each in the first year. McGrady is expected to get a six-year deal
worth an estimated $72 million. Hill wants only four years, worth
$44 million, to bring him to a 10-year level that allows a much
higher salary structure.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando is trying to clear room for Clippers forward Maurice
Taylor. The Magic was shopping former Georgia Tech star Matt
Harpring during the day. In the Miami-Charlotte deal, Jones took a
career deal worth about $86.3 million over seven years from the
Heat in a sign-and-trade. It was $20 million more than the Chicago
Bulls could offer in a six-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Turned down by all top free agents, the Bulls apparently will do
no better than much-traveled Ron Mercer, who has gone from Boston
to Denver to Orlando at a dizzying pace. The Bulls also might sign
the Hornets' backup center, Brad Miller, for $5 million a year,
about $1 million more than the league average Charlotte is allowed
to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Mason is one of several players who had persistent legal
problems in Charlotte. Mason played his best basketball for the
Knicks when Riley was the coach there. He played point forward, at
one stage of his career and moves into P.J. Brown's forward slot.
</P>
<P>
   Hornets executive Bob Bass, who helped the Lakers win a
championship when he dealt Glen Rice to Los Angeles,
unintentionally might have helped Miami reach that level. Jones and
Mason are much more versatile than Mashburn and Brown, the
principal players shipped north to Charlotte. Only five years ago,
the Heat acquired Alonzo Mourning from Charlotte for Rice and Matt
Geiger, who plays now for Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Hawks declined a deal from the Lakers that would have sent
Rice to Atlanta for power forward Lorenzen Wright.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Austin Croshere (Indiana) and Cuttino Mobley (Houston) were
not swayed by the prospect of playing for Lenny Wilkens in Toronto.
They agreed to remain with their original teams, Croshere with a
seven-year, $51 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Backup point guard Bobby Jackson is leaving Minnesota for
Sacramento for five years and $13.4 million. Jackson arrives as
Kings reserve guard Tony Delk leaves. Delk, a free agent, agreed to
contract terms with the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Former Knicks and Warriors guard John Starks said he is
signing with Utah to replace retired Jeff Hornacek, and guard
Derrick Anderson apparently will leave the Clippers. He might sign
with the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
