<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS AND THEIR ALLIES ATTACK BUSH IN ADS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Accusing the Republican Party of using its
convention to mask Gov. George W. Bush's stands on controversial
issues, Democrats and groups with close ties to them are unleashing
commercials that criticize his record in Texas as well as his
positions on gun control and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The groups _ Planned Parenthood, Handgun Control and the Sierra
Club _ are all running commercials singling out Bush in a week in
which Republicans are staging a convention that was intended to
sidestep divisive topics like abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest barrage is coming from the Democratic National
Committee, which has been releasing at least one new advertisement
each day, and plans to continue doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the committee unveiled a 30-second commercial, to be
broadcast in 17 crucial states from the Pacific Northwest to New
England, that accuses Bush of favoring ``the big drug companies,
the HMOs and the insurance industry'' over Texas residents.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic staff members, including one of the party's national
chairmen, Joe Andrew, have set up shop here to reinforce their
contention that the Republicans are glossing over what they view as
Bush's deeply conservative agenda in an effort to appeal to
moderate Democrats and independents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to create an illusion that they are something
other than they are,'' Andrew said, adding that his party has more
than 20 staff members and a bus, called the Rolling Donkey, that
ferries reporters to the news conferences it is holding in Sheet
Metal Hall, a couple of miles from the First Union Center, where
the Republicans are meeting. ``We knew they were going to try to
set up this Vegas lounge act, and not tell people who they are,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have injected a bit of partisan invective into an
otherwise thoroughly upbeat, stage-managed week in Philadelphia. It
is a reminder that though the campaign has been a fairly
understated affair, it could get a lot tougher fast.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew said that with all the mass communication techniques _
the party is running seven anti-Bush Web sites _ it may sound as if
the strategy is novel. ``But it's not,'' he said. ``It's actually
old-fashioned. We're back to making sure people know what's going
on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans say the Democrats' strategy is a sign of
weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Democrats look at Governor Bush's inclusive style
and they've gone into full party panic,'' said Ari Fleischer, a
Bush spokesman. ``The more they attack, the more people don't like
Al Gore's manner of campaigning. They are sick and tired of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest commercial follows a theme that forces allied with
Democrats have been returning to again and again: Bush's record in
Texas. This one compares the governor's commitment to health care
unfavorably with Gore's. ``George Bush: His plan protects special
interests instead of working families,'' the announcer says as the
screen shows a black and white portrait of an utterly forlorn woman
in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   The special interest groups say their goal is to ensure that
like-minded voters who might be misled by the convivial tone of the
convention and the campaign understand that on issues like health
care and abortion rights, Bush is out of step.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Feldt, president of the Planned Parenthood Federation of
America, said focus groups found that many women who identified
themselves as moderate to conservative and who supported abortion
rights were not aware of Bush's opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They assumed he was pro-choice because he appears moderate,''
Feldt said.
</P>
<P>
   Feldt said the advertising campaign, which began last month and
is running on cable television stations around the country, is the
first on the presidential level for the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has been extraordinarily successful at obfuscating, at
fuzzying around the edges of issues, especially on reproductive
health and rights,'' she said. Additional advertisements are
planned after the party conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer said that the Democrats' efforts only pointed up
Gore's own fuzziness on issues like gun control; Bush is considered
a reliable ally of the National Rifle Association, a group Gore
regularly attacks but did work with on issues when he was in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he'd stay on one position long enough on the question of
guns,'' Fleischer said, ``he'd be subject to criticism as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
