<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dow and S&AMP;P 500 Gain, But Nasdaq Slumps 2.2%
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were mixed as investors switched out of technology
companies on fears that their earnings growth might slow and moved
into more traditional and cheaper sectors, like consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average gained 84.97 points, or 0.8
percent, to 10,606.95, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
gained 7.27 points, or 0.5 percent, to 1,438.10. The
technology-laden Nasdaq composite index fell 81.47 points, or 2.2
percent, to 3,685.52.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G Meets Lowered Estimates
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble, beset by rising costs, management turmoil and
credibility problems on Wall Street, reported fourth-quarter
results that were in line with lowered forecasts but said that
earnings growth in the first half of its new fiscal year would be
sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Coke Manager Gives Suit Advice
</P>
<P>
   A former Coca-Cola benefits manager who has criticized the
company's treatment of black workers said that he would urge those
workers to retain lawyers to help them determine whether they
should accept a settlement reached in June between Coke and four
black employees or file their own suits.
</P>
<P>
   Three Labels to Sell Music Online
</P>
<P>
   In a potentially fundamental change to the way music has been
packaged, at least three major record labels _ EMI, Universal and
Sony _ plan to begin selling songs over the Internet by the end of
the year, enabling users to listen to or download songs for a flat
fee.
</P>
<P>
   Ad Server Attracts Big Investors
</P>
<P>
   Advertising.com, which develops systems that send ads to Web
sites to be shown to computer users, is hoping to help accelerate
its growth with investments totaling $57 million from sources that
include major agency and media companies.
</P>
<P>
   Softbank Won't Sell Shares in Units
</P>
<P>
   Softbank abandoned a plan to sell shares in five subsidiaries,
citing potentially costly tax consequences. But there was
speculation that Softbank abandoned the plan partly because a
spinoff might have made the company less attractive to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed Signals in Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Purchasing Management said that its
factory index was unchanged in July at 51.8, the lowest level since
January 1999, but government figures showed consumer spending rose
0.5 percent in June after rising 0.3 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
   Sales Offset Payouts on Air Delays
</P>
<P>
   Hal Rosenbluth, whose travel management company offered in May
to pay cash refunds to customers whose flights were delayed, has
paid out more than he expected during this summer of delays and
cancellations. But he isn't complaining because ticket sales on the
company's Web site are up 40 percent.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
