<HEADLINE>
BRUCE JAMES ENNIS, DIRECTOR OF THE ACLU, DIES AT 60 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn., N.H., Ill., Calif., Mo.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruce James Ennis, a First Amendment lawyer and former legal
director of the American Civil Liberties Union, died on Saturday at
a hospital in Boston, where he was taken from his summer home on
Martha's Vineyard. He was 60 and lived in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from leukemia, Paul Smith of the
Washington law firm Jenner &AMP; Block said. Ennis was a senior partner
there.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Ennis appeared as counsel in some 250 cases
before the U.S. Supreme Court, representing litigants as well as
friends of the court. The National Law Journal has listed him among
the country's 100 most influential lawyers since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He became known nationally for his work to protect the mentally
ill and retarded. More recently he dealt chiefly with First
Amendment matters involving the print media, cable television, the
Internet, communications laws and related Constitutional law
issues.
</P>
<P>
   He came to prominence with the first case he argued in the
Supreme Court. Known as the Donaldson case, it ended in the court's
unanimously ruling in 1975 that nonviolent mental patients had
important rights, including the right not to be deprived of liberty
and the right to sue state hospital officials for damages if that
right is violated.
</P>
<P>
   One case in the 1990s, ACLU et al. vs. Reno, helped clarify the
constitutionality of government regulation of free speech on the
Internet. While he was on the staff of the ACLU he successfully
defended The Progressive magazine when the federal government tried
to suppress an article about the hydrogen bomb.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Knoxville, Tenn., Bruce Ennis graduated cum laude
from Dartmouth College in 1962. He received a doctor of laws degree
in 1965 at the University of Chicago, where he was elected to the
Order of the Coif and served on The Chicago Law Review.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the ACLU as a staff lawyer in 1968. He was its lead
counsel in the notorious long-running Willowbrook case in the
1970s, exposing one of the world's largest and most squalid
institutions for the mentally retarded, on Staten Island. The
exposure resulted in sweeping reforms statewide.
</P>
<P>
   From 1977 to 1982 he served as the organization's legal
director, heading a national staff of 26 lawyers and coordinating
strategies with thousands of cooperating lawyers across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   He then was a founding member of the Washington law firm Ennis,
Friedman, Bersoff &AMP; Ewing. The firm was merged into Jenner &AMP; Block
in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Ennis is survived by his wife, Emily Newhall Ennis; two teen-age
sons, Alexander and Bradley; his mother, Jane Burgin of Kansas
City, Mo.; and a sister, Elizabeth Ennis-Thomas of Corte Madera,
Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9952 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-DRUGS-NYT &LR;      08-01 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC COMMISSION APPROVES NEW DRUG TESTS AT OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The medical commission of the International Olympic Committee
Tuesday approved the use of a combination of urine and blood tests
to detect the use of the performance-enhancing drug EPO at the 2000
Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   If the new test is endorsed as expected by the IOCs legal
commission and executive board later this month, between 300 and
700 out-of-competition tests will be conducted randomly in Sydney
from Sept. 2, when the Olympic Village opens, until the conclusion
of the Games on Oct. 1, said Dr. Patrick Schamasch, the IOCs
medical director. Out-of-competition tests, which are administered
without notice, are considered the only reliable way to catch drug
cheats.
</P>
<P>
   Erythropoietin, known as EPO, is produced naturally by the
kidneys and stimulates the production of red blood cells. A
synthetic version can be a wonder drug for those who suffer from
anemia and AIDS and those who are undergoing chemotherapy. In elite
sport, however, EPO is believed to be used widely and illicitly to
increase oxygen-carrying capacity in endurance sports such as
cycling, distance running and swimming.
</P>
<P>
   EPO was at the center of the Tour de France drug scandal in
1998, which led to enormous pressure by international governments
for the IOC to develop a reliable method to detect the drug's use.
For the Sydney Games, scientists intend to use an
Australian-developed blood test in combination with a urine test
developed by French researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Each test has its strengths and weaknesses. The blood test can
detect the use of EPO over several weeks, but only indirectly. The
urine test can detect direct use of EPO, but only for three days.
</P>
<P>
   Many questions remain about an EPO test for Sydney, scientists
and drug-testing experts said Tuesday. Has the fast-tracked test
undergone sufficient peer review? Can it withstand legal scrutiny?
Will a significant number of so-called false positives ruin
athletes' reputations unfairly? How much of a deterrent will the
test actually create in Sydney, after athletes have already
benefited from the training advantages provided by EPO?
</P>
<P>
   Even with the detectability of EPO, the use of
performance-enhancing drugs is likely to be extensive at the Sydney
Games. There will be no tests to detect substances like
human-growth hormone, insulin-growth factor and products that work
essentially as artificial blood. Drug use has become so
sophisticated that athletes use topical steroid gels that flush
from the system in hours. Some drug-testing experts also believe
that the introduction of an EPO test will simply lead athletes to
return to undetectable blood doping, in which blood is removed from
a particular athlete and later reinserted to increase
oxygen-carrying capacity.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, however, athletes who use EPO now face the
possibility that they could be caught while at the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we achieved a major step,'' Schamasch said in a
telephone conference call from IOC headquarters in Lausanne,
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the drugs that remain undetectable, he said: ``It's
a step you know. Paris wasn't built in one day. The final victory
against doping needs to be done step by step. Many steps build a
stairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gary I. Wadler, a professor of medicine at New York
University and an expert on performance-enhancing drugs, said that
although he believed the introduction of an EPO test was
significant, he wished there had been more time to validate the
test for athletes who live at various altitudes and with respect to
sex and race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the issues that always surface when someone tests
positive,'' Wadler said. ``The lawyers are going to feast on
whether this has been validated sufficiently by an independent
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Shorter, the 1972 Olympic marathon champion, who will head
an independent American drug-testing agency after the Sydney Games,
said an EPO test was a ``huge step'' in the fight against drug
cheats. But, he added, simply instituting the test in Sydney would
create only a mild deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   If the IOC is serious about treating the issue as a drug problem
instead of a public-relations problem, Shorter said, it would begin
using or threatening to use the EPO test immediately, saving urine
and blood samples of athletes taken now and through the Sydney
Games. Thus, cheating athletes would be worried that they might be
caught now or later, and a real deterrent would be created for the
Summer Games, he contended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is an opportunity to shift the psychological advantage
from cheaters to clean athletes,'' Shorter said. ``Let's not fall
asleep now.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Yesalis, a Penn State professor who is an authority on
performance-enhancing drugs and a longtime critic of the IOCs
drug-testing procedures, reacted skeptically. ``Nothing's changing
here,'' he said. ``Somebody tell me why athletes won't go back to
blood doping. These Games are going to be as drug laden as the
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesalis said he was concerned that what he called the
``short-circuiting'' of the scientific method to approve an EPO
test might result in innocent athletes being accused unfairly. He
said the test ``smacked of public relations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After four decades of pathetic behavior, the stench of
hypocrisy is overwhelming,'' he said, noting that the IOC had
fallen years and millions of dollars behind in research for drug
tests. ``If they expect me to get warm and fuzzy feelings, sorry,
I'm burned out after four decades of disingenuous behavior.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-GOP &LR; - &UR; N     08-01 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-GOP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: COLORIZING THE REPUBLICAN CONVENTION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT   By BRENT STAPLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The African-Americans and Latinos being paraded
across the stage at the Republican Convention are intended to give
a hip, multicultural feel _ and dispel the pervasive notion that
the GOP is largely a party of, by and for white Americans. But
subtract the minority props _ the break dancers and the gospel
choir and the beaming schoolchildren _ and what you have is the
same ultra-white party that shocked many Americans' sensibilities
at the 1992 and 1996 conventions. The deluge of black and Latin
faces on display in Philadelphia is deceptive, given that the
party's delegates and senior managers are as white as they have
ever been.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the realization among the party fathers that Americans
have grown uncomfortable with unremitting whiteness is a
breakthrough in itself. The problem for the GOP is how to move from
patronizing spectacles like this one, in which blacks and Latinos
serve as props, to a state of affairs where minority Americans are
both welcomed and actively recruited into the party as full-fledged
participants. Given the party's recent history of code words and
writing off the minority vote, it will take more than break dancers
on the convention stage to change this picture.
</P>
<P>
   This seemingly colorized convention in Philadelphia is in fact
very white, with black voters accounting for 4 percent of the
delegates and Asians about 2 percent. It may seem difficult to
believe, but the Philadelphia convention is whiter than the
convention of 1992, whose whiteness provoked many voters to reject
the GOP in favor of the multicultural Democrats. The Philadelphia
convention is whiter even than the convention of 1912, when 6
percent of the delegates were black. That gathering sent William
Howard Taft into his doomed re-election run and resulted in the
worst defeat ever experienced by an incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the party, angered that Taft had defeated the comeback
effort of their favorite, former President Theodore Roosevelt,
engineered a change in the rules. This undercut the strength of the
South, where most black voters, many of whom were Republicans,
still lived. The 6 percent figure for black delegates has been a
high-water mark since then.
</P>
<P>
   Black people were pushed further and further away, beginning in
the 1960s, when the GOP adopted its famed Southern strategy and
sought to portray the Democrats as hostile to white Southern
interests. This alienation reached its zenith in the 1980s, when
the party used divisive tactics as a way of getting out the white
vote.
</P>
<P>
   This strategy was helpful in the short term. But it ignored
demographic and attitudinal changes that would soon make it
self-defeating. First, white Americans, who make up about 80
percent of the population today, are a steadily shrinking majority,
losing ground to Americans of Latin, Asian and African descent. The
inevitable ``browning'' of America is happening fastest among
school-age children, where nonwhites will become the majority by
the year 2050. The Democrats went where the votes were, and by now
their party enrollment shows it. The Democratic National Committee
is 21 percent blacks, with blacks and Latinos in the highest
positions throughout the party.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP has given lip service to correcting this imbalance,
awarding blacks and women largely symbolic positions in the party,
typically through auxiliaries like the New Majority Council, where
black people are isolated in outreach efforts, with little or no
effect on policy. The Republican National Committee, for example,
has few black members, most from the Virgin Islands and only one
from the mainland United States.
</P>
<P>
   The stage in Philadelphia is brimming with minority faces. But
among the delegates and in the convention hall the crowds are
unremittingly white. Black people have been strategically placed
throughout the hall to show up on television, next to George and
Barbara Bush, for example, or near other important Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   As at the last convention, the Oklahoma Republican J.C. Watts is
omnipresent, this time as the master of ceremonies, but close
viewers of these events are beginning to notice that he is the only
black Republican elected official of any national standing involved
in these proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   For many African-Americans, this strategic deployment of blacks
as props and symbols suggests a symbolic form of minstrelsy, with a
Republican Party that has historically dismissed black voters as
irrelevant now seeking to erase that history by dressing up in
blackface.
</P>
<P>
   The truth here is that the party has written off black voters
for this election and is directing its entreaties to the white,
moderate suburbanites who abandoned the party in the last two
elections to vote for Bill Clinton. The ploy of cosmetically
colorizing the GOP could work once, but it is unlikely to work
forever. As the nation browns, the Republican Party will either
brown with it or be swept away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
