<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: MILLER AND `MONDAY' LAG EARLY IN GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If ABC wanted to generate a buzz by bringing Dennis Miller to
``Monday Night Football,'' it got it.
</P>
<P>
   The first wave came in June when the network hired the comedian.
</P>
<P>
   The second came with his debut Monday night from Canton, Ohio,
where the New England Patriots played the San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   USA Today placed the Miller story atop its front page Tuesday,
and employed a six-person reporting team to record reaction in New
York, Seattle, Philadelphia, Cheney, Wash., and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The dawn of Miller Time was judged more important at the
national newspaper than the Republican National Convention or the
failure of a no-confidence vote in the Israeli parliament against
Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Miller's political gibes won him USA Today's top spot: he
called the Democrats and the Republicans ``4-12 teams'' and said
George W. Bush, the presumed Republican presidential nominee,
possessed the same ``deer-in-the-headlights look'' shown by the
49ers' backup quarterback, Giovanni Carmazzi.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people cared enough to register their opinion about
Miller, a profane and witty comic whose trademark is a topical rant
on his weekly HBO program, which he has parlayed into best-selling
books.
</P>
<P>
   At least three Web sites conducted Miller polls. In a survey of
70,000 America Online members, 29.6 percent said Miller was ``fine
and adds something to the telecast,'' but 25.9 percent said he was
``bad'' and suggested that ABC find someone new.
</P>
<P>
   But 37.2 percent said the new ``Monday Night'' threesome of
Miller, Al Michaels and Dan Fouts was ``no better or worse'' than
last year's Michaels-Boomer Esiason team. Esiason was fired in
March. The fans' favorite ``Monday Night'' crew? Howard Cosell,
Frank Gifford and Don Meredith, with 36.2 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   At ESPN.com, 38.4 percent of more than 158,000 online voters
gave Miller a B for his performance, while 25.6 percent graded him
a C. Eleven percent flunked him.
</P>
<P>
   At CNN/SI.com, 45 percent of the 12,584 who voted dubbed Miller
great, but 26 percent sent a loud message: ``Bring Boomer back.''
The Web site augmented its survey with a digest of eight newspaper
critiques of Miller's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ABC Sports said about 50 newspaper critics weighed in on Miller,
focusing on a single subject the way they do only for the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The most withering assessment came from Leonard Shapiro of The
Washington Post: ``Hired last month to act as a lightning rod for
what has become a tranquil telecast, Miller's presence created
barely enough electricity to power a flashlight, let alone
jump-start ABC's marquee pro football attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Networks can't orchestrate such interest _ and since hiring
Miller, ABC has worked to reduce expectations by refusing interview
requests for him _ especially for a comedian analyzing a preseason
game.
</P>
<P>
   But seven weeks of anticipation of what Miller would say and how
he would behave guaranteed more attention than ``Monday Night'' has
garnered in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is banking that he will be a 21st century version of Cosell
_ or will at least be a reliable voice of outrageousness. At XTRA,
a sports radio station in San Diego, Lee Hamilton, a talk show
host, said a large majority of callers viewed Miller negatively,
some complaining that his commentary was sacrilegious to the church
of ``Monday Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's debut spurred at least 150 viewers to leave messages
overnight _ more than the usual 90 _ mostly to register their
displeasure. Adam Freifeld, a spokesman for ABC Sports, said that
most of the calls to ABC are routinely negative, and these followed
suit. Another 25 to 30 e-mail messages were received.
</P>
<P>
   But one measure of interest slipped. The rating for the New
England-San Francisco game tumbled 28 percent to a 7.3 from a 10.1
last year when Cleveland played Dallas in a close overtime game.
ABC started Monday's game at 7 p.m. Eastern, an hour earlier than
last year, a shift that lost viewers. The rating peaked with a 7.8
rating from 9 to 9:30.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
