<HEADER>
A9964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-GOP-DEFENSE-NYT &LR;      08-01 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GOP-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEFENSE DEBATE BEGINS
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Aug. 2:
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Convention in Philadelphia set aside its
nurturing themes about children Tuesday night and returned to the
traditional GOP territory of defense policy and military strength.
Popular war heroes like former Senator Bob Dole and Gen. Norman
Schwarzkopf implied that the Clinton administration had let
veterans down and allowed defenses to erode. But a strangely
wistful note was left by the keynote speaker, Sen. John McCain, the
self-described ``distant runner-up'' whose generous praise of Gov.
George W. Bush was leavened with intimations of his own mortality.
His address seemed designed to echo Gen. Douglas MacArthur's
farewell and perhaps to suggest a subtext of ``I shall return'' if
Bush falters in November.
</P>
<P>
   Keynote speeches are usually aimed at firing up the crowd with
partisan attacks. McCain's subdued approach was in keeping with the
placid mood decreed for this convention by Bush. How many
Republicans will be convinced by his praise of the prospective
nominee as ``my friend'' remains to be seen. Moreover, McCain, a
former prisoner of war in Vietnam, linked his own identity with the
Texas governor by means of a convoluted generational and military
framework. Noting that Bush's father had served in the Navy under
his own grandfather, Adm. John McCain, he said: ``Now it is my turn
to serve under the son of my grandfather's brave subordinate.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the podium Tuesday night seemed like a kind of
class reunion for the gulf war had pitfalls as well as advantages
for Bush. Like the choice of former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney
for vice president, the evening reminded the audience that the war
was the high point of Bush's father's term in the White House,
without offering much of a suggestion about the policies of another
Bush presidency. Some listeners might also recall that as a senator
from Tennessee, Al Gore broke with many Democrats and supported the
war. The idea that military spending suddenly declined under
President Clinton is also based partly on myth. The Pentagon budget
began declining under President Bush and has risen in recent years
under Clinton and his Republican defense secretary, William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Convention speeches are not things to be confused with subtle
foreign policy pronouncements. But there has been a certain
confusion about Republican declarations on foreign policy that Bush
will eventually have to clear up in the presidential campaign. The
most extensive statements on the subject have come from the
governor's main foreign policy adviser, Condoleezza Rice, who also
spoke at the convention Tuesday night. Her criticism of the
administration is that it has spent too much time on trivial
``humanitarian'' interests and failed to cultivate major allies or
deal seriously with potential rivals like China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   As it has in all things, the Republican Convention has papered
over cleavages within Republican ranks on foreign policy. Bush had
to repudiate his own congressional leadership early this year when
he called for support of American peacekeeping efforts in Kosovo.
Working cooperatively with American allies sounds good in
principle, but Bush seems determined to embark on a risky missile
defense system that major European allies regard as unworkable.
Sorting these issues out will come only when Gore gets a chance to
challenge Bush after the conventions. All that Americans learned
Tuesday night was the importance of military strength. How that
strength is to be used will have to be elucidated in the campaign
to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
