<SLUG> BC-SAM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN COALITION PRAISES BUSH'S NOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   PHILADELPHIA _ Not gone and not
forgotten was the message of the Christian Coalition of America
during a rally of more than 2,000 supporters at a downtown hotel
Tuesday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coalition leaders said Tuesday they are pleased with the
Republican ticket and mostly happy with the GOP platform, which
includes an unwavering stand against abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition founder Pat Robertson, who sought the White House in
1988, commended nominee George W. Bush in a speech to the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our candidate,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition did not have a clear favorite for president early
in the campaign. Missouri Sen. John Ashcroft courted the group's
favor in his exploratory White House bid, and Pat Buchanan defected
to the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican convention delegates attended the rally, which
organizers said was larger than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said the Christian Coalition was dead,'' Robertson said.
``I tell you, they ought to tell the Fire Department here that the
largest ballroom in the Downtown Marriott Hotel is jammed packed
with corpses.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson was preceded by a series of speakers from Congress,
including Sen. Sam Brownback of Kansas. Brownback said historic
Philadelphia ``is a great place to reflect'' on American values and
ideals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now let's look at the other party and where they are going to
be celebrating,'' Brownback said, alluding to plans for a
Democratic event at the mansion of Playboy magazine publisher Hugh
Hefner during its convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There, they will celebrate not liberty, but license, not
virtue but vice,'' Brownback said. ``The values of the Playboy
mansion do not belong in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft did not attend the rally. An organizer of the event
said he would have been welcome but had schedule conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Sigerson, a Nebraska delegate and chairman of his state's
party, said he is happy with what he called a ``pro-family''
platform. He was on the Family and Community Platform committee in
1996 and again this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very tense doing the platform in 1996,'' Sigerson said.
``No one felt good when it was done. This time there were smiles on
everyone's face.''
</P>
<P>
   Some at the rally want the party to follow up on its
anti-abortion platform by letting someone speak on the issue at the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Said Colleen Parro, a Texas abortion opponent, ``...it is the
pro-life movement's responsibility to raise the issue and keep it
before the campaign and the administration.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Jerry Falwell, founder of the Moral Majority and a
leader of religious conservatives, said in an interview on the
floor of the GOP convention that the anti-abortion forces need to
focus on winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laura Bush is clearly pro-life,'' he said, and vice
presidential candidate Dick Cheney is more staunchly anti-abortion
than Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be quiet,'' he said. ``We need to pray for him
(Bush). And we need to keep our big mouths shut.''
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the Christian right at the rally wanted the
platform to make a stronger statement on education and immigration,
preferring more local and family control of schools and more
restrictions on immigration.
</P>
<P>
   But moderation of the platform in those respects is not all bad,
said Kevin Denidon, a New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to just be the party of upper middle-class white
men,'' he said. ``The basic philosophy is to talk to a wider
audience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2235EDT &QL; 
