<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGMENT IN FLORIDA TOBACCO LAWSUIT HAS READERS FUMING 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A miraculous thing
happened after a recent column decrying the $145 billion
punitive-damage verdict against cigarette makers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of more than 50 e-mails and calls, more than 90 percent voiced
enthusiastic agreement with the contention that the award revealed
runaway tort law abuse for the fraud it is. About three-quarters of
those in agreement identified themselves as nonsmokers or former
smokers.
</P>
<P>
   The positive response was remarkable because it was the opposite
of previous reactions to commentaries perceived as taking up for
Big Tobacco. In the past the retorts were almost all outraged
disagreement of the ``Dear Sir: You Cur'' variety.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a succinct sampling of the tone of most replies:
</P>
<P>
   - It's about time someone told the truth about the tobacco
lawsuit. Everyone wants something for nothing these days.
</P>
<P>
   - When you consider the lead plaintiff is a PHYSICIAN, the claim
that plaintiffs didn't know (of smoking's) risks is absurd.
</P>
<P>
   - Though I am not a smoker and do not care for (secondhand)
smoke, I think the verdict is truly an injustice. ... What's next?
Alcoholics suing liquor companies ... diabetics suing (candy
companies)? Give me a break.
</P>
<P>
   - It is worse than you describe. ... The ``secrets'' about
smoking and addiction//health effects were knowable by anyone with
a library card.
</P>
<P>
   - It seems as if our court system has lost touch with reality. I
feel I'm watching the parade of the emperor wearing no clothes.
</P>
<P>
   - I don't always agree with you, (but) I liked your column. Who
don't we sue to get some sensible jurors? The problem is we are
unwilling to accept responsibilities for our actions.
</P>
<P>
   - With all the taxes government collects (on tobacco sales), I
do not agree that smokers are costing the government.
</P>
<P>
   - Your question (``Why shouldn't smokers sue those involved in
tobacco lawsuits for the economic damage suffered by skyrocketing
cigarette prices?'') is an excellent idea.
</P>
<P>
   - I have criticized your column, but (this one) was brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   - In my 65 years of life, the biggest injustice I have seen (is)
the states' class action against the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   - I fully agree. ... I (have smoked) for many years (and) am 89
years old. No one ever induced me to smoke. I have always been
warned to NOT smoke.
</P>
<P>
   What prompted this apparent reversal of attitude concerning
legal abuse of Big Tobacco? Although microcosmic in nature, it
seems significant given past reactions.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Americans have always been noted for their
fair-mindedness, even though their sense of fair play has often
abandoned them during the continuing demonization of the tobacco
industry in the pursuit of legal plunder.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the wretchedly excessive immorality of the exercise is
becoming too grotesque for people of otherwise good conscience to
ignore. As The Economist recently editorialized, it's ``high time
Americans abandoned their misguided attempt to `punish' the
industry through lawsuits'' and instead formulated a rational
scheme for regulating a product that's obviously ``never going to
disappear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0425 </DOCNO>
