<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIRY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIRY FARMERS OF AMERICA HELPS FOUND ONLINE EXCHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Got milk? Post it on
the Internet.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That is what Kansas City-based Dairy Farmers of America and
seven other dairy organizations expect to happen with the creation
of Dairy.com, an Internet exchange for buying from and selling to
the U.S. dairy industry.
</P>
<P>
   The dairy consortium joins a wave of other groups with plans for
business-to-business exchanges. They expect the exchanges to lower
costs by joining widespread buyers and sellers and reducing
paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Farmland Industries announced that it and five other
large meat companies were creating a meat exchange. In February,
General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and DaimlerChrysler said they
would create an exchange to buy from parts suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission as a cooperative is to improve the efficiencies of
our 24,000 members, to help them streamline their enterprises and
make them more profitable,'' said Agi Schafer, spokeswoman for
Dairy Farmers of America. ``Eventually we expect it to be a
one-stop shop. The farmer coming off the field cannot only check
commodity prices but do some comparative shopping for supplies. We
think the information on this site will lower their input costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Other founding members of Dairy.com are Dannon Co., Dreyer's
Grand Ice Cream, Kraft Foods, Land O Lakes, Leprino Foods,
Schreiber Foods and Suiza Foods. Each has made an equity investment
of $500,000 to $4 million, Schafer said. ``DFA is committed to the
maximum,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Dairy Farmers and the other founding members are
financing the start-up of the exchange, it will be open to any
producers or companies in the dairy industry that want to join,
Schafer said.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange is scheduled to open by April 1, 2001, with live
trading of milk, cream and some other commodities. Schafer said the
group is looking for a chief executive for the for-profit company.
It has not yet been decided where the company will have its
headquarters. In the interim, the company is being led by Gregg
Engles, chairman and chief executive of Suiza Foods. Other founding
members will contribute other people and services until the company
is up and running.
</P>
<P>
   The investors expect to generate financing for the operation
through fees paid on transactions made through the exchange. Some
services will carry subscriber fees, Schafer said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a dairy farmer might pay a subscription fee for a
management tool that would calculate which cows to keep and which
to sell based on how much feed they consume and how much milk they
produce, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The dairy industry is perfect for this kind of exchange because
many milk products have a short life, Schafer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our products are fresh and perishable. When you need it, you
need it now, and when you have too much, you need to get rid of it
now,'' she said. ``We all are spending hours on the phone looking
for buyers and sellers. This will save us all time, and time is
money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9968 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-VENEZUELA-NYT &LR;      08-01 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-VENEZUELA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELA'S POWERFUL PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Aug. 2:
</P>
<P>
   The voters of Venezuela, craving radical change, have reaffirmed
their confidence in Hugo Chavez, a president who promises a
``peaceful revolution.'' Chavez flattened the country's traditional
political parties in elections in 1998, vowing to end the
corruption and economic mismanagement that have brought a
once-prosperous country to misery. His election this week under a
new Constitution to a full six-year term _ the first of two, he
hopes _ capped his efforts to strengthen presidential authority.
But Venezuelans should be suspicious of how he plans to use his new
powers.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez is a former army paratroop colonel who served a jail term
after attempting a military coup in 1992. His charisma,
identification with the poor and revolutionary rhetoric won him the
presidency through the ballot box instead. Once in office he
established an assembly that sacked hundreds of allegedly corrupt
judges, stripped Congress of its powers and rewrote the
Constitution. That document gives him the right to run for a second
consecutive term, reduces civilian oversight of the armed forces
and weakens state and municipal governments.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's political changes have won overwhelming approval from
voters in several elections and referendums, the last of which took
place on Sunday. Besides Chavez's personal victory, his followers
took most state and local government posts. Although they fell
short of the two-thirds majority in the legislature that would in
effect allow him to rule by decree, Chavez supporters still make up
60 percent of the congress. Now, after 18 months of permanent
campaigning, Chavez says that at last he can begin to make real
changes.
</P>
<P>
   But there is reason to doubt that this accumulation of power
will be used to benefit Venezuela. His record on the economy has
been disappointing. The price of oil, Venezuela's mainstay export,
has more than tripled since he took office. But last year the
economy contracted by more than 7 percent. Oil revenues,
disastrously mismanaged in the past, have been no better used under
Chavez. His aggressive anti-business rhetoric has helped inspire
the flight of at least $8 billion to overseas banks.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez also promises to fight corruption, and he has swept out
of office many judges and legislators widely viewed as tainted. But
some of his lieutenants have themselves fallen under suspicion. In
addition, Chavez seems to choose aides not for their effectiveness
but for their loyalty. His emphasis on personal authority undercuts
the construction of institutions that can check official power and
expose abuses _ a necessity for clean government. It would be
ironic and unfortunate if the sweeping authority that Chavez has
accumulated to change Venezuela prevents him from truly breaking
with the past. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
