<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BRENNAN-INDICT-2TA     08-01 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRENNAN-INDICT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 LIVING IN THE LAP OF BANKRUPTCY, FINANCIER IS CHARGED WITH FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE EATON with ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Back in the early 1980's when many Americans first
started putting their money in the stock market, Robert E. Brennan
was probably the most prominent pitchman drawing them in, inviting
television viewers across the country to take a flyer on hot,
little-known stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Over the clatter of his helicopter he shouted, ``Come grow with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, ``Us'' was First Jersey Securities, which a
federal judge in New York later ruled was not a brokerage house,
but a fraud factory; and a New Jersey judge called Brennan not a
fabled financier, but ``a big crook.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Brennan, 56, who had managed to outwit federal and
state securities investigators for decades, was arrested and
charged with criminal fraud and, for the first time, could face a
prison term.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal prosecutors say that less than a month after
declaring bankruptcy in 1995, he cashed in $500,000 in gambling
chips and kept the money rather than turning it over to a
court-appointed trustee.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan denied the allegations. Though he has lost or settled
civil complaints and owes $200 million in fines and restitution to
defrauded investors, he had never been charged with a crime until
Tuesday. Until recently, when penny stock fraud exploded, criminal
prosecutors seldom brought securities fraud cases involving penny
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But the indictments were a signal moment in a tangled tale of
financial intrigue that has played out over a quarter century.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980's, Brennan became a power in New Jersey politics, a
celebrated philanthropist, and a racetrack magnate who tried to buy
the Meadowlands sports complex.
</P>
<P>
   He also developed a well-oiled machine for selling cheap stocks
in often dubious companies in which he had an interest. The stocks
were sold by more than 1,000 salesmen making cold calls and reading
from sales scripts. And he taught other ambitious young men how to
conduct the convoluted stock frauds that in recent years have cost
Americans billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Even after First Jersey was shuttered, and Brennan publicly
disgraced, he continued a gold-plated standard of living that
involved traveling from his beachfront home in Florida to Monaco,
Cannes, Paris, London, Istanbul, Thailand and Tahiti, all on a
private plane.
</P>
<P>
   Those trips, in fact, prompted both state and federal
prosecutors to ask for bail of $1 million in each court. Brennan
``poses a serious risk of flight,'' said Assistant United States
Attorney Henry E. Klingeman, citing Brennan's penchant for
luxurious living, his French girlfriend, his trips by private jets
and helicopters, and allegations that he has money hidden overseas.
``This defendant has the means to travel in ways that most
defendants don't.''
</P>
<P>
   He was released on $250,000 bail on the state charges, and was
given two days to raise $500,000 bail on the federal charges.
Meanwhile, he is under house arrest, and forbidden to travel except
on scheduled airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before Magistrate Stanley R. Chesler in Federal
District Court in Newark, Brennan said he had only $15,000 to
$20,000 in the bank and was restricted by other court orders to
drawing down only $5,000 a month from that amount.
</P>
<P>
   His voice rising a bit in exasperation, he added, ``My lawyers
are probably going to kill me for saying this, but this case might
be a blessing that God sent down so that we can bring all these
allegations that I have secret money all over the world and am
living this extravagant lifestyle to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Brennan had not been expecting his arrest, said his lawyer,
Michael Critchley, noting that law enforcement agents picked him up
about 6:30 Tuesday morning, while taking a shower at an apartment
he maintains at Due Process, his onetime horse farm, which is now a
private golf course.
</P>
<P>
   From the very beginning, Brennan has always been a high roller
in a world whose players generally stick to the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan did not simply squirrel away the money he made; he used
millions of it to buy racehorses, to donate bulletproof vests to
state troopers, and to buy a plane and houses in Brielle, N.J.,
Saratoga Springs, N.Y., and Juno Beach, Fla. He became chairman of
the board of Seton Hall University; he still owes it millions of
dollars in unfulfilled pledges.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, he took over a New Jersey brokerage house with
regulatory troubles and renamed it First Jersey Securities. Within
five years, federal securities watchdogs had sued Brennan and his
firm, alleging that they manipulated the shares of several obscure
companies. But because the Securities and Exchange Commission does
not have criminal powers, these were civil suits that did not carry
serious penalties.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Brennan technique, as outlined in many civil suits in the
intervening years, has since become familiar to thousands of
Americans who have lost money speculating in the low-priced shares
known as penny stocks. Indeed, the cold-calling salesmen pushing
no-name stocks over the phone have even been depicted for the
noninvesting public in the movie ``Boiler Room.''
</P>
<P>
   Basically, regulators and prosecutors contend, Brennan and his
colleagues controlled all of the shares in a small company, shares
which they pumped up through fake trades and false publicity.
Brokers pushed customers to buy shares, but ignored orders to sell
them, which might depress the price.
</P>
<P>
   Once the shares soared, the stock promoters and dealers would
unload their shares on the unsuspecting public. Then, after they
had cashed in, they would stop supporting the stock price; hapless
investors were usually left holding worthless shares.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, regulators forced First Jersey to sell its brokerage
operations and Brennan seemed to devote himself to horse-racing and
philanthropy. In fact, New Jersey prosecutors say, he was busy
controlling two other penny stock firms that used boiler-room
tactics similar to those at First Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he went on trial in Federal District Court in
Manhattan, facing civil charges of securities fraud brought by
federal regulators. In that case, Judge Richard Owen found him
guilty of a ``massive and continuing fraud'' that hurt thousands of
investors and netted Brennan $75 million in ill-gotten gains.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Brennan filed for bankruptcy protection, to
keep from having to disgorge his profits. The fight over his assets
has dragged on for years; this spring, Brennan agreed to turn over
the golf course to the bankruptcy trustee in return for more time
to recover money that investigators believe he has hidden in trusts
in places like Gibralter and the island of Nevis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
