</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HIRSCHFELD-SENTENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL DEVELOPER SENTENCED FOR PLOTTING TO KILL PARTNER 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Abe Hirschfeld, the flamboyant parking garage
developer, has never been one to go quietly. Nor did he Tuesday
when a Manhattan judge sentenced him to one to three years in
prison for plotting to kill his business partner.
</P>
<P>
   Upon hearing the sentence, Hirschfeld asked for and was granted
permission to kiss his wife, Zipora, but he refused to do so while
handcuffed and kicked at court officers who would not free him.
While he was being led away, he lavished a final obscenity upon the
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Hirschfeld, 80, has courted trouble and defied
crisis. In 1998, he offered Paula Jones $1 million to settle her
lawsuit against President Clinton. Last year, after his trial on
tax evasion charges ended with a deadlocked jury, he paid jurors
$2,500 each for their work.
</P>
<P>
   And three years ago, according to evidence presented in the
current case, he paid an intermediary $75,000 to hire a hit man to
kill his associate Stanley Stahl, then 72. The two men had
survivor-takes-control agreements covering many of their
properties.
</P>
<P>
   A jury found Hirschfeld guilty of criminal solicitation on June
16.
</P>
<P>
   In court Tuesday, Hirschfeld praised his own intellect and
legacy in grandiose and disjointed remarks before he was sentenced.
Judge Ira F. Beal of Criminal Court said, before he imposed
sentence, ``This was a mean-spirited crime by a very wealthy man _
out of greed,'' and added, ``The community has a right to see some
form of punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Stahl was not killed, but died in August after a stroke. But
Stahl's wife, Charisse, said Tuesday in court, ``He is as
responsible as if he shot a gun himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Stahl's life changed the day that he learned of Hirschfeld's
intention to kill him, his wife said. He hired bodyguards, wore a
bullet-proof vest and rode in a bullet-proof limousine. His health
also declined, as he suffered from heart problems and pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, she tried to keep him from seeing an article in New
York magazine about Hirschfeld and his plot against Stahl. But on
Aug. 5, he finally read it. ``After he got over being angry,'' she
recalled, ``he said, `I'm so happy to be home.''' Then he went to
the bathroom and fell to the floor, she said. He had suffered a
stroke and died 10 days later.
</P>
<P>
   Looking gaunt and pale, Hirschfeld challenged Stahl's
statements. He said Stahl did not ride in a bullet-proof limousine,
because he had never listed it as a business expense. He also
denied having plotted to kill Stahl and said he had no financial
incentive. ``No one benefits from dying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he said he had brought a copy of his own will. ``I am not
going to leave my wife or child anything,'' he said. ``I'm going to
build an immigrant hall of fame,'' in which he would feature
himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000801.0431 </DOCNO>
