<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOYS-R-US-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYS `R' US PLANNING 100,000-SQUARE-FOOT SUPERSTORE ON TIMES
SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an expensive bid to re-establish itself as the top
retailer in its field, Toys ``R'' Us announced Tuesday that it
would open the world's largest toy store amid the tourist-choked
streets and neon-infused ballyhoo of Times Square in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The glass-enclosed, 101,000-square-foot superstore at the
northeast corner of Broadway and 44th Street will feature a
60-foot-tall indoor Ferris wheel offering customers panoramic views
of the stuffed toys, action figures, dolls, science kits and
electronic games available on three floors, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate executives who have seen the company's plans said
Toys ``R'' Us would spend about $35 million to build the store,
which will sit opposite the MTV music studios and ABC-TV's studios
for ``Good Morning America.'' They said the company would pay about
$12 million a year in rent for the store and the animated video
screens and billboards overhead.
</P>
<P>
   It would be not only the largest toy store in the world, but
also the largest retail outlet in Times Square, one-third larger
than the Virgin Megastore one block north. The company is hoping
that the flagship store, scheduled to open next summer, will be so
dazzling and media friendly that toy manufacturers will flock to
the site to unveil new products, much the same way music groups
introduce new songs at the MTV studios.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be the center of the toy universe,'' John Eyler, chief
executive of Toys ``R'' Us, said Tuesday. ``We expect to draw over
20 million visitors a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The company described the new flagship store as one step in the
company's campaign to regain its position as the No. 1 toy
retailer, which it lost to Wal-Mart two years ago, and to develop
the same kind of cachet as its smaller but more upscale rival,
F.A.O. Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   It could be an expensive gamble, some retail experts said. Theme
restaurants, entertainment centers and movie theaters have moved to
Times Square in recent years. But many traditional retailers have
been put off by the enormous rents, as much as $300 per square foot
on the ground floor, more than twice as much as in many other areas
of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Gap and the Virgin Megastore moved to Times Square well
before the once-dowdy area rebounded in the late '90s and rents
skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, will customers brave streets crammed with tourists,
teen-age music fans, office workers and theatergoers to buy toys?
</P>
<P>
   ``With all that's going on in Times Square, I think they'll do
well there,'' said Jeffrey Winnick, a retail consultant. ``People
are buying records, Warner Brothers and Disney products. Why not
toys? They'll have foot traffic and it'll be great P-R for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Eyler, who joined Toys ``R'' Us as chief executive in January,
said he had been seeking a flagship location in Times Square, but
it was hard to find a large enough space. Brad Mendelson, a broker
with Insignia/ESG, eventually took the company to 1514 Broadway,
the former home of the Roundabout Theater, which offered big floors
with 38-foot ceilings and few columns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means we can do things three-dimensionally,'' said Eyler,
who plans to include a cafe in the store.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
