<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   McCAIN DELIVERS SOLID BUSH ENDORSEMENT, MUCH TO DISMAY OF
EX-McCAIN BACKERS
</P>
<P>
   By GREG McDONALD
</P>
<P>
   c. Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Gov. George W. Bush offered a video salute to his
former rival, Sen. John McCain, calling his vanquished primary
rival a hero as the Arizona senator finally prepared to exit the
presidential campaign stage.
</P>
<P>
   McCain in turn planned a ringing endorsement of Bush, and
steered clear of the campaign finance reform issues that catapulted
the Arizona senator to political prominence.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing speech to the second day of the Republican
National Convention, the senator sought to heal the wounds
inflicted on the party by his primary challenge to Bush. Sounding a
note of harmony, he called on his GOP colleagues to ``build a party
as big as the country we serve,'' according to an advance text of
his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am grateful for your kindness to a distant runner-up,'' the
senator said. ``I am proud to join you this evening in commanding
to all Americans the man who now represents your best wishes and
mine for the future of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Some among the delegates McCain won in the primary felt regret
for what might have been had McCain's maverick bid for the
presidency upset the well financed Bush juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the senator's supporters seemed upset that their hero
spoke not as a reform-advocate but instead offered one of the most
lavish Bush endorsements of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   They had expected a strongly worded endorsement, since the
senator is still, after all, a loyal Republican. But they had hoped
for the same kind of rousing reform-pushing message that helped
McCain attract so many independents and crossover Democrats in the
primary races and that alienated so many in the GOP establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Watson, a strident McCain supporter and the minority
leader of the Rhode Island House of Representatives, described the
speech as ``a bittersweet moment'' signaling the final end to
McCain's quest for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain is a bridge-builder. He's using his appearance to
support and unite the party,'' Watson said. ``This is George Bush's
convention, and John McCain is a loyal Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech text, McCain made a point of calling on both
independents and Democrats to join in the effort to elect Bush,
who, he said, ``believes in the greatness of America and the
justice of our cause.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to lead a Republican Party that is as big as the
country we serve,'' McCain told the convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   But absent from his remarks was any direct reference to the
government reform issues that drew 7 million voters to his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans fear that many of those voters will not support the
GOP ticket in November with the senator out of the race. But Watson
predicted that enough would shift their support to Bush to make the
difference in the election outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain brought a lot of independents and Democrats to the
party. That's his legacy, the new faces and the new blood,'' Watson
said. ``And for him to try to transfer their support to George
Bush, that's a very gracious and proper thing for him to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his campaign, McCain talked about the greatness of
American and how its strength is built on a ``cause greater than
self-interest.'' He returned to that theme in his endorsement of
the man he once described as a ``phoney reformer'' and a status quo
Republican whose close ties to the right wing elements of the party
would be divisive to the country.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the man who a few months ago was not
qualified to be president in McCain's view, had become a healer
instead of a divider.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants nothing to divide us into separate nations. Not
color. Not our race. Not our wealth. Not our religion. Not our
politics. He wants us to live for America as one nation,'' the
senator said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support him. I am grateful to him. And I am proud of him,''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
