<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD DEFLECTS JABS ON TITLE FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Evander Holyfield has spent a lifetime building a reputation as
a warrior, a true champion. But as he pursues another title in his
long career, he finds himself answering questions of just how
worthy his pursuit is. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield will try to capture the heavyweight crown for the
fourth time when he takes on John Ruiz for the vacant World Boxing
Association championship in Las Vegas on Aug 12. But the belt they
are fighting for was taken away from Lennox Lewis this year when
Lewis refused to defend the title against Ruiz, who is ranked as
the No. 1 contender, and opted instead to take on Michael Grant,
whom he beat handily.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Holyfield and Ruiz fighting for the belt, but
Holyfield had a hard time convincing inquisitors on Tuesday that he
deserved a chance to lay claim to the belt that he could not take
from Lewis in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't feel that it's tainted,'' said Holyfield, who also
has a long-range goal of taking Lewis' World Boxing Council and
International Boxing Federation titles. ``Because I look at what
this game's always been: when you don't follow rules and
regulations, you lose your title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it would be the same question with Lennox, how he got
his first belt. A lot of people didn't beat the champion. I look at
that and say, `Why does it have to be different with me?' I chose
to go by the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I feel I should be the champion now, but the
decision didn't swing my way,'' Holyfield said. ``I decided to keep
fighting, and the guy who was the best didn't follow the
regulations and he forfeited his belt. I don't feel ashamed.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield has maintained his belief that the Nov. 13, 1999,
decision he lost to Lewis that cost him his IBF and WBA titles was
tainted, with the judges making up for a perceived slight against
Lewis in a draw against Holyfield eight months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anybody that watched the fight knows that in that
fight I did beat Lennox,'' Holyfield said. ``They bring up the
first fight, but in the first fight they didn't take it from
Lennox, either. The next fight people say they corrected and made
it right, but they didn't. But that's no complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to fight because I believe in my ability to take it
again. I have a goal, to be undisputed champion of the world. I
fight for reasons. I have a goal. I believe that I'm the best even
if I don't fight a guy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who will turn 38 shortly after the fight, has
compiled a 36-4-1 record in a career filled with highlights.
</P>
<P>
   But this fight, originally scheduled for June 10 before an
injury to Holyfield caused a postponement, will be hard-pressed to
be seen as one of them.
</P>
<P>
   For Ruiz (36-3), his biggest fight came four years ago when he
faced David Tua and was knocked out in just 19 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I answer that?'' Ruiz said rhetorically. ``I put
myself on the line so many times. First of all, I wanted to fight
Michael Grant, then he decides to sign up with Lennox Lewis for a
fight. Lennox totally avoided me. What am I to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm basically going out there, going by the rules and I'm the
No. 1 contender in the WBC and WBA, which I earned. Nothing I can
say is going to change minds. I've definitely got a lot to prove,''
Ruiz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really think much about Lennox Lewis. He's done a lot
in his career, but I feel he'll never be the great champion like
Holyfield, Muhammad Ali, Joe Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think when his career is done he'll be put in with
those names. I feel that he just doesn't want to give a young guy a
chance and follow the rules, basically.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vargas' Task at Hand  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Vargas is also having a hard time keeping his attention
on the task at hand, having to make his way past Ross Thompson
(24-3-1) on Aug. 26 in Las Vegas before he can take on Felix
Trinidad on Dec. 2, the fight he is looking forward to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to get up for fight like this, to be honest with
you,'' said the 22-year-old Vargas (19-0), the IBF junior
middleweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get up for it, because I know after I get through
this fight I've got Trinidad. That's my main objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get this one out of the way fast. I want to look
great. I'm training hard. I feel this is my big fight right now,
not Trinidad.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
