<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 MAIN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Despite pledges to keep it clean, election banter begins to get
gritty
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By R.G. RATCLIFFE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Former President Bush threatened Tuesday to end
his self-imposed silence about President Clinton's character if he
persists in mocking his son, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to wait a month ... and if he continues that, then
I'm going to tell the nation what I think about him (Clinton) as a
human being and a person,'' the former president said on MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was driven from the White House by Clinton eight years
ago, has kept a low profile in George W. Bush's bid for the
presidency and has no formal role in this week's GOP convention in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and former first lady Barbara Bush said Tuesday they want
to remain on the sidelines but find it hard as Clinton and others
criticize their oldest son.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush is a great man,'' Barbara Bush said. ``He'll
take care of it. He doesn't need his mother, although she's dying
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   While the former president faced his share of criticism while in
the White House, he said, ``it's much worse when they criticize
your son.''
</P>
<P>
   What stirred their ire were recent assessments by Clinton about
George W. Bush's campaign and why he is running for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their strategy is to talk about compromise and all that and
it's a brilliant strategy, a pretty package, and they're hoping if
they wrap it tight enough nobody will open it before Christmas,''
Clinton said in Tampa, Fla., on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Clinton said Bush was running because his father
had been president. ``Nearest I can tell, the message of the Bush
campaign is just that, `How bad could I be? I've been governor of
Texas. My daddy was president. I've owned a baseball team,'''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush family reaction is another sign the GOP candidate still
lives in his father's shadow, said Chris Lehane, a spokesman for
Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells you something about George Jr. He has to send his
father out to defend him,'' Lehane said. ``People are starting to
wonder, does he have what it takes?''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush said he welcomes Clinton's criticism. ``It's
amazing to me the president of the United States would spend time
trying to be a political pundit,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so desperate to have his legacy intact by having Al Gore
elected he'll say anything, just like Al Gore will,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush says he does not speak ill of Clinton or Gore, he
was reminded Tuesday that he has told several audiences that his
running mate, Dick Cheney, is a man who knows what the definition
of the word ``is'' is.
</P>
<P>
   The wordplay is a reference to one of President Clinton's early,
obtuse explanations of his affair with White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was talking about him then, I sure was,'' Bush
acknowledged, adding that the remark was ``in the context of having
somebody who is going to shoot straight with the American people,
and Dick Cheney is a straight-shooter.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he also is not directing his comments at Clinton when
he talks about restoring morality to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people walk up and say, `Don't let us down,' we're just
reporting what's happening. I don't think I've ever mentioned
President Clinton's name on the stump recently,'' Bush told
reporters in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than an hour later in Charleston, W.Va., Bush said
the ``nation is looking for an administration that will appeal to
our better angels, not our darker impulses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This nation does not want four more years of Clinton-Gore,``
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush later told reporters he had been ``riled up'' by questions
about Clinton's comments and his name had just slipped out.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle reporter David Ivanovich contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   XXEND OF STORYXX
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
