<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-01 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0128 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-GOP-MAIN02-COX     08-01 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GOP-MAIN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCAIN SUPPORTS BUSH AS 'FUTURE OF OUR COUNTRY'
 &HT;    650&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By KEN HERMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Sen. John McCain, a reformer who earlier this
year branded George W. Bush as a snapshot of what's wrong with
politics, hailed him Tuesday night as ``the man who now represents
your best wishes and mine for the future of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I support him. I am grateful to him. And I am proud of him,''
McCain, who had been Bush's prime and bitter foe for the GOP
presidential nomination, told Republican National Convention
delegates who rose to their feet and cheered.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's warm words for Bush came on a night when the convention
concentrated on national defense issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``As commander in chief, I will rebuild America's military and
strengthen our alliances,'' Bush told delegates in a remote hookup
from Gettysburg, Pa., where he campaigned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, delegates saluted former Presidents Gerald Ford,
Ronald Reagan (who was represented by his wife, Nancy) and George
Bush. The elder Bush also appeared in a video presentation, saying
his son's record ``can stand all the scrutiny in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The ex-presidents were honored on a day when the tightly
choreographed convention was threatened by disruption from
protesters on the streets and delegates in the arena.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles north of the First Union Center, the sports arena
housing the convention, Philadelphia police arrested at least 230
people as protesters clogged downtown streets where many delegates'
hotels were located, sprayed graffiti on city hall and clashed with
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have taken the streets,'' death penalty foe Sue Kelly of
Richmond said during a downtown march and blockade. ``We just don't
like Republicans and what the ruling class stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the arena, a threatened walkout during a free-trade
speech by Rep. Jim Kolbe of Arizona, the only openly gay Republican
in Congress, didn't materialize. About a third of the Texas
delegation, which includes members whose religious beliefs tell
them homosexuality is a sin, prayed silently during the speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was to pray for Mr. Kolbe to be consistent with the values
of the party,'' said Larry Stevens of Fort Worth, who said a
walkout might have embarrassed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Texas GOP Chair Susan Weddington, who did not join the silent
prayer, said Kolbe should not have been allowed to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives the opportunity for radical gay rights advocates to
claim victory for their agenda,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's speakers included retired Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf,
1996 presidential nominee Bob Dole, his wife, Elizabeth, and Bush
foreign policy adviser Condoleezza Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarzkopf, speaking on the eve of the 10th anniversary of the
Iraqi invasion of Kuwait that led to Operation Desert Storm,
praised Bush as a man who can restore military might and morale.
</P>
<P>
   The retired general spoke from the USS New Jersey, docked in
nearby Camden, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't it be great for our armed forces and for America if
we could have another commander in chief named George Bush with
Dick Cheney on his team?'' he said, referring to Bush's running
mate, who served as secretary of defense during Desert Storm.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a former Vietnam POW, used his military background to
make his link to Bush. He noted that the candidate's father served
in World War II under McCain's grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it is my turn to serve under the son of my grandfather's
brave subordinate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his remote appearance, Bush returned the kind words from his
new ally, saying McCain's ``straight talk and strong convictions
are admired across America.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's speech offered only mild shot at the political system
he believes is fatally compromised by cash. He coupled it with a
theme often pushed by Bush, who believes partisanship _ not
political money _ is the root of Washington evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often, those who hold a public trust have failed to set
the necessary example,'' said McCain, drawing applause. ``Too
often, partisanship seems all consuming.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator offered a stronger campaign finance message
Sunday, when he addressed a so-called ``shadow convention'' at
which he was booed when he mentioned Bush. Prior to his Tuesday
speech, McCain said he was perturbed by the flow of
special-interest money at the convention, which is supported by a
long list of high-dollar donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system's broken. We are addicted to soft money,'' he said,
calling it a ``bipartisan issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, following a primary battle that grew increasingly
bitter, McCain, calling himself a ``distant runner-up'' and getting
an enthusiastic welcome from the floor, offered a no-holds-barred
endorsement of his ex-foe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is easy to forget in politics where principle ends and
selfishness begins. It takes leaders of courage and character to
remember the difference. Tomorrow, our party nominates such a
leader,'' said McCain. ``George Bush believes in the greatness of
America and the justice of our cause.''
</P>
<P>
   And McCain got prolonged applause with this line: ``I say to all
Americans; Republican, Democrat or independent, if you believe
America deserves leaders with a purpose more ennobling than
expediency and opportunism, then vote for Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a far different tone that McCain adopted in winning seven
primaries, including a New Hampshire contest that changed the tone
of the race, before being ousted in March. When the GOP field
narrowed to Bush and McCain, each man took shots at each other.
McCain accused Bush of being the darling of the religious right and
a candidate tainted by the kind of wealthy special interests who
make politics a fixed game.
</P>
<P>
   After a wealthy Bush friend of Dallas paid for $2.5 million
worth of ads assailing McCain's environmental records, McCain urged
voters in March, ``Do not let the Bush campaign and their cronies
hijack this election with negative ads and $2.5 million of their
dirty money.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, McCain called Bush ``a Pat Robertson
Republican who will lose to Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush fired back in kind, noting that McCain solicited the kind
of special-interest donations he damns. Bush also blasted the
McCain campaign for trying to portray Bush as anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   McCain later endorsed Bush, who said he would have considered
McCain as a running mate if the senator had not said he didn't want
the job.
</P>
<P>
   As the GOP continued a convention aimed at attracting support
from independents and minorities, Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway
criticized the event as a ``masquerade ball _ designed to conceal
the real identity and special interest agenda of the same old
party.'' He noted a New York Times delegate survey that found that
one in five delegates here put their net worth at more than $1
million. Eighty-three percent are white.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com or
445-1718.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
