<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATCHET MAN NO MORE, BOB DOLE DISPENSES WIT, PHILOSOPHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE and KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   PHILADELPHIA _ Four years ago, the stage
was set for Bob Dole to be the Republican nominee for president.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday, Dole's stage was cable TV's Comedy Central, where he
did a routine poking fun at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   A comedown?
</P>
<P>
   Not at all, Dole and his supporters said. Besides, two hours
after taping the comedy show, Dole got a thunderous ovation at the
convention when he spoke on veterans affairs.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Bob Dole is free to be anyone he wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a lot of fun,'' Dole said as he strolled the
convention hall Monday night, trailed by reporters, delegates and
well-wishers. ``There's a lot of happy people here. We're going to
win in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole went out of his way to greet security guards, ushers and
the elderly, a habit he picked up on the presidential campaign
trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``How ya doin?'' Dole boomed in his familiar baritone.
</P>
<P>
   As for his gig on Comedy Central's ``The Daily Show with Jon
Stewart,'' Dole shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing a lot of these things. I've been on Leno a
couple of times, Letterman, `Saturday Night Live.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dole serves as political commentator on ``The Daily Show,''
combining serious analysis with his omnipresent wit. He taped the
show before a highly enthusiastic audience at a University of
Pennsylvania studio.
</P>
<P>
   The running gag Tuesday night was the convention's lack of
suspense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been this excited since David Eisenhower married
Julie Nixon,'' Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boring?'' Dole said. ``It's so boring, even some of the
protesters were trying to get a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who came up short in presidential bids in 1980 and 1988
before winning the nomination four years ago, also poked fun at
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a little sentimental at conventions,'' Dole said. ``I
always feel like writing a concession speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who will tape another show Thursday, said he hopes
appearing on programs popular with young people will spur their
interest in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want more people to vote,'' Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole appeared on the show in December 1999 as a guest for a
two-part interview. He and host Jon Stewart hit it off, and Stewart
made an on-air plea for him to return for the conventions. Dole
agreed _ for a fee, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central spokesman Steve Albani said Dole's humorous side
shows now that he's not a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can really see it,'' Albani said. ``He's a lot more free.
He's not trying to be Bob Hope. He's first and foremost Bob Dole.
But he's very quick with a quip.''
</P>
<P>
   Albani called the Kansan a bonanza for the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't just go out and get ourselves a former Republican
nominee,'' he said. ``And having someone who is high-level person
who is completely serious and without a sense of humor would not
work for `The Daily Show.' We're still wondering how it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time Dole has served as a spokesman for
hire. In the years since his losing presidential bid, Dole has been
a pitchman for Target stores, Air France and Visa. Then, of course,
there was his much-discussed work for Viagra, the sexual stimulant
for men.
</P>
<P>
   The transition from politician to comedian began when he
appeared on ``The Late Show with David Letterman'' shortly after
losing to President Clinton in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Dole has done more than comedy since 1996. He was an adviser
on the Kosovo conflict and lately his focus is raising money for a
national World War II memorial in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have taken that (1996) defeat and said, `I'm out of
here,' '' said Sen. Sam Brownback, who took over Dole's Senate seat
in Kansas. ``The party could have taken it and said, `That's a
defeat of the World War II generation, and we're moving on.' But
neither happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Brownback and others suggested that if more voters had seen
Dole's humorous side, he would have fared far better four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he can be more effective for Bush than he was for
himself,'' Brownback said.
</P>
<P>
   But Missouri state Sen. Peter Kinder of Cape Girardeau saw it
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It strikes me as a little regrettable,'' said Kinder, a
Republican. ``I would rather see him at CNN or the Fox News Network
than with Comedy Central.''
</P>
<P>
   If Dole had any reservations about his diminished role at the
convention this year compared with four years ago, it hasn't shown.
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters this week his political standing at the 1996
convention was far different than the one George W. Bush enjoys
this year. For one thing, Dole was trailing in the polls to
Clinton. This year, Bush is leading Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   There's also something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three things Bush won't have to worry about:
Buchanan, Clinton and a sort of confrontational House in the
Congress with Gingrich and so forth,'' Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole was referring to Pat Buchanan, the firebrand TV commentator
who abandoned the GOP for the Reform Party; a popular sitting
president; and former Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich, a
Georgian who many found to be a polarizing figure.
</P>
<P>
   He praised Bush for reaching out to new voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to broaden the base of our party,'' Dole said. ``If
we want to be the majority party, we've got to have an agenda that
will attract people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's decision to accord Dole a coveted evening speaking slot
suggests that he still regards Dole as an asset.
</P>
<P>
   ``His name will continue to be invoked by lots of folks,'' said
Kansas Gov. Bill Graves, head of his state's delegation at the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Parkinson, chairman of the Kansas GOP, said he has no
problems with Dole's appearance on Comedy Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much bickering and fighting and partisanship,''
Parkinson said. ``If somebody wants to come along and make it a
little humorous, I think that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 77, Dole's ties to his home state have loosened. Graves said
he didn't know the last time Dole had visited, and Parkinson said
he hadn't talked to Dole since he became party chairman early in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas party went through a rough patch after Dole left the
Senate in 1996. One of the party's biggest fund-raisers, Dole
suddenly was no longer bringing in the bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he stopped the fund-raising, the party struggled for a
while,'' Parkinson said. ``We have really had to build up a list of
small donors, which the party never built up because it relied so
heavily on Senator Dole raising money from national contributors.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Pat Roberts, a Kansas Republican, said Dole has always had
a sense of humor that came in handy in the U.S. Senate during his
career there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could define the whole U.S. Senate as Comedy Central,''
Roberts said. ``Bob always had the ability to use self-deprecating
humor. I always wish the American electorate had seen the Bob Dole
as we know him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
