<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-keyword-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why party platforms don't really matter
</P>
<P>
   By JANE ELY
</P>
<P>
   c. Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Political eons ago, when the Democrats dominated
Texas politics, ideologues who managed to become convention
delegates and wanted their party to reflect their causes usually
found themselves shuffled off to make their cases to the
Resolutions Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when it came time to consider resolutions, you almost
could hear the train coming through the convention hall as the one
running this political railroad would take a motion to refer
resolutions to the party executive committee, rule it passed and
instantly bang the gavel to adjourn the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Only in 1972, the year of George McGovern, did the action change
as the liberals won enough seats to spout every cause and to drag
the doings into the night.
</P>
<P>
   After that, no matter which philosophy dominated the Dems, they
tended to devote little time to arguing ideology. In fact, they
even trended to reducing their national platform to the most
general of statements, written in the briefest _ and pretty much
the blahest _ of language.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a lot longer coming, but, at last, the Republicans
actually may be _ barely _ starting to go through the same
evolution in writing their ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: The platform, which, in comparison to GOP
documents of recent decades, virtually sailed through the
Republican National Convention here, is certainly not brief, and it
absolutely is not blah.
</P>
<P>
   But, for GOPers, especially those as conservative as most
delegates here, there were a fair number of concessions made in
ideology for the sake of George W. Bush, their certain presidential
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the approved platform does not call for the
elimination of the Department of Education, nor does it contain a
lot of the harshness of platforms past.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in obvious concession to Bush, it warmly welcomes
minorities and immigrants to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it sternly sticks to its GOP guns by emphatically
opposing abortion, gay rights and sex education. It covers pages
with the most tedious of details demanding the delegates'
particular wishes and ways be foisted onto all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the document leaves one question in particular
unanswered. That is: Is the GOP actually on its way to ultimately
recognizing the reality the platform of the party seldom is truly
the platform of the candidate?
</P>
<P>
   Are Republicans moving to realize that never is a candidate, nor
an elected officeholder, driven purely by the document contrived at
political conventions?
</P>
<P>
   For example, it's one thing for a president to subscribe to the
general tone of his party's platform. It's quite another for him to
expend political capital to achieve what the document dictates. One
has but to look at Ronald Reagan and abortion to recognize that.
</P>
<P>
   By all sane political definition, George W. Bush is a
conservative. Only the most ardent of conservative zealots _ and
there surely are some of those here _ would question it.
</P>
<P>
   But not even they can muster the power or the pure political
guts to do much more than mumble their unhappiness.
</P>
<P>
   It is little consolation to those who once again tried in vain
to remove the unyielding anti-abortion language from the GOP
platform, but they can take some relief in knowing lots of
ideologues of polar positions failed to win their ways here as
well.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, even Bush, who totally has dominated this confab even
though he has not yet been here, clearly has not had his full way
in the contents and ideology of his party's political platform.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is: While lots of Republicans won their ways in
having input into the party platform, Bush won the GOP presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And, when he leaves here to begin _ fully and formally _ his
Republican presidential campaign, GWB may not even have read the
platform produced here.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if modern political tradition prevails, the only ones
besides the most intense Republicans who will read the GOP platform
are the most intense Dems.
</P>
<P>
   And they, just like GOP zealots, will try hard to convince the
nation Bush embraces every word of the platform and will follow it
to the letter if he is elected.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with that is most voters won't have read the GOP
platform either. The platform they care about is the one for which
the candidate stands _ not the convention delegates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XX END OF STORY XX
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
