GRANT RESOURCES
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Some information sites for government grants for technology
innovation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-- Small Business Innovative Research program ( &LR; www.sba.gov &LR; 
 &LR; /hotlist/sbir.html &LR; ). This federal program includes 10
participating federal agencies, such as the departments of Defense,
Energy and Transportation. It makes $1 billion in research and
development grants directly to small technology companies or
individual entrepreneurs who form a company. The program is
administered by the Small Business Administration's Office of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   -- Small Business Technology Transfer program ( &LR; www.sba.gov/ &LR; 
 &LR; SBIR/sttr.html &LR; ). This program provides up to $600,000 in
early-stage R&AMP;D funding directly to small companies working
cooperatively with researchers at universities and other research
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bay Area Regional Technology Alliance ( &LR; www.barta.org &LR; ). This
nonprofit organization provides guidance and networking
opportunities to technology entrepreneurs and helps those who
receive federal R&AMP;D funding get additional financial assistance
from the California Technology Investment Partnership. This CalTIP
program supports commercialization of new technology and over the
past two years has made 26 grants worth more than $5 million to Bay
Area companies.
</P>
<P>
   -- Goldstrike partnership ( &LR; www.goldstrike.net &LR; ). This program
of the California Trade and Commerce Agency's Office of Strategic
Technology supports the development and commercialization of
technology to create jobs and companies. The office also
administers programs that provide matching cash grants to other
private and federal programs.
</P>
<P>
   Source: San Francisco Chronicle research
</P>
