 ENTREPRENEURS GET STARTED WITH GRANTS  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Entrepreneurs with technology visions but little
capital can often get going by trading a big chunk of equity in the
startup to outside investors or borrowing cash at high interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another lesser-known option. If they are not in a
hurry for the money and don't mind a load of paperwork or tailoring
their technology for a government application, they might win
millions of dollars in federal and state grants.)
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of Bay Area inventors and entrepreneurs have taken
advantage of the federal Small Business Innovative Research (SBIR)
program, which approves about $1 billion a year in research and
development grants to small technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses can often leverage those grants to get additional
funds from other governmental sources. For example, the California
Technology Investment Partnership (CalTIP) provides more than $6
million a year to about 30 California companies to help them
commercialize their technology and hire local employees.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to these and other government R&AMP;D programs, PowerLight of
Berkeley has combined solar energy technology with roofing
materials to produce a 2-for-1 product that provides electricity as
well as covering. Another Berkeley company, Integrated
Magnetoelectronics, is creating a newfangled magnetic memory
storage device for cell phones and other devices.
</P>
<P>
   In the South Bay, Acellent Technologies Inc. and Sensant Corp.
are developing sensor and imaging technologies that can peer
beneath the surfaces of aircraft as well as other man-made
structures and humans themselves to detect problems.
</P>
<P>
   Neither federal nor state technology grants require recipients
to pay back anything so ``they're a good way to build up equity,''
said CalTIP program manager Sharon Stagg.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is that ``it takes a while.'' Applicants for the
California grants must submit proposals by May, and the winners
(about 1 out of 3 or 4) aren't announced until this month. They
don't get any money until October or November. Federal contracts
can take even longer.
</P>
<P>
   PowerLight
</P>
<P>
   One fan of both SBIR and CalTIP grants is Berkeley entrepreneur
Thomas Dinwoodie.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving master's degrees in mechanical engineering from
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where he focused on
renewable energy, and in architecture from the University of
California at Berkeley, he came up with the idea of maximizing the
value of expensive photovoltaic cells by building them right into
other building materials.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, he won a patent for tile that serves as both a roofing
material and solar-electric power plant. He started his company,
PowerLight, and depended heavily on government grants to develop
the dual-purpose tile. His first grant was a $50,000 award from the
Sacramento Municipal Utilities District in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grants have helped us finance our long-term development work
and commercialize the technology,'' said Dinwoodie.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, PowerLight has received more than $5 million in
grants from the U.S. Department of Energy and other federal and
state programs.
</P>
<P>
   The company's year-old manufacturing plant in Berkeley produces
500,000 square feet of electricity-producing tiles annually, enough
to cover the roofs of several hundred commercial buildings and
generate 15 megawatts of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The company's main product, called PowerGuard, is dark blue tile
that has polystyrene foam on the bottom and a photovoltaic laminate
on top. The product has been installed on flat roofs from the Mauna
Lani hotel and club house in Hawaii, where it supplies nearly all
the hotel's electric power when the sun is shining, to the new
Chabot Observatory in the Oakland, Calif., hills and Clint
Eastwood's new Carmel, Calif., country club. The tiles also have
been installed overseas from Australia to Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to $825,000 in federal Small Business Innovation Research
grants, PowerLight also is working on a product for the residential
market. Called SunTile, it looks likes conventional shingles and
can be mounted on many types of roofs.
</P>
<P>
   The energy-generating shingles plug into each other to produce
electricity to run a the house. Whatever power is left over runs
back through the same power lines that bring electricity into the
house for the benefit of other electricity users. The homeowner's
electric meter then runs in reverse direction, lowering and perhaps
eliminating electricity bills.
</P>
<P>
   Although PowerLight's products are several times more expensive
than conventional roofing materials, the company says they offer
benefits aside from excellent insulation and protection from the
elements. ``We offer a way to turn your roof into a profit
center,'' said Executive Vice President Daniel Shugar.
</P>
<P>
   Integrated Magnetoelectronics, meanwhile, was started by Richard
Spitzer, a former physicist at the Stanford Linear Accelerator, to
develop new types of memory devices that use metallic thin film
rather than silicon or other semiconductor materials.
</P>
<P>
   After raising $600,000 in private capital, IME has relied on
government grants. Since 1996, it has received 13 grants totaling
$4.3 million, including money from the Department of Defense,
Department of Energy, National Science Foundation and CalTIP
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company is primarily interested in large commercial
markets such as memory devices for cell phones and cameras that
retain information when the power is turned off, magnetic memory
chips also have broad military and satellite applications because
the devices are nonvolatile and are not subject to radiation
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting government grants has been a beautiful strategy,''
said Bob Burger, IME's director of development. ``The downside is
you try to fulfill the requirements of the awards but those things
don't necessarily help you get to market very fast.'' To remedy
that, IME is raising $6 million from angel investors to build its
first manufacturing facility.
</P>
<P>
   Sensor Sensations
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, several Stanford University professors and
graduates with advanced degrees also are tapping government grants
to build high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford aeronautics Professor Fu-Kuo Chang and his former
doctoral student Mark Lin co-founded Acellent Technologies in
Sunnyvale last year to take advantage of sensor technology
advances.
</P>
<P>
   The price of an electronic sensor has declined during the past
decade from as much as $50 to 50 cents. That, together with
advances in software and computing technology, wireless
communications and the Internet, makes it possible to put sensors
in flexible film that can be mounted on or inside aircraft,
bridges, buildings and all sorts of structures to test their
soundness.
</P>
<P>
   For example, hundreds or thousands of sensors could be embedded
at load-bearing and other critical points inside an airplane and
could continually broadcast diagnostic signals. Or, their
measurements could be quickly downloaded and analyzed at regular
intervals, such as at the end of each flight.
</P>
<P>
   Important information can be gained when sensors pick up changes
to the structure caused by corrosion, cracks, delamination of
materials and other damage. Or, by running low electrical current
through the structure, the sensors can analyze the minuscule
vibrations to detect potential weaknesses and predict where a
structure might fail.
</P>
<P>
   While such diagnostic systems for a plane could cost $20,000 or
more, Acellent Director of Technology Mark Lin said they would be
far less expensive, cumbersome and time consuming than current
visual, touch and tap inspections and the occasional use of X-ray
and other probes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market could be huge,'' said Chang, who licensed the
technology for Acellent from Stanford. ``Aircraft, trains, ships,
autos, buildings, bridges and other infrastructure all need better
inspection systems. Just look at the unprecedented number of recent
space launch failures.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Military, Technology Meet
</P>
<P>
   Although Acellent is interested primarily in commercial markets,
there are obvious military applications for the technology. Since
September, the company has received $730,000 in SBIR grants from
the Army to investigate whether sensor networks mounted in missile
silos or on portable rocket launchers can quickly and easily
determine whether the equipment is safe to use.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has applied for a $250,000 matching CalTIP
grant to help it commercialize its technology.
</P>
<P>
   If an entrepreneur needs a lot of money and needs it fast, Chang
doesn't recommend applying for government grants. But if a startup
has patent protection, a few years to conduct R&AMP;D and doesn't want
to lose control to outside investors, he recommends government
grants.
</P>
<P>
   However, Acellent next plans to raise about $10 million in
venture capital. That's because, after proving the concept, the
company needs significantly more money to develop commercial
products.
</P>
<P>
   Sensant Corp. also is focused on high-tech monitoring.
Specifically, the San Jose, Calif., firm uses semiconductor
manufacturing techniques to create probes that can translate
ultrasonic signals into 3-D images for superior medical testing.
</P>
<P>
   The company was started in 1998 by Igal Ladabaum, who studied
bioengineering at UC Berkeley before receiving a doctorate in
electrical engineering from Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   To get an SBIR grant, Sensant redirected its attention from
serving cardiologists to helping the Navy find an easier, faster,
cheaper way to check aircraft for corrosion and other structural
defects. It turns out the inspection problem is much the same.
``Both involve imaging something underneath the skin,'' said Andrew
Cittadine, Sensant's vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Since May 1999, the San Jose startup has received two SBIR
grants from the Office of Naval Research totaling $520,000 and it
could get another $300,000. Sensant also has applied for a $200,000
CalTIP grant to help commercialize its technology for the $1
billion medical ultrasound probe market.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
