 STUDY TALLIES VALUE OF S.F. DIGITAL ECONOMY  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco's digital industry generated
nearly $4.9 billion last year, nearly five times the amount it made
in 1995, according to a study by the San Francisco Partnership, a
nonprofit business development organization.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the report's findings actually reflect the state of the
digital industry in San Francisco is unclear. Only 60 companies out
of 1,048 companies polled took part in the survey.
</P>
<P>
   The report, released Tuesday, details the tremendous growth of
the Internet, video game and software industries within San
Francisco's city limits. It also shows how this growth is causing
these companies to cope with such problems as the high cost of
office space, lack of skilled workers and high living costs.
</P>
<P>
   The survey is a follow-up of a 1995 survey done by accounting
firm PricewaterhouseCoopers for the partnership. This time around,
however, the San Francisco Partnership's own staff updated the
survey.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, the results, such as the size of the digital
industry's revenues, are extrapolated from the sample of 60
companies. In addition, much of the reporting, especially by the
small private firms that responded to the survey, was not
double-checked.
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, nearly 40,000 people work in San
Francisco for digital companies. Another 42,000 people work outside
the city for digital companies that are based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The employment figures could be much higher because the survey
did not count people who work for the online arms of traditional
companies such as stock brokerage Charles Schwab, Kmart and the
Gap. Marie Jones, director of economic development for San
Francisco Partnership, said it couldn't get these figures because
the companies couldn't provide the necessary information.
</P>
<P>
   The revenue figure of $4.9 billion in 1999 shows that the
digital industry is, as expected, a major part of the local
economy. For example, the tourism industry, one of the city's
largest moneymakers, took in $6.55 billion in 1999, according to
the San Francisco Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that the digital industry is strong and vital and
is a major piece of our economy,'' said Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest challenges to doing business in San Francisco,
according to 61 percent of the study's respondents, is the high
cost of rent. Another 41 percent complained about high wages,
parking scarcity and a lack of skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   Employee turnover in the digital industry is 24 percent,
according to the survey. But companies do not cite it directly as a
business obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be the focus of a high-wage industry,'' said
Stephen Levy, director of the Center for the Continuing Study of
the California Economy, a private research company in Palo Alto,
Calif. ``But there are a lot of challenges that come with
success.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
