 CALIFORNIA PRICE CAP ON ELECTRICITY HALVED  &HT;     By KELLY YAMANOUCHI 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Under pressure from Gov. Gray Davis and
regulatory agencies, the California Independent System Operator on
Tuesday slashed the maximum price it pays for wholesale power in
half to $250 per megawatt.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in a month that the board has taken action
to reduce the price cap from $750 per megawatt, as hot weather
triggered record customer demand and doubled energy bills in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups fear that similar price increases will show up
when the rate freeze on energy bills in Northern California is
lifted in March 2002 or earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The board, which operates much of the state's electricity grid,
had earlier lowered the maximum rate to $500 per megawatt. Two
other efforts to institute a $250 cap were defeated.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Davis and the Electricity Oversight Board,
which oversees the state's electricity market, stepped in and asked
the board to lower the cap to the ``lowest reasonable level.''
</P>
<P>
   The average price last year for a megawatt of energy, which
powers approximately 1,000 households per hour, was $62. On
Tuesday, wholesale energy rates on the state's power exchange hit
the $500 maximum when demand for electricity soared as consumers
cranked up their air conditioners.
</P>
<P>
   The board voted 15 to 6 in favor of the lower cap, with three
abstentions.
</P>
<P>
   The ISO faced threats from energy generators who said a $250 cap
would push them to sell their energy supply elsewhere. Alex
Goldberg, an attorney for power plant operator Williams Cos., told
the board that lowering the price cap could create a less reliable
electricity supply for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reliability is the primary objective of this board, it is not
controlling prices,'' Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Florio, who sits on the ISO representing the consumer
interest group The Utility Reform Network, told board members that
a recent study of energy rates showed that lowering the price cap
did not result in a loss of supply of energy.
</P>
<P>
   The possible effects of an energy shortage were obvious Tuesday
during the meeting. Pagers and cell phones sounded in the room as
the ISO declared a Stage 2 emergency. It called for large energy
consumers to voluntarily curtail their electricity usage and warned
of the possibility of rolling blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   The ISO's decisions are being closely watched by federal and
state authorities. With Davis pushing for action, the state's
Public Utilities Commission and Electricity Oversight Board filed
subpoenas with the ISO last week to gather information for a report
due to the governor by August 1. Davis said he intends to take
strong measures to hold down power rates.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission said last
week that it would investigate the ISO board. The commission wants
to issue a report by November 1 that will determine whether the
state's energy markets are working competitively, discuss what the
problems are and lay out a course of action.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Yamanouchi at  &LR; kyamanouchi(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
