<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SINTON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GROW A BUSINESS: TWO ATTORNEYS HANG THEIR SHINGLES ONLINE  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Setting up online marketplaces can be quite
risky, as stories and stock prices have recently shown. But that
hasn't deterred two San Francisco attorneys from separately giving
up the practice of law to practice entrepreneurship.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Dmitry Shubov, who tapped the computer
programming talents of fellow Russian-Jewish immigrants to create
LegalMatch, a Web site to connect lawyers with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The other is Richard Harroch, who retired as partner at San
Francisco's Orrick, Herrington &AMP; Sutcliffe to start
LawCommerce.com, an online marketplace where law firms can purchase
legal research, software and other products and services.
</P>
<P>
   Harroch knows a thing or two about law, entrepreneurship and
taking risks. In addition to working on hundreds of corporate deals
and writing a 1,600-page legal treatise, ``Startup &AMP; Emerging
Companies,'' he authored the popular IDG books ``Small Business Kit
for Dummies,'' ``Business Contracts Kit for Dummies'' and ``Poker
for Dummies.''
</P>
<P>
   In late 1998, Harroch founded AllBusiness.com, a Web service
designed to help small and growing businesses build and manage
their operations. In February, NBC Internet bought the company for
$225 million in stock and Harroch, 47, made more money than he had
in his career as corporate attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than retiring to his hobbies, playing poker and buying
domain names, Harroch got an idea for another Internet play, a B2B
marketplace for the legal community.
</P>
<P>
   Harroch figures the market on the Internet for legal services
and products can be huge. In the United States alone, more than 1
million lawyers purchase in excess of $50 billion in products and
services each year.
</P>
<P>
   Some prominent law firms including Wilson Sonsini, Skadden Arps
and Orrick Herrington have invested several million dollars in
Harroch's latest venture. On Friday, Andersen Consulting announced
it has invested in LawCommerce.com and will be a strategic partner.
In addition, more than 30 large law firms from Silicon Valley to
Wall Street have signed on as charter members.
</P>
<P>
   Harroch still finds time for his hobbies. He has participated in
three poker world championships and dabbles in domain names.
Harroch has been offered $10,000 for e-visionary and
eVisionary.com, $15,000 for Administer.com and $75,000 for
e-arbitration and eArbitration.com.
</P>
<P>
   But he isn't interested in selling these or other electronic
addresses such as resemble.com, e-achete.com and bazillions.com
that have yet to attract any offers. ``I think good dot-com names
are like San Francisco real estate,'' he said. ``They have
tremendous value and it keeps going up.''
</P>
<P>
   Shubov has a different business model for LegalMatch.com.
Instead of providing online procurement services for large law
firms, Shubov, 27, envisioned LegalMatch as a type of dating
service where small-business and other consumers of legal services
can check out qualified lawyers online and outline their needs.
Attorneys could then bid for their business.
</P>
<P>
   Shubov immigrated with his parents from Kiev, Ukraine, to Canada
when he was 11 and then moved to the Bay Area where he attended
Lowell High School and later the University of California at
Berkeley's Boalt Hall School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Then he worked for Fried, Frank, Harris, Shriver &AMP; Jacobson, a
large New York law firm. During his two years there, Shubov saw the
problem smaller firms and sole practitioners have in attracting new
clients and the difficulties individuals face finding good lawyers
at reasonable prices.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to San Francisco to bring the two sides together and
used his connections with the Russian and Jewish programming
community to build LegalMatch.com. Convinced Shubov's idea would
work, about 20 programmers and other experts contributed about $2
million worth of their time. Instead of cash compensation, they
took about 20 percent of the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Operating out of a converted two-bedroom apartment in San
Francisco's Richmond District, Shubov was able to launch the Web
site this week ( &LR; www.legalmatch.com &LR; ) with only about $300,000 from
friends, family and a few angel investors.
</P>
<P>
   Shubov says his service will provide significantly more than
other Web services such as Lawyer.com and Lawoffice.com, which are
primarily directories of attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Small businesses and individuals using the service can fill out
a questionnaire stating the services they are looking for, and
attorneys can advertise their expertise and bid for business.
</P>
<P>
   LegalMatch.com plans to charge law firms $20 to $200 a month for
membership and 3.5 percent commissions on business they book
through the online service. By contrast, Shubov said bar
associations typically take a 12 percent commission for referrals.
</P>
<P>
   Grow a Business appears every Wednesday. Send small-business
tips, comments and questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(AT)sfgate.com,  &LR; or
to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
</TEXT>
