MRS. CLINTON, ON OPPONENT'S HOME TURF, SAYS GOP LINES HAVE FAMILIAR
RING By SOMINI SENGUPTA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTBURY, N.Y. _ The day after the Republican National
Convention opened with a call to ``leave no child behind,'' Hillary
Rodham Clinton marveled at how familiar it all seemed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it sounded like the convention theme was `It Takes a
Village,''' Clinton said with a smirk, referring to the title of
her book, which was ridiculed by conservatives when it was
published in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The official theme at the Philadelphia convention on Monday was
actually ``Opportunity With a Purpose: Leave No Child Behind.'' The
phrase appeared in the remarks of many speakers, from experts on
adoption and literacy to Gen. Colin L. Powell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the issues that were discussed and the way they were
discussed were very much in line with what I've written about and
talked about for 30 years,'' Clinton said on Tuesday, the first day
of a three-day campaign trip on Long Island. ``I'm happy to have
even rhetorical support for our mutual obligation to care for
children.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's remarks came on the home turf of her Republican
opponent for the U.S. Senate, Rep. Rick Lazio. Clinton is likely to
have a much harder time winning votes on Republican-dominated Long
Island, where Lazio was born and raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Underneath all of that soothing rhetoric are very different
ideas about what we should do as a country,'' she told reporters
after a lunch meeting of the Nassau County Village Officials
Association here.``And if the people of New York know the
differences, the Democrats will do very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tailored her remarks on Tuesday to the crowds of largely
white, middle-aged and elderly Long Islanders, emphasizing issues
like lowering taxes and her support for using the federal surplus
to preserve Social Security and introduce prescription drug
benefits for Medicare patients.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also downplayed her earlier sharp criticism of Lazio,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the imminent Republican nominee for
president, and his designated running mate, Dick Cheney, saying
that she had merely been pointing out facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's an attack to say Governor Bush went to Bob
Jones University, Governor Bush supports the Republican platform
and Supreme Court nominees who are dedicated to doing away with a
woman's right to choose,'' she said. ``I don't think it's negative
or an attack to say here are the facts and let people make their
own judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seemed downright earnest, even returning, for the first
time in months, to the slogan of her book. ``It takes a village to
provide parks,'' she said earlier on Tuesday during a campaign stop
at a neighborhood park. ``It takes a village to keep the streets
safe. It takes a village to provide teachers and resources
necessary to educate our children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of villages,'' Clinton observed, ``to help
elect someone to the United States Senate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
