<HEADER>
A0166 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-UNORTHODOX-HNS &LR;      08-01 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-UNORTHODOX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Democrats debate Bush's diversity record
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By PATTY REINERT
 &HT;    and CLAY ROBISON
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Presidential hopeful George W. Bush may be
packing the stage of the Republican National Convention with
minority supporters, but his record and appointments destroy the
illusion of an all-inclusive GOP, Democrats said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This horse called `Vision' that Bush is riding into this
convention on is not real,'' said U.S. Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, an
African-American Democrat from Houston. ``If you can't sign a hate
crimes bill when a man in your state was dismembered, how can you
say you include all the American people?''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee was referring to the brutal 1998 murder of James
Byrd Jr., a black man who was chained to a pickup by three white
men and dragged to his death near Jasper. Despite pleas from Byrd's
daughter, the Texas governor refused to back a hate crimes bill
last year because it also included protection for crime victims
attacked because they are gay.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's record on hate crimes was one of many racially sensitive
issues pointed out during a news conference organized by the
Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Jackson Lee was joined by Democratic National
Chairman Joe Andrew; U.S. Rep. Harold Ford Jr., D-Tenn.; Sen.
Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.; Nelson Diaz, chairman of the Democratic
Hispanic Caucus; and Carol Price, the Maryland coordinator of the
Million Mom March and a mother who lost her 13-year-old son to gun
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Participants contrasted Bush's record with his claims that the
``new'' Republican Party, though still overwhelmingly white and
affluent, will embrace minorities and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Among the complaints were Bush's decision to invite retired Gen.
Colin Powell, who is African-American, to address the convention
Monday night vs. his decision to take the stage himself at Bob
Jones University, which prohibited interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also criticized Bush's refusal to condemn the flying
of the Confederate flag above the South Carolina statehouse, and
his opposition to affirmative action programs in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor's appointment of state Health Commissioner
William R. ``Reyn'' Archer and his appointment of Marshall Police
Chief Charles Williams to head a statewide law enforcement agency
also were criticized, as was his selection of former Defense
Secretary Richard Cheney as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Archer came under fire earlier this year for blaming Texas' high
teen pregnancy rate on a Hispanic culture that he said accepts
teen-age motherhood. Williams sparked a huge outcry when it was
reported that he said in a court deposition that he didn't consider
the term ``porch monkey'' to be racist.
</P>
<P>
   Bush defended both men, and refused calls to fire them. Williams
later resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, as a congressman from Wyoming, voted to abolish the
Department of Education and voted against funding for Head Start,
an educational program that 25 percent of Hispanic children
nationwide participate in. He also voted against a resolution
calling for the release of then South African political prisoner
Nelson Mandela, and, like Bush, has opposed gun control
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Diaz, chairman of the Democratic Hispanic Caucus, cited
Texas' poor record on providing health insurance for poor children
and criticized Bush for failing to visit South Texas colonias.
About half a million Texans, mostly Hispanic, live in the
unincorporated subdivisions, which lack basic provisions like
running water and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion on race was prompted by Monday's GOP activities,
which included performances and speeches by several minorities and
featured Powell's prime-time speech. The popular general praised
Bush, but also sharply criticized the party for its stand against
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some in our party miss no opportunity to roundly condemn
affirmative action that helped a few thousand black kids get an
education, but you hardly hear a whimper from them over affirmative
action for lobbyists who load our federal tax code with preferences
for special interests,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a spokeswoman for the NAACP confirmed Tuesday that
the group's president, Kweisi Mfume, had asked Republican Party
leaders if he could address the GOP convention here but received a
counter-offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They invited him to speak to a small group of black
Republicans at a reception,'' said Jean Ross, spokeswoman for the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People. ``Mr.
Mfume, of course, turned that down.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bush said he agrees with Powell that the party needs
to do more to reach out to minorities, but he did not support
Powell when asked whether Republicans spend too much time bashing
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I agree with Colin Powell that Republicans need to do more
to reach out to minorities, got a lot of work to do and I agree
with him that I'm the man to do it for the Republican Party,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought people heard his message that our party must do a
better job of recruiting minorities and as he said, specifically
African-Americans,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The 248 Texas delegates to the convention, who are
overwhelmingly white and social and religious conservatives,
generally gave high marks to Powell's speech, but there were
differences of interpretation on his affirmative action remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he was trying to say we should support
affirmative action,'' said Tim Lambert of Lubbock, a member of the
Republican National Committee and an at-large Texas delegate. ``I
think he was saying we ought to be consistent in opposing corporate
welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Geraldine Sam, a teacher from La Marque and one of a handful of
black delegates, said she left the Democratic Party a few years ago
because it was taking minorities for granted. She also lost two
races for Congress as a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Sam said Powell's speech was ``awesome,'' and she believed it
was a strong endorsement of affirmative action, which she also
supports.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle reporters R.G. Ratcliffe and Lori Rodriguez
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   XX END OF STORY xx
</P>
<P>
