<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S GIULIANI CONFIRMS PRELIMINARY CANCER TREATMENT WITH
HORMONE THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ New York City's mayor, Rudolph Giuliani,
acknowledged for the first time Tuesday night that he has been
undergoing hormone treatments for his prostate cancer for the past
two and a half months.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to indicate that the hormones were a preliminary
therapy and added that he would make a final decision about his
treatment within a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which could either be radiation or surgery,'' Giuliani said.
``But luckily the hormones are working.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said the hormone treatments had reduced the levels of
prostate-specific antigens in his blood to ``minuscule'' amounts.
``I have no problems right now, except every once in a while it
leaves you a little fatigued,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani made his comments at the Republican National Convention
here during a live, nationally televised interview on MSNBC with
Tom Brokaw, who immediately asked the mayor about his health.
Giuliani was relaxed and jovial in his response. His manner was in
striking contrast to the verbal lashings he has given to New York
City Hall reporters in recent weeks when they have asked the same
question.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, after The New York Daily News quoted unnamed sources
who said that the mayor was receiving treatments of the hormone
Lupon, Giuliani angrily reprimanded reporters for trying to confirm
the story during a news conference at City Hall Park. He neither
confirmed nor denied the report.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also told Brokaw that he expected his treatments to
take seven or eight months and that he was ``very optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani made similar remarks in another live television
interview Tuesday night with Judy Woodruff and Bernard Shaw of CNN,
although he did not say specifically at that time that he was
receiving hormones.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani announced on April 27 that he had prostate cancer in an
early, treatable form. On May 19, citing his cancer, he withdrew
from his Senate race against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
