<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMPTON DOES THE JOB ALL AROUND AS METS TOP REDS, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ See Mike Hampton pitch. See Mike Hampton bat. See
Mike Hampton field. See Mike Hampton sweat in the dugout before the
Mets complete a 3-2 victory over the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Just seeing Mike Hampton in a Mets uniform should be enough for
Shea Stadium fans because he offered no objections to the trade
that brought him to New York. Not that he had a choice when the
deal was made with Houston last winter, but the good guys get
credit no matter what the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Working on the mound Tuesday night, Hampton shut out the Reds
for seven innings before slipping in the eighth and setting the
stage for a parade of three relief pitchers. Armando Benitez
secured the final three outs, but it was the third out that John
Franco got in the eighth inning that was most critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was out there,'' said Hampton, who watched the last
five outs from the dugout. ``It's not any mystery that I don't like
being taken out of the game, but we have a good bullpen. You just
root your teammates on and hope they get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Turk Wendell didn't, giving up a run-scoring triple that put
Dante Bichette 90 feet from a tie game, but Hampton nevertheless
gained his 11th victory against 7 defeats and raised his record for
the past two months to 9-3. Then there were those other
contributions the left-hander made.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping to the plate in the second inning with Bubba Trammell
at third base and Mike Bordick at first on successive no-out
singles, Hampton lofted a sacrifice fly to right field, doubling
the lead to 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   The run batted in was Hampton's sixth of the season. His rbi
ratio of one per 8.67 at-bats is better than the ratios belonging
to Kurt Abbott, Matt Franco, Lenny Harris (with the Mets) and Rey
Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton displayed the third phase of his triple-threat talent in
the third inning. With two out, Chris Stynes rapped a ground ball
back to the mound. The ball was too far to Hampton's left to snare
with his glove so he quickly stuck out his left foot and knocked
the ball down. In another sport, someone would have said, ``Kick
save and a beauty.'' Having corraled the ball, Hampton coolly bent
over, picked it up and threw to first for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a reaction play,'' Hampton said. ``You see the
ball hit up the middle, I'm trying to kick it or do something with
it. I got it on the bottom of my shoe.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When Hampton signs with the Mets or another team as a free agent
sometime after the season, his fielding and hitting will be taken
into consideration, but he will get his $12 million or more a year
primarily for his pitching. He did a little bit of that Tuesday
night, too.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first seven innings, he allowed more than one
baserunner in an inning only once, and only once did he allow
runners to advance beyond first base. Those acts both occurred in
the fifth inning, which he ended by inducing Stynes to ground out.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds, scrambling to catch the St. Louis Cardinals in the
National League West or the Mets in the wild-card race, finally
scored in the eighth inning. Stynes began the inning with a single,
and Barry Larkin lashed a line drive to left that eluded Trammell
and became a run-scoring double.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. grounded out, and Valentine called for Wendell
to face Bichette, who promptly hit a high fly ball that collided
with the right field fence just as Derek Bell did. The ball won,
and Bichette raced to third with a run-scoring triple.
</P>
<P>
   Now Valentine brought in Franco, who, with the infield in,
induced Sean Casey to bounce to first for the second out. But then
he walked Alex Ochoa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to give him anything good to hit,'' Franco said.
``I wanted to nibble a little bit; maybe I nibbled too much. I
thought maybe he would chase. On the other hand, I didn't want to
walk him, which I did, and put the winning run on. It was a mistake
on my part, but it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Benito Santiago was next, and he worked the count to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking if he comes inside here he has no chance
because it's Johnny's bread and butter,'' Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   Good thinking. ``I fed him most of the pitches away, away,
away,'' Franco said, ``and kind of froze him up with a two-seam
fastball. Guys who have been with me a lot know I like to freeze
guys up inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Umpire Ed Rapuano called the pitch strike three, even though it
appeared to be so much inside that catcher Mike Piazza quickly
moved his glove to show the ball in the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion that was a strike,'' Franco protested, unable to
stifle a laugh. ``It was right down the middle and he took it. Let
me enjoy this, please.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the Mets, Hampton especially, enjoyed it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
