<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TOP ROYALS, 5-4, ON BROSIUS HOMER IN EIGHTH 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dwight Gooden pitched seven strong innings on
Tuesday, giving up only four hits and one walk, as the New York
Yankees beat the Kansas City Royals 5-4 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius put the Yanks over the top with a dramatic solo
homer in the eighth inning to break a 4-4 tie. The Yanks' Mike
Stanton picked up the win in relief.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Royals starter Dan Reichert was thoroughly
frustrating the Yankees and stranding runners in bunches, Gooden
kept pace. The Royals nicked him for an unearned run in the fourth
and another run in the fifth, but Gooden had a solid fastball,
precise control and confidence. Gooden, who is now 3-0 with a 1.86
earned run average in five appearances as a Yankee, is making the
team look shrewd for believing in him again. He had been dropped by
the Yankees twice previously before George Steinbrenner
sympathetically offered him one last chance this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, with the Yankees trailing by 2-1, Reichert
issued back-to-back walks to Chuck Knoblauch and Derek Jeter.
Reichert was followed by left-hander Tim Byrdak, who struck out
Paul O'Neill, then gave up a two-run double to Bernie Williams,
which put the Yankees ahead, 3-2. David Justice followed with a
double to make it, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden was six outs from his fourth victory with the Yankees and
he had thrown only 79 pitches, but Torre naturally turned to
Stanton in the eighth. A one-out single, a walk and Johnny Damon's
booming double off the right-center-field fence, which was a few
feet from being a three-run homer, tied the score, 4-4. The Royals
later loaded the bases against Jeff Nelson, but he whiffed Joe
Randa and pumped his fist as he returned to the dugout. All of the
Yankees were celebrating a few moments later as Brosius belted
Bottalico's 1-0 pitch over the left-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals had at least a few chances to score in the chaotic
fourth, but managed just one after having three of their players
thrown out on the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Rey Sanchez reached first when Jeter bounced a throw to first
base, his 14th error of the season. Mark Quinn lined a shot down
the left field line, but, after the ball caromed off the wall in
front of the first row seats, David Justice made a bare-handed
pickup and fired a one-bounce throw to nab Quinn at second. Sanchez
cruised into third.
</P>
<P>
   With the infield drawn in for the Yankees, Jermaine Dye hit a
slow tapper to shortstop. Sanchez inexplicably took three steps
toward the plate, realized Jeter would easily throw him out, tried
to return to third and was caught.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Randa followed by ripping a bullet to left center field that
scored Dye from first for a 1-0 lead. Randa tried to scoot to third
as Justice bobbled the ball on the warning track, but the relay
throw from Justice to Jose Vizcaino to Brosius got Randa.
</P>
</TEXT>
