<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATALK-0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Donnan says Dogs can do
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - More than eight months after Georgia's regular season
ended with a controversial fumble at Georgia Tech's 2-yard line,
the Bulldogs are still talking about bad calls.
</P>
<P>
   One day after Georgia announced it was suspending seven of its
players for making unauthorized telephone calls, Bulldogs coach Jim
Donnan addressed a standing-room-only crowd of about 5,000 fans at
a downtown Atlanta hotel. After apologizing for the phone incident,
Donnan quickly turned fans' attention to the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, who return 19 starters from last season's 8-4
squad, have been ranked as high as third nationally by one
preseason poll. Georgia was picked to finish second in the SEC East
at last week's media conference in Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even (Steve) Spurrier said we have a chance,'' Donnan joked,
referring to the Gators' coach.
</P>
<P>
   Although Donnan has tried to temper expectations surrounding his
team in recent weeks, he wasn't backing down on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting 55 years to be the head coach of a football
team that has this much potential,'' he said. ``And I guarantee you
that we're going to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan, entering his fifth season at Georgia, apologized for the
suspensions.Seven players were suspended for one of the first two
games after they charged more than $50 to a university
long-distance access code. Nine other players will pay restitution
and serve community service for charges less than $50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologize personally for what happened,'' Donnan said. ``I
wish I could keep tabs on what our players are doing day and night.
It's embarrassing for us and hopefully we'll be able to overcome
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan asked the crowd to focus on the season, which begins
Sept. 2 against Georgia Southern in Sanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people need to understand is that we need to get a sense
of direction around here,'' Donnan said. ``We need to understand
that this team has a chance to do something special. I promise you
that we're going to do a lot more good things than bad things this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of apprehension and expectations about our team
this year, but it should be that way at Georgia. We should be in
the upper echelon every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
