<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-RIGHT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVES STILL MAJOR PRESENCE IN GOP
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Away from the don't-rock-the-boat choreography of
the convention hall, more than 2,000 GOP faithful rocked to
conservative religious oratory Tuesday in a hotel ballroom and
showed that Christian conservatives remain a major presence in the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``From reading in the media, I thought there was no more
religious right. This is as big as the convention itself,''
Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating declared to cheers at the Philadelphia
Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd swayed to the strains of the ``Battle Hymn of the
Republic'' and Lee Greenwood's ``God Bless the U.S.A.''
</P>
<P>
   TV evangelist Pat Robertson, keynoting the ``Faith and Freedom
Celebration'' sponsored by the Christian Coalition, depicted the
presidential election as an opportunity to name U.S. Supreme Court
judges who will reverse the Roe vs. Wade decision that legalized
abortion across America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like two or three of these unelected officials are
getting ready to retire or go on to that great unelected court in
the sky,'' said Robertson, an outspoken backer of Texas Gov. George
W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have an election of a man who will appoint
righteous judges to the Supreme Court of the United States,''
Robertson added.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he will not make the abortion issue a litmus test
for court nominees, although he has expressed admiration for
anti-abortion positions taken by Justices Clarence Thomas and
Anthony Scalia.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Flournoy, a GOP delegate from Lufkin, Texas, explained the
outpouring of emotion as ``a hunger for a return to righteousness
in our nation.'' He looked around at the standing-room-only crowd
and added: ``I've never been in a rally of Christian people this
size.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion and the prospect of a turnover of the nation's highest
court were the crowd's catalysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the opportunity to elect (in Bush) a president who is
pro-life unapologetically ... who has endorsed a pro-life platform
and picked a pro-life running mate,'' declared Arkansas Gov. Mike
Huckabee.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Sekulow, lead counsel with the American Center for Law and
Justice, formed by Robertson to litigate against the liberal
American Civil Liberties Union, excoriated recent court rulings
against a Texas high school's prefootball game prayers. ``We have a
Supreme Court protecting pornography and penalizing prayer,''
Sekulow said.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was one of the few unabashedly partisan events at what
has been a deliberately non-controversial GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is a convention of sweetness and light,''
Robertson said. ``Nobody wants to rock the boat.'' With that said,
however, the TV evangelist and 1988 presidential candidate
proceeded to rock the ballroom with his oratory.
</P>
<P>
   In a year when Republicans have backed off from their 1996 call
to abolish Cabinet departments, Robertson brought back the earlier
pledge. ``I agree with Ronald Reagan. I think we should do away
with the federal Department of Education.''
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Education actually grew during Reagan's
presidency, but Robertson depicted it as a boondoggling
bureaucracy. ``I promise you, if I could ever get my hands on
one-tenth the budget of the federal Department of Education, there
would not be a single illiterate child in America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, in their official proceedings, have sought
never to have a repetition of 1992, when defeated GOP presidential
candidate Pat Buchanan declared from the podium that there was ``a
cultural war'' going on in America.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, many in the Republican Party believe what Buchanan said
that night.
</P>
<P>
   There is a ``great cultural battle for the soul of our
country,'' Sen. Sam Brownback of Kansas told the crowd. He decried
``cultural pollution'' in the entertainment industry that is, he
said, ``glorifying violence and hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Brownback also noted that a fund-raising party at the upcoming
Democratic National Convention will be held at the Playboy Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There they will celebrate not liberty, but license,''
Brownback said. ``The values of the Playboy Mansion do not belong
in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition's clout was noted by one speaker not
usually associated with the religious right. Sen. Mitch McDonnell
of Kentucky, chairman of the National Republican Senatorial
Committee, praised the group's efforts in turning back proposed
limits on campaign spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hear the three words `campaign finance reform,' some
liberal is trying to shut you up,'' McConnell told the rally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-00 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
